window.WORDPICTURES={"G1":{"b":"Alpha is the first letter of the Greek alphabet, the way A starts ours. It stands for what comes first. In Revelation God calls himself the Alpha. Before the whole row of letters, before anything at all, he is there. First.","g":"first letter","h":"The picture: the first letter, the start of the row."},"G10":{"b":"The name means father, or possessor, of renown. It joins a word for father with a word for grandeur, an imposing form and appearance. So the name pictures a man who holds great fame.","g":"Abihud","h":"The picture: father of renown."},"G100":{"b":"Abbott-Smith traces it to a word for thick, well-grown, and Strong's says plumpness. Paul uses it for the generous, full collection he is carrying, a heavy harvest of a gift, handled so no one can fault it.","g":"abundance","h":"The picture: a crop grown thick and plump."},"G1000":{"b":"From a word meaning to throw. A bole is a throw, used as a rough measure of distance, an arm's cast. Jesus withdrew from the disciples about a stone's throw, knelt down, and prayed.","g":"a throw, cast","h":"The picture: a stone's throw of distance."},"G1001":{"b":"This means to heave the lead, to drop a weighted line over the side and measure how deep the water is. The sailors did it twice as they neared land, and the number kept shrinking. Heaving the lead to find the bottom.","g":"take soundings","h":"The picture: a weighted line dropped over the side."},"G1003":{"b":"This is Boaz, the husband of Ruth and an ancestor of David. Strong's says the name is of Hebrew origin but supplies no meaning. It stands here only as a name, nothing to see inside it.","flat":1,"g":"Boaz","h":"No picture."},"G1004":{"b":"The word simply means mud, filth, mire. There is no root behind it, just the thing itself. Peter says the washed pig returns to wallow in this, a picture of those who go back to the sin they left.","g":"mire, mud","h":"The picture: thick wet mud."},"G1005":{"b":"Strong's says this is the north, \"properly, wind.\" It was Boreas, the north wind itself, before it named the direction. Jesus says people will come from north and south to sit at the feast. The word underneath is a wind.","g":"north","h":"The picture: the cold wind out of the north."},"G1006":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this is properly the herdsman's word, of a herdsman, to feed. The men feeding the pigs ran off when the herd drowned. Jesus turns it to people when he tells Peter, feed my sheep.","g":"feed, graze","h":"The picture: putting the herd out to graze."},"G1007":{"b":"The name means a lamp. It comes from a word meaning to kindle, to set alight. Bosor is Beor, remembered in the New Testament as the father of Balaam the prophet.","g":"Bosor","h":"The picture: a lamp."},"G1008":{"b":"The root means to graze or pasture. This is the green growth that the flock feeds on. Ground that drinks the rain and brings forth useful herbs receives God's blessing, unlike ground that grows only thorns.","g":"herb","h":"The picture: grass coming up for grazing."},"G1009":{"b":"The word means a cluster of grapes. Abbott-Smith gives \"a cluster of grapes.\" Picture ripe grapes hanging thick on the vine. So the angel gathered the earth's clusters and threw them into the winepress of wrath.","g":"cluster of grapes","h":"The picture: a heavy bunch of grapes."},"G101":{"b":"This is \"not\" joined to a word meaning able or powerful, from dynamis, power. To adynateo is to lack the strength for a thing, to find it impossible. Jesus turns it around. With God, no thing is too strong to do.","g":"be impossible","h":"The picture: no strength in the arm to do it."},"G1010":{"b":"The root means to take counsel, to weigh a matter and decide. This is a member of the council, here the Jewish ruling court. Mark names Joseph of Arimathea as one, a man of the very court that condemned Jesus, who then buried him.","g":"councillor","h":"The picture: a man who sits on the council."},"G1011":{"b":"This is to take counsel, to weigh a matter and settle on a plan. A king sits down first to reckon whether he can meet the enemy. The chief priests take counsel to put Lazarus to death. Turning a decision over until you resolve it.","g":"take counsel","h":"The picture: sitting down to weigh a decision."},"G1012":{"b":"The root is to will, to be willing. Boulē is the will settled into a plan, counsel, purpose, a decision reached and fixed. Peter says Jesus was handed over by the set boulē of God, no accident but a purpose decided before the world began.","g":"counsel","h":"The picture: the will settled into a plan."},"G1013":{"b":"Built from the word for to will. Abbott gives purpose, will. The centurion, his boulema set on saving Paul, stopped the soldiers from killing the prisoners, Acts 27:43. A resolve is not a wish. It decides what actually happens.","g":"will, purpose","h":"The picture: a settled decision."},"G1014":{"b":"Strong's calls it the middle voice of a primary verb, so there is nothing behind it. Abbott says it is stronger than the ordinary word for wanting, the will choosing between options.\n\nNo image. Just resolve.","flat":1,"g":"will, intend","h":"No picture."},"G1015":{"b":"The word simply means a hill, a small rise in the ground. Abbott-Smith notes it came into Greek from a foreign tongue. Luke quotes Isaiah with it: every mountain and hill will be made low, the road levelled for the Lord.","g":"hill","h":"The picture: a low, rounded hill."},"G1016":{"b":"Strong's names it an ox as grazing. The word ties the animal to feeding in the field, head down, always eating. So the ox is the working beast of the farm, the one that treads out the grain and must not be muzzled.","g":"ox","h":"The picture: the beast with its head in the grass."},"G1017":{"b":"This is the prize in the public games, the award handed out by the umpire. Paul says run the race so as to win it. In Philippians it is the prize of God's upward call in Christ.","g":"prize","h":"The picture: the prize handed out by the umpire."},"G1018":{"b":"The brabeus was the umpire at the games, the one who judged and awarded the prize. This word means to act as that umpire, to decide. Paul says let the peace of Christ be the umpire in your heart.","g":"rule, arbitrate","h":"The picture: the umpire whose call settles it."},"G1019":{"b":"The root simply means slow. To tarry is to drag your feet, to be late in coming. Peter says the Lord is not slow about his promise as some count slowness. What looks like delay is patience. He has not dragged his feet.","g":"delay, tarry","h":"The picture: dragging slow feet."},"G102":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means unable, powerless. It is built from not and the word for able or strong. A thing is impossible when there is no power to do it. With God, that changes.","g":"impossible, weak","h":"The picture: no power in it."},"G1020":{"b":"This is bradys, slow, plus pleo, to sail. It means to sail slowly. For many days the ship inches along, barely making headway against the wind. The word puts the slowness right into it, a vessel creeping when it should be running.","g":"sail slowly","h":"The picture: a ship crawling slowly over the water."},"G1021":{"b":"The word means slow, and by extension dull. James says be slow to speak and slow to anger. Jesus calls the two on the road slow of heart to believe. It is the drag of someone who takes far too long to catch on.","g":"slow","h":"The picture: dragging your feet, slow to move."},"G1022":{"b":"The root means slow. This is slowness, delay. Peter uses it to answer a complaint: the Lord is not slow about his promise, as some count slowness, but patient, not willing that any perish. What looks like dragging feet is God holding the door.","g":"slowness","h":"The picture: dragging feet."},"G1023":{"b":"The word is the arm. In the Old Testament and here, the arm of the Lord stands for his strength put to work. Mary sings that God has shown strength with his arm and scattered the proud. Muscle you can see.","g":"arm","h":"The picture: a bared arm flexed to strike."},"G1024":{"b":"This word means short, a little space or a brief while. Strong's says its origin is uncertain, so nothing stands behind it. Just smallness of time or distance, a short stretch. There is nothing here to picture.","flat":1,"g":"short, little","h":"No picture."},"G1025":{"b":"Strong's: \"an infant (properly, unborn).\" Abbott: an unborn child, and then a newborn babe. It is the very youngest child, still in the womb or just born. The baby leaped in Elizabeth's womb at this word.","g":"infant, babe","h":"The picture: a baby not yet or just born."},"G1026":{"b":"This word means to wet, especially by a shower of rain. God sends rain on the just and the unjust with it. The weeping woman wet Jesus' feet with her tears using this word. Water falling and soaking in.","g":"rain, moisten","h":"The picture: a shower soaking the ground."},"G1027":{"b":"Strong's says this is akin to a word meaning \"to roar.\" Abbott-Smith gives no origin, just \"thunder.\" So the name catches the sound itself, the sky's roar. James and John were called sons of thunder.","g":"thunder","h":"The picture: a roar."},"G1028":{"b":"The root means to wet, especially with a shower. Broche is the rain itself, the downpour. Jesus says the rain fell and the floods came and beat on both houses. The one on rock stood. The one on sand fell. Same storm, different foundation.","g":"rain","h":"The picture: rain beating down on a house."},"G1029":{"b":"Abbott gives it as a noose, a slip-knot, a halter. It pictures a looped cord that tightens over what it catches. Paul says he writes not to throw a noose on them, not to trap them, but for their good.","g":"snare, noose","h":"The picture: a looped cord thrown over."},"G103":{"b":"This word simply means to sing. Strong's calls it a primary verb, so nothing lies behind it to trace. Paul tells the church to sing to God in their hearts. The picture is the plain one, a voice raised in song.","g":"sing","h":"The picture: a voice lifted in song."},"G1030":{"b":"The root means to grate the teeth, in pain or rage. This is that grinding sound, teeth clenched and scraping against each other. Jesus pairs it with weeping in the place of judgment. The noise a body makes in torment and fury.","g":"gnashing","h":"The picture: teeth grinding together."},"G1031":{"b":"Strong's says the word means to grate the teeth in pain or rage. When the council hears Stephen's charge, they grind their teeth at him like cornered animals.","g":"gnash","h":"The picture: teeth grinding in rage."},"G1032":{"b":"The word means to be so full a thing bursts, and of a spring, to gush. James points to a spring. It does not pour fresh water and salt water from the same opening. Neither should your mouth.","g":"send forth","h":"The picture: a spring gushing water."},"G1033":{"b":"Strong's traces this to a word meaning to eat. A brōma is the thing you chew and swallow, a plate of food. So when Jesus says his food is to do the Father's will, he means it feeds him like a meal.","g":"food","h":"The picture: the thing you chew and swallow."},"G1034":{"b":"From a word for eating and food. Brosimos means eatable, fit to eat. Risen, Jesus asked, have you here anything to eat. A body that could take a meal was no ghost. They gave him broiled fish.","g":"food, meat","h":"The picture: food held out to eat."},"G1035":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this is the act of eating, and so food. It also means rust, the corrosion that eats metal away. When Jesus warns of moth and rust destroying, the \"rust\" is this word, decay gnawing like a mouth.","g":"eating, food","h":"The picture: the eating."},"G1036":{"b":"The root means the depth, the deep sea. This verb is to sink into it. Luke uses it for the two boats so loaded with fish that they begin to go under. Paul uses it for greed that drags people down into ruin.","g":"sink","h":"The picture: a boat going down into the deep."},"G1037":{"b":"Strong's gives depth, and by implication the sea. Abbott-Smith says the deep sea. Paul lists it among his dangers, a night and a day adrift out where the water has no floor beneath you.","g":"deep, sea","h":"The picture: the deep open sea, the bottom far under."},"G1038":{"b":"This word comes from the word for a hide, an animal's skin. A byrseus is a tanner, the man who scrapes and cures raw skins into leather. Peter lodged with Simon the tanner, in the house that smelled of hides.","g":"tanner","h":"The picture: the man who cures animal hides."},"G1039":{"b":"The word means made of byssos, white linen. Revelation clothes the bride and the armies of heaven in it, bright and clean. It is the costly white cloth, the fabric of the pure, worn by those made ready.","g":"fine linen","h":"The picture: fine white linen cloth."},"G104":{"b":"This word means always, ever. Strong's traces it to an old word for continued duration, an unbroken stretch of time. It just means going on and on. There is nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"always, ever","h":"No picture."},"G1040":{"b":"Abbott calls it a fine species of flax, and the linen made from it. Picture the smooth white cloth of the wealthy. The rich man dressed in it every day, while a beggar lay at his gate.","g":"fine linen","h":"The picture: fine flax spun into linen."},"G1041":{"b":"This is properly a stand, a raised base you step up to. Only then does it come to mean an altar. In Athens Paul found such a stand carved with the words, to an unknown god.","g":"altar","h":"The picture: a raised stone stand."},"G1042":{"b":"This is the local Aramaic name for the same spot the Greeks called the Stone Pavement. Strong's says it means the knoll, a raised place of rock. It was where Pilate sat to judge. Two names, one high, hard platform.","g":"Gabbatha","h":"The picture: a raised, rocky knoll."},"G1043":{"b":"Abbott-Smith reads the Hebrew name as hero of God. Gabriel is the angel who stands before God and is sent with news, to Zechariah and to Mary. Even the messenger's name carries God in it, God's own strong one.","g":"Gabriel","h":"The picture: the name means hero of God."},"G1044":{"b":"Strong's traces this to a word meaning to gnaw. It is our gangrene, an eating sore that spreads and kills the flesh around it. Paul says false teaching spreads like this. It does not sit still. It eats outward.","g":"gangrene","h":"The picture: a sore that eats the flesh."},"G1045":{"b":"The name comes from a word meaning to crowd upon, to press in as a throng. Gad was a son of Jacob and became one of the twelve tribes of Israel.","g":"Gad","h":"The picture: a crowd."},"G1046":{"b":"This names someone from Gadara, a town east of the Jordan. It tells you where a person is from. A place name carries no picture of its own. There is nothing here to see but a location.","flat":1,"g":"Gadarene","h":"No picture."},"G1047":{"b":"This is a Persian word that came into Greek for the royal treasure, the king's stored wealth. The Ethiopian official Philip met had charge of all the queen's gaza. Think of a guarded room piled with gold.","g":"treasure","h":"The picture: a royal treasure hoard."},"G1049":{"b":"Built from a word for treasure and a word for guarding. It is the guarded treasure room, and the trumpet-shaped chests where people dropped their gifts. Jesus watched the poor widow drop in her two small coins.","g":"treasury","h":"The picture: the temple offering box."},"G105":{"b":"The root is the air itself, for the eagle rides it as naturally circumambient. Aetos is the eagle, named for its wind-like flight. Where the carcass lies, Jesus says, the aetoi gather, circling down out of the sky.","g":"eagle","h":"The picture: an eagle riding the air."},"G1050":{"b":"This is just a name, Gaius, borne by more than one Christian. It comes from Latin, so the Greek holds no picture. A man's name, nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"Gaius","h":"No picture."},"G1051":{"b":"The word just means milk. Abbott-Smith notes the New Testament uses it of elementary Christian teaching. Milk is what an infant can take before solid food. Paul fed the immature milk, the simple first things, because they could not yet chew meat.","g":"milk","h":"The picture: milk for a baby."},"G1052":{"b":"The word means a Galatian, from the region in Asia Minor. Paul flings it at them in frustration: O foolish Galatians, who has bewitched you. A whole church named in one word, used like a parent grabbing a child by the shoulders.","g":"Galatian","h":"The picture: the people of Galatia."},"G1053":{"b":"This is Galatia, a region in Asia Minor. Strong's says only that the name is of foreign origin. Gauls once settled there, but that is history, not a meaning inside the word. It is a place name, nothing to see.","flat":1,"g":"Galatia","h":"No picture."},"G1054":{"b":"Belonging to Galatia, a region of Asia. Picture Paul crossing the Galatian country, strengthening the disciples town by town, Acts 18:23. The word marks the churches he later wrote his sharpest letter to, pleading with them about grace.","g":"of Galatia","h":"The picture: the Galatian country."},"G1055":{"b":"This is a calm, the flat glassy water left after a storm. Watch the scene. Jesus speaks, the wind drops, and the sea goes smooth. The word is that sudden stillness on the water, quiet where a moment before there was chaos.","g":"calm","h":"The picture: the sea gone flat and still."},"G1056":{"b":"The name is Hebrew, not Greek. Abbott-Smith gives its meaning as the circle, district. Strong's calls it the heathen circle.\n\nGalilee is a ring drawn around the northern part of the country.","g":"Galilee","h":"The picture: a circle of land."},"G1057":{"b":"The root is Galilee, the northern region Strong's calls the heathen circle, ringed by Gentiles and looked down on. A Galilaios is a man from there. Peter's accent gives him away in the courtyard, you are a Galilean, your speech betrays you.","g":"Galilean","h":"The picture: a man from the heathen circle."},"G1058":{"b":"This is a Roman name, Gallio, the proconsul of Achaia. It comes over from Latin. A name resting on a person, with no picture inside the word itself for us to see here.","flat":1,"g":"Gallio","h":"No picture."},"G1059":{"b":"The name means reward of God. It blends a word for how God treats a person with a word for strength, that is, God. Gamaliel was a respected teacher of the law who taught Paul.","g":"Gamaliel","h":"The picture: reward of God."},"G106":{"b":"Built from not and leaven. It pictures the flat bread of Passover, made with no yeast. Paul turns it on believers: be unleavened, clean of the old corruption, like fresh dough.","g":"unleavened","h":"The picture: bread with no yeast."},"G1060":{"b":"This comes from gamos, the wedding feast, nuptials. To gameo is to marry, to take a husband or wife. So in the days of Noah they were marrying and given in marriage, gameo, ordinary weddings going on right up to the flood.","g":"marry","h":"The picture: the wedding, taking a spouse."},"G1061":{"b":"From the word for a wedding. It means to give a daughter in marriage. Jesus says the children of this age marry and are given in marriage, but not so in the resurrection. The father giving the bride away.","g":"give in marriage","h":"The picture: handing a daughter to a husband."},"G1062":{"b":"Strong's says it means nuptials. Abbott-Smith calls it a wedding, especially the wedding feast. Its origin is uncertain, so no image sits behind it. It simply names the marriage celebration.","flat":1,"g":"wedding, marriage","h":"No picture."},"G1064":{"b":"The plain meaning is the belly. To say a woman is pregnant, Greek says she has in the belly. The same word can name a glutton, a person who is all belly.","g":"belly, womb","h":"The picture: to have someone in the belly."},"G1066":{"b":"The name means feller, a warrior who cuts down. It comes from a word meaning to fell a tree. It fits Gideon, who tore down his father's altar to Baal.","g":"Gideon","h":"The picture: the one who cuts down."},"G1067":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says Gehenna was a real valley outside Jerusalem. It became a dumping-place for the offal of the city, always smoldering. Jesus used that burning rubbish heap as the name for the place of final punishment.","g":"hell, Gehenna","h":"The picture: the city dump on fire."},"G1068":{"b":"The name means oil-press, the place where olives were crushed under stone to squeeze out their oil. It is the garden where Jesus prays in agony, his sweat like drops of blood, pressed down under the weight of what is coming.","g":"Gethsemane","h":"The picture: the press that crushes olives for oil."},"G1069":{"b":"The word grows out of the word for ground, and means a neighbour, the one whose land adjoins your own. The woman who finds her lost coin calls her geiton together to rejoice, the folk next door whose fields and walls meet hers.","g":"neighbour","h":"The picture: the one whose land touches yours."},"G107":{"b":"Azor is a name in Jesus' family line. Strong's says it is of Hebrew origin, brought into Greek. The word points to the man, with nothing to see inside the sound.","flat":1,"g":"Azor","h":"No picture."},"G1070":{"b":"The word simply means to laugh, the laugh of joy or relief. Its beginnings are uncertain, so there is no older word behind it. Jesus promises those who weep now that they will laugh, their grief turned right over into it.","g":"laugh","h":"The picture: a face breaking into laughter."},"G1071":{"b":"This is plain laughter, the laugh of a satisfied man pleased with himself. James says turn it into mourning. The careless laughter of the proud is exactly what ought to break into weeping.","g":"laughter","h":"The picture: the laugh of a self-satisfied man."},"G1072":{"b":"This means to fill or load. Abbott-Smith says it is used properly, of a ship being loaded. The waves filled the boat in the storm. Jesus told the servants to fill the jars with water.","g":"fill, load","h":"The picture: loading a ship."},"G1073":{"b":"Strong's says it means to swell out, to be full. Abbott-Smith notes it was used properly of a ship, loaded down with cargo. To be full is to be packed like a freighter riding low.","g":"be full","h":"The picture: a ship loaded to the brim."},"G1074":{"b":"This is kin from the same root as being born. A genea is a generation, all the people born and living in one stretch of time. So this generation shall not pass sweeps its arm across everyone alive at once, one link in a long family chain.","g":"generation","h":"The picture: everyone alive in one family span."},"G1075":{"b":"This comes from the word for a generation. It means to count back the line of descent, name by name. Melchizedek's line was not counted from Levi, yet he received tithes from Abraham himself.","g":"trace descent","h":"The picture: counting back the generations."},"G1076":{"b":"This word comes from a root meaning to reckon by generations, to trace a family back name by name. It is the pedigree, the list of who fathered whom. Paul warns Timothy off endless genealogies. Long chains of ancestors that lead nowhere.","g":"genealogy","h":"The picture: a family tree traced back."},"G1077":{"b":"Built from genesis, birth, this is the feast held to mark a birthday. In older Greek it marked the dead instead. Here it is Herod's birthday party, the banquet where a girl's dance costs John the Baptist his head.","g":"birthday","h":"The picture: the birthday feast."},"G1078":{"b":"This is the word \"Genesis,\" a nativity, a beginning. \"Book of the genesis of Jesus Christ\" opens Matthew like a family register. James speaks of the wheel of our genesis, the whole course set spinning from birth.","g":"birth, origin","h":"The picture: a birth, a family line."},"G1079":{"b":"From a word for a generation and begetting. Genete means birth, the moment of being born. As Jesus passed by, he saw a man blind from birth, dark from his first day. Not an accident later in life, but from the very start.","g":"birth","h":"The picture: the first day of a life."},"G108":{"b":"The name means ravager, one who lays waste. Azotus is the Greek name for Ashdod, a city of the Philistines in Palestine, where Philip once preached.","g":"Azotus","h":"The picture: ravager."},"G1080":{"b":"Abbott splits it two ways. Of the father, to beget. Of the mother, to bring forth, bear.\n\nOne word for both sides of a birth. It is the word behind being born again.","g":"beget, give birth","h":"The picture: a birth."},"G1081":{"b":"Abbott ties it to γεννάω, to father or bring forth. Strong's: \"offspring. by analogy, produce.\" It is the young that come from parents, or the crop that comes from the ground. John calls his hearers offspring of vipers.","g":"offspring, produce","h":"The picture: what is born from something."},"G1082":{"b":"This is the name of a place, a lake and the green plain beside it on the shore of the Sea of Galilee. It is where they landed the boat. The name points to the spot and holds no picture of its own.","flat":1,"g":"Gennesaret","h":"No picture."},"G1084":{"b":"The root means to beget or bear. This word means born, and Jesus uses it in the phrase born of women, an old way of saying every human being. Jesus says among all born of women none is greater than John. Yet the least in the kingdom is greater still.","g":"born","h":"The picture: everyone a mother ever bore."},"G1085":{"b":"Abbott-Smith traces it to the verb for coming into being and lists three senses. Family. Offspring. Race or nation.\n\nStrong's sums it in one word. Kin. All three senses run back to who your people are.","g":"family, race","h":"The picture: one line of birth."},"G1086":{"b":"This is the name for a person from the region of the Gergesenes, on the east shore of the lake. It is where Jesus met the man full of demons among the tombs. The word only marks the place, and carries no picture.","flat":1,"g":"Gergesene","h":"No picture."},"G1087":{"b":"This word comes from the word for an old man. It means a council of elders, a senate. Luke uses it of the ruling body of Israel called together to face the apostles. The old and weighty men, gathered to judge.","g":"senate","h":"The picture: a room full of grey-bearded elders."},"G1088":{"b":"This word means simply an old man, gray and far along in years. Picture the bent frame and lined face. Nicodemus asked how a man could be born when he is old. Being born from above puzzled him.","g":"old","h":"The picture: the gray old man."},"G1089":{"b":"Strong's says the word means to taste, and figuratively, to experience (good or ill). Picture putting a bite to your lips to know it. The Bible says taste and see that the Lord is good, and speaks of tasting death.","g":"taste","h":"The picture: a taste on the tongue."},"G109":{"b":"Aer is the lower air that surrounds the earth, the air we breathe, set against the pure sky above. Strong's ties it to breathing. Paul speaks of beating the air, punches that hit nothing. We shall be caught up to meet the Lord in the air.","g":"air","h":"The picture: the air you breathe."},"G1090":{"b":"This comes from the word for a farmer, the worker of the soil. It means to till the ground. Land that is worked and drinks the rain brings forth a crop and shares in the blessing.","g":"till the soil","h":"The picture: working the ground like a farmer."},"G1091":{"b":"This comes from a word for a land-worker, a farmer. A georgion is his worked ground, a plowed and planted field. Paul tells the church, you are God's field, ground he tills and grows.","g":"farm, tilled field","h":"The picture: a plowed field."},"G1092":{"b":"Strong's takes it apart. A land-worker, and so a farmer. Abbott-Smith adds a second sense that fits most Gospel uses. A vine-dresser.\n\nThe parables about tenants in the vineyard use this word.","g":"farmer","h":"The picture: the man who works the ground."},"G1093":{"b":"Strong's says only that it is squeezed down from a primary word, and does not say which. Abbott-Smith gives no history. The senses are plain: the earth, dry land, farmed ground, the dirt itself.","flat":1,"g":"earth, land, soil","h":"No picture."},"G1094":{"b":"The word means old age. Luke sets it in a wonder: Elizabeth, called barren, has conceived a son in her old age, for nothing is impossible with God. The age when a womb is closed and hope has gone quiet, and God opens it anyway.","g":"old age","h":"The picture: gray-haired years."},"G1095":{"b":"The root is old age itself. Abbott says \"to grow old.\" Jesus tells Peter that when he grows old he will stretch out his hands and be led where he does not want to go. Hebrews says what grows old is ready to vanish.","g":"grow old","h":"The picture: a body growing old and frail."},"G1096":{"b":"Strong's traces this only to a primary verb, stretched out. Abbott-Smith gives no history at all. It means to come into being, to happen, to be made. Old and plain, with nothing behind it.","flat":1,"g":"become, happen","h":"No picture."},"G1097":{"b":"Abbott-Smith defines it as taking in knowledge, coming to know. Not a fact you already hold.\n\nHis note adds that this is knowing by watching and living through something, unlike the other word for knowing, which is knowing by thinking.","g":"know, come to know","h":"The picture: knowledge arriving a piece at a time."},"G1098":{"b":"This word comes from the word for sweet. It means new wine, the sweet fresh juice of the grape, which could still make a man drunk. The Pentecost mockers used it: these men are full of new wine. Sweet on the tongue, strong in the head.","g":"new wine","h":"The picture: fresh, sweet wine from the press."},"G1099":{"b":"The word means sweet, set against bitter or salt. James asks whether a spring pours sweet water and bitter from the same opening. In Revelation the little scroll is sweet as honey in the mouth. A plain taste.","g":"sweet","h":"The picture: sweet water on the tongue."},"G11":{"b":"The name means father of a multitude. God changed it from Abram, adding a nation to it. In Genesis 17 he is promised descendants beyond counting, and the new name carries the promise.","g":"Abraham","h":"The picture: father of a multitude."},"G110":{"b":"The roots are a, not, and thanatos, death. So the word is no-death, life that death cannot touch. Paul uses it for the resurrection, this mortal must put on immortality, the dying body clothed in a life death has no hold on.","g":"immortality","h":"The picture: death cannot touch it."},"G1100":{"b":"One word for the flesh behind your teeth and for a language.\n\nStrong's puts it plainly: the tongue, and by implication a language. Abbott-Smith adds a third use, for anything shaped like a tongue.","g":"tongue, language","h":"The picture: the tongue in your mouth."},"G1101":{"b":"Strong's says this was \"a case to keep mouthpieces of wind-instruments in.\" A box first made for the reeds of flutes came to mean any small chest, then the money box. Judas carried this bag for the group, and helped himself to what was put in it.","g":"money bag, box","h":"The picture: a case for the reeds of pipes, used as a cashbox."},"G1102":{"b":"A fuller was the worker who cleaned, thickened, and bleached wool cloth. The root means to card wool, combing it out. In Mark 9:3 Jesus' garments shine whiter than any fuller on earth could ever make them.","g":"fuller, launderer","h":"The picture: the launderer who whitens cloth."},"G1103":{"b":"Strong's says this word means legitimate, of birth, genuine. It pictures a true-born child, lawfully begotten, not a pretender slipped in. From birth it moved to mean real and sincere. Paul calls Timothy his true child in the faith.","g":"genuine, true","h":"The picture: a true-born child."},"G1104":{"b":"This comes from a word for legitimate birth, a real child and not a pretender. It means genuinely, from the heart. Paul says Timothy will genuinely care for their welfare, like true-born family.","g":"genuinely","h":"The picture: a true-born child, not a pretender."},"G1105":{"b":"This is the black of a storm, the gloom that rolls in with the tempest. It is kin to the word for cloud. Hebrews sets it at Sinai, the mountain wrapped in darkness when God came down on it.","g":"blackness","h":"The picture: the black of a storm."},"G1106":{"b":"Abbott traces this to the mind, its operations and results. The root is the verb to know. So this is knowing hardened into a settled view, a judgment. Paul gives his considered mind on a matter.","g":"opinion, mind","h":"The picture: the mind made up."},"G1107":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the usual older sense was to come to know, discover, know. In the New Testament it flips. Now it means to make known.\n\nThe knowing does not stop with you. It gets passed on.","g":"make known","h":"The picture: handing over what you know."},"G1108":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is a seeking to know, inquiry, investigation. Knowledge is where the looking ends up.\n\nSo this is not a stock of facts sitting on a shelf. It began as the search that gets you there.","g":"knowledge","h":"The picture: looking into something."},"G1109":{"b":"The root is the common word to know. This is one who knows, an expert. Paul says it to Agrippa: I am glad, because you are an expert in all the customs of the Jews. Not a dabbler but someone who knows the subject cold.","g":"expert","h":"The picture: the one who really knows."},"G111":{"b":"The root, themis, means the custom, the thing laid down as right, and the piece in front cancels it. So athemitos is what breaks the settled rule. Peter says it is athemitos for a Jew to enter a foreigner's house. Then God tells him to go in.","g":"unlawful","h":"The picture: crossing a line laid down as right."},"G1110":{"b":"The root is the verb to know. Gnōstos means known. In the plural Abbott notes it means acquaintances, the people whose faces you know. And in Acts the healing was gnōston, known to all Jerusalem, a fact too public to deny.","g":"known","h":"The picture: the faces you know."},"G1111":{"b":"Abbott: \"to mutter, murmur.\" It is the low, under-the-breath complaining of people who are unhappy but will not speak out plainly. In the parable the workers grumble against the owner over their pay.","g":"murmur, grumble","h":"The picture: low muttering under the breath."},"G1112":{"b":"Say the word aloud and you hear it, gong-goos-mos, a low muttering under the breath. Strong's: \"a grumbling.\" It is the sound of a crowd complaining just below open speech. Israel did it in the desert. Do all things without it.","g":"murmuring","h":"The picture: the low mutter of a crowd."},"G1113":{"b":"The root means to grumble, a word that sounds like the low muttering it names. So this is a murmurer, one who mutters under his breath. Jude lists these as grumblers and fault-finders who follow their own lusts.","g":"grumbler","h":"The picture: the low mutter of a grumbler."},"G1114":{"b":"Strong's traces this to a word meaning to wail. It first meant a wizard, the kind who mutters and chants spells. From there it came to mean a fraud. Paul says evil men and impostors grow worse. The old picture is a muttering sorcerer.","g":"seducer","h":"The picture: a wizard muttering spells."},"G1115":{"b":"The name means \"the skull.\" It was a low hill outside Jerusalem, likely shaped like a skull, where Jesus was crucified. The Latin for it gives us Calvary. The place of execution was named for the bare rounded rock that looked like a head.","g":"Golgotha","h":"The picture: a skull-shaped hill."},"G1116":{"b":"The name means a ruined heap. Behind it stands a word for gathering grain. Gomorrah was the city near the Dead Sea destroyed alongside Sodom for its wickedness.","g":"Gomorrah","h":"The picture: a ruined heap."},"G1117":{"b":"This word comes from a word meaning to swell out, to be full. Gomos is the load a ship is stuffed with, its cargo. Paul's ship carried it. Revelation lists the merchandise no buyer will take anymore.","g":"cargo","h":"The picture: a ship swollen full with cargo."},"G1118":{"b":"Abbott-Smith traces it to the verb for coming into being. His first gloss is a begetter, a father.\n\nIn practice it is nearly always plural. Parents. The word names them by what they did.","g":"parent","h":"The picture: the one who brought you into being."},"G1119":{"b":"This word just means the knee. Strong's says its origin is of uncertain affinity, so no one knows where it comes from. There is nothing behind it, only the joint people bend to kneel.","flat":1,"g":"knee","h":"No picture."},"G112":{"b":"The word is theós, God, with the not in front, the very root of our word atheist. Paul says the nations once stood without God, not knowing God in the world, no hope, no covenant. An empty place where God should be.","g":"without God","h":"The picture: no God in the picture."},"G1120":{"b":"Two words make this one, knee and fall. It means to drop, knees hitting the ground, in front of someone. That is how the desperate father comes to Jesus, not standing to ask but falling on the knee before him.","g":"kneel down","h":"The picture: dropping down onto the knees."},"G1121":{"b":"Abbott says the word means that which is traced or drawn. A letter is a mark cut or scratched onto a surface. From there it covers a bill, a book, and learning.","g":"letter, writing","h":"The picture: a mark scratched down."},"G1122":{"b":"Strong's says it means a writer, and by profession a scribe or secretary. Abbott traces it to the word for a letter of the alphabet.\n\nIn the Gospels the clerk has become the Bible scholar.","g":"scribe","h":"The picture: a man with a pen."},"G1123":{"b":"The root means to grave, to write. This is the word for something written. Abbott's other sense even carries painted. Paul says the work of the law is written on the heart, cut in where it can be read.","g":"written","h":"The picture: letters cut into the surface."},"G1124":{"b":"The word comes from the verb to write. But the very first thing Abbott-Smith lists for it is a drawing, painting.\n\nBefore Scripture meant a holy book, the word meant marks made by hand.","g":"scripture, writing","h":"The picture: a drawing."},"G1125":{"b":"Strong's says the word means to grave, and then to write. Abbott-Smith gives the older sense: to scrape or graze, later to sketch and draw.\n\nWriting began as cutting. Something scratched in stays there.","g":"write","h":"The picture: scratching a mark into a surface."},"G1126":{"b":"This joins graus, an old woman, and eidos, the look of a thing. So it means having the shape of an old woman's story, silly gossip. Paul tells Timothy to refuse profane and old wives' fables and train himself for godliness.","g":"old wives'","h":"The picture: an old woman's tale."},"G1127":{"b":"Strong's gives the plain action. To keep awake, and so to watch.\n\nAbbott-Smith adds that it can mean simply being awake. Most New Testament uses are the figure. Watchfulness is refusing to fall asleep.","g":"stay awake, watch","h":"The picture: staying awake."},"G1128":{"b":"The root is the word for naked. Greek athletes trained and competed with nothing on, and their training is this word. So it means to train hard, like an athlete. Train yourself for godliness, Paul tells Timothy.","g":"to train","h":"The picture: the naked athlete in the arena."},"G1129":{"b":"The root means to train naked, the way athletes stripped down to exercise in the Greek games. Paul says bodily exercise profits a little, but godliness is profitable for all things.","g":"exercise","h":"The picture: athletes training stripped for the games."},"G113":{"b":"Abbott traces this to a word meaning law or custom, with the not set in front. It marks those who trample the law of nature and conscience. Lot was worn down living among the athesmos, the lawless of Sodom, Second Peter 2:7.","g":"lawless, wicked","h":"The picture: trampling the settled law."},"G1130":{"b":"This grows from a word meaning nude, bare. It means to go naked or barely clothed. It pictures a body with little covering, exposed to the cold. Paul names it among his hardships, hunger and nakedness.","g":"be naked","h":"The picture: a body with no covering."},"G1131":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means naked, without clothing. Strong's says its origin is uncertain. It simply means bare, with no covering. There is nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"naked","h":"No picture."},"G1132":{"b":"The root gymnos means naked, a body with nothing on it. Gymnotes is that bareness. Paul lists it among his hardships, cold and hunger and nakedness, and Christ offers to clothe the naked in Revelation.","g":"nakedness","h":"The picture: a bare body."},"G1133":{"b":"This is the word for a woman shrunk down by its ending, a 'little woman'. The small form is meant with contempt. Paul uses it for weak women loaded with sins, whom false teachers creep in to capture. The word itself belittles them.","g":"silly woman","h":"The picture: the word for woman made small."},"G1134":{"b":"This adjective is built straight from the root G1135, a woman and specially a wife. Abbott sums it up as female. Peter uses it of the wife as the weaker vessel, calling husbands to give her honor.","g":"feminine, wife","h":"The picture: the word for wife itself."},"G1135":{"b":"Strong's gives a woman, specially a wife. Abbott adds that as a form of address gyne carries respect and endearment, the way Jesus speaks to his own mother. So the one word covers every woman and narrows to the one a man calls wife.","g":"woman, wife","h":"The picture: the woman, the wife."},"G1136":{"b":"Gog is a name, taken from Hebrew. Revelation pairs it with Magog for the nations that make war at the end. As a bare name it points to no thing you can see.","flat":1,"g":"Gog","h":"No picture."},"G1137":{"b":"Abbott-Smith links this word to the knee. A corner is a bend, an angle, like a knee folded. It is the word in the stone the builders rejected has become the head of the corner.","g":"corner, angle","h":"The picture: the bend of a knee."},"G1138":{"b":"The name means loving, or beloved. It comes from a word meaning to love. David was the shepherd boy who became Israel's great king and a man after God's own heart.","g":"David","h":"The picture: loving."},"G1139":{"b":"Abbott's sense is to be under the power of a demon, to be possessed. The word paints a person no longer their own, driven by something inside. The Gospels are full of them, the man in the tombs, the boy by the fire, freed at a word.","g":"to be possessed","h":"The picture: a person no longer their own."},"G114":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the word means to do away with what has been laid down. Something was firmly set. This word un-sets it. It treats a law, a promise, or a person as if it were never put there.","g":"reject, set aside","h":"The picture: canceling what was set in place."},"G1140":{"b":"Abbott says the word first meant divine power. Then an inferior divinity, deity or demon.\n\nIt started out neutral, even lofty. The New Testament keeps only the low end of it.","g":"demon","h":"The picture: a lesser god."},"G1141":{"b":"The word means demon-like, shaped after an evil spirit. James says the wisdom that runs on envy and rivalry does not come down from heaven. It is earthly, and worse, it belongs to the demons.","g":"devilish","h":"The picture: shaped after an evil spirit."},"G1142":{"b":"This is a demon, an evil spirit. Strong's ties the name to a word for handing out fortunes. A spirit has no shape to see. The demons begged Jesus to send them into the herd of swine.","flat":1,"g":"demon","h":"No picture."},"G1143":{"b":"Both lexicons give the plain word, to bite. Paul warns that if they keep biting and devouring one another, they will be eaten up, a pack turning its teeth on itself until nothing is left.","g":"bite","h":"The picture: teeth sinking into flesh."},"G1144":{"b":"Strong's calls it of uncertain affinity. The word simply means a tear, the kind that runs down a face when someone weeps. Nothing hidden sits behind it, only the tear.","flat":1,"g":"a tear","h":"No picture."},"G1145":{"b":"This word comes straight from the word for a tear. It is the word for the shortest verse: Jesus wept. The lexicon sets it apart from crying out loud. Not wailing. Just tears sliding down a face.","g":"to shed tears","h":"The picture: a single tear running down."},"G1146":{"b":"This word comes from the word for a finger. Abbott-Smith gives it as a finger-ring. When the lost son came home, the father did not scold him. He called for the best robe, a ring for his hand, and sandals for his feet.","g":"ring","h":"The picture: a ring for the finger."},"G1147":{"b":"This word simply means a finger. If I cast out demons by the finger of God, Jesus says. They lay heavy loads on others but will not lift a finger to help. Jesus wrote in the dust with his. The one digit that points, or works, or refuses.","g":"finger","h":"The picture: the single finger of the hand."},"G1148":{"b":"This is a place name, Dalmanutha, a spot near the Sea of Galilee that no one can now locate. The sources give no meaning for it. In Mark 8:10 Jesus and the disciples get into the boat and come to its region. It is only a name.","flat":1,"g":"Dalmanutha","h":"No picture."},"G1149":{"b":"Dalmatia is a place, a region on the coast of the Adriatic. Strong's says the name is probably of foreign origin. There is nothing behind it to picture. It is simply where Titus had gone.","flat":1,"g":"Dalmatia","h":"No picture."},"G115":{"b":"The root means to set aside, to cancel. This is a disannulling, a rule lifted off the books and put away. Hebrews says the former commandment was set aside for something better. And Christ appeared to put away sin. The old order taken down.","g":"annulling, setting aside","h":"The picture: a rule taken off the books."},"G1150":{"b":"This word means to tame, to subdue a wild thing until it obeys. Every kind of beast can be tamed by man, James says. But not the tongue. No one can damazo that. The wildest animal of all sits in your mouth.","g":"tame","h":"The picture: breaking a wild animal to the hand."},"G1151":{"b":"This is a heifer, a young cow, named from the word to tame. The ashes of a red heifer, burned outside the camp, were sprinkled on the unclean to make them ceremonially clean.","g":"heifer","h":"The picture: a young tamed cow."},"G1152":{"b":"Abbott ties the name to damar, a poet's word for a wife, and Strong's guesses it means gentle. Damaris appears once, among the few at Athens who heard Paul and believed, named beside Dionysius. A woman remembered for saying yes when most sneered.","g":"Damaris","h":"The picture: the name that means wife."},"G1153":{"b":"The word means someone of Damascus, Damascene, the old Syrian city. Paul recalls it among his dangers: in Damascus the governor set a guard on the gates to seize me, and I was lowered through a window in a basket. A city that nearly caught him.","g":"Damascene","h":"The picture: the man from Damascus."},"G1154":{"b":"The origin of this name is foreign, and no clear meaning can be recovered. Damascus was a major city of Syria, the place where Saul was struck down and converted.","flat":1,"g":"Damascus","h":"No picture."},"G1155":{"b":"The root is a loan. This verb means to lend money on interest, and in the middle voice, to borrow. Jesus says lend expecting nothing back, unlike the ordinary loan handed over to be repaid with more. Coins go out, meant to return larger.","g":"lend, borrow","h":"The picture: money handed over at interest."},"G1156":{"b":"This word means a loan. Strong's ties it to the idea of a gift given. A loan is money handed to you that is not yours to keep. In Matthew 18:27 a servant owes a loan he can never repay, and the king wipes it out.","g":"loan, debt","h":"The picture: money placed in your hands to pay back."},"G1157":{"b":"This word comes from the word to loan at interest. Abbott-Smith gives it as a money-lender. In Jesus' story, one man owed him a huge sum and another a small one. He forgave both, and the one let off the larger debt loves him more.","g":"creditor","h":"The picture: the moneylender who holds your debt."},"G1158":{"b":"The name means judge of God, or God is my judge. It joins a word for judging with a word for God. Daniel stood before kings and read the writing on the wall.","g":"Daniel","h":"The picture: God is my judge."},"G1159":{"b":"The root means expense, money seen as something consumed. To spend here is to use up until nothing is left. The prodigal son spent everything he had, ate it all, and then a famine came. Consumed to the last coin.","g":"spend, waste","h":"The picture: money eaten up."},"G116":{"b":"This is Athens, named for the goddess of wisdom said to have founded it. Abbott notes the plural form, because the city was made of several parts. Paul stood here among the idols and philosophers. A city name, nothing to picture.","flat":1,"g":"Athens","h":"No picture."},"G1160":{"b":"This word comes from a word meaning to devour. It means expense, cost, what a thing eats up. Which of you, wanting to build a tower, does not first sit down and count the cost. A cost is a sum, not a thing to see.","flat":1,"g":"cost","h":"No picture."},"G1162":{"b":"The root means to beg, binding yourself to the one you ask. A deesis is a petition that rises out of need, the cry of someone who lacks. So Abbott notes deesis gives prominence to the sense of need. It is prayer with empty hands held out.","g":"petition, prayer","h":"The picture: the empty-handed plea of one in need."},"G1163":{"b":"Strong's connects it to a verb for binding and calls it necessary as binding. Abbott points to the same root but does not explain it.\n\nAbbott adds that it is logical necessity. Not a moral duty. Just how things must go.","g":"must, it is necessary","h":"The picture: being tied to it."},"G1164":{"b":"The root means to show. So this is a thing shown, a specimen, here a warning put on display. Jude says Sodom and Gomorrah are set out as an example, suffering the punishment of eternal fire.","g":"example","h":"The picture: a sample held up for all to see."},"G1165":{"b":"The root is a specimen, a sample held up to be seen. This word means to make a show of someone, to put them on display. Paul says Christ did this to the powers of evil at the cross. He stripped them and marched them out in the open, beaten, for all to see.","g":"to make a show of","h":"The picture: held up in front of the crowd."},"G1166":{"b":"Strong's says this is a longer form of an older verb that meant the same thing. Nothing was added, and nothing lies underneath.\n\nAbbott gives only to show, exhibit, and to make known. A plain word for pointing something out.","flat":1,"g":"show","h":"No picture."},"G1167":{"b":"This means cowardice, and the sources say never in a good sense. It comes from a word for timid. Picture a man cringing back from danger, small and afraid. Paul says God gave us not this spirit of fear, but of power.","g":"fear, timidity","h":"The picture: shrinking back in fear."},"G1168":{"b":"The root is timidity, cowardice. To do this is to lose your nerve, to be cowardly, timid, fearful. Jesus says it the night before he dies: let not your hearts be troubled, neither let them be afraid. He hands them peace where fear would rush in.","g":"be afraid","h":"The picture: the shrinking heart."},"G1169":{"b":"This word means cowardly, afraid. Abbott traces it to a word for dread. There is no thing to see here, only the feeling itself, the fear that makes a person shrink back when trouble comes.","flat":1,"g":"fearful","h":"No picture."},"G117":{"b":"A person of Athens, the capital of Greece. Picture the Athenians on Mars Hill, who Luke says spent their days doing nothing but telling or hearing some new thing, Acts 17:21. Clever, curious, and now standing before Paul.","g":"Athenian","h":"The picture: the crowd on Mars Hill."},"G1170":{"b":"The word stands in for a name you cannot or will not say, such an one, a certain one. Jesus uses it sending the disciples for the Passover: go into the city to a certain man and tell him the Teacher's time is near. A blank left blank.","g":"such a man","h":"The picture: the man left unnamed."},"G1171":{"b":"Abbott traces this to a word for dread. It means terribly, dreadfully. The centurion says his servant lies at home deinos tormented, in fearful pain, Matthew 8:6. Later the scribes press Jesus deinos, fiercely, trying to trap Him in His words.","g":"grievously, vehemently","h":"The picture: terribly, dreadfully."},"G1172":{"b":"This comes from deipnon, \"the chief meal (usually in the evening).\" Not a snack. The main meal after the work is done, when people sit down together. So when Jesus says he will come in and sup with a man, he means that table.","g":"sup, dine","h":"The picture: the big meal at the end of the day."},"G1173":{"b":"Abbott calls it the chief meal of the day, dinner, supper, the big evening meal where people leaned back and lingered. Jesus turns it into a picture of the kingdom, the great banquet, the marriage supper of the Lamb at the end.","g":"supper","h":"The picture: the big evening meal."},"G1174":{"b":"The word joins two ideas, to fear and the deity. It paints someone who dreads the unseen powers and works to keep them happy. Paul told the Athenians they were very careful about their gods.","g":"very religious","h":"The picture: a man afraid of the gods."},"G1175":{"b":"Abbott traces this to fear of the gods. The word can mean religion or superstition, but under it is the dread of unseen powers. Festus says the Jews argued with Paul over their own such matters. The picture is a person shrinking before the gods.","g":"religion","h":"The picture: a man in dread of the gods."},"G1176":{"b":"Strong's calls this a primary number, which means it is not built from anything else. It is just ten. There is nothing behind it to look at.","flat":1,"g":"ten","h":"No picture."},"G1178":{"b":"Ten and five. John notes that Bethany lay about fifteen stadia from Jerusalem, John 11:18, close enough that the mourners had walked out to Martha and Mary. The small number sets the short distance that grief had to travel.","g":"fifteen","h":"The picture: ten and five."},"G1179":{"b":"The name is two words joined: ten, and city. The Decapolis was a league of ten cities east of the Jordan. So the place name simply counts itself, ten towns named as one. Crowds from there followed Jesus.","g":"Decapolis","h":"The picture: ten cities together."},"G118":{"b":"This is the word for competing in the games, wrestling and fighting for the prize. The root is a contest, in war or in sport. Paul says no athlete is crowned unless he competes by the rules. The prize goes to the one who actually enters the ring.","g":"compete, contend","h":"The picture: the wrestler in the arena."},"G1180":{"b":"The Greek has no single word for fourteen. It stacks two numbers, ten and four. Picture counting all ten fingers, then four more on the next hand. That is how this number is built up in speech, one count laid on another.","g":"fourteen","h":"The picture: ten fingers, then four more."},"G1181":{"b":"The word means a tenth, from the word for tenth. It is the tithe, one portion out of every ten, counted off and given. Abraham gave Melchizedek a tenth of everything, the writer notes, honoring him with it.","g":"a tithe","h":"The picture: one part in ten set aside."},"G1182":{"b":"This word just means tenth, the ordinary number, built from the word for ten. It was about the tenth hour when the first disciples came to Jesus. A number has no image behind it, only its place in the count.","flat":1,"g":"tenth","h":"No picture."},"G1183":{"b":"The root is a tenth. This word is to take or pay the tithe, to hand over one part in ten. Hebrews says Abraham gave Melchizedek a tenth of the spoils. Count out ten, and give one away. The tithe made concrete.","g":"tithe","h":"The picture: one part in ten set aside."},"G1184":{"b":"The root means to receive, to take with open hands. Something acceptable is what you gladly receive, not push away. Jesus proclaimed the acceptable year of the Lord, the welcome time. Taken in, not turned back.","g":"acceptable","h":"The picture: taken gladly with both hands."},"G1185":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this word comes from the word for a bait. It means to lure with bait, the way you hide a hook inside something a fish wants. Peter says false teachers do this, baiting people with promises. The catch is hidden until it is too late.","g":"to entice","h":"The picture: bait on a hook."},"G1186":{"b":"Strong's guesses it comes probably from a word for an oak, but does not name that word. Abbott-Smith gives no origin. So there is no picture we can stand on.","flat":1,"g":"tree","h":"No picture."},"G1187":{"b":"This is built from the right hand and a word for taking or throwing. It names a soldier who holds his weapon in his right hand, a spearman or guard. The commander sends two hundred of them with Paul. The word points to the fighting hand.","g":"spearman","h":"The picture: a weapon gripped in the right hand."},"G1188":{"b":"Strong's links this word to the verb to receive. The right hand is the one that usually takes.\n\nAbbott-Smith adds that giving someone your right hand meant friendship, and that the right side was the place of honour.","g":"right hand","h":"The picture: the hand that takes."},"G1189":{"b":"Strong's says the word means to beg as if binding oneself. Abbott links it to the word \"bind.\" You tie yourself to the person, holding on in your need. It is a word for earnest prayer.","g":"beg, pray","h":"The picture: binding yourself to the one you beg."},"G119":{"b":"The root means to compete in the games. This is the athlete's hard contest in the arena. After they were enlightened, the readers endured a great struggle of sufferings, and did not give up.","g":"struggle, fight","h":"The picture: the athlete in the contest."},"G1190":{"b":"The word means someone of Derbe, a town in Asia Minor. Luke uses it naming Paul's traveling companions, Gaius of Derbe and Timothy among them. A small-town label that quietly records where one of the church's helpers first came from.","g":"of Derbe","h":"The picture: the man from Derbe."},"G1191":{"b":"This is the name of a city in Asia Minor. It came into Greek from some foreign tongue. A place on the map, with no picture inside the word itself for us to see.","flat":1,"g":"Derbe","h":"No picture."},"G1192":{"b":"The root means to flay, to strip the skin off. This is the hide of a beast. The persecuted covered themselves in skins for lack of proper clothing, wandering in deserts and mountains and caves.","g":"skin, hide","h":"The picture: the flayed hide of a beast."},"G1193":{"b":"The root is a hide, an animal's skin. This word means made of that, leather. John the Baptist wore a leather belt around his waist. Rough animal skin, not fine cloth. The clothes told you what kind of man he was.","g":"leathern","h":"The picture: a belt of animal hide."},"G1194":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the first sense is to skin, flay. From taking the hide off an animal, the word came to mean to beat a person hard. In our own slang we still say tan his hide. That is this word.","g":"beat, thrash","h":"The picture: skinning a hide."},"G1195":{"b":"The word comes from a chain or bond. It means to bind, to chain a prisoner or tie a load into a bundle. Jesus says the scribes bind heavy burdens and lay them on other men's shoulders. They rope the loads and make others carry them.","g":"bind","h":"The picture: tying a heavy load into a bundle."},"G1197":{"b":"This is a bundle, a batch of things tied together. Jesus says gather the weeds and bind them in bundles to be burned. Picture stalks gathered and roped tight into a sheaf.","g":"a bundle","h":"The picture: stalks bound into a sheaf."},"G1198":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means bound, captive. The word is built on the word for a chain or bond. The prisoner is simply the one who is tied. Paul calls himself this, bound for Christ.","g":"prisoner","h":"The picture: the man in chains."},"G1199":{"b":"Abbott-Smith traces it to the verb for binding. Strong's names two everyday things it covers. A ligament in the body and a shackle on a prisoner.\n\nMark uses it of a man's tongue being untied.","g":"bond, chain","h":"The picture: something tied around."},"G12":{"b":"Built from not and a word for depth or bottom. Abbott-Smith gives boundless, bottomless. It pictures a place with no floor. It names the deep, and the pit where the demons are held.","g":"abyss, bottomless pit","h":"The picture: a pit with no floor."},"G120":{"b":"Thymos is passion, named as if from breathing hard. The a in front takes it away. So this is the breath gone, the fire cooled, the heart sunk. Paul warns fathers not to provoke their children, lest they be disheartened like this.","g":"be disheartened","h":"The picture: the wind knocked out of you."},"G1200":{"b":"This word is built from a word for the shackle of a prisoner and the word for a guard. The keeper of the chains. The Philippian jailer woke, saw the doors open, thought his prisoners fled, and drew his sword.","g":"jailer","h":"The picture: the keeper of the shackles."},"G1201":{"b":"The root is a shackle, the band on a prisoner. This is the place full of them, a prison, a dungeon. John the Baptist heard in prison what Christ was doing and sent word from behind those walls. The word underneath is chains.","g":"prison","h":"The picture: a dungeon of chains."},"G1202":{"b":"This is built from the word for a place of bondage, a dungeon. Under it lies the idea of being bound. A prisoner is one held in chains. Paul was handed over as a captive to sail under guard for Rome.","g":"prisoner","h":"The picture: a man in chains."},"G1203":{"b":"Thayer says this word denoted absolute ownership and uncontrolled power. It is the master set over against a slave. So this is not a boss with limits. It is the one who owns you outright, correlative of the servant.","g":"master","h":"The picture: the owner who answers to no one."},"G1204":{"b":"This means here, and as a command, come here. Jesus says it to the rich young ruler: come, follow me. Strong's calls it of uncertain affinity, so there is no picture behind it.","flat":1,"g":"come here","h":"No picture."},"G1205":{"b":"The root means hither, here, and deute is the shout, come on, come here, come. It is the beckoning hand, the summons to move now. Come to me, Jesus calls, all you who are weary. And at the end, Come, you blessed of my Father.","g":"come","h":"The picture: the beckoning hand."},"G1206":{"b":"The word means on the second day. Luke uses it on the last leg of Paul's voyage: a south wind sprang up, and on the second day they reached Puteoli. It measures a journey by when you land, the day the traveler steps ashore.","g":"next day","h":"The picture: arriving on day two."},"G1208":{"b":"This grows from duo, two. Deuteros is the second in order, the next one after the first. So the second commandment is like the first, and the second death waits past the first. The word counts them off, one then the next.","g":"second","h":"The picture: the second in line."},"G1209":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's examples are hands doing something: taking a cup, taking a letter, taking a child into the arms. It is the word for accepting what is offered.\n\nThe same word covers welcoming a person into your house.","g":"receive, accept","h":"The picture: open hands."},"G121":{"b":"This puts \"not\" before a word for a penalty. Athoos means free of penalty, with nothing to pay. Pilate washes his hands and says he is innocent of this man's blood, trying to leave the price with someone else.","g":"innocent","h":"The picture: no penalty to pay."},"G1210":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is to tie, bind, fasten. His examples are plain: a donkey tied up, a dead body wrapped in cloth, a prisoner in chains.\n\nThat is the word behind binding and loosing.","g":"bind, tie","h":"The picture: rope work."},"G1212":{"b":"The first sense of this word is visible, out where it can be seen. Then clear to the mind, obvious. In the courtyard they tell Peter, your accent makes it plain you are one of them. What he tried to hide stood out in the open.","g":"clear","h":"The picture: out in plain sight."},"G1213":{"b":"The root simply means clear. To make plain, to show, to declare. Paul says the Day will make each man's work plain, revealed by fire. Bringing a hidden thing out where the mind can see it.","g":"make plain","h":"The picture: bringing it into the clear."},"G1214":{"b":"A short form of Demetrius. Abbott names him a companion of Paul. Picture the sad line, Demas, in love with this present world, has deserted me and gone to Thessalonica, Second Timothy 4:10. Once a fellow worker, then simply gone.","g":"Demas","h":"The picture: the fellow worker who left."},"G1215":{"b":"The word joins 'the people' with the town-square where they gathered. It means to make a public speech. Herod, robed and shining, delivers an oration to the crowd, who shout that he is a god.","g":"make an oration","h":"The picture: addressing the crowd in the square."},"G1216":{"b":"This is the name of the Ephesian silversmith, tied to the old goddess Demeter. A name resting on a person, with no picture inside the word itself for us to see.","flat":1,"g":"Demetrius","h":"No picture."},"G1217":{"b":"Two words join here, people and work: one who works for the public. It came to mean the maker of the world. Abraham looked for a city whose designer and builder is God himself.","g":"maker, builder","h":"The picture: the master builder at work."},"G1218":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning \"to bind (in various applications.\" The demos is the people tied together into one body, the citizens gathered as a whole, not a loose crowd. When the mob at Ephesus surges into the theatre, Paul wants to face this assembled people.","g":"people","h":"The picture: a crowd tied together into one body."},"G1219":{"b":"This comes from demos, \"the public (as bound together socially),\" the people gathered as one. It means belonging to the people, and so, done out in the open before everyone. Paul was beaten publicly, in full view, not in some back room.","g":"public, openly","h":"The picture: out in the open before everyone."},"G122":{"b":"This comes from the word for a goat. It describes the goatskins the destitute wrapped around themselves. They wandered in sheepskins and goatskins, homeless and hunted, though the world was not worthy of them.","g":"of a goat","h":"The picture: rough goatskin worn for clothing."},"G1220":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it is a Roman coin. Strong's says the name is borrowed from Latin. It is a piece of money worth about a day's wage. Just a coin, with no image behind the word.","flat":1,"g":"denarius, penny","h":"No picture."},"G1224":{"b":"The word is built on a stride, a pace of the foot, with a piece meaning through. It means to step across. By faith Israel crossed the Red Sea on dry land. In the parable a great gulf is fixed that no one can cross over.","g":"cross over","h":"The picture: stepping across to the other side."},"G1225":{"b":"Abbott says the word first meant to throw across. You fling something at a person from a distance. So to slander is to hurl a charge at someone behind his back. The steward had accusations thrown across at him.","g":"slander, accuse","h":"The picture: a charge thrown across at a man."},"G1226":{"b":"This word is built on a root meaning to make firm and steady, like solid footing. To affirm this way is to plant your words down hard and stand on them. Paul wants Timothy to insist on these things. Said with both feet firmly set.","g":"affirm firmly","h":"The picture: both feet planted firm."},"G1227":{"b":"The roots are \"through\" and \"to look.\" This word is to look right through, to see clearly. First take the plank out of your own eye, Jesus says, and then you will see clearly to take the speck from your brother's.","g":"see clearly","h":"The picture: eyes clearing to see straight through."},"G1228":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is slanderous, accusing falsely. As a noun, a slanderer, false accuser.\n\nThe word for the devil is an ordinary word for a gossip. Abbott lists it used of people, not the devil, in 1 Timothy 3.","g":"devil, slanderer","h":"The picture: the man who spreads the rumor."},"G1229":{"b":"The word is built on messenger, with a piece meaning through. It means to publish abroad, to proclaim everywhere. Jesus tells the healed man to go and spread the news of the kingdom. Carrying word through the whole place, street by street.","g":"declare, proclaim","h":"The picture: a herald crying the news through town."},"G123":{"b":"An aigialos is the beach, the strip of sand where the waves break. The crowd stood on it while Jesus taught from a boat offshore. At dawn he stood on the shore and they did not know him. Where the sea meets the land.","g":"shore","h":"The picture: the beach where waves break."},"G1230":{"b":"The word joins through and become. Of time it means to pass, to elapse. When the Sabbath was past, the women bring their spices. It is the plain sense of time going through, one day after the next slipping by.","g":"elapse, pass","h":"The picture: days going by one after another."},"G1231":{"b":"Built from a word for through and a word for knowing. To know a thing all the way through, not just its surface. As a court term it means to settle a case by knowing it fully. Not a guess, but a thorough knowing.","g":"determine","h":"The picture: seeing all the way through."},"G1233":{"b":"This is where our word diagnosis comes from. The root means to know a thing thoroughly, to tell it apart from the rest. As a legal term it is the ruling that settles a case. Festus holds Paul until the Emperor's decision, the knowing-through that ends it.","g":"examination","h":"The picture: a doctor telling one symptom from another."},"G1234":{"b":"The root word sounds like what it means, a low grumble. With \"through\" added it is the mutter passing from mouth to mouth. Abbott says \"to murmur or mutter among themselves.\" The crowd grumbles that Jesus eats with sinners.","g":"murmur, grumble","h":"The picture: a grumble spreading through the crowd."},"G1235":{"b":"This word joins through and to keep awake. Abbott-Smith gives it as to be fully awake. Peter and the others were heavy with sleep on the mountain. When they came fully awake, they saw Jesus shining and two men standing with him.","g":"be awake","h":"The picture: forcing your eyes open all the way."},"G1236":{"b":"This word joins through and to lead. It means to lead your life across the years, to pass the time from one end to the other. Paul prays we may pass a quiet and peaceable life. Days led through, from start to finish.","g":"live, pass time","h":"The picture: leading your days across."},"G1237":{"b":"The word joins 'through' with 'to receive.' It means to receive in turn, one hand passing to the next. In Acts the fathers pass the tent of worship to the next generation, who take it up in their turn.","g":"succeed to","h":"The picture: a thing handed down the line."},"G1238":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this comes from a word meaning to bind round. A diadem is the band tied around a Persian king's head, the badge of a ruler. Revelation puts many of these on the dragon and on Christ. Not a prize won but a crown of rule. It says who reigns.","g":"a diadem, crown","h":"The picture: the royal band tied around the head."},"G1239":{"b":"The word is \"give\" with \"through\" on it, to give out right through a crowd, dealing to each. Jesus takes the loaves and diadidomi them, passing bread through the whole seated multitude. Sell what you have, he tells the ruler, and distribute it.","g":"distribute","h":"The picture: handing bread out through a crowd."},"G124":{"b":"This means an Egyptian, someone from Egypt, the land of the Nile. It only marks where a person is from. Moses was learned in all the wisdom of the Egyptians. A great river and the country along it.","g":"Egyptian","h":"The picture: a person of the Nile land."},"G1240":{"b":"The root means to receive in turn, to take over from another. A successor is the next man who takes the office as it is passed to him. Festus comes in and Felix hands the post over. The word is the handover, one taking up what the other sets down.","g":"successor","h":"The picture: one runner handing the baton to the next."},"G1241":{"b":"This word is built from a word for across and a word meaning to bind with a belt. To wrap a belt tight around yourself. Jesus did this before washing feet, tying a towel around his waist.","g":"gird","h":"The picture: tying a belt tight around your waist."},"G1242":{"b":"Abbott says the ordinary Greek sense is a disposition, testament, will. The Greek Old Testament used it for God's covenant instead.\n\nAbbott quotes a note that a different word might have suggested equal terms. This one does not.","g":"covenant, testament","h":"The picture: a will read after a death."},"G1243":{"b":"The root diaireo means to divide and distribute. Diairesis is that dividing up, a whole broken into portions and handed out. Paul says there are different kinds of gifts, shares dealt out, but the same Spirit behind them all.","g":"diversity","h":"The picture: portions dealt out."},"G1244":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is \"to divide into parts, cut asunder.\" Then it means to hand those parts out. The father divides his living between his sons. Paul says the Spirit divides gifts, giving a portion to each as he chooses.","g":"divide, distribute","h":"The picture: cutting the whole into portions."},"G1245":{"b":"The word joins through and to cleanse. It means to clean all the way through, to clear out completely. Here it is the threshing floor. John says Christ will thoroughly clear his floor, sweeping the grain into the barn and leaving nothing of the chaff behind.","g":"to winnow, cleanse","h":"The picture: sweeping the threshing floor clean."},"G1246":{"b":"At the core is a word meaning to confute, to prove a man wrong. Prefixes pile on the force, down and through, until he is beaten flat. Apollos publicly out-argued the Jews from their own Scriptures.","g":"confute","h":"The picture: arguing an opponent down."},"G1247":{"b":"Abbott says the word means to wait upon, especially at table. Serving food and seeing to someone's needs.\n\nThat is the word behind minister and deacon. It starts in the dining room, not the pulpit.","g":"serve, minister","h":"The picture: waiting on tables."},"G1248":{"b":"Abbott's second sense is domestic duties, the ordinary work of running a house.\n\nThe same word becomes ministry in the church. The grand word for service starts with someone doing the housework.","g":"ministry, service","h":"The picture: household chores."},"G1249":{"b":"Strong's describes this person as a waiter at table. Abbott-Smith is honest and says the derivation is unknown.\n\nSo the safest picture is the job itself. This is our word deacon. It starts with carrying food to people.","g":"servant, minister","h":"The picture: waiting on tables."},"G125":{"b":"Strong's says the origin of this place name is uncertain. Abbott-Smith gives none. It is the land of the Nile and nothing in the sources tells us why it is called that.","flat":1,"g":"Egypt","h":"No picture."},"G1250":{"b":"Two words, twice and a hundred, so two hundred. Philip counts the cost, two hundred denarii of bread would not feed the crowd. A plain number that measures how far short the money falls.","g":"two hundred","h":"The picture: two hundred days' wages."},"G1251":{"b":"This is akouo, to hear, with dia, through. It means to hear a case fully, right through to the finish. The governor tells Paul he will hear him out when his accusers arrive. Not a snatch of it. The whole thing, start to end.","g":"hear fully","h":"The picture: listening all the way through to the end."},"G1252":{"b":"Strong's starts with to separate thoroughly. From there come the other meanings. To tell things apart. To decide a case.\n\nAnd then to doubt, which Strong's calls hesitating. The doubter is a person divided down the middle.","g":"distinguish, doubt","h":"The picture: sorting into two piles."},"G1253":{"b":"The root diakrino means to separate thoroughly, to tell apart. Diakrisis is that sorting, dividing a mixed pile so you can judge one thing from another. The New Testament uses it for discerning spirits and telling good from evil.","g":"discernment","h":"The picture: sorting a mixed pile."},"G1254":{"b":"The root means to prevent, and the prefix drives it home, to hinder thoroughly. Matthew uses it at the river: John tried to stop Jesus, saying I need to be baptized by you. A man planting himself in the way, sure he is right, and gently overruled.","g":"forbid","h":"The picture: standing in the way."},"G1255":{"b":"The root means to talk, and \"through\" carries the words across a whole group. It is talk that spreads from house to house. After John's birth, Luke says all these things were talked over through the hill country of Judea.","g":"talk over","h":"The picture: talk passing all through a neighborhood."},"G1256":{"b":"Abbott says the root means to pick out, to distinguish. To reason is to sort ideas through, back and forth. Paul reasoned in the synagogue from the Scriptures. Our word \"dialogue\" comes from it.","g":"reason, discuss","h":"The picture: sorting the words out."},"G1257":{"b":"This word is built from through and to leave. Abbott-Smith reads it as to leave off for a time, to pause. From the moment Jesus came in, the weeping woman never did. She has not stopped kissing my feet, he said.","g":"cease","h":"The picture: never once stopping to take a break."},"G1258":{"b":"This is the way a particular people talk, the local tongue of a country or district. At Pentecost each person heard the wonders of God in his own language. Paul quiets the crowd by speaking to them in their own Hebrew dialect.","g":"language, dialect","h":"The picture: the local tongue people talk in."},"G1259":{"b":"The root means to make different, to exchange. This word is to change enmity for friendship, to reconcile. Jesus says leave your gift at the altar and first go be reconciled to your brother. Two enemies swap that standing for peace before God is approached.","g":"reconcile","h":"The picture: trading enmity for friendship."},"G126":{"b":"Built from a word meaning ever, always. Abbott gives everlasting. Paul says God's aidios power and divine nature have been plain since creation, Romans 1:20, seen in the things He made. Power that never began and will never end.","g":"eternal, everlasting","h":"The picture: never began, never ends."},"G1260":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the old sense is to balance accounts. Picture someone adding up the books, working the numbers through. That becomes the word for turning a matter over in your mind, reasoning it out step by step.","g":"reason, deliberate","h":"The picture: balancing the accounts."},"G1261":{"b":"The root means to reckon thoroughly, to count something back and forth. A dialogismos is the mind's inner accounting, a thought, reasoning, inward questioning, sometimes an argument with itself. Jesus says these tangled reckonings rise up out of the heart.","g":"reasoning","h":"The picture: the mind's inner accounting."},"G1262":{"b":"This word joins through and to loosen. It means to dissolve, to come apart completely. Gamaliel says the followers of Theudas were scattered after he died, the whole band loosened and gone. Like a knot untied, everything fell away.","g":"to scatter","h":"The picture: a knot coming loose and falling apart."},"G1263":{"b":"The root means to be a witness. Add dia and it turns solemn, a witness who stands and testifies with full weight. Paul uses it when he charges Timothy before God, swearing to the truth of his words like a man under oath.","g":"to testify","h":"The picture: the witness under oath."},"G1264":{"b":"Under this word is machomai, to war, to fight. The dia makes it fierce. Here the fight is not with fists but with words. The Pharisees battle it out in the council over Paul, contending hard. The word borrows the picture of combat for a fierce argument.","g":"fight, contend","h":"The picture: two men fighting hand to hand."},"G1265":{"b":"Built from a word meaning through and a word meaning to stay. To stay in one spot the whole way through, not moving. Zechariah stayed speechless. The heavens grow old but he remains, staying the same all the way through.","g":"remain, continue","h":"The picture: staying put the whole way through."},"G1266":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is to distribute. The word is built from through and divide, to cut all the way into parts and hand them out. The soldiers used it when they parceled out Jesus' clothes.","g":"divide, share out","h":"The picture: parceling out into shares."},"G1267":{"b":"The root means to partition thoroughly, to divide up. This is a division, set opposite peace. Jesus says a hard thing: do you think I came to give peace. No, but division. Even one house split, father against son, over him. A clean cut.","g":"division","h":"The picture: a household split down the middle."},"G1268":{"b":"This word means to distribute, to parcel out to many. It came to mean spreading news about. The rulers feared the report of the healing would spread no further among the people, so they tried to shut it down. But word gets passed around.","g":"to spread","h":"The picture: handing pieces out all around."},"G1269":{"b":"This word means to nod or signal across the space between people. It is talking with the head and hands, not the voice. Struck dumb in the temple, Zechariah could only nod and gesture to the waiting crowd. He could not speak a word.","g":"beckon","h":"The picture: nodding across the room."},"G127":{"b":"Strong's traces this word to the idea of downcast eyes. Modesty here is the lowered gaze, the eyes that do not brazenly stare, a sense of shame that keeps you from overstepping. Paul asks for it in how believers carry themselves. The face turned humbly down.","g":"modesty","h":"The picture: eyes cast down."},"G1270":{"b":"The word is built on a root meaning to think, and it means a thought, something turned over in the mind. Luke uses it of Jesus: knowing their thoughts, he answered them. They kept their doubts silent, but he read straight through them.","g":"thought","h":"The picture: the thought thought through."},"G1271":{"b":"The root is nous, mind, with dia, through. Dianoia is the mind thinking a matter all the way through. Jesus says love God with all your dianoia, not a lazy nod but the whole reasoning power bent toward him, thought pushed to the end.","g":"mind","h":"The picture: the mind thinking a matter through."},"G1272":{"b":"Abbott: \"to open up completely, to open.\" It joins \"through\" with the word for open. It is opening a thing all the way, ears unstopped, eyes opened, the Scriptures opened up so the meaning shines out plain.","g":"open up","h":"The picture: opening a thing all the way."},"G1273":{"b":"This word is built from through and night. Strong's reads it as to sit up the whole night. Before choosing the twelve, Jesus spent the entire night alone on a hillside in prayer, awake from dusk to dawn.","g":"continue all night","h":"The picture: staying awake through the whole night."},"G1274":{"b":"This is built on through, and it means to accomplish thoroughly, to carry a thing all the way to its finish. Paul finished the sail from Tyre and came down to Ptolemais.","g":"finish","h":"The picture: seeing the voyage through."},"G1276":{"b":"Dia means through, and the root means across. Diaperao pictures going clean over to the other side, sailing across the water. Jesus crossed over and came to his own town. A crossing from this shore to the far one.","g":"cross over","h":"The picture: crossing to the far shore."},"G1277":{"b":"This is dia, through, plus pleo, to sail. It means to sail across, from one side of a stretch of sea to the other. Paul's ship sails over the open sea off Cilicia and Pamphylia. The word is the crossing, the vessel cutting straight across the water.","g":"sail across","h":"The picture: a ship crossing open water."},"G1278":{"b":"This is built from \"through\" and a word for toil that shades into anguish. It is the feeling of being worked through, worn down. So when the priests were like this at the apostles, they were not mildly annoyed. They ached with it.","g":"be grieved","h":"The picture: worn out from hard labor."},"G1279":{"b":"Built from a word meaning through and a word meaning to travel. It is journeying all the way through a place, in one side and out the other. Jesus went through the towns and villages, teaching as he passed.","g":"travel through","h":"The picture: a road passing straight through."},"G128":{"b":"Abbott builds this name from two words: to burn, and face. A burnt face, darkened by the sun. That was the Greek name for the people to the far south. So the man Philip met on the road was an Aithiops, an Ethiopian.","g":"Ethiopian","h":"The picture: a face darkened by the sun."},"G1280":{"b":"The root means to have no way out, no road, no exit. To diaporeo is to be stuck like that all through, thoroughly at a loss. The crowd at Pentecost are in this state, hearing their own tongues and finding no way to explain it.","g":"be perplexed","h":"The picture: trapped with no way out."},"G1281":{"b":"The word for through is added to the trading word. Abbott says it means to gain by trading, to carry the deal all the way to a return. The master called the servants to learn how much each had gained.","g":"gain by trading","h":"The picture: trading through to a profit."},"G1282":{"b":"The root means to saw in two, and \"through\" sits in front. Picture a saw grinding all the way through a log. When the council heard Stephen, they were sawn through. The anger cut them like a blade cutting into wood.","g":"cut to the heart","h":"The picture: a saw grinding through wood."},"G1283":{"b":"The root means to seize, to snatch. Add \"through\" and it is stripping a place clean. Jesus says you must first tie up the strong man, and then you can plunder his house. Grab everything and carry it off.","g":"plunder","h":"The picture: snatching a house bare."},"G1284":{"b":"The root is to break or wreck, and dia sends the tear all the way through. The high priest diarresso his robes at Jesus' words, ripping the cloth top to bottom. The demoniac diarresso his chains, snapping them apart.","g":"tear apart","h":"The picture: cloth torn right through."},"G1285":{"b":"This joins \"through\" to a word meaning clear. To diasapheo is to make a thing clear all the way through, with nothing left cloudy. In the parable the servants come and lay the whole matter before their master, holding nothing back.","g":"explain, tell","h":"The picture: laying it all out until it is clear."},"G1286":{"b":"This word joins through with a word meaning to rock and shake back and forth. To do it to a person is to rattle money out by threats. John tells the soldiers to stop. Do not shake people down or accuse them falsely. Be content with your pay.","g":"intimidate","h":"The picture: shaking someone down."},"G1287":{"b":"This means to scatter abroad. Abbott-Smith points to winnowing grain, throwing it up so it scatters. Sheep scatter when the shepherd is struck. The prodigal scattered his money away.","g":"scatter, squander","h":"The picture: winnowing grain into the wind."},"G1288":{"b":"This joins dia, apart, to spao, to draw or pull. Diaspao is to pull a thing apart, to tear it in two. The man among the tombs is so strong that the chains binding him are wrenched apart, and no one can subdue him.","g":"pull in pieces","h":"The picture: chains wrenched apart."},"G1289":{"b":"This word is built from a word for across and a word meaning to scatter and sow. To fling seed over the whole field. The believers were scattered by persecution, and carried the word to every place they landed.","g":"scatter","h":"The picture: seed flung across the whole field."},"G129":{"b":"Strong's says the derivation is uncertain. Abbott offers none either. The word means blood and that is all the sources will say. Nothing is hiding underneath it.","flat":1,"g":"blood","h":"No picture."},"G1290":{"b":"This word comes from a word meaning to sow throughout. Seed flung wide across a field. The scattered Israelites were thrown out across foreign lands like grain, far from home, planted where they fell.","g":"dispersion","h":"The picture: seed flung across a field."},"G1291":{"b":"The root means to set or arrange, with a prefix meaning apart. First to separate and define, then to command, charge expressly. After raising the girl, Jesus orders them firmly to tell no one. A line drawn, a command pressed.","g":"charge, command","h":"The picture: laying down a strict order."},"G1292":{"b":"This word comes from a verb meaning to stand apart. It means an interval, a gap, here a stretch of time. About three hours stood between the death of Ananias and his wife coming in. A space opened between the two moments.","g":"interval","h":"The picture: the gap standing between two things."},"G1293":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is a separation. The word is built on setting things apart, putting a gap between them so you can tell one from the other. Paul says there is no such gap between Jew and Greek, no distinction before God.","g":"distinction","h":"The picture: a gap set between two things."},"G1294":{"b":"This word is built from through and to twist. It means to bend a thing crooked, to wrench it out of line. They accused Jesus of perverting the nation. A crooked and twisted generation, Paul writes. Straightness forced out of shape.","g":"pervert","h":"The picture: twisting something out of true."},"G1295":{"b":"Abbott: \"to bring safely through a danger.\" It joins \"through\" with \"save.\" It is getting someone all the way through peril to safety, like sailors carried through the sea and brought safe to dry land.","g":"bring safely through","h":"The picture: carried safe through the storm to shore."},"G1296":{"b":"The root means to arrange thoroughly, to set things in order like troops drawn up in ranks. This word is that ordering. Stephen says the law came by the arranging of angels, handed down in due order.","g":"ordinance","h":"The picture: things set out in ordered ranks."},"G1297":{"b":"The root means to arrange thoroughly, to draw up in order. An edict is a command set out and fixed. Moses' parents saw he was a fine child and did not fear the king's decree to kill the boys.","g":"edict","h":"The picture: the command set in order."},"G1298":{"b":"The root means to stir or agitate, the way a stick roils clear water until it clouds. This word is that churning made strong. When the angel greeted her, Mary's mind was troubled like that, stirred up and unsettled by his words.","g":"trouble, agitate","h":"The picture: water stirred up and muddied."},"G1299":{"b":"The root means to arrange in an orderly manner, to set each thing in its place, like troops drawn up in rank. Dia adds thoroughness. So when Paul sets a church in order or God ordains the law, nothing is left to chance.","g":"to ordain","h":"The picture: troops drawn up in rank."},"G13":{"b":"This is a man's name, Agabus, a prophet who warned of famine and of Paul's arrest. The worksheet gives no meaning behind it, only that he was an Israelite. There is nothing pictured here to see.","flat":1,"g":"Agabus","h":"No picture."},"G130":{"b":"Two words join here, blood and pouring out. It means blood poured out. Without blood spilled there is no forgiveness. Under the law almost everything was cleansed by blood poured from the sacrifice.","g":"shedding of blood","h":"The picture: blood poured out."},"G1300":{"b":"This is dia, through, plus teleo, to finish or complete. It means to keep on all the way through to the end. Paul tells them they have gone on fasting for two whole weeks without stop. The word is the act carried right through, unbroken from start to finish.","g":"continue","h":"The picture: carrying on straight to the finish line."},"G1301":{"b":"The root means to guard by keeping your eye on a thing. Add \"through\" and you keep watch all the way through, right on. Luke uses it for Mary, who kept all these things, guarding them carefully in her heart.","g":"keep carefully","h":"The picture: keeping careful watch over something."},"G1303":{"b":"Dia means apart, and tithemi means to place. Diatithemai pictures a man setting his affairs in order, laying out who gets what, drawing up his will. It is the word behind God making a covenant. He sets its terms like a testament.","g":"make a covenant","h":"The picture: drawing up a will."},"G1304":{"b":"Strong's: \"to wear through (time).\" Abbott: \"to rub hard, rub away, consume.\" To stay somewhere is to wear the time down, rubbing the hours thin until the days are spent. That is how the word says people lingered in a place.","g":"stay, tarry","h":"The picture: rubbing the hours away."},"G1305":{"b":"The root trepho means to feed and nourish, and dia carries the sense of through. So it is nourishment, the food that sustains you day by day. Paul says having food and clothing, we should be content.","g":"food","h":"The picture: the food that keeps you fed."},"G1306":{"b":"This joins \"through\" to a root meaning to beam forth. So it is light shining through, day breaking. Peter says hold to the word until the day dawns and the morning star rises in your hearts.","g":"dawn","h":"The picture: first light breaking through."},"G1307":{"b":"The word means light shining through, appearing through. Abbott-Smith gives \"transparent.\" Picture clear glass with light passing clean through it. So the city's main street was pure gold, transparent as glass.","g":"transparent","h":"The picture: glass you can see straight through."},"G1308":{"b":"The word joins \"carry\" to \"through\" or \"apart.\" Strong's says it means to bear through, and so to differ. Things carried apart are set apart. Jesus said you are worth more than many sparrows.","g":"differ, be better","h":"The picture: carried apart."},"G1309":{"b":"The root here means to run away. Put the word for through in front and you get someone slipping out through an opening. Abbott says to flee through, escape. It is a man getting clear alive when everything around him is breaking apart.","g":"escape","h":"The picture: running out through the gap."},"G131":{"b":"Two words joined, blood and to flow like running water. So it means to bleed, to suffer a flow that will not stop. This was the woman who touched Jesus' hem. Picture blood running like water for twelve years.","g":"flow of blood","h":"The picture: blood running like water."},"G1310":{"b":"The root is a saying, a rumor, where we get \"fame.\" The dia means through. So it is a report carried all the way through a district. The men Jesus healed could not keep quiet. They spread the word everywhere.","g":"spread abroad","h":"The picture: the rumor carried through the country."},"G1311":{"b":"The root means to shrivel and spoil, to rot. This word carries it all the way through, ruined completely. Moths and rust destroy treasure on earth. Paul says the outward body wastes away, decaying, while the inward is renewed.","g":"corrupt, destroy","h":"The picture: fruit rotting all the way through."},"G1312":{"b":"The root is to rot right through. This is decay, the corruption of a dead body in the grave. Peter and Paul quote the promise that God's Holy One would not see corruption. His flesh would not rot in the tomb like all others.","g":"corruption, decay","h":"The picture: a body rotting in the grave."},"G1313":{"b":"The root means to bear apart, to carry things away from each other. Things borne apart end up different. So this word means differing, and then rising higher, more excellent. The gifts differ, Paul says, and Christ's name is more excellent than the angels'.","g":"differing, excellent","h":"The picture: carried in different directions."},"G1314":{"b":"This word joins through with a word meaning to keep watch, to stand guard. So it is to guard something carefully, all through. The promise quoted to Jesus is that angels are set to guard you closely, watching over all your ways.","g":"guard, protect","h":"The picture: a watchman guarding on every side."},"G1315":{"b":"The word is built on the word for hand. It means to handle a thing thoroughly, to take it fully in hand. When it turns dark it means to lay violent hands upon a man and kill him. That is what the council wanted to do to the apostles.","g":"kill, slay","h":"The picture: hands laid on a man to kill him."},"G1316":{"b":"This word comes from the word to place room between, to part. As Moses and Elijah were parting from Jesus and drawing away, Peter blurted out that it was good to be there and offered to build three shelters.","g":"depart","h":"The picture: drawing apart, putting space between."},"G1317":{"b":"Built from the word for taught. Abbott gives apt at teaching. Among the marks of an overseer, Paul lists didaktikos, able to teach, First Timothy 3:2. Not merely knowing the truth for yourself but being skilled to hand it on to others.","g":"apt to teach","h":"The picture: skilled to hand it on."},"G1318":{"b":"This word is built from the word to teach. It means taught. Not self-taught, not guessed at, but learned from someone else. When John says they will all be taught by God, he means God himself sits as the teacher.","g":"taught","h":"The picture: a pupil taught by a teacher."},"G1319":{"b":"From didasko, to teach. Didaskalia is teaching, instruction, both the act and the thing taught. So Paul warns against being tossed by every wind of didaskalia, and calls for sound teaching, healthy instruction that keeps a church on its feet.","g":"teaching, doctrine","h":"The picture: instruction laid out to be learned."},"G132":{"b":"This is a man's name, Aeneas, the paralyzed man Peter healed at Lydda. Strong's says its origin is of uncertain derivation. So there is no meaning behind the name to picture, only the man who was made well.","flat":1,"g":"Aeneas","h":"No picture."},"G1320":{"b":"This comes from didasko, to teach. A didaskalos is the teacher, the one who stands and instructs. Abbott notes it renders the Hebrew rabbi. So when they call Jesus Teacher, they put him in the seat of the rabbi, the one whose word you are meant to learn.","g":"teacher","h":"The picture: the teacher at the front of the room."},"G1321":{"b":"Strong's says it is a longer form of a plain verb meaning to learn, built so that it causes the action.\n\nSo teaching here is not talking. It is doing something to a person until they know.","g":"teach","h":"The picture: making someone learn."},"G1322":{"b":"From didasko, to teach. Didache is the teaching itself, the thing that is taught, the content passed from teacher to learner. So the crowds are astonished at his didache, not just that Jesus speaks but at the very lesson coming out of his mouth.","g":"teaching, doctrine","h":"The picture: the lesson handed over to be learned."},"G1323":{"b":"The word joins \"twice\" to drachma, a silver coin handled in the palm. A didrachmon is worth two of them, about the Jewish half-shekel, the exact temple tax. It is the coin the collectors ask whether Jesus pays.","g":"temple tax","h":"The picture: a two-drachma silver coin."},"G1324":{"b":"This name comes from a word meaning twice. It means double, a twin. Two born where you expect one. It is the surname given to the apostle Thomas, Thomas the twin.","g":"twin","h":"The picture: two born at once."},"G1325":{"b":"Strong's says this is a stretched out form of a primary verb. Nothing older is named. Abbott-Smith lists a long line of senses, bestow, grant, supply, deliver, but offers no history. Nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"give","h":"No picture."},"G1326":{"b":"The root is to waken, to rouse from sleep, and the front of the word means all the way through. To shake someone completely awake. The terrified disciples do it to Jesus in the storm. The same word stirs the sea into waves.","g":"wake fully, rouse","h":"The picture: shaking someone fully awake."},"G1327":{"b":"The pieces mean through and a way out. It is the point where a town road spills out and splits into the open highways. In Matthew 22:9 the king sends servants to these partings of the ways to bring in anyone they find.","g":"highway, crossroads","h":"The picture: where the roads branch out of town."},"G1328":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to explain thoroughly, to translate. A diermeneutes is the go-between who turns strange words into your own. Paul says if no such interpreter is there, the tongue-speaker should keep silent.","g":"interpreter","h":"The picture: the go-between who turns the words."},"G1329":{"b":"The root means to translate, and the front means all the way through. To carry a meaning fully across so it can be understood. On the road Jesus opened up all the scriptures. In church someone must interpret the tongue. To make a hidden sense plain.","g":"interpret, translate","h":"The picture: carrying a meaning across."},"G133":{"b":"The root is the word for praising God. Strong's ties it to a thank-offering, a gift laid down to say thank you. Hebrews says offer God a sacrifice of praise. The words of your own mouth, laid on the altar.","g":"praise","h":"The picture: a thank-offering laid on the altar."},"G1330":{"b":"Abbott gives the plain sense, to go through, pass through. Strong's calls it traversing.\n\nIt is used of things and of people. Not stopping at the edge of a place. All the way across it.","g":"go through, pass through","h":"The picture: in one side and out the other."},"G1331":{"b":"The word joins 'through' with 'to ask,' to question all the way to the end. The men from Cornelius ask around through the town until they find the house where Peter is staying.","g":"make enquiry","h":"The picture: asking your way through the streets."},"G1332":{"b":"The word joins twice and year: two years old. Matthew uses it in a dark hour: Herod, tricked by the wise men, killed all the boys in Bethlehem two years old and under. A child's age becoming the measure of a king's fear.","g":"two years old","h":"The picture: two years old and under."},"G1333":{"b":"A span of two years, built from the word for two years old. Abbott points to Paul, held two years while Felix left him bound, Acts 24:27, and later two whole years preaching in his own rented house in Rome. Two years marked off.","g":"two years","h":"The picture: two years marked off."},"G1334":{"b":"Abbott: \"to set out in detail, recount, describe.\" It joins \"through\" with a word for leading. To tell a thing this way is to lead the hearer all the way through it, step by step from start to finish.","g":"tell fully","h":"The picture: walking someone through the whole story."},"G1335":{"b":"The root means to relate fully, to lead a story all the way through. This is a narrative. Luke opens with it: since many have undertaken to draw up a narrative of the things fulfilled among us, I too decided to write an orderly account.","g":"narrative","h":"The picture: the story set in order."},"G1336":{"b":"The roots mean to bear through, to carry all the way across. This word describes something unbroken, continuous. Christ remains a priest without a break, his one sacrifice offered once for all time.","g":"continuous","h":"The picture: carried straight through without a break."},"G1337":{"b":"This is dis, twice, plus thalassa, the sea. It names a place where two seas come together, a reef or a tongue of land with water on both sides. The ship struck such a place and ran aground. The word is the point where two seas meet over a bar.","g":"where two seas meet","h":"The picture: a spit of land where two seas meet."},"G1338":{"b":"This word means to reach through, to pass all the way in. God's word does not stop at the surface. It drives through to divide soul and spirit, joints and marrow, reaching the deepest inside.","g":"pierce","h":"The picture: driven all the way through."},"G1339":{"b":"The word joins apart and stand. It means to separate, to put an interval between. About an hour comes between Peter's second and third denials. At the end Jesus parts from the disciples and is carried up. A space opening in between.","g":"be parted","h":"The picture: a gap opening as two things stand apart."},"G134":{"b":"The root of this word means, properly, a story. Before it meant praise it meant a tale told about someone. So to praise God is to tell his story out loud, in front of others, so they hear what he has done.","g":"praise","h":"The picture: telling the story out loud."},"G1340":{"b":"The word is built on \"strong,\" and Abbott's first sense is \"to lean upon.\" It is putting your whole weight behind what you say. By the fire a bystander leans on it and insists Peter was with Jesus. Rhoda does the same at the door.","g":"affirm confidently","h":"The picture: planting your feet and leaning hard on a claim."},"G1341":{"b":"This joins the word for just with the word for a decision or tribunal. So it is a righteous judgment, a fair ruling from the bench. Abbott says righteous judgment. Paul says God's judgment on the day of wrath will be exactly this.","g":"righteous judgment","h":"The picture: a fair verdict handed down in court."},"G1342":{"b":"Abbott says the early Greek writers used it of someone observant of custom, rule, right. He does his duty to gods and men.\n\nIn the New Testament the rule becomes God's standard, but the shape stays.","g":"righteous, just","h":"The picture: a man who keeps to the rule."},"G1343":{"b":"Abbott defines it as conformity to the divine will in purpose, thought and action. A standard is set and you match it.\n\nHe gives a narrower sense too. Plain justice.","g":"righteousness","h":"The picture: measuring up to the rule."},"G1344":{"b":"Abbott's older sense is to do one justice, and in the passive, to be treated rightly.\n\nSo being justified is not being made nice. It is a verdict going your way.","g":"justify","h":"The picture: the court finds for you."},"G1345":{"b":"Abbott calls it a concrete expression of righteousness. It can be an ordinance, a sentence of acquittal, or a righteous act. So it is not a feeling about what is right. It is the ruling made official and handed down.","g":"ordinance, verdict","h":"The picture: the verdict read out in court."},"G1346":{"b":"Strong's root means equitable. To act dikaios is to give each person exactly what is due, nothing shaved off and nothing added. Picture the scales balanced, level. Abbott lists two senses, righteously and justly. It is a life weighed and found fair.","g":"justly, righteously","h":"The picture: the scales come out even."},"G1347":{"b":"The root means to declare someone just, to regard as innocent. This is the verdict itself, the acquittal spoken over the accused. Not made good by trying harder, but pronounced right by the Judge. The gavel falls, and the word is innocent.","g":"justification","h":"The picture: a verdict of not guilty."},"G1348":{"b":"The root is the word for what is right, self-evident justice. A dikastes is the man who sits and settles it, the courtroom judge. So the Israelite pushed Moses off: who made you a ruler and judge over us.","g":"judge","h":"The picture: the man who decides what is right."},"G1349":{"b":"Abbott traces the word from custom to right to a court hearing, and finally \"the execution of a sentence, punishment.\" The Maltese watch the snake bite Paul and say Justice will not let a murderer live. To them it hunts the guilty down.","g":"justice, vengeance","h":"The picture: the sentence carried out on the guilty."},"G135":{"b":"Abbott gives it as a dark saying, a riddle. It pictures a puzzle spoken in shadow, meaning half hidden. Paul says now we see in a mirror dimly, as through a riddle, but one day face to face.","g":"riddle, darkly","h":"The picture: a puzzle spoken in shadow."},"G1350":{"b":"Strong's says this probably comes from a verb meaning \"to cast.\" So a net is named for the throwing of it, the mesh flung out over the water. Abbott-Smith gives the verses where the disciples left their nets to follow Jesus.","g":"net","h":"The picture: the thing you throw."},"G1351":{"b":"This joins dis, twice, and logos, a word. So it is double-worded, saying one thing to this person and another to that one. Paul says deacons must not be double-tongued, telling different stories.","g":"double-tongued","h":"The picture: a man who says it two ways."},"G1353":{"b":"The root means to travel, from the word for a road, and \"through\" carries you across the whole land. Luke uses it for Jesus, going through one town and village after another, preaching the good news of God's kingdom.","g":"travel through","h":"The picture: walking the road through town after town."},"G1354":{"b":"This is a man's name, Dionysius, an Athenian who believed after Paul spoke on Mars' Hill. It is only a label for a person, so there is nothing here to picture.","flat":1,"g":"Dionysius","h":"No picture."},"G1356":{"b":"Strong's calls this sky-fallen, an aerolite, a meteorite. A rock dropped out of heaven. The Ephesians claimed their image of Artemis had fallen from the sky, and no one could deny it.","g":"fallen from sky","h":"The picture: a stone fallen from the sky."},"G1357":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to make straight, to set right, like straightening what is bent. The old rules stood only until the time of setting things straight, when God would put all in order.","g":"reformation","h":"The picture: setting things straight again."},"G1358":{"b":"The word is through plus to dig. Abbott-Smith ties it to house-breaking. Mud walls could be dug straight through. Jesus warns that thieves break in and steal earthly treasure. Picture a hole clawed through the wall in the dark.","g":"break through","h":"The picture: a thief digging through the wall."},"G1359":{"b":"Abbott says this joins the name of Zeus with a word for a son. So it means the sons of Zeus, the twins Castor and Pollux. Sailors prayed to them for safe voyage, and their figures rode on Paul's ship.","g":"Castor and Pollux","h":"The picture: the twin sons of Zeus."},"G136":{"b":"This word first meant a tale, a story spoken aloud. From telling stories it came to mean praise, saying out loud what someone has done. Jesus quotes the psalm, out of the mouths of children God has drawn perfect praise.","g":"praise","h":"The picture: a story told out loud."},"G1361":{"b":"Abbott says the name is built from Zeus and a word meaning to nourish, so it means cherished by Zeus. John names this man, who loved to be first and would not welcome the brothers.","g":"Diotrephes","h":"The picture: a name meaning nourished by Zeus."},"G1362":{"b":"The word means twofold, doubled, like cloth laid back on itself so one thickness becomes two. Elders who lead well are worth double honour, Paul says. Babylon gets it the other way, paid back double for what she poured out.","g":"double","h":"The picture: folded over to make two."},"G1363":{"b":"The word means \"to double,\" from a word meaning two-fold. Picture a cloth folded over on itself so there are two layers where there was one. So God repays Babylon double, folding her own cup back on her twice over.","g":"to double","h":"The picture: folding a cloth in two."},"G1364":{"b":"From the word for two. It means twice. Jesus tells Peter that before the rooster crows twice, you will deny me three times. A count of two, and it undid him.","g":"twice","h":"The picture: the cock crows twice."},"G1365":{"b":"The root is dis, twice. To distazo is to be doubled in mind, wavering between two thoughts. It is Peter again, on the water. Jesus asks why he doubted, why his one trust split in two the moment he saw the wind.","g":"doubt","h":"The picture: pulled two ways at once."},"G1366":{"b":"The word joins twice and mouth. The Greeks called a sword's edge its mouth, the part that bites. A distomos blade has two mouths, sharp on both sides. Hebrews says God's word is sharper than any such sword. It cuts going in and coming out.","g":"two-edged","h":"The picture: a sword with two mouths."},"G1367":{"b":"The number two thousand, twice a thousand. Mark reaches for it at the drowning: the unclean spirits entered the pigs, and the herd, about two thousand, rushed down the bank into the sea. One count measuring the weight of what possessed one man.","g":"two thousand","h":"The picture: two thousand pigs in the sea."},"G1368":{"b":"The word means to strain a liquid all the way through, to filter it. In Matthew 23:24 Jesus pictures men pouring their drink through a cloth to catch a tiny gnat, then gulping down a whole camel.","g":"strain out","h":"The picture: straining wine through a cloth."},"G1369":{"b":"The root means apart, in two. So this word is to cut in two, to split down the middle. Jesus came to set a man against his father, a household divided. Picture one thing cut cleanly into two.","g":"set at variance","h":"The picture: cut clean in two."},"G137":{"b":"Strong's reads the name as place of springs, from a Hebrew word for a spring of water. John was baptizing at Aenon because there was much water there. The name itself promised water welling up from the ground.","g":"Aenon","h":"The picture: springs bubbling from the ground."},"G1370":{"b":"This is built from a word for twice and a word for standing. It pictures people who have taken their stand apart, split into two camps. Paul warns the church to mark those who cause such divisions.","g":"division","h":"The picture: two camps standing apart."},"G1371":{"b":"This comes from words meaning in two and to cut. Dichotomeo is to cut a thing clean in half. Jesus says the master will cut the faithless servant in two and cast him out, a violent end for the one caught unready.","g":"cut asunder","h":"The picture: cut clean in two."},"G1372":{"b":"Strong's says it means to thirst for (literally or figuratively). Start with the real thing. A parched mouth that must have a drink. Jesus takes that craving and points it higher. Thirst for righteousness. Long for it like water.","g":"thirst","h":"The picture: a dry throat craving water."},"G1373":{"b":"Both lexicons give one word, thirst. There is no story behind it, just the craving itself. Paul lists it among his hardships, hunger and thirst, the plain bodily need dogging him as he traveled.","g":"thirst","h":"The picture: a dry throat aching for water."},"G1374":{"b":"Built from twice and a word for the soul or breath. So it pictures a man with two souls inside him. Each soul wants a different thing. He is not lying, he is pulled two ways at once.","g":"double-minded","h":"The picture: two souls in one man."},"G1375":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to pursue, to chase down. So persecution is not only insults. It is being run down like game. The hunters keep coming and do not tire.","g":"persecution","h":"The picture: the hunt."},"G1376":{"b":"The root dioko means to chase or pursue, the way a hunter runs after game. A dioktes is one who hunts people down. Paul says he was one before, a persecutor, until mercy found him.","g":"persecutor","h":"The picture: a hunter running down his prey."},"G1377":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is to put to flight, drive away. Then it becomes simply to pursue.\n\nThe same word covers following after something you want and hunting a person down. Chasing is chasing.","g":"pursue, persecute","h":"The picture: the chase."},"G1378":{"b":"The root means to think or seem good. What a ruler decides becomes a decree, a public order posted for all to obey. Caesar's decree sent everyone home to be counted. A command with the ruler's weight behind it.","g":"decree","h":"The picture: an edict posted for all."},"G1379":{"b":"This comes from a word for a law, a decree laid down. The middle form means to place yourself under it, to bow to the ordinance. Paul asks why, having died with Christ, they still let themselves be tied down by such rules.","g":"submit to rules","h":"The picture: bowing to a posted rule."},"G138":{"b":"This word is akin to airo, to take up. It means to take a thing for yourself, to pick out the one you prefer. Choosing is reaching for what you want. Moses chose rather to suffer with God's people than enjoy sin.","g":"choose","h":"The picture: reaching for the one you want."},"G1380":{"b":"Strong's calls this a prolonged form of a primary verb, so there is nothing older behind it. The word covers both what a person supposes and how a thing looks to other people.","flat":1,"g":"think, seem","h":"No picture."},"G1381":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this was primarily a word for metals. You test the metal to find out what it really is.\n\nHe adds the key point. The test is made hoping it will pass. The second sense is the result. To approve.","g":"test, approve","h":"The picture: testing gold in the fire."},"G1382":{"b":"The root is the assayer's word, metal shown good, current after assayal. Dokime is that testing itself and the proof it leaves behind. Paul says suffering works it in us. It is what comes through the fire and is found real.","g":"proof, test","h":"The picture: metal proven in the fire."},"G1383":{"b":"Abbott calls this a test. It is the trial that proves a thing is real, the way metal is put to the assay to show it is not fake. So when faith is tested, it is being proved genuine, not thrown away.","g":"testing, trial","h":"The picture: metal put to the test."},"G1384":{"b":"Strong's pictures money that passed the test, coin proved genuine and let into circulation. A dokimos man is metal that took the assay and rang true. Tested and approved, worn currency that survived the check.","g":"approved","h":"The picture: coin that passed the test."},"G1385":{"b":"A dokos is a beam of timber, a great plank of wood, the kind that holds up a roof. Jesus puts one in your own eye while you hunt the speck in your brother's. The absurd log you somehow cannot see past.","g":"beam","h":"The picture: a plank of timber."},"G1386":{"b":"The root is a bait, a trick set to catch. Abbott-Smith says deceitful. Paul calls the false apostles workers like that, baited men, dressing lies up as truth to reel the church in.","g":"deceitful","h":"The picture: a lure with a hook inside."},"G1387":{"b":"The root means guileful, full of trickery. This is to deceive, to work deceit. Paul strings it into his indictment: their throat is an open grave, with their tongues they keep deceiving, the poison of asps under their lips. Speech bent to trap and mislead.","g":"use deceit","h":"The picture: the tongue that tricks."},"G1388":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says in Homer this word meant a bait. Then a snare. Only later did it mean craft or deceit. Deceit is bait on a hook, something tempting set out to catch you.","g":"deceit, guile","h":"The picture: bait in a trap."},"G1389":{"b":"The root is a word for a trick, a bait. Abbott-Smith also gives it as watering down wine. Either way something good is doctored to fool you. Paul says he will not tamper with God's word that way.","g":"handle deceitfully","h":"The picture: bait hiding a hook."},"G139":{"b":"Abbott: \"choosing, choice.\" It comes from a word meaning to take or seize. A sect is a group of people who have chosen their own way and taken it for their own. The choice becomes a party, and then a division.","g":"sect, party","h":"The picture: a side you choose."},"G1390":{"b":"The word comes straight from the verb to give. A doma is the thing given, a gift set in someone's hand. Jesus says if you who are evil know how to give good gifts to your children, how much more your Father in heaven.","g":"gift","h":"The picture: a present placed in the hand."},"G1391":{"b":"Abbott-Smith builds this word on a verb of thinking and seeming. In older Greek it meant opinion, then the repute a person is held in.\n\nOnly later does it mean brightness, the light that shines out from God's presence.","g":"glory, honour","h":"The picture: the good opinion people hold of you."},"G1392":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives a striking sense for this word: to clothe with splendour. Glory here is not something a person produces. It is put on them, the way a bright garment is put on.\n\nGod does that to people.","g":"glorify","h":"The picture: clothing someone in brightness."},"G1393":{"b":"This name is the plain Greek word for a gazelle. It belongs to the same woman as Tabitha, the two names meaning one animal in two languages. A gazelle is known for its bright wide eyes and its quick, light step.","g":"Dorcas","h":"The picture: a gazelle."},"G1394":{"b":"This word comes from the word to give. It is both the act of giving and the gift itself, the thing placed into another's hand. James says every good gift comes down from the Father of lights. Underneath the word is simply an open hand.","g":"gift, giving","h":"The picture: an open hand giving."},"G1395":{"b":"The root is the plain word to give, and this names the one who does it, the giver. Paul says God loves a cheerful one of these, the person whose hand opens gladly rather than clutches.","g":"giver","h":"The picture: the open hand that gives."},"G1396":{"b":"This joins slave with a word meaning to lead or drive. It pictures driving a slave along under command. Paul says he treats his own body this way, driving it hard and bringing it into service.","g":"bring into subjection","h":"The picture: driving a slave under command."},"G1397":{"b":"This comes from the verb to be a slave. Douleia is the whole state of it, bondage. Paul sets it against sonship. The slave belongs to someone else and cannot leave. That is the condition the word names, being owned.","g":"bondage, slavery","h":"The picture: a life owned by another."},"G1398":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives it as to be a slave, be subject to, serve. Not hired help. Owned.\n\nThat is why Jesus says nobody can do this for two masters. A slave has one.","g":"serve as a slave","h":"The picture: one owner."},"G1399":{"b":"This is the woman's form of the word for slave. Strong's calls her a female slave. Not a hired maid who can leave, but one owned. Mary calls herself this before God, the servant girl of the Lord, wholly at his word.","g":"handmaid, female slave","h":"The picture: the woman who belongs to a master."},"G14":{"b":"Built from the word for good and the word for work, plain toil as an effort or occupation. It means to do good as a job of work, not just to wish it. Paul says God did good, sending rain and fruitful seasons, filling hearts with food and gladness.","g":"do good","h":"The picture: hands busy doing good work."},"G140":{"b":"The root means to take for oneself, to reach for the one you prefer. So this word is to choose. God says of Jesus, my servant whom I have chosen. Picture a hand reaching out to take the one it wants.","g":"to choose","h":"The picture: a hand reaching to take."},"G1401":{"b":"Strong's traces this to a word meaning to bind. A doulos is roped to a master, not an employee who can quit. So when Paul calls himself a servant of Christ, he is telling you who owns him.","g":"servant, slave","h":"The picture: the one who cannot walk away."},"G1402":{"b":"From doulos, the slave who cannot walk away. To douloo is to put someone under that rope, to make them property. Yet Paul turns it. You were set free from sin and enslaved to God. Bound again, but to a new master.","g":"enslave","h":"The picture: put under the rope."},"G1403":{"b":"The root means to receive, to welcome. This is the welcome spread out as a feast, a banquet. Luke uses it for the great meal Levi the tax collector throws in his house for Jesus, his table crowded with his old friends.","g":"feast","h":"The picture: a great table set for guests."},"G1404":{"b":"Strong's says this probably comes from a word meaning \"to look,\" the serpent thought to fascinate by its gaze. Abbott-Smith gives no origin, only \"a dragon, a mythical monster.\" John uses it for Satan.","g":"dragon","h":"The picture: the one that stares."},"G1405":{"b":"Abbott gives it as to grasp with the hand, to lay hold of. It pictures a hand closing tight on something caught. Paul quotes it of God, who takes the wise in their own cleverness.","g":"grasp, catch","h":"The picture: the hand closing tight."},"G1406":{"b":"The root means to grasp, and this coin was named as the amount handled, a graspful. It is about a day's wage in silver. The woman lights a lamp and sweeps the whole house to find the one drachma she has lost.","g":"silver coin","h":"The picture: a silver coin gripped in the hand."},"G1407":{"b":"Strong's: \"a gathering hook (especially for harvesting).\" Abbott ties it to δρέπω, to pluck. It is the curved blade you swing to cut and gather the grain. Revelation swings one over the ripe earth.","g":"sickle","h":"The picture: the curved blade that reaps the grain."},"G1408":{"b":"This word comes from the word to run. Dromos is the race, the course a runner covers from start to finish. Paul says near the end I have finished my race, the track run all the way out.","g":"course, race","h":"The picture: the runner's race to the finish."},"G1409":{"b":"This is a woman's name, Drusilla, the wife of Felix the governor. It is a Roman name, a small form of Drusus. There is no picture inside a name like this, only the person who carried it.","flat":1,"g":"Drusilla","h":"No picture."},"G141":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to make a choice. A factious man is one who chooses his own way and splits off a party around it. Paul says reject such a person after two warnings. The word is rooted in choosing sides.","g":"heretic","h":"The picture: a man who picks his own party."},"G1410":{"b":"Strong's says the origin is uncertain. Abbott-Smith gives no history either, only the meaning: to be able, to have power, whether by ability, permission or opportunity. Nothing older stands behind it.","flat":1,"g":"be able, can","h":"No picture."},"G1411":{"b":"Abbott-Smith builds this noun on the verb meaning to be able, and defines it as power, strength, ability to perform.\n\nSo it is not force shoving against something. It is capacity. Strong's notes a miracle is called by this same word.","g":"power, ability","h":"The picture: being able to do the thing."},"G1412":{"b":"This word is built from the word for force and power, the root behind dynamite. To strengthen is to put power into someone weak. Paul says he can do all things through the one who strengthens him. Force from outside, filling arms that had none.","g":"strengthen","h":"The picture: power poured into weak arms."},"G1413":{"b":"The word is built from being able. A dynastes is the one who can, the man with power in his hands. Mary sings that God pulls such rulers down from their thrones. The Ethiopian official Philip meets is one.","g":"ruler, potentate","h":"The picture: the man with power to make it happen."},"G1414":{"b":"Built from the word for powerful. Abbott gives to be able, to be mighty. Paul says the servant will stand, for God dynateo, is strong enough, to hold him up, Romans 14:4. This is the word for having the power to do it.","g":"be mighty","h":"The picture: strong enough to hold him up."},"G1415":{"b":"Abbott builds it from the verb for being able. It covers strong men, spiritual strength, and the chief men of a city.\n\nIn the neuter it simply means possible. Power in this word is that a thing can be done.","g":"able, powerful","h":"The picture: the ones who can."},"G1416":{"b":"The old root means to sink. Dyno is to go down, used of the sun setting, dropping below the edge of the world. At evening when the sun had set they brought all the sick to Jesus, and he healed them.","g":"set, go down","h":"The picture: the sun sinking down."},"G1417":{"b":"Strong's calls it a primary numeral. Numbers this basic come from nothing else. Abbott-Smith gives no history, only the ways it is used, including sending people out two by two. There is nothing behind it.","flat":1,"g":"two","h":"No picture."},"G1419":{"b":"This word joins hard and to carry. Abbott-Smith gives it as hard to be borne. The lawyers pile burdens on people that are crushing to lift, Jesus says, while they themselves will not touch the loads with even one finger.","g":"grievous to be borne","h":"The picture: a load too heavy to carry."},"G142":{"b":"Abbott gives it in order. First to raise or lift. Then to carry. Then to carry off and remove.\n\nJohn 1:29 uses the last one. The Lamb picks sin up and carries it away.","g":"lift, take away","h":"The picture: picking something up."},"G1420":{"b":"This is built from a word for bad and a word for the inside, the bowel. So the name itself says bad insides. It is the illness we still call dysentery. Paul healed a man on Malta who was down with it.","g":"dysentery","h":"The picture: something wrong deep in the gut."},"G1421":{"b":"This is built from 'hard' and 'to translate.' Some truths are hard to carry over into plain words. The writer says this of Melchizedek. There is much to say, but it is hard to put into speech.","g":"hard to explain","h":"The picture: a word too hard to translate."},"G1422":{"b":"The word began as fussy about food, hard to satisfy at the table. From there it grew to mean hard in general, difficult. In Mark 10:24 Jesus says how hard it is for those who trust in riches to enter the kingdom of God.","g":"hard, difficult","h":"The picture: too fussy to feed."},"G1423":{"b":"The root pictures someone hard to feed, fussy and never satisfied at the table. From there it came to mean difficult, done only with trouble. Jesus says how hard it is for a rich man to enter the kingdom. The way is stiff, like pleasing a picky guest.","g":"hardly","h":"The picture: hard to please, like a fussy eater."},"G1424":{"b":"From dyno, to go down. Dysme is where the sun sets, and so the west. Many will come from east and west to sit at the feast. The direction named for the sundown, the horizon that swallows the last light.","g":"west","h":"The picture: the sun going down."},"G1425":{"b":"The word joins hard and to understand. Peter admits it plainly: in Paul's letters are some things hard to understand, which the ignorant twist to their own destruction. Even an apostle can be tough going, and misreading him is dangerous, not innocent.","g":"hard to understand","h":"The picture: hard to get your mind around."},"G1426":{"b":"The root is a saying, a rumor, where we get fame. Stick bad in front and it is a name being dragged down. Paul says he presses on through evil report and good report alike.","g":"evil report","h":"The picture: an ugly rumor passed mouth to mouth."},"G1427":{"b":"The word is just two and ten laid side by side. A dozen. Abbott notes hoi dodeka, the Twelve, became a name of its own for the apostles. So twelve is not only a number. It is the count of the men Jesus chose to stand for a new Israel.","g":"twelve","h":"The picture: two and ten counted out."},"G1428":{"b":"The word means twelfth. John counts jewels with it in the city to come: the twelfth foundation of the New Jerusalem's wall was amethyst. Twelve stones for twelve apostles, and this is the last one named, closing out the base of the eternal city.","g":"twelfth","h":"The picture: the twelfth stone in the wall."},"G1429":{"b":"This is dodeka, twelve, plus phyle, a tribe. The word for tribe means an offshoot, a shoot growing from a stock. So this is the twelve tribes seen as twelve shoots from one root. Paul says they serve God night and day, hoping for the promise.","g":"twelve tribes","h":"The picture: twelve shoots from one root."},"G143":{"b":"Strong's says this means to apprehend, properly by the senses. It is to catch on, to grasp. The disciples did not perceive what Jesus meant about his death. Understanding happens inside the mind, so there is nothing here to see.","flat":1,"g":"perceive","h":"No picture."},"G1430":{"b":"This word comes from a word meaning to build. It settled on the housetop, the flat roof people went up onto. What you hear whispered, proclaim from the housetops, Jesus says. The men lowered the paralytic down through one to reach him.","g":"housetop","h":"The picture: the flat roof of the house."},"G1431":{"b":"From the word for giving, a present laid in your open hand. The dorea is a gift, and its adverb means free of charge. The gift of God, the free gift of righteousness. Nothing paid for it, only given.","g":"gift","h":"The picture: a present laid in your hand."},"G1432":{"b":"The root is a gift, a gratuity, something handed over for nothing. Dōrean is the adverb, freely, gratis, no bill attached. Freely you received, Jesus says, freely give. Paul says we are justified dōrean, put right at no cost to ourselves.","g":"freely","h":"The picture: handed over for nothing."},"G1433":{"b":"The root is a present, a gift. This verb means to hand that gift over freely, expecting nothing back. Pilate uses it when he grants the body of Jesus to Joseph, and Peter says God has given us everything we need for life.","g":"give, bestow","h":"The picture: pressing a gift into someone's hand."},"G1434":{"b":"The root means to give freely, to bestow with nothing asked in return. A dorema is the gift itself, the free present. Paul contrasts one man's sin with the free gift of grace that followed. Something placed in your hands for nothing.","g":"gift","h":"The picture: a present put in your hands."},"G1435":{"b":"Abbott-Smith traces it straight to the verb for giving. A gift, a present.\n\nMost New Testament uses are gifts brought to God at the altar. The word makes no distinction. A present and an offering are one act.","g":"gift, offering","h":"The picture: the thing handed over."},"G1439":{"b":"This word means to let alone, to permit, to leave be. Strong's says it is of uncertain affinity, so no one knows where it came from. There is no picture behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"let, permit","h":"No picture."},"G144":{"b":"The root means to grasp with the senses, the way you feel or taste or smell a thing. Aisthesis is perception. Paul prays their love would grow in knowledge and all discernment, able to tell good from bad.","g":"discernment","h":"The picture: catching it with your senses."},"G1440":{"b":"Abbott builds this from the word for seventh, and behind it the word for seven. Seventy is seven tens, seven full hands of ten counted out. When Jesus sent out seventy, He sent seven tens of workers ahead of Him into the towns.","g":"seventy","h":"The picture: seven full tens."},"G1441":{"b":"The word means seventy times. Peter asks if seven times is enough forgiveness. Jesus answers, not seven but seventy times seven. The number is huge on purpose, so large you stop tallying, forgiveness meant to run past the point of keeping score.","g":"seventy times","h":"The picture: forgiving past all counting."},"G1442":{"b":"This means seventh, built on the number seven. Hebrews points to the seventh day, when God rested from all his work. Seven is the number of completion and rest. A plain count that lands on the sabbath.","g":"seventh","h":"The picture: the seventh day."},"G1443":{"b":"The worksheet gives no clear meaning for this name. Eber was a patriarch, one of the ancestors in the family line long before the days of Abraham.","flat":1,"g":"Eber","h":"No picture."},"G1445":{"b":"Strong's traces the name to Eber, an early patriarch. Abbott notes it marks a Jew of Hebrew speech and custom, not one who had taken up Greek ways. Paul calls himself a Hebrew of Hebrews, Philippians 3:5, claiming the old stock.","g":"Hebrew","h":"The picture: a son of Eber."},"G1446":{"b":"This is the Hebrew tongue, really the Aramaic spoken in Palestine, named after Eber the patriarch. When Paul spoke to the mob in their own language, this word, the shouting died down and they grew quiet to listen.","g":"Hebrew","h":"The picture: hearing your own mother tongue."},"G1447":{"b":"This is the adverb in Hebrew, or in the Aramaic then spoken. The charge over the cross was written in Hebrew, Latin, and Greek, so everyone could read it. The mother tongue on the page.","g":"in Hebrew","h":"The picture: the sign written in Hebrew."},"G1448":{"b":"Strong's reads it as to make near. Abbott-Smith gives both sides: to bring near, and to come near.\n\nIt is used of people walking up to someone, and of a day or an hour getting close.","g":"draw near","h":"The picture: closing the gap."},"G1449":{"b":"The word joins in and write, and Strong's reads it engrave, inscribe. Not ink on a page but marks cut in. Paul says the Corinthians are a letter written not on stone but on human hearts. Names carved so they stay.","g":"engrave, inscribe","h":"The picture: letters cut into the surface."},"G145":{"b":"This means an organ of perception, like the tongue that tastes or the eye that sees. Trained by long practice, the senses grow sharp. The mature use them to tell good from evil apart.","g":"senses","h":"The picture: the tongue trained to taste."},"G1450":{"b":"This is a surety, the one who pledges himself for another's debt. Strong's ties it to a hand given in pledge. Jesus stands as the guarantee of a better covenant, staking himself for it.","g":"surety","h":"The picture: the one who stands as your guarantee."},"G1451":{"b":"Strong's ties this to the word for an arm, the curved arm. Engys is near, close enough to reach out and touch. So the kingdom of God is engys, at hand, near as the thing your fingers could brush, and the Lord is near.","g":"near","h":"The picture: close enough to touch, within arm's reach."},"G1452":{"b":"This word means nearer. It is built on a word for near, close by in place or time. Paul uses it of salvation. It is nearer now than when we first believed. The gap is smaller than it was.","g":"nearer","h":"The picture: the distance closing."},"G1453":{"b":"Strong's says the word means to waken, to rouse, first of all from sleep. Abbott-Smith starts there too: to arouse from sleep.\n\nThe same word is then used for raising the dead. Death is being handled like a nap.","g":"raise, wake up","h":"The picture: shaking a sleeper awake."},"G1454":{"b":"The root means to rouse someone, to wake them from sleep or lift them from their seat. This word is the waking. Abbott says here it is a rising from death. In Matthew 27:53 the dead come out of the tombs after Jesus is raised.","g":"resurrection","h":"The picture: waking from sleep."},"G1455":{"b":"Built from a word for in and a word meaning to lower or let down. Picture a man secretly planted among the crowd to lie in wait. They sent spies pretending to be honest, hoping to catch Jesus in his words.","g":"spy","h":"The picture: a spy let down among the people."},"G1456":{"b":"This word is built on the word for new. It names the feast that marked the temple being made fresh again after it was defiled. Not new from scratch. Renewed. The old thing cleaned and given back.","g":"dedication, renewal","h":"The picture: making it new again."},"G1457":{"b":"This word is built on the word for new. To dedicate here is to inaugurate, to open something fresh for the first time. Hebrews says Christ opened a new and living way through the curtain. A path never walked before, now thrown wide open.","g":"dedicate, inaugurate","h":"The picture: opening something brand new."},"G1458":{"b":"Enkaleo first meant to call in a debt, to summon a man to pay up. Then it moved into court, to call a charge against someone. No one can bring a charge against God's elect. The summons that finds no one to answer.","g":"accuse","h":"The picture: calling in a debt."},"G1459":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means to leave behind, and so to abandon or desert. It is the cry from the cross: my God, why have you left me behind. To forsake is to walk off and leave someone there.","g":"forsake, abandon","h":"The picture: left behind."},"G146":{"b":"This word joins a root meaning shameful and base with the word for gain. It is greed for dirty money, profit a man should be ashamed to take. Paul says an overseer must not be like this. Not the one who grabs at gain no matter how it smells.","g":"greedy for gain","h":"The picture: grabbing at dirty money."},"G1460":{"b":"This joins \"in\" to a root meaning to house permanently, to settle down. So it is living right among others. Peter says righteous Lot, living among the wicked, was tormented day by day by what he saw.","g":"dwell among","h":"The picture: making your home in the middle of them."},"G1461":{"b":"Strong's says to prick in, i.e. ingraft, and the root is a sharp point. To enkentrizo is to cut a slit and press a fresh branch into the wound so it grows. Paul says God grafted the wild branch into the good tree that way.","g":"graft in","h":"The picture: a branch pressed into the tree."},"G1462":{"b":"The root means to call someone in, the way a lender calls in a debt. A charge is a demand called against you, brought to account. It is being summoned to answer for what is said to be owed.","g":"charge","h":"The picture: a debt called in."},"G1463":{"b":"Abbott traces this to a knot, and to the apron a slave tied on over his clothes for work. So Peter tells them to tie on humility toward each other, like a servant knotting on his apron.","g":"be clothed with","h":"The picture: tying on a slave's apron."},"G1464":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to cut into, to impede. It pictures a road cut across to block the way and stop an advance. Paul bore all things so as to put no such cut in the path of the gospel.","g":"hindrance","h":"The picture: the road cut to block the way."},"G1465":{"b":"Strong's says this means to cut into. The root is a word for chopping. Picture breaking up the road so no one can pass. That is the word for hindering someone. Not a soft delay, but the path chopped through.","g":"hinder","h":"The picture: cutting a trench across the road."},"G1466":{"b":"The root means \"strong in a thing (masterful),\" having a grip. Add \"in\" and it is a grip on yourself, holding your own passions in hand. Paul reasons with Felix about this self-control, and Felix trembles. A firm hand on the reins within.","g":"self-control","h":"The picture: a firm grip on yourself."},"G1467":{"b":"The root means strong in a thing, masterful, holding power within. Paul uses it of the athlete who is temperate in all things, keeping a firm grip on himself so he can win the prize.","g":"self-control","h":"The picture: a firm grip on yourself."},"G1468":{"b":"This joins 'in' to a word for strength and grip. To be temperate is to have a strong hold on yourself, master of your own appetites. An overseer must be like this. His hand is closed firmly around his own desires.","g":"self-controlled","h":"The picture: a firm grip on yourself."},"G1469":{"b":"The roots are in and judge. Strong's says to judge in, to count among. Paul says the boasters measure themselves by themselves, and he will not rank himself into their number by their rules.","g":"count among","h":"The picture: a judge sorting a man into the accepted group."},"G147":{"b":"Abbott explains it as \"from eagerness for base gain.\" It is the greed that grabs at dirty profit. Peter tells the elders to tend the flock not for money like this, but with a ready mind.","g":"filthy lucre","h":"The picture: reaching for shameful money."},"G1470":{"b":"Built from in and a word meaning to conceal by covering. So it means to hide something inside something else. Jesus says a woman hid leaven in the meal until it all rose. Picture yeast worked deep into the dough.","g":"to hide in","h":"The picture: yeast hidden in the dough."},"G1471":{"b":"Strong's reads this as swelling inside. The second root is the word for a billow, a wave that rises and swells. So pregnancy is pictured as the body swelling like a wave lifting. Mary was great with child when they reached Bethlehem.","g":"pregnant","h":"The picture: swelling like a rising wave."},"G1472":{"b":"The word is \"in\" plus a word meaning to smear or rub with oil. Abbott-Smith gives \"to rub in, anoint.\" Picture fingers working ointment into sore eyes. So Christ tells the church to rub in salve so it can see.","g":"to anoint","h":"The picture: rubbing oil into the skin."},"G1474":{"b":"The root is a word for the soil, the ground. This verb means to bring a thing down flat with the earth. They will dash you to the ground, Jesus said, you and your children within you, and leave nothing standing.","g":"level to the ground","h":"The picture: buildings leveled to the ground."},"G1475":{"b":"The word comes from the idea of something that sits fixed and immovable. It means the ground, the floor, the bottom you stand on. When Paul is knocked down on the Damascus road, this is what he falls to. The firm earth that does not move.","g":"ground","h":"The picture: the solid ground under your feet."},"G1476":{"b":"Abbott traces this to hedra, a seat. So the word first means seated, planted, sitting firm. From there it came to mean steadfast, immovable. Paul says be like this, unshaken in the work of the Lord, fixed as a man in his chair.","g":"steadfast","h":"The picture: seated and planted."},"G1477":{"b":"The root means seated and immovable. A hedraioma is the solid support that props a thing up, a bulwark that will not shift. Paul calls the church the pillar and ground of the truth, holding it steady.","g":"support","h":"The picture: the firm base that holds it up."},"G1478":{"b":"The name means strengthened of Jah. It joins a word meaning to fasten upon, to make strong, with Jah, a short form of the Lord's name. Hezekiah was a faithful king of Judah.","g":"Hezekiah","h":"The picture: strengthened of the Lord."},"G1479":{"b":"This joins a word for the will and a word for worship. So it is self-imposed worship, devotion a person chooses on his own that God never asked for. Paul says such made-up religion looks wise but does nothing for the flesh.","g":"will-worship","h":"The picture: worship you picked for yourself."},"G148":{"b":"This is built from a word for shameful and a word for speech. So it means abusive, dirty talk, foul words spoken out loud. Paul tells them to put it away, along with anger and malice.","g":"filthy talk","h":"The picture: filthy words out of the mouth."},"G1480":{"b":"The root is a custom, a usage shaped by habit. To do this is to accustom, to make something customary. Luke uses the settled form: Joseph and Mary brought the child to do what the custom of the law required. The groove worn by long practice.","g":"accustom","h":"The picture: the well-worn habit."},"G1481":{"b":"The roots are nation and ruler. Strong's says the governor, not king, of a district. Paul tells how the ethnarch under King Aretas guarded Damascus to seize him, and he escaped down the wall.","g":"ethnarch","h":"The picture: a governor set over a people, below a king."},"G1482":{"b":"The root is ethnos, a nation or foreign tribe. An ethnikos is one of the outside peoples, a Gentile, not of Israel. Jesus uses it for those who do not know God, warning his followers not to pray or love the way the outsiders do.","g":"Gentile, heathen","h":"The picture: the outsider from the nations."},"G1483":{"b":"The root is ethnos, the nations, the Gentiles. This means in Gentile fashion. Paul confronts Peter with it: if you, a Jew, live like a Gentile, why force Gentiles to live like Jews. Caught eating freely, then pulling back for show.","g":"as a Gentile","h":"The picture: living like a Gentile."},"G1484":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's oldest sense, from Homer, is a multitude or company, whether of beasts or men. Strong's says a race, people of the same habit.\n\nA nation here is a group that lives the same way, not a country on a map.","g":"nation, Gentiles","h":"The picture: a herd moving together."},"G1485":{"b":"The root means to be used to a thing by habit. Ethos is the well-worn groove, the way it is always done. Luke says Jesus went to the Mount of Olives as was his custom, the familiar path his feet already knew. Habit hardened into practice.","g":"custom","h":"The picture: the well-worn groove of habit."},"G1486":{"b":"This word just means to be used to a thing, to do it out of habit. There is no object here to see, only the settled way a person always acts. As his custom was, Luke says, Jesus went to the synagogue.","flat":1,"g":"be custom","h":"No picture."},"G1491":{"b":"Strong's calls this a view, the form a thing shows to the eye. It comes from a word for seeing. The Spirit came down in bodily form like a dove, something you could look at. The outward shape.","g":"form, appearance","h":"The picture: the outward look the eye sees."},"G1492":{"b":"Abbott-Smith defines it as to have seen or perceived, and from there, to know.\n\nStrong's says the same. The word is really the past tense of seeing. What you have laid eyes on, you now know.","g":"know, be aware","h":"The picture: knowing because you saw it."},"G1493":{"b":"This comes from a word for an image made for worship, an idol. An eidoleion is the idol's house, the temple built to hold it. Paul warns against sitting down to eat inside such a place.","g":"idol's temple","h":"The picture: the house built for an idol."},"G1494":{"b":"Abbott-Smith builds it from idol and to sacrifice. It pictures the meat of an animal offered to an idol, then sold in the market or served at a meal. That leftover meat is the whole question in Corinth.","g":"food offered to idols","h":"The picture: meat left over from a sacrifice."},"G1495":{"b":"The word joins two roots: an image made for worship, and the service given to God. Put together it is worship handed to an image. So idolatry is service that belongs to God, poured out before a statue instead.","g":"idolatry","h":"The picture: bowing to a statue."},"G1496":{"b":"It joins eidolon, a carved image for worship, with a word for a servant on hire. The eidololatres is one hired out to a statue, bowing and serving a thing of wood and stone, an idolater in service to what cannot answer.","g":"idolater","h":"The picture: a servant bowing to a statue."},"G1497":{"b":"Strong's says the word means an image, one made for worship. An idol is just that, a made image, a stand-in for a god. It is not the real thing, only a copy people bowed to.","g":"idol","h":"The picture: only an image."},"G15":{"b":"This joins two words, good and to do. It means to actually do good, not just wish it. Abbott points to Jesus asking whether the sabbath is for doing good or harm, then healing. Goodness that acts.","g":"do good","h":"The picture: hands doing good."},"G150":{"b":"Abbott traces this to a word meaning shame and disgrace. The picture is the thing that makes a face burn to be seen doing it. Paul says it is aischros even to speak of what such people do in secret, Ephesians 5:12.","g":"shameful, filthy","h":"The picture: the thing that makes a face burn."},"G1500":{"b":"It means without cause, or to no purpose, in vain. Paul fears he labored over the Galatians vainly, fruitlessly, to no purpose. Effort poured out that yields empty hands. Work with no harvest.","g":"in vain","h":"The picture: labor that comes to nothing."},"G1501":{"b":"This is simply the number twenty. Strong's says it is of uncertain affinity, so no one knows where it came from. It is a number and nothing more. There is no picture to see.","flat":1,"g":"twenty","h":"No picture."},"G1502":{"b":"Strong's says properly to be weak, to yield. Abbott-Smith gives to yield. Paul says he did not give way to the false teachers, not for an hour, refusing to step back even under pressure.","g":"give way, yield","h":"The picture: a man giving ground, stepping back under a push."},"G1503":{"b":"Abbott gives to be like, to resemble. James says the doubter eiko, is like a wave of the sea, driven and tossed by the wind, James 1:6. And like a man who studies his face in a mirror and walks off forgetting it. A word of likeness.","g":"be like, resemble","h":"The picture: looking just like it."},"G1504":{"b":"Abbott-Smith explains this as a derived likeness, like the head on a coin or a parent's face showing in a child. It always implies an original behind it.\n\nJesus held up a coin and asked whose image was on it.","g":"image, likeness","h":"The picture: the face stamped on a coin."},"G1505":{"b":"The root means judged by sunlight, tested as genuine. You held a thing up to the sun to see if it hid any flaw. Eilikrineia is that kind of purity, clean when held to the light, what Paul calls sincerity and truth.","g":"sincerity","h":"The picture: held up to the sunlight."},"G1506":{"b":"Strong's says this word means judged by sunlight. You hold a thing up to the sun to see if it is pure, if cracks or dirt hide inside. Paul prays they be sincere, tested in full light and found genuine. Nothing hidden in the shadows.","g":"pure, sincere","h":"The picture: held up to the sunlight."},"G151":{"b":"The root means shameful, base. This is baseness, filthiness, the ugly and shameful. Paul lists it among things that should not even be named among the saints: filthiness, foolish talk, coarse joking. The grime that clings to lips and does not belong in holy company.","g":"filthiness","h":"The picture: talk that shames."},"G1514":{"b":"Built from the word for peace. Jesus says have salt in yourselves and eireneuo with one another, Mark 9:50. As far as it depends on you, Paul adds, live at peace with all men. Not just wanting peace but keeping it.","g":"live in peace","h":"The picture: keeping the peace."},"G1515":{"b":"Strong's says it probably comes from a verb meaning to join. The old King James even renders it set at one again.\n\nAbbott's senses fit. Peace between people. Concord. Two sides put back together.","g":"peace","h":"The picture: joined back together."},"G1516":{"b":"Built from the word for peace. Abbott gives peaceful. Discipline is painful at the time, Hebrews says, but afterward it yields the eirenikos fruit of righteousness, Hebrews 12:11. The wisdom from above is first pure, then peaceable. Peace-bearing.","g":"peaceable","h":"The picture: the calm after the rod."},"G1517":{"b":"The word joins peace and to make: to make peace, to build it where there was war. Paul uses it of the cross: through him God reconciled all things, making peace by the blood of his cross. Peace not merely wished but manufactured, at terrible cost.","g":"make peace","h":"The picture: hands that build peace."},"G1518":{"b":"The word joins peace and to make: peace-making, a peacemaker, one whose work is building peace. Jesus blesses them in the Sermon: blessed are the peacemakers, for they shall be called sons of God. Not the peace-lovers but the ones who go make it.","g":"peacemaker","h":"The picture: the peace-builder."},"G152":{"b":"The root is to feel shame for yourself. This is the disgrace that makes you want to cover up and hide your face. Revelation speaks of the shame of nakedness. Jesus faced the cross and thought nothing of its shame.","g":"shame","h":"The picture: the face you want to hide."},"G1520":{"b":"Strong's calls it a primary numeral. Numbers this basic do not come from anything else. Abbott-Smith gives no history, only the uses, including one as against many. There is nothing behind it.","flat":1,"g":"one","h":"No picture."},"G1521":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means to bring in. The word is made of into and lead. It is the picture of taking someone by the hand and leading them in through the door to a place.","g":"bring in, lead in","h":"The picture: leading someone in."},"G1522":{"b":"The parts mean \"into\" and to hear. Eisakouo is hearing that goes all the way in, hearing that answers. It is used of God hearing prayer, not just catching the sound but taking it in and acting on it.","g":"listen to","h":"The picture: hearing that goes all the way in."},"G1523":{"b":"The roots are into and receive. Abbott-Smith gives to admit, receive. God says come out from them, and I will take you in, welcomed through the door as his own.","g":"receive","h":"The picture: opening the door and taking someone inside."},"G1524":{"b":"The word is \"into\" plus \"to go,\" a plain \"to or into (indicating the point reached or entered).\" Simply to step in, to pass through the doorway. Paul goes in to the temple, the priests go in to do their service. The plain act of entering.","g":"enter, go in","h":"The picture: stepping in through the doorway."},"G1525":{"b":"Strong's builds this from two pieces: into, and come.\n\nAbbott-Smith fills in the doorways. People go in through gates and doors, under a roof. Food goes in. Demons go in. Thoughts go in. Anything that crosses a threshold.","g":"enter, go in","h":"The picture: walking in through a gate."},"G1528":{"b":"The word joins 'into' with 'to call.' Peter calls the strangers in and gives them a bed for the night, the first crack in the wall between Jew and Gentile.","g":"call in, invite in","h":"The picture: calling a guest in over the threshold."},"G1529":{"b":"Built from a word meaning into and a word meaning a road or way. It is the way in, the road that leads through the door. We have boldness to enter the holy place, an entrance opened by Jesus. The path inside.","g":"entrance","h":"The picture: the road that leads in."},"G153":{"b":"The word comes from a word for shame, and its first sense is to disfigure, to mar. Shame shows on the face and the head drops. The steward said he was ashamed to beg. A face marred, unable to look up.","g":"be ashamed","h":"The picture: a face that will not lift."},"G1530":{"b":"Built from \"into\" and a word meaning to leap. It is a running jump through the doorway. The jailer, when the earthquake stopped and the prisoners stayed, called for lights and sprang in trembling and fell down before Paul.","g":"rush in","h":"The picture: leaping in through the door."},"G1531":{"b":"Strong's builds it from into and a verb for going. Abbott-Smith gives to go into, enter.\n\nOne phrase in his list is worth seeing. House after house, used of a man dragging Christians out of their homes.","g":"go in, enter","h":"The picture: walking in through the door."},"G1532":{"b":"The word joins 'into' with 'to run.' It is Rhoda, so overjoyed at Peter's voice that she runs back inside without opening, to tell them he is standing at the gate.","g":"run in","h":"The picture: running in through the door."},"G1533":{"b":"Strong's: \"to carry inward.\" Abbott: \"to bring in, into.\" It joins \"into\" with \"carry.\" It is simply carrying or leading someone in through a door, like the men who carried the paralyzed man in to Jesus.","g":"bring in","h":"The picture: carrying something in through the door."},"G1534":{"b":"This is just a joining word. It means then, next, after that. Strong's says it is of uncertain affinity, so no one is sure where it came from. There is nothing behind it to picture.","flat":1,"g":"then, next","h":"No picture."},"G1538":{"b":"Strong's can only offer a puzzled guess, as if a superlative of a word meaning afar. Abbott gives nothing. The word means each and every, one at a time.","flat":1,"g":"each, every","h":"No picture."},"G1539":{"b":"The word joins each and then: at each time, always. Peter uses it near his death: I will make every effort so that after my departure you may be able at any time to recall these things. Not now and again but on every occasion.","g":"always","h":"The picture: every single time."},"G154":{"b":"Strong's says the derivation is uncertain. Abbott gives none. It means to ask or request. He notes that it and a second Greek word for asking had blurred together by then.","flat":1,"g":"ask","h":"No picture."},"G1540":{"b":"This is just the number one hundred. Strong's says its origin is of uncertain affinity. A number has nothing behind it to see. It counts and stops there.","flat":1,"g":"a hundred","h":"No picture."},"G1541":{"b":"This simply joins a hundred with a year. So it means a hundred years old. Abbott says a hundred years old. Paul says Abraham was this old, his body as good as dead, yet he did not waver at God's promise of a son.","g":"hundred years old","h":"The picture: a body worn out by a hundred years."},"G1542":{"b":"A hundred times over. Picture the good soil, where one seed gave back a hundredfold at harvest, Mark 4:8. Jesus promises the same to those who leave home for Him, a hundred returned for what was given up. The harvest dwarfs the seed.","g":"hundredfold","h":"The picture: one seed, a hundred back."},"G1543":{"b":"Abbott-Smith builds it from the word for a hundred and the word for rule. Strong's states it plainly. The captain of one hundred men.\n\nThe English word centurion hides the number. The Greek says it out loud.","g":"centurion","h":"The picture: the officer over a hundred."},"G1544":{"b":"Strong's says eject. Abbott lists the uses, including expulsion from home and from the church.\n\nIt is also the word for driving out demons. And oddly, for sending workers into the harvest.","g":"cast out, drive out","h":"The picture: put out of the house."},"G1545":{"b":"This is built from out and a word for a step or footing. It means a way out, the place where you can step clear. Paul says God gives with every temptation a way of escape, so you can bear it.","g":"way out","h":"The picture: the step clear of trouble."},"G1546":{"b":"This comes from ekballo, to throw out. It means the jettison, the throwing of cargo overboard. Beaten by the storm, the next day they began to lighten the ship, heaving the freight into the sea. The word is that cargo flung over the rail to save the vessel.","g":"jettison","h":"The picture: cargo hurled over the side."},"G1549":{"b":"This joins ek, out of, and ginomai, to be born. So it is one born from you, here a grandchild sprung from your children. Paul says let children and grandchildren learn to repay their parents.","g":"grandchild","h":"The picture: one born out of your own line."},"G155":{"b":"Built from the word to ask, this means the thing asked for, the request itself. Pilate grants the crowd's request and releases Barabbas. Paul says let your requests be made known to God. Not the asking only, but the item named in it.","g":"petition, request","h":"The picture: the very thing you ask for."},"G1550":{"b":"The root is to spend money, with out driving it to the end. Abbott-Smith says to spend oneself wholly. Paul says he will gladly spend and be spent for their souls, poured out to the bottom.","g":"spend fully","h":"The picture: emptying the purse down to the last coin."},"G1551":{"b":"The parts mean from and to receive. To wait with open hands for something to come to you. The farmer waits for the precious fruit of the earth. Abraham waited for the city with foundations. Expecting, with your hand already out.","g":"await, expect","h":"The picture: waiting with open hands."},"G1552":{"b":"This joins 'out' to a word meaning clear. Together it means fully clear, plain for all to see. Paul says the folly of these men will become manifest, dragged out where everyone can see it. Nothing left hidden.","g":"manifest","h":"The picture: brought out into the open."},"G1553":{"b":"The roots are ek, out, and demos, your own town and people. So the word is to be away from home, abroad. It pairs with its opposite. To be absent from the body, Paul says, is to be present with the Lord.","g":"be absent","h":"The picture: away from home."},"G1554":{"b":"The word is \"give\" with \"out\" in front. It means to give a thing out of your hands to someone else, here to let out for hire. The vineyard owner does this, leasing his land to tenants and going away.","g":"lease, let out","h":"The picture: handing your field out to renters."},"G1555":{"b":"The heart of this word means to lead. To tell a thing in full is to lead your hearer all the way through it, out the far side, leaving nothing out. So Paul warns of a work so great no one could lead you through the telling of it.","g":"declare","h":"The picture: leading someone the whole way through a story."},"G1556":{"b":"The root idea is carrying justice out, a punisher who follows the sentence through. The widow keeps coming, avenge me against my adversary. Paul says leave it, do not avenge yourselves. To see that a wrong is paid back and set right.","g":"avenge, vindicate","h":"The picture: justice carried out."},"G1557":{"b":"This is built on the word for justice, with a prefix meaning out or fully. Abbott gives vengeance, vindication. So it is setting a wrong fully right, whether that clears the victim or punishes the offender. Vengeance is mine, says the Lord.","g":"vengeance","h":"The picture: justice carried all the way out."},"G1558":{"b":"This is built from a word meaning justice and a word meaning out. The ekdikos carries justice out, the one who exacts the penalty owed. Paul says the ruler bears the sword as exactly this, God's avenger on the wrongdoer.","g":"avenger","h":"The picture: the one who collects the penalty."},"G1559":{"b":"The root dioko means to chase, the way a hunter runs down game. The ek adds out. So it is driving someone off, hunting them away. Paul says they drove out the prophets and him, and please not God.","g":"drive out","h":"The picture: chasing a man out like prey."},"G156":{"b":"Strong's explains it as a cause, as if asked for. The reason you would give.\n\nAbbott-Smith adds the courtroom use. The charge against a man. It is the word used for the writing above the cross.","g":"cause, charge","h":"The picture: the answer when someone asks why."},"G1560":{"b":"This word joins out and to give. It means given up, handed over. Peter says Jesus was delivered up by God's own set plan, and then killed. The word is about being placed out of one hand and into another.","g":"delivered","h":"The picture: handed over into other hands."},"G1561":{"b":"This comes from the word to await, to receive from. It is the waiting that expects something to come. For those who keep sinning there remains only a fearful looking for of judgment and fire.","g":"looking for","h":"The picture: waiting with hands out to receive."},"G1562":{"b":"This word is built from a word meaning to go down and a word for out. Picture a garment sinking off the shoulders, sliding down and away. That is undressing. The soldiers used it when they stripped Jesus of his clothes.","g":"strip off","h":"The picture: a robe sliding off the body."},"G1563":{"b":"Strong's says the origins are uncertain. It is a small pointing word meaning there, and with verbs of motion, to that place. There is nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"there","h":"No picture."},"G1564":{"b":"This is built on ekei, there. Ekeithen means from there, thence, the point you move away from. So Jesus departs ekeithen, from that place, moving on from town to town. The word marks the spot left behind in his tracks.","g":"thence","h":"The picture: away from that spot, leaving there."},"G1566":{"b":"Built from the word for there. Abbott gives thither, meaning to that place. The ship was headed to Tyre, for there, ekeise, it was to unload its cargo, Acts 21:3. A word that points away from you, off toward yonder place.","g":"thither, there","h":"The picture: pointing to yonder place."},"G1567":{"b":"Ek means out, and zeteo means to seek. Ekzeteo is not a glance around the room but a search that turns everything over until the thing is found. It is the word for seeking God, who rewards those who search him out.","g":"seek out","h":"The picture: searching until you find it."},"G1568":{"b":"Strong's root means utterly astounded. Abbott gives to be amazed, terrified. Picture the crowd that saw Jesus coming down from the mountain and were ekthambeo, struck to the core, Mark 9:15. This is amazement that shakes a person where they stand.","g":"greatly amaze","h":"The picture: struck to the core."},"G1569":{"b":"The word is thambos, astonishment, with ek driving it clean out, utterly amazed. Luke uses it after the lame man walks: the people ran together to Solomon's portico, greatly amazed. Wonder so strong it drives a crowd off its feet toward the miracle.","g":"greatly amazed","h":"The picture: struck out of your senses."},"G157":{"b":"The root is a cause, and in law a crime alleged. This is the charge itself, a charge, accusation. Luke uses it at Paul's trial: the Jews stood around him, bringing many serious charges they could not prove. The indictment piled up, all of it hollow.","g":"accusation","h":"The picture: charges laid at your feet."},"G1570":{"b":"The word joins 'out' with 'to place,' placed outside. Strong's says exposed to perish. In Acts it is the Hebrew infants, set out in the open by Pharaoh's order so they would not live.","g":"cast out, exposed","h":"The picture: a baby left outside to die."},"G1571":{"b":"This is built from out and a word for cleansing. It means to cleanse out, to sweep every last bit away. Paul tells the church to purge out the old leaven, so the whole lump is fresh and new.","g":"purge out","h":"The picture: sweeping out the old leaven."},"G1572":{"b":"The root means to set on fire, to kindle. Add the word for out. So it is fire breaking out and burning up. Abbott uses it of the passions catching. Paul says men were inflamed with lust for one another.","g":"burn, inflame","h":"The picture: bursting into flame."},"G1573":{"b":"The parts mean out and bad or weak. To have your strength go bad and drain out, to lose heart. It is what happens to someone who keeps praying and sees no answer. Do not faint, do not let your courage leak away.","g":"faint, lose heart","h":"The picture: courage draining out."},"G1574":{"b":"The root is a point, a sting or goad, and \"out\" is added. Abbott says \"to pierce.\" John says they will look on the one they pierced. It is the spear thrust into Jesus' side, run through, the wound John saw with his own eyes.","g":"pierce","h":"The picture: driving a sharp point clean through."},"G1575":{"b":"The roots are ek, off, and klao, to break, the same word used for breaking bread. So the word is to snap something off. Paul uses it for branches broken off the olive tree so that others could be grafted in.","g":"break off","h":"The picture: a branch snapped off."},"G1576":{"b":"Built from out and to close, the shutting of a door against someone. Paul asks where boasting is: it is shut out, the door closed on it. Faith leaves pride standing outside. A door swung shut so it cannot come in.","g":"shut out","h":"The picture: a door closed in your face."},"G1577":{"b":"Strong's says a calling out, and then a popular meeting. Abbott-Smith builds it from the verb to call out, and gives the plain civic sense first: an assembly of citizens regularly convened.\n\nIt is a word for a gathering, not a building.","g":"church, assembly","h":"The picture: the town called out to a meeting."},"G1578":{"b":"The roots are ek, out, and klino, to lean or bend. So the word is to bend yourself out of the road, to step aside. Abbott says it means turning away from the right path. In Romans all have turned aside, everyone has leaned out of the way.","g":"turn aside","h":"The picture: bending out of the road."},"G1579":{"b":"This is ek, out, plus kolymbao, to plunge into water and swim. It means to escape by swimming out. The soldiers wanted to kill the prisoners in case any should swim off and get away. The word is a man diving into the water and striking out for land.","g":"swim out","h":"The picture: plunging into the sea and swimming for shore."},"G158":{"b":"The word means a cause, a ground, and so a fault worth charging, a reason or crime. Pilate uses its family at the trial: I find no fault in this man, no basis for the charge. It is the ground a case stands on, and here there is none.","g":"cause, fault","h":"The picture: no ground for a charge."},"G1580":{"b":"This word joins out and to carry. Abbott-Smith notes it was the regular word for carrying a corpse out for burial. They were bearing the widow's dead son out of the town gate when Jesus met the procession and stopped it.","g":"carry out","h":"The picture: carrying the dead out for burial."},"G1581":{"b":"Strong's lists cut down, cut off, hew down. The word joins out and a word for cutting or striking. It is the axe taken to a tree that bears no fruit, chopped down and thrown away.","g":"cut off, cut down","h":"The picture: chopping a tree down."},"G1582":{"b":"Strong's says it means to hang upon the lips of a speaker, built from a word for hanging. Picture a listener leaning in, his whole weight resting on each word. All the people hung on Jesus as he taught in the temple.","g":"be attentive","h":"The picture: hanging on the speaker's lips."},"G1583":{"b":"This is laleo, to talk, with ek, out. To divulge is to let the words out, to spill what was meant to stay hidden. Paul's nephew hears of the plot and tells it to the commander. The word is speech leaking out where the plotters did not want it.","g":"divulge","h":"The picture: words let out into the open."},"G1584":{"b":"Built from out and a word meaning to beam, to radiate brightness. So it means to blaze forth, to shine out. Jesus says the righteous will shine like the sun in the kingdom. Picture light bursting out, too bright to face.","g":"shine forth","h":"The picture: light blazing out."},"G1585":{"b":"The root means to lie hidden, out of sight. Add \"utterly\" and the thing drops completely from view. Hebrews says you have wholly forgotten the encouragement spoken to you. It slipped clean out of sight.","g":"forget","h":"The picture: a thing that slips out of sight."},"G1586":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says to pick out, choose. In the New Testament it is nearly always in the middle voice, which he renders to pick out for oneself.\n\nSo the choosing is personal. The chooser wanted this one.","g":"choose","h":"The picture: picking one out of the pile."},"G1587":{"b":"Abbott points to Luke 23:45, the sun in an eclipse. The word means to leave off, to cease, to give out. A light that was there simply stops. So when faith is said to fail, it is a lamp going out.","g":"fail","h":"The picture: the sun going dark in an eclipse."},"G1588":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is choice, select. It comes from the verb meaning to pick out.\n\nSomeone went through and lifted this one from the rest. That is what the word says. Chosen, not merely present.","g":"chosen","h":"The picture: picked out by hand."},"G1589":{"b":"Ek means out, and lego means to pick or gather. Ekloge pictures reaching into a group and picking some out. In the New Testament it is always God who chooses. A chosen vessel, lifted out from the rest by his own hand.","g":"election, choice","h":"The picture: picking some out of the group."},"G159":{"b":"Strong's gives a causer, and Abbott traces the word to a term for cause. The aitios is the one a thing comes from, the source. Hebrews says Christ became the aitios of eternal salvation, the cause every saved life traces back to.","g":"author, cause","h":"The picture: the source a thing flows from."},"G1590":{"b":"Abbott-Smith pictures a bowstring unstrung, loosed and gone slack. To be ekluo is to lose all your tension, to go limp with weariness. Do not ekluo in doing good, Paul says. Do not let your string sag before the harvest.","g":"to faint","h":"The picture: a bowstring gone slack."},"G1591":{"b":"This means to wipe off, to wipe a thing dry with pressure. The woman wet Jesus' feet with her tears and wiped them with the hair of her head. Rubbing something clean and dry, hard against the skin.","g":"wipe","h":"The picture: wiping something dry by hand."},"G1592":{"b":"The word is built on the nose. Abbott says \"to hold up the nose in derision at, scoff at.\" It is the sneer that lifts the nostrils. The rulers do it at the foot of the cross, curling their lips at a dying man.","g":"deride, sneer","h":"The picture: turning up the nose in scorn."},"G1593":{"b":"Built from a word for out and a word meaning to nod. Abbott says it first meant to bend the head aside, then to turn away and slip off. Jesus had withdrawn, a crowd being in the place. He turned aside quietly and was gone.","g":"withdraw","h":"The picture: a turn of the head and slip away."},"G1594":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means to become sober after drunkenness. The head clears, the fog lifts. Paul tells them to wake up like that, out of the stupor of sin, and stop giving it a home.","g":"awake, sober up","h":"The picture: the morning you sober up after being drunk."},"G1595":{"b":"Abbott says this describes an act done of free will. A hekousion offering is one you bring because you want to, with no hand forcing you. So it measures the heart. Not what you were made to give, but what you chose to give.","g":"voluntariness","h":"The picture: nobody is twisting your arm."},"G1596":{"b":"Built from a word meaning of one's own will. Abbott gives voluntarily, willingly. Peter says shepherd God's flock hekousios, not under compulsion but freely, First Peter 5:2. A thing done by choice, with no hand forcing it.","g":"willingly","h":"The picture: done by choice, not forced."},"G1597":{"b":"Built from a word meaning long ago, with out set in front. Abbott gives from of old. Peter says the judgment of the false teachers, decreed ekpalai, from long ago, is not idle, Second Peter 2:3. Something set in motion far back in time.","g":"long ago, of old","h":"The picture: set in motion far back."},"G1598":{"b":"The word is an intensified to test. Abbott-Smith says to put to the proof, to make trial of. It is pressing hard to see what a thing is made of. Jesus answers the tempter, you shall not put the Lord your God to the test.","g":"tempt, test","h":"The picture: putting something to the proof."},"G1599":{"b":"Built from \"out\" and a word meaning to dispatch, it is sending a person off from where you stand, out on their way. The Spirit set apart Barnabas and Saul, and the church sent them out to sail for Cyprus.","g":"send out","h":"The picture: sending someone out the door on their way."},"G16":{"b":"Strong's reads it as well-doing, good actually done. The word joins good to doing, so it is not kind feelings but kind deeds. Peter tells suffering Christians to keep at it. Hands still doing good while it hurts.","g":"well-doing","h":"The picture: good put into action."},"G160":{"b":"The word is built from \"not showing,\" giving no sign ahead. Abbott says \"sudden, unexpected.\" Jesus warns that the day could close on you like a trap, all at once, catching those who never saw it coming. Paul says it comes like labor pains.","g":"sudden, unexpected","h":"The picture: a snare springing with no warning."},"G1600":{"b":"The root is to fly, and this word means to spread out, as a sail catches the wind, to stretch forth. Abbott says to spread out. Paul quotes Isaiah, all day long God stretched out his hands to a stubborn people.","g":"stretch forth","h":"The picture: spreading out like a sail or open wings."},"G1601":{"b":"Built from out and fall. Abbott-Smith points to the withering of flowers, whose petals fall away. He also uses it for a ship driven off its course. To fall from grace is to drop off like that.","g":"fall off, fall away","h":"The picture: petals dropping off."},"G1602":{"b":"This word is built from a word for out and a word meaning to sail. To sail out, the ship leaving port and standing out to sea. From there Paul and his company sailed away toward Syria.","g":"sail away","h":"The picture: a ship sailing out of harbor."},"G1603":{"b":"The root means to fill up, even to cram a net or level up a hollow. With 'fully' in front, it means to fill right to the brim. God, Paul says, has completely filled full the promise to the fathers.","g":"fulfill","h":"The picture: a net crammed full to the edge."},"G1604":{"b":"This means a completion, a fulfilment, a thing carried all the way to full. Nothing left undone. Paul waited for the days of purification to be completed, every one counted out to the end.","g":"completion","h":"The picture: the days run out to the last one."},"G1605":{"b":"Strong's says the word means to strike with astonishment. Abbott adds it first meant to strike out. Amazement lands like a blow. The crowds were struck at Jesus' teaching.","g":"astonish, amaze","h":"The picture: knocked out of yourself."},"G1606":{"b":"The word joins out and breathe. It means to breathe out, and so to breathe one's last. Mark uses it for the moment on the cross when Jesus lets out his final breath. Life leaving on one last exhale.","g":"expire, breathe out","h":"The picture: breathing out for the last time."},"G1607":{"b":"Abbott's sense is to go forth, to come forth, proceed. He lists it used of a river, of a sword, and of what comes out of a person's mouth.\n\nIt is the plain motion of coming out of something.","g":"go out, proceed","h":"The picture: something coming out."},"G1608":{"b":"The root means to act the harlot, to chase unlawful lust. The \"out\" makes it total, giving oneself up entirely. Jude says Sodom and Gomorrah did this, and stand as a warning under eternal fire.","g":"fornication","h":"The picture: giving the body over completely."},"G1609":{"b":"The roots are out and spit. Abbott-Smith says to spit out, to spit at in disgust. Paul says the Galatians did not do that to him when illness made him hard to look at. They took him in instead.","g":"reject, spit out","h":"The picture: spitting something foul out of your mouth."},"G161":{"b":"The root aichmalotos is a prisoner of war. Aichmalosia is captivity, a whole train of captives led away. Paul quotes the psalm, when he ascended he led captivity captive, dragging the captors off as prisoners themselves.","g":"captivity","h":"The picture: a train of captives."},"G1610":{"b":"This word is ek, \"out,\" joined to a word for root. So it does not mean cut down. It means grab the whole plant and pull, roots and all, out of the ground. Jesus uses it for what will not stay planted.","g":"uproot","h":"The picture: a plant torn out by its roots."},"G1611":{"b":"The root means to stand out of your wits, moved clean out of place. Ekstasis is a displacement of the mind, a man carried past his normal self. It became the word for a trance, standing outside yourself, amazement so deep you leave your own mind behind.","g":"trance, amazement","h":"The picture: standing outside your own mind."},"G1612":{"b":"This joins 'out' to a word meaning to twist or turn around. Abbott says it means to turn a thing inside out. Paul says such a person is subverted, twisted completely from what he was. Turned wrong side out and sinning.","g":"subvert","h":"The picture: turned inside out."},"G1613":{"b":"Underneath sits a word meaning to stir or agitate, to roil water. Add a prefix that means completely and you get churning a whole crowd up. Paul's accusers said the two men were troubling their city.","g":"trouble greatly","h":"The picture: stirring water to mud."},"G1614":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means to stretch out or forth. Again and again it is the hand that is stretched. Jesus stretches out his hand and touches the leper. The arm extended, reaching toward.","g":"stretch out","h":"The picture: the hand reaching out."},"G1615":{"b":"This is the word for finishing with \"out\" added, finishing all the way out. Abbott says \"to bring to an end, finish, complete.\" Jesus warns of the man who lays a foundation and cannot finish, and everyone mocks the half-built tower.","g":"finish","h":"The picture: finishing the tower you started."},"G1616":{"b":"The word means intentness, earnestness, the whole self bent toward something. Picture a runner straining forward, every muscle stretched to the goal. Paul says the twelve tribes serve God with this earnestness, night and day. It is effort held at full stretch, not slack.","g":"earnestness","h":"The picture: a body straining forward at full stretch."},"G1617":{"b":"Strong's reads it more intently. It is the pitch of someone leaning in hard, all attention fixed on one thing. Luke uses it of Jesus praying in the garden. Not a mumbled request. Effort poured out, reaching.","g":"more earnestly","h":"The picture: straining forward to catch every word."},"G1618":{"b":"The root means to stretch out. Abbott says this word is literally \"stretched, strained,\" then earnest. Peter tells them to have love stretched at full reach toward one another, love that covers many sins.","g":"fervent","h":"The picture: a muscle stretched to full reach."},"G1619":{"b":"The root pictures a thing intent, stretched out at full strain. Abbott gives fervently, earnestly. While Peter sat in prison, the church prayed ektenos to God for him, Acts 12:5, straining toward heaven without a break. Love one another this way.","g":"fervently, earnestly","h":"The picture: stretched out at full strain."},"G162":{"b":"The root is the word for a prisoner of war, a captive taken in battle. This verb means to lead such a one away. Paul quotes the psalm: Christ ascended on high and led captivity captive.","g":"lead captive","h":"The picture: a prisoner of war led away."},"G1620":{"b":"The word is \"out\" plus \"to place,\" Abbott's \"to set out, expose.\" It is used of baby Moses set out on the water, and of Priscilla and Aquila setting out the way of God plainly to Apollos.","g":"expose, expound","h":"The picture: setting a thing out where all can see."},"G1621":{"b":"The word means to shake off. Abbott-Smith points to shaking the dust from the feet and clothes. Jesus tells the disciples that where they are not welcomed, they should shake the dust off their feet as they leave. A clean break, dust and all.","g":"shake off","h":"The picture: shaking the dust off your feet."},"G1622":{"b":"This comes from ek, out of. Ektos is the outside, the exterior, and as a preposition it means apart from, besides, except. So Paul speaks of being caught up, whether in the body or ektos the body he cannot tell, outside the flesh entirely.","g":"outside, except","h":"The picture: out beyond, on the outside."},"G1624":{"b":"The word is out plus turn. Abbott-Smith says to turn out of the course, to turn aside. Picture leaving the track and wandering off. Paul warns of people who turned aside from the truth into empty talk, off the road and lost.","g":"turn aside","h":"The picture: turning off the road."},"G1625":{"b":"This word is built from a root meaning to feed and nourish. It is what a parent does raising a child, feeding it all the way up to maturity. Paul tells fathers to bring up their children. Not just keep them alive, but feed them to full growth.","g":"bring up, nourish","h":"The picture: feeding a child to full growth."},"G1626":{"b":"Abbott gives it as an untimely birth. It pictures a child born too soon, before its time. Paul uses it of himself, last to see the risen Christ, like one born out of due time.","g":"untimely birth","h":"The picture: a child born too soon."},"G1627":{"b":"Abbott: \"to carry out, bring out.\" It joins \"out\" with \"carry.\" It is carrying something out of a place, including carrying the dead out for burial. It also means the ground bringing forth what grows on it.","g":"carry out","h":"The picture: carrying a thing out the door."},"G1628":{"b":"This is built from out and a word meaning to run away. The picture is a man breaking loose and running, feet moving, getting clear into the open. So to escape is not just to avoid trouble. It is to flee out and away from it.","g":"escape","h":"The picture: breaking out and running."},"G1629":{"b":"The roots are fear and out. Abbott-Smith says to frighten away, terrify. Paul says he does not want to seem to be scaring them off with his stern letters, as if all he had were threats on paper.","g":"terrify","h":"The picture: scaring someone so badly they bolt."},"G163":{"b":"The root is \"a prisoner of war,\" someone caught in battle. This verb means to take that captive and lead him away. So when Paul says sin takes him captive, the picture is a soldier marched off in chains after losing the fight.","g":"lead captive","h":"The picture: a prisoner marched off after the battle."},"G1630":{"b":"Two words: \"out\" and \"fright\". The fear is so strong it pushes you outside your own wits. Strong's says frightened out of one's wits. At the transfiguration the disciples feel it, and Moses says it at the mountain, shaking.","g":"terrified","h":"The picture: fear that drives you out of yourself."},"G1631":{"b":"This joins \"out\" to a word meaning to swell and grow. Ekphyo is to push something out, here the fig tree putting forth its leaves. When the tender branch shoots out leaves, Jesus says, summer is close. The tree tells the time.","g":"put forth","h":"The picture: the branch pushing out its leaves."},"G1632":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first example is John 2:15, where Jesus pours out the money changers' small coins. The word is plain spilling.\n\nThe same verb is used of blood poured out and the Spirit poured out.","g":"pour out","h":"The picture: coins tipped onto the floor."},"G1633":{"b":"Built from a word for out and a word meaning to give space, to move through. To clear out and withdraw. When you see the armies, Jesus said, let those in Judea flee to the hills and get out of the city.","g":"depart out","h":"The picture: clearing out of the place."},"G1634":{"b":"This word is built from a word for out and a word meaning to breathe. It means the breath going out for the last time. Ananias heard the words, fell down, and breathed his last.","g":"expire","h":"The picture: the last breath going out."},"G1635":{"b":"This means willing, of one's own free will. Strong's says its origin is uncertain. Creation was subjected to futility not willingly, not by its own choice. A choice of the will is not something the eye can see.","flat":1,"g":"willingly","h":"No picture."},"G1636":{"b":"This word names the olive tree and its fruit. Strong's traces it to an obsolete primary word, so no origin survives. It simply means olive. There is no image behind the word itself.","flat":1,"g":"olive tree","h":"No picture."},"G1637":{"b":"The root is the olive. Elaion is the oil pressed from it. It burns in the lamps of the wise virgins waiting for the bridegroom. The Samaritan pours it on the wounds of the beaten man. It anoints the sick and the honored guest.","g":"oil","h":"The picture: oil pressed from the olive."},"G1638":{"b":"This word comes from the word for an olive. It means an olive grove, and it named the hill outside Jerusalem thick with olive trees, the Mount of Olives. From there they watched Jesus taken up into the sky.","g":"olive grove","h":"The picture: a hillside of olive trees."},"G1639":{"b":"The name means hidden, and so distant. It comes from a word meaning to veil from sight. An Elamite was a person from Elam, the far country of the Persians.","g":"Elamite","h":"The picture: hidden and distant."},"G164":{"b":"Abbott builds this from the word for a spear and a word for being taken. A captive is one caught in war at spearpoint and led away. Jesus reads the scroll: he was sent to proclaim release to such captives, freedom to the bound.","g":"captive","h":"The picture: a prisoner taken at the spear's point."},"G1640":{"b":"Abbott traces this to an old word meaning little. It is the smaller, the lesser, the younger of two. Paul quotes the word straight from Genesis, the elder shall serve the younger, Romans 9:12. The lesser one is elasson.","g":"less, smaller","h":"The picture: the smaller, the younger one."},"G1641":{"b":"The root means smaller, less in amount. Paul recalls the manna, where the one who gathered little had no lack. The short pile fell short of nothing. God levels it out.","g":"have lack","h":"The picture: the smaller heap that still comes out even."},"G1642":{"b":"The word is built from smaller. It means to make less, to bring down. John the Baptist says of Jesus, he must increase, but I must decrease. Hebrews says man was made a little lower than the angels. Growing smaller so another grows large.","g":"decrease, lessen","h":"The picture: shrinking down smaller."},"G1643":{"b":"This word means to push, as wind pushes or oars push. The disciples were straining at the oars against the wind. The same word covers wind driving a ship and a demon driving a man. Force shoving something along.","g":"drive, row","h":"The picture: oars pushing the boat."},"G1644":{"b":"The root means light, not heavy. Abbott-Smith gives lightness, levity. A light person shifts with every wind. Paul asks if he made his plans that way, saying yes and no in the same breath.","g":"lightness, fickleness","h":"The picture: something so light it drifts on any breeze."},"G1645":{"b":"Elaphros means light in weight, easy to bear. Not heavy, not a strain to lift. Jesus says his yoke is easy and his burden is light. He does not promise no load at all. He promises one you can actually carry.","g":"light (in weight)","h":"The picture: a load light enough to carry easily."},"G1646":{"b":"This word means smallest, least. Strong's says it is the superlative of a word for \"short.\" It is simply the very littlest. There is no image hiding in it.","flat":1,"g":"least, smallest","h":"No picture."},"G1648":{"b":"The name means God is helper. It joins a word for God, or strength, with a word meaning to surround and come to aid. Eleazar was Aaron's son who followed him as priest.","g":"Eleazar","h":"The picture: God is helper."},"G1649":{"b":"The root means to expose and cross-examine. An elenxis is the moment your fault is brought into the light and proved. Peter uses it of Balaam. The donkey's voice was the rebuke that stopped a prophet in his tracks.","g":"rebuke","h":"The picture: caught out and shown the evidence."},"G165":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means a space of time: a lifetime, a generation, a period of history.\n\nSo it is not endlessness first. It is a span. The synonym note calls it the world seen under time.","g":"age, era","h":"The picture: a stretch of time as long as a life."},"G1650":{"b":"This word is proof, the evidence that convicts. The root means to confute, to expose someone as wrong. Faith is called the conviction of things not seen. Not a wish, but the solid proof that settles the matter, evidence you could set on the table.","g":"proof, reproof","h":"The picture: evidence laid on the table."},"G1651":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means to convict, and to reprove or rebuke. It is about proving someone wrong to their face until they see it. There is no concrete image behind the word. It simply means to expose a fault.","flat":1,"g":"convict, rebuke","h":"No picture."},"G1652":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning compassion or pity. Eleeinos means pitiable, the kind that draws mercy out of you. Paul says if our hope in Christ is only for this life, we are of all men most to be pitied.","g":"pitiable","h":"The picture: the one you cannot help but pity."},"G1653":{"b":"This comes from eleos, compassion, mercy. To eleeo is to have pity on someone and act, to bend toward the misery of another. So the blind men cry Son of David, have mercy, eleeson, asking not for a coin but for a hand that reaches down.","g":"have mercy","h":"The picture: bending down to the wretched."},"G1654":{"b":"Abbott says the word first means mercy, pity. Giving to the poor was simply doing a mercy. Our English word \"alms\" is worn down from this very Greek word.","g":"alms, mercy","h":"The picture: mercy you can hand over."},"G1655":{"b":"Strong's builds this on a word meaning to show compassion by word or deed. So mercy here is not soft feeling that stays inside. Abbott says merciful. This mercy has hands. It reaches the person in front of you and does something.","g":"merciful","h":"The picture: mercy that does something."},"G1656":{"b":"Strong's says the roots of this word are of uncertain affinity, and Abbott-Smith offers no origin either. It means mercy, pity, compassion. Nobody knows where it came from.","flat":1,"g":"mercy","h":"No picture."},"G1657":{"b":"The root is the free person, the one not a slave, free to go where they please. Eleutheria is that state. Paul says it is for freedom that Christ set us free, so do not slip the collar back on. Creation itself groans for that liberty.","g":"freedom","h":"The picture: the one who is not a slave."},"G1658":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's main sense is the civil one. Not a slave. It is a legal status before it is a feeling.\n\nSo when Jesus says the Son makes you free, he is talking about who holds the paperwork.","g":"free","h":"The picture: nobody owns you."},"G1659":{"b":"The root means not a slave, free to go where you please. To eleutheroo is to cut a person loose. The truth shall make you free. Where the slave is roped to a master, this is the rope untied and the door opened.","g":"set free","h":"The picture: the rope untied."},"G166":{"b":"Abbott's first words are age long, eternal. The word is built on the noun for an age.\n\nHe then sorts the uses. Without beginning. Without end. Or neither. The New Testament uses all three.","g":"eternal","h":"The picture: lasting a whole age."},"G1660":{"b":"The word comes from 'to come or go' and means simply a coming. The prophets, Stephen says, foretold the arrival of the Righteous One long before he ever walked among them.","g":"coming, advent","h":"The picture: someone arriving at last."},"G1661":{"b":"The word comes from the word for elephant, and means ivory. Abbott-Smith gives \"of ivory.\" Picture smooth white tusk carved into vessels. So the merchants weep, for no one buys their ivory goods.","g":"of ivory","h":"The picture: carved ivory."},"G1662":{"b":"The name means God of raising. It joins a word for God with a word meaning to rise or set up. It pictures God as the one who raises up.","g":"Eliakim","h":"The picture: God of raising."},"G1663":{"b":"The name means God of help. It joins a word for God with a word for aid. It declares that true help comes from God alone.","g":"Eliezer","h":"The picture: God of help."},"G1664":{"b":"The name means God of majesty. It points to God clothed in splendor and greatness. Eliud appears in Matthew's list of the ancestors of Jesus.","g":"Eliud","h":"The picture: God of majesty."},"G1665":{"b":"The name means God of the oath. Behind it lie words for God and for seven, the sacred number used in swearing an oath. Elizabeth was the mother of John the Baptist.","g":"Elizabeth","h":"The picture: God of the oath."},"G1666":{"b":"The worksheet points this name to another form and gives no plain meaning. Elissaeus is Elisha, the prophet who took up the mantle of Elijah.","flat":1,"g":"Elisha","h":"No picture."},"G1667":{"b":"This word means to roll up, to coil or wrap. It is what you do to a scroll when finished, or a cloak folded and put away. Hebrews says God will roll up the heavens like a worn-out garment. The whole sky wrapped up and set aside.","g":"roll up, fold","h":"The picture: rolling up a scroll."},"G1668":{"b":"The word means a sore, an ulcer, an open wound. The beggar Lazarus lies at the rich man's gate covered in sores, and the dogs come and lick them. In Revelation grievous sores break out on those marked by the beast.","g":"sore, ulcer","h":"The picture: open sores on the skin."},"G1669":{"b":"The root is a word for an ulcer, as if the flesh is drawn together into a wound. Picture raw open sores. Lazarus lay at the gate covered in them, and the dogs came to lick him.","g":"full of sores","h":"The picture: skin drawn into a sore."},"G167":{"b":"The first sense Abbott gives is uncleanness, impurity, and physical at that. Jesus uses it of a tomb, white and clean outside but full of dead men's bones within. That hidden rot is the picture behind moral uncleanness.","g":"uncleanness","h":"The picture: the tomb full of bones."},"G1670":{"b":"This word means to drag. Peter drags his sword out. A mob drags Paul to court. It is pulling something heavy that does not move on its own. So when Jesus says he will draw all people to himself, the word underneath is drag.","g":"drag, draw","h":"The picture: hauling something that will not come."},"G1671":{"b":"This is simply Hellas, another name for Greece, a country of Europe. It is a bare place name of uncertain origin, so there is nothing behind it to picture. Paul spent three months there.","flat":1,"g":"Greece","h":"No picture."},"G1672":{"b":"The word means a Greek. But Abbott-Smith says that in the New Testament it usually means Greek Gentiles, set opposite the Jews.\n\nSo one nation's name came to cover the whole rest of the world.","g":"Greek, Gentile","h":"The picture: everyone outside Israel."},"G1673":{"b":"This marks something as Greek, the common tongue of the marketplace. In Revelation the destroyer's name is given in the Greek. Even a foreign title gets spoken in the language ordinary people carried on their lips.","g":"Greek","h":"The picture: written so a Greek could read it."},"G1674":{"b":"The word is the feminine of Greek. Abbott-Smith adds the sense that mattered to a Jew: a Gentile woman, an outsider to Israel. In Mark this is the mother who begs Jesus to heal her daughter. She is not one of the chosen people, and she knows it.","g":"Greek woman","h":"The picture: a Greek woman, not a Jew."},"G1675":{"b":"This word comes from a word meaning to take up Greek ways, to live in Greek. A Hellenist is a Jew who spoke Greek and lived in its customs. These were the ones whose widows were being overlooked.","g":"Hellenist","h":"The picture: a Jew living in the Greek tongue."},"G1676":{"b":"Abbott says this word means in Greek. Pilate hung the sign over the cross in Greek so every passerby could read it. It marks the language a thing was said in, the common tongue of the wider world.","g":"in Greek","h":"The picture: spoken in Greek."},"G1677":{"b":"This is an accounting word, from in plus a word here meaning account. To impute is to write something into the ledger against a name, to charge it to the account. Sin was in the world but not entered on the books where there was no law.","g":"impute","h":"The picture: an entry in the account book."},"G1678":{"b":"This is only a name. Strong's traces it to Hebrew and here it marks one man in the family line Luke follows from Jesus back toward Adam. A name stands for a person, not a picture. There is nothing to see.","flat":1,"g":"Elmodam","h":"No picture."},"G1679":{"b":"From elpis, expectation, confidence. To elpizo is to look for, to expect, to lean out toward something not yet here. So hope that is seen is not hope. Elpizo keeps the eyes on the road, waiting for what has been promised to come into view.","g":"hope","h":"The picture: leaning forward, watching the road."},"G1680":{"b":"Strong's traces it to a word meaning to anticipate, usually with pleasure.\n\nAbbott-Smith says that in older Greek it could mean expecting anything, good or bad, but in the New Testament it is always good. This is expecting, not wishing.","g":"hope","h":"The picture: leaning toward what is coming."},"G1681":{"b":"Elymas is a name of foreign origin, and the sources cannot pin down its root. It belonged to the wizard who opposed Paul. With no clear meaning, there is no picture, only the man's name.","flat":1,"g":"Elymas","h":"No picture."},"G1682":{"b":"The word is Aramaic. Strong's says it means my God. It is the first word of Jesus' cry from the cross, my God, my God, why have you forsaken me. Even there the word keeps its \"my\", still holding on.","g":"Eloi","h":"The picture: my God, cried out loud."},"G1684":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means to step into. The word is built on the idea of the foot. It is used again and again for climbing aboard a boat. One foot onto the deck, and in.","g":"embark, get in","h":"The picture: stepping into the boat."},"G1685":{"b":"This word joins in and to throw. Abbott-Smith gives it as to cast into. Do not fear those who kill the body, Jesus says. Fear the One who, after killing, has power to throw a person into hell.","g":"cast into","h":"The picture: throwing someone into the pit."},"G1686":{"b":"This joins \"in\" to bapto, to dip or plunge into liquid. Embapto is to dip a thing in. At the last supper Jesus says the one who dips his hand with him in the dish is the very one who will betray him.","g":"dip","h":"The picture: dipping bread into the bowl."},"G1687":{"b":"The plain sense is to step in or on a place. From there it means to march in and take over ground that is not yours. Paul uses it of a proud man pushing into things he has not seen, claiming what he has no right to.","g":"intrude","h":"The picture: setting foot where you do not belong."},"G1688":{"b":"This comes from the word to embark, to step onto a vessel. It means to put someone on board. At Myra the centurion finds a ship for Rome and puts Paul and the others aboard it. The word is the loading of a person onto the deck.","g":"put aboard","h":"The picture: a man set aboard a ship."},"G1689":{"b":"This is \"look\" with \"in\" or \"on\" in front. Strong's says \"to observe fixedly.\" It is not a glance but a steady look right at someone. Jesus looked straight at Peter after the denial.","g":"look at, gaze","h":"The picture: a fixed gaze."},"G169":{"b":"Strong's builds this from a negative particle and a word meaning cleansed. The clean word with a no in front of it.\n\nAbbott shows three uses. Dirty in fact, unclean by ceremony, and unclean in character.","g":"unclean","h":"The picture: not cleaned."},"G1690":{"b":"The root is the snort of a horse, the hard blast of breath from a powerful animal. Embrimaomai carries that force. Jesus snorted in himself at the tomb of Lazarus, deep feeling breaking out. Elsewhere he sternly charges the healed to keep quiet.","g":"sternly charge","h":"The picture: a horse snorting in anger."},"G1692":{"b":"The word simply means to vomit. Abbott-Smith lists it used as a figure of speech. Picture the body forcing out what it will not keep down. So Christ says the lukewarm church makes him want to spew it out.","g":"to vomit","h":"The picture: the mouth spitting something out."},"G1693":{"b":"The root is mainomai, to rave like a madman. To be enraged here is to be out of your mind with fury against someone. Paul says he was so mad against the believers that he chased them to foreign cities. The word is a man raving, driven wild.","g":"rage against","h":"The picture: a man raving in fury."},"G1694":{"b":"The name means with us is God. It is built from small words meaning with, us, and God. Isaiah gave it as a sign, and Matthew names it for Christ.","g":"Emmanuel","h":"The picture: with us is God."},"G1695":{"b":"Emmaus is the name of a village, about seven miles from Jerusalem. It is only a place on the map, with no meaning behind the name to picture. Two disciples walked there the day Jesus rose.","flat":1,"g":"Emmaus","h":"No picture."},"G1696":{"b":"The word is \"in\" plus \"to stay (in a given place, state, relation or expectancy).\" To stay put. Paul stayed two whole years in his rented house. Turned inward, it means to hold to a promise, to keep abiding by the covenant.","g":"continue, abide in","h":"The picture: staying planted in one spot."},"G1697":{"b":"The name means donkey. It comes from a word for a male ass, named for its dun red color. Emmor is Hamor, a Canaanite of Shechem.","g":"Hamor","h":"The picture: donkey."},"G1699":{"b":"This is the possessive of the word I, meaning my or mine. Abbott shows it marking what belongs to me, proceeds from me, relates to me. It draws a line from a person to a thing, but the line is grammar, not something you can see.","flat":1,"g":"my, mine","h":"No picture."},"G17":{"b":"This word is built from two others, good and to make or do. So it is not someone who merely feels good or means well. Abbott says doing well, acting rightly. It names a person whose hands actually do good.","g":"well-doer","h":"The picture: the one who does good."},"G170":{"b":"Built from no and kairos, the right moment. Abbott reads it to have no opportunity. Paul says the Philippians cared for him but for a while had no chance to show it. The season for helping had not come around.","g":"lack opportunity","h":"The picture: the open door has closed."},"G1701":{"b":"The root means to jeer at, to make sport of someone. Empaigmos is mocking, treating a person as a plaything for laughs. Hebrews says some of the faithful endured mockings and scourgings. Held up to be laughed at before they were whipped.","g":"mocking","h":"The picture: making a plaything of someone."},"G1702":{"b":"The root means to sport as a boy, to play a game. Empaizō is to make someone your plaything, to play games at their expense. The soldiers do it to Jesus, dressing him as a mock king, kneeling in jest, turning his pain into sport.","g":"to mock","h":"The picture: making someone your plaything."},"G1703":{"b":"From a word meaning to jeer at, to deride. Underneath is the idea of making sport of someone. A mocker treats you as a joke. Peter and Jude warn of scoffers who make a game of the promise.","g":"mocker, scoffer","h":"The picture: the jeering scoffer."},"G1704":{"b":"The roots are in and walk around. Abbott-Smith says to walk about in or among. God promises to live among his people and move through them, not off at a distance but walking their streets.","g":"walk among","h":"The picture: someone strolling through the middle of a crowd."},"G1705":{"b":"This means to fill full, up to the brim, and so to satisfy. Picture an empty bowl filled until it can hold no more. God has filled the hungry with good things and sent the rich away empty.","g":"fill, satisfy","h":"The picture: a bowl filled to the brim."},"G1706":{"b":"This word is built from into and to fall. The picture is falling into something you cannot climb out of, a pit or a trap. It is a fearful thing to fall into the hands of the living God, Hebrews warns. The rich fall into a snare this way.","g":"fall into","h":"The picture: dropping into a pit."},"G1707":{"b":"This word joins \"in\" with a word meaning to twine or braid. It is being woven in, tangled up the way a foot catches in cords. Paul says a soldier does not get entangled in civilian affairs. Keep free, and don't let daily business braid itself around you.","g":"entangle","h":"The picture: a foot tangled in cords."},"G1708":{"b":"The root means to weave and twist together. This is hair plaited up into elaborate braids. Peter says do not let your beauty be that outward thing. Let it be the quiet spirit inside instead.","g":"plaiting","h":"The picture: hair plaited into braids."},"G1709":{"b":"The word joins 'in' with 'to breathe hard.' Saul comes breathing threats and murder against the disciples, every breath of him full of it, until the light knocks him flat.","g":"breathe","h":"The picture: breath hot with threats."},"G171":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning unseasonable, off the right time. Paul tells Timothy to preach in season and out of season. The word paints the wrong moment, like fruit that comes when it should not. Be ready even then.","g":"out of season","h":"The picture: showing up out of season."},"G1710":{"b":"Strong's pictures a peddler traveling through a country to sell his wares. The word joins in and to travel. So a trader is a man on the road doing business. James warns those who plan their profit town by town.","g":"to trade","h":"The picture: the traveling peddler."},"G1711":{"b":"This comes from the word for a traveling merchant, the man who buys and sells. It means his trade, his business. In Matthew 22:5 the invited guests brush off the feast, one going to his farm, another to his business.","g":"business, trade","h":"The picture: the trader going about his business."},"G1712":{"b":"From a word for a tradesman, a merchant. An emporion is a trading place, a market. Picture stalls and haggling and coin. Do not make my Father's house a house of trade, Jesus said. It was meant for prayer.","g":"merchandise","h":"The picture: a busy market of traders."},"G1713":{"b":"The root is a journey. An emporos first meant a man aboard ship, then the trader who travels to buy and sell. The merchant seeking fine pearls sold all he had for the one. This is the word behind our \"emporium.\"","g":"merchant","h":"The picture: a trader traveling to buy and sell."},"G1714":{"b":"Strong's builds this from a word for blowing a flame. To burn a thing you breathe on the coals until fire catches. In Matthew 22:7 the king sends soldiers and burns the city of those who killed his servants.","g":"burn up","h":"The picture: blowing embers into flame."},"G1716":{"b":"This is on joined to a word that simply means to spit. The soldiers do it to Jesus, spitting in his face. A crude, bodily act of contempt. The word puts the spit right onto the person.","g":"spit on","h":"The picture: spit landing on a face."},"G1717":{"b":"The root means to lighten, to shine, to bring a thing to light so it shows. This word is what has been made plainly visible. God raised Jesus and made him emphanes, not to all, but shown openly to chosen witnesses who ate with him.","g":"manifest","h":"The picture: a thing brought out into the light."},"G1718":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means to show oneself, to appear. It carries the idea of bringing a thing into view. Jesus promised to show himself to those who love him, to step into plain sight before them.","g":"make known, appear","h":"The picture: showing your face."},"G1719":{"b":"Built from a word meaning in and a word for alarm or fright. It puts the person inside the fear, surrounded and held by it. The women bowed their faces to the ground, afraid. Not just feeling fear but held down in it.","g":"afraid","h":"The picture: gripped inside fright."},"G172":{"b":"The a in front means not, and the root means bad or worthless. So akakos is a person with nothing bad in them, guileless and easy to trust. Hebrews uses it of Christ, harmless and undefiled.","g":"harmless","h":"The picture: nothing bad in it."},"G1720":{"b":"This word means to breathe or blow upon. Abbott points back to Genesis, God breathing life into the first man. The risen Jesus breathed on the disciples and said, Receive the Holy Spirit. Warm breath, blown out onto them.","g":"to breathe on","h":"The picture: breath blown onto someone's face."},"G1721":{"b":"Strong's and Abbott both see a seed pressed into soil and rooted there. This word plants something in you. James says welcome the word rooted in you, the one that has the power to save your soul.","g":"engrafted","h":"The picture: a seed rooted in the soil."},"G1723":{"b":"The root is the word for an arm, the arm as it curves. This verb is to take someone into that curve, to fold them in. Mark uses it twice for Jesus with children, lifting them up and holding them close against him.","g":"embrace","h":"The picture: a child folded into curved arms."},"G1724":{"b":"Built from \"in\" and the old word for the sea, this is the sea's own creatures, the things that live in the water. James says every one of them has been tamed by man, yet no man can tame the tongue.","g":"in the sea","h":"The picture: the creatures that live in the sea."},"G1727":{"b":"This word means set against, right in front of you facing the other way, over against, opposite, contrary. It is used of the wind, the contrary wind that beat against the boat so the disciples could make no headway. Something standing opposite, pushing back.","g":"contrary","h":"The picture: the wind blowing in your face."},"G1728":{"b":"The root means to commence, to make a beginning. It marks the first move, the moment a hand is set to the task. Paul uses it of God starting a good work in you. And what God begins, he finishes.","g":"to begin","h":"The picture: the first stroke of work."},"G1729":{"b":"This word means in want, lacking what you need. Luke says of the first believers that none among them was needy, because those who had land or houses sold them and shared. No one was left with empty hands.","g":"needy, lacking","h":"The picture: empty hands with nothing in them."},"G173":{"b":"Abbott traces the word to a root meaning \"a point.\" A thorn is the plant that pricks. They twisted these into a crown and pressed it on Jesus' head.","g":"thorn","h":"The picture: a sharp point."},"G1730":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to point at or show. An endeigma is the plain token, the visible proof. Paul says their patience under persecution is proof of the righteous judgment of God.","g":"token, proof","h":"The picture: the proof held up for all to see."},"G1731":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is to mark, to point out. The word joins in and show. It is the picture of pointing a thing out so others notice it, putting a quality on display for all to see.","g":"show, display","h":"The picture: pointing something out."},"G1732":{"b":"Abbott says this word is \"a pointing out, showing forth, proof.\" The root means to indicate by word or act. It is the finger that points so all can see. Paul uses it for God showing plainly, in the open, that he himself is just.","g":"proof, showing","h":"The picture: pointing something out."},"G1733":{"b":"This is just the number eleven, one plus ten. It became a name, the Eleven, the apostles left after Judas fell away. The word itself is only a count. There is nothing to picture behind it.","flat":1,"g":"eleven","h":"No picture."},"G1734":{"b":"The ordinal of eleven. Picture the workers hired at the eleventh hour, with barely an hour of daylight left, who were paid a full day's wage anyway, Matthew 20:9. The last ones called, and not one of them shortchanged.","g":"eleventh","h":"The picture: hired at the eleventh hour."},"G1735":{"b":"The root is dechomai, to receive. This asks what a situation will admit or take in. Jesus says it cannot be received that a prophet die outside Jerusalem. Some things the moment simply will not let through.","g":"it is possible","h":"The picture: whether the moment will let it in."},"G1736":{"b":"The root demos is your own people, your town. So the word is to be at home, among your own. Paul says while we are at home in the body we are away from the Lord, and he would rather be home with him.","g":"be at home","h":"The picture: at home among your own."},"G1737":{"b":"The root means to clothe, to put a garment on. Mark uses this word for the soldiers who dress Jesus in a purple robe to mock him as a king. The same word later dresses the rich man in his fine purple.","g":"clothe","h":"The picture: pulling a robe onto someone."},"G1738":{"b":"This is built on díkē, the word for justice and a court's decision. So éndikos is what lands squarely inside what is right. Hebrews uses it of a penalty that was just. The punishment matched the crime exactly, nothing crooked in it.","g":"just","h":"The picture: the sentence that fits."},"G1739":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this comes from a word meaning \"to build.\" It names the material built into a structure. Picture jasper set right into the courses of a wall. So the wall of the city was built of jasper stone.","g":"structure","h":"The picture: stones built into a wall."},"G174":{"b":"The root is the word for a thorn. This describes something made of them. Mark uses it for the crown the soldiers weave and press onto Jesus' head, sharp thorns bent into a circle, a cruel joke about a king.","g":"of thorns","h":"The picture: a crown twisted from thorns."},"G1740":{"b":"This word is built from a root meaning in glory, splendid. To glorify is to fill someone with visible splendor, to make them shine with honor. Paul says Christ will be glorified in his people. His name lit up in those who bear it.","g":"glorify","h":"The picture: lit up with splendor."},"G1741":{"b":"The word is \"in\" joined to \"glory,\" clothed in brightness. It means splendid, glorious, and Luke uses it of gorgeous clothing, robes that shine. Those in soft splendid dress, Jesus says, live in kings' courts, not the wilderness where John preached.","g":"glorious","h":"The picture: robes that gleam and shine."},"G1742":{"b":"Abbott ties it to ἐνδύω, to put on. Strong's: \"apparel (especially the outer robe).\" A garment is the thing you climb into and wear. This is the word for John's rough coat of camel's hair.","g":"clothing","h":"The picture: the thing you put on."},"G1743":{"b":"En means in, and the root means power. Endynamoo pictures strength put inside a person, power poured in. I can do all things through him who strengthens me. Not cheering from the sidelines but strength set within the bones.","g":"strengthen","h":"The picture: strength poured inside."},"G1744":{"b":"The root means to go down, to sink. This word pictures worming your way in, sinking low to slip inside unnoticed. Paul warns of those who creep into households to lead the weak astray. They come in low and quiet.","g":"creep","h":"The picture: sneaking down into a house."},"G1745":{"b":"The root G1746 means to invest with clothing. Abbott sums this word up as \"a putting on\" of garments. Peter uses it of outward dress, gold and fine clothes. He points past what you put on to who you are underneath.","g":"putting on","h":"The picture: pulling clothes on over the body."},"G1746":{"b":"Strong's reads the word as sinking into a garment. Abbott-Smith adds a second sense of entering or pressing into.\n\nSo when Paul says put on Christ, the image is climbing inside the clothing.","g":"clothe, put on","h":"The picture: sinking down into a coat."},"G1747":{"b":"The word is built from a seat, from sitting down. An ambush is men who have sat themselves in hiding to wait. Forty of them sat still, sworn to kill Paul as he passed by. To ambush is to sit and wait.","g":"ambush","h":"The picture: men sitting in hiding."},"G1748":{"b":"The root is a word for an ambush, \"an ambuscade.\" Abbott says \"to lie in wait for.\" It is armed men crouched out of sight, waiting to spring. Forty of them once swore to catch Paul this way.","g":"lie in wait","h":"The picture: men hidden in ambush along the road."},"G175":{"b":"This word is built from not and the word for fruit, the kind you pluck off a branch. So it is the tree that bears none, barren. The seed sown among thorns proves unfruitful. Leaves on the branch but nothing to gather. Empty of fruit.","g":"unfruitful","h":"The picture: the branch with nothing to pick."},"G1750":{"b":"Abbott gives the plain sense: to roll in, to wind in. It is wrapping something round and round in cloth. Joseph took Jesus down, wound the linen sheet around him, and laid him in the rock tomb.","g":"wrap in","h":"The picture: winding cloth around a body."},"G1751":{"b":"This word joins in and to be. Abbott-Smith gives it as to be within, the things inside. Give as alms what is inside the cup and dish, Jesus says, and then the whole thing is clean, not just the polished outside.","g":"what is within","h":"The picture: what is inside the cup."},"G1753":{"b":"Our word energy comes from this. Abbott marks it as operative power, the force actually at work, as opposed to power just stored up and sitting still. Paul uses it for the power that raised Christ. Not strength held in reserve, but strength in motion, pushing.","g":"working, energy","h":"The picture: power actually doing the work."},"G1754":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives the plain sense. To be at work or in action, the opposite of being idle.\n\nHe quotes Meyer on the New Testament use. It is always used of some principle or power at work.","g":"work, be active","h":"The picture: something at work inside."},"G1755":{"b":"The root means to be at work, active and effective. An energema is the effect, the thing actually worked, the result that shows the power was really operating. Paul says there are many workings but one Spirit.","g":"working, effect","h":"The picture: the work actually done."},"G1756":{"b":"The roots are en, in, and ergon, work. So the word is a thing that is in-work, up and doing, never idle. The writer says God's word is living and active, and Paul speaks of a wide door standing open and effective.","g":"active, effective","h":"The picture: a thing hard at work."},"G1757":{"b":"The root means to speak well of a person. Underneath the word \"bless\" is that plain act, saying good over someone out loud. God told Abraham that in him all the families of the earth would be blessed. Good words spoken, and they land.","g":"bless","h":"The picture: good words spoken over someone."},"G1758":{"b":"The roots mean to hold and \"in.\" So it is holding something fast inside, being tangled up in it. Herodias held a grudge against John and wanted him dead. The word is a hatred gripped tight and kept, a snare you will not loosen.","g":"hold a grudge","h":"The picture: gripping a grudge and not letting go."},"G1759":{"b":"From the word meaning in. It points to here, this place, or hither, to this place. The risen Jesus asks the startled disciples, have you anything here to eat. A word that plants you on the spot.","g":"here","h":"The picture: right here, this spot."},"G176":{"b":"The root means to note something against a person, to find fault. With 'not' in front, this means no fault can be marked against you. Paul wants sound speech that cannot be condemned, so opponents find nothing to write down.","g":"unblamable","h":"The picture: no fault marked against you."},"G1760":{"b":"The roots are \"in\" and passion, a word tied to breathing hard. This word is to hold a thing inside and turn it over with feeling, to ponder it. While Joseph pondered the divorce this way, the angel came to him.","g":"to ponder","h":"The picture: turning it over in the heat of the heart."},"G1761":{"b":"Built from a word meaning to ponder. Abbott says this is not cold reasoning but the stirring of the heart's feelings. Jesus, seeing their enthymesis, knew the thoughts moving inside them, Matthew 9:4. The word for what churns within.","g":"thought","h":"The picture: what stirs inside the heart."},"G1762":{"b":"A short form meaning there is, there is in, it has a place. Paul stacks it up, in Christ there is neither Jew nor Greek, slave nor free, male nor female. Those walls have no place inside.","g":"there is","h":"The picture: no room for that here."},"G1763":{"b":"Abbott says the word properly means a cycle of time. A year is one whole turn of the seasons, back to where it began. Jesus read of \"the acceptable year of the Lord.\"","g":"year","h":"The picture: a full circle come round."},"G1764":{"b":"En means in, and histemi means to stand. Enistemi pictures something standing right here, set in place before you now. Paul splits things standing present from things still to come. The present, planted in front of you and pressing.","g":"be present","h":"The picture: standing right here, now."},"G1765":{"b":"The word puts \"in\" before the word for having force. Abbott says \"to strengthen.\" In the garden, when Jesus is worn to the ground, an angel comes and puts strength into him. Force pressed back into someone who has none left.","g":"strengthen","h":"The picture: strength poured into a failing body."},"G1766":{"b":"This just means ninth, built on the number nine. In the Gospels the ninth hour is mid-afternoon, three in the day. It is the hour Jesus cried out and died. A plain number that marks a heavy moment.","g":"ninth","h":"The picture: the ninth hour."},"G1767":{"b":"This is simply the number nine. Ten lepers were healed, and nine of them never came back to give thanks. A number holds no picture.","flat":1,"g":"nine","h":"No picture."},"G1768":{"b":"Ninety and nine, built on the word for nine. Picture the shepherd who left the ninety nine safe in the open country and went after the single sheep that was lost, Luke 15:4. The number is large, but heaven counts the one missing.","g":"ninety-nine","h":"The picture: ninety-nine left for the one."},"G1769":{"b":"The root means to beckon by gesture. Strong's says the word is dumb as one making signs, silent from shock. Saul's companions stand there speechless, unable to get out a word.","g":"speechless","h":"The picture: struck dumb, only gesturing."},"G177":{"b":"This is built from not and a word meaning to cover up. It means uncovered, unveiled. Paul uses it of a woman's head left bare while she prays, with no covering over it.","g":"uncovered","h":"The picture: the bare head, no veil."},"G1770":{"b":"This word means to nod at someone, to beckon or speak by gesture instead of words. Unable to hear or be answered by the mute Zechariah, they nodded and made signs to him, asking what to name the child.","g":"make signs","h":"The picture: nodding to get an answer."},"G1771":{"b":"The word carries noûs, the mind, with in fastened to the front. It means a thought, purpose, design, what goes on inside your head. Hebrews says God's word cuts down to these, reading the plans you have never spoken.","g":"thought, purpose","h":"The picture: the thought inside the mind."},"G1772":{"b":"Built from \"in\" and the word for law, prescriptive usage. To be ennomos is to be inside the law, within its lines. The town clerk says any real charge must be settled in a lawful assembly, a gathering held inside the rules, not a mob in the street.","g":"lawful","h":"The picture: standing inside the bounds of the law."},"G1773":{"b":"The two pieces mean in and night. It means while night still holds, before dawn. In Mark 1:35 Jesus gets up long before daylight, while it is still dark, goes out to a lonely place, and prays.","g":"by night","h":"The picture: while it is still dark."},"G1774":{"b":"The root means to occupy a house, to reside. With in added, it is to dwell inside. Paul says the Spirit does this in you. Not visiting. Moving in and living there, the way a person settles into a home.","g":"dwell in","h":"The picture: living inside a house."},"G1775":{"b":"This word means oneness, unity of mind. It is built from the word for the number one, many people counted as a single one. There is no object here to see, only the fact of being at one.","flat":1,"g":"unity","h":"No picture."},"G1776":{"b":"The root is the word for a crowd, and behind this verb is the idea of a mob crowding in to harass. Luke uses it for those troubled by unclean spirits, hounded and pressed, who came to be healed by Jesus.","g":"trouble","h":"The picture: a crowd mobbing and pressing you."},"G1777":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means held in, bound by. To be guilty is to be caught and held fast, tied to a charge you cannot walk away from. It is a courtroom word for being on the hook.","g":"guilty, liable","h":"The picture: held in the grip of a charge."},"G1778":{"b":"Built from a word meaning to command, to charge. Abbott gives a precept. Jesus rebukes worship built on the entalma of men, human rules taught as if they were God's own, Matthew 15:9. A commandment handed down from below, not above.","g":"commandment, precept","h":"The picture: a rule laid down."},"G1779":{"b":"This joins \"in\" to taphos, a grave. Entaphiazo is to make a body ready for burial, wrapping it in cloth and spices for the tomb. Jesus says the woman pouring perfume on him has done it beforehand, preparing his body for the grave.","g":"prepare for burial","h":"The picture: wrapping the body for the grave."},"G178":{"b":"The root means to judge against a man, to sentence him, and the piece in front cancels it. This word is a person never sentenced, never even tried. Paul protests: they beat us in public, Romans, uncondemned, with no verdict ever brought down.","g":"uncondemned","h":"The picture: a man beaten before any verdict was passed."},"G1780":{"b":"The root means to wrap a body in grave-cloths for burial. This word is that whole preparing. Jesus says the woman pouring perfume on him has done it for his burial ahead of time, readying his body while he still breathes.","g":"burial","h":"The picture: wrapping a body for the grave."},"G1781":{"b":"The root is telos, the point aimed at, the goal. To entellomai is to command with an aim in view, to lay a charge on someone and send them at it. Jesus binds his whole teaching into one when he commands the disciples to love.","g":"to command","h":"The picture: a charge sent toward its goal."},"G1782":{"b":"The word means from here, and doubled it means on each side. John sees the river of life, and enteuthen and enteuthen, on this side and on that, on each side, stands the tree of life. A word that sets you at a spot and points outward.","g":"hence","h":"The picture: a spot with sides pointing out."},"G1783":{"b":"The root means to fall in with someone, to meet and talk. From there it grew to mean an audience with a king, and the petition you bring him. Paul asks for prayers, intercessions for all. Not shouting from afar, but coming close to ask.","g":"intercession, prayer","h":"The picture: an audience with the king."},"G1784":{"b":"Built from a word meaning in and a word for value, the money paid for something. To be entimos is to be held at a high price. The centurion's servant was precious to him. A costly, valued stone.","g":"precious","h":"The picture: a thing worth real money."},"G1785":{"b":"The root means to enjoin, to lay a charge on someone. An entole is that charge made solid, an order, injunction, command handed down to be kept. So the commandments are not advice. They are orders from a king who has the right to give them.","g":"commandment","h":"The picture: an order handed down."},"G1786":{"b":"Two parts, in and a spot or place. The in-place ones, the residents of that spot. The local people of Caesarea joined Paul's companions in begging him not to go up to Jerusalem.","g":"resident","h":"The picture: the local folk of the place."},"G1787":{"b":"The root is en, in. Entos means the inside, what is within. Jesus tells the Pharisee to clean first the inside of the cup, and then the outside will be clean too. Start on the inside and the rest follows.","g":"within","h":"The picture: the inside of the cup."},"G1788":{"b":"Built from in and turn. Abbott-Smith gives to turn about. Turned inward in shame, it means to shame someone. Turned toward another, it means to show respect. They will respect my son.","g":"shame, respect","h":"The picture: turning a person in on themselves."},"G1789":{"b":"The root trepho means to feed and nourish. So it is being fed up on something, raised and nurtured in it. Paul says a good minister is nourished up in the words of faith and good doctrine.","g":"nourish up","h":"The picture: a child fed and raised on it."},"G179":{"b":"The root means to loosen down, to take a thing apart or pull it down. Put 'not' in front and it cannot be undone. Christ holds his office by a life that death cannot dissolve.","g":"endless","h":"The picture: what cannot be pulled apart."},"G1790":{"b":"This word is built from a word for in and a word for trembling, the body quaking with fear. Moses said I am trembling at the burning bush. The jailer came in shaking and fell down before Paul.","g":"trembling","h":"The picture: a body quaking with fear."},"G1791":{"b":"The root means to invert, to turn inward. Shame is that inward turn, the face dropped and the eyes cast down. Paul says he writes this to your shame, to turn you back to your senses.","g":"shame","h":"The picture: the face turned down."},"G1792":{"b":"This joins \"in\" to a root meaning to indulge in luxury. So it is reveling, living soft and loose. Peter says the false teachers do this even at the believers' feasts, sporting in their own deceptions.","g":"revel in","h":"The picture: wallowing in soft luxury."},"G1793":{"b":"Abbott-Smith walks the word up in steps. First to fall in with, then to meet and talk, then to petition. It is falling in with a person and pressing a request. So Christ meets God for us, bringing our case in person.","g":"make intercession","h":"The picture: meeting someone to plead."},"G1794":{"b":"This means to wind up in, to wrap and roll something about. Joseph took the body of Jesus and wrapped it in a clean linen cloth. The word is the sheet wound around, coiled about the body for burial.","g":"wrap up","h":"The picture: winding cloth around and around."},"G1795":{"b":"The root is a stamp or the mark a blow leaves. Abbott-Smith says to imprint, engrave. Paul remembers the law chiselled into stone tablets, and sets that against words written on living hearts.","g":"engrave","h":"The picture: letters cut into stone."},"G1796":{"b":"The root means to use violence, to abuse. This word is to insult, to heap contempt on. To spurn Christ's blood is to insult the Spirit of grace, throwing scorn in his face.","g":"insult","h":"The picture: insult thrown in the face."},"G1797":{"b":"The root means something seen in sleep, a dream. Abbott simply says \"to dream.\" Peter quotes the promise that in the last days old men will dream dreams and the young see visions, God speaking through pictures that come in the night.","g":"dream","h":"The picture: seeing visions while asleep."},"G1798":{"b":"This word joins in and sleep. It means a dream, the thing seen in sleep. Peter quotes Joel: your old men will dream dreams. The word is plain about where dreams live, behind closed eyes, deep in sleep.","g":"dream","h":"The picture: what you see while asleep."},"G18":{"b":"Strong's calls it a primary word, so nothing sits behind it. Abbott adds only a comparison. Another Greek word for good points to how a thing looks. This one points to inner worth.","flat":1,"g":"good","h":"No picture."},"G180":{"b":"This puts \"not\" before a root meaning to settle down, to desist. So it is unable to stop. Peter says the false teachers have eyes full of adultery that never cease from sin, always hunting.","g":"that cannot cease","h":"The picture: something that will not come to rest."},"G1800":{"b":"The name comes from a word for a man in general, mankind in its frailty. Enosh was a patriarch, the son of Seth and grandson of Adam.","g":"Enosh","h":"The picture: a man."},"G1801":{"b":"This word is built on the word for ear. It means to take something into your ears, to give ear. Peter opens his Pentecost sermon with it: listen, take these words in. Not just hear the sound. Let it into your ear.","g":"to hearken","h":"The picture: putting the words into your ear."},"G1802":{"b":"The name means initiated, set apart at a start. Enoch was the man who walked with God and was taken up, not seeing death like other men.","g":"Enoch","h":"The picture: initiated."},"G1803":{"b":"This word means six. Strong's calls it a primary numeral. It is just a plain number, with nothing standing behind it to picture and nothing to see.","flat":1,"g":"six","h":"No picture."},"G1804":{"b":"The root is the word for a messenger, one who brings tidings. Add \"out\" and the news is told abroad, carried into the open. Peter uses it: you are to tell out the praises of the one who called you from darkness into light.","g":"proclaim","h":"The picture: a messenger carrying the news out."},"G1805":{"b":"The root means to go to the market and buy. With \"out\" in front it means to buy out, to redeem. Abbott notes it is used especially of slaves. Christ bought us out from under the curse, off the block, and set us free.","g":"to redeem","h":"The picture: buying a slave out of the market."},"G1806":{"b":"This is \"lead\" with \"out\" in front. Abbott-Smith says \"to lead out.\" It pictures taking someone and bringing them outside. It is the word for God leading Israel out of Egypt.","g":"lead out","h":"The picture: leading someone out."},"G1807":{"b":"Strong's: \"actively, to tear out.\" Abbott: \"to take out.\" The base picture is snatching a thing out, even tearing out an eye. From there it means to rescue, to pluck a person out of danger.","g":"rescue, deliver","h":"The picture: tearing something out."},"G1808":{"b":"This joins out with a word meaning to lift or take up. Abbott gives it as to lift up, lift off the earth, remove. It pictures hoisting a thing off the ground and carrying it out. Paul says put the wicked person away.","g":"put away","h":"The picture: lifted off the ground and carried out."},"G1809":{"b":"Built from a word for out and a word for asking. Abbott says it means to ask for oneself, to demand. Satan has asked to have you, Jesus told Peter, to sift you like wheat. You were asked for by name.","g":"desire, demand","h":"The picture: a hand demanding a man be handed over."},"G181":{"b":"The root means not settled, not standing firm. This is instability, a thing that cannot stand steady, and so confusion and uproar. When you hear of wars and tumults, do not be afraid. Nothing holding its place.","g":"confusion, disorder","h":"The picture: a thing that will not stand still."},"G1810":{"b":"Abbott points to the light that flashed around Paul on the Damascus road, Acts 22:6. One moment the dusty road, the next a blaze from heaven. That is exaiphnes, a thing on you before you can brace or turn away.","g":"suddenly","h":"The picture: no warning, and it is already here."},"G1811":{"b":"The root means to go along with someone, to walk behind as a disciple. This form adds out, to follow all the way out. Peter uses it two ways. He did not follow made-up stories. But false teachers do follow their own filthy ways. You walk behind something.","g":"to follow","h":"The picture: walking behind, following the path out."},"G1812":{"b":"Just a number, six times a hundred. It shows up in Revelation as part of the beast's number, six hundred sixty-six. A plain count, but John tells the reader to reckon it. Sometimes Scripture stops and asks you to add.","g":"six hundred","h":"The picture: six hundred counted out."},"G1813":{"b":"Built from a word meaning out and a word meaning to smear. To smear out is to rub writing away until nothing is left. God will blot out the record of sins, and wipe away every tear from their eyes. Rubbed clean.","g":"wipe out, blot out","h":"The picture: rubbing writing away until it is gone."},"G1814":{"b":"This word joins out and to jump. It means to leap up. The moment the lame man was healed, he leaped up, stood, and walked, jumping and praising God. The word is all motion, feet springing off the ground.","g":"to leap up","h":"The picture: springing up onto your feet."},"G1815":{"b":"Built from a word meaning to stand up, with out added. It means a rising up out of the dead. Paul says he presses on that he might attain the resurrection out from among the dead.","g":"resurrection","h":"The picture: standing up out of the grave."},"G1816":{"b":"Two words are joined here, \"out\" and \"to rise up.\" Strong's says it means to start up out of the ground. It is what a seed does. In the parable the seed on rocky soil springs up fast because the ground is shallow.","g":"spring up","h":"The picture: a seed breaking out of the ground."},"G1817":{"b":"The root means to stand up, with a piece meaning out. In the law of Moses a man would raise up children for his dead brother, making a line stand where none stood. The plain root under it is a body rising to its feet.","g":"raise up","h":"The picture: standing someone up on their feet."},"G1818":{"b":"The root means to cheat, to delude. The ek in front makes it total, to fool someone all the way through. It is the word for how the serpent took in Eve. Not a small lie. A complete con.","g":"deceive","h":"The picture: a con that fools you all the way."},"G1819":{"b":"The word means suddenly, with no warning. Mark uses it at the transfiguration. The disciples looked around and exapina saw no one but Jesus. Moses and Elijah were there, then in an instant only Jesus stood.","g":"suddenly","h":"The picture: gone in a blink."},"G182":{"b":"The root means to place down permanently, to set a thing firmly in place. Put not in front of it. So this is something that will not stay set, restless, sliding loose, never settling where it is put.","g":"unstable","h":"The picture: what will not stay set in place."},"G1820":{"b":"The root means to have no way out, to be at a loss with no path forward. The ek in front deepens it. Paul says he was pressed so hard he despaired even of life, then learned to trust the God who raises the dead.","g":"despair","h":"The picture: no road out."},"G1821":{"b":"Strong's says the word means to send away forth. It stacks \"out\" and \"away\" onto \"send.\" The messenger is sent out and away from you. \"God sent forth his Son, born of a woman.\"","g":"send forth","h":"The picture: sending out on a mission."},"G1822":{"b":"The root means fresh and, by implication, complete, fully fitted. To exartizo is to finish something out so nothing is lacking, like a workshop stocked with every tool. Paul says Scripture leaves the man of God fully equipped for every good work.","g":"equip fully","h":"The picture: fitted out with every tool in place."},"G1823":{"b":"This word is built from the word to flash as lightning. Abbott-Smith gives it as to flash like lightning, gleam, be radiant. On the mountain Jesus' clothes turned dazzling white, blazing like a bolt of lightning as he prayed.","g":"glistening","h":"The picture: a flash of lightning."},"G1824":{"b":"This is built from out of and hour. Literally, out of this very hour. Not later, not the next hour, but straight out of the one you are standing in. Cornelius sends his men at once. It means right now.","g":"instantly","h":"The picture: straight out of this very hour."},"G1825":{"b":"Built from out and to waken, the rousing of someone from sleep. God raised Pharaoh up onto the stage for a purpose, and the same word raises the dead. Like shaking a sleeper fully awake and lifting him to his feet.","g":"raise up","h":"The picture: shaking a sleeper awake."},"G1826":{"b":"The word is \"out\" plus \"to go,\" simply to leave a place. Strong's adds \"escape (to the shore),\" which is just what the shipwrecked men do, wading out of the sea onto the beach at Malta.","g":"go out, depart","h":"The picture: wading out of the sea onto the beach."},"G1828":{"b":"The root means to drag, to haul. This is being dragged out of your place. James says each man is dragged off by his own craving, hooked and hauled the way a fish is pulled from the water.","g":"draw away","h":"The picture: dragged off like a fish on a hook."},"G1829":{"b":"The root means to disgorge, to throw up. So the word is vomit, food thrown back out. Peter quotes the proverb: the dog returns to its own vomit, and the washed pig to the mud.","g":"vomit","h":"The picture: a dog's vomit on the ground."},"G1830":{"b":"Built from \"out\" and a word meaning to track and hunt for a thing, this is searching every corner, turning the place over. Peter says the prophets searched like this into the salvation they wrote about.","g":"search diligently","h":"The picture: turning the place over in a search."},"G1831":{"b":"Strong's builds this from two pieces: out of, and come.\n\nAbbott-Smith shows how far it stretches. Demons come out of people. Prisoners come out of jail. And news comes out, spreading from where it started.","g":"go out, come out","h":"The picture: stepping out through the door."},"G1832":{"b":"Strong's suggests the figurative idea of being out in public, but flags it as figurative, so hold it loosely.\n\nAbbott gives only the solid sense. It is permitted, lawful. A thing you are allowed to do.","g":"it is lawful","h":"The picture: out where everyone can see."},"G1833":{"b":"Abbott traces this to a word meaning to examine, with out set in front. It means to search a thing out with questions. Herod told the wise men, exetazo carefully for the child, Matthew 2:8, dig out exactly where He is.","g":"inquire carefully","h":"The picture: searching it out with questions."},"G1834":{"b":"The root means to lead, and the front means out. To lead the story out into the open, to unfold and tell it fully. John says no one has seen God, but the Son has led him out into view, made him known. To guide others through what you know.","g":"declare, tell","h":"The picture: leading the story out into view."},"G1835":{"b":"This is just the number sixty. It shows up in the harvest that yielded sixty times over. A plain counting word, with nothing behind it.","flat":1,"g":"sixty","h":"No picture."},"G1836":{"b":"Strong's traces this to a word meaning to hold, in the sense of taking hold of and adjoining. Each day holds onto the one before, touching, linked in a line. On the next day, joined to this one, Jesus went to Nain.","g":"next","h":"The picture: links holding one another in a row."},"G1837":{"b":"The root means to make a loud noise, to reverberate. With ek, out, it is sound thrown forth, a trumpet or thunder rolling out. Paul says from the Thessalonians the word of the Lord sounded out across the regions.","g":"ring out","h":"The picture: sound ringing out like a trumpet."},"G1838":{"b":"This comes from the word to have or hold. A habit is what you come to hold firmly by doing a thing again and again. By such practice the mature have trained their senses to discern.","g":"use, habit","h":"The picture: the grip that practice gives."},"G1839":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the word means to be beside oneself. It is built from standing and out of. You are pushed out of your normal footing, out of your senses. That is what wonder does. It stands you outside yourself.","g":"amaze, astonish","h":"The picture: knocked out of your place."},"G184":{"b":"Strong's says this Aramaic name means field of blood. It was the plot bought with the money Judas took to betray Jesus and then threw back. The people called it that, a field marked forever by the blood behind the coins.","g":"Akeldama","h":"The picture: a field named for blood."},"G1840":{"b":"Built from a word meaning to have force or strength, with out in front for full measure. It means to be strong enough, quite able. Paul prays they will have the full strength to grasp how wide Christ's love is.","g":"be able","h":"The picture: full strength for the task."},"G1841":{"b":"The word joins out and road. It means a going out, a departure, the same word as the Exodus from Egypt. On the mountain Moses and Elijah speak with Jesus of his departure, which he would accomplish at Jerusalem.","g":"departure, death","h":"The picture: the road leading out the door."},"G1842":{"b":"This word means to destroy utterly, to wipe out. It joins out with a word meaning to slay. Peter warns that anyone who will not hear the prophet will be cut off entirely from the people. Not just punished. Pulled out by the roots.","g":"to destroy","h":"The picture: rooted out completely."},"G1843":{"b":"Strong's says it means to agree fully. The word carries out inside it, so it is to say the same thing out loud and openly. It is used both for confessing sins and for giving open praise.","g":"confess, praise","h":"The picture: saying it out in the open."},"G1844":{"b":"The pieces mean out and to make swear. To adjure is to drag a binding oath out of a person, to put them under solemn promise. In Matthew 26:63 the high priest says, I adjure you by the living God, tell us if you are the Christ.","g":"adjure","h":"The picture: forcing an oath out of someone."},"G1845":{"b":"This rests on the idea of one that binds by an oath. An exorcist tried to tie down a spirit by swearing solemn oaths over it. The seven sons of Sceva tried this on an evil spirit and were mauled.","g":"exorcist","h":"The picture: binding a spirit by oath."},"G1846":{"b":"This joins \"out\" to orysso, to dig or burrow. Exorysso is to dig something out. The friends of the paralyzed man cannot reach Jesus for the crowd, so they dig open the roof above him and lower him down through it.","g":"dig out","h":"The picture: digging open the roof to get through."},"G1847":{"b":"The pieces mean out and nothing, so to make someone utterly nothing, to count them as zero. In Mark 9:12 Jesus says the Son of Man must suffer many things and be treated as nothing, despised and cast aside.","g":"despise, set at nought","h":"The picture: treated as nothing at all."},"G1848":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means to set at nought, to despise utterly. The word is built on the word for nothing. To scorn someone this way is to treat them as a zero, worth nothing at all.","g":"despise","h":"The picture: counting someone as nothing."},"G1849":{"b":"Abbott sets it beside another word for raw strength. This one is not the strength itself. It is the liberty or power to act, the freedom to use it.\n\nPermission, not muscle.","g":"authority, right","h":"The picture: being free to use what you have."},"G185":{"b":"The root means to mix, as you mix wine with water. Put the \"not\" in front and it means unmixed. Pure, nothing watered in. Jesus wants his people like that, wise as snakes and unmixed as doves.","g":"innocent","h":"The picture: wine with nothing mixed in."},"G1850":{"b":"Built from the word for authority. Abbott gives to exercise authority over. Jesus says the kings of the Gentiles exousiazo their people, they throw their weight over them and lord it, but among you it shall not be so, Luke 22:25.","g":"exercise authority","h":"The picture: throwing your weight over someone."},"G1851":{"b":"The word comes from standing out. Abbott's first sense is a projection, a rock that sticks out from the rest. Used of people it means the ones who stand out, the chief men. Paul speaks before the leading men of the city, those jutting above the crowd.","g":"prominence","h":"The picture: a crag jutting out from the cliff."},"G1852":{"b":"This word means to wake someone out of sleep. Jesus says it of Lazarus. Our friend has fallen asleep, but I go to wake him. To the disciples it sounded like rest. He meant he was raising the dead.","g":"to waken","h":"The picture: shaking a sleeper awake."},"G1853":{"b":"Two parts, out and sleep. It means yanked up out of sleep, awake in an instant. When the earthquake shook the jail, the keeper was startled out of sleep and drew his sword.","g":"awake","h":"The picture: jolted out of sleep."},"G1854":{"b":"This comes from ek, out of. Exo is the place outside, out of doors, beyond the wall. Abbott uses it for those outside the church. So cast into the outer dark, or left standing exo at a shut door, is to be on the wrong side of the threshold.","g":"outside","h":"The picture: out the door, on the outside."},"G1855":{"b":"The word means from without, the outer part. Jesus said you clean the outside of the cup while the inside is full of greed. It comes from the word for \"out.\"","g":"outside, without","h":"The picture: the outside."},"G1856":{"b":"Built from \"out\" and a word meaning to push, it is a hard shove that sends something out. God pushed the nations out before Israel. Later the same word drives a ship up onto the shore, forced out of the sea.","g":"drive out","h":"The picture: shoving something out with your hands."},"G1857":{"b":"The root is the word for outside, out of doors. So \"outer darkness\" is the dark that lies past the door of the lit and crowded house. It is the place a man is put when he is shut out. The far side of the door, in the cold.","g":"outer","h":"The picture: past the door, outside."},"G1858":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning a festival. It means to keep the feast. It pictures the whole feast day, the gathered celebration. Paul says keep it not with old leaven but with sincerity and truth.","g":"keep the feast","h":"The picture: the festival day."},"G1859":{"b":"Strong's says this word is of uncertain affinity. Abbott-Smith gives no origin. It means a feast day, and where the word came from is simply not known.","flat":1,"g":"feast, festival","h":"No picture."},"G186":{"b":"The root means to lean or slope. Put 'not' in front and it stands straight, without a tilt. Let us hold the confession of our hope firm, not leaning or swaying away from it.","g":"without wavering","h":"The picture: standing without a lean."},"G1860":{"b":"Before it meant promise, it was a law word. Abbott-Smith's first sense is a summons, an old Attic legal term.\n\nSo a promise here is a formal thing, not a kind word said in passing.","g":"promise","h":"The picture: a court summons."},"G1861":{"b":"Strong's says the word means to assert something respecting oneself. A promise is not a quiet wish. It is announcing out loud what you will do. When God promises, he goes on record.","g":"promise, profess","h":"The picture: announcing it about yourself."},"G1862":{"b":"Strong's calls this a self-committal. The root means to announce that you yourself will do something, to engage to do something. A promise here is not a wish. It is a person binding himself to act. Peter says God gave us his precious promises.","g":"promise","h":"The picture: putting yourself on the line."},"G1863":{"b":"This word is built from a word for upon and a word meaning to lead or drive. To drive something down onto a person. The crowd wanted to bring the blood of Jesus down upon the apostles' heads.","g":"bring upon","h":"The picture: driving a thing down onto someone."},"G1864":{"b":"The root means to struggle in the games, competing for a prize or fighting an adversary. So this is to contend hard for something. Jude urges readers to fight for the faith once handed to the saints.","g":"contend for","h":"The picture: an athlete straining for the prize."},"G1865":{"b":"Strong's reads this as to accumulate, and Abbott-Smith as to assemble besides. The crowds kept piling in around Jesus, thickening by the minute, and it was to this swelling mass that he said, this is an evil generation seeking a sign.","g":"gather thick together","h":"The picture: a crowd packing in thicker and thicker."},"G1866":{"b":"His name comes from a word meaning to applaud. It means praised. Epaenetus was the first person in his region to turn to Christ, Paul says. A man whose name is the sound of clapping hands.","g":"Epaenetus","h":"The picture: applause."},"G1867":{"b":"Strong's makes it to applaud. The parts mean upon and to praise, praise laid onto someone. Even the master commends the shrewd steward. Paul says he cannot praise the Corinthians for the way they eat. To clap approval onto a person.","g":"praise","h":"The picture: applause laid on someone."},"G1868":{"b":"The root is to praise. Epainos is praise heaped on, the word of approval spoken over someone. Paul says wait, and then each will have his epainos from God, the well done said to your face. We live, he says, to the praise of God's glory.","g":"praise","h":"The picture: the well done said to your face."},"G1869":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives the action and then a list of what gets lifted. Eyes. Hands. Heads. The voice. A ship's sail.\n\nOne more use is the figure. To be lifted up with pride. Same motion, aimed at yourself.","g":"lift up","h":"The picture: lifting your eyes."},"G187":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this is used \"of produce of the ground, to be ripe,\" at its prime. Picture grapes swollen full, ready to burst. So the earth's grapes were fully ripe, and the harvest of judgment had come.","g":"fully ripe","h":"The picture: fruit at the peak of ripeness."},"G1870":{"b":"The root is to feel shame, the hot face that wants to look away. Epaischunomai is being ashamed of someone, disowning them so no shame rubs off. Jesus warns, whoever is ashamed of me, of him I will be ashamed. Paul answers, I am not.","g":"to be ashamed","h":"The picture: the face that turns away."},"G1871":{"b":"This is the word for asking, sharpened toward one who must ask to live. Abbott says \"to beg, as a mendicant.\" The dishonest steward says he is ashamed to do it. A blind man does it by the roadside as Jesus passes.","g":"beg","h":"The picture: the beggar with his hand out by the road."},"G1872":{"b":"This is \"follow\" with \"upon\" on the front, to follow after, to come close behind. Signs followed after the disciples' preaching, Mark says, backing it up. Some men's sins follow after them into the open, catching up later.","g":"follow after","h":"The picture: coming along right behind."},"G1873":{"b":"The root is simply to hear, with a prefix that leans in. Abbott-Smith says to hearken to, to hear with favour. Paul quotes God, in a welcome time I heard you, the ear bent down and listening.","g":"hear favorably","h":"The picture: an ear turned toward a cry."},"G1874":{"b":"This is built on the word for a hearer, with a prefix pressing it closer. Not idle hearing but leaning toward the sound. In the dark jail the other prisoners listened to Paul and Silas singing.","g":"listen intently","h":"The picture: leaning in to listen."},"G1876":{"b":"The word is built on a root meaning constraint, even distress, the press of a force you cannot shake. It marks what is compulsory. The council names only a few necessary things the Gentiles must keep.","g":"necessary","h":"The picture: held fast under constraint."},"G1877":{"b":"The root leads up and out, and includes sailing away. This word is to put a boat out to sea, to push off from the shore into deep water. Jesus asked Peter to put out a little from land, and taught the crowd from the boat.","g":"put out to sea","h":"The picture: pushing the boat off from shore."},"G1878":{"b":"The root is mimnesko, to remind. The stacked prefixes make it remind again, thoroughly. Paul says he wrote boldly to the Romans, not with new teaching but to bring back to mind what they knew. A nudge, not a lecture.","g":"put in mind","h":"The picture: jogging a memory back to the surface."},"G1879":{"b":"Built on the word for rest, with \"upon\" in front. Abbott says \"to rest upon.\" It is the man who leans his whole weight on a thing. Paul says some rest on the law like that, all their weight upon it.","g":"rest upon","h":"The picture: leaning your weight on something."},"G188":{"b":"Abbott says this word is a point, the same as the word acme, the very tip. Used of time it means at this exact point, still, even now. In Matthew 15:16 Jesus asks the disciples if they are even yet without understanding.","g":"still, yet","h":"The picture: the sharp point of a blade."},"G1880":{"b":"The word is built on \"ascend\" with \"upon\" added. Abbott simply says \"to return.\" The Samaritan tells the innkeeper he will come back this way. It is the traveler retracing his steps, returning to where he was.","g":"return","h":"The picture: coming back up the road."},"G1881":{"b":"The word joins upon and to stand up. It means to rise up against someone, to get to your feet as an enemy. Jesus warns that children will rise up against their parents and have them put to death. The people who should stand with you stand against you instead.","g":"to rise up against","h":"The picture: standing up to attack."},"G1882":{"b":"The root means to straighten up. This word means a straightening up again. Scripture is useful for correction, for taking what has bent or fallen crooked and setting it upright once more. Not scrapping it. Straightening it.","g":"correction","h":"The picture: setting a bent thing straight."},"G1884":{"b":"The roots are epi, upon, and arkeo, to ward off. First the word meant to hold danger off, to keep it back like a raised shield. Then it came to mean to help, to relieve. Paul praises the widow who relieved the afflicted.","g":"relieve, help","h":"The picture: holding danger off like a shield."},"G1885":{"b":"This is the district a Roman prefect ruled. It comes from the word for a ruler, one set over others. A province is a piece of the map handed to one governor. Paul kept being passed from one governor's territory to the next.","g":"province","h":"The picture: land under one governor."},"G1886":{"b":"This word is built on the word for a yard or courtyard. It means a dwelling, a homestead. Peter quotes a psalm against Judas: let his home be left empty, with no one living there. An abandoned house.","g":"dwelling","h":"The picture: a walled yard with a roof over it."},"G1887":{"b":"Strong's traces the root to a word meaning fresh. Tomorrow is the fresh day, the one not yet used or spoiled. Epaurion is what comes when that fresh morning arrives. In the Gospels it keeps opening the next scene, the day after the day before.","g":"the morrow","h":"The picture: the fresh day, tomorrow."},"G1889":{"b":"A shortened form of Epaphroditus. Picture the man Paul commends, Epaphras, always wrestling in prayer for the Colossians that they would stand mature, Colossians 4:12. His name is tied to hard, hidden work no one but God saw.","g":"Epaphras","h":"The picture: the man who wrestled in prayer."},"G189":{"b":"One word covers the sense of hearing, the ear itself, and the thing heard. Abbott-Smith's last sense is a report, rumour.\n\nThat is how word about Jesus spread through Galilee. Person telling person.","g":"hearing, report","h":"The picture: news travelling ear to ear."},"G1890":{"b":"The root means to froth, to foam at the mouth. So this is to foam up. Jude calls the false men wild waves of the sea, foaming out their own shame like scum thrown on the shore.","g":"foam out","h":"The picture: waves foaming up their scum."},"G1891":{"b":"The name is built on Aphrodite, goddess of love, and Abbott says it means charming, lovely. Yet this Epaphroditus won his beauty another way. Paul says he nearly died for the work of Christ. His loveliness was risk, not looks.","g":"Epaphroditus","h":"The picture: the name that means lovely."},"G1892":{"b":"The root means to waken someone, to rouse them from sleep. Add \"upon\" and it turns outward: to rouse a crowd against a person. The opponents shook the city awake against Paul and stirred up trouble for him.","g":"stir up","h":"The picture: shaking a sleeper awake."},"G1896":{"b":"The root means to see, and \"upon\" fixes the gaze. It is to look on someone with attention. Elizabeth says the Lord looked on her to take away her shame, his eyes turning to notice her in her long childlessness.","g":"look upon","h":"The picture: eyes turned upon you."},"G1898":{"b":"This is built on the word to bring in or lead in. The law made nothing perfect, so a better hope is led in alongside it, and by that hope we draw near to God.","g":"bringing in","h":"The picture: a better hope led in."},"G1899":{"b":"This is a pure sequence word, then, thereafter, next. It only marks where one thing falls in an order after another. There is nothing concrete to picture, only the ranking of first and then.","flat":1,"g":"then, thereafter","h":"No picture."},"G19":{"b":"Built from the word for good. Abbott calls it the kindlier side of goodness, good that reaches out to help a person. It stands in Paul's list of the Spirit's fruit, Galatians 5:22, the goodness that actually does someone good.","g":"goodness","h":"The picture: good that does someone good."},"G190":{"b":"Strong's says it properly means to be in the same way with a person. Abbott points to a poetic word for a road inside it.\n\nSo following Jesus is not admiring him. It is walking where he walks.","g":"follow","h":"The picture: on the same road with someone."},"G1901":{"b":"The root means to stretch out. This word means to stretch forward, like a runner leaning toward the line with arms reaching. Paul says he forgets what is behind and strains toward what is ahead.","g":"reach forward","h":"The picture: a runner straining forward."},"G1902":{"b":"This is built from upon and a word meaning to put on clothing. It means to pull one garment on over another. Paul longs to be clothed over with our dwelling from heaven, so that mortal life is swallowed up by life.","g":"clothed upon","h":"The picture: one garment pulled over another."},"G1903":{"b":"This word means an outer garment, the tunic worn on top. It comes from a word meaning to put on over oneself. Peter, stripped for the fishing, wrapped this around himself and jumped into the sea to reach Jesus.","g":"outer garment","h":"The picture: the coat thrown on over the rest."},"G1904":{"b":"Built from upon and come. Abbott-Smith gives the sense to come in upon. It pictures something arriving over you, whether the Spirit coming upon a person or trouble coming upon a place.","g":"come upon","h":"The picture: it comes upon you."},"G1905":{"b":"This lays epi, upon, onto the verb to ask. Strong's gives to ask for, to inquire and seek. The extra weight makes it a question pressed home. So when they keep questioning Jesus, eperotao, they are not curious, they are leaning in to test him.","g":"ask, question","h":"The picture: pressing the question harder."},"G1906":{"b":"The root means to ask, to inquire. Abbott also gives \"a demand.\" So this is a formal question or pledge made to God. Peter says baptism is that appeal, a good conscience answering back to him.","g":"inquiry","h":"The picture: a question put to someone."},"G1907":{"b":"Built from a word meaning upon and a word meaning to hold. To hold onto a thing, to hold it out toward someone, or to fix your mind upon it. Paul says to hold forth the word of life, offered in the open hand.","g":"hold, heed","h":"The picture: holding something out in your hand."},"G1908":{"b":"Abbott-Smith traces this to a word for spiteful abuse. It means to revile, to pile insult on a person. Jesus tells his followers to pray for those who treat them this way, blessing the ones who hurl abuse at them.","g":"revile","h":"The picture: spite heaped on someone."},"G191":{"b":"Strong's calls it a primary verb. Nothing older stands behind it. Abbott-Smith simply defines it: to hear, listen, attend, perceive by hearing. A plain word for a plain act.","flat":1,"g":"hear, listen","h":"No picture."},"G1910":{"b":"Epi means upon, and the root means the foot. Epibaino pictures setting your foot up onto something, mounting a donkey or stepping aboard a ship. Behold your king comes to you, riding on a colt. A foot set on the deck, ready to sail.","g":"embark, mount","h":"The picture: setting foot aboard."},"G1911":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives it as to cast, lay or put upon.\n\nThe list of what gets thrown on is wide. Hands on a prisoner. A patch on an old coat. A hand on the plough. Waves into the boat.","g":"lay on, throw on","h":"The picture: throwing something on top."},"G1912":{"b":"The roots are epi, upon, and bareo, to weigh down. Picture stacking a heavy load on top of someone. Paul worked night and day so he would not lay this weight on anyone, not be a burden to the church he served.","g":"burden","h":"The picture: weight stacked on top."},"G1913":{"b":"The word means to cause to mount an animal. The good Samaritan sets the wounded man on his own beast and walks. The disciples set Jesus on the colt for his ride into Jerusalem. Hoisting a person up onto the back of a mount.","g":"set on","h":"The picture: lifting someone up onto a donkey."},"G1914":{"b":"The word joins upon and look. It means to look on, and in the Bible to look on with favor. God looked upon Mary in her low place. It is a gaze that settles on the small and forgotten and does not pass by.","g":"look upon","h":"The picture: eyes turning to look right at someone."},"G1915":{"b":"The root means to throw upon. An epiblema is what is thrown on, a patch laid over a hole. Jesus says no one sews new cloth onto an old coat. The new patch shrinks and tears away, and the rip gets worse.","g":"patch, piece","h":"The picture: a patch sewn onto a garment."},"G1917":{"b":"The word is \"will\" aimed \"against\" someone, a plot. The old translators pictured it as \"laying (lying) in wait,\" men crouched in ambush. The Jews laid such a plot for Paul, waiting to kill him on the road.","g":"plot, ambush","h":"The picture: men crouched in wait to strike."},"G1918":{"b":"The root is the word for a wedding. This word means to become a relative by marriage, and here to marry a dead brother's widow. In Matthew 22:24 the Sadducees build a riddle on this old law about a brother taking his brother's wife.","g":"marry","h":"The picture: marrying into the family."},"G1919":{"b":"Epi means on, and ge means the earth, the soil underfoot. Epigeios marks what sits down here on the ground, in the dirt, not up in heaven. Paul sets earthly bodies against heavenly, earthly wisdom against wisdom from above.","g":"earthly","h":"The picture: down here in the soil."},"G192":{"b":"This is \"not\" joined to a word for mastery and strength. Akrasia is having no grip on yourself, no hold on your own appetites. Jesus says the Pharisees look clean outside but inside are full of greed and this loss of self-control.","g":"lack of self-control","h":"The picture: no grip on yourself."},"G1920":{"b":"Strong's says this means to spring up, as a wind does. It is the breeze that comes on after a calm. In Acts a south wind sprang up and carried the ship north toward the next harbor.","g":"spring up","h":"The picture: a wind springing up behind you."},"G1921":{"b":"Strong's reads it as to know upon some mark, that is to recognize.\n\nAbbott-Smith calls it the directive form of the ordinary word for know. Not knowing in general. Knowing this one, by a sign.","g":"recognize, know fully","h":"The picture: knowing by a mark."},"G1922":{"b":"The root means to know upon a mark, to recognize. Epignosis is knowledge with the epi driving it home, full acquaintance, real recognition, not a guess. So growing in the epignosis of God is coming to know him the way you know someone you have truly met.","g":"knowledge","h":"The picture: knowing a thing full in the face."},"G1923":{"b":"The parts mean \"on\" and to write. An epigraphe is the writing put on a thing, the inscription. Whose epigraphe is this, Jesus asked, holding up the coin with Caesar's name stamped on it. And over the cross they nailed the charge in writing.","g":"inscription","h":"The picture: letters cut into the surface."},"G1924":{"b":"Built from a word meaning upon and a word meaning to grave or write, to cut letters in. The charge was written up over Jesus on the cross. God says he will write his laws upon their hearts, carved in to stay.","g":"inscribe","h":"The picture: letters cut into the surface."},"G1925":{"b":"This word is built from a prefix and to show. It means to hold something up and display it. Show me the coin for the tax, Jesus says, and they hold it out. The widows showed Peter the garments Dorcas had made. Put on view.","g":"show","h":"The picture: holding a thing up to view."},"G1926":{"b":"The root means to receive. Strong's adds the picture of admitting a guest, welcoming someone into your house. John speaks of Diotrephes, who would not receive the brothers. Picture the door opened wide, or shut.","g":"to receive","h":"The picture: the door opened to a guest."},"G1927":{"b":"The word is built on the word for a people, a town's public. Abbott says \"to stay in a place, sojourn.\" It is the visitor staying a while among folk not his own. Romans were doing this in Jerusalem when the Spirit fell at Pentecost.","g":"sojourn, reside","h":"The picture: lodging a while among another town's people."},"G1928":{"b":"Strong's says to supplement, like a codicil. Abbott-Smith says to add provisions to a document. Paul says no one adds to a covenant once it is ratified, so the law cannot rewrite the promise made to Abraham.","g":"add to","h":"The picture: extra clauses tacked onto a signed will."},"G1929":{"b":"Built from to and give. It pictures handing something straight into another's hand, like a father handing bread to his son. Abbott-Smith also gives to give way, as a ship let the wind carry it along.","g":"hand over, give","h":"The picture: handing it right into the hand."},"G193":{"b":"This joins 'not' to a word for strength and power, the grip that holds. Without it, a man cannot hold himself in check. Paul lists such people in the last days. They have no grip on their own appetites.","g":"without self-control","h":"The picture: no grip to hold himself."},"G1930":{"b":"This is built on a word meaning straight, upright. It means to straighten out further, to set right. Paul left Titus in Crete to set in order what was lacking. The picture is taking things gone crooked and standing them straight.","g":"set in order","h":"The picture: setting crooked things straight."},"G1931":{"b":"The root means to go down. This word is used of the sun setting. Paul says do not let the sun go down on your anger, do not carry your rage past sundown.","g":"go down","h":"The picture: the sun going down."},"G1932":{"b":"Abbott calls it sweet reasonableness. The root means fitting or appropriate. It is fairness that will not push a rule to its harsh limit when mercy fits better. Paul appeals by the gentleness of Christ, the King who could crush and does not.","g":"gentleness","h":"The picture: not pressing your full claim."},"G1933":{"b":"Abbott's settled sense is equitable, fair, moderate. This is the person who will not press every right to the limit, who bends where a strict man would stand and insist. Paul says let this gentleness be known to all men.","g":"gentle","h":"The picture: the one who will not demand the last inch."},"G1934":{"b":"The root is to seek. The prefix aims it, a search pointed at one thing, to inquire for, seek after, wish for. Jesus says the nations epizēteō after food and clothes, chasing them hard. He tells us to aim that same hunger at the kingdom.","g":"to seek after","h":"The picture: a search pointed at one thing."},"G1935":{"b":"This joins upon with a word for death. Abbott reads it as condemned to death. It pictures the prisoner already sentenced, led out before a watching crowd. Paul says God set the apostles out like such men.","g":"doomed to death","h":"The picture: the condemned led out to die."},"G1936":{"b":"The word means \"a laying on,\" and in the New Testament it is always the laying on of hands. Picture palms pressed on someone's head to bless them or set them apart. The gift is passed through the laying on of the elders' hands.","g":"laying on","h":"The picture: hands pressed on a person's head."},"G1937":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means to set one's heart upon something. The word joins upon with the inner fire of feeling. Your heart lands on a thing and fixes there. It can be a good longing or a greedy one.","g":"desire, covet","h":"The picture: the heart set down on a thing."},"G1938":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to set the heart upon a thing. It pictures the whole heart leaning toward what it wants. Paul warns them not to be such cravers of evil, as some of Israel were.","g":"craver","h":"The picture: the heart leaning toward the thing."},"G1939":{"b":"This comes from a verb meaning to set the heart upon something, to long for it. Epithymia is that longing, often aimed at what is forbidden. So lust of the flesh and lust of the eyes is the heart fixed hard on a thing it was never meant to have.","g":"lust, desire","h":"The picture: the heart set hard on a thing."},"G194":{"b":"The word joins \"not\" to a word meaning to mix wine for drinking. Abbott-Smith gives \"unmixed, pure.\" The Greeks watered their wine, so undiluted wine hit at full strength. So God's wrath is poured out full strength, with no water in the cup.","g":"undiluted","h":"The picture: wine with no water added."},"G1940":{"b":"Two pieces make this word, one meaning upon and one meaning to sit down. Together it is settling down on top of something. In Matthew 21:7 they lay their clothes on the donkey and Jesus sits on them for the ride into Jerusalem.","g":"sit upon","h":"The picture: sitting down on top."},"G1941":{"b":"Abbott's middle sense is to call upon, invoke, appeal to. It is the word used for appealing to Caesar in Acts 25.\n\nThe same verb covers calling on the name of the Lord. Appealing over everyone's head.","g":"call upon, appeal","h":"The picture: calling on a higher court."},"G1942":{"b":"This is a cloth thrown over a thing to hide it, a veil or cloak. Peter says do not use your freedom that way, as a cover pulled over wickedness. Live as free people, but not as a cover for evil.","g":"cloke","h":"The picture: a cloth thrown over to hide something."},"G1943":{"b":"The root means to cover up. Add over. So it is to cover something over, out of sight. Abbott says to cover over. Paul quotes the Psalm, blessed are those whose sins are covered, hidden from view.","g":"cover, forgive","h":"The picture: a cloth laid over to hide what is under."},"G1944":{"b":"This word is built from a word for on and a word meaning to curse or doom. It is a curse pressed down on top of someone. The law calls everyone accursed who breaks it, and then Christ took that curse himself.","g":"accursed","h":"The picture: a curse pressed down on a man."},"G1945":{"b":"Epi means upon, and keimai means to lie outstretched. So epikeimai is one thing lying heavy on another, weight pressing down. Luke uses it of the crowd pressing on Jesus by the lake. A demand or a storm lies on you the same way.","g":"press upon","h":"The picture: weight lying heavy on you."},"G1946":{"b":"An Epicurean is a follower of Epicurus, the philosopher of pleasure. In Athens these men met Paul in the market and argued. The label tells you whose school shaped them before they ever heard the gospel.","g":"Epicurean","h":"The picture: a student who wears his teacher's name."},"G1947":{"b":"Abbott traces this to a word meaning an ally. It means help, the aid a comrade brings. Paul says he has had help from God to this very day, still standing. The image is not a vague boost but an ally stepping in beside you to hold you up.","g":"help","h":"The picture: an ally arriving at your side."},"G1948":{"b":"Built from a word for upon and a word meaning to judge. To bring judgment down on a case, to give sentence. Pilate gave sentence that their demand should be granted. It is the word from the bench that seals a fate.","g":"give sentence","h":"The picture: the judge pronouncing sentence."},"G1949":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives one meaning. To lay hold of.\n\nIt is used of catching a sinking man, of seizing a prisoner, and of taking hold of eternal life. The same grip in very different scenes.","g":"take hold of","h":"The picture: grabbing hold."},"G195":{"b":"This word means exactness, precision. Its root is the word for most exact. Picture a craftsman measuring to the last hair, nothing left loose or rough. Paul was trained in the law to this degree, taught strictly and precisely, down to the fine point.","g":"exactness","h":"The picture: measuring to the last hair."},"G1950":{"b":"Strong's: \"to lose out of mind.\" Abbott ties it to a word meaning to cause to forget. A thing drops out of sight inside you and is gone. God, it says, will not lose his people out of mind.","g":"forget","h":"The picture: it slips out of your mind."},"G1951":{"b":"The old root behind this meant to gather or pick, then to say. Abbott gives two turns: \"to call by name\" and \"to choose for oneself.\" Paul picks Silas out and takes him. A pool gets called by its name, Bethesda. To single out.","g":"choose, name","h":"The picture: picking one out from the rest."},"G1952":{"b":"The root means to leave, to fail or run short. This is what gives out before the job is done. The writer says the time would fail him if he tried to tell of all the others who lived by faith.","g":"fail","h":"The picture: the time running out."},"G1953":{"b":"The root means to lose out of mind. James pictures a hearer of the word as a man who studies his face in a mirror, then walks away. He cannot recall what he saw. The truth dropped straight out of his memory.","g":"forgetfulness","h":"The picture: it slips out of your mind."},"G1954":{"b":"This joins \"upon\" to a root meaning the remaining ones. So it is what is left, here the time still left. Peter tells readers to live the rest of their days for God, not for old desires.","g":"rest, remaining","h":"The picture: the part still left over."},"G1955":{"b":"The root means to loose or release, and so to explain. Abbott gives \"release,\" then solution, interpretation. Peter says no prophecy of Scripture is a matter of one's own private untangling. It came from God.","g":"interpretation","h":"The picture: untying a knot to solve it."},"G1956":{"b":"This joins epi to lyo, to loosen. Epilyo is to untie a thing, and so to loosen a hard saying until it makes sense. In private Jesus loosens every parable for his own disciples, untying what the crowd is left to puzzle over.","g":"explain, expound","h":"The picture: untying the knot to explain it."},"G1957":{"b":"The root means to be a witness, to testify. The \"upon\" adds weight, to attest firmly. Peter says he has written this to bear witness that this is the true grace of God. Stand in it.","g":"testify","h":"The picture: a witness standing up to testify."},"G1958":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to care for, to look after. It is attentive care, the kind you give a person who needs tending. Julius let Paul's friends see to him and look after his needs. The word is the hands that tend, not cold duty.","g":"care","h":"The picture: hands tending someone who is sick."},"G1959":{"b":"The word means to take care of, to put your concern onto someone. The Samaritan takes care of the beaten man, then pays the innkeeper to take care of him. Hands-on tending, food and bandages and time.","g":"take care of","h":"The picture: tending a wounded man through the night."},"G196":{"b":"This is the top form of the word for exact, and the family points back to the extremity, the outermost edge. Paul says he lived as a Pharisee, the strictest sect, precise to that last edge. It is exactness pushed as far as it can go.","g":"most exact","h":"The picture: exact right to the outer edge."},"G1960":{"b":"The root means to care for something. Luke uses this word for the woman who lost one coin. She lights a lamp and searches epimelos, sweeping the whole house until she finds it. Careful attention that does not quit.","g":"carefully","h":"The picture: sweeping every corner for the lost coin."},"G1961":{"b":"Strong's says the word means to stay over, to remain. It puts \"on\" in front of \"stay.\" You do not leave. You stay on, you keep at it. Paul uses it for holding fast in the faith.","g":"remain, continue","h":"The picture: staying on."},"G1962":{"b":"This is built on the word to nod, tipping the chin as a signal. A nod that means yes, granting a request. When they begged Paul to stay longer at Ephesus, the word for his answer is this nod.","g":"consent","h":"The picture: a nod of the head."},"G1963":{"b":"Abbott gives a thought, design. It is built on the mind contriving a plan. Peter tells Simon the sorcerer to repent of the epinoia of his heart. The word names the plot forming inside before it reaches the hands.","g":"thought, design","h":"The picture: a scheme taking shape in the mind."},"G1964":{"b":"The root is epiorkos, a false swearer, from the word for an oath. Abbott gives to swear falsely, forswear oneself. Jesus quotes the old command against it. You raised your hand, you gave your word, and then you did not keep it.","g":"commit perjury","h":"The picture: an oath sworn and then broken."},"G1965":{"b":"Horkos is an oath, a sacred limit you bind yourself with. This is the man who takes that oath and swears falsely, breaking the very thing that bound him. Paul lists the perjurer among the lawless.","g":"false swearer","h":"The picture: swearing an oath and breaking it."},"G1966":{"b":"Built from a word meaning upon and a word meaning to go. It pictures a day coming on, walking up upon you. The next day, the one advancing toward you. On the following day they sailed on to Samos.","g":"next day","h":"The picture: the day coming up upon you."},"G1967":{"b":"No one is fully sure how this word is built. Abbott-Smith lands on for the coming day. It appears only with the word bread, the loaf you need for the day in front of you. Jesus teaches us to ask for it. Not a full storehouse. Enough for today.","g":"daily","h":"The picture: bread enough for the day ahead."},"G1968":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means to fall upon. It is built from upon and fall. It is the word for the father in the story who ran and fell on his lost son's neck to embrace him.","g":"fall upon","h":"The picture: falling on someone's neck."},"G1969":{"b":"The root plesso means to strike or pound. So the plain sense is to strike at, to hit, and it turns to striking with words. Paul says do not sharply rebuke an elder, but appeal to him as a father.","g":"rebuke sharply","h":"The picture: landing a blow."},"G197":{"b":"The comparative of the word for exactly. Abbott points to Priscilla and Aquila, who took Apollos aside and explained the way of God akribesteron, more exactly, Acts 18:26. They filled in what the eloquent preacher had only half right.","g":"more exactly","h":"The picture: filling in what he had half right."},"G1971":{"b":"The base means to yearn, and the prefix piles on, toward, intensely. Abbott gives to long for, desire. So this is aching desire. Paul uses it of longing to see his friends again. Both sources press the strength of the craving.","g":"long for","h":"The picture: leaning hard toward what you want."},"G1972":{"b":"The root means to dote upon, to intensely crave possession. This is not mild wishing but the ache of wanting someone. Paul hears of the Corinthians' longing for him and it comforts him. Desire that pulls you toward a person.","g":"longing","h":"The picture: leaning hard toward something."},"G1973":{"b":"The root means to crave and dote upon. Paul opens Philippians 4 calling them his longed-for brothers. The word carries the pull of missing someone, the heart reaching across the miles for people it cannot stop wanting to see.","g":"longed for","h":"The picture: aching to see a face again."},"G1974":{"b":"Same root as its sister word, to crave intensely. Abbott gives simply longing. Paul tells the Romans he has had this epipothia for many years to come and see them. A want that has waited long and still burns.","g":"intense longing","h":"The picture: a craving that will not settle."},"G1975":{"b":"This word is built on the word to travel. Abbott-Smith gives it as to journey to. People were making their way to Jesus out of every town, and as the crowd gathered he told them the parable of the sower.","g":"come, travel","h":"The picture: people journeying in from town after town."},"G1976":{"b":"The pieces mean upon and a needle. It is sewing one piece onto another. In Mark 2:21 Jesus says no one sews a patch of new cloth on an old coat, or the new pulls away and the tear gets worse.","g":"sew on","h":"The picture: stitching a patch on with a needle."},"G1977":{"b":"The root means to fling with a quick toss, and \"upon\" is added. Abbott says \"to cast or place upon.\" The disciples throw their coats onto the colt for Jesus to ride. Peter uses it too: throw all your worry onto God.","g":"cast upon","h":"The picture: flinging a cloak over its back."},"G1978":{"b":"The root is sema, a mark. Episemos means bearing a mark, as a coin is stamped and stamped clear. So it means standing out, marked among the rest. Paul calls Andronicus and Junia notable among the apostles, well marked and known.","g":"notable, of note","h":"The picture: a coin stamped with a clear mark."},"G1979":{"b":"This word grows from the word for grain. Abbott-Smith gives it as provisions, food. The disciples wanted to send the crowd away to buy food, since they were in a lonely place with nothing to eat. Then Jesus fed them all.","g":"victuals, food","h":"The picture: a store of food for the road."},"G198":{"b":"The root means most exact. Abbott says to enquire with exactness, learn carefully. Herod uses it, dragging the precise time the star appeared out of the wise men. It is the hunt for the exact fact, no rounding, no guessing.","g":"inquire exactly","h":"The picture: pinning down the exact detail."},"G1980":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is to inspect, to examine. From looking closely came the idea of going to see people, especially the sick. To visit is to look in on someone and care for them.","g":"visit, look after","h":"The picture: looking in on someone."},"G1981":{"b":"The root means to camp or pitch a tent, with upon in front. Abbott-Smith says to spread a tabernacle over. Paul says Christ's power does that, coming down like a tent over his weakness to cover it.","g":"rest upon","h":"The picture: a tent pitched right over you."},"G1982":{"b":"The root is a shadow, and epi puts it over you. To episkiazo is to cast a shade across someone. The bright cloud episkiazo the disciples on the mountain. The power of the Most High would episkiazo Mary, covering her like a shadow.","g":"overshadow","h":"The picture: a cloud casting its shade over you."},"G1983":{"b":"The main root means to take aim at, to spy, to keep your eyes fixed on something. Add a word for over. So this is watching over people the way a lookout watches, eyes on them from above.","g":"oversee","h":"The picture: the lookout keeping watch."},"G1984":{"b":"The root means to inspect, to go and see. Abbott's first sense is \"a visiting, visitation.\" Picture someone coming to your door to see how you are. It can mean mercy or judgment. The day God comes to look.","g":"visitation","h":"The picture: someone coming to look in on you."},"G1985":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this comes from skopos, a watcher. The word for bishop is built from the man who stands guard and scans for danger. So the church officer is first a lookout, watching over people, not lording over them.","g":"bishop, overseer","h":"The picture: the watchman on the wall."},"G1986":{"b":"Abbott gives it as to draw on. It rests on a word meaning to draw or pull. It pictures pulling a covering over to hide a mark already made in the flesh. Paul says the circumcised should not try to undo it.","g":"become uncircumcised","h":"The picture: drawing a cover over the mark."},"G1987":{"b":"Strong's says the word means to put the mind upon a thing. Abbott links it to a word for standing upon. To know something is to plant your mind on it and stand there.","g":"know, understand","h":"The picture: setting your mind on it."},"G1988":{"b":"Epi means over, and histemi means to stand. The epistates is the one who stands over the work, the foreman in charge. It is Luke's word when the disciples call Jesus Master. The one standing above you, giving the orders.","g":"master","h":"The picture: the one who stands over you."},"G1989":{"b":"This word means to send a message by letter, to write word. The apostles did not travel to every convert. They wrote. James says we should epistello to the Gentile believers, put it in a letter telling them to keep from a few things.","g":"write a letter","h":"The picture: a letter sent off with instructions."},"G199":{"b":"Abbott points to Herod pressing the wise men for the exact time the star appeared, Matthew 2:8. Not roughly, not about then. To the moment. Akribos is care that measures a thing down to the last detail and misses nothing.","g":"exactly, carefully","h":"The picture: measured to the last detail."},"G1990":{"b":"This word means skilled, knowing a thing all the way through, the way a craftsman knows his tools. Its root is to fix your mind on something and take it in. James says do not just claim wisdom. Show it by how you live.","g":"knowing","h":"The picture: the craftsman who knows his trade."},"G1991":{"b":"This word is built from a word for upon and a word meaning to set fast, to prop firm. To make a thing stronger, to set it solid again. Paul went from town to town strengthening the disciples, propping up the young churches.","g":"strengthen","h":"The picture: propping a thing up firm."},"G1992":{"b":"The root means to send word in writing. An epistole is that letter, a message put on paper and carried to someone far off. So Paul says you are our epistle, written on the heart, known and read by all. The church itself is his letter to the world.","g":"letter, epistle","h":"The picture: a letter sent to be read aloud."},"G1993":{"b":"This joins 'upon' to the word for the mouth. It means to put something over the mouth and so to silence. Abbott adds the picture of a bridle. Paul says these empty talkers must be stopped, their mouths shut like a bridled horse.","g":"stop mouths","h":"The picture: a hand clapped over the mouth."},"G1994":{"b":"Abbott's sense is to turn, turn oneself around. The same word covers turning your body and turning to God.\n\nConversion in this word is not a feeling. It is a change of direction.","g":"turn, turn back","h":"The picture: turning around on the road."},"G1995":{"b":"The word comes from a root meaning to turn back, to turn about. Conversion is an about-face. Paul and Barnabas report the turning of the Gentiles, and the brothers are filled with joy.","g":"conversion","h":"The picture: turning right around on the road."},"G1996":{"b":"Strong's: \"to collect upon the same place.\" Abbott: \"to gather together.\" The prefixes stack \"upon\" and \"together\" onto the word for bring. The picture is drawing scattered people in from all sides into one spot.","g":"gather together","h":"The picture: drawing scattered ones into one place."},"G1997":{"b":"This word comes from a root meaning to collect people into one place. It is the gathering, the crowd drawn together to meet. Hebrews warns against neglecting to assemble. Paul uses it of being gathered to Christ. Scattered people brought to one spot.","g":"assembling together","h":"The picture: a crowd gathered to one place."},"G1998":{"b":"The pieces mean upon, together, and to run. It is a crowd rushing in to one spot at a run. In Mark 9:25 Jesus sees the people come running together, and he rebukes the unclean spirit before the crowd swells.","g":"run together","h":"The picture: a crowd rushing in from all sides."},"G1999":{"b":"The root means to set together, to stand things in one place. This is a crowd stood together against someone, a riotous throng. It is people massed and pressing in. Paul faced these gatherings when they boiled over into mobs.","g":"riotous gathering","h":"The picture: a mob pressed together."},"G2":{"b":"This is just a name, Aaron, the brother of Moses. It comes from Hebrew, so the Greek carries no picture. A person, not an image, nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"Aaron","h":"No picture."},"G20":{"b":"The root means to jump for joy. This is that leaping gladness, joy so full the body springs up. The baby leaped in Elizabeth's womb when Mary greeted her. Not calm, but jumping.","g":"gladness, joy","h":"The picture: leaping for joy."},"G200":{"b":"Strong's links this to the word for a point or top, since the locust lights on the tips of the greenery. It is the insect that swarms and strips fields bare. John the Baptist ate them in the desert with wild honey.","g":"locust","h":"The picture: a locust on the tip of a plant."},"G2000":{"b":"Abbott traces this to a word meaning to cause to fall, to trip. It means dangerous, on the edge of a fall. Paul warns that sailing on now would be risky, the voyage about to come to grief. The image is footing that gives way, a step from a stumble.","g":"dangerous","h":"The picture: a foot about to slip."},"G2001":{"b":"Built from a word for upon and a word meaning to exert force. To pile on strength, to press the harder. The crowd grew more fierce, insisting Jesus stirs up the people. They threw more weight behind the charge.","g":"be more fierce","h":"The picture: leaning your full weight into a push."},"G2002":{"b":"This joins 'upon' to a word meaning to pile up. It means to heap more and more on. Paul says people will heap up teachers to suit themselves. The picture is a growing pile, one added on top of another, higher and higher.","g":"heap up","h":"The picture: piling up a heap."},"G2003":{"b":"The root means to arrange upon, to order, the way an officer draws up troops and tells them where to stand. An epitage is that kind of order, a command with rank behind it. Paul writes by the epitage of God. Not a suggestion.","g":"command","h":"The picture: an officer drawing up his troops."},"G2004":{"b":"Strong's says it means to arrange upon, that is, to order. The word sets an arrangement on top of someone, putting them in their place. Jesus gives orders, and even the unclean spirits obey him.","g":"command, order","h":"The picture: laying an order on someone."},"G2005":{"b":"Built from upon and to finish. One sense Abbott-Smith gives is to pay in full, pay the tax. So it means carrying a thing all the way through. God will finish what he began in you.","g":"complete, finish","h":"The picture: paying it in full."},"G2006":{"b":"This word just means useful, the things a person actually needs. James pairs it with the body: food and clothes, the bare necessaries. There is no picture in the word, only what you cannot do without.","flat":1,"g":"needful","h":"No picture."},"G2007":{"b":"Abbott's sense is to lay, set or place upon. Strong's adds that it works in a friendly or a hostile sense.\n\nThe same motion blesses and attacks. Abbott's last sense is to throw oneself upon someone.","g":"lay on, put on","h":"The picture: a hand laid on."},"G2008":{"b":"Abbott's older senses are to honour, to raise in price, and to mete out due measure. Strong's says to tax upon.\n\nSo a rebuke here is measuring out what is owed. Not a tantrum. A reckoning.","g":"rebuke","h":"The picture: setting the price on someone."},"G2009":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives punishment, penalty. The root is a word for value or price. Paul says the man has paid enough, and now it is time to forgive him and lift the penalty off his back.","g":"punishment","h":"The picture: the price a wrongdoer is made to pay."},"G201":{"b":"This comes from the word for a hearer, one who listens. The room is a place of hearing, a hall where people gather to listen. Paul is brought into it before Agrippa. The word names the room by what it is for, the listening that happens inside.","g":"hearing room","h":"The picture: a hall built for listening."},"G2010":{"b":"Strong's says to turn over, to transfer, and so to allow. Abbott-Smith's first sense is to turn to, commit, entrust.\n\nPermission here is not a shrug. It is placing the thing in someone else's hands.","g":"permit","h":"The picture: handing the matter over."},"G2011":{"b":"The root means to turn over, to hand across. This word is authority given to you, full power to act. Paul went to Damascus with power turned over to him by the chief priests. The image is the reins passed from one hand into another.","g":"authority","h":"The picture: the reins of power handed into your hands."},"G2012":{"b":"This is the steward, the man the owner puts in charge to run the household and pay the workers. The root behind it is being handed full power. He is not the master, but he holds the keys and settles the accounts in the master's place.","g":"steward","h":"The picture: the man handed the keys to run the house."},"G2013":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is to light upon. The word carries the idea of hitting a mark. It grows into to obtain, to attain. So getting the thing is not luck alone. It is your reach landing on what you went after.","g":"obtain","h":"The picture: hitting the thing you reached for."},"G2014":{"b":"The word is \"shine\" with \"upon\" joined to it. It means to shine down on a thing, to make it visible with light. The dawn from on high, Zechariah sings, will epiphaino on those who sit in darkness, light falling on faces long in the shadow.","g":"shine upon","h":"The picture: light breaking over those in the dark."},"G2015":{"b":"Strong's calls it a manifestation. The word carries the idea of shining out, coming into full view, and was used when a god was thought to appear or a king arrived in splendor. The New Testament saves it for the appearing of Christ. Light breaking in.","g":"appearing","h":"The picture: light breaking into view."},"G2016":{"b":"This word comes from a verb meaning to shine upon, to become visible. It means notable, one that stands out. Peter quotes Joel about the great and notable day of the Lord, a day that shines out, impossible to overlook.","g":"notable","h":"The picture: a day that shines out from the rest."},"G2017":{"b":"The root means to shine upon. This word means to shine forth. Paul quotes a call to the sleeper: rise from the dead, and Christ will shine on you like dawn breaking.","g":"give light","h":"The picture: light breaking over you."},"G2018":{"b":"Built from upon and to carry. It means to bring something and lay it on a person, whether a charge or a punishment. Paul asks whether God is unjust to bring his wrath upon us. A weight carried over and set down on your shoulders.","g":"bring against","h":"The picture: a load set down on you."},"G2019":{"b":"The word is \"at\" plus \"to make a sound.\" Abbott: \"to call out, shout.\" It is a voice thrown at someone, the way a crowd shouts a man down or roars its approval. Real noise aimed at a target.","g":"cry, shout","h":"The picture: a shout thrown at someone."},"G202":{"b":"This word means a hearer, one who takes words in through the ears. Strong's calls it an intensive of the word to hear, the listener catching every sound. James warns against being only that. Be a doer of the word, not a hearer only.","g":"a hearer","h":"The picture: someone taking it in by ear."},"G2020":{"b":"The root has to do with shining. Epiphosko is the light beginning to break, the first grey glow of dawn. It is as the first day of the week begins to dawn that the women come to the tomb and find it open.","g":"dawn","h":"The picture: the sky beginning to grow light."},"G2021":{"b":"The word is built on the hand. It means to put your hand upon something, to take it in hand and try. Luke uses it in his opening line, where many have taken in hand to write down the story. To set your hand to a task.","g":"take in hand","h":"The picture: putting your hand to a job."},"G2022":{"b":"This word means to pour upon. The Samaritan poured oil and wine over the traveler's wounds, the oil to soothe and the wine to clean, letting it run down into the torn skin before he bound it up.","g":"pour on","h":"The picture: pouring oil and wine onto the wounds."},"G2023":{"b":"The root is the chorus-leader, the man who paid to equip a chorus for the stage. The verb means to furnish fully, to supply. Peter says to add virtue to faith like this, God generously outfitting you, sparing no cost.","g":"supply, minister","h":"The picture: the sponsor who outfits the whole chorus."},"G2024":{"b":"This word is a supply, the provisions one part passes to the next. Strong's root means to fully supply and contribute. Paul pictures the body fed by what each joint hands on. Every part gives its share, and the whole thing grows.","g":"supply","h":"The picture: provisions passed down the line."},"G2025":{"b":"The root means to rub with oil, and \"on\" is added. Abbott says \"to spread on, anoint.\" Jesus makes mud with his spit and smears it over the blind man's eyes, spreading it on like ointment. Then he sends him to wash and see.","g":"anoint, smear on","h":"The picture: smearing wet clay over the eyes."},"G2026":{"b":"Epi means upon, and the root means to build a house. Epoikodomeo pictures laying courses of stone on a foundation already set. I laid the foundation, another builds on it. Build yourselves up on your holy faith. Real masonry, rising.","g":"build upon","h":"The picture: laying stone on the foundation."},"G2027":{"b":"Abbott's form of this word is used of a ship running ashore. It means to drive a vessel onto the shore, to beach it. They ran the ship aground, forcing the bow up onto a sandbar. The word is the deliberate driving of the hull onto land.","g":"run aground","h":"The picture: driving the hull up onto the beach."},"G2028":{"b":"The root means to give a name, to assign a title. With upon it means to name someone, to call them by that name. Abbott says to surname. Paul speaks to the man who calls himself a Jew and rests on the name.","g":"call, name","h":"The picture: a name laid on you like a title."},"G2029":{"b":"Built on a word meaning to gaze with wide-open eyes at something remarkable. So it is more than a glance. It is steady watching. Peter uses it of outsiders watching how believers live, eyes fixed on them.","g":"to watch","h":"The picture: eyes fixed and wide."},"G203":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives the bodily meaning first. The foreskin. From there it becomes an abstract word for uncircumcision.\n\nThen it stands for the people themselves. Paul uses it to mean the non Jewish world.","g":"uncircumcision","h":"The picture: a piece of skin."},"G2030":{"b":"The root means to gaze with wide-open eyes at something remarkable. So this is a spectator, one who saw it himself. Peter says they did not follow clever tales. They watched Christ's majesty with their own eyes.","g":"eye-witness","h":"The picture: an eyewitness gazing wide-eyed."},"G2031":{"b":"The root is epo, to speak. Abbott's note calls epos the articulated expression of a thought. Hebrews uses it in the phrase so to speak. A single word carrying an idea out of the mind and into the air.","g":"a word","h":"The picture: a thought pressed out into a spoken word."},"G2032":{"b":"Strong's gives three words for it. Above the sky.\n\nAbbott-Smith notes Homer used it of the gods. In the New Testament it marks off one set of things from everything that belongs to the earth.","g":"heavenly","h":"The picture: higher than the sky."},"G2033":{"b":"Strong's calls it a primary number. Abbott gives no origin at all. It is the number seven, and there is nothing behind it to look at.","flat":1,"g":"seven","h":"No picture."},"G2034":{"b":"Built from the word for seven. Peter asked if forgiving seven times was enough. Jesus stretched it far past that. If your brother sins against you heptakis in a day and turns back seven times, forgive him, Luke 17:4.","g":"seven times","h":"The picture: forgiving again, and again."},"G2035":{"b":"The number is simply seven times a thousand. But Paul uses it of Elijah's dark hour. God answers that he has kept seven thousand who never bowed to Baal. A hidden count of the faithful the prophet could not see.","g":"seven thousand","h":"The picture: seven thousand knees that never bowed."},"G2036":{"b":"Abbott-Smith notes that in Homer this word first meant to pick out, to gather, to count up. Only later did it become to say. So speaking is laying out words gathered and chosen, picked one by one and set in order.","g":"say, speak","h":"The picture: picking words out one by one."},"G2037":{"b":"This is a man's name, Erastus, a helper of Paul. It comes from a word meaning to love, so the name means beloved. Even so it stays a name, with no picture to see.","flat":1,"g":"Erastus","h":"No picture."},"G2038":{"b":"Abbott points to this as the word for working for pay. It shows up for labouring with the hands and for working at a trade.\n\nWork in these letters is ordinary paid work before it is anything else.","g":"work, labor","h":"The picture: a day's work for a day's pay."},"G2039":{"b":"The root is a toiler, a workman. This is work, a trade, and the money it brings in. The fortune-telling slave girl earned her owners much gain. The silversmiths grew rich by their craft. Labor, and the profit that comes off it.","g":"work, gain","h":"The picture: a trade and its profit."},"G204":{"b":"The word joins the tip or extreme point and a corner. It names the cornerstone, the great stone set at the outermost angle where two walls meet and lock. Christ is that stone, holding the whole building together.","g":"cornerstone","h":"The picture: the cornerstone at the angle."},"G2040":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the proper sense is a field labourer, husbandman. Picture the worker out in the crop, bent over the harvest. From there the word grew to mean any workman, and even teachers sent into God's field.","g":"worker, laborer","h":"The picture: the field hand at harvest."},"G2041":{"b":"Strong's traces this noun to an old verb meaning to work. So the word for work comes from a word meaning to work. Abbott-Smith notes an older spelling and nothing more. There is no image underneath.","flat":1,"g":"work, deed","h":"No picture."},"G2042":{"b":"The root is a word for a quarrel, wrangling. To erethizo is to stir up, to poke a reaction out of someone. It can rouse children to anger, or, in a good sense, stir zeal, as the Corinthians stirred many others.","g":"provoke","h":"The picture: poked into a reaction."},"G2043":{"b":"This word means to prop, to fix a thing firmly in place. When the ship struck, the bow drove in and stuck fast, wedged like a post, and would not move. The word is that jammed, immovable hold, the front of the ship fixed while the stern broke up.","g":"stick fast","h":"The picture: the bow rammed in and stuck fast."},"G2044":{"b":"Abbott says this was used of oxen, to bellow and roar, and so came to mean to speak out loud. Matthew: I will utter things hidden from the foundation. Picture the deep bellow of an ox breaking loose.","g":"to utter","h":"The picture: the bellow of an ox."},"G2045":{"b":"This means to search out, to hunt and examine closely. Jesus tells them to search the scriptures. Paul says the Spirit searches even the deep things of God. God is the one who searches the heart, tracking down what is hidden inside.","g":"search","h":"The picture: hunting through to track something down."},"G2046":{"b":"In Homer this word meant to pick out, gather, reckon, recount. Later it became to say.\n\nAbbott-Smith adds that it points to the meaning of what is said, while another word points to the sound.","g":"say, speak","h":"The picture: picking words out and laying them in order."},"G2047":{"b":"The root means lonesome, waste, empty. An eremia is a solitude, a wilderness, ground with no town and no people. That is where the crowd stands with Jesus asking where bread could come from out here.","g":"wilderness","h":"The picture: empty land with no one in it."},"G2048":{"b":"The desert is named for how empty it is, not how dry. Abbott-Smith gives solitary, lonely, desolate, deserted.\n\nThe same word describes a woman left on her own. It is the place with nobody in it.","g":"desert, wilderness","h":"The picture: the lonely place."},"G2049":{"b":"The root is the desert, empty waste ground. To eremoo is to turn a place into that, to strip it bare. Every kingdom divided against itself is eremoo, Jesus says, laid waste like a ruined town where no one lives.","g":"lay waste","h":"The picture: land stripped to desert."},"G205":{"b":"This is literally the top of a heap. When soldiers piled their plunder, the choicest lay on top. Abraham gave Melchizedek a tenth of the best of the spoils, skimmed from the top of the pile.","g":"spoils","h":"The picture: the best off the top of the pile."},"G2050":{"b":"The root means to lay waste, to empty out. This is the ruin left behind, a place stripped bare and abandoned. Jesus speaks of the abomination of desolation standing in the holy place. It is the desert made where a city stood.","g":"desolation","h":"The picture: a place left empty and ruined."},"G2051":{"b":"The root is eris, a quarrel. Matthew quotes Isaiah of the Servant. He will not erizo, will not wrangle or raise his voice in the streets. The word is the noise of a public fight the gentle Servant refuses.","g":"to wrangle","h":"The picture: a shouting quarrel in the street."},"G2052":{"b":"Abbott calls it ambition, self-seeking, rivalry, the drive to push your own interest. Strong's ties it to a word that stirs up anger. Paul warns, do nothing from selfish rivalry. Laboring only for your own side.","g":"strife, faction","h":"The picture: working only your own corner."},"G2053":{"b":"This word is simply wool, the fleece off a sheep. Hebrews describes Moses sprinkling the people with scarlet wool dipped in blood. And Revelation says the Son's hair was white as wool. Soft and white, taken from the flock.","g":"wool","h":"The picture: wool off a sheep."},"G2054":{"b":"This means strife and quarreling. Strong's admits its background is \"of uncertain affinity.\" Abbott gives no origin either. So the word names the fighting but shows nothing behind it.","flat":1,"g":"strife","h":"No picture."},"G2055":{"b":"The root is the word for a goat, and this is the little one, a kid. In Matthew 25:33 the King divides the crowd like a shepherd, the sheep on his right and the goats on his left.","g":"goat, kid","h":"The picture: a young goat."},"G2056":{"b":"An eriphos is a kid, a young goat, perhaps named for its hairy coat. In the judgment Jesus divides people as a shepherd parts sheep from goats, the goats set on his left. Same flock, split in two.","g":"goat, kid","h":"The picture: the young goat set on the left."},"G2057":{"b":"His name is a short form of Hermes, who in the old Greek stories was the messenger of the gods, the runner carrying word between them. Paul greets Hermas simply, one name in a long list of friends at Rome.","g":"Hermas","h":"The picture: the messenger of the gods."},"G2058":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to translate. Interpretation is carrying a message across from one language into another so it can be understood. Paul lists it as a gift set beside speaking in tongues.","g":"interpretation","h":"The picture: carrying words across."},"G2059":{"b":"Strong's traces this to Hermes, the messenger of the gods and the god of language. To interpret is to carry a meaning from one tongue into another. John keeps stopping to say what a name means, like Messiah, which is to say Christ.","g":"interpret, translate","h":"The picture: the messenger god carrying words across."},"G206":{"b":"This means the far tip, the outermost point. The rich man begs for the tip of a finger dipped in water. Jacob leans on the top of his staff. Angels gather people from one end of the sky to the other. The extreme edge.","g":"tip, edge","h":"The picture: the very tip."},"G2060":{"b":"Hermes was the messenger of the Greek gods, and Strong's traces the name to a word meaning to utter, to speak or say. Because Paul was the one doing the talking at Lystra, the crowd called him Hermes. The name carries a voice.","g":"Hermes","h":"The picture: the messenger who does the talking."},"G2061":{"b":"His name joins Hermes, the messenger of the Greek gods, to a word meaning to be born. It means born of Hermes. Like Phygelus, he deserted Paul. A man named for a god who abandoned the faith.","g":"Hermogenes","h":"The picture: born of the god Hermes."},"G2062":{"b":"Abbott traces this to herpo, \"to crawl.\" It is a creeping thing, a creature that drags itself along the ground. Peter's sheet let down from heaven is full of them. God has cleansed even the crawling things.","g":"creeping thing","h":"The picture: a creature dragging along the ground."},"G2063":{"b":"This word just means red. In the New Testament it always sits with the word for sea, the Red Sea, which Israel crossed on dry ground. A plain color, the one the water was named for.","g":"red","h":"The picture: the color red."},"G2064":{"b":"Strong's says this is the middle voice of a primary verb. Nothing older lies behind it. Abbott-Smith gives two senses and no history: to come, and to go. A plain travel word.","flat":1,"g":"come, go","h":"No picture."},"G2065":{"b":"Strong's gives to interrogate, to ask. It is speech aimed at a person, a question set before them, and by extension a request. So when Jesus is asked, erotao, someone stands in front of him, laying a question or a plea at his feet.","g":"ask","h":"The picture: putting a question to someone's face."},"G2066":{"b":"This word comes from a word meaning to clothe. It is simply the cloth put on, a robe, the apparel you wrap around yourself against the cold. In James it is the fine robe that gets the good seat, while the poor man in rags is pushed aside.","g":"clothing","h":"The picture: cloth wrapped on the body."},"G2068":{"b":"Strong's says it is strengthened from an older word that already meant to eat. So there is nothing hiding behind it. It is the plain, everyday word for having a meal.","flat":1,"g":"eat","h":"No picture."},"G2069":{"b":"This is a name and nothing more. Strong's traces it to Hebrew. It marks an ancestor in Jesus' family tree. A name is a label for a person, so there is no image hidden behind it to picture.","flat":1,"g":"Esli","h":"No picture."},"G207":{"b":"Strong's traces this name to the Latin word aquila, an eagle. Aquila was a tentmaker who, with his wife Priscilla, worked beside Paul and taught Apollos the way more fully. A man named for the bird that flies highest.","g":"Aquila","h":"The picture: an eagle."},"G2072":{"b":"This is a mirror, the thing you look into. Ancient mirrors were polished metal and gave back a dim, blurred reflection. Paul says now we see through such a glass darkly, but then face to face.","g":"mirror","h":"The picture: the dim metal mirror."},"G2073":{"b":"The word means evening, the hour the sun goes down in the west. On the road to Emmaus the two urge Jesus to stay because it is toward evening and the day is far spent. The close of the day, dusk coming on.","g":"evening","h":"The picture: the light fading toward sundown."},"G2074":{"b":"The name means court-yard. It comes from a word for a yard closed in by a fence. Esrom is Hezron, listed among the ancestors of David and of Jesus.","g":"Hezron","h":"The picture: a court-yard."},"G2078":{"b":"Not just last in a queue. Abbott-Smith says it is used of the lowest or least honoured place.\n\nThe same word marks the last days. Furthest out, whether in space, in rank, or in time.","g":"last","h":"The picture: the far end of the table."},"G2079":{"b":"The root means farthest, the very last. This word puts a person at that final edge. In Mark 5:23 Jairus falls at Jesus' feet and begs, my little daughter is at the point of death, come lay your hands on her.","g":"at death's door","h":"The picture: standing at the last edge."},"G208":{"b":"The root means to make a thing binding, to ratify it. Put \"not\" in front and you cancel it, strip its force. Jesus says the Pharisees void the word of God with their tradition. They take something settled and treat it as if it never stood.","g":"annul","h":"The picture: cancelling a settled deal."},"G2080":{"b":"From a word meaning into, this points within. Abbott shows it for the room inside and, most of all, the inner man, the self that is renewed day by day while the outside wastes away.","g":"inside","h":"The picture: the inner man."},"G2081":{"b":"The root is inside. Esōthen means from within, out of the hidden interior. Jesus says it is not from outside but from within, out of the heart, that evil comes. He calls the Pharisees cups scrubbed outside but esōthen full of greed.","g":"within","h":"The picture: out of the hidden interior."},"G2082":{"b":"This is the comparative of the word \"inside,\" preposition or adjective, so it means further in, the innermost. The jailer took Paul and Silas to the inner prison, the deepest cell. Hebrews uses it for the place within the veil, as far in as you can go.","g":"inner","h":"The picture: the deepest room, furthest inside."},"G2083":{"b":"Strong's traces this to a clansman, one of your own group. It means comrade or companion, and Jesus uses it to address people, \"friend.\" He says it to the grumbling worker, to the guest with no wedding clothes, and to Judas in the garden. Friend, with a chill in it.","g":"friend","h":"The picture: one of your own circle."},"G2084":{"b":"This joins other with a word for the tongue and its language. It pictures lips moving in a strange tongue you cannot follow. Paul quotes God, with other tongues I will speak to this people.","g":"other tongue","h":"The picture: lips speaking a strange language."},"G2085":{"b":"This word joins different with the word for a teacher. It means to stand up and teach a different lesson than the one handed down. Paul tells Timothy to stop those who do it. The teacher whose message has drifted off the true one.","g":"teach other doctrine","h":"The picture: a teacher with the wrong lesson."},"G2086":{"b":"The roots are different and yoke. Two mismatched animals cannot pull straight together. Paul says do not be yoked like that with unbelievers, the two dragging against each other down the row.","g":"unequally yoke","h":"The picture: an ox and a donkey strapped under one yoke."},"G2087":{"b":"Strong's says the origins are uncertain. Abbott adds one useful note. It properly means the second of a pair, though by New Testament times it had spread to mean any other.","flat":1,"g":"other, different","h":"No picture."},"G2088":{"b":"The root heteros means the other of two, a genuinely different one. Paul says if in anything you think heteros, God will make it plain. Not a shade of difference. A mind pointed the other direction, waiting to be turned.","g":"differently","h":"The picture: seeing it the other way round."},"G2089":{"b":"Eti means still, yet, the sense that something keeps going on. It holds a state open that has not ended. So while we were eti sinners, still sinners, Christ died for us. The word marks that the old condition was still in force when grace broke in.","g":"yet, still","h":"The picture: still there, not gone yet."},"G209":{"b":"The root means to prevent, to block by word or act. Put the not in front. So it means with nothing standing in the way. Abbott says without hindrance. Paul preached in Rome freely, and no one shut him down.","g":"freely","h":"The picture: no hand raised to stop him."},"G2090":{"b":"Abbott's first use is hospitable preparation, the work done before people arrive.\n\nThe same word covers what God has made ready ahead of time. A place prepared, like a house before company comes.","g":"prepare, make ready","h":"The picture: getting the room ready for a guest."},"G2091":{"b":"The root is hetoimazo, to make ready. Abbott gives readiness. Paul sets it in the armor, feet fitted with the readiness of the gospel of peace. Shoes already on, standing prepared to move the moment the call comes.","g":"preparation","h":"The picture: boots laced and ready to march."},"G2092":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means prepared, ready. Strong's traces it to an old word for fitness, but that gives no clear image. It just describes something set and waiting to be used.","flat":1,"g":"ready","h":"No picture."},"G2093":{"b":"Built from the word for ready. Abbott gives readily. Paul says he is hetoimos not only to be bound but to die at Jerusalem for the name of the Lord, Acts 21:13. A man already prepared, waiting only for the word to go.","g":"ready, readily","h":"The picture: bags already packed."},"G2094":{"b":"Strong's calls it apparently a primary word, so it comes from nothing older. Abbott-Smith gives one meaning, a year, then lists grammar. There is nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"year","h":"No picture."},"G2095":{"b":"This little word just means well, or good. It is the master's cry to the faithful servant, well done. Strong's says it is the neuter of an old word for good. There is nothing behind it to picture.","flat":1,"g":"well","h":"No picture."},"G2096":{"b":"The name means life-giver. Eve was the first woman, and Adam gave her the name after the fall, marking her as the mother of all the living.","g":"Eve","h":"The picture: life-giver."},"G2097":{"b":"The word is built from good and messenger. Strong's says it means to announce good news. Abbott-Smith gives to bring or announce glad tidings.\n\nIt is not about explaining anything. It is about carrying word that is good.","g":"bring good news","h":"The picture: news worth carrying."},"G2098":{"b":"Abbott says that in older Greek the word was not the message. It was a reward for good tidings. What you handed the runner who brought word the battle was won.\n\nIt could also be the thank offering.","g":"good news, gospel","h":"The picture: the reward for good news."},"G2099":{"b":"This word comes from a word meaning to announce good news. An evangelist is the one who carries that news, the messenger running with glad tidings. Philip was called the evangelist. Timothy was told to do this work.","g":"evangelist","h":"The picture: the messenger running with good news."},"G21":{"b":"Strong's says it properly means \"to jump for joy,\" to exult. Abbott-Smith says \"to exult, rejoice greatly.\" This is not a quiet gladness. It is joy that gets the body moving, joy that leaps.","g":"rejoice greatly","h":"The picture: jumping for joy."},"G210":{"b":"Built from not and hekon, willing. Abbott gives unwilling. Paul says if he preaches akon, against his own will, he still has a trust laid on him. A job pressed into your hands that you did not choose.","g":"unwilling","h":"The picture: doing what you would rather not."},"G2100":{"b":"Built from well and pleasing. Abbott gives to be well pleasing. Before Enoch was taken up, Scripture says he euaresteo God, his whole life pleased Him, Hebrews 11:5. To do good and to share, God is well pleased with such sacrifices.","g":"please well","h":"The picture: a life that pleases God well."},"G2101":{"b":"Two words, well and pleasing. It describes what fully pleases someone. Paul asks for bodies offered as a living sacrifice, holy and well-pleasing to God. Not merely allowed. Welcomed.","g":"well-pleasing","h":"The picture: the gift that pleases."},"G2102":{"b":"Built from well and pleasing. It describes worship that arrives as a gladness to the one who receives it. Hebrews says to serve God euarestos. Not just doing the duty. Doing it so it lands as welcome.","g":"acceptably","h":"The picture: service that lands as welcome."},"G2103":{"b":"Strong's reads the name as good-willer, from well and to will. Eubulus is a Christian who sends greetings at the close of Second Timothy. His name carries a good wish built right in, one who means well.","g":"Eubulus","h":"The picture: a name that means good counsel."},"G2104":{"b":"The word joins well and born. It means well born, of noble stock. A certain nobleman goes into a far country to receive a kingdom and return. Paul says not many of you were of noble birth. High blood, marked from the cradle.","g":"noble","h":"The picture: born into a high family."},"G2105":{"b":"Strong's says this word means a clear sky, fine weather. It is built from a word for well and the name of the old sky god. In Matthew 16:2 Jesus notes that people read a red evening sky and say fair weather is coming.","g":"fair weather","h":"The picture: a clear evening sky."},"G2106":{"b":"Strong's builds it from two words and gives the sense as to think well of, to approve.\n\nAbbott-Smith notes it was common in legal documents for giving consent. Approval that someone was willing to sign.","g":"be pleased","h":"The picture: thinking well of it."},"G2107":{"b":"Built from well and a word for thinking or seeming good. It is God's good pleasure, what he gladly wills. The angels sing of it over Bethlehem, peace toward the people of his good pleasure. His glad choice.","g":"good pleasure","h":"The picture: what seems good to God."},"G2108":{"b":"The root names a worker of good, someone who does good works for others. This word is the deed itself, the kindness performed. Peter healed a lame man and was questioned about the good deed done. A kind act you can point at.","g":"good deed","h":"The picture: a good deed done with your hands."},"G2109":{"b":"The word comes from 'a worker of good.' It means to go about doing kindness. Peter sums up the whole life of Jesus this way: he went around doing good and healing all the oppressed.","g":"do good","h":"The picture: hands busy doing good."},"G211":{"b":"This is a box carved from alabaster, a smooth white stone, made to hold perfume. To pour it out you broke the neck. The woman brings one to Jesus, snaps it open, and empties the whole thing over him.","g":"alabaster box","h":"The picture: a sealed jar of costly perfume."},"G2110":{"b":"Built from a word for well and a word for work or deed. A doer of good, one who does you a good turn. The kings of the nations are called benefactors, Jesus said, but among you the leader must serve.","g":"benefactor","h":"The picture: a worker of good turns."},"G2111":{"b":"The word joins well and placed. It means well positioned, ready for use, fit. Land that drinks the rain and bears a crop is fit. Jesus says a man who looks back after starting the plow is not fit for the kingdom.","g":"fit, suitable","h":"The picture: set well in its place, ready to hand."},"G2112":{"b":"This comes from euthys, straight, level. Straightway means the road runs dead straight from one thing to the next with no bend and no pause. So in Mark, eutheos, immediately, they leave the nets and follow. No gap between the call and the going.","g":"immediately","h":"The picture: a straight line, no bend, no delay."},"G2113":{"b":"Built from \"straight\" and a word for a run or race. It is a ship running a straight course, no tacking, the wind full behind. Luke uses it when they set sail from Troas and made a straight run to Samothrace.","g":"sail direct","h":"The picture: a ship running a straight line across the sea."},"G2114":{"b":"Built from a word meaning good spirits. Abbott gives to be of good cheer. On the storm-tossed ship, with all hope gone, Paul stood and said, euthymeo, take heart, not one life will be lost, Acts 27:22. Cheer held up in a gale.","g":"be cheerful","h":"The picture: cheer held up in a gale."},"G2115":{"b":"This joins a word for well with a word for the passions, one that pictures hard breathing. Good cheer here is breathing easy, the chest settled. Paul told the storm-tossed sailors to take heart. Their breathing could slow and calm.","g":"good cheer","h":"The picture: breathing easy."},"G2116":{"b":"Strong's says \"to straighten,\" and \"technically, to steer.\" James points to the tiny rudder that turns a huge ship wherever the pilot wills. John the Baptist uses the other side of the word: make the road straight for the Lord.","g":"steer, make straight","h":"The picture: a small rudder steering a great ship."},"G2117":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is straight, direct, used of paths. He notes a street in Damascus was actually named this.\n\nThe second sense moves to people. A straight heart is the same word as a straight road.","g":"straight","h":"The picture: a road with no bends."},"G2118":{"b":"The root means straight, level, without a bend. This word is uprightness. A king's rule that is straight does not lean to favor or fraud. The scepter of God's kingdom is a straight one.","g":"uprightness","h":"The picture: a line that runs straight."},"G2119":{"b":"The roots are \"good\" and \"time,\" a well-timed moment. This word is having a spare hour, room in the day. So many were coming and going that Jesus and the disciples had no leisure even to eat. Not even a gap to sit and take a meal.","g":"have leisure","h":"The picture: a free gap in a crowded day."},"G212":{"b":"From a word for a braggart. So this is the swagger of a boaster, the loud talk of a man puffing himself up bigger than he really is. James warns against exactly this vaunting over tomorrow's plans.","g":"boasting, pride","h":"The picture: the boaster puffing himself up."},"G2120":{"b":"This joins eu, well, to kairos, the right time or season. Eukairia is the well-timed chance, the gap that opens to act. From that moment Judas watched for a good time to hand Jesus over, waiting for the crowd to thin.","g":"opportunity","h":"The picture: watching for the right moment."},"G2121":{"b":"Two words joined: \"well\" and the word for a set or proper time. Not clock time, but the right moment, when everything lines up. Mark uses it for the day Herod's guard came down at his feast. The opening was there.","g":"well-timed","h":"The picture: the day that lines up just right."},"G2122":{"b":"This is the adverb of the last word, well-timed. It means doing a thing just when the moment opens. Mark uses it for Judas, watching for the right chance to hand Jesus over quietly, when the crowd would not be there.","g":"opportunely","h":"The picture: catching the right moment."},"G2123":{"b":"This is built from well and a word for hard toil, the kind that cuts your strength down. Put together it means easy, light work. Jesus uses it when he asks whether it is easier to forgive sins or to say rise and walk. Little effort either way for him.","g":"easier","h":"The picture: labour that hardly cuts your strength."},"G2124":{"b":"The root means taking hold well, carefully, the way you handle something fragile and precious. From caution it grew to mean godly fear, reverence. Hebrews says Christ was heard for his reverence. He came to God like one who handles holy things with care.","g":"reverence, godly fear","h":"The picture: handling something precious with care."},"G2125":{"b":"The root means to take hold well, with care. This word is the caution that reveres what it handles. Warned by God of things not yet seen, Noah took care and built an ark to save his house.","g":"reverence","h":"The picture: handling with careful hands."},"G2126":{"b":"The word is \"well\" joined to \"take hold.\" It pictures grasping a thing carefully, the way you handle something precious so as not to drop it. Turned toward God it means devout, reverent. Simeon was such a man, waiting for the comfort of Israel.","g":"devout","h":"The picture: handling something carefully, as if fragile."},"G2127":{"b":"Strong's builds this from the words for well and for speech. Abbott-Smith's first sense is to speak well of, praise.\n\nTo bless God is to say good of him. To bless a person is to say good over them.","g":"bless","h":"The picture: good words spoken over someone."},"G2128":{"b":"The root joins well and word, to speak well of. So this one is blessed, worthy of good words. It is how Zechariah opens his song, blessed be the Lord God of Israel. Praise spoken up toward God.","g":"blessed","h":"The picture: good words spoken over God."},"G2129":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it can mean fair speaking, flattering speech. The word is built from good and word. To bless is to speak good words over a person. Aimed wrongly the same word becomes smooth flattery.","g":"blessing","h":"The picture: good words spoken over someone."},"G213":{"b":"The root means wandering. It first pictured a vagabond, a roamer who moved town to town selling cures and boasting of wonders. From that came the braggart, the impostor who oversells himself. A big talker always on the move.","g":"boaster","h":"The picture: a wandering quack."},"G2130":{"b":"This is 'well' joined to a word meaning to give over, to share. It describes someone good at handing what they have to others. Not just willing to give. Good at it. The word is about the open hand.","g":"ready to distribute","h":"The picture: handing your things over."},"G2131":{"b":"Timothy's mother's name is built from 'well' and the word for victory, conquest. Eunice means something like good victory. The name carries a win in it, though here it marks the woman who raised him in the faith.","g":"Eunice","h":"The picture: a good victory."},"G2132":{"b":"Built from well and mind, to be well-minded toward someone. Jesus says eunoeo with your accuser quickly while you walk together to the judge. Turn a warm mind toward the man suing you before the courtroom door shuts.","g":"be kindly disposed","h":"The picture: making peace on the way to court."},"G2133":{"b":"Same root, a good mind toward others. Abbott gives goodwill. Paul tells slaves to work with eunoia, as to the Lord. The word turns forced labor into willing kindness, the same task done with the heart in it.","g":"good will","h":"The picture: serving with a warm heart, not a grudge."},"G2134":{"b":"The root is eunouchos, a castrated man, often set to guard a royal bedchamber. To eunouchizo is to make one. Jesus speaks of some who make themselves eunuchs for the kingdom, giving up marriage to serve it wholly.","g":"make a eunuch","h":"The picture: a man made a eunuch."},"G2135":{"b":"Strong's builds it \"from (a bed)\" and the word for having or keeping. Abbott agrees: the one who keeps the bed. Such men guarded the bedchambers of a household or court. So the name pictures the keeper of the bedroom.","g":"eunuch","h":"The picture: the keeper of the bedchamber."},"G2136":{"b":"This is a woman's name, Euodia. Underneath it means a good journey, well and road joined, a smooth trip. Paul pleads with her and Syntyche to agree, to travel the same road in the Lord.","g":"Euodia (name)","h":"The picture: a good road, an easy journey."},"G2137":{"b":"The word joins \"well\" to \"road,\" hodos, \"a road. by implication, a progress.\" To have a good road, a smooth journey with no blocks. From there it means to prosper. John prays his friend may prosper and be in health, the way clear before him.","g":"prosper","h":"The picture: a clear, open road ahead."},"G2138":{"b":"Built from well and persuaded. Abbott gives ready to obey, compliant. James lists it among the marks of wisdom from above. Not stubborn, not dug in. Willing to listen and yield when the right word comes.","g":"compliant","h":"The picture: quick to be won over to good."},"G2139":{"b":"The word is built from \"well,\" \"around,\" and \"to stand.\" Put together it means a thing that stands all around you, crowding in from every direction. That is how Hebrews describes sin. It surrounds the runner and blocks each way out.","g":"easily beset","h":"The picture: a crowd that hems you in on every side."},"G214":{"b":"The word copies a sound. Abbott-Smith says it first meant to raise a war-cry, the shout an army lets out charging in. It can be a scream of triumph or a wail of grief. Paul uses it for a clanging cymbal, all noise.","g":"wail, clang","h":"The picture: the war-cry going up."},"G2140":{"b":"Built from well and to do. Abbott gives beneficence, doing good. Hebrews pairs it with sharing and calls it a sacrifice that pleases God. Not good intentions. Good actually done for someone who needed it.","g":"doing good","h":"The picture: hands busy with kindness."},"G2141":{"b":"Strong's says the word means to be good for passing through. To have means is to have a clear way, room to move. In Acts each disciple gives as much as he is able.","g":"have means","h":"The picture: an open road with nothing blocking it."},"G2142":{"b":"This rests on a word meaning to be good for passing through, an easy passage, a clear road. From an open way came the sense of means and plenty. Demetrius told the craftsmen their wealth flowed from the shrines.","g":"wealth","h":"The picture: an open road."},"G2143":{"b":"Built from \"well\" and a word meaning to stand out and catch the eye, this is good looks, the beauty that turns heads. James says the rich man fades like a flower whose lovely bloom drops off in the heat.","g":"grace","h":"The picture: the good looks that turn heads."},"G2144":{"b":"The word joins well with a verb meaning to receive or admit. It is something taken in gladly, welcomed at the door. Peter says our offerings to God are this, not merely tolerated but received well, the way a host gladly lets a guest in.","g":"acceptable","h":"The picture: the guest welcomed gladly in."},"G2145":{"b":"This joins well with a word meaning to sit near and attend as a servant. It pictures a servant seated close by, always ready. Paul wants them to wait on the Lord this way, undistracted.","g":"diligent service","h":"The picture: the servant seated close at hand."},"G2146":{"b":"Built from well and face. Abbott-Smith points to a word meaning fair of face, to look well and make a fair show. It is putting on a good face for the crowd. Paul says some do it only to dodge trouble.","g":"make a show","h":"The picture: putting on a good face."},"G2147":{"b":"Strong's says it is a stretched out form of a primary word, and names nothing older. Abbott-Smith gives no origin. He does note one thing worth keeping: it means to find, with or without previous search.","flat":1,"g":"find","h":"No picture."},"G2148":{"b":"This joins the east wind to klydon, a surge of the sea. The name is a storm-wind that drives the waves into surging swells. It struck the ship and drove it helpless before it. The word packs the wind and the heaving water into one name.","g":"Euroclydon","h":"The picture: the east wind whipping up the waves."},"G2149":{"b":"Built from broad and a word for open space or room. So it means wide, roomy, spacious. Jesus says broad is the road that leads to destruction. Picture a wide-open road with plenty of room on it.","g":"broad, spacious","h":"The picture: the wide-open road."},"G215":{"b":"Built from not and laleo, to utter words. Abbott gives not to be uttered. Paul says the Spirit prays for us with groans past speech. The ache is real but no words are big enough to carry it.","g":"unutterable","h":"The picture: a groan too deep for words."},"G2150":{"b":"The root joins well and reverence. Eusebeia is reverence done rightly. Abbott says it begins close to home, toward parents and others, then rises toward God. Not a feeling only but a whole life bent low in respect toward the One it owes.","g":"godliness","h":"The picture: a life bent low in reverence."},"G2151":{"b":"This means to show good reverence, and it reaches two ways. Toward God it is worship. Toward parents it is to respect and support them. Paul uses it for children paying back their aged parents. Reverence that shows itself in what your hands do.","g":"worship, show piety","h":"The picture: children caring for their aged parents."},"G2152":{"b":"This word is built from a word for well and a word meaning to revere and bow before. Eusebes is the man who reveres God rightly, who worships the way he should. Cornelius was called this, a devout man who feared God.","g":"devout","h":"The picture: bowing low the right way."},"G2153":{"b":"The root means well-reverent, i.e. pious, reverence pointed the right direction. To live this way is to let worship shape your days. Paul warns that all who want to live godly in Christ will be persecuted. Devotion you can see.","g":"piously","h":"The picture: bowing the right way."},"G2154":{"b":"This joins well with a word for a sign. It means well-marked, easy to understand. It pictures a clear signal, a plain mark anyone can read. Paul says unless your words are this clear, you speak into the air.","g":"easy to understand","h":"The picture: a clear, plain mark."},"G2155":{"b":"This word joins \"well\" to the word for the intestines, the guts. The Greeks felt pity low in the body, deep in the bowels. So to be tender-hearted is to have good insides. It is the kind of feeling that hits you in the stomach.","g":"tender-hearted","h":"The picture: good guts."},"G2156":{"b":"The root euschemon means well-formed, good in shape. The word behind it is schema, form. So this is doing a thing in good shape, gracefully. Paul says walk this way, decently, the way a well-formed figure carries itself in the open.","g":"decently","h":"The picture: good shape, good form."},"G2157":{"b":"This joins well with a word for shape and form. It grows from a word meaning well-formed, graceful. It pictures the comely, well-shaped parts of the body. Paul says the unpresentable parts are dressed with this borrowed grace.","g":"comeliness","h":"The picture: the well-shaped part."},"G2158":{"b":"Built from a word meaning well and a word for shape or figure. First it means good-looking, a graceful bearing. Then it means high in rank. Joseph of Arimathea was such a man, of honorable standing, who asked for the body of Jesus.","g":"honorable","h":"The picture: a well-shaped, graceful figure."},"G2159":{"b":"Strong's says \"in a well-strung manner.\" The word is built from \"well\" and \"to stretch,\" like a cord drawn taut. The chief priests accuse Jesus this way, tight and forceful. Apollos argues like this too, straining every nerve to prove his point.","g":"vehemently","h":"The picture: a bowstring pulled tight."},"G216":{"b":"The root is to talk, to utter words. Put \"not\" in front and it is speechless, dumb. A father brought his son who had a spirit that made him mute. Jesus commanded the deaf and dumb spirit to come out. A mouth stopped, unable to make a word.","g":"mute","h":"The picture: a mouth that cannot form a word."},"G2160":{"b":"Built from well and a word meaning a turn. It first meant quick wit, a mind that turns fast with words. It slid into coarse jesting and dirty jokes. Paul says such talk is out of place.","g":"coarse jesting","h":"The picture: a quick-turning tongue."},"G2161":{"b":"Strong's reads the name as fortunate, from well and fate. Eutychus is the young man who dozed off in a high window during Paul's long sermon and fell three floors. He was taken up alive. The name held.","g":"Eutychus","h":"The picture: a boy whose name means Lucky."},"G2162":{"b":"The root means well spoken of. Abbott-Smith gives good report, praise, the opposite of slander. Paul says he keeps going whether people speak well of him or ill, unmoved by both.","g":"good report","h":"The picture: a good word spoken about you behind your back."},"G2163":{"b":"Built from well and a word for a saying or report. Abbott-Smith says it first meant uttering words of good omen, then fair-sounding and auspicious. Paul says fix your mind on whatever is of good report.","g":"of good report","h":"The picture: good words spoken over you."},"G2164":{"b":"This word joins well and to bear. Abbott-Smith gives it as to be fruitful. The ground of a rich man produced so heavily he had nowhere to store it. He tore down his barns to build bigger, and that night his life was required.","g":"bring forth abundantly","h":"The picture: a field heavy with a bumper crop."},"G2165":{"b":"Strong's says the word means to be in a good frame of mind, to rejoice. It is the glad heart at a feast. The father said, let us eat and be merry, for my son is home.","g":"rejoice, be merry","h":"The picture: the mind set at ease."},"G2166":{"b":"This is the Euphrates, the great river of Asia. The name is foreign, so its meaning is lost. But the thing is real, a wide river at the edge of the known world. Revelation dries it up to open a way.","g":"Euphrates","h":"The picture: a great river."},"G2167":{"b":"The word is built on a root meaning cheerful, a mind set in a good frame. Peter quotes the Psalm, you will fill me with gladness in your presence. It is joy that lifts the whole inner mood, face and heart turned bright.","g":"gladness","h":"The picture: a mind turned glad."},"G2168":{"b":"Strong's says this word specially means to say grace at a meal. Abbott lists a run of verses about giving thanks before food.\n\nThe thanksgiving in Paul's letters is a table word carried into prayer.","g":"give thanks","h":"The picture: saying grace at the table."},"G2169":{"b":"The word carries grace inside it, eu and charis, grace answered well. Abbott's sense is the giving of thanks, thanksgiving, said out loud. Paul wants every request wrapped in it. The early church took this word to name its meal of thanks.","g":"thanksgiving","h":"The picture: thanks said out loud."},"G217":{"b":"This just means salt. Strong's links it to the older word for salt, and adds \"figuratively, prudence.\" Abbott notes speech can be salted with wit. But the word itself simply names salt, with no picture behind it.","flat":1,"g":"salt","h":"No picture."},"G2170":{"b":"This joins eu, well, and a word meaning to give freely as a favor. So it is the good response to a gift, a thankful heart. Paul tells them to be thankful, answering God's kindness in kind.","g":"thankful","h":"The picture: a gift met with thanks."},"G2171":{"b":"This word comes from a word meaning to wish and to pray. A euche is a prayer, or a vow bound before God. Paul cut off his hair at Cenchreae because of a vow, this word, a promise made and paid.","g":"vow","h":"The picture: a vow bound before God."},"G2172":{"b":"This word means to wish, and so to pray. Strong's calls it a primary verb, not built from anything. It is a longing turned toward God, with nothing behind it to picture.","flat":1,"g":"pray, wish","h":"No picture."},"G2173":{"b":"The word puts together well and useful. It is a thing that serves, that does the job when you reach for it. Abbott-Smith says useful, serviceable. Paul says Onesimus was once no use and now is useful. A person can become a good tool in the Master's hand.","g":"useful","h":"The picture: the tool that works when you pick it up."},"G2174":{"b":"Built from well and the word for soul, which underneath means breath. To be eupsycheo is to be in good spirits, to breathe easy again. Paul sends Timothy so he too may be cheered by news of them.","g":"be cheered","h":"The picture: breathing easy again."},"G2175":{"b":"The roots are eu, well, and ozo, to smell. So the word is a good smell, a sweet aroma rising. Paul says we are the fragrance of Christ, and calls a life given up for others a sweet-smelling sacrifice.","g":"fragrance","h":"The picture: a sweet smell rising."},"G2176":{"b":"Built from good and name, so of good name or omen. The left side was seen as the unlucky side. So people gave it a kind name, the good-name side, to soften the bad omen. It simply means left.","g":"left (hand)","h":"The picture: the flattering name for the unlucky side."},"G2177":{"b":"This joins upon with a word meaning to jump. To spring onto something with a leap. The man with the evil spirit leaped on the sons of Sceva and overpowered them all.","g":"leap on","h":"The picture: the pounce."},"G2178":{"b":"Built on the word for once. Abbott gives once for all. The picture is a single act that never needs doing again. Hebrews says Christ offered Himself ephapax, one sacrifice, and the door stayed shut behind it forever.","g":"once for all","h":"The picture: one act, never repeated."},"G218":{"b":"Abbott-Smith links it to a word for oil. It pictures rubbing oil or perfume onto skin or hair. Mary anointed Jesus with perfume. Jesus said, when you fast, put oil on your head.","g":"anoint","h":"The picture: rubbing on oil."},"G2180":{"b":"The word names a person from Ephesus, a city of Asia Minor. Picture the theater crowd that roared for two solid hours, Great is Artemis of the Ephesians, Acts 19. That mob defending its goddess is this word made flesh.","g":"Ephesian","h":"The picture: a face from Ephesus."},"G2181":{"b":"This is a place name. Strong's says it is probably of foreign origin, with no meaning given. It is a city on the map, not a word with an image behind it.","flat":1,"g":"Ephesus","h":"No picture."},"G2182":{"b":"The root means to find, and this word is one who finds out, who devises. Abbott says an inventor, a contriver. Paul pins it to evil, inventors of wicked things, minds busy thinking up fresh ways to sin.","g":"inventor","h":"The picture: one who keeps finding new ways to do harm."},"G2183":{"b":"The root means for a day, day by day. This is the rota that split the priests into groups, each taking its turn of temple duty. Luke opens his Gospel with Zechariah, on duty because his group's turn had come round.","g":"priestly course","h":"The picture: the priests' turn on the roster."},"G2184":{"b":"Built from \"for\" and the word for a day, this means lasting just one day, gone by nightfall. James uses it of daily bread, the food a poor brother needs today. Wishing him well fills no plate.","g":"daily","h":"The picture: something that lasts a single day."},"G2185":{"b":"This is built from upon and a word meaning to arrive, to be present. It means to reach all the way to a place. Paul says his God-given bounds reach even as far as Corinth, so he does not overstretch himself.","g":"reach","h":"The picture: reaching all the way there."},"G2186":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's plain sense is to stand upon. Strong's adds the result. To be present.\n\nStrong's notes the tone can go either way. The same word covers a friendly arrival and an assault.","g":"come upon, stand by","h":"The picture: someone standing right over you."},"G2187":{"b":"The name means double fruit, doubly fruitful. Ephraim was a place in Palestine, named after Joseph's son, whose birth made Joseph fruitful in the land of his suffering.","g":"Ephraim","h":"The picture: double fruit."},"G2188":{"b":"This is the Aramaic word Jesus spoke aloud, ephphatha, be opened. In Mark 7:34 he looks up to heaven, sighs, and says it over the deaf man, and at once his ears open and his tongue is loosed.","g":"be opened","h":"The picture: swing open."},"G2189":{"b":"This is enmity, the hostility that stands between enemies. It comes from the word for a foe. Herod and Pilate had been at odds until that day. Paul says the natural mind is at war with God. The cold hatred that keeps two sides apart.","g":"enmity","h":"The picture: the cold gap between enemies."},"G219":{"b":"This word is built from the word for a cock and the word for a sound or voice. It means the rooster's crow. That crow marked the third watch of the night. Jesus warns his coming will be sudden, before the cock crows.","g":"cockcrow","h":"The picture: the rooster crowing."},"G2190":{"b":"Abbott traces it to a noun meaning hatred. His first sense is passive, hated, hateful. Then active, hating, hostile.\n\nThe word runs both ways. An enemy is someone caught in a hatred, from either end of it.","g":"enemy","h":"The picture: hated and hating at once."},"G2191":{"b":"This is a viper, a poisonous snake. John calls the crowd a brood of echidnai, a nest of young vipers. On Malta one fastened on Paul's hand from the fire. A small snake with a deadly bite.","g":"viper","h":"The picture: a viper."},"G2192":{"b":"Strong's calls this a primary verb, so it does not come from anything older. It means to hold, and it stretches to owning, keeping, and even being ill or well. There is nothing underneath it.","flat":1,"g":"have, hold","h":"No picture."},"G2194":{"b":"The name means habitation, a dwelling place. It comes from a word meaning to reside. Zebulun was a son of Jacob, a tribe of Israel, and the region they settled.","g":"Zebulun","h":"The picture: habitation."},"G2195":{"b":"This is a man's name, Zacchaeus, the short tax collector who climbs a tree to see Jesus. Strong's says it is of Hebrew origin. A name for a person, not a word built from an image. There is nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"Zacchaeus","h":"No picture."},"G2196":{"b":"The name comes from a word picturing a rising of light, like dawn breaking. Zara is Zerah, a son of Judah, listed in the ancestry of Jesus.","g":"Zerah","h":"The picture: a rising of light."},"G2197":{"b":"The name means Jah has remembered. Jah is a short form of the Lord's name. Zacharias was the priest and father of John the Baptist, who doubted the angel's word.","g":"Zacharias","h":"The picture: the Lord has remembered."},"G2198":{"b":"Strong's calls it a primary verb. Nothing older lies behind it. Abbott-Smith gives no origin either, only the plain sense: to live, to be alive, and then to spend a life a certain way.","flat":1,"g":"live, be alive","h":"No picture."},"G2199":{"b":"This is the name of James and John's father. Strong's says it is of Hebrew origin but gives no meaning for it. There is nothing to picture, only the man.","flat":1,"g":"Zebedee","h":"No picture."},"G22":{"b":"The root is the word for a wedding, the nuptials. The letter in front means not. So this word is simply the one with no wedding, unmarried. Paul speaks to them plainly about their freedom to serve the Lord.","g":"unmarried","h":"The picture: no wedding."},"G220":{"b":"Strong's guesses this comes from a word \"to ward off,\" but that link is thin and Abbott-Smith gives no origin at all. So there is no solid picture here, only the bird that crowed at Peter's denial.","flat":1,"g":"rooster","h":"No picture."},"G2200":{"b":"The root means to boil or glow with heat. Zestos is boiling hot, water bubbling on the fire. Jesus tells the church at Laodicea he wishes they were hot or cold. Not lukewarm. He wants them at a boil.","g":"hot, boiling","h":"The picture: water at a rolling boil."},"G2201":{"b":"The root is the word for a yoke, the bar that couples two oxen. So the word means a pair joined. Luke uses it for the offering Mary and Joseph bring at the temple, a pair of turtledoves, the poor family's gift.","g":"pair, yoke","h":"The picture: two yoked together as a pair."},"G2202":{"b":"This comes from a word for yoking or coupling, the same idea as a yoke on oxen. It names the bands that lashed the two steering-oars in place. As they made for the beach, they loosed these rudder-ropes. The word ties the rudders together like a yoke.","g":"rudder-band","h":"The picture: the ropes yoking the steering-oars."},"G2203":{"b":"This is the name of the chief god of the Greeks, the supreme deity of the Greeks. The worksheet gives no meaning behind the name itself. The crowd at Lystra took Barnabas for Zeus. There is nothing to picture in the word.","flat":1,"g":"Zeus","h":"No picture."},"G2204":{"b":"This word means to be hot, to boil, of liquids, or to glow, of solids, water bubbling over a fire or metal glowing in it. Luke says Apollos was boiling in spirit as he spoke of Jesus. Paul tells us to stay at that heat, never lukewarm.","g":"be fervent","h":"The picture: water boiling in the pot."},"G2205":{"b":"Strong's says the word properly means heat. It comes from a word for boiling. Zeal is emotion at boiling point. Turned one way it is burning devotion. Turned another it boils over into jealousy.","g":"zeal, jealousy","h":"The picture: something boiling hot."},"G2206":{"b":"Strong's calls it \"warmth of feeling for or against.\" Abbott-Smith says \"to burn with envy or jealousy.\" The heat can turn either way. It burns as jealousy, or it burns as eager desire for a good thing.","g":"be zealous, jealous","h":"The picture: burning with feeling."},"G2207":{"b":"The root means to have warmth of feeling for or against something. A zealot is someone who runs hot, not cool and distant. So when a man is called a zealot, he is burning about his cause, on fire and unable to sit still.","g":"zealot","h":"The picture: a man running hot."},"G2209":{"b":"Abbott gives damage, loss, the opposite of gain. Picture a ship's cargo thrown overboard, the loss Paul foresaw at sea, Acts 27:10. He uses the same word for everything he once prized, now counted loss for Christ, Philippians 3:8.","g":"loss, damage","h":"The picture: the loss column in the ledger."},"G221":{"b":"This just means a person from the city of Alexandria, from the city so called. The word points to a place, not to a picture. There is nothing behind it to see beyond the name of a town and the people who lived there.","flat":1,"g":"Alexandrian","h":"No picture."},"G2210":{"b":"From zemia, loss. To zemioo is to forfeit, to lose what you held. Paul says he suffered the loss of all things for Christ and counts them as garbage. Gaining the whole world means nothing if you forfeit your own soul.","g":"suffer loss","h":"The picture: goods thrown away."},"G2211":{"b":"His name means Jove-given, a gift of Zeus, chief of the Greek gods. Abbott says it is shortened from a longer name meaning gift of Zeus. Zenas is a lawyer Paul wants helped on his way. A believer whose name once honored Zeus.","g":"Zenas","h":"The picture: a gift of Zeus."},"G2212":{"b":"Strong's says the origin is uncertain. Abbott-Smith gives no history either. Three senses only: to seek for, to strive after, and to demand. There is nothing older to look at.","flat":1,"g":"seek, look for","h":"No picture."},"G2213":{"b":"The root means to seek, to search for. This is the thing being searched out, a question, a matter argued back and forth. The charges against Paul were questions about their own law. A search carried on in words.","g":"question, debate","h":"The picture: a thing hunted for."},"G2214":{"b":"Under this word for a dispute lies the word for seeking. Abbott's first sense is a seeking, search. A questioning is a hunt, people searching for an answer. Paul warns against the kind that never finds anything and only stirs up more arguments.","g":"dispute, questioning","h":"The picture: people hunting for something."},"G2215":{"b":"Abbott: \"a kind of darnel, resembling wheat.\" Strong's: \"darnel or false grain.\" It is a weed that grows up looking almost exactly like wheat, so you cannot tell them apart until the harvest comes.","g":"tares, weeds","h":"The picture: a weed that looks just like wheat."},"G2216":{"b":"The name means descended from Babylon, born there. It joins a word for flowing away with Babel, that is Babylon. Zerubbabel led the exiles back and helped rebuild the temple.","g":"Zerubbabel","h":"The picture: born in Babylon."},"G2217":{"b":"Strong's says this is gloom that shrouds like a cloud. In Homer it was the murk of the underworld. It is deep darkness, thick and heavy. Peter and Jude use it for the blackness kept in store for the rebellious, a smothering dark.","g":"blackness, gloom","h":"The picture: a shrouding black cloud."},"G2218":{"b":"From a word meaning to join. A zygos is the wooden yoke laid across two oxen to couple them, and also the beam of a balance. Take my yoke upon you, says Jesus, for mine is easy. The bar that binds you to pull with another.","g":"yoke","h":"The picture: a wooden yoke on two oxen."},"G2219":{"b":"Strong's says the word means ferment, as if boiling up. Leaven makes dough swell and bubble as though it were on the boil. A little of it works through the whole lump.","g":"leaven","h":"The picture: dough bubbling up."},"G222":{"b":"The word means belonging to Alexandria, the great port of Egypt. Luke uses it of the grain ship that carried Paul toward Rome. A label of origin, it puts a real harbor and a real hull behind the word.","g":"Alexandrian","h":"The picture: the ship from Alexandria."},"G2220":{"b":"The root is the word for leaven, described as if the dough were boiling up. A little is worked into the lump and the whole thing swells and changes. Jesus says the kingdom spreads like that, quietly, all through.","g":"leaven","h":"The picture: dough bubbling up as it rises."},"G2221":{"b":"The word joins \"alive\" and \"to hunt\". It means to take a creature alive, to capture rather than kill. Jesus tells Peter that from now on he will catch men this way, hauling them in living, saved, not destroyed.","g":"catch alive","h":"The picture: catching them alive, not killing."},"G2222":{"b":"Abbott-Smith separates two Greek words. This one is the life by which we live. The other is the life we live, the course of it and the means.\n\nSo this word points at life itself, not at how a life is spent.","g":"life","h":"The picture: the life you live by, not the life you lead."},"G2223":{"b":"Strong's: \"a belt. by implication, a pocket.\" Abbott says it served \"as a receptacle for money.\" People tucked their coins into the folds of the belt at the waist. So the belt was also the purse.","g":"belt, girdle","h":"The picture: a belt used as a purse."},"G2224":{"b":"This word comes from the word for a belt. To gird is to wrap the belt on and cinch it. When you were young you dressed yourself, Jesus tells Peter, but another will gird you and lead you where you would not go.","g":"gird","h":"The picture: fastening on a belt."},"G2225":{"b":"The word joins alive and bring forth. It means to keep alive, to spare from death. Jesus says whoever loses his life will preserve it. In Egypt the word is used of the midwives who let the baby boys live. To hold a life safe.","g":"preserve alive","h":"The picture: keeping a living thing alive."},"G2226":{"b":"Abbott-Smith builds this on a word meaning alive. It is not the word for a wild beast. It simply names something that lives.\n\nKJV says beast in Revelation. The Greek says living one.","g":"living creature","h":"The picture: a thing that is alive."},"G2227":{"b":"The word joins living thing and make. Zōopoieō is to make alive, to breathe life into what is dead. The Spirit does it, the letter kills but the Spirit makes alive. As all die in Adam, so in Christ all are made alive, the buried seed quickened.","g":"make alive","h":"The picture: breathing life into the dead."},"G223":{"b":"Strong's says this name means man-defender. It joins a word for man to the idea of warding off. Several men in the New Testament carry it, including a son of the man who bore Jesus' cross. A name that pictures someone guarding people.","g":"Alexander","h":"The picture: a man standing guard over people."},"G2230":{"b":"The root is the word for a leader, the chief man who goes out front. This verb is to be that leader, to govern a region. Luke fixes the time of Jesus' birth by it: when Quirinius was governor of Syria.","g":"be governor","h":"The picture: the one who leads the province."},"G2231":{"b":"The root is hegemon, a leader, the chief person of a province. Luke dates John's ministry by the hegemonia of Tiberius Caesar. The word marks a span of rule, the years a chief man holds the reins of power.","g":"government, reign","h":"The picture: the governor's years in office."},"G2232":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is a leader, guide. Then a commander. Then a governor of a province.\n\nThe word climbs from showing the way to holding the office. The Roman governor of Judaea is called by this name.","g":"governor","h":"The picture: the one who goes first."},"G2233":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives the plain sense as to guide, go before. A leader here is the one out ahead on the road.\n\nThe same word also means to reckon or count something up in your mind.","g":"lead, consider","h":"The picture: walking out in front."},"G2234":{"b":"The root means sweet, like something that tastes good. This word is gladly, with that same pleasure. Herod, though he later killed John, used to listen to him gladly. The preaching went down sweet to him even while it troubled him.","g":"gladly","h":"The picture: sweet on the tongue."},"G2235":{"b":"Ede means already, now, the thing has come sooner than you thought. Abbott points to Matthew, where John warns the axe is already laid to the root of the trees. So already is not idle. It says the moment you waited for has quietly arrived.","g":"already, now","h":"The picture: the axe already at the root."},"G2236":{"b":"The root means sweetly, with pleasure, the sweet taste behind gladness. Hedista is most gladly, sweetest of all. Paul says most gladly will I glory in my weaknesses, so that the power of Christ may rest on me.","g":"most gladly","h":"The picture: sweet to the taste."},"G2237":{"b":"This word just means pleasure, the feeling of delight to the senses. It comes from a word meaning to be glad. It is an inward feeling, not a thing you can see. There is no picture behind it.","flat":1,"g":"pleasure","h":"No picture."},"G2238":{"b":"This joins \"sweet\" to a word for smell. Hedyosmon is the sweet-scented herb, mint. Jesus says the Pharisees carefully tithe even their mint and herbs but let justice and mercy go. Counting leaves, missing the point.","g":"mint","h":"The picture: the sweet-smelling mint leaf."},"G2239":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is a haunt, abode, the spot you always come back to. From that comes the word for a habit. So your manners are the grooves you keep walking back into.","g":"manners","h":"The picture: the haunt an animal keeps returning to."},"G224":{"b":"The word comes from a verb meaning to grind. Aleuron is what is left, the grain crushed to flour. It is the flour the woman hides the yeast in. The wheat had to be broken down before it could ever become bread.","g":"flour, meal","h":"The picture: grain ground down to flour."},"G2240":{"b":"Abbott-Smith explains the grammar simply. The word means to have come, be present. It is not travelling. It has landed.\n\nWhen Revelation says the hour is come, this word says it is already here.","g":"have come, be here","h":"The picture: already standing at the door."},"G2241":{"b":"The word simply means my God. Jesus cried it out from the cross, Eli, Eli, lama sabachthani, which means my God, my God, why have you forsaken me.","g":"Eli","h":"The picture: my God."},"G2243":{"b":"The name means God of Jehovah, my God is the Lord. It joins a word for God with Jah, the Lord's name. Elijah was the prophet who confronted the priests of Baal.","g":"Elijah","h":"The picture: my God is the Lord."},"G2244":{"b":"Abbott calls it \"a stage of growth whether measured by age or stature.\" It marks how far someone has grown, in years or in height. Zacchaeus was small in this, short in stature.","g":"age, stature","h":"The picture: how far you have grown, in years or height."},"G2246":{"b":"Strong's traces the word for sun back to a word meaning a ray, though it hedges on the wider link.\n\nAbbott offers no derivation at all. So the sun is named for what it throws, not for what it is.","g":"sun","h":"The picture: a ray."},"G2247":{"b":"Strong's says \"a stud, i.e. spike.\" Abbott says \"a nail.\" Thomas says unless he sees the mark of the nails in Jesus' hands and puts his finger where they were, he will not believe. The hard iron that held him to the cross.","g":"nail","h":"The picture: an iron nail, a spike."},"G225":{"b":"Abbott quotes a definition worth keeping. Truth is the reality lying under an appearance. The actual thing, not the look of it.\n\nHe adds a second sense for people. Not just saying true things. Being true all the way through.","g":"truth","h":"The picture: what is really there."},"G2250":{"b":"Strong's traces this word back to a root meaning tame, or gentle. Day would then be the quiet part, the space between dawn and dark.\n\nAbbott-Smith does not confirm it. He gives no origin, only the uses.","g":"day","h":"The picture: the tame stretch of time."},"G2251":{"b":"This is the word ours, built from we. Abbott points to our people, those inside the circle. Titus is told to let our people learn to do good works. It draws a line around us.","g":"our","h":"The picture: our own people."},"G2253":{"b":"This word joins half and to die. Abbott-Smith gives it as half-dead. Robbers stripped the traveler, beat him, and left him lying on the road half dead, too far gone to help himself. Two men passed him by.","g":"half dead","h":"The picture: a man beaten and left half dead."},"G2255":{"b":"Picture a heap divided into two equal parts, one kept, one given. That is this word, the half. Zacchaeus stood and said half of his goods would go to the poor. One thing cut cleanly down the middle.","g":"half","h":"The picture: one pile split in two."},"G2256":{"b":"The word is simply half plus hour. John uses it once. When the seventh seal opens there is silence in heaven for about a hemiorion. A short, measured stillness, the whole of heaven holding its breath.","g":"half-hour","h":"The picture: half an hour, and heaven falls silent."},"G226":{"b":"The root means true, in the sense of not concealing, nothing hidden. To aletheuo is to speak what is real and hold nothing back. Paul says speak the truth in love, so that the body grows up into Christ.","g":"speak truth","h":"The picture: nothing kept hidden."},"G2261":{"b":"The word means mild, gentle. Paul reaches for it and paints the scene himself, gentle among you as a nursing mother caring for her children. Strong's links it to being easy to speak to. Softness in the hands and in the voice.","g":"gentle","h":"The picture: a nurse with a child."},"G2262":{"b":"The name means watchful, wide awake. It comes from a word meaning to wake, to stir and be alert. It pictures someone who does not sleep at his post.","g":"Er","h":"The picture: watchful."},"G2263":{"b":"Strong's traces this to the word for a desert, through the idea of stillness. Think the hush of a wide, empty place. Paul asks that we may lead a quiet and peaceable life in all godliness.","g":"quiet","h":"The picture: the stillness of an empty land."},"G2264":{"b":"The name is built to mean heroic, hero-like. Abbott lists the line of Herods, the kings who bore it. So the word sounds grand, yet it hangs on the man who killed the infants and the one who beheaded John. A heroic name over an unheroic house.","g":"Herod","h":"The picture: a name meaning hero-like."},"G2265":{"b":"The word means partisans of Herod, his political party. Picture them joining hands with the Pharisees, old enemies, to plot how they might destroy Jesus, Mark 3:6. Men named for the earthly king whose side they had chosen.","g":"Herodians","h":"The picture: Herod's political party."},"G2266":{"b":"Her name is the feminine of Herod, a name Strong's ties to the word heroic. She was Herod's granddaughter, and it was her grudge that took John the Baptist's head. A royal name over a deadly wish.","g":"Herodias","h":"The picture: the woman who carried Herod's name."},"G2267":{"b":"The name is built on Herod, which Strong's traces to a word meaning heroic. Herodion is a believer Paul greets in Rome. Whatever his ties to that royal house, he now belongs to Christ and is named among the saints.","g":"Herodion","h":"The picture: a man carrying a king's name."},"G2268":{"b":"The name means Jah has saved. Jah is a short form of the Lord's name. It declares that salvation comes from the Lord, and from no one else.","g":"Jeshaiah","h":"The picture: the Lord has saved."},"G2269":{"b":"The name means rough, hairy to the touch. Esau was Isaac's firstborn, born red and covered with hair, who sold his birthright to his brother Jacob.","g":"Esau","h":"The picture: rough."},"G227":{"b":"Abbott-Smith traces this to a word for escaping notice, with the negative in front. So it primarily means unconcealed, manifest.\n\nTruth here is not a claim you defend. It is a thing left uncovered.","g":"true, truthful","h":"The picture: nothing hidden."},"G2270":{"b":"The root pictures keeping one's seat, staying sat down and undisturbed. It is to be still, to rest from work, to hold your peace. The women rested on the Sabbath. When they could not persuade Paul, they fell silent.","g":"keep quiet, rest","h":"The picture: keeping your seat, sitting still."},"G2271":{"b":"The root means \"keeping one's seat (sedentary),\" sitting still instead of bustling about. So the word is quietness, the calm of someone who stays put and holds their peace. Work quietly and eat your own bread, Paul says.","g":"quietness, silence","h":"The picture: sitting still instead of bustling about."},"G2272":{"b":"Strong's says this means keeping one's seat, staying put. The quiet person does not jump up and stir. He keeps his seat, undisturbed and not disturbing others. Peter praises a quiet spirit. Settled, not restless.","g":"quiet, peaceable","h":"The picture: the one who keeps his seat."},"G2274":{"b":"The root means worse, or less. So the word is to be the lesser, to come out beaten. Peter warns that a man is enslaved by whatever overcomes him, brought low and made the loser by the thing he could not master.","g":"be overcome","h":"The picture: the beaten, lesser side."},"G2275":{"b":"The root means to make worse, to defeat, to vanquish. This is the loss itself, the defeat. Paul says Israel's fall, their defeat, brought riches to the world. It is the coming up short, the ground lost in a contest. A beating taken.","g":"loss, defeat","h":"The picture: a beating taken in a contest."},"G2276":{"b":"This is the comparative, inferior, less, the lower end of a scale. Paul tells the Corinthians their gatherings make things worse, not better. The word weighs two things and marks the one that came out smaller. A downward tilt.","g":"worse, less","h":"The picture: the worse side of the scale."},"G2278":{"b":"This comes from a word for a loud or confused noise, a roar. It means to make a booming sound. It pictures brass clanging, a hollow blare that fills the air. Paul says love-less words are just sounding brass.","g":"sound, roar","h":"The picture: brass clanging in the air."},"G2279":{"b":"This is a loud, rolling noise, the roar that gives us the word echo. The sound of a rushing wind fills the house at Pentecost. Men will faint with fear, Jesus says, at the echos of the sea and the waves, the roar of the deep.","g":"noise, sound","h":"The picture: the roar of a crashing sea."},"G228":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this means true in the sense of real, genuine. It is set against what is fake or half made.\n\nSo the true vine and the true light are the originals. Everything else is the imitation.","g":"true, real","h":"The picture: the real thing, not a copy."},"G2280":{"b":"Thaddaeus is a name, one of the twelve apostles. Strong's says it is of uncertain origin, so no one is sure what it is built from. The word names the man, with no picture.","flat":1,"g":"Thaddaeus","h":"No picture."},"G2281":{"b":"Abbott separates two words. One means the vast open water. This one is the sea as set against the land.\n\nThat is why it also covers a lake. The Sea of Galilee gets this word.","g":"sea","h":"The picture: the sea where the land stops."},"G2282":{"b":"Strong's says this word means to brood, the way a bird warms its eggs with its own body. Abbott starts with to heat, to warm. Paul says a man cherishes his own flesh, and Christ the church. To cherish is to keep something warm.","g":"cherish, warm","h":"The picture: a bird brooding over its eggs."},"G2283":{"b":"The name comes from a word for a palm tree, tall and upright. Tamar was the daughter-in-law of Judah, listed among the mothers in Matthew's genealogy.","g":"Tamar","h":"The picture: a palm tree."},"G2284":{"b":"The root is being stunned by surprise, stopped in your tracks. This verb is to be struck with amazement. As they walked up to Jerusalem, the people were amazed and afraid. It is the jolt that freezes you when something staggering happens.","g":"amaze","h":"The picture: struck still with shock."},"G2285":{"b":"Strong's links this to an old word meaning to dumbfound, to strike silent. It is the shock that freezes a crowd. Amazement takes hold of everyone when Jesus drives out an unclean spirit, and no one can find words.","g":"astonishment","h":"The picture: struck dumb where you stand."},"G2286":{"b":"This word is built from the word for death. Strong's says it means poisonous, something deadly to drink. Jesus tells his followers that if they drink anything poisonous it will not harm them. The deadly cup loses its sting.","g":"deadly","h":"The picture: poison in the cup."},"G2287":{"b":"Built from two words, death and to carry, this is a thing that carries death in it, hauling it about ready to deliver. James says the tongue is loaded with poison like that, death waiting to be spilled.","g":"deadly","h":"The picture: a thing that carries death in it."},"G2288":{"b":"This is built on the verb to die. Abbott starts with the death of the body, whether it comes slow and natural or sudden and violent. So the wages of sin is death, the body going still, and behind it what John calls the second death.","g":"death","h":"The picture: the body goes still."},"G2289":{"b":"The root is death. Thanatoō is to put to death, to hand over to dying. The council seeks it against Jesus. Paul turns the blade inward, by the Spirit put to death the deeds of the body. And, for your sake we are killed all day long.","g":"put to death","h":"The picture: handing over to dying."},"G229":{"b":"The word means to grind, from the same root as flour. It is turning the handmill, crushing grain between two stones. Jesus says two women will be grinding together at the mill, and one is taken, one left.","g":"grind","h":"The picture: grinding grain at the mill."},"G2290":{"b":"This word means to bury. Strong's calls it a primary verb, so it does not come from anything else. There is no picture behind it, only the act itself.","flat":1,"g":"bury","h":"No picture."},"G2291":{"b":"This is the name of Terah, the father of Abraham. Strong's traces it to Hebrew. It marks one man in the family line. A name points to a person, not a picture. There is nothing to see.","flat":1,"g":"Thara","h":"No picture."},"G2292":{"b":"A later form of the word for courage. To be of good cheer or courage, to be confident. Paul says we are always confident, whether at home in the body or away, our courage set on the Lord. Firm footing, no dread.","g":"be bold","h":"The picture: standing without fear."},"G2293":{"b":"From the word for boldness. It means to be of good courage. It is Jesus' word to the frightened, be of good cheer. He says it to the paralyzed man, to the woman who touched him, and to disciples in the storm.","g":"be of good cheer","h":"The picture: take heart."},"G2294":{"b":"This word means courage or boldness. Strong's ties it to a word for daring. It names something felt inside, a lift of nerve, not a thing you can see. When Paul saw the believers coming, he took courage.","flat":1,"g":"courage","h":"No picture."},"G2295":{"b":"The root means to look closely, to gaze at. A thauma is a wonder, the sight that stops you and makes you stare. So it is no wonder, Paul says, that Satan himself disguises as an angel of light.","g":"wonder","h":"The picture: the sight that stops you to stare."},"G2296":{"b":"This comes from thauma, a wonder, something that stops you. To thaumazo is to marvel, to stand there amazed at what you see. So the crowds thaumazo at Jesus, jaws dropping, and he himself marvels at a soldier's faith. The word is a face caught off guard.","g":"wonder, marvel","h":"The picture: the jaw drops, eyes go wide."},"G2297":{"b":"The root is a word for wonder, the gasp when you see something amazing. Here it means the wonderful things themselves, the marvels. In Matthew 21:15 the chief priests see the wonders Jesus does in the temple and the children shouting, and they are angry.","g":"wonderful thing","h":"The picture: the wonders that turn heads."},"G2298":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to wonder, to marvel. It is not just nice. It is the sight that stops you cold. The stone the builders threw away became the cornerstone, and they called it this. A jaw-drop.","g":"wonderful","h":"The picture: the thing that stops you and makes you stare."},"G2299":{"b":"This is simply the female form of the word for god, a goddess. Here she is great Artemis of the Ephesians, whose silver shrines were sold, and for whose honor the whole city rioted.","g":"goddess","h":"The picture: the she-god."},"G23":{"b":"Abbott builds it from two words, much and to grieve. Much grief that turns hot. So it is indignation. Jesus was indignant when the disciples pushed the children away, and told them to let the little ones come.","g":"be indignant","h":"The picture: grief boiled into anger."},"G230":{"b":"This comes from alethes, true, and Strong's catches the sense, true as not concealing, with nothing kept back. So truly this was the Son of God, the centurion says, alethos. Not a guess but the plain thing standing uncovered before his eyes.","g":"truly","h":"The picture: nothing hidden, out in the open."},"G2300":{"b":"This is not a glance. Abbott-Smith calls it careful and deliberate vision which interprets its object.\n\nHe adds that early writers used it with a sense of wondering. It is the look that stays until it understands.","g":"behold, gaze at","h":"The picture: the long look."},"G2301":{"b":"This comes from the word for a theatre. To be made a spectacle is to be set on the stage before the crowd, exposed to their jeers. The believers were held up publicly to reproach and abuse.","g":"make a spectacle","h":"The picture: put on stage for the crowd to jeer."},"G2302":{"b":"This word comes from a word meaning to look closely, to watch. A theatron is the place of watching, the theatre, and also the show itself. The Ephesus mob rushed into the theatre. We are made a spectacle to the world.","g":"theatre","h":"The picture: the theatre where a crowd watches."},"G2303":{"b":"Theion is sulphur, brimstone, the yellow rock that catches fire and reeks. It rained on Sodom out of the sky. Strong's ties the word to flashing, as of lightning. Fire and brimstone falling, the stink of it in the air.","g":"brimstone","h":"The picture: yellow brimstone that burns."},"G2304":{"b":"Built from the word for God. Abbott gives divine. Peter says His theios power has given us everything we need for life and godliness, Second Peter 1:3, and calls us to share the divine nature. What belongs to God, held out to us.","g":"divine","h":"The picture: what belongs to God."},"G2305":{"b":"The root is theios, divine. Abbott gives divine nature, divinity. Paul says creation puts God's theiotes on display, his divine nature read off the things he made. The invisible qualities pressed visibly into hills and stars.","g":"divinity","h":"The picture: God's fingerprints on the made world."},"G2306":{"b":"The word comes from the word for sulphur. Abbott-Smith gives \"of brimstone, sulphureous.\" Picture yellow sulphur catching fire with a choking stench. So the breastplates of the riders were the color of burning brimstone.","g":"of brimstone","h":"The picture: yellow brimstone burning."},"G2307":{"b":"This word grows out of the verb to want. But Abbott-Smith says it often points to the thing that is willed, not the act of willing.\n\nSo God's will is a settled thing, not a mood.","g":"will","h":"The picture: the thing wanted, not the wanting."},"G2308":{"b":"The root is thelo, to determine as an active choice. Abbott ties it to willing. Hebrews says God bore witness by signs according to his own thelesis. Not drift, not chance. A will that decides and then moves.","g":"will","h":"The picture: the deliberate choice to act."},"G2309":{"b":"Strong's says this is to choose or prefer, an active option from your own impulse. It is the will reaching out and taking one thing over another. So God's will is not a daydream. It is a choice, God setting his desire on something and reaching for it.","g":"will, wish","h":"The picture: the will reaches out and picks."},"G231":{"b":"The root is the word for the sea, the salt water. A halieus is a man who works that water, a fisherman. Jesus found them by the lake and said he would make them fishers of men.","g":"fisherman","h":"The picture: a man working the salt water."},"G2310":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means a foundation stone, foundation. The word comes from placing. It is the stone set down first, the one the whole house rests on. Paul says he laid such a stone, and it is Christ.","g":"foundation","h":"The picture: the base stone laid in the ground."},"G2311":{"b":"The root is a foundation, the stonework laid down first. To themelioo is to set that base. The wise man's house stood because it was founded on rock. Dug deep, footed on stone, and the flood could not move it.","g":"to found","h":"The picture: stonework laid down first."},"G2312":{"b":"Two words, theos, God, and didasko, to teach. So it means taught by God directly, not needing a man to instruct you. Paul says about loving one another they are taught of God, God teaching their hearts himself.","g":"taught by God","h":"The picture: God himself as the teacher."},"G2314":{"b":"This word joins God with a word meaning to fight or do battle. It means one who fights against God. Gamaliel warns the council: if this movement is from God, you cannot stop it, and you may find yourselves at war with God himself.","g":"fighting God","h":"The picture: taking up arms against God."},"G2315":{"b":"This joins the word for God to a word meaning to breathe, to blow like a breeze. Scripture is God-breathed. The picture is air leaving God's mouth. Every word carried out on his breath, the way your words ride on yours.","g":"God-breathed","h":"The picture: breathed out by God."},"G2316":{"b":"Strong's says the origin of this word is uncertain. Abbott-Smith gives no history either, only the plain meaning, a god or deity. The most important word in the book has nothing behind it to look at.","flat":1,"g":"God, a god","h":"No picture."},"G2317":{"b":"This joins theos, God, and a word for being reverent, standing in awe before him. So it is godliness, a life turned toward God. Paul says this, not gold and fine hair, is the true adorning for women who profess it.","g":"godliness","h":"The picture: a life bent toward God in awe."},"G2318":{"b":"Built from a word for God and a word meaning to revere and adore. A theosebes is one who stands in awe of God, God-fearing. God does not listen to sinners, the healed man said, but to one who fears him and does his will.","g":"worshipper of God","h":"The picture: the head bowed before God."},"G2319":{"b":"Built from God and a root meaning to hate with a shudder. Abbott gives hateful to God. Paul lists it among the marks of a wrecked mind in Romans 1. The word names a settled loathing aimed straight at heaven.","g":"hateful to God","h":"The picture: a face set in hatred against God."},"G232":{"b":"This word comes from the word for a fisherman. It means to fish. Peter says it after the resurrection: I am going fishing. He went back to the boat and the nets, to the trade he knew, and caught nothing until dawn.","g":"to fish","h":"The picture: going out to catch fish."},"G2320":{"b":"The root is theos, God. Abbott gives deity, Godhead. Paul says in Christ all the theotes dwells bodily. Not a spark of the divine but the whole of it, God himself housed in flesh you could touch.","g":"deity, godhead","h":"The picture: the fullness of God in a body."},"G2321":{"b":"Two words make this name: God and friend. Strong's reads it friend of God. He is the man Luke writes his Gospel and Acts to, named or perhaps described. Whoever he was, his name says he was dear to God.","g":"Theophilus","h":"The picture: the name means friend of God."},"G2322":{"b":"The root means to wait on, to serve. From it comes both healing, the tending of the sick, and the household staff, the servants who attend a master. Jesus asks who is the faithful steward set over the household servants.","g":"healing, household","h":"The picture: the servants who wait on a household."},"G2323":{"b":"Healing starts as serving. Abbott-Smith's first sense is to do service, serve. Strong's says to wait upon menially.\n\nOnly then does it become the doctor's word: to treat, cure, heal. Care and cure are one word.","g":"heal","h":"The picture: waiting on someone."},"G2324":{"b":"This is a servant, but Strong's adds 'as if cherishing.' It is the attendant who serves with care, not merely a slave who is owned. Moses was this kind of servant in all God's house, faithful and caring.","g":"servant","h":"The picture: the attendant who serves with care."},"G2325":{"b":"The word means to reap. Abbott-Smith lists the plain farming use, then the figure.\n\nPaul uses it for what a life yields. What you sow you also reap. A whole growing season packed into one verb.","g":"reap","h":"The picture: harvest time."},"G2326":{"b":"Strong's says the word means the reaping, the crop cut down. It comes from the word \"to reap.\" Jesus looked at the crowds and said the harvest is plentiful but the workers are few.","g":"harvest","h":"The picture: the reaping."},"G2327":{"b":"The root is therizo, to harvest. A theristes is the man who does it, the reaper walking the field with his blade, cutting and gathering. In the parable Jesus says the reapers are the angels, and the harvest is the end of the age.","g":"reaper","h":"The picture: the reaper in the harvest field."},"G2328":{"b":"The root is simply warmth. This is to warm yourself, hands stretched toward a fire. Peter stands at the courtyard fire warming himself while, a few steps away, he denies that he ever knew Jesus. Heat on the skin against the cold.","g":"warm oneself","h":"The picture: hands held out to a fire."},"G2329":{"b":"This comes from a word for the heat of summer. Strong's just says \"warmth.\" It is the felt heat of the flames. Paul feels this warmth from the fire, and a snake feels it too and stirs from the sticks.","g":"heat, warmth","h":"The picture: the heat coming off a fire."},"G233":{"b":"This word comes from the word for salt. It means to salt, to season food with it so it keeps and tastes right. Jesus warns about salt that loses its saltiness. Nothing can salt it again. A thing meant to preserve is worthless once it goes flat.","g":"to salt","h":"The picture: salt rubbed into food."},"G2330":{"b":"The root means to heat. The word is summer, the hot season. Jesus points to the fig tree, when its branch turns soft and puts out leaves, you know summer is near. The tender green shoot is the sign warm days are coming.","g":"summer","h":"The picture: the fig tree in leaf, summer near."},"G2331":{"b":"A person from Thessalonica, a place in Asia Minor. Picture the believers there, whose faith rang out so loudly that Paul said he needed to say nothing about it, First Thessalonians 1. This word names that church.","g":"Thessalonian","h":"The picture: a believer of Thessalonica."},"G2332":{"b":"This city's name holds the word for victory, joined to the name of the Thessalians. It means a Thessalian victory. Paul preached there three sabbaths in the synagogue. The name itself is a shout of triumph.","g":"Thessalonica","h":"The picture: a victory cry in the name."},"G2333":{"b":"This is the name of a man, Theudas, who once led a failed revolt. Gamaliel names him as a warning to the council. Both sources call the name's origin uncertain. So it stays a name with nothing settled behind it.","flat":1,"g":"Theudas","h":"No picture."},"G2334":{"b":"Abbott-Smith traces this word to one meaning a spectator. It is the person who came to look and stands there with eyes fixed.\n\nLater it softened into plain seeing. But the root is someone watching on purpose.","g":"look at, behold","h":"The picture: a spectator watching."},"G2335":{"b":"From a word meaning to be a spectator. A theoria is a viewing, a spectacle, a sight people gather to watch. The crowds who came for the spectacle of the cross went home stricken. They came to watch and left changed.","g":"sight, spectacle","h":"The picture: onlookers pressing in for a show."},"G2336":{"b":"This word comes from the verb to place or put. It is the case a thing is placed in, here the sheath of a sword. Jesus tells Peter to put his sword back into it. The word means the place you set the blade to rest.","g":"sheath","h":"The picture: the sheath you slide a sword into."},"G2337":{"b":"The root is the breast. Thelazo is what a mother and baby do there, to give suck and to suck. Woe to those nursing infants in that day, Jesus says. Blessed the breasts that thelazo you, a woman calls out.","g":"to nurse","h":"The picture: a mother nursing at the breast."},"G2338":{"b":"The root is the word for nursing, giving suck at the breast. Thelys is the female, named for the one who nurses the young. From the beginning God made them male and thelys, Jesus says, quoting the first pages.","g":"female","h":"The picture: the one who nurses the young."},"G2339":{"b":"This is the hunt, the chase after wild game, and by turn the net that takes it. Abbott lands on a net. Paul quotes the Psalm, let their table become a snare and a trap, the good things turning into a net around them.","g":"net, trap","h":"The picture: a hunter's net thrown over the prey."},"G234":{"b":"The word comes from a root meaning to pollute, to soil. James asks the Gentile believers to keep clear of the defilement of idols, meat left dirty by the pagan altars.","g":"pollution","h":"The picture: food smeared with filth."},"G2340":{"b":"This word comes from the word for hunting. Abbott-Smith gives it as to hunt, ensnare, catch. The scribes and Pharisees lay in wait for Jesus like hunters after game, trying to trap him in his own words.","g":"catch","h":"The picture: hunters lying in wait for prey."},"G2341":{"b":"Strong's says this is to be a beast-fighter in the gladiatorial show. Two roots sit under it, a dangerous animal and to war. Paul says he fought beasts at Ephesus. If the dead are not raised, why face that.","g":"fight wild beasts","h":"The picture: a man in the arena facing wild animals."},"G2342":{"b":"Strictly this is the small form of the ordinary word for beast. But Abbott-Smith says it is used of a wild beast, and Strong's calls it a dangerous animal.\n\nIt is also the word Revelation uses of Antichrist.","g":"wild beast","h":"The picture: a little beast."},"G2343":{"b":"Abbott: \"to lay up, store up: of riches.\" It comes from the word for treasure and its storehouse. You heap up wealth and lock it away. Jesus warns against storing treasure only for yourself.","g":"store up","h":"The picture: heaping treasure into a storehouse."},"G2344":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the word first means a place of safe keeping. A casket. A treasury. A storehouse. Only later does it mean the treasure itself. So the picture is the locked room where you store what you value most.","g":"treasure","h":"The picture: the strongroom, not the gold."},"G2345":{"b":"Strong's traces this to an old word meaning to finger. So thingano is to touch, to lay a finger on a thing. It is the word in the rule Paul quotes and rejects, do not touch, do not taste, do not handle.","g":"touch, handle","h":"The picture: a finger laid on it."},"G2346":{"b":"Strong's says it means to crowd. Abbott-Smith says to press, and speaks of a narrow, squeezed road. Trouble is a crowd pressing in on you from all sides, or a path so tight it crushes you.","g":"press, afflict","h":"The picture: being pressed and squeezed."},"G2347":{"b":"The plain first meaning Abbott-Smith gives is pressure, from a verb meaning to press.\n\nThe trouble in this word is not a blow from outside. It is weight bearing down, a squeeze that does not let up.","g":"trouble, affliction","h":"The picture: being squeezed."},"G2348":{"b":"This just means to die, or in one form, to be dead. Strong's calls it a strengthened form of an older root. Nothing lies behind it to picture.","flat":1,"g":"to die","h":"No picture."},"G2349":{"b":"The root is the plain word to die. Thnetos labels a thing death has a claim on, a body that will one day stop. So when Paul says do not let sin reign in your mortal body, he means the body already headed for the grave.","g":"mortal","h":"The picture: a body already headed for the grave."},"G2350":{"b":"The root is a disturbance, a din. To thorybeo is to make that racket. Jesus came to the dead girl's house and found the mourners thorybeo, wailing and carrying on. Why the noise, he said. She only sleeps.","g":"make uproar","h":"The picture: a crowd making a din."},"G2351":{"b":"This is the noise of an excited crowd, a tumult, an uproar. Let us not seize him during the feast, they said, or there will be an uproar among the people. The mourners at the girl's house made this same din. A mob's clamour rising.","g":"uproar, tumult","h":"The picture: the roar of an angry mob."},"G2352":{"b":"This word means to break in pieces, to shatter. Here it is people broken down and crushed by their troubles. Jesus reads that he was sent to set the shattered ones free, to lift those the world had broken.","g":"bruise, crush","h":"The picture: something shattered to pieces."},"G2353":{"b":"From a word meaning to feed and rear. Abbott says a thremma is a nurseling, especially of animals, and so the cattle raised on a farm. Jacob drank from this well, the woman said, and his sons, and his cattle.","g":"cattle","h":"The picture: the fed flocks on the farm."},"G2354":{"b":"The word means to lament, to wail. It comes from a word for a dirge, the song sung over the dead. Jesus says we sang a lament and you did not mourn. Picture the loud crying at a funeral, the wail that rises over a body.","g":"lament, mourn","h":"The picture: wailing a funeral song."},"G2356":{"b":"Abbott says this is religion in its outward form, the ceremony and observance you can watch. James turns it, pure threskeia before God is this, to visit orphans and widows in their trouble, James 1:27. Worship in the hands.","g":"religion, worship","h":"The picture: worship you can see in the hands."},"G2357":{"b":"This word points to the outward side of worship, the person careful about every form and ceremony. James turns it over. Keep a tight rein on your tongue and help the widow, or all your ceremony counts for nothing.","g":"religious","h":"The picture: a man careful with every outward form of worship."},"G2358":{"b":"The word points to the Roman triumph, the victory parade where a conqueror led his captives through the streets. Paul says God leads us in that procession in Christ, spreading the fragrance of him in every place.","g":"triumph","h":"The picture: the Roman victory parade."},"G2359":{"b":"Strong's says it is of uncertain derivation and just means hair. There is nothing behind it to see. Even the hairs of your head, this plain word for hair.","flat":1,"g":"hair","h":"No picture."},"G236":{"b":"The root is the word for other, something else. To change is to make a thing other than it was, or to swap one for another. We shall all be changed, Paul says, in a moment. They exchanged God's glory for images of birds and beasts.","g":"change","h":"The picture: swapping one thing for another."},"G2360":{"b":"The root is a noise, an uproar. The word came to mean shaken by that kind of clamor, alarmed. Jesus says when you hear of wars and rumors of wars, do not be troubled. Do not let the loud news throw you into a panic.","g":"troubled","h":"The picture: a loud alarm that rattles you."},"G2361":{"b":"Abbott traces it to a word meaning to thicken. A thrombos is a lump, a clot of blood, a thick heavy drop. His sweat became like clots of blood falling to the earth. The weight of his dread pressed it out of him.","g":"great drop, clot","h":"The picture: thick clots of blood."},"G2362":{"b":"Long before it meant power, this word meant a place to sit. Abbott-Smith says that in Homer it was a seat, chair. Later it became the chair of state.\n\nGod's throne is where he sits down.","g":"throne","h":"The picture: a chair."},"G2363":{"b":"This is Thyatira, a city in Asia Minor. Strong's says the name is \"of uncertain derivation,\" so even the scholars cannot see behind it. Lydia the seller of purple came from here. A place name with nothing to picture.","flat":1,"g":"Thyatira","h":"No picture."},"G2364":{"b":"Strong's calls this apparently a primary word, which means it is not built from anything else. It is simply the word for daughter, and our English word is its cousin.","flat":1,"g":"daughter","h":"No picture."},"G2365":{"b":"The root is thygater, daughter, and the ending makes it small and tender. It is a word of endearment. Jairus uses it of his dying girl, my little daughter is at the point of death, come and lay your hands on her.","g":"little daughter","h":"The picture: the little girl, a father's own."},"G2366":{"b":"The root means to rush and blow hard. So this is wind gone violent, a hurricane, a whirlwind. Hebrews stands it beside the fire and darkness of Sinai, the storm the people could not touch or bear.","g":"tempest","h":"The picture: a whirlwind."},"G2367":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this wood came from \"an African aromatic tree, with ornamentally veined wood of varying colour.\" Picture a rich panel of scented, streaked timber. So Babylon's traders sold costly thyine wood, and now no one buys it.","g":"citron-wood","h":"The picture: sweet-smelling grained wood."},"G2368":{"b":"This is fragrant powder burned in worship, and the smoke that lifts off it. While it burned, the people prayed outside and Zechariah met the angel. Revelation says the rising smoke is the prayers of God's people. Sweet smoke going up.","g":"incense","h":"The picture: fragrant smoke rising."},"G2369":{"b":"The root means to send up fragrant smoke. This is the altar of incense, or the censer, where sweet smoke rose before God. It stood among the holy furnishings of the tabernacle.","g":"altar of incense","h":"The picture: incense smoke rising off the altar."},"G237":{"b":"This word means from another place. Jesus uses it of the thief who does not enter the sheep pen by the door but climbs in some other way. The honest man walks through the gate. The thief comes from elsewhere.","g":"from elsewhere","h":"The picture: coming in the side way, not the gate."},"G2370":{"b":"The root carries the idea of smoke, of something blown up and burning. To do this is to send up fragrant smoke. That was Zechariah's task, burning incense. The smoke rose while the people prayed outside.","g":"burn incense","h":"The picture: sweet smoke rising from the altar."},"G2371":{"b":"The word joins 'hot passion' with 'to fight.' The root of the first part is passion, as if breathing hard. Herod is in a furious quarrel with the people of Tyre and Sidon.","g":"highly displeased","h":"The picture: breathing hard, spoiling for a fight."},"G2372":{"b":"Strong's explains it as passion, as if breathing hard. Abbott-Smith calls it hot anger, wrath.\n\nHe adds that the plural means impulses or outbursts of anger. This is the kind that flares up.","g":"rage, wrath","h":"The picture: hard breathing."},"G2373":{"b":"The root is passion pictured as hard breathing, the snorting breath of a person in a rage. So this word means to be enraged, chest heaving. Herod, tricked by the wise men, was filled with this fury.","g":"to enrage","h":"The picture: hard, snorting breath of rage."},"G2374":{"b":"Strong's calls this apparently a primary word and notes it looks like our own word door. Nothing stands behind it.\n\nThe famous uses, Christ as the door and an open door for the gospel, are pictures the writers built.","flat":1,"g":"door, gate","h":"No picture."},"G2375":{"b":"The root is the word for a door. A thyreos was a large shield, tall and oblong like a door, that a soldier could hide his whole body behind. Paul calls faith this shield, putting out every flaming dart.","g":"shield","h":"The picture: a shield the size of a door."},"G2376":{"b":"This is an aperture, a window, the small word behind the big word \"door.\" A window is a small opening cut in a wall. A young man named Eutychus sat in one during Paul's long sermon, sank into sleep, and fell out from the third floor.","g":"window","h":"The picture: a small opening cut in a wall."},"G2377":{"b":"The word joins \"door\" to \"guardian.\" A thyroros is the doorkeeper, the porter set to watch the entrance and let the right ones in. The master leaves and tells this one to stay awake. A servant girl keeps the door when Peter is let in.","g":"doorkeeper","h":"The picture: the servant posted at the door."},"G2378":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the word points to what is offered, not just the act of offering. Something real changes hands.\n\nPaul asks for living bodies with this word. The offering gets up and walks.","g":"sacrifice","h":"The picture: the thing handed over."},"G2379":{"b":"Abbott-Smith builds this word on the verb meaning to sacrifice. It is the sacrifice place.\n\nHe adds that the word first appears in the Greek Old Testament. It looks like a word made for the job.","g":"altar","h":"The picture: the place where the killing happens."},"G238":{"b":"The roots are other and to speak in public. Abbott-Smith says to speak allegorically. Paul takes Hagar and Sarah and reads a second, hidden meaning out of the old story.","g":"allegorize","h":"The picture: speaking one thing in the town square while meaning another."},"G2380":{"b":"Strong's says the word first meant to rush, to breathe hard, to blow, to smoke. From there it came to mean sacrifice by fire, the smoke going up. Abbott gives no origin. It also plainly means to kill.","g":"sacrifice, kill","h":"The picture: smoke rising from the fire."},"G2381":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this name comes from a Hebrew word meaning \"a twin.\" So Thomas is the Twin. It is his actual name, not a comment on his doubting.","g":"Thomas","h":"The picture: the twin."},"G2382":{"b":"The word first means the chest, then the corslet worn over it. A breastplate is the metal that guards the heart and lungs in battle. Paul says put on the breastplate of righteousness, real armor over the vital parts.","g":"breastplate","h":"The picture: armor strapped over the chest."},"G2383":{"b":"The name means enlightener, one who gives light. Jairus was the synagogue ruler whose little daughter Jesus took by the hand and raised from the dead.","g":"Jairus","h":"The picture: enlightener."},"G2384":{"b":"The name means heel-catcher, a supplanter. It comes from a word meaning to seize by the heel. Jacob was born gripping the heel of his twin brother Esau.","g":"Jacob","h":"The picture: heel-catcher."},"G2385":{"b":"James is really Jacob, the patriarch's name put into Greek. Abbott counts three men who carry it, among them the son of Zebedee mending nets by the sea. So every James in the Gospels wears the name of Israel's father, handed down the generations.","g":"James","h":"The picture: the old name Jacob, in Greek dress."},"G2386":{"b":"The root iaomai means to cure. Abbott's first sense is a means of healing, a remedy. Iama is the cure itself, the healing that happens. Paul lists gifts of healings among the things the Spirit hands out to the church.","g":"healing","h":"The picture: a remedy that heals."},"G2387":{"b":"Jambres is the other magician who opposed Moses, named beside Jannes. Strong's says the name is of Egyptian origin. There is no meaning behind it to picture. It is just his name.","flat":1,"g":"Jambres","h":"No picture."},"G2388":{"b":"This is only a name. Strong's traces it to Hebrew and here it marks one man in the family line Luke follows from Jesus back toward Adam. A name stands for a person, not a picture. There is nothing to see.","flat":1,"g":"Janna","h":"No picture."},"G2389":{"b":"Jannes is a name, one of the magicians who withstood Moses. Strong's says it is of Egyptian origin. There is nothing behind the name for us to see. It is simply who the man was.","flat":1,"g":"Jannes","h":"No picture."},"G2390":{"b":"Strong's calls this apparently a primary verb, which means it is not made from other words. Abbott-Smith adds no origin. It means to heal, and there is nothing older to see.","flat":1,"g":"heal","h":"No picture."},"G2391":{"b":"The name means a descent. It comes from a word meaning to descend or come down. Jared was a patriarch before the flood, the father of Enoch.","g":"Jared","h":"The picture: a descent."},"G2392":{"b":"The word means a healing, a cure, the act itself. Jesus says tell that fox I cast out demons and perform cures today and tomorrow. It is the moment sickness lifts and the body works right again. Health handed back.","g":"cure, healing","h":"The picture: a sick body made well again."},"G2393":{"b":"This is jasper, a precious stone. Abbott says it was not the stone we now call jasper but a translucent one, with light passing through it. John sees God's glory shining like this clear gem, and the city's wall built of it.","g":"jasper","h":"The picture: a clear, glowing gem."},"G2394":{"b":"This name comes from a word meaning to cure or heal, and reads about to heal. Jason took Paul and Silas into his house, and a mob dragged him before the rulers for it. His name means healer.","g":"Jason","h":"The picture: a healer."},"G2395":{"b":"The root means to cure, to heal. A physician is the one who does it. Those who are well need no physician, Jesus says, but the sick. Luke, who wrote his Gospel, was one himself, the beloved physician.","g":"physician","h":"The picture: the healer at the sickbed."},"G2397":{"b":"The root is the word for seeing. This word is what is seen, the look or appearance of a thing, its aspect. In Matthew 28:3 the angel's appearance is like lightning and his clothing white as snow.","g":"appearance","h":"The picture: the look the eye catches."},"G2398":{"b":"Strong's says the origin is uncertain. Abbott-Smith gives no history either, only the senses: one's own, and then peculiar, distinct, appropriate. Nothing older lies behind it.","flat":1,"g":"one's own","h":"No picture."},"G2399":{"b":"The root means one's own, private, separate. An idiotes is a private person, not an official, not trained in a craft. The council saw Peter and John as unlearned, ordinary men. Our word idiot grew from it.","g":"unlearned","h":"The picture: a plain private man off the street."},"G24":{"b":"The root aganakteo is the boil of a heart stirred to anger, the word for disciples grown indignant. Paul praises the Corinthians for the aganaktesis their repentance produced. A clean burning against sin, not a shrug.","g":"indignation","h":"The picture: heat rising at a wrong."},"G2401":{"b":"The name means red. Idumaea is Edom, the land of Esau, who was born red and later sold his birthright for a bowl of red stew.","g":"Idumaea","h":"The picture: red."},"G2402":{"b":"This word means sweat, perspiration. Picture beads standing out on the skin under strain. In the garden Jesus was in agony, and his sweat became like great drops of blood falling to the ground.","g":"sweat","h":"The picture: beads of sweat on the skin."},"G2403":{"b":"The roots behind this name are uncertain, joining a word for not with the name Zebul. Jezebel was the Tyrian queen whose name became a byword for wickedness and false teaching.","flat":1,"g":"Jezebel","h":"No picture."},"G2404":{"b":"The name is two words, hieros, sacred, and polis, a town with walls. So it means Holy City. Paul notes the hard work of Epaphras for the believers there, a real city in the Lycus valley.","g":"Hierapolis","h":"The picture: a walled town called holy."},"G2405":{"b":"The root means to serve as a priest, to do a priest's tasks. This word is that office, the job itself. In Luke it falls to Zechariah by lot to go in and burn incense, the daily work of the priesthood.","g":"priesthood","h":"The picture: the priest's work at the altar."},"G2406":{"b":"The root means to serve as a priest. This word gathers them into one, a whole body of priests. Peter calls all believers this. Not one holy man at the altar, but every one of them serving.","g":"priesthood","h":"The picture: a whole body of priests."},"G2407":{"b":"This word is built from the word for a priest. It means to do a priest's work, serving at the altar. Zechariah was doing this, burning incense in the temple, when the angel appeared and told him of his son John.","g":"serve as priest","h":"The picture: a priest at his work in the temple."},"G2408":{"b":"The name means Jah will rise, the Lord lifts up. It joins a word meaning to be high with Jah, the Lord's name. Jeremiah was the weeping prophet of Judah.","g":"Jeremiah","h":"The picture: the Lord will rise."},"G2409":{"b":"This comes from hieros, sacred. A hiereus is the priest, the one set apart to handle holy things and stand at the altar between God and people. So Christ our great priest is the man who walks straight into the holy place carrying his own blood.","g":"priest","h":"The picture: the man at the altar."},"G241":{"b":"Built from a word for other and a word for kin, one's family and race. So a person of another stock, an outsider. Ten lepers were healed. Only one came back to give thanks, and he was of another race, a Samaritan.","g":"foreigner, stranger","h":"The picture: someone of another stock."},"G2410":{"b":"The name means fragrant. Jericho was a city in Palestine, the first that fell to Israel when its walls came tumbling down at the sound of the trumpets.","g":"Jericho","h":"The picture: fragrant."},"G2411":{"b":"Strong's makes a careful distinction. This word is the entire precincts. A different word means the inner sanctuary itself.\n\nSo when Jesus teaches daily in the temple, he is out in the courts, not inside the holy place.","g":"temple","h":"The picture: the whole temple grounds."},"G2412":{"b":"This joins the word for sacred to a word meaning to be suitable, fitting. It describes conduct that fits a holy setting, like garments proper for the temple. Paul says aged women should carry themselves in a way that suits sacred things.","g":"reverent","h":"The picture: dressed to fit a holy place."},"G2413":{"b":"The word means sacred, set apart for God. As a noun it names the temple itself, the whole sacred precinct. Paul uses it of those who serve at the temple and live from what is offered there.","g":"sacred","h":"The picture: the temple precincts."},"G2414":{"b":"The name means founded peaceful. Behind it lies a sense of being safe and at peace. Jerusalem was the capital of Israel, the city of the great King.","g":"Jerusalem","h":"The picture: founded peaceful."},"G2415":{"b":"The word means an inhabitant of Jerusalem. Mark uses it for the crowds that streamed out of the city to John at the Jordan. It puts faces on the capital, real residents leaving their streets to be baptized in the river.","g":"Jerusalemite","h":"The picture: the people of Jerusalem."},"G2416":{"b":"The root is a temple-robber. So this word is to plunder a temple, to carry off what is holy. Abbott says to rob a temple. Paul asks the man who hates idols whether he robs their shrines himself.","g":"commit sacrilege","h":"The picture: stealing from inside a temple."},"G2417":{"b":"Two words, temple and to despoil. Robbers who strip a shrine of its treasures. The clerk said Paul's companions had not robbed the temple nor blasphemed the goddess, so there was no case.","g":"temple-robber","h":"The picture: looting a temple."},"G2418":{"b":"This word puts two words together, the temple and work. It means the work a priest does at the altar, handling the sacrifices. Paul uses it for preaching the gospel. He treats his own preaching as priestly work.","g":"minister as priest","h":"The picture: a priest at work in the temple."},"G2419":{"b":"The name means founded peaceful, a foundation of peace. This is the Hebrew form of Jerusalem, the holy city set on the hills of Judah.","g":"Jerusalem","h":"The picture: founded peaceful."},"G242":{"b":"The word means to jump, and of water, to gush and spring up. The healed lame man leaps to his feet and jumps for joy. Jesus says the water he gives becomes a spring inside you, leaping up to eternal life. Life bursting upward.","g":"leap, spring up","h":"The picture: water leaping up like a spring."},"G2420":{"b":"This word means the priesthood, the office of the priest. The root behind it means sacred, set apart for God. The priest is the man who stands between the people and God. Hebrews says that office has changed hands. The old priests died. This one holds it forever.","g":"priesthood","h":"The picture: the man who stands between."},"G2421":{"b":"The name means extant, one who is present and stands. Jesse was the father of David, the shepherd king, and so an ancestor of Christ himself.","g":"Jesse","h":"The picture: existing."},"G2422":{"b":"The name means he will open. It comes from a word meaning to open wide. Jephthah was a judge of Israel who led its armies against the Ammonites.","g":"Jephthah","h":"The picture: he will open."},"G2423":{"b":"The name means Jah will establish. Jah is a short form of the Lord's name. Jeconiah was a king of Judah carried away in the exile to Babylon.","g":"Jeconiah","h":"The picture: the Lord will establish."},"G2424":{"b":"The name means Jehovah saved. It joins the Lord's name with the idea of salvation. He was named Jesus because he would save his people from their sins.","g":"Jesus","h":"The picture: the Lord saves."},"G2425":{"b":"Abbott traces this to a verb meaning to reach, attain. Something that stretches far enough.\n\nSo the word means enough, competent, fit. Not a measure of how big a thing is, but of whether it gets there.","g":"enough, sufficient","h":"The picture: it reaches."},"G2426":{"b":"The root hikanos means fit and ample, enough to meet the need. Paul says our hikanotes is not from ourselves but from God. The word is the sense of being equal to the load, and it credits that entirely to him.","g":"ability","h":"The picture: having just enough for the task."},"G2427":{"b":"The root means enough, ample, fit for the task. To hikanoo is to make a person sufficient, to bring them up to the measure. Paul says God made us able ministers of a new covenant, our sufficiency coming from him.","g":"make able","h":"The picture: brought up to the measure."},"G2428":{"b":"This was the olive branch a suppliant carried when begging for mercy. Later it meant the plea itself. In his suffering Christ offered up prayers with strong crying and tears, holding out his need to God.","g":"supplication","h":"The picture: the olive branch a beggar holds out."},"G2429":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives one word: moisture. It is the damp in the soil that roots drink from. The seed on rock withered because it had no moisture. Nothing under it held the water the young plant needed to live.","g":"moisture","h":"The picture: damp in the ground that keeps a plant alive."},"G243":{"b":"Strong's calls it a primary word. Abbott-Smith gives no origin, only a note that it is like the English word else. It marks one thing off from another and carries no image.","flat":1,"g":"other, another","h":"No picture."},"G2430":{"b":"Strong's ties this town's name to the word for an image, a likeness or statue. Iconium sits on Paul's road through Asia Minor. Its very name echoes the word for a carved likeness.","g":"Iconium","h":"The picture: the city named like an image."},"G2431":{"b":"This is the word behind hilarious. Abbott-Smith gives cheerful, joyous. Paul says God loves a cheerful giver, one who hands it over grinning, glad to give, not the man who pays up wincing.","g":"cheerful","h":"The picture: a bright, laughing face."},"G2432":{"b":"The root means merry, cheerful, the word behind our hilarious. So this is cheerfulness, gladness of heart. Abbott says cheerfulness. Paul says the one who shows mercy should do it with this, cheerfully, not grudgingly.","g":"cheerfulness","h":"The picture: a bright, glad face in the giving."},"G2433":{"b":"The root means gracious, favorable. Abbott says \"to be propitious, merciful.\" It asks that a face set against you turn kind instead. The tax collector beats his chest and asks God for exactly this, mercy toward a sinner.","g":"be merciful, atone","h":"The picture: asking an angry face to turn kind."},"G2434":{"b":"This word means an appeasing, the turning away of anger. Its root means to appease, to be gracious. That is an act between persons, not a thing to see. John says Jesus himself is this for our sins.","flat":1,"g":"propitiation","h":"No picture."},"G2435":{"b":"Strong's points to a concrete thing: the lid of the Ark in the Temple, the mercy seat. Once a year blood was sprinkled there to cover sin. Paul says God set forth Christ as this, the place where wrath is met and sin is covered.","g":"mercy seat","h":"The picture: the blood-sprinkled lid of the Ark."},"G2436":{"b":"Strong's says it first means cheerful and attractive, then favorable and merciful. It is the word for someone looking on you with favor rather than anger. Peter blurts it over Jesus, God be gracious to you, this must never happen.","g":"merciful, gracious","h":"The picture: a face looking on you with favor."},"G2437":{"b":"This is a place, a region on the coast of the Adriatic Sea. Strong's calls it the Illyrican shore. Paul names it to mark how far he had carried the gospel, all the way to that distant coastline.","g":"Illyricum","h":"The picture: the far shore of the Adriatic."},"G2438":{"b":"This is a leather thong, a strap. It ties a sandal to the foot, or it is the lash of a whip. John the Baptist says he is not worthy to stoop and loosen the strap of Jesus' sandal, the lowest slave's job.","g":"strap, thong","h":"The picture: the leather strap of a sandal."},"G2439":{"b":"The root is himation, a garment. Himatizo is to put clothes on someone. The people come and find the man who had the demons sitting there, dressed and in his right mind, and they are afraid.","g":"clothe","h":"The picture: dressed in proper clothes again."},"G244":{"b":"This joins \"another's, not your own\" to \"overseer.\" So it is a person who supervises what does not belong to them. Peter lists it beside murder and theft, telling Christians not to suffer as this kind of meddler.","g":"busybody","h":"The picture: the self-appointed overseer of other people's business."},"G2440":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this word is almost always an outer garment, a mantle, cloak, thrown over the tunic underneath.\n\nIt is the layer everyone sees, and the one you wrap up in when it is cold.","g":"cloak, garment","h":"The picture: the coat, not the shirt."},"G2441":{"b":"The root means to dress, to put clothing on. This is the clothing itself, usually fine and costly robes. The soldiers divided his garments among them and cast lots for his robe. What a person wears.","g":"clothing","h":"The picture: fine robes worn on the body."},"G2442":{"b":"This means to long for someone with deep affection. Strong's says its origin is uncertain, so there is no root to trace and nothing concrete to picture. It is the longing itself. Paul says he yearned for them like this.","flat":1,"g":"long for","h":"No picture."},"G2444":{"b":"Two words fused, a word for purpose and the word what, making why, for what reason. It is the cry Jesus takes up from the cross, my God, my God, to what end have you left me. A question aimed straight at the reason.","g":"why","h":"The picture: the cry, to what end."},"G2445":{"b":"The name means beautiful. Joppa was a port city in Palestine, where Peter saw the vision of the sheet and raised Tabitha back to life.","g":"Joppa","h":"The picture: beautiful."},"G2446":{"b":"The name means a descender, the one going down. The Jordan is the river that flows down through Palestine, where Jesus was baptized by John.","g":"Jordan","h":"The picture: a descender."},"G2447":{"b":"Strong's gives two concrete pictures for one word, rust as if given off by metal and venom as if given off by a snake. The same word covers both, the stuff that eats and kills. James says the tongue is full of it, deadly poison.","g":"poison, rust","h":"The picture: venom from a snake."},"G2448":{"b":"The name means celebrated, one who is praised. Judah was both a son of Jacob and the region his tribe settled in the south of Palestine.","g":"Judah","h":"The picture: celebrated."},"G2449":{"b":"The name means the Judaean land, the region belonging to Judah, with the word for land understood. So Judea is dirt and hills you can walk, the home ground of the tribe of Judah, where much of the Gospel story unfolds.","g":"Judea","h":"The picture: the land of Judah."},"G245":{"b":"The root is other. Allotrios means belonging to another, not one's own, someone else's property. Paul refuses to build on another man's foundation. Jesus' sheep run from a stranger's voice, the allotrios they do not know and will not follow.","g":"another's","h":"The picture: someone else's property."},"G2450":{"b":"The root is Ioudaios, a Jew. Abbott gives to conform to Jewish practice. Paul confronts Peter for pressing Gentiles to ioudaizo, to keep the law and eat as Jews do. The word is living by another people's rulebook.","g":"to Judaize","h":"The picture: a Gentile taking up Jewish customs."},"G2451":{"b":"The root is Ioudaios, a Jew. Abbott gives simply Jewish. Paul warns Titus against Ioudaikos myths, Jewish fables that pull people from the truth. The word tags a thing by the people and traditions it came from.","g":"Jewish","h":"The picture: marked as belonging to the Jews."},"G2452":{"b":"The adverb from the last word. Abbott gives in Jewish fashion. Paul asks Peter why, being a Jew, he compels Gentiles to live ioudaikos. It describes not a belief but a daily manner, keeping the customs day by day.","g":"in Jewish fashion","h":"The picture: living the way the Jews live."},"G2453":{"b":"Strong's says the word means belonging to Jehudah, that is, Judah. Abbott-Smith builds it from the name Judas, or Judah.\n\nSo the word starts as a place and a family, then becomes the name for a whole people.","g":"Jewish, a Jew","h":"The picture: a person from Judah."},"G2454":{"b":"The root means to Judaize, to live as a Jew. The word gathers up the whole practice, the observance of Jewish rites. Paul uses it of his old life, when he advanced in Judaism beyond his peers and hunted the church.","g":"Judaism","h":"The picture: living out the Jewish way."},"G2455":{"b":"The name means celebrated, praised. It is the Greek form of Judah. Many Israelites bore it, and it belonged also to the tribe and its region.","g":"Judas","h":"The picture: celebrated."},"G2456":{"b":"Julia is a common Roman family name, the feminine of Julius. Paul greets her among the believers in Rome. The name carries no image of its own, only a plain Roman household label worn by one of the saints.","flat":1,"g":"Julia","h":"No picture."},"G2457":{"b":"This is the name of Julius, the centurion who guarded Paul on the voyage and treated him kindly. Strong's says it is simply Latin. A name has nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"Julius","h":"No picture."},"G2458":{"b":"This is just a name, of Latin origin, with no meaning attached to it. Junias, or Junia, is greeted by Paul in the same breath as Andronicus. There is nothing behind the name to see.","flat":1,"g":"Junias","h":"No picture."},"G2459":{"b":"This is a man's name, Justus, worn by three different Christians in the New Testament. It comes from the Latin for \"just.\" A name carries no picture of its own, only the people who bore it.","flat":1,"g":"Justus","h":"No picture."},"G246":{"b":"The word joins 'other, different' with 'race or clan.' It means someone of another people, a Gentile. Peter says a Jew was forbidden to visit such a man, then walks in and does it.","g":"of another nation","h":"The picture: a man from another tribe."},"G2460":{"b":"This comes from the word for a horse. A hippeus is a man on horseback, a rider. Seventy of them were sent through the night to carry Paul away safely. The picture is simply the horse and the man on its back.","g":"horseman","h":"The picture: a rider on a horse."},"G2461":{"b":"The word comes from the word for horse. Abbott-Smith gives \"cavalry,\" the mounted soldiers. Picture rank on rank of riders on horseback. So John hears the count of the mounted army, two hundred million strong.","g":"cavalry","h":"The picture: a troop of horsemen."},"G2462":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means a horse. Strong's calls its origin uncertain. It is just the animal, the horse of the rider and the war chariot. Nothing is hidden behind the word. It names the beast and stops there.","flat":1,"g":"horse","h":"No picture."},"G2463":{"b":"This is the rainbow. The old Greeks also made Iris the messenger of the gods, the bow that bridges sky and earth. John sees a rainbow around the throne. Picture the arc of colored light after rain.","g":"rainbow","h":"The picture: the rainbow after rain."},"G2464":{"b":"The name means laughter. It comes from a word meaning to laugh outright, in joy or in scorn. Sarah laughed when God promised her a son in her old age.","g":"Isaac","h":"The picture: laughter."},"G2465":{"b":"Built from a word for equal and a word for a messenger, an angel. In the resurrection they neither marry nor die, Jesus said, but stand equal to the angels. Picture the deathless messengers of God, and the risen among them.","g":"equal to angels","h":"The picture: standing equal to the angels."},"G2466":{"b":"The name means he will bring a reward. Behind it lie words for lifting and for the payment of a contract. Issachar was a son of Jacob and a tribe of Israel.","g":"Issachar","h":"The picture: he will bring a reward."},"G2469":{"b":"Strong's says this means an inhabitant of Kerioth. It marks which Judas this was, the man from that town. The town's own meaning is not given, so there is nothing more to picture.","flat":1,"g":"Iscariot","h":"No picture."},"G247":{"b":"The root allos means another of the same kind. Paul says some good works are plain to see, and those that are allos, otherwise, cannot stay hidden either. The word points to the other side of a thing already named.","g":"otherwise","h":"The picture: the other case, on the flip side."},"G2470":{"b":"Equal, the same in size, number, or worth. Abbott lists the matching witnesses at Jesus' trial and the pay equal for all in the vineyard. Most of all, Christ counted equality with God. Level, matched, the same.","g":"equal","h":"The picture: two things the same size."},"G2471":{"b":"This word means likeness in condition or proportion, equality. Picture two sides of a balance resting level. Paul asks the ones with plenty to supply the ones with need, so that there may be evenness, a scale brought level.","g":"equality","h":"The picture: a balance resting level."},"G2472":{"b":"This joins \"equal\" to a word meaning value, the money paid for a thing. So the faith is of equal worth. Peter opens by saying his readers received a faith as precious as the apostles' own.","g":"like precious","h":"The picture: the same price tag on two things."},"G2473":{"b":"Built from equal and the word for soul, which underneath means breath. Isopsychos is a soul of equal measure. Paul says he has no one else like Timothy, no one so truly of one mind, who cares for them.","g":"like-minded","h":"The picture: sharing one breath."},"G2474":{"b":"The name means he will rule as God, or he strives with God. God gave it to Jacob after he wrestled through the night and prevailed.","g":"Israel","h":"The picture: he will rule as God."},"G2475":{"b":"The word marks a descendant of Israel, the name given to Jacob. Abbott says it carries theocratic privilege, insider standing with God. Jesus greets Nathanael as a true one with no guile. To be an Israelite is to belong.","g":"Israelite","h":"The picture: a child of Jacob."},"G2476":{"b":"Strong's says the word works both ways: to stand, and to make something stand.\n\nAbbott-Smith adds a use worth knowing. It also means to set in a balance, to weigh. That is the word used when Judas is paid.","g":"stand, set up","h":"The picture: setting something on its feet."},"G2477":{"b":"This is the root behind history, one who knows by inquiry. Strong's says to visit for information. Paul went up to Jerusalem to get to know Peter, fifteen days spent hearing him firsthand.","g":"visit, get to know","h":"The picture: calling on someone in person to learn from them."},"G2478":{"b":"From ischys, force, strength. Ischyros is strong, mighty, the man with power in his body you cannot move. So no one plunders the strong man's house, the ischyros, until someone stronger ties him up first. It is raw strength the word points to.","g":"strong, mighty","h":"The picture: the strong man you cannot budge."},"G2479":{"b":"This word means strength, might, power, force, ability. The sources give no origin story for it. There is nothing hidden behind the word, just raw strength itself.","flat":1,"g":"strength, might","h":"No picture."},"G248":{"b":"The root halon is a threshing-floor. To aloao is to thresh, to tread the grain out, the work an ox did walking round on the floor. Paul quotes the law, do not muzzle the ox that treads out the grain.","g":"thresh","h":"The picture: an ox treading grain."},"G2480":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is to be strong in body. Muscle, not willpower.\n\nFrom there it stretches to being able to do a thing at all. When Paul says he can do all things, this is the word.","g":"be able, be strong","h":"The picture: a strong body."},"G2481":{"b":"The root isos means equal, evenly balanced. Abbott's first sense is equally. The vineyard owner says isos they will respect my son when I send him. Even odds, a hope weighed out with no certainty which way it falls.","g":"perhaps","h":"The picture: the scales resting even."},"G2482":{"b":"This is Italy, \"a region of Europe.\" Strong's says the name is \"probably of foreign origin,\" borrowed from outside Greek. Paul sailed toward it as a prisoner bound for Rome. A land's name holds no picture of its own.","flat":1,"g":"Italy","h":"No picture."},"G2483":{"b":"The root is Italia, the land. Luke names Cornelius a centurion of the Italikos cohort. The Italian band was stationed at Caesarea. The word ties a company of soldiers to the home country their ranks were drawn from.","g":"Italian","h":"The picture: the regiment raised in Italy."},"G2484":{"b":"The name means encircled, closed in on every side. It comes from a word for a row or wall. Ituraea was a region of Palestine, taking its name from Jetur, a son of Ishmael.","g":"Ituraea","h":"The picture: encircled."},"G2485":{"b":"The root is ichthys, fish, and the ending makes it small. It is what the disciples have beside the loaves, a few little fish, when Jesus feeds the four thousand from almost nothing at all.","g":"little fish","h":"The picture: a few small fish."},"G2486":{"b":"Strong's says the word is of uncertain affinity, which means nobody knows where it came from. It means a fish. There is nothing behind it to look at.","flat":1,"g":"fish","h":"No picture."},"G2487":{"b":"Abbott's plain sense is a track, footstep, the print a foot leaves in the ground. The New Testament uses it for following, walking in someone's footprints. Peter says Christ left us his tracks so we would step where he stepped.","g":"footstep","h":"The picture: a footprint in the ground."},"G2488":{"b":"The name means Jehovah is perfect. It joins the Lord's name with a word meaning complete or whole. Jotham was a king of Judah in the line of David.","g":"Jotham","h":"The picture: the Lord is perfect."},"G2489":{"b":"Joanna is the feminine form of John. Luke names her twice, the wife of Herod's steward who bankrolled Jesus from her own means, and one of the women who found the tomb empty. A name tied to a purse opened and a stone rolled away.","g":"Joanna","h":"The picture: the woman at the tomb."},"G249":{"b":"This word is built from a word for not and logos, word or reason. Alogos is without reason, the dumb brute that neither speaks nor thinks. Peter says false teachers are like these animals, driven by instinct, born to be caught.","g":"irrational","h":"The picture: a dumb beast with no reason."},"G2490":{"b":"Joannas is another form of the name John, listed in Luke's record of Jesus' ancestors. The sources give it no meaning, only its place in the family line. A name in a genealogy with no image of its own.","flat":1,"g":"Joannas","h":"No picture."},"G2491":{"b":"The worksheet points this name to a fuller form and gives no plain meaning here. John was a common Israelite name, borne by the Baptist and by the beloved apostle.","flat":1,"g":"John","h":"No picture."},"G2492":{"b":"The name means hated, and so persecuted. It comes from a word meaning to hate, as toward an enemy. Job was the patriarch who lost everything yet held to God.","g":"Job","h":"The picture: hated."},"G2493":{"b":"The name means Jehovah is his God. It joins the Lord's name with a word for God. Joel was a prophet of Israel whose words Peter quoted at Pentecost.","g":"Joel","h":"The picture: the Lord is his God."},"G2494":{"b":"Jonan is a name in Luke's genealogy of Jesus, linked by Strong's to John or Jonah. The worksheet gives no settled meaning, so there is no image to draw. It stands as one more link in the ancestral chain.","flat":1,"g":"Jonan","h":"No picture."},"G2495":{"b":"The name comes from a word for a dove. Jonah was the prophet who fled from God, was swallowed by a great fish, and later preached to Nineveh.","g":"Jonah","h":"The picture: a dove."},"G2496":{"b":"The worksheet points this name to a fuller form, Jehoram, and gives no plain meaning here. Joram was a king in the royal line of Judah.","flat":1,"g":"Joram","h":"No picture."},"G2497":{"b":"Jorim is a name in Luke's genealogy, perhaps a form of Joram. The sources supply no meaning and no image. It is a bare name in the long line running from Adam down to Jesus, remembered only by its place.","flat":1,"g":"Jorim","h":"No picture."},"G2498":{"b":"The name means Jehovah judged. It joins the Lord's name with a word meaning to judge. Jehoshaphat was a king of Judah who trusted God against great armies.","g":"Jehoshaphat","h":"The picture: the Lord has judged."},"G2499":{"b":"Jose is a shortened form of Joses, a name in Luke's genealogy of Jesus. The worksheet gives no meaning behind it. With no image to hold, it stands simply as one ancestor named in the record.","flat":1,"g":"Jose","h":"No picture."},"G25":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means to feel and show esteem and goodwill toward a person.\n\nHis note calls it love that follows the will, and so love that can be commanded as a duty. He also warns the distinction may not always hold.","g":"love","h":"The picture: love you decide on."},"G250":{"b":"This word names aloes, the powder ground from a sweet-smelling wood. It was mixed with myrrh to prepare a body for burial. Nicodemus carried it to the tomb of Jesus. A fragrance laid against death.","g":"aloes","h":"The picture: the sweet-smelling powder of a fragrant wood."},"G2500":{"b":"A form of the name Joseph. Abbott lists him among the brothers of our Lord, named by the villagers of Nazareth, is this not the carpenter, the brother of James and Joses, Mark 6:3. A family name from the house Jesus grew up in.","g":"Joses","h":"The picture: a brother in the carpenter's house."},"G2501":{"b":"The name means let him add, or simply adding. It comes from a word meaning to add or increase. Joseph is the name of several Israelites, including Jacob's son sold into Egypt.","g":"Joseph","h":"The picture: let him add."},"G2502":{"b":"The name means founded of Jah, established by the Lord. It joins a word for foundation with Jah, the Lord's name. Josiah was the boy king who renewed Judah's worship.","g":"Josiah","h":"The picture: founded of the Lord."},"G2503":{"b":"This is the name of the smallest letter, iota, a single tiny stroke of the pen. Jesus says not one iota will pass from the law. Picture the least mark on the page, smaller than all the rest.","g":"jot, iota","h":"The picture: the smallest letter."},"G2506":{"b":"The root kathaireo means to demolish, to pull down with force. Kathairesis is that tearing down, a wall brought to the ground. Paul says his weapons are mighty for the pulling down of strongholds, breaking fortresses of thought.","g":"pulling down","h":"The picture: a wall pulled down."},"G2507":{"b":"Built from down and take. Abbott-Smith notes it was the technical term for removal after crucifixion. Joseph took Jesus down from the cross. It also means to pull down or demolish a building.","g":"take down, demolish","h":"The picture: taking a body down from the cross."},"G2508":{"b":"This word means to make clean, and here it means to prune. Jesus says the Father prunes every branch that bears fruit so it bears more. The knife is not punishment. It is the gardener cutting back a healthy branch to make it fuller.","g":"to prune, cleanse","h":"The picture: pruning the vine."},"G2510":{"b":"The root means to attach oneself, to touch and take hold. Add the word for down onto it. Abbott says to fasten on. In Acts a snake fastens onto Paul's hand and hangs there, and the people wait for him to die.","g":"fasten on","h":"The picture: latching on and not letting go."},"G2511":{"b":"Abbott sorts the uses three ways. Physical dirt, disease healed, and the heart cleaned.\n\nIt is one verb doing all three. Washing a cup and cleansing a conscience use the same word.","g":"cleanse","h":"The picture: scrubbing something clean."},"G2512":{"b":"This is a washing off, the rinse that leaves a thing clean. The stone water jars at Cana stood ready for the Jews' washing. He made purification for sins, Hebrews says of Christ. Water carrying the dirt away.","g":"cleansing","h":"The picture: water rinsing a thing clean."},"G2513":{"b":"Abbott-Smith points at John 15:3 and explains it as a vine cleansed by pruning. Clean here is not scrubbed. It is cut back.\n\nThe dead wood comes off and the plant is clean.","g":"clean, pure","h":"The picture: a vine after pruning."},"G2514":{"b":"This comes from the word for clean. It means cleanness. The blood of goats and bulls could reach only the surface, cleaning the outside flesh. It could not scrub the conscience clean within.","g":"cleanness","h":"The picture: scrubbed clean."},"G2515":{"b":"This is a seat, a chair, built from \"down\" and the word for a sitting place. Jesus overturned the seats of the dove-sellers. And he says the scribes sit in Moses' seat, the chair of the teacher.","g":"seat","h":"The picture: a chair to sit down on."},"G2516":{"b":"This word is built from down and a word for being seated and settled. It means to sit down and stay. Mary sat at Jesus' feet. The boy Jesus sat among the teachers in the temple. The angels sat where the body had lain. Settled in place.","g":"sit down","h":"The picture: settling down into a seat."},"G2517":{"b":"Built from a word meaning successive, one thing following another. Abbott gives in order. Luke says he set his gospel down kathexes, event following event in a row, so that Theophilus could trust the sequence of what happened.","g":"in order","h":"The picture: one thing after another, in a row."},"G2518":{"b":"Strong's gives the bodily action first. To lie down to rest, and then to fall asleep.\n\nAbbott-Smith notes two further uses. The word stands for death, and for people who are morally and spiritually numb.","g":"sleep","h":"The picture: lying down to rest."},"G2519":{"b":"The root means to go before and lead. A kathegetes is a guide, the one who walks ahead so others follow, and so a master or teacher. Jesus says do not be called this, for you have one leader, the Christ.","g":"master, guide","h":"The picture: the one who walks ahead to lead the way."},"G252":{"b":"This word means salty, briny, the taste of sea water. A salt spring cannot give sweet water, James says, and by the same rule a cursing mouth cannot pour out blessing. The source shows in the taste.","g":"salt","h":"The picture: the taste of salt water."},"G2520":{"b":"The plain sense is to reach down to something, built from a word for down and a word for arriving. What is fitting is what reaches its proper place. It arrives where it belongs, like a thing set exactly where it should sit.","g":"fit, proper","h":"The picture: reaching down to its place."},"G2521":{"b":"Abbott gives the plain sense, to sit, be seated. Then he notes it is used of where someone lives.\n\nSitting slides into staying. To be seated somewhere is to be settled there.","g":"sit","h":"The picture: sitting down and staying."},"G2522":{"b":"This word comes from the word for a day. It means daily, happening every day. Luke uses it of the daily handout of food to the widows in the early church. Not now and then. Each day, without a break, the same duty came round.","g":"daily","h":"The picture: day after day after day."},"G2523":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is causal: to make to sit down, set, appoint.\n\nSeating a person was appointing them. The same word is used for settling down in a place and simply staying there.","g":"sit down, seat","h":"The picture: putting someone in a chair."},"G2524":{"b":"The word means to let down, to lower a thing on ropes. The friends kathiemi the paralyzed man down through the roof tiles to reach Jesus. Later Peter sees a great sheet let down from heaven by its four corners, sinking toward him.","g":"let down","h":"The picture: a man lowered down through the roof."},"G2525":{"b":"Strong's says to place down, and adds permanently.\n\nAbbott-Smith's first sense is simply to set down, or to bring down to a place. From that comes the official use. To appoint is to put someone somewhere and leave him there.","g":"appoint, set in place","h":"The picture: setting a man down in a post."},"G2526":{"b":"This word joins two things and measures one by the other, according as, in proportion as. Paul says a gift is accepted katho a man has, measured to what he owns, not to what he lacks, Second Corinthians 8:12.","g":"according as","h":"The picture: one thing measured against another."},"G2527":{"b":"Built from kata and holos, the whole. Abbott gives on the whole, in general. The council orders the apostles not to speak katholou, not at all, in Jesus' name. It sweeps in the entire matter and forbids the lot.","g":"at all, entirely","h":"The picture: the whole thing, top to bottom."},"G2528":{"b":"This word means to arm fully, to equip head to foot with armor. Jesus pictures a strong man fully armed guarding his own house, and his goods are safe, until someone stronger comes, overpowers him, and strips the armor away.","g":"arm","h":"The picture: a strong man in full armor guarding his house."},"G2529":{"b":"This joins down with the word for seeing. Abbott's first sense is to look down, then to discern clearly. It is the full, plain sight of a thing. Paul says God's unseen power has been clearly seen in what He made.","g":"clearly see","h":"The picture: looking down and taking it all in."},"G253":{"b":"Built from without and lype, sadness. Abbott gives free from grief. Paul sends Epaphroditus back so the Philippians may rejoice and he himself may be alypoteros, carrying less sorrow. The word measures grief growing lighter.","g":"less sorrowful","h":"The picture: a weight of grief lifted off."},"G2533":{"b":"This is the name Caiaphas, the high priest. Strong's says it is of Chaldee origin and guesses it means the dell, but Abbott-Smith gives no meaning. So there is no sure picture.","flat":1,"g":"Caiaphas","h":"No picture."},"G2535":{"b":"The name comes from words for a lance, a striking spear, and for setting up or erecting. Cain was the firstborn son of Adam, who killed his brother Abel in the field.","g":"Cain","h":"The picture: a lance."},"G2536":{"b":"The name means fixed, set firm. Behind it stands a word for a nest, a settled place. Cainan was a patriarch in the early family line before the flood.","g":"Cainan","h":"The picture: fixed."},"G2537":{"b":"Greek has two words for new. Abbott-Smith says this one is new in form or quality, fresh, unused, while the other means new in time, young.\n\nA new tomb, a new name, a new song. Never used before.","g":"new","h":"The picture: unused, not just recent."},"G2538":{"b":"The root means new, and especially fresh, not worn out. This is that freshness itself. Paul says we walk in newness of life, in the fresh newness of the Spirit and not the old worn way. Everything unused, just made, still clean.","g":"newness","h":"The picture: something brand-new and fresh."},"G254":{"b":"This word means a chain or fetter. Strong's says it is of uncertain derivation, so no one knows where it came from. It plainly names the chain on a prisoner. There is no picture behind it.","flat":1,"g":"chain","h":"No picture."},"G2540":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is not about time at all. Due measure, fitness, proportion. The right amount.\n\nFrom there it becomes the right moment. Another Greek word covers time as duration. This one is time that fits.","g":"right time","h":"The picture: the fitting measure."},"G2541":{"b":"Caesar is a Roman title carried straight into Greek. Strong's says it is of Latin origin and stops there. Nothing in the sources says what the name once meant.","flat":1,"g":"Caesar","h":"No picture."},"G2542":{"b":"Strong's traces this to Caesar, a title of the Roman emperor. Caesarea is a city built to flatter him, his name stamped on the map. It marks where Roman power pressed into Palestine, the seat of Pilate and the port where Paul was held.","g":"Caesarea","h":"The picture: the emperor's name on the map."},"G2545":{"b":"This word means to light or to burn. Strong's calls it a primary verb, so it does not come from anything else. It simply names fire at work, with no hidden picture.","flat":1,"g":"burn, light","h":"No picture."},"G2549":{"b":"The root is bad, worthless at the core. Kakia is badness of quality, wickedness, depravity, malignity, the rot that spoils a person from the inside. Paul says strip it off like a filthy coat. Jesus uses its plainer edge, each day has trouble enough.","g":"malice","h":"The picture: the rot that spoils from inside."},"G255":{"b":"The word is a \"no\" set in front of a word meaning it pays off, it is worth the cost. So this is a thing that never pays. Hebrews says leaders who grieve over you would be no gain to you. A loss.","g":"unprofitable","h":"The picture: a deal that never pays off."},"G2550":{"b":"Built from bad and ethos, settled habit. It is a character hardened into taking everything the wrong way. Paul lists it in Romans 1. Not a passing bad mood but an ingrained bent that reads evil into every motive.","g":"malignity","h":"The picture: a mind bent to think the worst."},"G2551":{"b":"This is \"bad\" welded to \"word.\" It means to aim evil speech at a person, to speak ill of them out loud. When the command says the one who does this to father or mother must die, the sin is words used as weapons.","g":"revile","h":"The picture: throwing bad words at someone."},"G2552":{"b":"Built from bad and pathos, suffering. Abbott gives distress, affliction. James points to the prophets as an example of kakopatheia, of enduring hardship patiently. The word is being knocked about and not quitting.","g":"hardship","h":"The picture: bearing up under rough treatment."},"G2553":{"b":"The word joins two others, bad and suffer. It means to feel hard things and keep going, to endure affliction. Not to dodge the pain but to stay in it. Paul writes this word from prison. He is in chains, and he tells Timothy to bear it too.","g":"to suffer hardship","h":"The picture: staying in the pain instead of fleeing."},"G2554":{"b":"The word is built from \"bad\" and \"do,\" a bad-doer. It means to do harm, to injure. Jesus asks in the synagogue, is it lawful on the Sabbath to do good or to do harm, to save a life or to kill. He healed rather than hurt.","g":"do evil","h":"The picture: a hand that harms instead of helps."},"G2555":{"b":"The two roots are bad and to do. This word is one who does bad, an evil-doer, a criminal. Peter says live so cleanly that those who call you an evil-doer see your good works instead. Do not suffer as one.","g":"evil-doer","h":"The picture: the one caught doing wrong."},"G2556":{"b":"Strong's calls it apparently a primary word, so nothing lies behind it. Abbott-Smith simply sets it opposite good.\n\nStrong's does note it means bad in itself, where another word points to bad effects.","flat":1,"g":"bad, evil","h":"No picture."},"G2557":{"b":"This joins \"bad\" to \"work,\" ergon, \"toil (as an effort or occupation).\" A kakourgos is a man whose trade is harm. Not one stray bad act, but evil as his line of work. The word names the two criminals crucified beside Jesus.","g":"evildoer, criminal","h":"The picture: the man whose work is harm."},"G2558":{"b":"This word joins a word for bad or evil with a word meaning to hold. To be tormented here is to be held in evil hands, kept and treated cruelly. Hebrews speaks of the faithful being ill-treated, of whom the world was not worthy.","g":"maltreat, torment","h":"The picture: held in cruel hands."},"G2559":{"b":"The root is the word for bad. To do someone bad, to hurt, ill-treat, and afflict. God warned Abraham his people would be badly treated in Egypt. Herod stretched out his hand to harm the church. It also means to embitter, to sour minds.","g":"harm, ill-treat","h":"The picture: doing someone bad."},"G256":{"b":"Alphaeus is a man's name, father of Levi and of James. It comes from Aramaic, not from Greek parts. A name in the record, with nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"Alphaeus","h":"No picture."},"G2560":{"b":"Abbott's first use is physical, to be ill. To have it badly is to be sick. The Gospels crowd this word with the people carried to Jesus, all who were kakōs, held down by disease and desperate for a healer.","g":"badly","h":"The picture: being sick, held down."},"G2561":{"b":"Abbott's sense is ill-treatment. The word grows from a root meaning to injure. In Acts, God tells Moses from the bush that he has seen how his people are being hurt down in Egypt.","g":"affliction","h":"The picture: harm done to a body."},"G2562":{"b":"The word means a stalk of grain, and gathered together, stubble. It is the dry straw left standing, quick to catch fire. Paul lists it among poor building stuff, wood, hay, stubble, that the flames will test.","g":"stubble","h":"The picture: dry stubble in the field."},"G2563":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it is a reed, the tall stalk from the water's edge. Depending on its use it became a flute, a walking staff, a measuring rod, or a pen. Jesus asked if the crowds went out to see a reed shaken by the wind.","g":"reed","h":"The picture: a marsh reed."},"G2564":{"b":"Strong's says the word properly means to call aloud.\n\nAbbott-Smith gives three uses: to summon, to invite to your house for a meal, and to name. Being called by God, in his list, sits with the dinner invitations.","g":"call, invite","h":"The picture: shouting someone's name across a room."},"G2565":{"b":"This joins a word for good or fine with the word for an olive tree. So it is the cultivated olive, the garden tree, set against the wild one. Abbott says the garden olive. Paul says the wild branch was grafted into it against nature.","g":"good olive tree","h":"The picture: the good olive tree in a tended garden."},"G2567":{"b":"This joins a word that first means beautiful, then good and valuable, to the word for a teacher. Paul wants the aged women to be teachers of good. The root reminds us that what is truly good is also beautiful, and they teach that.","g":"teacher of good","h":"The picture: a teacher of what is beautiful."},"G2569":{"b":"This joins kalos, which first means beautiful and then good, with poieo, to do. So it is doing the good, honorable thing. Paul tells them not to grow weary in well doing, in keeping on with what is right.","g":"do good","h":"The picture: doing the fine and good thing."},"G257":{"b":"A halon is a threshing floor, ground packed hard and flat, Strong's says rolled hard. Here the sheaves are beaten to knock the grain loose from the stalk. John pictures Christ clearing this floor, gathering the wheat and burning the rest. Judgment happens where the harvest is sorted.","g":"threshing floor","h":"The picture: the hard floor where grain is beaten out."},"G2570":{"b":"Abbott says it is primarily about outward form. Fair. Beautiful. He puts it beside another word for good and says this one is the appearance, the other is the essence.\n\nGood works you can see.","g":"good, beautiful","h":"The picture: good to look at."},"G2571":{"b":"The root means to cover up. This word is the cloth that covers, a veil. Paul remembers the veil Moses put over his face, and says a veil still lies over the heart until Christ takes it away.","g":"veil","h":"The picture: a veil over the face."},"G2572":{"b":"Strong's: \"to cover up.\" Abbott adds \"to veil, conceal.\" It is laying a cover over something, a lamp hidden under a bowl, a wave covering a boat. From that it means to cover over sins.","g":"cover, hide","h":"The picture: laying a cover over something."},"G2573":{"b":"Abbott says this adverb is used as an exclamation of approval. Someone speaks and you answer, well said.\n\nMostly it just means finely, rightly, well. Abbott notes it can also be said with a sneer.","g":"well, rightly","h":"The picture: a nod of approval."},"G2574":{"b":"A kamelos is the camel, the animal. John the Baptist wore a coat of its hair. Jesus built a joke on it. Easier for a camel to squeeze through a needle's eye than a rich man into heaven. A great beast against a tiny gap.","g":"camel","h":"The picture: a camel."},"G2575":{"b":"This is an oven built to blaze, and its root word means to set on fire. Not a cooking hearth but a furnace hot enough to melt or destroy. That is the image Jesus reaches for when he warns of the end of the weeds.","g":"furnace","h":"The picture: the roar of a furnace fire."},"G2576":{"b":"This word means to shut the eyes, and it is deliberate. The people in Isaiah's words have closed their own eyes so they will not have to see. They are not blind. They are refusing to look at what is right in front of them.","g":"close the eyes","h":"The picture: eyes squeezed shut."},"G2577":{"b":"This word starts with work. Abbott says it means to work, and then, from the effect of continued work, to grow weary. So the picture is a laborer worn down by his own toil. When you are tired out, this is the word.","g":"grow weary","h":"The picture: the worker worn down by his toil."},"G2578":{"b":"The word simply means to bend. Abbott shows it used for bending the knee. It is the body folding down low. Paul bends his knees to the Father with it, and one day every knee will bend at the name of Jesus.","g":"to bow","h":"The picture: the knee folds."},"G2579":{"b":"This is a small conditional word, and if, even if. It is glue between clauses, holding a supposition together. It names no thing and no act, so there is nothing here for the eye to rest on.","flat":1,"g":"even if","h":"No picture."},"G258":{"b":"This is the animal, the fox. Strong's notes it can also stand for a cunning person. Jesus says foxes have holes but he has nowhere to lay his head. And he calls Herod a fox. Sly, and always at home in a hole.","g":"fox","h":"The picture: the fox in its den."},"G2580":{"b":"This is a place name, Cana of Galilee, where Jesus turned water into wine. Strong's says only \"Cana, a place in Palestine.\" A name on a map has nothing built into it to see.","flat":1,"g":"Cana","h":"No picture."},"G2581":{"b":"This is an epithet for Simon, one of the apostles. Abbott-Smith says it marks him as a Cananaean or Zealot, a member of the party fierce for God's law. It names a kind of man, with no picture inside.","flat":1,"g":"Zealot","h":"No picture."},"G2582":{"b":"Candace is a name, a queen of the Ethiopians whose treasurer met Philip on the road. The sources give it no meaning to unfold. There is no picture here, only the name of a ruler.","flat":1,"g":"Candace","h":"No picture."},"G2583":{"b":"Behind the word \"canon\" is a straight reed, a rod. A reed cut straight was used to measure and to draw a line. So a rule or standard is a straightedge you check things against. Paul blesses those who walk by it.","g":"rule, standard","h":"The picture: a straight measuring reed."},"G2584":{"b":"This is a place name. Abbott-Smith notes it means Nahum's village. That names a town after a man, but tells you nothing about a concept. It is a dot on the map by the lake.","flat":1,"g":"Capernaum","h":"No picture."},"G2585":{"b":"Abbott-Smith traces this to a huckster, a market trader. The cheat stretches the goods and pockets the difference. Paul says he does not peddle God's word like that, watered down for profit.","g":"corrupt, adulterate","h":"The picture: a peddler watering down his wine to sell it."},"G2586":{"b":"This word just means smoke. Strong's says its origin is of uncertain affinity, which means no one is sure where it comes from. There is nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"smoke","h":"No picture."},"G2587":{"b":"This is a place name. Strong's says \"Cappadocia, a region of Asia Minor.\" It is one of the far-off homelands of the pilgrims who heard their own tongue at Pentecost. A name on a map, of foreign origin, with no image inside.","flat":1,"g":"Cappadocia","h":"No picture."},"G2588":{"b":"Strong's says the word can simply mean the middle. Abbott-Smith points to the pith at the centre of a piece of wood, and to Matthew 12:40, the heart of the earth.\n\nSo the heart is the innermost part, where the real person sits.","g":"heart","h":"The picture: the middle of a thing."},"G2589":{"b":"The word simply joins \"heart\" and \"knower.\" Abbott says \"knower of hearts.\" When the apostles must choose between two men, they pray to the God who sees inside every chest and knows which one he has picked. Nothing is hidden from him.","g":"heart-knower","h":"The picture: one who reads what is hidden in the heart."},"G259":{"b":"The word means a taking, a capture. Abbott ties it to being caught. Peter says false teachers are like wild beasts, born to be caught and killed, and they will perish in their own corruption.","g":"capture","h":"The picture: an animal caught and taken."},"G2590":{"b":"Strong's says fruit as plucked. Abbott lists trees, vines and fields.\n\nThen the stretch. Fruit of works. Fruit of the Spirit. Fruit of the lips, meaning praise. Something grown, then gathered.","g":"fruit","h":"The picture: fruit picked off the tree."},"G2591":{"b":"Strong's says his name is perhaps from the word for fruit, the kind you pluck from a branch. Carpus is the man with whom Paul left his cloak at Troas. A friend whose name means fruit.","g":"Carpus","h":"The picture: fruit on the branch."},"G2592":{"b":"Abbott: \"to bear fruit.\" It joins the word for fruit with the word for carrying. The picture is a plant loaded down with its fruit. Jesus uses it for a life that carries good fruit from good soil.","g":"bear fruit","h":"The picture: a plant loaded with fruit."},"G2593":{"b":"The word joins 'fruit, as plucked' with 'to bear or carry.' It means fruit-bearing. God, Paul says, sends rain and fruitful seasons, filling human hearts with food and gladness.","g":"fruitful","h":"The picture: a branch bending with fruit."},"G2594":{"b":"This comes from the word for strength and vigor. It means to hold on with force, to stand firm and not give way. Moses left Egypt and endured, as one seeing him who is invisible.","g":"endure","h":"The picture: holding firm by main strength."},"G2595":{"b":"A karphos is a bit of dry straw, a tiny twig. It is the speck in your brother's eye. Jesus sets this fleck of chaff against the plank in your own eye. A dry crumb of stalk, small enough to blow away in a breath.","g":"speck, mote","h":"The picture: a fleck of dry straw."},"G2597":{"b":"Abbott gives the plain sense, to go or come down. Then he lists the things that do it. A sheet let down. Rain. A squall on the lake.\n\nThe same word for Jesus coming down from heaven.","g":"come down","h":"The picture: rain coming down."},"G2598":{"b":"This is built from down and a word meaning to throw, sometimes violently. To be cast down is to be thrown flat on the ground. Paul says we are struck down but not destroyed, never abandoned.","g":"cast down","h":"The picture: thrown flat to the ground."},"G2599":{"b":"The root means to weigh down, and \"down\" only drives it deeper. It is the feeling of a heavy pack on the shoulders. Paul uses it to say he did not lay that weight on the Corinthians, taking no money from them.","g":"burden","h":"The picture: a load pressing you down."},"G26":{"b":"Strong's notes that in the plural this word becomes a love-feast, the shared meal of the early church. The love has a table and hands. So agape is not only a warm feeling. It is love that picks its object and sits down to eat with it.","g":"love","h":"The picture: a shared meal."},"G260":{"b":"This little word means at the same time or together. Strong's calls it a primary particle, which means it does not come from anything else. There is nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"together, at once","h":"No picture."},"G2600":{"b":"The word is the down-going, from a root meaning to descend. Picture a slope, the road falling away below your feet. At the descent of the Mount of Olives the whole crowd began to praise God with a loud voice.","g":"descent","h":"The picture: the road running downhill."},"G2601":{"b":"This word means to cause to go down, to cast down. Capernaum thought itself lifted up to heaven, Jesus says, but it will be brought down to the depths, dragged from the height it imagined it stood on.","g":"bring down","h":"The picture: dragged down from the heights."},"G2602":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is a laying down. Then it means a foundation, the base of a house. The Bible speaks of things planned before the foundation of the world, before the first stone was laid.","g":"foundation","h":"The picture: laying something down to build on."},"G2603":{"b":"In the Greek games the brabeus was the umpire. This word puts kata, against, in front of him. So it is the umpire ruling against you, robbing you of the prize you ran for. Paul warns no one should judge a believer out of his reward.","g":"rob of the prize","h":"The picture: the umpire rules against you."},"G2604":{"b":"This is a proclaimer, herald, the man who cries news aloud in public. Someone stands and announces for all to hear. The Athenians called Paul a herald of strange gods, of Jesus and the resurrection.","g":"proclaimer","h":"The picture: the town herald."},"G2605":{"b":"This joins down to the word behind messenger, the bringer of tidings. To kataggello is to proclaim, to announce a thing openly and loudly. So as often as you eat this bread you kataggello the Lord's death, heralding it out like news that must be told.","g":"proclaim","h":"The picture: a herald crying the news down the street."},"G2606":{"b":"This is to laugh down at someone. The kata means down, the rest means laugh. It is not laughing with, it is laughing at. When Jesus said the girl only slept, they laughed him down. Scorn with a grin on it.","g":"laugh to scorn","h":"The picture: the crowd laughing a man down."},"G2607":{"b":"The roots are kata, against, and ginosko, to know. So the word is to know a thing against someone, to find them at fault. John says if our own heart knows something against us, God is greater than our heart.","g":"condemn, blame","h":"The picture: knowing something against you."},"G2608":{"b":"The word means to break, to crack apart. Isaiah's line, quoted of Jesus, says a bruised reed he will not break. Picture a cracked, bent stalk that a hand could snap with no effort. He does not finish it off. He spares the nearly broken.","g":"break","h":"The picture: snapping a reed in two."},"G2609":{"b":"Built from down and lead. It means to bring down. As a sailors' word Abbott-Smith gives to bring to land. They brought the boats to land and left everything to follow Jesus.","g":"bring down, land","h":"The picture: bringing a ship in to shore."},"G261":{"b":"Built from not and manthano, to learn. Abbott gives unlearned, ignorant. Peter says the amathes twist Paul's letters to their own ruin. The word is the untaught mind, missing the training that would keep it steady.","g":"unlearned","h":"The picture: never taught, so easily misled."},"G2610":{"b":"The root means to struggle in the contest, to compete for a prize. This word adds 'down,' to fight down and overcome. By faith these men subdued kingdoms and wrestled their enemies to the ground.","g":"subdue","h":"The picture: wrestling the opponent down."},"G2611":{"b":"This word joins down and to bind. Strong's reads it as to bandage a wound. The Samaritan poured oil and wine on the man's injuries and bound them up, wrapping each one before lifting him onto his own animal.","g":"bind up","h":"The picture: binding up a wound."},"G2612":{"b":"This is built on the word for clear, with a bit added meaning 'quite.' It means fully plain, out in the open. It is more than evident that another kind of priest has arisen, like Melchizedek.","g":"quite evident","h":"The picture: plain in full view."},"G2613":{"b":"The parts mean \"against\" and justice, a verdict handed down. To katadikazo is to declare a man guilty from the bench. You would not have condemned the guiltless, Jesus said, if you knew what mercy meant. The sentence falling on the innocent.","g":"condemn","h":"The picture: a sentence handed down against you."},"G2614":{"b":"The pieces mean down and to pursue, so to chase a thing down, to track it hard. In Mark 1:36 Simon and the others hunt Jesus down and find him praying alone, then tell him everyone is looking for him.","g":"hunt down","h":"The picture: tracking down like a hunter."},"G2615":{"b":"This is built from a word meaning to enslave, with kata for utterly. It means to bring someone fully under the yoke. Paul warns of false brethren who slipped in to spy on our freedom and drag us back into bondage.","g":"enslave","h":"The picture: dragged under the yoke."},"G2616":{"b":"Built from \"down\" and the word for a ruler or officer, one who holds power. It means to press that power down on people. Jesus went about freeing all who were held down this way by the devil.","g":"oppress","h":"The picture: a ruler's power pressed down on the weak."},"G2617":{"b":"Strong's says the word means to shame down, to disgrace. It is pushing someone down into shame, making them blush. Paul turns it around. Hope does not put us to shame.","g":"put to shame","h":"The picture: shamed down."},"G2618":{"b":"This is \"burn\" with \"down\" in front. Abbott-Smith says \"to burn up, burn completely.\" Not a scorch but a total burning, with nothing left. The weeds are gathered and burned up.","g":"burn up","h":"The picture: burned to the ground."},"G2619":{"b":"The roots are kata, down, and kalypto, to cover. So the word is to pull a covering down over, to veil. Paul uses it for a woman covering her head, the cloth drawn down over what is underneath.","g":"veil, cover","h":"The picture: a veil pulled down."},"G262":{"b":"Abbott ties it to amaranth, a flower the ancients said never faded. So this is an unfading crown. Peter promises the elders a wreath that, unlike real flowers, will never wither.","g":"unfading","h":"The picture: the flower that never wilts."},"G2620":{"b":"The root means to boast, to vaunt. The prefix means down or against. So this is boasting aimed down at someone, gloating over them. Paul warns the grafted branches not to do it. James says mercy does it over judgment.","g":"boast against","h":"The picture: crowing over a fallen rival."},"G2621":{"b":"This is \"lie\" with \"down\" in front. Abbott-Smith says it means to lie down, and so to lie sick in bed, or to recline at a meal. The same posture covers the paralyzed man and the dinner guest.","g":"lie down","h":"The picture: lying down."},"G2622":{"b":"The root is the word for breaking, especially breaking bread. Add \"down\" and you break it right up, into pieces. This is what Jesus does with the five loaves, snapping them apart in his hands so there is enough to hand around.","g":"break","h":"The picture: bread snapped into pieces."},"G2623":{"b":"The root means to shut, to close. Add \"down\" and it is to shut someone right down, into a dungeon. Luke uses it for Herod, who added this to his sins: he shut John up in prison for speaking against him.","g":"shut up","h":"The picture: locked behind a prison door."},"G2624":{"b":"The word is built on 'a die for drawing chances' and 'to give.' The land of Canaan was parceled out to the tribes by lot, each portion settled as the lots fell.","g":"divide by lot","h":"The picture: casting lots to divide the land."},"G2625":{"b":"Built from a word meaning down and a word meaning to lean or slope. At meals they did not sit up, they lay down on couches, leaning on one elbow. This is taking that place at the table, stretched out to eat.","g":"sit at table","h":"The picture: leaning back on a couch to eat."},"G2626":{"b":"This joins \"down\" to a root meaning a surge of the sea. So it is to flood, to deluge. Peter says the old world was overflowed with water and perished, and the present one is kept for fire.","g":"overflow, deluge","h":"The picture: a wave washing everything down."},"G2627":{"b":"The root means to wash down, to dash water over a thing. A kataklysmos is the flood, the deluge that swept the world in Noah's day. It came, Jesus says, while they ate and married, and took them all away.","g":"flood","h":"The picture: water crashing down over everything."},"G2628":{"b":"The root means to walk the same road with someone, even as a disciple. With \"after\" added Abbott says \"to follow after.\" The women follow close behind as Jesus' body is carried, watching where the tomb is so they can return.","g":"follow after","h":"The picture: keeping close on someone's heels."},"G2629":{"b":"The pieces mean down and to chop or strike. It is cutting a thing to pieces. In Mark 5:5 the man among the tombs cries out night and day and cuts himself with stones, gashing his own body.","g":"cut, gash","h":"The picture: gashing with a stone."},"G263":{"b":"Add \"not\" to the word for a flower withering and you get the amaranth, the bloom the Greeks said never wilts. Peter says your inheritance is kept like that in heaven. It will not fade, ever.","g":"that fadeth not away","h":"The picture: the flower that never wilts."},"G2630":{"b":"This word is built from the Greek for a steep cliff. Abbott-Smith says it means to throw over a precipice, cast down headlong. It is one hard push off a high rock. That is what the crowd in Nazareth tried to do to Jesus.","g":"cast down headlong","h":"The picture: one shove off a high cliff."},"G2631":{"b":"The root katakrino means to judge against, to sentence. The katakrima is the sentence itself, the verdict handed down against the accused. Paul's word in Romans 8, now there is no condemnation for those in Christ, no sentence left to read.","g":"condemnation","h":"The picture: the sentence handed down."},"G2632":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means to give judgment against someone. The word joins judging with a downward, against sense. It is the guilty verdict falling on a person. Not just an opinion. A sentence handed down.","g":"condemn","h":"The picture: the verdict brought down against you."},"G2633":{"b":"This is built from a word meaning to judge against, to sentence. It is the guilty verdict brought down on someone. Paul contrasts the ministry of condemnation with the far greater ministry of righteousness.","g":"condemnation","h":"The picture: the verdict brought down."},"G2634":{"b":"This is \"rule\" with \"down\" pressed onto the front. It means to lord it over people, to hold them down under you. The rulers of the nations do this, Jesus says. Among you it must not be so.","g":"lord over","h":"The picture: pushing someone down under your rule."},"G2635":{"b":"The word is against plus speak. Abbott-Smith says to speak evil of, to rail at. It is running someone down with your words. James says do not do it to one another, do not stand and talk a brother down.","g":"slander, speak against","h":"The picture: talking a man down behind his back."},"G2636":{"b":"This is built from a word meaning to talk against, to speak someone down. Katalalia is speech aimed at a person's back, running them down where they cannot answer. Paul fears finding such backbiting in the church.","g":"backbiting","h":"The picture: words thrown at a back."},"G2637":{"b":"This joins against with the word for talking. So it is one who talks against another. Where the whisperer works in secret, this one speaks it out. Abbott says a railer, a defamer. Paul sets the two side by side.","g":"backbiter","h":"The picture: talking someone down behind their back."},"G2638":{"b":"Abbott says the word means to lay hold of, to seize. Paul presses on to seize the prize. It also means to overtake or to grasp with the mind. The darkness has not seized the light.","g":"seize, grasp","h":"The picture: grabbing hold."},"G2639":{"b":"The root first meant to lay out or pick, and here it means to enrol, the way soldiers are counted onto a list. Paul says let a widow be taken into the number if she is past sixty and known for good works.","g":"enrol","h":"The picture: names written on the muster roll."},"G264":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is to miss the mark, straight out of Homer. Strong's adds a detail: to miss, and so not share in the prize.\n\nAiming at something and falling short. Then, failing in general.","g":"sin","h":"The picture: the shot goes wide."},"G2641":{"b":"Abbott-Smith notes this word is used of sailing past a place, as in Acts 21:3. The land is left behind you.\n\nThe same verb covers a man leaving father and mother to marry.","g":"leave behind","h":"The picture: the coast dropping behind the ship."},"G2642":{"b":"Built from a word for down and a word meaning to throw stones. Abbott says it means to cast stones at, to stone. The people will stone us, the priests said, if we deny that John was a prophet.","g":"stone","h":"The picture: stones hurled at a man."},"G2643":{"b":"The plain sense of this word is exchange. The root means to change mutually, one thing swapped for another. So reconciliation is an exchange. The old standing of an enemy is handed over, and God's favor is given back in its place.","g":"reconciliation","h":"The picture: an exchange."},"G2644":{"b":"The plain sense is to change, exchange, especially of money. You swap one thing for another across the table. Paul uses it for God turning enemies into friends. The old standing is traded in for a new one.","g":"reconcile","h":"The picture: coins traded at the money table."},"G2645":{"b":"The word joins 'behind' with 'the remaining ones.' In the prophecy Paul quotes, it is the rest of humankind, all those left over, who will seek the Lord and be called by his name.","g":"residue, the rest","h":"The picture: what is left behind."},"G2646":{"b":"The word comes from loosening down, the breaking up of a journey. It is the place where travelers halt, unhitch the animals, and unpack for the night. This is the room with no space for Mary, and the upper room where Jesus keeps the Passover.","g":"inn, lodging","h":"The picture: where travelers unstrap their packs."},"G2647":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this word can mean to unloose, unyoke (e.g. horses). At day's end a traveler unhitches the animals and stops for the night. The same word means to pull a building apart. To loosen down what was joined.","g":"destroy; lodge","h":"The picture: unhitching the horses for the night."},"G2648":{"b":"The root is manthano, to learn, deepened to learn thoroughly. Abbott gives to learn thoroughly, observe well. Jesus says katamanthano the lilies of the field. Do not glance. Look until the flower teaches you about God's care.","g":"consider","h":"The picture: studying the wildflowers closely."},"G2649":{"b":"The root means to be a witness, to testify. The kata means \"against.\" So it is standing up in court to give evidence against someone. At Jesus' trial they hunted for witnesses to testify against him, and their stories did not even agree.","g":"testify against","h":"The picture: a witness pointing across the court."},"G265":{"b":"The root means to miss the mark, the arrow falling short of the target. This word is the sin itself, the actual missed shot. Not the habit but the single arrow that flew wide. One concrete act that fell short.","g":"a sin","h":"The picture: the arrow that flew wide."},"G2650":{"b":"This word joins down and to stay. The down makes it settled, staying put for good. Luke uses it of the disciples in the upper room where they were living. Not visiting. Lodged there, day after day.","g":"to abide","h":"The picture: settling in to stay."},"G2652":{"b":"Built on anathema, a thing handed over to destruction under a ban. Strong's gives an imprecation. It is the act of pronouncing doom on someone, devoting them to ruin with words. A curse laid heavy and meant.","g":"curse","h":"The picture: a curse called down on a head."},"G2653":{"b":"The root means to vow under a penalty, to place yourself under a curse if you lie. The added piece means down, driving it harder. In Matthew 26:74 Peter begins to curse and swear that he never knew Jesus.","g":"curse","h":"The picture: calling down a curse on your own head."},"G2654":{"b":"This is fire finishing its work, burning a thing all the way down to nothing. Abbott ties it straight to fire. Hebrews ends with it: our God is a consuming fire. Not a spark. A blaze that leaves ash.","g":"consume","h":"The picture: fire burning a thing down to ash."},"G2655":{"b":"Abbott traces this to narkao, to grow numb, like a limb that has fallen asleep. Paul turns it into a strange picture of being a dead weight. He says he was not numb upon them, not a burden he laid on the church.","g":"be burdensome","h":"The picture: a limb gone numb."},"G2656":{"b":"This word is built from the word to nod. Abbott-Smith gives it as to make a sign by nodding the head. Peter's partners were too far off in the other boat to shout, so they tipped their heads to wave the men over.","g":"beckon","h":"The picture: a nod of the head across the water."},"G2657":{"b":"The root is the mind at work. Kata drives it down deep, to fix the mind fully, to take note of, perceive, consider carefully. Jesus tells us to katanoeō the ravens and the lilies, to really look until we see how God feeds and clothes them.","g":"to consider","h":"The picture: fixing your eyes until you see."},"G2658":{"b":"Abbott's sense is to come to, arrive at, to reach a place after travel. Luke uses it for Paul's ship touching port after port. Paul lifts it higher, the day we all katantaō at the unity of the faith, the whole church arriving home.","g":"to arrive","h":"The picture: reaching port after the voyage."},"G2659":{"b":"The root means to pierce, to prick. Strong's says a prickling, like a limb fallen asleep, which passes into a heavy stupor. Abbott says torpor of mind. Paul quotes Isaiah, God gave them a spirit of slumber, eyes that would not see.","g":"slumber, stupor","h":"The picture: the pins-and-needles of a limb gone numb."},"G266":{"b":"This was an archery word first. Abbott-Smith says it means \"missing the mark.\"\n\nSo sin is not only breaking a rule. It is aiming and falling short.","g":"sin","h":"The picture: the arrow misses."},"G2660":{"b":"This word joins down with the word for pricking or piercing, driving it deep. When the crowd heard Peter's sermon, they were pricked to the heart, stabbed inside, and cried out, What shall we do. A sharp wound in the chest.","g":"to prick, sting","h":"The picture: a stab straight to the heart."},"G2661":{"b":"Built from a word meaning to deem worthy. The apostles left the council rejoicing that they had been kataxioo, counted worthy to suffer shame for the Name, Acts 5:41. To be weighed on the scale and reckoned fit for it.","g":"count worthy","h":"The picture: weighed and reckoned fit."},"G2662":{"b":"The root means to trample, and \"down\" makes it stamping underfoot. Do not throw pearls to pigs, Jesus says, or they will katapateo them into the mud. Salt that lost its taste gets trodden down the same way.","g":"trample","h":"The picture: grinding it underfoot."},"G2663":{"b":"Abbott's older sense is \"a putting to rest, causing to cease.\" Strong's: \"reposing down.\" The picture is motion settling down and coming to a full stop. It is the word for the rest God promises his people.","g":"rest","h":"The picture: everything settles and stops."},"G2664":{"b":"The word is \"down\" plus \"to stop (transitively or intransitively).\" To bring a thing to a full stop and let it settle. It is used of God resting on the seventh day, ceasing from all his work. Joshua could not give the people that settled rest.","g":"give rest, cease","h":"The picture: a thing brought to a full stop to settle."},"G2665":{"b":"This is the door screen spread across the way into the Most Holy Place, the inner veil of the Temple. When Jesus died it tore from top to bottom. Hebrews calls his flesh the veil. A heavy cloth that shut people out, now split open.","g":"veil","h":"The picture: a great curtain across a doorway."},"G2666":{"b":"This word is built from down and to drink. It means to gulp something down entire, to swallow it. You strain out a gnat and swallow a camel, Jesus says. Death is swallowed up in victory. The throat taking it all the way down.","g":"swallow","h":"The picture: gulping something down whole."},"G2667":{"b":"The word joins down and fall. It means to fall down. Some seed falls on rock and withers. On the Damascus road Paul and his men all fall to the ground before the light. A body going straight down.","g":"fall down","h":"The picture: dropping flat to the ground."},"G2668":{"b":"This word joins down and to sail. Abbott-Smith gives it as to sail down, sail to land, put in. After crossing the lake, Jesus and the disciples brought the boat in to shore in the country of the Gerasenes.","g":"arrive, land","h":"The picture: a boat running in to shore."},"G2669":{"b":"Built from \"down\" and a word for toil that turns into anguish, it means to wear with toil, to grind a person down under labor. Moses saw an Israelite worn down like this and struck the Egyptian who was doing it.","g":"oppress","h":"The picture: a man ground down under a heavy load."},"G267":{"b":"The word is 'not' plus 'a witness.' Paul says God never left himself without one: the rains and the fruitful seasons stand up like witnesses and testify that he is good.","g":"without witness","h":"The picture: a courtroom with no witness to call."},"G2670":{"b":"This joins \"down\" to a word for the open sea. Katapontizo is to be plunged down into deep water and drowned. It is Peter, walking on the waves, who begins to sink and cries out for Jesus to save him.","g":"drown, sink","h":"The picture: going down under the sea."},"G2671":{"b":"The root is a prayer lifted to heaven. Put \"down\" in front and the prayer turns against someone, called down on their head. Christ became a katara for us. He took the prayer that was aimed down at us.","g":"curse","h":"The picture: a prayer called down on your head."},"G2672":{"b":"This is the verb of the curse, kataraomai, to call down harm on someone. Bless and do not kataraomai, Paul says. With the same tongue we bless God and kataraomai men made in his likeness. Words aimed down at a person's head.","g":"to curse","h":"The picture: harm called down on a person."},"G2673":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is to make idle or inactive. His example is the fig tree in Luke 13:7, taking up ground and producing nothing.\n\nSo the word does not always mean destroy. It means stopped from working.","g":"abolish, make useless","h":"The picture: put out of work."},"G2674":{"b":"This word is built on the verb to count. It means to number someone among a group. Peter says Judas was once counted in with the twelve, one of their tally, before he turned and fell away.","g":"to number among","h":"The picture: counted in with the group."},"G2675":{"b":"Abbott points to Matthew 4:21 and Mark 1:19 for this word. Both are the same scene. James and John sit in the boat, mending their nets. It is the word for God restoring a person. Not throwing away. Mending.","g":"mend, restore","h":"The picture: mending a fishing net."},"G2676":{"b":"The root means to repair, to set right, to adjust. Abbott-Smith says a making fit. Paul prays for exactly this for them, to be mended and put back together, whole again rather than thrown away.","g":"perfecting","h":"The picture: a torn net mended back to working order."},"G2677":{"b":"This is the noun from the word for mending, the same word used for fishermen repairing their nets. It means putting people fully in order, each part made ready. Paul says leaders are given to fit the saints for their work.","g":"perfecting","h":"The picture: a net put back in order."},"G2678":{"b":"The word is \"down\" plus \"to shake.\" Abbott: \"to shake or wave as a signal.\" Paul does it on the stairs, beckoning the crowd, and the roar dies to silence so he can speak. A hand raised to quiet the noise.","g":"beckon","h":"The picture: a hand waved to hush a crowd."},"G2679":{"b":"Built from \"down\" and a word meaning to dig. It is digging away at the base of a wall until the whole thing collapses. Elijah's complaint uses it: they have dug down your altars and killed your prophets, and I am left alone.","g":"dig down","h":"The picture: digging away the foundation until it falls."},"G268":{"b":"This is the person-word built on the verb that means to miss the mark. A sinner is someone defined by missing.\n\nAbbott-Smith says it covers all people, and also those thought especially wicked.","g":"sinner","h":"The picture: the one who keeps missing."},"G2680":{"b":"The root is gear, a vessel or equipment. To kataskeuazō is to build and fit out, to make ready down to the furnishings. Noah kataskeuazō the ark. The tabernacle is prepared this way. And the messenger goes ahead to make ready the road.","g":"to build","h":"The picture: building and fitting out."},"G2681":{"b":"Under this word is the word for a tent. It means to make camp. So when the birds of the air kataskenoo in the mustard tree, they are not just landing. They are settling in to stay, pitching their tents in its shade.","g":"lodge, dwell","h":"The picture: birds pitching a tent in the branches."},"G2682":{"b":"The root means to camp down, to settle and take up quarters. This word is the lodging itself, a place to roost, used of birds. Jesus says the birds have their nests but he has nowhere to rest. The creatures settle in for the night. He kept moving.","g":"a nest","h":"The picture: the bird's roost."},"G2683":{"b":"The root is the word for shade or shadow. This word means to cast a shadow down over something. The cherubim stretched their wings and overshadowed the mercy seat, covering it with their shade.","g":"overshadow","h":"The picture: wings casting shade over it."},"G2684":{"b":"The root is a spy sent to reconnoiter. Abbott-Smith says to view closely, spy out. Paul says the false brothers slipped in to do this, to spy on the freedom the believers had in Christ.","g":"spy out","h":"The picture: a scout creeping close to size up the ground."},"G2685":{"b":"The root means a watcher or scout. This is a spy, one sent to look a place over in secret. By faith Rahab took in the spies who came to scout Jericho, and was not destroyed with the rest.","g":"spy","h":"The picture: the scout sent to watch the land."},"G2686":{"b":"The word is 'against' plus a root meaning to render wise. Abbott's sense is to outwit. In Acts, Pharaoh deals shrewdly with Israel, bending his own cunning against them to grind the people down.","g":"deal craftily","h":"The picture: cleverness turned into a weapon."},"G2687":{"b":"Built from \"down\" and a word meaning to set fast, to repress. It is pushing something that has risen back down, holding it still. The town clerk at Ephesus quieted the roaring crowd this way, pressing the uproar down until they would listen.","g":"quiet, appease","h":"The picture: pressing a rising crowd back down."},"G2688":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to place or set down firmly. A person's demeanor is the way they are set, their steady bearing. Paul wants the aged women reverent in this. Not a passing mood but the fixed way they hold themselves.","g":"behaviour","h":"The picture: the settled set of a person."},"G2689":{"b":"The root means to let down or lower. A katastole is the garment let down around a person, one's dress and attire. Paul says women should adorn themselves in modest apparel, with restraint.","g":"clothing","h":"The picture: a robe let down over the body."},"G269":{"b":"This word joins \"not\" with the word for a battle. It is the man who will not be drawn into a fight, who refuses to trade blows and heated words. Paul wants leaders like this. Standing down from the quarrel others itch to start.","g":"not a brawler","h":"The picture: the one who won't be drawn into a fight."},"G2690":{"b":"This joins \"down\" to strepho, to turn. Katastrepho is to turn a thing right over, to tip it upside down. It is what Jesus does in the temple, flipping the money-changers' tables so the coins scatter across the floor.","g":"overthrow","h":"The picture: the tables flipped upside down."},"G2691":{"b":"The root means to run wild in luxury and desire. With kata, against, it is that appetite straining against a pledge already made. Paul says younger widows do this against Christ, growing restless and wanting to marry.","g":"grow wanton","h":"The picture: appetite grown wild and restless."},"G2692":{"b":"The root means to turn upside down, to upset. A katastrophe is an overturning, the whole thing flipped and thrown down. Paul warns that wrangling over words ruins the hearers. It tips them over. Their footing turned on its head.","g":"overthrow","h":"The picture: everything flipped upside down."},"G2693":{"b":"This joins down with a word meaning to spread, as a carpet or couch. It pictures bodies strewn flat across the ground. Paul recalls that God laid the disobedient low, scattered dead in the wilderness.","g":"overthrow","h":"The picture: bodies strewn across the ground."},"G2694":{"b":"This word joins down and to drag or trail. Abbott-Smith gives it as to drag away. Settle with your accuser on the way, Jesus warns, or he may drag you before the judge, and you land in prison.","g":"hale, drag","h":"The picture: dragged off to the judge."},"G2695":{"b":"Built from a word for down and a word meaning to butcher an animal for food or sacrifice. Picture the blade at the throat. Bring my enemies here, the king says in the parable, and slay them before me.","g":"slay","h":"The picture: the knife to the throat."},"G2696":{"b":"The word joins \"down\" to a word meaning to stamp with a signet ring. Abbott-Smith gives \"to seal up, secure with a seal.\" Picture hot wax pressed with a ring so no one can open it. So the scroll in God's hand was sealed tight.","g":"to seal shut","h":"The picture: a scroll stamped shut with a seal."},"G2697":{"b":"The root means to hold down fast. This word is a holding down turned into a thing owned. To press a piece of land down under your hand is to possess it. God gave Abraham no such holding in the land, not even a foot of ground.","g":"possession","h":"The picture: a hand pressing down to hold ground as your own."},"G2698":{"b":"Built from down and to place, to set a thing down. It means to lay something by, to store it up. Felix laid up favor with the crowd by leaving Paul bound. He was depositing goodwill like coins set aside for later.","g":"lay up, deposit","h":"The picture: setting money aside."},"G2699":{"b":"Built from down and a word meaning to cut. Katatome means a cutting off, mutilation. Paul turns it into a sharp pun against those who trust in circumcision, calling them not the circumcision but the mutilation.","g":"mutilation","h":"The picture: a cutting of the flesh."},"G27":{"b":"This is the passive of agapao, to love. An agapetos is someone who has been loved, the child a father holds dear. So when the voice from heaven calls Jesus my beloved Son, it names him the one on whom the Father's whole love rests.","g":"beloved","h":"The picture: the one held dear."},"G270":{"b":"This word means to reap, to cut down the standing grain and gather it in. James says the pay of the workers who reaped your fields is crying out. You kept back their wages, and God hears it.","g":"reap down","h":"The picture: cutting down the standing grain."},"G2701":{"b":"This is kata, down, plus trecho, to run. The commander in the tower hears the uproar and runs down to the crowd. It is a fast movement from high ground to low. Not marching. Running, on the double, to stop a riot.","g":"run down","h":"The picture: soldiers running down the stairs."},"G2702":{"b":"The word is \"down\" plus \"to carry,\" Strong's \"to bear down.\" To be carried downward, weighed down. Young Eutychus was borne down by deep sleep and fell from the window. It also means to cast a vote, dropping the pebble down into the jar.","g":"sink down, cast","h":"The picture: sleep dragging a man's head down."},"G2703":{"b":"Built from \"down\" and a word meaning to run away, it is fleeing not just from danger but to somewhere safe. Paul and Barnabas ran for refuge to the next towns. Hebrews says we ran this way to lay hold of our hope.","g":"flee","h":"The picture: running hard for a safe place."},"G2704":{"b":"The root means to shrivel or wither, to spoil. With 'down' added it means to spoil completely. Paul speaks of men corrupt in mind. The picture is something once whole now rotted through, shriveled like fruit left too long.","g":"corrupt","h":"The picture: fruit shriveling and rotting."},"G2705":{"b":"Abbott: to kiss fervently, kiss affectionately. It is more than a peck. The father runs and covers the returned son with kisses. Judas uses the same warm word to betray. A kiss pressed down hard, whether for love or for a lie.","g":"kiss earnestly","h":"The picture: a kiss pressed hard."},"G2706":{"b":"Built from down and to think. Abbott-Smith gives to think little of, despise. It pictures thinking down on a person, treating them as worth little. No one can serve two masters, he will despise one.","g":"despise","h":"The picture: looking down on someone."},"G2707":{"b":"The word comes from a root meaning to think against, to hold in low regard. Paul quotes the prophet: look, you despisers, and wonder, for God is doing a work you would never believe.","g":"despiser","h":"The picture: looking down on something."},"G2708":{"b":"This joins \"down\" to cheo, to pour. Katacheo is to pour a thing down over something. The woman breaks her jar of costly perfume and pours it down over Jesus' head, the whole flask emptied on him at once.","g":"pour","h":"The picture: oil poured down over the head."},"G2709":{"b":"Abbott-Smith traces this to the word for the earth, with down in front. It means under the ground, below the soil. Paul says every knee will bow, in heaven, on earth, and under the earth.","g":"under the earth","h":"The picture: down under the earth."},"G271":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the amethyst was \"regarded as an antidote against drunkenness,\" its name meaning not drunk. Picture a deep purple quartz worn to stay clear-headed at the cup. So amethyst was the twelfth foundation of the city wall.","g":"amethyst","h":"The picture: the purple stone that keeps you sober."},"G2710":{"b":"This joins a word for use with kata for full force. It means to use a thing to the uttermost, to use it up. Paul says use this world without using it up, for its shape is passing away.","g":"misuse","h":"The picture: a thing used all the way up."},"G2711":{"b":"Built from a word for down and a word for breathing gently, like a cool breeze. Abbott says it means to cool. The rich man begged for one wet fingertip to cool his burning tongue.","g":"cool","h":"The picture: a cool touch of water on the tongue."},"G2712":{"b":"Built on the word for an image made for worship, with a prefix piling it high. A place crammed full of statues. Paul's spirit was stirred as he saw Athens packed with idols.","g":"full of idols","h":"The picture: a city stuffed with idols."},"G2715":{"b":"This joins \"down over\" to a word meaning to control. Katexousiazo is to throw your weight down on the people you rule. Jesus says the rulers of the nations do this, but among you it must not be so. The greatest serves.","g":"lord it over","h":"The picture: rulers pressing down on those beneath them."},"G2716":{"b":"Abbott-Smith calls it an emphatic form of the ordinary word for work. He renders it to effect by labour, achieve, work out.\n\nThe force is not in starting. It is in finishing. Labour carried through to a result.","g":"work out, achieve","h":"The picture: working a thing all the way through."},"G2718":{"b":"The word puts \"down\" in front of \"come.\" Strong's says it means to come or go down. Abbott uses it for coming down to port by ship. It is a plain downward move, often from a high place to a low one.","g":"come down","h":"The picture: coming down."},"G2719":{"b":"Strong's says the word means to eat down, to devour. It is not a polite bite. It is gobbling the whole thing. The birds devoured the seed, and greedy men devour widows' houses.","g":"devour","h":"The picture: eating it all the way down."},"G272":{"b":"Built from a word meaning to care, with the not set in front. To ameleo is to not care, to wave a thing off. Jesus tells of guests who neglected the wedding invitation and went off to a field and a shop, Matthew 22:5.","g":"neglect","h":"The picture: waving a thing off."},"G2720":{"b":"The root means to straighten, and to steer a ship. This word asks God to make the path straight, to guide our feet into the way of peace. Like a hand on the tiller holding the boat dead on line.","g":"guide, direct","h":"The picture: steering onto a straight course."},"G2721":{"b":"The parts mean down and stand-upon, so the sense is to rise up against, to bear down and stand over someone. The Jews rose against Paul as one and dragged him before Gallio's seat.","g":"rush upon","h":"The picture: bearing down on a man."},"G2722":{"b":"Strong's says it means to hold down (fast). Whatever you have, you press it down and will not let it go. The same word means to hold someone back, and to keep a truth firmly in memory. A tight grip.","g":"hold fast","h":"The picture: gripping something down tight."},"G2723":{"b":"Strong's puts it in a courtroom. To be a plaintiff, and so to charge someone with an offence.\n\nAbbott-Smith fills in the setting. Most uses happen before a judge. This is not gossip. It is a formal charge.","g":"accuse","h":"The picture: the man who brings the case."},"G2724":{"b":"This word comes from a word for the one who speaks against you in the assembly, the accuser at law. It is a charge laid out loud. What accusation do you bring against this man, Pilate asks the crowd.","g":"accusation","h":"The picture: the finger pointed at you in court."},"G2725":{"b":"Strong's breaks this into against and the town square. It is the person who stands up in the assembly to speak against you at law. Revelation gives this name to Satan, the one always pointing the finger in open court.","g":"accuser","h":"The picture: the man who rises against you in the public square."},"G2726":{"b":"Strong's builds this from \"down\" and the look on a face, the eyes dropped to the ground in shame. James says let your joy turn to this, the downcast face of a person who has finally seen his own sin.","g":"heaviness","h":"The picture: eyes dropped to the ground."},"G2727":{"b":"Strong's: \"to sound down into the ears.\" Abbott's first sense is simply \"to resound.\" The picture is a sound echoing down into someone's ears. From that it means teaching by voice, drilling truth in by word of mouth.","g":"instruct, teach","h":"The picture: sound ringing down into the ears."},"G2728":{"b":"The root is the word for rust, the reddish scale that eats into metal. James says your gold and silver have rusted through, and the rust will testify against you and eat your flesh like fire.","g":"canker, rust","h":"The picture: rust eating into metal."},"G2729":{"b":"The root is to have force, raw strength. The kata means down. Together it is to overpower, to press a thing down by force. Jesus says the gates of death will not overpower his church. They push with all their strength and still cannot force it down.","g":"overpower","h":"The picture: forcing something down by strength."},"G273":{"b":"Built from a word for not and a word meaning to blame. No one can lay a finger on this person, no fault to point at. Zechariah and Elizabeth walked so, blameless in the commandments. Nothing to accuse.","g":"blameless","h":"The picture: no finger can point at you."},"G2730":{"b":"Not camping. Strong's reads it as to house permanently. Abbott-Smith gives to settle, dwell.\n\nIt is the word used of the fullness of God settling in Christ, and of Christ settling in a person's heart.","g":"dwell, settle","h":"The picture: moving in for good."},"G2731":{"b":"The root means to house permanently, to settle down and live somewhere. This is that dwelling place. In Mark 5:3 the tormented man's home is among the tombs, and no one can bind him even with chains.","g":"dwelling","h":"The picture: the place a man settles to live."},"G2732":{"b":"The root means to house permanently, to settle down and reside for good. A katoiketerion is a settled dwelling place. Paul says you are being built together into a permanent home for God, made by his Spirit.","g":"dwelling place","h":"The picture: a permanent home."},"G2733":{"b":"This is a dwelling, a place where people settle down and live. Not passing through but staying. God fixed both the times and the homelands of every people, where each would live.","g":"dwelling","h":"The picture: the settled home."},"G2734":{"b":"The word is built on the word for a mirror. Abbott-Smith says to see oneself mirrored, or to reflect as a mirror. Paul says we gaze at the Lord's glory and are changed into the same reflection.","g":"behold in a mirror","h":"The picture: your own face looking back from a mirror."},"G2735":{"b":"This comes from orthos, upright, standing straight. The word means something made fully straight, a wrong put right. Tertullus flatters the governor for the good order he has set up. The image is a crooked thing pulled straight, lifted to stand upright again.","g":"worthy deed","h":"The picture: something set fully upright."},"G2736":{"b":"This means down, downwards, below. Abbott points to the temple curtain torn from the top clear to the bottom. A plain direction word that marks the moment the way inside was opened.","g":"down","h":"The picture: torn from top to bottom."},"G2737":{"b":"This comes from the word for downwards. It means lower, and Paul writes of the lower parts of the earth, the depths Christ went down into before he rose above all the heavens.","g":"lower","h":"The picture: the ground down below."},"G2738":{"b":"From a word meaning to set on fire. Strong's calls it a burn, a glow. So this is heat you feel on the skin, the scorch of fire or sun. Revelation uses it of the sun's scorching.","g":"heat","h":"The picture: the scorch of heat."},"G2739":{"b":"The root is a burn, a scorching glow. This verb means to scorch up. In the parable the young plants on rocky ground are scorched when the sun rises, because they have no root. The heat burns what could not dig deep.","g":"scorch","h":"The picture: scorched by the sun."},"G274":{"b":"The root means not to be blamed, a life with no fault anyone can name. Paul prays your whole spirit, soul and body be kept blamelessly until Christ comes. Picture an inspector walking around you and finding nothing to charge.","g":"blamelessly","h":"The picture: no finger pointed at you."},"G2740":{"b":"The root means to set on fire. This word is the burning itself. Ground that grows thorns and briers is worthless, near to being cursed, and its end is to be burned off in the fire.","g":"burning","h":"The picture: the field set to the fire."},"G2741":{"b":"The root is burning, a fever's heat. So this means to burn with fierce heat. Peter uses it of the last day, when the heavens burn and melt. Picture heat fierce enough to dissolve metal.","g":"burn with heat","h":"The picture: heat fierce enough to melt metal."},"G2742":{"b":"The root means to set on fire. This is burning heat, and Abbott says it is also the sirocco, the hot dry wind off the desert. The laborers complain they bore the burden and the scorching heat of the day. It withers grass and skin alike.","g":"scorching heat","h":"The picture: the burning heat of the day."},"G2743":{"b":"From kaio, to set on fire, this means to brand with a hot iron, searing the skin until it feels nothing. Paul says such liars have a conscience seared as with a hot iron, gone numb to wrong.","g":"seared","h":"The picture: flesh seared with a hot iron."},"G2744":{"b":"Strong's says the word works in a good or a bad sense. Abbott says that in the Greek Old Testament it carries joyous exultation.\n\nSo boasting in the Lord is closer to cheering than to showing off.","g":"boast, glory","h":"The picture: a shout, not a brag."},"G2745":{"b":"The root is to boast, to vaunt. The -ma ending makes kauchēma the thing boasted in, the ground or matter of glorying, the trophy you hold up. Paul makes his converts his kauchēma, lifted up on the last day. Boast only, he says, in the cross.","g":"boasting","h":"The picture: the trophy you hold up."},"G2746":{"b":"Same root, to boast, but this ending names the act, a boasting, glorying, the bragging as it happens. Paul asks where boasting has gone. Faith shuts its mouth, kauchēsis is excluded. When it is right, he says, it turns outward, my glorying is in the Lord.","g":"boasting","h":"The picture: the bragging as it happens."},"G2747":{"b":"This is the name of a harbor town, a port of Corinth, where Paul cut his hair for a vow. Strong's only guesses at the origin. So there is no sure meaning behind it to picture. A place.","flat":1,"g":"Cenchreae","h":"No picture."},"G2748":{"b":"The name means dusky place, dark and shadowy. It comes from a word meaning to be ashy or dim. The Kidron was a brook Jesus crossed on the night he was betrayed.","g":"Kidron","h":"The picture: a dusky place."},"G2749":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives two examples side by side. An infant in Luke 2:12 and a dead body in Matthew 28:6.\n\nThe manger and the tomb use the same word. Something placed, not moving.","g":"lie, be laid","h":"The picture: laid down and left there."},"G275":{"b":"This is \"not\" joined to merimna, anxious care, the worry that pulls the mind in pieces. Amerimnos means free of it, untroubled. The soldiers are told to spread a lie, and the priests promise to keep them out of trouble with the governor.","g":"without care","h":"The picture: a mind with no weight of worry on it."},"G2750":{"b":"The old sense of this word is a bed-cord, the strips that laced a wooden bed. In the plural it means the bands wound round a body for burial. Lazarus walks out of the tomb still tied in them, hand and foot.","g":"graveclothes","h":"The picture: the cords that lace a bed frame."},"G2751":{"b":"This means to shear, \"to cut short the hair, shear\" a sheep. Abbott points to Isaiah, the lamb dumb before its shearer, and the Ethiopian reads that verse. It is also used of a man cutting off his hair to keep a vow.","g":"shear","h":"The picture: shearing the wool off a sheep."},"G2752":{"b":"The root means to order by word, to hail. A keleuma is the loud shout of command, the cry that sets men moving all at once. Paul says the Lord will come down from heaven with such a shout.","g":"shout, command","h":"The picture: the shouted word of command."},"G2753":{"b":"Abbott-Smith explains it as to urge on, bid by word of mouth. Spoken, not written. Nobody sends a note.\n\nHe adds it is mostly used of someone in authority. In Acts it is usually the Romans.","g":"command, order","h":"The picture: an order shouted out."},"G2754":{"b":"This comes from the word for empty glorying, empty and glory joined. Kenodoxia is glory over what is empty, praising yourself for nothing. Paul says do nothing from this empty conceit.","g":"vainglory","h":"The picture: puffed up over nothing."},"G2755":{"b":"This word is built from two others, empty and glory. The first, kenos, means empty. A conceited man is puffed up with glory that has nothing inside it. He struts over what is not there. Paul warns against it.","g":"conceited","h":"The picture: puffed up over nothing."},"G2756":{"b":"Strong's gives one word. Empty. Abbott-Smith points to a pit with nothing in it.\n\nFrom there it goes everywhere. Empty words. Empty faith. Empty-handed men sent back from the vineyard with nothing.","g":"empty, vain","h":"The picture: an empty jar."},"G2757":{"b":"This word joins empty with the word for a sound or voice. It is empty noise, words that make a sound but carry nothing, like a drum with nothing inside. Paul tells Timothy to avoid it. Talk that fills the air and says nothing at all.","g":"empty talk","h":"The picture: an empty drum."},"G2758":{"b":"The root simply means empty. This verb is to make empty, to pour out until nothing is left. Paul uses it of Christ, who emptied himself. The picture is a vessel turned over and drained down to the bottom.","g":"make empty","h":"The picture: pouring a jar out empty."},"G2759":{"b":"The root means \"to prick.\" A kentron is the sharp point, a bee's sting or the ox-goad, the spiked stick that jabs a beast forward. Where is your sting, death. And to Saul, hard to kick against the goads.","g":"sting, goad","h":"The picture: the sharp point that jabs a beast."},"G276":{"b":"This word joins \"not\" with a word meaning to move something from its place, to transfer it. So it is what cannot be shifted, unchangeable. Hebrews says God's purpose is immutable, backed by an oath. Two things that cannot be moved, so we can hold on hard.","g":"unchangeable","h":"The picture: what cannot be moved from its place."},"G2760":{"b":"This is a Latin word carried straight into Greek. It names the captain of one hundred soldiers. He is the one standing at the cross who, watching Jesus die, says truly this man was the Son of God.","g":"centurion","h":"The picture: the officer over a hundred men."},"G2761":{"b":"The root is the word for empty, like a jar with nothing in it. So to speak this way is to speak into thin air, words with nothing behind them. James says Scripture does not say anything emptily like that.","g":"in vain","h":"The picture: an empty jar."},"G2762":{"b":"The root is a horn. This word is a little horn, the tiny stroke that tells one Hebrew letter from another, the hook that makes one letter not its lookalike. Jesus says not one little horn will pass from the law until all is done. The smallest mark counts.","g":"a tittle","h":"The picture: the little horn on a letter."},"G2763":{"b":"This is a potter, the man who shapes wet clay into pots. The root is earthenware. The chief priests used Judas' returned silver to buy the potter's field, the ground where he dug his clay, and made it a burial place for strangers.","g":"potter","h":"The picture: the potter shaping wet clay."},"G2764":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this means \"earthen.\" It comes from the word for earthenware, a tile or pot baked from clay. Picture a potter's jar, easy to shatter. So the nations are broken to pieces like a clay pot.","g":"made of clay","h":"The picture: a clay pot."},"G2765":{"b":"The root is the word for baked clay, the stuff of tiles and pots. This is a jar made of it. Jesus tells the disciples to follow a man carrying one of water, and he will lead them to the upper room.","g":"jar, pitcher","h":"The picture: a clay jar of water."},"G2766":{"b":"Strong's says this is earthenware, a tile. It starts as potter's clay mixed with water, then baked hard. In Luke, men pulled these tiles off a roof to lower a paralyzed friend down through the gap to Jesus.","g":"tile","h":"The picture: a baked clay roof tile."},"G2767":{"b":"The word means to mix, mostly of watering down wine to pour a drink. You blend the two in the cup. Revelation turns it dark. God's wrath is poured full strength, mixed unmixed, into the cup. A drink made ready for the one who must swallow it.","g":"to mix, pour out","h":"The picture: mixing the wine in the cup."},"G2768":{"b":"This word means a horn, like the horn of an animal. Abbott-Smith notes it stands as a symbol of strength. The Bible calls the Savior a horn of salvation, a raised horn of power to rescue.","g":"horn","h":"The picture: an animal's horn."},"G2769":{"b":"This word comes from the word for a horn, and means a little horn, then the curved carob pods shaped like one. The starving son longed to fill his belly with the pods the pigs were eating, and no one gave him anything.","g":"husk","h":"The picture: the little horn-shaped carob pods."},"G277":{"b":"The root means to stir something to another place, to shift it. Put not in front and it cannot be moved. Abbott-Smith says immovable, firm. Paul wants believers planted like that, steadfast, never shaken loose.","g":"immovable","h":"The picture: a stone that will not budge."},"G2770":{"b":"Abbott says it means to make profit, get gain, the merchant's word for coming out ahead on a deal. So when Jesus asks what it profits to gain the whole world and lose your soul, he is doing the math on the worst trade ever made.","g":"to gain","h":"The picture: coming out ahead on a trade."},"G2771":{"b":"This word means gain, especially money, the profit that ends up in your hand. Paul takes the accountant's word and flips it. What things were gain to me, he says, I counted as loss for Christ.","g":"gain","h":"The picture: money in the hand."},"G2772":{"b":"The root means to shear or cut. Abbott says it first meant a slice, then a small coin, a bit clipped off. Jesus poured out the coins of the money changers and overturned their tables. The small change scattered on the floor.","g":"money, coin","h":"The picture: a small slice of metal."},"G2773":{"b":"From a word for a small coin. A kermatistes is a handler of coins, a money changer. Picture the man at his table sorting little bits of metal. Jesus found them in the temple and drove them out.","g":"money changer","h":"The picture: coins sorted on the table."},"G2774":{"b":"This comes straight from the word for head. The main point of a thing is its head, the top of it. It also means a sum of money, the head total. Paul's citizenship, someone says, was bought with a large sum.","g":"sum, main point","h":"The picture: the head of the matter."},"G2775":{"b":"The word is built from the word for the head. Elsewhere it means to bring to a head, to sum up. But in Mark 12:4 it means to strike the head, as the tenants beat the vineyard owner's second servant on the head and send him away shamed.","g":"wound the head","h":"The picture: a blow to the head."},"G2776":{"b":"Strong's says the head is the part most readily taken hold of, and links the word to seizing. Abbott gives no origin, so this rests on Strong's alone.\n\nThe plain meaning is safe. The head.","g":"head","h":"The picture: the part you grab first."},"G2777":{"b":"This is a little head, the knob at the end of the stick a scroll was rolled on. It came to mean the roll itself. In the roll of the book it is written of me, Christ says.","g":"scroll, volume","h":"The picture: the knob on the end of the scroll."},"G2778":{"b":"This is a Latin word carried into Greek. It began as the census, the head count, and became the poll-tax paid because you were on the list. When they ask Jesus whether to pay the kensos to Caesar, they mean this hated head-tax.","g":"tribute, tax","h":"The picture: the coin you owe just for being counted."},"G2779":{"b":"This word just means a garden, a plot of ground planted and tended. A man sowed a mustard seed in his garden and it grew into a tree. There was a garden where Jesus was laid in the tomb. A real, walled patch of growing things.","g":"garden","h":"The picture: a garden."},"G278":{"b":"The a in front means not. The root means to care afterwards, to regret. So God's gifts and calling are things he never looks back on with regret. Once given, they are not reached for again.","g":"without repentance","h":"The picture: the gift never reached for again."},"G2780":{"b":"This word joins garden and watcher. It means the one who tends and guards a garden. On Easter morning Mary saw the risen Jesus and thought he was this man, the gardener, and asked where he had laid the body.","g":"gardener","h":"The picture: the man who watches over the garden."},"G2782":{"b":"Abbott: \"that which is cried by a herald, a proclamation.\" It is the message a herald shouts out in the open for all to hear. In the New Testament it becomes the preaching of the gospel.","g":"preaching","h":"The picture: a herald's cry in the square."},"G2783":{"b":"The root kerusso means to herald, to cry out as a public crier. A keryx is that crier, the man who stands and shouts the king's message so all can hear. Paul calls himself a herald of the gospel, a voice sent to proclaim it.","g":"herald, preacher","h":"The picture: the town crier."},"G2784":{"b":"Strong's says the word means to herald, as a public crier. Abbott-Smith agrees: to be a herald, to proclaim.\n\nA crier does not explain the king's news or argue for it. He announces it out loud.","g":"preach, proclaim","h":"The picture: the town crier."},"G2785":{"b":"Strong's calls this a huge fish, gaping open for prey, its mouth like a chasm. This is the great fish that swallowed Jonah. Jesus points to it as a sign. Picture a sea monster's jaws yawning wide.","g":"huge fish","h":"The picture: the sea monster's gaping jaws."},"G2786":{"b":"Strong's calls it \"the Rock,\" a surname of Peter. It is an Aramaic word Jesus used for Simon. Not a soft or pretty name. A rock. That is what Jesus chose to call him.","g":"Cephas, Peter","h":"The picture: the Rock."},"G2787":{"b":"Abbott says it plainly: a wooden box or chest. Not a ship. The same word covers Noah's great box that floated and the gold chest that held the covenant. Under the grand word ark is a plain wooden container built to keep something safe.","g":"ark, box","h":"The picture: a wooden box."},"G2788":{"b":"This is simply a lyre, the stringed harp of the ancient world. Its origins are unknown, but the thing itself is plain, an instrument held and plucked. In Revelation the saints hold these harps before the throne of God.","g":"harp","h":"The picture: a harp."},"G2789":{"b":"The root is the lyre, a stringed instrument. To kitharizo is to play it. Paul says even a flute or a harp must give clear, distinct notes, or no one can tell what tune is being played.","g":"play the harp","h":"The picture: fingers on the lyre strings."},"G279":{"b":"Built from not and metanoeo, to change the mind. Abbott gives impenitent. Paul warns that an ametanoetos heart stores up wrath for the day of judgment. The word is a will dug in, refusing to face the other way.","g":"impenitent","h":"The picture: a heart that will not turn around."},"G2790":{"b":"Two words joined, a lyre and a singer. So this is the harper, the one who plays the strings and sings along with them. John hears them like harpers playing before the throne. Picture hands on the strings, voice raised.","g":"harper","h":"The picture: hands on the lyre strings."},"G2791":{"b":"This is just the name of Cilicia, a region of Asia Minor. Strong's says it is probably of foreign origin. It is a place on the map, with nothing behind the name to picture.","flat":1,"g":"Cilicia","h":"No picture."},"G2792":{"b":"The word means cinnamon, borrowed from Phoenician traders. Abbott-Smith gives \"cinnamon.\" Picture curls of fragrant reddish bark. So cinnamon is among the spices Babylon can no longer sell.","g":"cinnamon","h":"The picture: rolls of cinnamon bark."},"G2793":{"b":"Built from the word for danger. Abbott gives to be in danger. Picture the boat on the lake filling with water as Jesus slept in the stern, and the disciples kindyneuo, in real peril of drowning, Luke 8:23.","g":"be in danger","h":"The picture: the swamping boat."},"G2794":{"b":"This simply means danger or peril. Strong's calls its background \"of uncertain derivation.\" Abbott adds no origin. The word names the risk but hides nothing to picture.","flat":1,"g":"danger","h":"No picture."},"G2795":{"b":"Abbott: \"to set in motion, move.\" Strong's: \"to stir.\" It is moving a thing from its place, shaking the head, stirring up a crowd. At the cross the passers-by wagged their heads with this word.","g":"move, stir","h":"The picture: setting a thing in motion."},"G2797":{"b":"The name means a bow, as for shooting. It comes from a word meaning to set a trap or snare. Kish was the father of Saul, Israel's first king.","g":"Kish","h":"The picture: a bow."},"G2798":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this first meant a young tender shoot broken off for grafting. Then it came to mean a branch. Paul uses it for branches broken off a tree and others grafted in.","g":"branch","h":"The picture: a shoot snapped off to be grafted."},"G2799":{"b":"Abbott says this covers any loud expression of pain or sorrow. Strong's sets it against a quieter word for crying silently.\n\nThis is not a tear on the cheek. It is the sound the neighbours hear.","g":"weep, wail","h":"The picture: crying out loud."},"G28":{"b":"The origin of this name is uncertain, perhaps foreign, and no clear meaning can be recovered. Hagar was the Egyptian servant of Sarah and the mother of Ishmael.","flat":1,"g":"Hagar","h":"No picture."},"G280":{"b":"The a means not, and the root is a measure, a measuring rod or line. Ametros is without measure, past all bounds. Paul refuses to boast beyond measure, staying within the line God himself marked out for him.","g":"without measure","h":"The picture: no measuring line, no limit."},"G2800":{"b":"The root means to break, and specially to break bread. Abbott says \"a breaking.\" The two from Emmaus knew Jesus in this, the moment he took the loaf and broke it. The snap of bread pulled in two.","g":"breaking","h":"The picture: bread broken apart in the hands."},"G2801":{"b":"Abbott-Smith builds it from the verb to break. It is a piece broken off. After Jesus fed the crowds, the disciples gathered the broken pieces that were left over.","g":"fragment, piece","h":"The picture: a broken-off piece of bread."},"G2802":{"b":"This is a place name, Cauda or Clauda, a small island south of Crete. The ship ran under it for brief shelter from the gale. Its origin is uncertain and the name holds no meaning to open, so there is only the island to see.","flat":1,"g":"Clauda","h":"No picture."},"G2803":{"b":"Claudia is a Roman name, the feminine of Claudius. She sends greetings at the close of Second Timothy. The sources give no meaning behind the name, only a Roman household label carried by one of the believers.","flat":1,"g":"Claudia","h":"No picture."},"G2804":{"b":"This is a Roman name, Claudius, borne by an emperor. It comes over from Latin. A name resting on a person, with no picture inside the word itself for us to see.","flat":1,"g":"Claudius","h":"No picture."},"G2805":{"b":"The root means to wail aloud, not to cry quietly. So this is loud weeping. Jesus pairs it with the gnashing of teeth in the outer dark. Grief that everyone can hear.","g":"weeping","h":"The picture: weeping out loud."},"G2806":{"b":"This word means to break, especially bread. Strong's calls it a primary verb, so it does not come from anything else. The breaking of bread is its plain meaning, with no hidden image.","flat":1,"g":"break bread","h":"No picture."},"G2807":{"b":"From a word meaning to shut. A kleis is the key that turns a lock. I give you the keys of the kingdom. He holds the keys of death and Hades. What it locks stays locked, what it opens stays open.","g":"key","h":"The picture: a key in a lock."},"G2808":{"b":"Strong's says this is a primary verb, which means it does not come from anything else. It just means to shut or close. There is nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"shut","h":"No picture."},"G2809":{"b":"The word comes from a verb meaning to filch. Abbott-Smith gives \"a thing stolen,\" and then plainly theft. Picture something snatched and hidden away. So even after the plagues, the people would not repent of their thefts.","g":"theft","h":"The picture: goods carried off by a thief."},"G2810":{"b":"Strong's traces the name to a word for renown and a word for a father. A father of renown, a name spoken with honor. Cleopas was one of the two who walked the Emmaus road and did not know Jesus at first.","g":"Cleopas","h":"The picture: a father whose name is called with honor."},"G2811":{"b":"Strong's ties this to being called, your name spoken from mouth to mouth until it spreads as fame. Peter says there is no glory in taking a beating for doing wrong. Endure suffering for doing right, and that report is glory.","g":"glory","h":"The picture: your name called out from mouth to mouth."},"G2812":{"b":"Trench's note pins it down. Not the robber who plunders openly with violence, but a thief who steals in secret, by fraud and cunning. So when the day of the Lord comes like a thief, the point is you will not hear it coming.","g":"thief","h":"The picture: the one who steals in secret."},"G2813":{"b":"This word means to steal. Strong's calls it a primary verb, so it does not come from anything else. It names the act plainly, with no picture behind it.","flat":1,"g":"steal","h":"No picture."},"G2814":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to break, and Strong's calls it \"a limb or shoot (as if broken off).\" It is a vine-branch, the green shoot that snaps easily from the stem. Jesus says he is the vine and we are these branches, useless once broken off.","g":"branch","h":"The picture: a vine-shoot snapped off the stem."},"G2815":{"b":"This is a man's name, Clement. Strong's says it is Latin and means merciful. It is only a name, with nothing to picture. Paul counts him among his fellow workers whose names are in the book of life.","flat":1,"g":"Clement (name)","h":"No picture."},"G2816":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is to receive by lot.\n\nSo an inheritance is not earned and not chosen. It falls to you. The New Testament uses it for the kingdom, for the land, and for eternal life.","g":"inherit","h":"The picture: a share drawn by lot."},"G2817":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is an inherited property, an inheritance, land handed down in the family. The root pictures a share given by lot. The wicked tenants kill the heir to grab the klēronomia. Peter says ours is being kept safe in heaven.","g":"inheritance","h":"The picture: land handed down in the family."},"G2818":{"b":"Strong's says an heir is a sharer by lot. In old times the inheritance was divided by casting lots, and each got his portion. The heir is the one who receives his allotted share. Christians are called heirs of God.","g":"heir","h":"The picture: a share handed out by lot."},"G2819":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it is a lot, that which is cast or drawn. Strong's mentions bits of wood used to decide chances. Your lot is what falls to you, and so it also means your share or inheritance.","g":"lot, share","h":"The picture: the lot that gets cast."},"G282":{"b":"This is the word for mother with 'not' in front. Greek writers used it of the gods, born of no mother. Here it means Melchizedek, who enters the story with no mother listed in his line.","g":"without mother","h":"The picture: no mother's name in the record."},"G2820":{"b":"The root is the word for a die for drawing chances, a lot. Abbott-Smith says kleroo means to cast lots and to assign by lot. A share falls to you the way a lot falls. In Christ believers were given their portion.","g":"assign by lot","h":"The picture: drawing lots."},"G2821":{"b":"Strong's says the word means an invitation. Abbott-Smith says in the New Testament it is always the divine call to salvation. God does not only command. He invites, your name called out and a seat kept for you.","g":"calling, invitation","h":"The picture: an invitation."},"G2822":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means called or invited, as to a banquet. It comes from the word to call. The called are the invited ones, the names read off the list, welcomed in to belong to God.","g":"called, invited","h":"The picture: on the guest list."},"G2823":{"b":"A klibanos is an earthen vessel for baking bread, a clay oven. Dry grass and stubble were stuffed in to fire it. Jesus says the wild grass is alive today and thrown into the oven tomorrow, burned as fuel. Yet God clothes it. How much more will he clothe you.","g":"an oven","h":"The picture: the clay oven fired with dry grass."},"G2824":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is a slope, especially the slope of the earth from the equator to the pole. Our word climate comes from it. That tilt of land came to mean a region. Paul speaks of the regions of Syria.","g":"region","h":"The picture: the slope of the earth."},"G2825":{"b":"Abbott-Smith builds it from a word meaning to lean or recline. So it is the thing you lie down on, a bed or couch. Jesus tells the paralyzed man to take up his bed and walk.","g":"bed, couch","h":"The picture: the thing you lie down on."},"G2826":{"b":"The ending makes it small, a little couch. Strong's calls it a pallet. This is the mat the paralyzed man is lowered on through the roof, and the same one he picks up and carries home when Jesus heals him.","g":"little bed","h":"The picture: a little bed you can carry."},"G2827":{"b":"This word means to make to bend, to bow. Jesus bowed his head with it as he died. The Son of Man has nowhere to lay his head to rest. It is also the day that declines toward evening. Something tipping over, sloping down.","g":"incline, recline","h":"The picture: the head bowing down."},"G2828":{"b":"This word comes from the word to recline. Abbott-Smith gives it as a company lying down together to eat. Jesus told the disciples to sit the crowd down in groups of about fifty before he broke the loaves and the fish.","g":"company","h":"The picture: people reclining in groups to eat."},"G2829":{"b":"The root is klepto, to steal, and it carries the sense of doing it on the sly. Klope is theft, taking by stealth what belongs to someone else. Jesus lists it among the things that come out of a person and make them unclean.","g":"theft","h":"The picture: something slipped away when no one looks."},"G283":{"b":"The root means to sully or taint, to contaminate. With \"not\" in front, this word is untainted, undefiled. The inheritance kept in heaven is this, Peter says, unstained and past all spoiling. Marriage is to be kept undefiled.","g":"undefiled","h":"The picture: not a spot of dirt on it."},"G2830":{"b":"Strong's calls this \"a surge of the sea.\" Abbott ties it to a word for the sea washing over. It is water piled up and driven by wind. James says the doubter is like this, tossed and never still.","g":"wave, surge","h":"The picture: the sea heaving up into a wave."},"G2831":{"b":"The root is a surge of the sea. This word means to be tossed like waves. Paul says the immature are thrown back and forth like a small boat on rough water, carried off by every new teaching.","g":"tossed about","h":"The picture: tossed on the waves."},"G2832":{"b":"Clopas is an Aramaic name, borne by the husband of one of the Marys who stood at the cross. The sources give it no meaning to picture. It is a bare personal name, remembered only for the woman tied to it.","flat":1,"g":"Clopas","h":"No picture."},"G2833":{"b":"This means to scratch, and so to tickle or itch. Paul says people gather teachers to suit their own desires, having itching ears. The picture is an ear that itches and wants scratching. They pick teachers who scratch it.","g":"itching","h":"The picture: scratching an itch."},"G2834":{"b":"This is a place name, Cnidus, a city on the southwest tip of Asia Minor. The ship sailed slowly and came off it before the wind forced a change of course. The name is likely foreign, with no meaning we can see, so there is nothing to picture.","flat":1,"g":"Cnidus","h":"No picture."},"G2835":{"b":"A kodrantes was a Roman coin, the fourth part of an as, one of the smallest pieces of money there was. Jesus says you will not get out of prison until you have paid the last kodrantes. Down to the tiniest coin. The whole debt, nothing forgiven.","g":"a small coin","h":"The picture: the smallest coin."},"G2836":{"b":"Abbott-Smith traces it to the word for hollow. That is all it means. The empty space inside a body.\n\nSo it covers the stomach and the womb with one word, and John 7:38 uses it for the heart.","g":"belly, womb","h":"The picture: a hollow inside."},"G2837":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives the active sense first. To lull to sleep, put to sleep. In the New Testament it is nearly always passive. To fall asleep.\n\nMost of its uses are about death, spoken of as sleep.","g":"sleep, die","h":"The picture: being put to sleep."},"G2838":{"b":"This word means a sleeping, a resting. When Jesus said Lazarus had fallen asleep, the disciples thought he meant ordinary rest, lying down to recover. The word underneath is the plain word for sleep. That is why they misheard him.","g":"sleeping, rest","h":"The picture: lying down to rest."},"G2839":{"b":"Strong's says the word means shared by all. The first believers held everything common. The same word then came to mean unclean, what is ordinary and unhallowed rather than set apart for God.","g":"common, unclean","h":"The picture: what everyone shares."},"G284":{"b":"The name means people of liberality, a generous people. It joins a word for a people gathered as one with a word for willing giving. Amminadab appears in the genealogy of Jesus.","g":"Amminadab","h":"The picture: people of liberality."},"G2840":{"b":"Abbott says the word means to make common. To make something common was to make it ordinary, unhallowed, unclean. Jesus said what goes into the mouth does not make a person common.","g":"defile, make common","h":"The picture: making a thing common."},"G2841":{"b":"This means to have a share of, go shares in something with someone. The root is the partner, the one who holds it in common with you. Believers share money and share suffering this way. Not giving from a distance, but having it together.","g":"share","h":"The picture: hands on the same loaf."},"G2842":{"b":"Strong's calls it partnership, and literally participation.\n\nAbbott-Smith shows the range. It is fellowship with the Father and the Son, and it is also the money collected for poor Christians. Sharing is sharing.","g":"fellowship, sharing","h":"The picture: partners in one business."},"G2843":{"b":"This comes from a word for a sharer, a partner. It means someone ready to share what they have. The word behind it is the friend who puts things in the common pot, not the one who guards his own.","g":"willing to share","h":"The picture: holding things in common."},"G2844":{"b":"Strong's says this word means a sharer, an associate. It comes from the word for what is common or shared. A partner is someone who holds a thing in common with you, sharing the same catch or the same work.","g":"partner, sharer","h":"The picture: sharing in common."},"G2845":{"b":"The word comes from lying stretched out, and it means a bed. My children are with me in bed, the man inside says when the friend knocks at midnight. It also stands for the marriage-bed, which Hebrews says must be kept undefiled.","g":"bed","h":"The picture: a bed to lie down on."},"G2846":{"b":"The word comes from a word for a couch or bed. It means a bedroom. The servant set over it, the one 'over the bedchamber,' is the king's chamberlain, Blastus.","g":"chamberlain","h":"The picture: the room where the king's bed stands."},"G2847":{"b":"The root is a kernel of seed. Strong's notes the scarlet dye came from a small insect shaped like a grain, clinging to a tree. That berry-like speck colored the mocking robe they threw on Jesus. A whole red drawn from one little seed.","g":"scarlet","h":"The picture: a tiny grain that dyes cloth red."},"G2848":{"b":"This is one grain, a kernel of seed. The mustard seed, smallest of them all, is this word. Unless a grain of wheat falls into the ground and dies, Jesus says, it stays alone. One tiny seed you could lose between your fingers.","g":"grain, seed","h":"The picture: a single kernel of seed."},"G2849":{"b":"The first meaning is to curtail, dock, prune. A gardener trims the branch so the plant is held in check, not killed. That cutting-back became the word for punishment. To kolazo is to prune the wrongdoer, cut him back, not throw him away.","g":"punish","h":"The picture: pruning a plant back."},"G285":{"b":"This is sand, heaped along the beach. The foolish man built his house on ammos, and when the rain came it slid. Yet the same sand, uncountable on the seashore, pictures a people too many to number.","g":"sand","h":"The picture: sand on the shore."},"G2850":{"b":"This word means flattery, smooth words meant to win someone over. Strong's ties it to a word for one who fawns. It names the thing itself, with no concrete image behind it. Paul says he never came with such words.","flat":1,"g":"flattery","h":"No picture."},"G2851":{"b":"The root, kolazo, properly means to curtail, to lop or prune back. Kolasis is the punishment that follows, first a correction meant to check and cut down. Jesus sets everlasting kolasis against everlasting life at the judgment.","g":"punishment","h":"The picture: the branch cut back."},"G2852":{"b":"The root is the closed fist, the knuckles. To kolaphizo is to punch, to beat with the fists. They spat in Jesus' face and kolaphizo him. Paul speaks of a thorn, a messenger of Satan sent to kolaphizo him, pounding away.","g":"to buffet","h":"The picture: a blow from the closed fist."},"G2853":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this comes from a word for glue. It means to glue or cement together, then to stick fast to something. A man cleaves to his wife, or a person joins to the Lord and holds on.","g":"cleave, join","h":"The picture: glued together."},"G2854":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this was \"an eye salve shaped like a roll,\" named after a small bread roll of the same shape. Picture a thumb of salve you smear on sore eyes. So Christ tells the blind church to buy salve and see.","g":"eyesalve","h":"The picture: a little roll of eye ointment."},"G2855":{"b":"The word comes from a small coin and the rate of exchange. A money-changer sat swapping foreign coins for temple money and taking his cut. These are the tables Jesus turned over, scattering the coins across the temple floor.","g":"money-changer","h":"The picture: coins stacked on the changer's table."},"G2856":{"b":"The word means to dock, to cut off, to amputate, like a tail lopped short. Used of time, it means to chop days off the end. For the sake of the chosen, Jesus says, those terrible days will be cut short.","g":"shorten","h":"The picture: a tail cut short."},"G2857":{"b":"This is a place-name, Colossae, a city in Asia Minor on the river Lycus. It is only the name of a town, with nothing to picture. Paul writes to the believers who live there.","flat":1,"g":"Colossae","h":"No picture."},"G2859":{"b":"This is the chest, and the loose fold of a robe over the belt that served as a pocket. Grain is poured into your bosom, good measure pressed down. The beloved disciple leans on Jesus' chest. Lazarus rests in Abraham's bosom, held close.","g":"bosom","h":"The picture: the fold of a robe against the chest."},"G286":{"b":"This just means a lamb, a young sheep. Abbott notes it is used of Christ and points to Isaiah's picture, the lamb led to the slaughter that does not open its mouth. Behold the Lamb of God.","g":"lamb","h":"The picture: the lamb led to the slaughter."},"G2860":{"b":"Strong's says this means \"to plunge into water.\" Abbott adds to dive, plunge into the sea. It is the swimmer going over the side. In Acts the prisoners who could swim jumped and struck out for the shore.","g":"swim, dive","h":"The picture: a diver plunging into the sea."},"G2861":{"b":"The word for this pool comes from a word that means to plunge into water. It is the diving place, the swimming spot. So the pool where the sick man lay waiting was named for the splash of a body going in.","g":"pool","h":"The picture: a body plunging into the water."},"G2862":{"b":"Strong's calls this a Roman colony for veterans. A colony was land given to retired soldiers, who settled it and held it for Rome. Philippi was such a place, a garrison town of old fighting men, when Paul arrived.","g":"colony","h":"The picture: a town of old soldiers."},"G2863":{"b":"The root is the word for the hair of the head, the locks worn as ornament. To komao is to wear the hair long. Paul says long hair is a woman's glory, given to her as a covering.","g":"long hair","h":"The picture: long flowing hair."},"G2864":{"b":"The word means the hair of the head, the locks worn as an adornment. It pictures long hair falling as a covering. Paul says a woman's long hair is given to her for a glory and a veil.","g":"hair","h":"The picture: long hair as a covering."},"G2865":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means to take care of, and to carry off safe. To receive here is to carry something home unharmed, to get back what is yours and keep it safe. You will carry off the reward.","g":"receive, carry off","h":"The picture: carrying your prize home safe."},"G2866":{"b":"From a word meaning to take care of. The word means well-dressed, elegant, and so, of a sick man, doing finely. The father asked when the boy began to amend, and they said the fever left him at the very hour Jesus spoke.","g":"began to amend","h":"The picture: the sick man looking well again."},"G2867":{"b":"The root is konia, lime or dust. Koniao is to coat a thing white with it. Jesus calls the Pharisees whitewashed tombs, gleaming clean on the outside but full of dead men's bones within. Bright paint over rot.","g":"whitewash","h":"The picture: a tomb painted white with lime."},"G2868":{"b":"The word joins dust and stirring-up, so it means dust kicked into the air. Shake the koniortos off your feet, Jesus told them, when a town will not hear. Leave even their dirt behind you.","g":"dust","h":"The picture: a cloud of dust kicked up."},"G2869":{"b":"The root is hard labor, the kind that wears you down. This word is used of the wind growing weary and abating. When Jesus climbed into the boat the wind ceased, as if it had tired itself out and lay still.","g":"cease","h":"The picture: the wind tiring and dropping."},"G287":{"b":"The root means to exchange or repay. An amoibe is the return you give, a kindness paid back for a kindness received. Paul says children should repay their parents, giving back the care once given to them.","g":"recompense","h":"The picture: the kindness handed back."},"G2870":{"b":"The root means to chop, and then to beat the breast in grief. In Acts the devout men make great lamentation over Stephen, striking their own chests as they weep.","g":"lamentation","h":"The picture: fists beating the breast."},"G2871":{"b":"The root means to chop or strike. This word is a cutting down, a slaughter in battle. Melchizedek met Abraham as he came back from the cutting-down of the kings, and blessed him.","g":"slaughter","h":"The picture: cutting down in battle."},"G2872":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is to grow weary. The tiredness comes first, then the work that caused it.\n\nSo when Jesus says come to me all who labour, he is talking to people who are already worn out.","g":"labour, toil","h":"The picture: worked until you ache."},"G2873":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is a striking, beating. Strong's calls it a cut, and then toil, because it reduces your strength.\n\nAbbott-Smith adds the fine point. This word puts the weight on the tiredness, not on the effort.","g":"toil, weariness","h":"The picture: a beating."},"G2874":{"b":"Strong's just says \"manure.\" Abbott says \"a dung hill.\" It is the heap of dung and refuse outside a house. Jesus says salt gone flat is no use even for that pile. Thrown out entirely.","g":"manure, dunghill","h":"The picture: a pile of manure behind the house."},"G2875":{"b":"Strong's: \"to beat the breast in grief.\" The word first means to strike or cut. Abbott: \"to beat one's breast with grief, to mourn.\" It is the striking of your own chest as you wail aloud for the dead.","g":"mourn, wail","h":"The picture: beating your chest in grief."},"G2876":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives one word: a raven. Consider the ravens, Jesus says. They do not plant or harvest, they have no storehouse or barn, yet God feeds them. You are worth far more than the birds.","g":"raven","h":"The picture: a raven."},"G2877":{"b":"Abbott: \"(dimin. of κόρη)\", a small, fond form of the word for girl. Strong's: \"a (little) girl.\" It is an everyday, affectionate word. Jesus uses it waking the child: little girl, get up.","g":"little girl","h":"The picture: a little girl."},"G2878":{"b":"Korban is a Hebrew word for an offering, a gift set apart and dedicated to God. Jesus rebukes those who tell their parents their money is korban, promised to God, and so refuse to help them. A holy label hiding neglect.","g":"Corban, offering","h":"The picture: a gift labeled given to God."},"G2879":{"b":"The name means ice. Behind it lies a word about being made bald or bare. Korah was the Levite who led a rebellion against Moses and was swallowed by the earth.","g":"Korah","h":"The picture: ice."},"G288":{"b":"Strong's pictures a vine coiling about a support. Abbott-Smith only says vine, so lean on Strong's for the image. The plant clings and climbs on what holds it. Jesus says, I am the vine, you are the branches.","g":"vine","h":"The picture: the vine coiling on its support."},"G2880":{"b":"This means to cram full, to eat until stuffed. It comes from a word for having too much. After many days without food the crew ate their fill, then threw the leftover wheat overboard to lighten the ship. A body crammed and satisfied.","g":"eat enough","h":"The picture: a body stuffed full."},"G2881":{"b":"The word means a Corinthian, a person from the busy trading city of Greece. Luke reports that many Corinthians heard, believed and were baptized. Paul later opens his heart wide to them. Real people in a rough port town.","g":"Corinthian","h":"The picture: the people of Corinth."},"G2882":{"b":"This is Corinth, a busy port city of Greece where Paul stayed and worked, and to whose church he wrote two of his letters. The word is only the name of the city.","flat":1,"g":"Corinth","h":"No picture."},"G2883":{"b":"This is just the name Cornelius, a Roman. It is of Latin origin. It is a man's name and nothing more, with no picture hidden inside it.","flat":1,"g":"Cornelius","h":"No picture."},"G2884":{"b":"A kor is a Hebrew measure, a large unit for grain or oil. Picture the container filled and heaped over. In the parable one debtor owed a hundred of them. It stands for a real amount and a real debt.","g":"a measure","h":"The picture: the heaped grain measure."},"G2885":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is to order, arrange, prepare. Then to adorn. To beautify a thing is to set it in good order. The wise girls used it when they trimmed their lamps and set them right.","g":"adorn, put in order","h":"The picture: setting things in order."},"G2886":{"b":"The root is kosmos, the world. This word means worldly, belonging to this present earth. Titus speaks of turning from worldly desires. Cravings that reach no higher than the dust, tied wholly to the here and now.","g":"worldly","h":"The picture: tied to the dust of this world."},"G2887":{"b":"The root means orderly arrangement, the same word behind cosmetics and cosmos. To be modest here is to be well-ordered, each thing set in its right place. Paul wants believers adorned in orderly dress. Not flashy, but arranged with care.","g":"modest, orderly","h":"The picture: everything in its right place."},"G2888":{"b":"Built from world and a word meaning to use strength, to seize and hold. A kosmokrator is a world-ruler. Paul uses it for the dark powers, the rulers of this present darkness that grip the world.","g":"world ruler","h":"The picture: a fist that grips the world."},"G2889":{"b":"Strong's says this word means orderly arrangement, and so decoration. Abbott-Smith lists order first, then ornament, and points to 1 Peter 3:3, where it means a woman's adornment.\n\nOnly later did it mean the world, as an ordered whole.","g":"world","h":"The picture: a woman putting on her jewellery."},"G289":{"b":"This word joins vine and work. Abbott-Smith gives it as a vinedresser, the man who prunes and tends the plants. When the owner wanted the barren fig tree cut down, the vinedresser begged for one more year to dig around it and feed it.","g":"vine-dresser","h":"The picture: the worker who tends the vines."},"G2890":{"b":"His Latin name means fourth, a number-name like Tertius, third, just before him. Paul calls Quartus simply a brother. Two men named third and fourth, side by side in the same greeting.","g":"Quartus","h":"The picture: the fourth child."},"G2891":{"b":"This is the Aramaic command Jesus spoke, koum, meaning rise, get up. In Mark 5:41, paired with talitha, he says it to the dead girl, little girl, arise, and at once she stands and walks.","g":"cumi, arise","h":"The picture: get up onto your feet."},"G2892":{"b":"This is a Latin word, custodia, a guard of soldiers. Pilate told the priests, take a guard, make the tomb as secure as you can. So they set the watch at the stone. The word is armed men posted to keep watch.","g":"guard","h":"The picture: soldiers posted at the tomb."},"G2893":{"b":"This comes from kouphos, light in weight. It means to lighten, to make light. When they had eaten enough, they threw the wheat into the sea to lighten the ship. The word is the vessel rising in the water as the load is lifted off it.","g":"lighten","h":"The picture: the ship riding higher as weight comes off."},"G2894":{"b":"A kophinos is a basket, likely woven of wicker, the kind a Jew carried food in on a journey. Twelve of them were filled with the scraps after the five thousand ate. A handheld hamper, brimming with what was left over.","g":"basket","h":"The picture: a wicker food-basket."},"G2895":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this is a camp bed, a pallet. Not a fine bed, but the cheap mat a poor man slept on. It is what the healed man rolled up and carried home on his shoulder.","g":"mat, pallet","h":"The picture: a poor man's mat."},"G2896":{"b":"The word copies a sound. Abbott-Smith says it is the croak of a raven, and from there any harsh, wordless cry.\n\nThis is not speech. It is the noise a person makes when words will not do.","g":"cry out","h":"The picture: a raven croaking."},"G2897":{"b":"Strong's calls it a headache from drunkenness, the pain that seizes the skull the morning after. Picture the throbbing head of a hangover. Take heed, Jesus said, that your hearts are not weighed down with drinking, and that day catch you unaware.","g":"surfeiting","h":"The picture: the morning-after headache."},"G2898":{"b":"This word means a skull. It comes from the word for the head. The place they crucified Jesus was called kranion, the Place of a Skull, likely a bare rounded hill that looked like one. The name itself is a picture of death.","g":"skull","h":"The picture: a bare skull on the hill."},"G2899":{"b":"This is the fringe or tassel on the edge of a robe, the knotted threads a Jew wore at the corners of his cloak. The sick woman reached for the kraspedon of Jesus. Just the hem, the very border of his garment.","g":"fringe, hem","h":"The picture: the tassel on a robe's edge."},"G29":{"b":"This is a Persian word for the king's courier system, where anyone could be seized to carry loads or messages. So it means to force someone into service. If a soldier presses you to go one mile, Jesus says, go two. Simon was made to carry the cross.","g":"to compel","h":"The picture: seized to carry a soldier's pack."},"G290":{"b":"Abbott-Smith builds this word straight on the word for a vine. The vine word, made into the place where vines grow.\n\nMost of Jesus' hired workers and rebel tenants are standing in one of these.","g":"vineyard","h":"The picture: a field full of vines."},"G2900":{"b":"The root means vigor, raw strength. This word is strong, mighty. Peter uses it of God's hand, telling them to humble themselves under that mighty hand so it will lift them up in time.","g":"mighty","h":"The picture: sheer strength in a hand."},"G2901":{"b":"The word is built from \"powerful.\" It means to be strengthened, to wax strong, to gain force you did not have. The boy John grew and became strong this way. Be watchful, Paul says, stand firm, be krataioo, strengthened through the Spirit within.","g":"be strengthened","h":"The picture: a child growing strong."},"G2902":{"b":"Strength first. Abbott-Smith's oldest sense is to be strong, mighty, and so to rule.\n\nFrom there it becomes gripping: taking someone by the hand, or laying hold of a man to arrest him. Holding on takes force.","g":"hold fast, seize","h":"The picture: a strong grip."},"G2903":{"b":"The word is the top form of \"strength, might.\" It first meant strongest, mightiest. It became a title of respect, most excellent, the way you address a man of rank. Luke opens his book with it: most excellent Theophilus.","g":"most excellent","h":"The picture: the strongest man in the room."},"G2904":{"b":"Abbott says the word means strength, and especially bodily strength. It is muscle and force. Strong's is unsure of its origin. The great prayers give God this power and dominion forever.","g":"power, might","h":"The picture: raw strength."},"G2905":{"b":"This comes from a word for a loud cry. Abbott-Smith notes it is even used of animals, to bay, to croak. For people it means to shout out loud, as the crowd shouted for Jesus to be crucified.","g":"cry out, shout","h":"The picture: crying out loud."},"G2906":{"b":"The root is a word for the croak of a raven, then any scream. A krauge is a raw shout, not calm speech. Elizabeth lifts it when Mary arrives. Revelation promises that in the end there will be no more of it, no more crying.","g":"outcry","h":"The picture: the croak of a raven."},"G2907":{"b":"Strong's calls this butcher's meat, plain flesh from the market. In Romans it is the meat that may have been offered to idols. Paul says he would give up meat forever rather than trip a brother over it.","g":"meat, flesh","h":"The picture: meat on the butcher's block."},"G2909":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it is properly the comparative of a word meaning strong, though in use it works as the comparative of good.\n\nHebrews leans on it hard. A better covenant, a better hope. Underneath better lies stronger.","g":"better","h":"The picture: the stronger one."},"G291":{"b":"This is a Latin name, a short form of Ampliatus, which meant enlarged. It was a common name for a servant. Paul calls him his beloved in the Lord. There is no picture behind it, just a man he loved.","flat":1,"g":"Amplias","h":"No picture."},"G2910":{"b":"This word means to hang, to suspend. They hanged Jesus on a tree, Peter says. Better a millstone hung round the neck than to trip a little one. On these two commands the whole law hangs, Jesus said, dangling from them like weight on a hook.","g":"hang","h":"The picture: weight suspended from above."},"G2911":{"b":"The root means to hang. A kremnos is a cliff face that seems to hang out over the water below. It is the steep bank where the herd of pigs rushed down and drowned. Ground that falls away sheer under your feet.","g":"steep place","h":"The picture: the cliff that hangs over the drop."},"G2912":{"b":"The word means a Cretan, from the island in the Mediterranean. Paul quotes a Cretan poet against his own people: Cretans are always liars, evil beasts, lazy gluttons. An island, a people, and a reputation Paul does not flinch from naming.","g":"Cretan","h":"The picture: a man from Crete."},"G2913":{"b":"Crescens is a man's name, Latin in origin, and Paul notes he had gone to Galatia. The name carries the sense of growing, but here it is only a name. There is no picture to draw from it.","flat":1,"g":"Crescens","h":"No picture."},"G2914":{"b":"Crete is a place, an island in the Mediterranean sea. The name comes from nowhere the sources can trace. It is just what people called the island. There is nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"Crete","h":"No picture."},"G2915":{"b":"The word means barley, the cheap grain the poor ate. Abbott-Smith notes it usually comes in the plural. Picture rough barley heads in the field, worth less than wheat. So in the famine, three measures of barley cost a whole day's wage.","g":"barley","h":"The picture: grains of barley."},"G2916":{"b":"The root is simply barley, the poor man's grain. Abbott says \"of barley.\" The boy's five loaves that Jesus multiplies are this kind, cheap barley bread, not fine wheat. From that small, plain lunch he feeds thousands.","g":"of barley","h":"The picture: coarse loaves of barley bread."},"G2917":{"b":"Abbott-Smith calls this the issue of a judicial process. Not the trial. The result of the trial.\n\nHe adds it can also mean the lawsuit itself, which is how Paul uses it when Christians drag each other to court.","g":"judgment, verdict","h":"The picture: the verdict read out."},"G2918":{"b":"A krinon is a lily, a wildflower of the fields. Jesus says look at the lilies, how they grow. They do not work or spin thread, yet not even Solomon in all his glory was dressed like one of them. God clothes the grass. He will clothe you.","g":"a lily","h":"The picture: wild lilies in the field."},"G2919":{"b":"Strong's says the word properly means to distinguish, and so to decide. Abbott-Smith's first sense is to separate, select, choose.\n\nSo judging starts as sorting. Only later does it harden into condemning and punishing.","g":"judge, decide","h":"The picture: telling one thing apart from another."},"G292":{"b":"Strong's says the word means to ward off, and so to protect. In Acts, Moses sees his countryman being beaten and steps in to defend him, striking the Egyptian down.","g":"defend","h":"The picture: pushing away the blow."},"G2920":{"b":"Sorting comes before sentencing. Abbott-Smith's first sense is a seperating, selection.\n\nJudgment in this word is the act of dividing one thing from another. Only later does it mean the verdict, or the court that hands it down.","g":"judgment","h":"The picture: sorting things into piles."},"G2921":{"b":"This is the Latin name Crispus, and Strong's notes it means crisp, that is curly, the nickname of a man with curling hair. Beyond that it is simply the ruler of the synagogue at Corinth who believed and was baptized.","g":"Crispus","h":"The picture: curly hair."},"G2922":{"b":"The root is krites, a judge. Abbott's second sense is a tribunal, the court where judging is done. Paul asks whether the saints, who will judge the world, are unfit to settle the smallest cases dragged before such courts.","g":"tribunal","h":"The picture: the judgment court."},"G2923":{"b":"From krino, to judge, decide. A krites is the judge himself, the one who hears the case and hands down the verdict. So God the krites of all, and Christ the krites of living and dead, is the one seated to give the final ruling no one can appeal.","g":"judge","h":"The picture: the judge on the bench."},"G2924":{"b":"This comes from the word for a judge. It means able to judge and tell apart. God's word sits like a judge over the heart, weighing and sorting the thoughts and the intentions.","g":"discerner","h":"The picture: the judge who weighs it."},"G2925":{"b":"This just means to knock or rap, especially at a door. Strong's calls it apparently a primary verb, so nothing older lies behind it. Knock, and it will be opened to you.","flat":1,"g":"knock","h":"No picture."},"G2926":{"b":"This word comes from the word for hidden. Abbott-Smith gives it as a cellar, a crypt, a place tucked out of sight. No one lights a lamp and hides it in a cellar, Jesus says. You set it up high so everyone coming in sees the light.","g":"cellar, secret","h":"The picture: a dark cellar under the floor."},"G2927":{"b":"This is the adjective built on the verb for hiding, which Strong's explains as covering.\n\nAbbott-Smith lists the phrase in secret, used of giving and praying, and also the hidden person of the heart.","g":"hidden, secret","h":"The picture: kept under cover."},"G2928":{"b":"Strong's is specific. To conceal, properly by covering.\n\nAbbott-Smith lists the treasure hidden in the field and the city that cannot be hidden. The action is not moving the thing. It is putting something over it.","g":"hide","h":"The picture: putting a cover over it."},"G2929":{"b":"The word comes from the word for ice or rock crystal. Abbott-Smith gives \"to shine like crystal, be crystal-clear.\" Picture a stone as clear as frozen water. So the holy city shone like jasper, crystal-clear.","g":"clear as crystal","h":"The picture: clear ice you can see through."},"G293":{"b":"The parts mean to throw around. So this is the round net a fisherman flings out, spreading wide before it drops on the fish. Peter and Andrew were casting one when Jesus called them. Picture a net thrown, opening in the air.","g":"fishing net","h":"The picture: the casting-net thrown wide."},"G2930":{"b":"The word comes from frost. It first meant ice, then the clear rock we call crystal, ice so hard it never melts. John sees a sea like crystal before the throne. Picture frozen, clear, unmelting ice.","g":"crystal","h":"The picture: clear, unmelting ice."},"G2931":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to conceal by covering. Kryphe means secretly, in secret. It pictures a thing done under cover, out of sight. Paul says it is shameful even to speak of what such people do in secret.","g":"in secret","h":"The picture: done under cover."},"G2932":{"b":"This means to procure for oneself, to get, gain, acquire. The KJV even renders it purchase. Do not get gold for your belts, Jesus tells them, using it. It is the hand closing on a thing so that it is now yours.","g":"acquire, obtain","h":"The picture: the hand closing on what it now owns."},"G2933":{"b":"The word comes from a verb for getting and owning. A ktema is what you have acquired, an estate, a piece of property. The rich young man had many, and it was these fields and holdings he could not walk away from when Jesus said sell.","g":"possession","h":"The picture: land held in your own name."},"G2934":{"b":"The word comes from owning, a thing acquired, and it means a beast, especially a beast of burden. The good Samaritan sets the wounded man on his own ktenos and walks beside it. A donkey or mule, the animal that bears the weight.","g":"beast","h":"The picture: the pack animal that carries the load."},"G2935":{"b":"This word comes from a verb meaning to get or own. It means an owner. Luke says those in the church who were owners of land or houses sold them and brought the money to share. The word marks the person who held the property.","g":"owner","h":"The picture: the one who holds the title deed."},"G2936":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the older sense is to people or found a region or city. Picture staking out empty ground and raising a settlement where there was none. In the Bible this becomes the word for God creating the world.","g":"create","h":"The picture: founding a city from nothing."},"G2937":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives the classical sense first. A founding, settling, foundation.\n\nIn the Bible it shifts to the act of creating, and then to the thing created. Behind creation lies the idea of setting something up to last.","g":"creation","h":"The picture: founding a settlement."},"G2938":{"b":"The root means to found, to form something from the start. This word is the result, a created thing, a creature. Every creature of God is good, Paul says. We are a kind of firstfruits of the things he made.","g":"creature","h":"The picture: a thing that was made."},"G2939":{"b":"The root means to found, as one founds a city. Abbott gives \"a founder,\" then a creator. Peter calls God this, telling the suffering to entrust their souls to the one who built them.","g":"Creator, founder","h":"The picture: the founder who lays the first stone."},"G294":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this comes from a word meaning to clothe, with a part meaning around. It is putting a garment around someone. Jesus says God clothes the grass of the field. If he wraps the grass so well, how much more will he clothe you.","g":"clothe","h":"The picture: cloth wrapped around the body."},"G2940":{"b":"The root is the word for a cube, a die for playing. Kybeia is dice-playing, and from the cheating of gamblers it came to mean trickery and sleight of hand. Paul warns of teachers who play their followers like a rigged game.","g":"sleight, trickery","h":"The picture: a rigged dice game."},"G2941":{"b":"Abbott gives it as steering, pilotage. It pictures the pilot's hands on the rudder, guiding a ship through open water. Paul lists it among church gifts, the steady work of steering the people.","g":"government","h":"The picture: hands on the ship's rudder."},"G2942":{"b":"This is the man at the helm, the steersman of a ship. Strong's calls him the helmsman, the one who becomes captain by holding the wheel. The pilot chose to sail on against Paul's warning. His hands were on the steering.","g":"shipmaster","h":"The picture: hands on the helm."},"G2944":{"b":"The word comes from the word for a circle. It is to draw a ring all the way around, to surround. When you see Jerusalem circled by armies, Jesus said, know its ruin is near. A closing circle.","g":"surround","h":"The picture: a circle closing around."},"G2945":{"b":"Abbott: \"a ring, circle.\" Strong's says it means in a circle, all around. The word is the one for a ring. It pictures the crowd that sat round about Jesus, circled up close to hear him.","g":"all around","h":"The picture: sitting in a ring around."},"G2946":{"b":"The root means to roll about. So this is a wallow, the rolling in filth, or the muddy place itself. Peter says the washed sow went back to her wallowing in the mire.","g":"wallowing","h":"The picture: the muddy hollow a pig rolls in."},"G2947":{"b":"This word means to roll, to roll along, and of a person to wallow. In Mark 9:20 the spirit throws the boy into a fit, and he falls to the ground and rolls about, foaming at the mouth, while his father watches.","g":"wallow, roll","h":"The picture: rolling on the ground."},"G2948":{"b":"The word ties back to rolling about. It pictures someone who cannot walk straight, rocking on a bent or missing limb. Jesus heals crowds of these. Better, he says, to enter life kyllos than whole into the fire.","g":"maimed","h":"The picture: a body that rocks as it moves."},"G2949":{"b":"Abbott-Smith ties this to a word meaning to swell, as a body swells in pregnancy. A kyma is the sea rising into a wave and breaking over. In the storm the waves swamped the boat while Jesus slept.","g":"wave","h":"The picture: a wave swelling up and toppling over."},"G295":{"b":"Abbott says the town was so named because the river Strymon flowed around it. The water curled about the city on both sides. Paul passed through it on the road to Thessalonica.","g":"Amphipolis","h":"The picture: a city ringed by a river."},"G2950":{"b":"Abbott traces this to a word for a cup. A kymbalon is the hollow metal cymbal, shaped like a cup, that clashes when struck. Paul says without love he is only a clanging cymbal, loud and empty.","g":"cymbal","h":"The picture: a metal cup you strike."},"G2951":{"b":"Cummin is a small seed used to flavor food. In Matthew 23:23 Jesus names it with mint and dill as the tiny things the Pharisees measured out to tithe, while they let justice and mercy slip.","g":"cummin","h":"The picture: a handful of cummin seeds."},"G2952":{"b":"This is not the wild dog of the street but a little dog, the small house pet. That softer word matters. The woman catches it and answers that even the little dogs under the table get the crumbs the children drop.","g":"little dog","h":"The picture: the little dog under the table."},"G2953":{"b":"This word comes from Cyprus, the island out in the sea. A Kyprios is a man born there. Barnabas was one, a man of Cyprus who sold his field and laid the money at the apostles' feet.","g":"Cyprian","h":"The picture: a man from the island of Cyprus."},"G2954":{"b":"This is Cyprus, an island in the Mediterranean. Its name is of uncertain origin, so there is nothing in the Greek to picture. Just a place on the map, where Barnabas was from.","flat":1,"g":"Cyprus","h":"No picture."},"G2955":{"b":"This word means to bend forward, to bow the head and stoop. In Mark 1:7 John says he is not worthy to stoop down and untie the strap of Jesus' sandals, the work of the lowest servant.","g":"stoop down","h":"The picture: bending down to the ground."},"G2956":{"b":"This means someone from Cyrene, a region over in Africa. The one the Gospels name is Simon, pulled from the crowd to carry Jesus' cross. A foreigner far from home, caught up in the walk to Golgotha.","g":"Cyrenian","h":"The picture: the man from Cyrene."},"G2957":{"b":"This is the name of a city in North Africa, Cyrene. People from there were among the crowd at Pentecost, and later a man of Cyrene carried Jesus' cross. Strong's says the name's origin is uncertain. Nothing to open up.","flat":1,"g":"Cyrene","h":"No picture."},"G2958":{"b":"This is just a name, the Roman governor known as Quirinius. Strong's says it is of Latin origin. A name marks the man who held the office. There is nothing behind it to picture.","flat":1,"g":"Cyrenius","h":"No picture."},"G2959":{"b":"This is the woman's form of the word for lord or master, one supreme in authority. So it means a lady, the mistress of a house, a woman with authority in it. John writes to the elect lady.","g":"lady","h":"The picture: the lady of the house."},"G296":{"b":"The pieces mean on both sides and a road. It is a fork or crossing, the open street. In Mark 11:4 the disciples find the colt tied at a door outside, where two ways meet, and they untie it as Jesus told them.","g":"crossroads","h":"The picture: where two roads meet."},"G2960":{"b":"This comes from kyrios, lord or master. In everyday papers it meant imperial, belonging to the emperor. So the Lord's supper and the Lord's day are the Master's own, stamped as belonging to him.","g":"the Lord's","h":"The picture: the owner's stamp."},"G2961":{"b":"It comes from kyrios, the master, the one who owns and controls. To kyrieuo is to be lord over someone. Paul says death is no longer lord over Christ, and sin shall not be lord over you. To hold the mastery.","g":"rule over","h":"The picture: the master over the house."},"G2962":{"b":"Strong's offers only the bare word supremacy, with no source word named. Abbott-Smith says it means having power or authority. The word covers slave owners, husbands, teachers and the Emperor. No older image sits behind it.","flat":1,"g":"lord, master","h":"No picture."},"G2963":{"b":"Built from the word for lord. Abbott gives lordship, dominion. It names a rank of unseen powers, thrones and dominions, all made through Christ and standing under Him, Colossians 1:16. Whatever kyriotes rules, He is the one who made it.","g":"dominion, lordship","h":"The picture: the sphere a lord rules."},"G2964":{"b":"The word comes from a root meaning authority and validity. To kyroo is to make a thing binding, to ratify it. Paul says even a man's confirmed covenant no one sets aside, so how much more God's sworn promise.","g":"confirm","h":"The picture: the covenant sealed and binding."},"G2965":{"b":"This is a dog, the half-wild scavenger of the streets, not a pet. It was a word of contempt. Do not give what is holy to the kuon, Jesus says. Paul warns, beware the dogs. Snapping, unclean animals.","g":"dog","h":"The picture: a street dog."},"G2966":{"b":"This is a limb, a member of the body, as if lopped off. Here it means the dead bodies. The corpses of those who rebelled fell one by one and lay scattered across the wilderness sand.","g":"carcase","h":"The picture: bodies fallen in the desert."},"G2967":{"b":"Abbott ties it to kolos, cut short. To kolyo is to hinder, restrain, forbid, to cut an action off before it goes further. So let the children come and do not kolyo them, do not throw up a hand to stop them reaching Jesus.","g":"forbid, hinder","h":"The picture: a hand thrown up to hold you back."},"G2968":{"b":"Abbott-Smith defines it as a country town, set against a walled city. That is the whole difference. No gates, no defences.\n\nBethlehem is called one of these. So is Bethany.","g":"village","h":"The picture: a town with no wall."},"G2969":{"b":"The word joins village and city. A walled city meant safety, a village meant none. This is the in-between, a country town with no walls. In Mark 1:38 Jesus says let us go to the next towns so he can preach there too.","g":"town","h":"The picture: a town with no walls."},"G297":{"b":"This word just means both, both of two. Strong's ties it to a word for \"around.\" It is a plain counting word. There is nothing behind it to picture.","flat":1,"g":"both","h":"No picture."},"G2970":{"b":"Abbott's plain sense is a revel, carousal, a wild drinking party that spills out into the street. Paul lists it beside drunkenness among the works of darkness, the noisy party you would be ashamed to be caught in by daylight.","g":"revelling","h":"The picture: a wild drinking party."},"G2971":{"b":"Strong's says this bug is named for its stinging proboscis, the sharp point it jabs you with. It is the gnat, the smallest of pests. In Matthew 23:24 it stands for the tiniest rule, strained out while the camel is swallowed whole.","g":"gnat","h":"The picture: a mosquito's stinging point."},"G2972":{"b":"This is Cos, an island in the sea, a stop on the voyage after Paul left Miletus. It is only a bare place name of uncertain origin, so there is nothing here to picture.","flat":1,"g":"Cos","h":"No picture."},"G2973":{"b":"This is a name and nothing more. Strong's traces it to Hebrew. It marks an ancestor in Jesus' family tree. A name is a label for a person, so there is no image hidden behind it to picture.","flat":1,"g":"Cosam","h":"No picture."},"G2974":{"b":"Abbott says the word means blunt, dull. Picture a blade gone dull. The word is used for a sense that has been blunted, an ear that cannot hear or a tongue that cannot speak.","g":"deaf, dumb","h":"The picture: a blunted edge."},"G2975":{"b":"This word means to get something by lot, by the draw. Zechariah is chosen by lot to burn incense. The soldiers lanchano for Jesus' seamless coat, casting lots rather than tear it, so a garment is decided by chance.","g":"obtain by lot","h":"The picture: drawing lots to decide."},"G2976":{"b":"The name means God is helper. It is a shortened form of Eleazar, joining a word for God with the idea of coming to aid. Lazarus was the man Jesus raised after four days.","g":"Lazarus","h":"The picture: God is helper."},"G2977":{"b":"The root means to lie hidden. Lathra is doing a thing secretly, where no eye follows. Joseph decided to send Mary away quietly, not to shame her in public. The word keeps it in the shadows, out of everyone's sight.","g":"secretly","h":"The picture: done out of sight."},"G2978":{"b":"This is a whirlwind, a sudden violent squall. A great storm of wind came down on the lake and the waves broke into the boat while Jesus slept. The word is the gust that drops without warning and whips the water into chaos.","g":"whirlwind","h":"The picture: a sudden squall on the water."},"G2979":{"b":"Abbott says this comes from a word meaning with the foot. It means to kick. The voice tells Paul it is hard to kick against the goads, like an ox lashing its foot back at the sharp stick. The word is the kick itself, foot striking out.","g":"kick","h":"The picture: a foot kicking out."},"G298":{"b":"This puts \"not\" before a root meaning to find fault, to censure. It is kin to the word for a blemish. So it is blameless, unspotted. Peter says be found by God in peace, without spot and blameless.","g":"blameless","h":"The picture: without a single blot."},"G2980":{"b":"Strong's traces it to a verb that has since dropped out of use. That verb is gone, so nothing can be seen behind it. Abbott-Smith gives no origin, only the sense: to utter, to talk, to say.","flat":1,"g":"speak, talk","h":"No picture."},"G2981":{"b":"The word means talk, the way a person speaks. In the courtyard they tell Peter, your lalia gives you away, your speech marks you as a Galilean. Not what he said but how it sounded, the accent he could not hide.","g":"speech, talk","h":"The picture: the accent that gives you away."},"G2982":{"b":"This little word is not a name but a question. It simply means why. It is part of the cry Jesus raised from the cross, lama sabachthani, why have you forsaken me.","g":"lama","h":"The picture: why."},"G2983":{"b":"Strong's says this word means to get hold of something. It is the open hand closing on a thing. So when the New Testament says you receive grace or receive the Spirit, it means you actually take hold, not just stand and watch.","g":"take, receive","h":"The picture: the hand takes hold."},"G2984":{"b":"This is the name of an old patriarch. Strong's traces it to Hebrew. It marks one man in the line running from Jesus back through Noah to Adam. A name points to a person, not a picture. Nothing to see.","flat":1,"g":"Lamech","h":"No picture."},"G2985":{"b":"Abbott-Smith builds it from the verb to shine. It pictures a burning torch, often fed with oil like a lamp. The ten girls took their lamps out to meet the bridegroom.","g":"lamp, torch","h":"The picture: a burning torch."},"G2986":{"b":"Abbott traces this to λάμπω, to shine. So the word is about light coming off a thing. It describes a clear river, a bright star, and shining, splendid clothes.","g":"bright","h":"The picture: it shines."},"G2987":{"b":"This comes from lampros, radiant, shining. It means brightness, blazing brilliance. Paul says a light from heaven shone around him on the road, brighter than the sun at midday. The word is that pure blaze of light, too strong to look at.","g":"brightness","h":"The picture: light brighter than the sun."},"G2988":{"b":"The root word means radiant, shining. From there it means magnificent and sumptuous. Picture a table gleaming with luxury. The rich man feasted this way each day. The word carries the glitter of a life spent on itself.","g":"sumptuously","h":"The picture: bright shining robes at a feast."},"G2989":{"b":"This word means to shine, to give off light like a lamp set on its stand. Let your light so shine before men, Jesus says, using it. On the mountain his face shone with it. Bright light streaming out into a dark room.","g":"shine","h":"The picture: a lamp beaming light."},"G299":{"b":"Abbott: \"of sacrificial victims, without blemish.\" It is built from a word for a spot or blemish, with \"not\" in front. The picture is a lamb checked over and found with no spot or flaw on it.","g":"unblemished","h":"The picture: a lamb with no spot on it."},"G2990":{"b":"This means to lie hidden, to escape notice, to slip past unseen. Jesus enters a house wanting to hide, but he cannot be hidden. Hebrews says some entertained angels without knowing it. The thing that passes right by your eyes unseen.","g":"lie hidden","h":"The picture: slipping by unnoticed."},"G2991":{"b":"Abbott builds it from a word for a stone and a word meaning to scrape. Rock cut and scraped away. They laid Jesus in a tomb hewn out of the rock, where no one had ever been laid. It was carved, not built.","g":"hewn in stone","h":"The picture: a tomb scraped out of rock."},"G2992":{"b":"Strong's calls it apparently a primary word. Abbott-Smith gives no origin, only the uses: people gathered in a crowd, and then a people of one race and language. Nothing sits behind it.","flat":1,"g":"people","h":"No picture."},"G2993":{"b":"Strong's builds this city's name from two words, one for a people and one for justice or right. Laodicea, the lukewarm church of Revelation, carried a proud name about the people's justice while being neither hot nor cold.","g":"Laodicea","h":"The picture: justice of the people."},"G2994":{"b":"The root is Laodicea, a wealthy city in Asia Minor. Paul asks that his letter be read among the Laodikeus. The word simply marks a person by the city whose streets and trade shaped them.","g":"a Laodicean","h":"The picture: a citizen of Laodicea."},"G2995":{"b":"This is simply the throat, the larynx, the word we still use. Abbott notes it stands for speech. Paul quotes the Psalm, their throat is an open grave, meaning the deadly things that come up out of their mouths.","g":"throat","h":"The picture: the open throat, ready to speak."},"G2996":{"b":"This is a place name, Lasea, a city on the south coast of Crete, near the harbour called Fair Havens. Its origin is unknown and it is barely known otherwise. There is no meaning behind the name to turn into a picture.","flat":1,"g":"Lasea","h":"No picture."},"G2997":{"b":"This word first meant to clang or crash, a loud noise. Then to crack or burst open noisily. Luke uses it of Judas' body splitting apart in the field. A sound of something breaking, and everything spilling out.","g":"to burst open","h":"The picture: bursting open with a loud crack."},"G2998":{"b":"The word comes from stone and cutting, a stonecutter's work. Latomeo is to hew, to carve out of rock. Joseph lays Jesus in a new tomb he had cut for himself out of the rock, then rolls a stone across the mouth.","g":"hew, quarry","h":"The picture: a tomb cut out of solid rock."},"G2999":{"b":"The root means to serve, and the first sense is hired service, the work a laborer does for pay. Turned toward God it becomes worship. Paul calls offering your body a living sacrifice your true service. Work as worship.","g":"service, worship","h":"The picture: a hired worker's labor."},"G3":{"b":"The name comes as an intensive form of a word meaning to perish or destroy. Abaddon is the angel of the bottomless pit, whose very name means destruction.","g":"Abaddon","h":"The picture: a destroying angel."},"G30":{"b":"Strong's links it to something bent, the curved shape of a container. An angeion is a vessel, here the small jars the wise girls fill with oil. The foolish ones bring lamps but no jar, so their light runs out at midnight.","g":"vessel","h":"The picture: a jar for holding oil."},"G3000":{"b":"Abbott-Smith traces it to a word for a hired servant. His first sense is to work for hire.\n\nThen it becomes the word for serving God, and in the New Testament it always is. Worship as a day's work done for someone else.","g":"serve, worship","h":"The picture: the hired workman."},"G3001":{"b":"The word comes from a word meaning to dig. A lachanon is a garden plant, the kind you turn the soil for. When Jesus calls the mustard the greatest of these, he means the humble stuff of a vegetable patch.","g":"vegetable","h":"The picture: the plant you dig up to eat."},"G3003":{"b":"This is a Latin army word, a legion, a full Roman regiment of thousands of soldiers. The demons in the man give this as their name, \"Legion, for we are many.\" Jesus says he could call more than twelve legions of angels.","g":"legion","h":"The picture: a Roman army division, thousands strong."},"G3004":{"b":"Strong's says the word properly means to \"lay\" forth. Speech as setting something down where it can be seen.\n\nAbbott-Smith notes an older use in Homer: to pick out, gather, count up. Words gathered and put in order.","g":"say, speak","h":"The picture: words laid out in front of you."},"G3005":{"b":"The root means to leave. A leimma is what is left over, the remainder, the small piece that survives when the rest is gone. Paul says even now there is a remnant chosen by grace. A leftover kept back on purpose, not by accident.","g":"remnant","h":"The picture: the piece left behind."},"G3006":{"b":"This word means smooth, the opposite of rough and rocky. It is a flat, even surface. In the prophet's cry the rough paths are made smooth for the Lord. The broken road is planed flat before him.","g":"smooth","h":"The picture: a smooth, level road."},"G3007":{"b":"This means to leave behind, and so to be left short, to be missing. Jesus tells the rich man, one thing you still lack. James says if anyone lacks wisdom, ask. It marks the empty spot where something ought to be.","g":"lack","h":"The picture: the empty spot where something should be."},"G3008":{"b":"This word comes from a word for a public servant. In old Athens it meant a rich man paying out of his own pocket for the city's needs. In worship it is costly service to God. As they served the Lord, the Spirit spoke.","g":"minister","h":"The picture: serving the city at your own cost."},"G3009":{"b":"In old Greek this was a rich citizen doing public work at his own expense, funding a service the city needed. It became priestly ministry, Zechariah serving in the temple. Costly work done for the public good, out of your own pocket.","g":"service, ministry","h":"The picture: public work paid from your own pocket."},"G301":{"b":"The name means strong. It comes from a word meaning to be alert and to bear up under a load. It pictures a person of firm and steady strength.","g":"Amos","h":"The picture: strong."},"G3010":{"b":"The root means to be a public servant, doing work for others. This word describes the angels as ministering spirits, sent out to serve those who will be saved. They are on duty, not idle.","g":"ministering","h":"The picture: the servant sent out on a job."},"G3011":{"b":"The word joins people and work. In old Greek a leitourgos was one who discharges a public office at his own expense. It is service for the community at personal cost. The New Testament uses it for those who serve God and the church.","g":"minister, servant","h":"The picture: work done for the whole people."},"G3012":{"b":"The word comes from the Latin for linen. Abbott says \"a linen cloth, towel.\" At the last supper Jesus takes one, ties it around himself like a servant, and kneels to wash the disciples' feet, drying them with the same cloth.","g":"towel","h":"The picture: a linen towel tied at the waist."},"G3013":{"b":"The word comes from 'to peel' and means a scale or flake, like the scale of a fish. Something like these drops from Saul's eyes, and the blind man sees again.","g":"scale, flake","h":"The picture: a flake peeling away."},"G3014":{"b":"The root is a flake or scale. Leprosy here is the scaliness, skin turning rough and flaking away. When the leper begs Jesus, he stretches out his hand and touches the untouchable, and the flaking skin is made clean.","g":"leprosy","h":"The picture: skin gone scaly and flaking."},"G3015":{"b":"Abbott-Smith links this to a word for a scale. In older Greek it meant scaly, rough. It became the word for a leper, a person with scaly skin whom others kept at a distance.","g":"leper","h":"The picture: scaly, rough skin."},"G3016":{"b":"The root is a flake, from a word meaning to peel. So this coin was named for being thin and light, the smallest one there was. That is the coin the widow drops in the treasury, two of them, all she had.","g":"mite, small coin","h":"The picture: a coin thin as a peeled flake."},"G3017":{"b":"The name means attached, joined. Levi was a son of Jacob, and his tribe was joined to the service of God. Leah named him hoping her husband would be joined to her.","g":"Levi","h":"The picture: attached."},"G3018":{"b":"The name Levi belonged to the priestly line of Israel. Hebrews says Levi, still in Abraham's body, paid tithes to Melchizedek. The word carries a whole tribe of priests, sons set apart to stand before God for the people.","g":"Levi","h":"The picture: the tribe that served at the altar."},"G3019":{"b":"A descendant of Levi, set apart for temple service. Picture the Levite in Jesus' story who came upon the wounded man, looked, and passed by on the other side, Luke 10:32. The religious insider who saw the need and did nothing.","g":"Levite","h":"The picture: the temple man who passed by."},"G3020":{"b":"The root is Leuites, a Levite. Abbott gives Levitical. Hebrews speaks of the Leuitikos priesthood, the whole system of priests drawn from Levi. The word ties an office and its rituals back to that one tribe set apart to serve.","g":"Levitical","h":"The picture: belonging to the priestly order."},"G3021":{"b":"The root simply means white. This verb is to make white, to bleach. Mark uses it for Jesus' clothes at the transfiguration, gone whiter than any laundry could scrub them. And for robes washed white in Revelation. The color of light itself.","g":"whiten","h":"The picture: cloth turned dazzling white."},"G3022":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is bright, brilliant, used of clothing. White here is not just a colour. It gives off light.\n\nThat is the word for the clothes at the transfiguration, white as snow.","g":"white","h":"The picture: cloth that shines."},"G3023":{"b":"This just means a lion. Strong's calls it \"a primary word,\" meaning it comes from nothing older. It names the animal plainly. There is nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"lion","h":"No picture."},"G3024":{"b":"The root means to lie hidden, out of view. This is forgetfulness, the memory gone dark. Peter says the one who lacks these graces has taken this, forgetting he was cleansed from his old sins.","g":"forgetfulness","h":"The picture: a thing slipped out of sight."},"G3025":{"b":"This is the winepress, the stone trough where grapes are trampled and the juice runs out. A man planted a vineyard and dug a lenos in it. In Revelation the lenos of God's wrath is trodden, and what flows is not wine.","g":"winepress","h":"The picture: the trough where grapes are trodden."},"G3026":{"b":"This word means idle talk, nonsense. Strong's calls it a primary word, so it comes from nothing older. There is nothing behind it to see, just empty chatter. The women's report seemed to the disciples like nonsense.","flat":1,"g":"idle tale","h":"No picture."},"G3027":{"b":"Abbott-Smith traces the word to a root meaning booty, plunder. It is the violent robber who takes by force in the open, not the sneaking thief. The man beaten on the Jericho road fell among these.","g":"robber, brigand","h":"The picture: the bandit after plunder."},"G3028":{"b":"This comes from the word to take or receive, to lay hold. Lempsis is the receiving. Paul speaks of giving and receiving, an account of what goes out and what comes in, and no church shared it but them.","g":"receiving","h":"The picture: a hand taking hold."},"G3029":{"b":"This word just means very or exceedingly. Strong's says its origin is of uncertain affinity, so no one knows where it comes from. There is nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"very, greatly","h":"No picture."},"G303":{"b":"This is a small preposition meaning \"up,\" also used for \"each\" or \"apiece.\" Strong's calls it a primary preposition. It is a grammar word, with nothing behind it to picture.","flat":1,"g":"up, each","h":"No picture."},"G3030":{"b":"The word names the frankincense tree and the sweet-smelling gum it gives. Burned, it sends up fragrant smoke. The wise men bring it to the child Jesus. Frankincense was burned before God in worship. A gift that says who this baby is.","g":"frankincense","h":"The picture: fragrant incense from the tree."},"G3031":{"b":"From the word for the incense-tree and its gum, frankincense. The word came to mean the censer that burns it. John sees an angel with a golden censer full of incense. Picture it trailing sweet smoke.","g":"censer","h":"The picture: a censer trailing smoke."},"G3032":{"b":"Strong's calls this a Roman freedman. He was once a slave, then set free, but the name still marks where he came from. The synagogue that argued with Stephen was named for such freed men.","g":"freedman","h":"The picture: the man who used to be owned."},"G3033":{"b":"Libya was a region of Africa. Strong's traces its name to the word for the south wind, the wind that brought rain up from the south. People from there were in Jerusalem at Pentecost. A country named, perhaps, for a wind.","g":"Libya","h":"The picture: the land of the rain-bringing south wind."},"G3034":{"b":"This word is built straight from the word for a stone. It means to throw stones at someone until they die. Picture a crowd bending to pick rocks off the ground. The word is the stone in the fist, raised against a man.","g":"stone","h":"The picture: the rock in the hand."},"G3035":{"b":"The word means made of stone. At the wedding in Cana six stone waterpots stand ready for washing, and Jesus turns their water to wine. Paul contrasts letters cut in stone with words written on the heart. Cold, hard, hewn rock.","g":"of stone","h":"The picture: carved out of solid stone."},"G3036":{"b":"This word is built from stone and to throw. It means to pelt someone with stones until they die. Jerusalem, you stone the prophets sent to you, Jesus grieves. Stephen was killed this way, stones flung by an angry crowd.","g":"stone","h":"The picture: stones hurled by the crowd."},"G3037":{"b":"Strong's calls it apparently a primary word, so it grew from nothing earlier. A stone is a stone. Abbott-Smith lists tomb stones, building stones and precious stones, but the word itself hides nothing.","flat":1,"g":"stone","h":"No picture."},"G3038":{"b":"This word joins stone and to spread. It means a pavement laid with stones, a mosaic floor. Pilate set his judgment seat on it to sentence Jesus. The name is just what it was: stones, spread out underfoot.","g":"stone pavement","h":"The picture: a floor laid with stones."},"G3039":{"b":"The word comes from the winnowing-fan, the fork that tosses threshed grain so the wind blows the chaff away. Likmao is to scatter like that, or to grind to dust. The stone that falls, Jesus says, will scatter a man like chaff.","g":"scatter, grind","h":"The picture: chaff scattered on the wind."},"G304":{"b":"Strong's just calls it a stairway. It is built from a word meaning to go up and a word meaning a step. Put steps together and you climb. This is where Paul stood above the crowd to speak.","g":"stairs","h":"The picture: a flight of stairs."},"G3040":{"b":"This word means a harbor, a haven, the sheltered water where ships ride safe from the open sea. Fair Havens was such a harbor, but Paul warned it was a poor one to winter in.","g":"harbor","h":"The picture: the sheltered harbor where ships ride safe."},"G3041":{"b":"Abbott says a lake, still inland water. Luke uses it for Galilee, where the fishermen washed their nets and the storm nearly swamped the boat. And John names the last end of evil the limnē of fire, the burning lake that has no far shore.","g":"lake","h":"The picture: still inland water."},"G3042":{"b":"Strong's says this probably comes through the idea of destitution, of being left with nothing. Abbott-Smith gives hunger, famine. So famine is the land emptied out. The prodigal son met one in a far country.","g":"famine, hunger","h":"The picture: being left without."},"G3043":{"b":"This is flax, the tall plant whose stalks are beaten and combed into thread, and the thread woven into linen. The same word covers both, the plant and the cloth. In Matthew the smoking flax is a dying wick, and Jesus will not snuff it out.","g":"flax, linen","h":"The picture: the flax plant that becomes cloth."},"G3044":{"b":"Strong's says his name is perhaps from the word for flax, the plant spun into linen. Linus is a Christian in Rome who greets Timothy. A friend whose name may carry the thread of linen in it.","g":"Linus","h":"The picture: flax spun into linen."},"G3045":{"b":"The word comes from the word for fat. Abbott-Smith gives \"oily, fatty,\" and by extension the rich, dainty life. Picture a table shining with greasy food. So all the fat, bright things are lost to Babylon and never found again.","g":"rich, dainty","h":"The picture: rich, fatty food."},"G3046":{"b":"The word comes from the Latin libra, a set weight. Abbott says \"a pound.\" Mary pours out a whole pound of costly ointment on Jesus' feet. Later Nicodemus brings a hundred pounds' weight of spices to bury him. Measured out by weight.","g":"pound","h":"The picture: a pound weight on the scale."},"G3047":{"b":"Strong's ties this to a word for pouring out, because this southwest wind brings the rain. It names the direction the wind blows from. The harbour they hoped to reach looked toward it. The word is the wet wind out of the southwest, heavy with water.","g":"southwest wind","h":"The picture: the wind that pours rain."},"G3048":{"b":"This comes from logos used in the money sense, an account or reckoning. A logia is a collection, funds gathered up. Paul gives orders for the collection for the saints, each person setting something by every week.","g":"collection","h":"The picture: coins gathered in a collection."},"G3049":{"b":"Strong's says the word means to take an inventory. Abbott starts with numerical calculation, to count, reckon.\n\nWhen faith is counted as righteousness, it is a bookkeeping word. Something written into the column.","g":"reckon, count","h":"The picture: adding up the ledger."},"G305":{"b":"Abbott lists what rises. A fish. Smoke. Plants growing. Things coming up in your mind.\n\nHe also lists prayers. In Acts they go up the way smoke does.","g":"go up","h":"The picture: smoke going up, plants coming up."},"G3050":{"b":"The word is built on lógos, reason or word. Paul calls offering your body to God your reasonable worship, the service that fits a thinking creature. Peter tells babies to crave its pure milk. Devotion shaped by the word, not blind ritual.","g":"reasonable","h":"The picture: worship that makes sense."},"G3051":{"b":"Abbott calls this a little logos, a small but weighty saying. It means an oracle, a word straight from God's mouth. Paul says the Jews were entrusted with the logia of God, Romans 3:2, the very sayings kept safe for the world.","g":"oracle","h":"The picture: a small, weighty saying from God."},"G3052":{"b":"This grows from the word for something said, a spoken thing. So it paints a man overflowing with words, quick and skilled in speech. Apollos was such a man, eloquent and mighty in the Scriptures.","g":"eloquent","h":"The picture: a man full of words."},"G3053":{"b":"The root means to take an inventory, to add up the count. A logismos is the mind reckoning like an accountant working the figures. Paul says our thoughts accuse or excuse us, the inward tally of right and wrong. The mind doing its sums.","g":"reasoning","h":"The picture: an accountant totting up figures."},"G3054":{"b":"This joins the word for a word to a word meaning to war, to quarrel. It means to fight about words. Paul warns against it as useless. The picture is two people at war, but the ground they fight over is only words.","g":"strive about words","h":"The picture: a battle over words."},"G3055":{"b":"This joins logos, a word, and a word for battle. So it is a war made of words, quarreling over terms. Paul says such word-fights breed envy, strife, and evil suspicions among the proud.","g":"strife of words","h":"The picture: a battle fought with words."},"G3056":{"b":"Abbott-Smith builds this noun from the verb to say. He then splits it two ways: that by which the inward thought is expressed, and the inward thought itself.\n\nStrong's agrees, calling it something said, including the thought.","g":"word, message","h":"The picture: the thought and the saying of it together."},"G3057":{"b":"This word means a spear, and first the spear-head itself, the iron point. It is the weapon the soldier drove into Jesus' side as he hung on the cross. Not the shaft. The sharp end.","g":"spear","h":"The picture: the iron head of a spear."},"G3058":{"b":"This means to abuse and revile, to rail at a person to their face. The root is a word for a blackguard, a foul-mouthed man. So when Peter says Christ was reviled and reviled not again, picture curses shouted at him and no curse thrown back.","g":"revile","h":"The picture: curses shouted in a man's face."},"G3059":{"b":"The root is a blackguard, a foul-mouthed man. Loidoria is what pours out of him, a stream of abuse and railing. Peter says do not give back railing for railing. When the insult comes at you, do not fling it back.","g":"slander, railing","h":"The picture: the mouth that runs with insults."},"G306":{"b":"This is ana, up, with ballo, to throw. To defer is to throw the matter back, to toss it up for another day. Felix throws Paul's case aside, putting it off. The word is the motion of tossing something out of your hands to deal with later.","g":"defer, put off","h":"The picture: tossing a thing aside for later."},"G3060":{"b":"Abbott calls this a railer, an abusive person. Strong's traces it only vaguely to mischief. A loidoros is one whose words attack and revile. Paul says such a person will not inherit the kingdom of God.","g":"reviler","h":"The picture: the tongue that lashes."},"G3061":{"b":"Strong's says \"a plague,\" the disease itself. Abbott says \"pestilence.\" Jesus lists these among the signs, sickness spreading town to town. The same word gets thrown at a person, a plague of a man, when the crowd wants to smear Paul.","g":"plague, pestilence","h":"The picture: a plague sweeping through a town."},"G3062":{"b":"Abbott-Smith traces this to the verb to leave. These are the leftovers, the ones still there once the others have been counted or taken.\n\nThe New Testament uses it for everybody else.","g":"the rest, others","h":"The picture: what is left over."},"G3063":{"b":"The root is the remaining ones, what is left over after the rest is gone. Loipon is the remainder. As a word thrown into a sentence it means for what is left, and so, finally. Finally, brothers, Paul writes.","g":"finally, remaining","h":"The picture: what is left over."},"G3064":{"b":"From a word meaning to leave, loipos is what is left over, the rest, the remainder. In the phrase from henceforth it means for the time that remains. Paul says from now on let no one trouble him.","g":"henceforth","h":"The picture: what is left over."},"G3065":{"b":"This is a name. Strong's says only that it is contracted from the Latin Lucanus. The worksheet gives no meaning behind it, so there is nothing here to picture, only the man, Paul's companion.","flat":1,"g":"Luke","h":"No picture."},"G3066":{"b":"This is the Latin name Lucius. Strong's calls it illuminative and ties it to light, the name once given to a child born at dawn. Beyond that it is simply the name of a Christian who was with Paul at Antioch.","g":"Lucius","h":"The picture: born at first light."},"G3067":{"b":"This is the word for a bath, a washing of the whole body. The root means to bathe the entire person, not just rinse a hand. Paul calls the cleansing of the church a washing of water. Clean all over, not spot-cleaned.","g":"washing, bath","h":"The picture: a full bath."},"G3068":{"b":"This means to bathe, to wash the whole body, not just a hand or foot. They washed the body of Dorcas and laid her in an upper room. Christ washed us from our sins. Water poured over the whole person.","g":"bathe, wash","h":"The picture: washing the whole body."},"G3069":{"b":"This is the name of a town in Palestine, from the Hebrew name Lod. A place on the map, with no picture inside the word itself for us to see here.","flat":1,"g":"Lydda","h":"No picture."},"G307":{"b":"Strong's says this word means to cause to go up, to haul a net. Abbott points to Matthew 13:48, where fishermen drag the loaded net up onto the shore. It is heavy work, something full pulled out of the water and sorted on the sand.","g":"haul, draw up","h":"The picture: dragging the net up onto the beach."},"G3070":{"b":"This is a woman's name, Lydia, the seller of purple who believed at Philippi. It is of foreign origin and likely means simply the woman from the region Lydia. No meaning stands behind it to picture.","flat":1,"g":"Lydia","h":"No picture."},"G3071":{"b":"Strong's says the name may come, far back, from the word for a wolf. Lycaonia is the inland region where Paul heals a lame man and the crowds try to sacrifice to him as a god.","g":"Lycaonia","h":"The picture: a wolf."},"G3072":{"b":"The root is Lycaonia, a region of Asia Minor. Abbott gives in Lycaonian speech. When Paul heals a lame man the crowd erupts lykaonisti, in their own tongue, calling the apostles gods. Language bursting out under strong feeling.","g":"in Lycaonian","h":"The picture: a crowd shouting in its home dialect."},"G3073":{"b":"Strong's traces this name, far back, to the word for wolf. Lycia is a region on the coast of Asia Minor, where the port of Myra stood. The link is distant and uncertain, but Strong's hears the word for wolf under the name of the land.","g":"Lycia","h":"The picture: wolf-country."},"G3074":{"b":"A lykos is a wolf. I send you out as sheep among wolves. Fierce ones will come in, Paul warns, wolves that do not spare the flock. The predator circling the fold, teeth hidden behind a borrowed fleece.","g":"wolf","h":"The picture: a wolf at the fold."},"G3075":{"b":"Strong's says the word properly means to soil. Abbott says to outrage and maltreat. In Acts, Saul ravages the church, dragging men and women out of their houses to prison.","g":"make havock of","h":"The picture: trampling something into the dirt."},"G3076":{"b":"From lype, sadness, pain. To lypeo is to distress, to cause pain or grief, to press sorrow onto someone. So the rich young ruler goes away lypeo, grieved, the weight of the choice pressing on him. And we are told not to grieve the Holy Spirit.","g":"grieve","h":"The picture: a weight of grief pressed on the heart."},"G3077":{"b":"Strong's says it is apparently a primary word, which means it does not come from anything else. It just means grief, pain of body or mind. There is nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"sorrow, grief","h":"No picture."},"G3078":{"b":"Strong's reads the name as grief-dispelling, from a root meaning to loosen. Lysanias is the tetrarch of Abilene named in Luke's careful dating of John's ministry. His name promises to drive sorrow away, built to sound like relief.","g":"Lysanias","h":"The picture: a name meaning grief-dispelling."},"G3079":{"b":"This is just a man's name, Claudius Lysias, the Roman commander who rescued Paul. Strong's says its origin is uncertain. A name has nothing built into it to see.","flat":1,"g":"Lysias","h":"No picture."},"G308":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is to look up. His second is to recover sight.\n\nOne word does both. When the blind man is healed, the Greek says he looked up. The eyes open and the head comes up together.","g":"look up, see again","h":"The picture: the head lifting."},"G3080":{"b":"The word means a loosening, from a word meaning to loosen or untie. It pictures a knot pulled loose, a bond undone, here the loosing of marriage. Paul says if you are bound to a wife, do not seek this.","g":"loosing, divorce","h":"The picture: the knot untied."},"G3081":{"b":"Abbott says it first meant to pay expenses, to settle the dues. Picture a toll paid so the account clears. So it profits a man. Better a millstone hung on him than that he trip up a little one.","g":"it is better","h":"The picture: paying off what is owed."},"G3082":{"b":"This is Lystra, a town in Lycaonia where Paul healed a lame man and the crowd tried to worship him as a god. Timothy came from here. The word is only the name of a place.","flat":1,"g":"Lystra","h":"No picture."},"G3083":{"b":"The root is lyo, to loosen or untie. A lytron is the price that loosens someone, the money paid to free a slave or ransom a captive. Jesus says he came to give his life as the lytron for many. The payment that unlocks them.","g":"ransom","h":"The picture: the price that unlocks a slave's chains."},"G3084":{"b":"The root is the price paid to loosen someone's chains. This verb means to pay that price and set the prisoner free. The two on the road hoped Jesus would redeem Israel. Peter says you were redeemed not with silver but with blood.","g":"redeem","h":"The picture: the price laid down to loose a captive."},"G3085":{"b":"The word means a ransoming, the buying back of a prisoner. Zacharias praises God for coming to ransom his people. It is money laid down so a captive can walk out free. Behind it lies the sense of loosing chains.","g":"redemption","h":"The picture: the price paid to free a captive."},"G3086":{"b":"The word comes from a root meaning to ransom, to buy a captive out of slavery. In Acts, Moses is called a redeemer, the man God sent to buy Israel free from Egypt.","g":"redeemer, deliverer","h":"The picture: the one who pays the ransom."},"G3087":{"b":"This comes from the word for a lamp. Abbott-Smith says it is the lampstand, the thing you set a light on so it shines for the whole room. In Revelation the seven churches are lampstands.","g":"lampstand","h":"The picture: the stand that holds the lamp."},"G3088":{"b":"Abbott describes it as a lamp, portable, and usually set on a stand. It is the small clay lamp you carry room to room. Jesus calls the eye the lamp of the body, and John the Baptist a burning lamp.","g":"lamp","h":"The picture: a little oil lamp on a stand."},"G3089":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives to loose, unbind, release, used of things tied and of animals tied up.\n\nHis second sense goes further: to resolve a whole into its parts. Undo enough knots and the thing falls apart.","g":"loose, untie","h":"The picture: undoing the knots."},"G309":{"b":"The root means to look up and to see once more. This word is the recovering of sight, the blind looking up into the light. Jesus reads it as part of his work, sight given back to those who had lost it.","g":"recovery of sight","h":"The picture: eyes opening to the light again."},"G3090":{"b":"Lois is the name of Timothy's grandmother. Strong's says it is of uncertain origin, so there is nothing behind the name to see. It is simply who she was, a woman of real faith.","flat":1,"g":"Lois","h":"No picture."},"G3091":{"b":"The name comes from a word for a veil, a covering. Lot was Abraham's nephew, who settled in Sodom and was pulled out before its destruction.","g":"Lot","h":"The picture: a veil."},"G3092":{"b":"Just a name in the list. Strong's ties it to Hebrew. It is one link in the long chain of fathers and sons that Luke records. A name points to a man, not to a thing you can see or draw.","flat":1,"g":"Maath","h":"No picture."},"G3093":{"b":"Strong's says the name of this town means the tower. Magdala was likely named for a watchtower or a tall building that marked the spot. The place where Jesus landed in Matthew 15:39 carried the name of a tower.","g":"Magdala","h":"The picture: a tower."},"G3094":{"b":"The town Magdala means the tower. Mary Magdalene is Mary of the tower town on the lake. Freed of seven demons, she stays to the end, watches the cross, comes to the tomb in the dark, and is first to see the risen Lord.","g":"Magdalene","h":"The picture: Mary of the tower town."},"G3095":{"b":"The word means the lore of the Magians, magic arts and sorceries. It is what Simon had used to amaze the crowds of Samaria, until he saw real power in the apostles' hands.","g":"sorcery, magic","h":"The picture: a bag of magic tricks."},"G3096":{"b":"The word comes from 'a Magian,' the eastern magician. In Acts it is Simon, dazzling a whole city with his spells until the apostles arrive with something greater.","g":"use sorcery","h":"The picture: the sorcerer at his craft."},"G3097":{"b":"A magos was a priest of the East, one of a Median caste who read the stars and old religion. The wise men who followed one to Bethlehem were magoi. The same word names Elymas the sorcerer, a worker of spells.","g":"magi, sorcerer","h":"The picture: an eastern star-reader."},"G3098":{"b":"The worksheet ties this name only to Gog and gives no plain meaning. Magog stands in Scripture for a distant nation gathered against the people of God.","flat":1,"g":"Magog","h":"No picture."},"G3099":{"b":"The name comes from a word for a contest or quarrel, a place of strife. Midian was a region of Arabia, where Moses fled and kept flocks for forty years.","g":"Midian","h":"The picture: strife."},"G31":{"b":"From the word for a messenger, the one who runs to bring news. So a message is what he carries in his mouth. John says the message we heard is that God is light. Picture the runner arriving with word.","g":"message","h":"The picture: the runner bringing news."},"G310":{"b":"The pieces mean up and to shout. It is a cry sent up, a loud call. In Matthew 27:46 Jesus cries out from the cross with a loud voice, My God, my God, why have you forsaken me.","g":"cry out","h":"The picture: a shout going up."},"G3100":{"b":"This word is built from the word for a learner, a pupil. To matheteuo someone is to take them on as a student, not just to teach a lesson but to enrol them for good. When Jesus says make disciples, he means make learners.","g":"disciple","h":"The picture: a pupil learning at a teacher's side."},"G3101":{"b":"Strong's defines it flatly: a learner, a pupil. Abbott-Smith builds it from the verb to learn and sets it opposite the word for teacher.\n\nSo a disciple is a student. The word says nothing more spiritual than that.","g":"disciple, learner","h":"The picture: a pupil at his lessons."},"G3102":{"b":"The word comes from 'a learner, a pupil,' made feminine. It names Tabitha, a woman disciple in Joppa, known for the coats and clothes she sewed for the widows.","g":"female disciple","h":"The picture: a woman who is a learner."},"G3103":{"b":"The name means man of a dart. It joins a word for man with one for a missile of attack, a thrown spear. Methuselah lived longer than any man in Scripture.","g":"Methuselah","h":"The picture: man of a dart."},"G3104":{"b":"This is a name and nothing more. Strong's traces it to Hebrew. It marks an ancestor in Jesus' family tree. A name is a label for a person, so there is no image hidden behind it to picture.","flat":1,"g":"Mainan","h":"No picture."},"G3105":{"b":"This word means to rave, to be out of your mind like a maniac. Strong's traces it to a craving that overtakes the senses. They told Rhoda she was mad. Festus said Paul's learning had driven him to raving. Wild and beside oneself.","g":"be mad, rave","h":"The picture: a person raving, out of his mind."},"G3106":{"b":"The root is the word for the deep happiness the old Greeks gave their gods. This verb is to point at a person and call them that, blessed, fortunate. Mary sings that from now on every generation will call her blessed.","g":"call blessed","h":"The picture: pointing and calling someone happy."},"G3107":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the old poets used this word chiefly of the gods and the departed. It belonged to those past all trouble.\n\nJesus says it over the poor and the grieving.","g":"blessed, happy","h":"The picture: the happiness of the gods."},"G3108":{"b":"This is the word for saying out loud how happy someone is. Abbott calls it a declaration of blessedness, a pointing at a person and calling them fortunate. Paul uses it for David naming the forgiven man blessed.","g":"blessedness","h":"The picture: calling someone happy out loud."},"G3109":{"b":"The name marks Macedonia, a region of Greece, home of the Macedonians. So when a man of Macedonia stands in Paul's night vision begging come over and help us, the gospel steps from Asia onto European soil for the first time.","g":"Macedonia","h":"The picture: the northern region of Greece."},"G311":{"b":"The root anaballomai means to put off. Abbott gives delay. Festus says he made no anabole but took his seat the next day to hear Paul's case. The word is pushing a matter back down the calendar.","g":"delay","h":"The picture: setting a matter aside for later."},"G3110":{"b":"This just means a Macedonian, a person from Macedonia. The name is of uncertain origin, so the Greek gives nothing to picture. It only tells you where someone is from.","flat":1,"g":"Macedonian","h":"No picture."},"G3111":{"b":"Abbott gives it plainly, a meat-market. It pictures the butcher's stalls where meat hangs for sale. Paul says eat whatever is sold there, asking no questions about where it came from.","g":"meat market","h":"The picture: meat hanging in the market stall."},"G3112":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this is really \"a long way,\" with the word for \"road\" understood. So it pictures distance as a long road stretching away. The father saw his son while he was still far off.","g":"far off","h":"The picture: a long road off."},"G3113":{"b":"Abbott says the word means from afar. It comes from the word for \"long\" or \"far.\" The tax collector stood far off and would not lift his eyes. Peter followed at a distance.","g":"from afar","h":"The picture: from far off."},"G3114":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the word behind it means long-tempered. Patience here is a temper that takes a long, long time to run out. A farmer waits like this for his crop, in no rush at all.","g":"be patient","h":"The picture: a long fuse."},"G3115":{"b":"The word joins long and temper. Makrothumia is the long fuse, the heat that takes a long time to reach the boil. God shows it, holding back anger through the days of Noah, giving even the chief of sinners time. Slow to burn.","g":"longsuffering","h":"The picture: the long fuse."},"G3116":{"b":"This is makros, long, joined to thymos, hot passion, breathing hard. To be long-tempered is to have a long fuse, slow to flare. Paul asks Agrippa to hear him this way, with patience. The image is the long breath a man takes before he loses his temper.","g":"patiently","h":"The picture: a long, slow breath before anger."},"G3117":{"b":"The word means long, in space or time. Abbott-Smith gives the far, far distant land. This is the far country the younger son travels to, so distant he can waste everything he has before word ever gets home. Long enough to get lost in.","g":"long, far","h":"The picture: the country a long way off."},"G3118":{"b":"Built from two plain words, long and time. It means long-lived. Paul quotes the command with its promise: honour your father and mother, that you may live long on the earth.","g":"long-lived","h":"The picture: a long stretch of years."},"G3119":{"b":"The root means soft. This word is softness, and so weakness, the body gone slack with sickness. Jesus went through the towns healing every disease and every softness of the body, every kind of failing.","g":"sickness","h":"The picture: the body gone soft."},"G312":{"b":"Abbott says the word means to bring back word, to report. It is the messenger returning to tell what he saw. Jesus said the Spirit will take what is his and announce it to you.","g":"announce, report","h":"The picture: bringing word back."},"G3120":{"b":"The word means soft to the touch, and so fine clothing. Jesus asks what the crowds went out to see. A man in soft clothes. Those who wear soft things live in kings' palaces. John wore rough camel hair, not the soft robes of the court.","g":"soft","h":"The picture: soft fine clothing."},"G3121":{"b":"The name means praise of God. It joins a word for fame or praise with a word for God. Mahalalel was a patriarch in the early line from Adam.","g":"Mahalalel","h":"The picture: praise of God."},"G3122":{"b":"This word just means especially or most of all. Strong's says it is the top form of an apparently primary adverb meaning \"very.\" It is a plain intensifier with nothing behind it.","flat":1,"g":"especially, most","h":"No picture."},"G3123":{"b":"Mallon means more, to a greater degree, or rather, by preference. Abbott traces its work in comparison, more than this. So how much mallon will your Father give good things, Jesus argues from less to more. The word leans the balance toward the greater side.","g":"more, rather","h":"The picture: the balance leaning toward the greater."},"G3124":{"b":"The name means king. It comes from a Hebrew word for a king. Malchus was the high priest's servant whose ear Peter cut off in the garden, and whom Jesus healed.","g":"Malchus","h":"The picture: king."},"G3125":{"b":"Strong's calls this of natural origin, our 'mammy'. It began as a child's name for mother, the sound a baby makes. Later it slid up a generation to mean grandmother. The word underneath is baby talk.","g":"grandmother","h":"The picture: the baby word mama."},"G3126":{"b":"Mammon is an Aramaic word for wealth. Strong's says it grows from a word for confidence, the thing you put your trust in. Jesus names it a rival master to God. It is money lifted up until you serve it and lean your whole weight on it.","g":"mammon","h":"The picture: money made into a master."},"G3127":{"b":"Manaen is a name, and the sources call its origin uncertain. It belongs to a teacher at Antioch who had grown up with Herod. With no meaning given, there is no picture, only the man himself.","flat":1,"g":"Manaen","h":"No picture."},"G3128":{"b":"The name means causing to forget. It comes from a word meaning to forget. Joseph gave the name to his firstborn son in Egypt, saying God had made him forget all his hardship.","g":"Manasseh","h":"The picture: causing to forget."},"G3129":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives a second sense of learning by use and practice, getting into the habit.\n\nThat is the word Paul uses in Philippians 4:11. He did not read about being content. He practised until he had it.","g":"learn","h":"The picture: learning by doing it."},"G313":{"b":"From again and a word meaning to father a child, to give birth. So it means to be born a second time. Peter uses it of new birth into living hope. Picture a baby born, but over again.","g":"beget again","h":"The picture: born a second time."},"G3130":{"b":"This comes from mainomai, to rave like a maniac. The word means madness, frenzy. Festus tells Paul his much learning has driven him to this, out of his mind. The word is the raving itself, a person no longer in control.","g":"madness","h":"The picture: a raving fit."},"G3131":{"b":"Strong's calls it \"an edible gum,\" the food that lay on the ground each morning in the wilderness. The name comes from the Hebrew, roughly \"what is it.\" So the bread from heaven that Israel ate and could not name.","g":"manna","h":"The picture: flakes of food on the desert ground."},"G3132":{"b":"Strong's traces this to a word meaning to rave as a maniac. The idea was that a seer worked himself into a frenzy before he spoke. So this is not calm foretelling but wild raving, the trade of the slave girl.","g":"to divine","h":"The picture: the raving fortune-teller."},"G3133":{"b":"First it meant a fire dying down to embers and out. Later it meant a flower drying up and withering on the stem. James says the rich man will fade like that, right in the middle of his business.","g":"fade away","h":"The picture: a fire dying out, a flower withering."},"G3134":{"b":"These are two Aramaic words carried straight into Greek, a cry from the early church. They mean the Lord comes, or our Lord has come. Paul ends the letter with them. There is no image, only the shout itself.","flat":1,"g":"Maranatha","h":"No picture."},"G3135":{"b":"This just means a pearl. It appears in do not throw your pearls before swine, and in the one pearl of great price. There is no hidden image, a pearl is simply a pearl.","flat":1,"g":"a pearl","h":"No picture."},"G3136":{"b":"This is Martha of Bethany. Strong's says her name probably means \"mistress,\" the lady of the house. It fits the woman busy serving the meal. Abbott gives no meaning for it.","g":"Martha","h":"The picture: the lady of the house."},"G3137":{"b":"The name means rebelliously. Behind it lies a word for bitterness. It was a very common name, carried by six different women in the New Testament, including the mother of Jesus.","g":"Mary","h":"The picture: rebelliously."},"G3138":{"b":"This is just the name Mark, a Christian, the one who wrote the second Gospel. It is of Latin origin. A person's name, nothing more, with nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"Mark","h":"No picture."},"G3139":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the word comes from a verb meaning \"to glisten,\" and in later writers means marble. Picture polished white stone catching the light. So the merchants mourn their marble that no one will buy.","g":"marble","h":"The picture: white glistening marble."},"G314":{"b":"Strong's says the word literally means to know again, and from there, to read. Abbott starts with recognize.\n\nAbbott also notes it often means reading aloud. Reading was something a whole room heard.","g":"read","h":"The picture: knowing the letters again."},"G3140":{"b":"This comes straight from the word for a witness, the person who stands and tells what they saw. The same root gives us martyr. So to testify of Christ is court language. You are under oath, reporting what your own eyes have seen.","g":"testify, witness","h":"The picture: a witness telling what they saw."},"G3141":{"b":"Strong's says evidence given, judicially. Abbott's sense is witness, testimony, evidence.\n\nSo testimony is courtroom language. A witness is not offering an opinion. He is stating what he saw.","g":"testimony, witness","h":"The picture: evidence given in court."},"G3142":{"b":"Abbott-Smith traces it to the word for a witness. Strong's calls it something evidential.\n\nSo it is not the person and not the speech. It is the proof itself, the thing that stands as evidence.","g":"testimony","h":"The picture: what the witness puts forward."},"G3143":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the first sense is to summon as witness. Behind the word is a witness, someone hauled in to testify. So when Paul uses it he is not just stating a thing. He is putting a witness under oath before you.","g":"testify, take to record","h":"The picture: calling a witness to the stand."},"G3144":{"b":"Abbott gives the courtroom sense first, a witness at a trial. Then he notes the use for those who have witnessed for Christ by their death.\n\nOur word martyr is this Greek word. It meant witness before it meant dying.","g":"witness, martyr","h":"The picture: a witness in the dock."},"G3145":{"b":"The word means \"to bite, chew.\" Abbott-Smith gives that plainly. Picture someone in agony biting down hard on their own tongue. So in the darkness the people gnawed their tongues for the pain.","g":"to chew, gnaw","h":"The picture: teeth gnawing in pain."},"G3146":{"b":"The root is the whip, the Roman flagellum used on criminals. To scourge is to lay that whip across a man's back. They will scourge him, Jesus says of himself. Hebrews says God scourges every son he receives. The lash falling.","g":"scourge","h":"The picture: the whip across a back."},"G3147":{"b":"This word means to whip, plainly and literally. It is the scourge coming down on the skin. Paul is bound and about to feel it when he asks whether it is lawful to whip a Roman. The word is the whip itself, doing its work.","g":"whip, scourge","h":"The picture: the lash falling on a bare back."},"G3148":{"b":"This is a whip, the Roman scourge used on criminals. The Gospels also use it for disease, as if sickness were lashes on the body. The bleeding woman is freed from her scourge. Suffering pictured as the crack of a whip.","g":"whip, scourge","h":"The picture: the Roman whip."},"G3149":{"b":"The word is the breast. A woman in the crowd calls out, blessed is the womb that bore you and the breasts that nursed you. In days of trouble, Jesus says, some will call the breasts that never nursed blessed instead.","g":"breast","h":"The picture: the breast that nurses a child."},"G315":{"b":"The root means constraint, even distress, a pressure you cannot escape. So this is to compel. The master says go out and compel them to come in, so the house will be full. A push that leaves no easy no.","g":"compel","h":"The picture: forced through the door."},"G3150":{"b":"This comes from a word for an idle talker. It means empty, foolish talk, words with nothing behind them. Paul says some had turned aside to it, wanting to teach the law without knowing what they were saying.","g":"empty talk","h":"The picture: talk that goes nowhere."},"G3151":{"b":"This joins a word meaning empty, profitless, to a word for speaking. A vain talker pours out words that are hollow. Paul warns of many such men. Their talk looks full but there is nothing in it, like a jug pouring out air.","g":"vain talker","h":"The picture: words with nothing inside."},"G3152":{"b":"The root means to no purpose, in vain. This word is empty, hollow, leading nowhere. Paul says if Christ is not raised your faith is empty. Idols are called the vain things, gods with nothing inside. Effort poured out that comes to nothing.","g":"vain, empty","h":"The picture: effort that comes to nothing."},"G3153":{"b":"The root mataios means empty, holding nothing, without profit. Mataiotes is that emptiness itself, a puff with no substance. Paul says creation was handed over to it, made to run empty, subjected to vanity against its will.","g":"vanity, emptiness","h":"The picture: an empty puff."},"G3154":{"b":"The root means empty, without profit. So this word is to be made empty, hollowed out. Abbott says to make vain, foolish. Paul says their thinking was emptied, and their foolish hearts went dark.","g":"become vain","h":"The picture: thinking emptied out and hollow."},"G3155":{"b":"Abbott ties this to a word meaning a folly, an empty thing. It means in vain, to no purpose. Jesus quotes Isaiah, in vain they worship me, teaching rules as doctrine. All the motion, none of the result. Hands hitting air.","g":"in vain","h":"The picture: effort that hits nothing."},"G3156":{"b":"Strong's traces the name to Mattathias. Picture the man himself at the tax booth, Matthew 9:9, who got up and left the money on the table to follow Jesus. Abbott lists him plainly among the twelve.","g":"Matthew","h":"The picture: the man who left the tax booth."},"G3157":{"b":"The name comes from a word meaning a present, a gift. Matthan was an ancestor of Jesus, named in the genealogy that Matthew records from Abraham down to Christ.","g":"Matthan","h":"The picture: a present."},"G3158":{"b":"Matthat is a shortened form of Mattathias. It sits in Luke's long genealogy, one quiet link in the chain of names running from Jesus back through David to Adam. Most of these men left no story, only a name passed down.","g":"Matthat","h":"The picture: a name in the family line."},"G3159":{"b":"Matthias is a shortened form of Mattathias. He steps into Scripture once. Two men stand, the disciples pray, they cast lots, and the lot falls on Matthias to take Judas's place among the Twelve. A name lifted by one drawing.","g":"Matthias","h":"The picture: the name the lot fell on."},"G316":{"b":"The root means constraint, a force pressing on you that you cannot escape. So a necessary thing is one that bears down and leaves no other way. The same word can mean close kin, the people bound to you by nature. What you cannot walk away from.","g":"necessary","h":"The picture: a pressure you cannot get out from under."},"G3160":{"b":"Mattatha is a name in Luke's genealogy of Jesus, a shortened form of Mattathias. The worksheet gives no meaning to picture. It stands as one more ancestor named in the long line, a link with no image of its own.","flat":1,"g":"Mattatha","h":"No picture."},"G3161":{"b":"The name means gift of Jah. It joins two words: a present, and Jah, a short form of the Lord's name. So the name says the gift comes from God.","g":"Mattathias","h":"The picture: gift of Jah."},"G3162":{"b":"Abbott says this is a large knife or dirk, used for sacrifice, and then a short sword or dagger. He marks it off from the big broad sword.\n\nThis is a close-up blade.","g":"sword, knife","h":"The picture: a knife, not a battle sword."},"G3163":{"b":"The root means to war, to quarrel. Strong's calls this word a battle. First it was actual fighting, blows traded. Then it came to mean the quarrels of words, strife and contention. Paul tells Timothy to have nothing to do with them.","g":"fighting, strife","h":"The picture: a fight breaking out."},"G3164":{"b":"The first sense is plain: \"to fight,\" to come to blows. From there it softens to quarrel and dispute with words. James asks where wars and fightings come from. This is the word under it, the swing before the shout.","g":"fight, strive","h":"The picture: two men coming to blows."},"G3166":{"b":"Built from \"big\" and a word for boasting, this is talking big, swelling your words up large. James says the tongue is a tiny thing that brags huge, like a small spark that sets a whole forest ablaze.","g":"boast great things","h":"The picture: swelling your words up big."},"G3167":{"b":"This word comes from the word for big or great. It means magnificent, grand. At Pentecost the crowd heard the apostles telling the great deeds of God in their own languages. Not small talk. The huge things God has done.","g":"great things","h":"The picture: something too big to miss."},"G3168":{"b":"The word rests on greatness. It means splendour, magnificence, greatness you can see and feel. When Jesus heals the boy, the crowd is amazed at the majesty of God on display. Peter saw it on the mountain. Grandeur that overwhelms.","g":"majesty","h":"The picture: blazing, weighty grandeur."},"G3169":{"b":"This joins \"great\" to a root meaning to tower up, to stand out. So it is greatness that looms, majestic. Peter uses it of the voice from the Majestic Glory on the mountain, naming Jesus his Son.","g":"majestic","h":"The picture: towering, impossible to miss."},"G317":{"b":"The root anankazo means to compel. Abbott gives by constraint. Peter tells elders to shepherd the flock not anankastos but willingly. The word is work done under pressure, an arm twisted, the opposite of a glad choice.","g":"by constraint","h":"The picture: doing it because you are forced."},"G3170":{"b":"Abbott traces it to μέγας, great. \"To make great.\" It means to enlarge, to make big, and then to call someone great and lift up their name. Mary's soul magnifies the Lord.","g":"magnify","h":"The picture: making a thing great and large."},"G3171":{"b":"The root is megas, big. Abbott gives greatly. Paul says he rejoiced megalos in the Lord that the Philippians revived their care for him. The word takes an ordinary gladness and stretches it out big, joy sized up.","g":"greatly","h":"The picture: joy on a large scale."},"G3172":{"b":"The root simply means big. This word turns bigness into a name. The writer of Hebrews says Christ sat down at the right hand of the Majesty on high. God is not called kind here, or wise. He is called the Bigness. Everything else is small beside him.","g":"majesty","h":"The picture: sheer bigness."},"G3173":{"b":"Strong's first word is simply big. Abbott starts with size you can see, a great stone, a large fish, a huge city. So when God is called great, the word reaches for the biggest thing your eyes have measured, then says bigger still.","g":"great, big","h":"The picture: bigger than anything you can measure."},"G3174":{"b":"The root is megas, big. Abbott gives greatness. Paul prays the Ephesians would grasp the megethos of God's power toward them. The word invites you to take the measure of a thing and find it far larger than you thought.","g":"greatness","h":"The picture: sheer size you have to measure."},"G3175":{"b":"The root means greatest. These are the grandees, the great men, the nobles. Herod threw a birthday feast for his lords and officers and the chief men of Galilee. The word gathers the big men of the land at the top table.","g":"great men","h":"The picture: the great men at the top table."},"G3176":{"b":"This is the top form of the word for big, meaning greatest. Nothing lies behind it but size pushed to its limit. Peter uses it of God's very great and precious promises, the largest gifts of all.","g":"exceeding great","h":"The picture: the biggest of them all."},"G3177":{"b":"Strong's: \"to explain over, i.e. translate.\" The word joins \"across\" with a word for interpreting. It takes a word in one language and hands it over in another, so John explains that Messiah means Christ.","g":"translate","h":"The picture: carrying words over into your language."},"G3178":{"b":"The word means drunkenness, the state of being intoxicated. Jesus warns his followers not to let their hearts grow weighed down with drunkenness and the cares of life. It is the heaviness of too much wine dulling a man till he cannot watch.","g":"drunkenness","h":"The picture: a head heavy with wine."},"G3179":{"b":"Built from a word for change and one meaning to stand. To take something from where it stands and set it somewhere else. God moved us out of the power of darkness into the kingdom of his Son. Shifted from one place to another.","g":"remove, transfer","h":"The picture: lifting a thing from where it stands."},"G318":{"b":"Strong's traces the root to a word for an arm, curved. Necessity is the bent arm that grips you and will not let go. Not a gentle nudge but a hold. When Paul says necessity is laid on him to preach, he means he is pinned.","g":"necessity","h":"The picture: the bent arm that grips you."},"G3180":{"b":"This word is built from the word for travelling a road. It is the trickster's winding route, the path taken to catch someone off guard. Paul warns of the deceitful scheming that lies in wait for the church. Cunning that comes by the back way.","g":"trickery, wile","h":"The picture: a roundabout road to trap you."},"G3182":{"b":"The word means to make drunk, and in the passive to get drunk. The wicked servant beats the others and gets drunk while the master is away. Paul says do not get drunk with wine but be filled with the Spirit.","g":"be drunk","h":"The picture: a man reeling with too much wine."},"G3183":{"b":"The root means to drink to intoxication, to get drunk. A methysos is a drunkard, a sot. Paul lists such among those whose way of life shuts them out of the kingdom of God.","g":"drunkard","h":"The picture: the one soaked in wine."},"G3184":{"b":"This word comes from the word for wine. It means to be drunk, soaked in it. The master keeps the good wine until the guests are drunk. These men are not drunk as you suppose, Peter says, for it is only nine in the morning.","g":"be drunk","h":"The picture: a body full of wine."},"G3186":{"b":"This is a comparative piled on a comparative, larger than larger. It only pushes size further. John says he has no greater joy than to hear that his children are walking in the truth.","g":"greater","h":"The picture: bigger still than big."},"G3187":{"b":"This is the comparative of the word for big, so it means bigger, greater. It is used when the older, elder son will serve the younger. Simply the larger set beside the smaller, more in size or in standing.","g":"greater","h":"The picture: the larger of two."},"G3188":{"b":"The root melas means black. Melan is simply the black stuff, ink. Paul says the Corinthians are his letter, written not with ink but with the Spirit of the living God, on hearts instead of stone.","g":"ink","h":"The picture: black ink."},"G3189":{"b":"The word means black, a primary word from nothing else. Set against white, it is the black horse, the sun turned black as sackcloth. Used as a noun it means the black stuff, ink. John would rather not write with paper and ink.","g":"black","h":"The picture: black ink on the page."},"G319":{"b":"The word joins 'again' with 'to make known.' Abbott says it means to recognize. In Acts it is Joseph, standing before the brothers who sold him, at last letting them know who he is.","g":"make known","h":"The picture: a face known again."},"G3190":{"b":"This is just a name, and Strong's says its origin is uncertain. It marks one ancestor in Jesus' family line. A name stands for a person, not for a thing you can see. There is nothing here to picture.","flat":1,"g":"Meleas","h":"No picture."},"G3191":{"b":"Strong's says it means to revolve something in the mind, to turn it over as you would care for a thing. Not a passing thought but attention kept on it. So the nations meletao empty things. They chewed on them, turned them round.","g":"meditate","h":"The picture: turning a thing over and over in your mind."},"G3192":{"b":"The word means honey. In Revelation the little scroll tastes sweet as honey in the mouth, then turns the stomach sour. John the Baptist lived on locusts and wild honey. It is the plain sweet food gathered from the comb.","g":"honey","h":"The picture: wild honey."},"G3194":{"b":"This is the name of an island, the one we now call Malta. Strong's says its origin is uncertain, so the name does not come from any word that means a thing we can see. Paul was shipwrecked there.","flat":1,"g":"Melita","h":"No picture."},"G3195":{"b":"Abbott gives to be about to be or do. It is the moment of standing on the edge, foot already lifted, the thing not done yet but right on the point of happening. So the age to come, ho aion ho mellon, is the world already leaning toward you.","g":"about to","h":"The picture: the foot lifted, about to step."},"G3196":{"b":"Strong's says the origin is uncertain. The word simply means a limb or part of the body.\n\nPaul's picture of Christians as members of one body is a picture he builds. It is not hiding inside the word.","flat":1,"g":"limb, member","h":"No picture."},"G3197":{"b":"Strong's reads this Hebrew name as my king. It belongs to two men in Luke's list of Jesus' ancestors, names read out one after another back toward Adam. This one carries a small crown in it, my king.","g":"Melchi","h":"The picture: the name means my king."},"G3198":{"b":"The name means king of right. It joins a word for a king with a word for the right or just. Melchizedek was the priest-king of Salem who blessed Abraham, called king of righteousness in Hebrews.","g":"Melchizedek","h":"The picture: king of right."},"G3199":{"b":"This word means to be a care or concern, as in it matters to me. Strong's calls it a primary verb, which means it does not come from anything else. There is nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"it matters, care","h":"No picture."},"G32":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is a messenger, one sent. Strong's says the root idea is to bring tidings.\n\nSo angel is a job, not a species. It names someone carrying word from one place to another.","g":"angel, messenger","h":"The picture: a runner carrying news."},"G320":{"b":"This word comes from a word meaning to know again. To read is to know the words again as your eyes cross them. This is the public reading of Scripture aloud. After the reading of the Law and Prophets, they were asked to speak.","g":"reading","h":"The picture: the scroll read aloud."},"G3200":{"b":"Strong's says this is a sheep-skin written on, our word membrane. Before paper, people wrote on scraped and dried animal hide. Paul asks for the books, and especially the parchments. He wanted his skins to read in prison.","g":"parchment","h":"The picture: a written sheep-skin."},"G3201":{"b":"This simply means to blame, to find fault. Strong's calls it a primary verb, so it does not come from anything else. God finds fault with his people, Paul says. There is nothing behind the word to see, only the act of blaming.","flat":1,"g":"find fault","h":"No picture."},"G3202":{"b":"Abbott builds this from a word meaning to blame and one meaning fate or lot. So it is complaining of your portion in life. Jude calls the false men this, always blaming their share, following their own desires.","g":"complainer","h":"The picture: cursing the lot you were dealt."},"G321":{"b":"The word means to lead up. Abbott-Smith notes that in the middle voice it is a sailor's word meaning to put to sea.\n\nMost of Paul's voyages in Acts start with this verb. Ropes off, out into open water.","g":"lead up, set sail","h":"The picture: a ship leaving harbour."},"G322":{"b":"The word joins \"up\" to \"show.\" Abbott says it means \"to lift up and show.\" When the apostles pick a replacement for Judas they ask God to lift up and show the man he has chosen. Not guessed. Pointed out.","g":"appoint, show","h":"The picture: holding a thing up so all can see."},"G323":{"b":"The root anadeiknumi means to show forth or point out. Abbott gives a shewing forth, announcement. Luke says John stayed in the desert until his anadeixis to Israel. The day he was brought out where all could see.","g":"exhibition","h":"The picture: stepping out into public view."},"G324":{"b":"Built from a word meaning to receive, to take to yourself. It is used of welcoming guests, taking travelers into your home. Publius received Paul's whole company and lodged them three days. Open hands and an open door for a stranger.","g":"receive, welcome","h":"The picture: open hands taking a guest in."},"G325":{"b":"This is ana, up, with didomi, to give. It means to give over, to hand up or deliver. The horsemen carry the commander's letter to the governor and hand it across to him. The word is the passing of something from one hand into another.","g":"hand over","h":"The picture: a letter passed from hand to hand."},"G326":{"b":"The root is the word for living, and \"again\" is added. Abbott says \"to live again, regain life.\" The father says his lost son was dead and is alive again. The same word: sin, once quiet, comes back to life in Paul.","g":"revive, live again","h":"The picture: the dead coming back to life."},"G327":{"b":"The word means to search carefully, and Abbott-Smith notes it is used for hunting down a missing person, with a hint of difficulty. This is Mary and Joseph combing Jerusalem for the boy Jesus. A hard, anxious search.","g":"seek out","h":"The picture: hunting everywhere for a lost child."},"G328":{"b":"The root is to fasten a belt. In those days a man tucked his long robe up into his belt before running or hard work. Peter says do that to your mind. Pull it together and get ready to move.","g":"gird up","h":"The picture: tucking your robe up into your belt."},"G329":{"b":"This is built from 'again', a word for living, and the word for fire. It means to kindle afresh. Paul tells Timothy to stir up the gift of God in him. Like breathing on dying coals until the fire catches again.","g":"stir up","h":"The picture: blowing embers back to flame."},"G330":{"b":"Abbott-Smith traces this to a word meaning to flourish, to put out shoots. With again in front it means to bloom once more. Paul says their care for him has flourished again, like a plant leafing out after winter.","g":"flourish again","h":"The picture: a plant sprouting green again."},"G3306":{"b":"Strong's calls it a primary verb. Nothing older stands behind it. Abbott-Smith gives no origin, only the sense: to stay, abide, remain. A plain word for staying put.","flat":1,"g":"stay, remain, abide","h":"No picture."},"G3307":{"b":"Abbott says the word means to divide into parts. It comes from the word for \"a part.\" You split one thing into portions. Jesus warns that a house divided against itself cannot stand.","g":"divide, share","h":"The picture: breaking into shares."},"G3308":{"b":"The root means to part, to disunite, to pull into parts. Merimna is worry, the mind torn up and dragged different ways. The cares of this life, Jesus says, choke the seed. A heart split apart until nothing grows.","g":"care, anxiety","h":"The picture: a mind pulled to pieces."},"G3309":{"b":"From merimna, care, solicitude. To merimnao is to be anxious, to let a worry pull the mind tight. So do not merimnate about tomorrow, do not be anxious. Jesus points to birds that neither sow nor store, and to a Father who already knows the need.","g":"be anxious","h":"The picture: the mind pulled tight with worry."},"G331":{"b":"First it meant a gift set up in a temple, something laid aside and kept for God. Then it darkened into a thing handed over to God for destruction, cursed. Paul says, let him be anathema. Set apart, but now for ruin.","g":"curse, anathema","h":"The picture: an offering set apart, then for ruin."},"G3310":{"b":"The root means a division or share. This is your portion, the piece marked off as yours. Mary chose the good portion, Jesus said, and it would not be taken from her. One part out of the whole.","g":"portion, share","h":"The picture: a piece cut off from the whole."},"G3311":{"b":"This word comes from a root meaning to part, to divide into portions. It is the act of splitting a thing and handing out shares. Hebrews says the word of God pierces to the dividing of soul and spirit. A blade parting what looked joined.","g":"dividing, distribution","h":"The picture: a blade parting what looked joined."},"G3312":{"b":"This word comes from the word to divide or apportion. Abbott-Smith gives it as a divider, the one who splits property between heirs. A man wanted Jesus to settle his inheritance, but Jesus refused, asking who made him a divider.","g":"divider","h":"The picture: the man who splits the inheritance."},"G3313":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives a part, share, portion, and says the word stretched to mean lot, destiny.\n\nThe share handed to you becomes the life you get. Strong's traces it to an old word for getting an allotment.","g":"part, share","h":"The picture: your slice of it."},"G3314":{"b":"Built from the words for middle and day, mesembria is midday, the sun at the top of the sky. Because the noon sun stands in the south, the word also came to mean the south. Both meanings sit inside one high sun.","g":"noon, south","h":"The picture: the sun straight overhead at the middle of the day."},"G3315":{"b":"This comes from the word for a go-between, the one who stands in the middle of two parties. God stepped in between himself and us, guaranteeing his promise with an oath so it could not be doubted.","g":"mediate","h":"The picture: the man who stands in the middle."},"G3316":{"b":"The root simply means middle. A mesites is the man who stands in the gap between two sides and joins their hands. One mesites between God and men, Paul says. Someone standing in the middle, touching both.","g":"mediator","h":"The picture: a man standing in the middle."},"G3317":{"b":"The word puts \"middle\" onto \"night.\" It is midnight, the hinge of the dark hours when everyone sleeps. A friend comes knocking at this hour asking for bread. The master may come home at midnight, Jesus warns, so keep watch.","g":"midnight","h":"The picture: the dead middle of the night."},"G3318":{"b":"The name joins \"middle\" to \"river.\" Strong's spells it out: the country lying between the Euphrates and the Tigris, land cupped between two running streams. From there some had come to Jerusalem for the feast.","g":"Mesopotamia","h":"The picture: the land held between two rivers."},"G3319":{"b":"Abbott gives middle, in the middle or midst. Mesos is the center point, the spot with the same distance on every side. So where two or three gather, Christ stands en meso, right in the middle of them, not off at the edge.","g":"middle, midst","h":"The picture: dead center, in the middle."},"G332":{"b":"The root is the anathema, a thing put under a ban, devoted to destruction. To anathematizo is to call that curse down. Peter does it on himself, swearing he never knew the man. Others bind themselves this way, vowing not to eat till Paul is dead.","g":"curse","h":"The picture: a thing set apart to be destroyed."},"G3320":{"b":"Built from two plain words, middle and wall. A mesotoichon is the wall that stands in the middle and keeps two sides apart. Paul says Christ broke down the middle wall that divided Jew and Gentile.","g":"middle wall","h":"The picture: a wall down the middle."},"G3321":{"b":"The word joins middle and sky. It is the top of the sky, the spot where the sun stands at noon, seen by everyone. In Revelation an eagle cries out from mid-heaven. It flies where the whole earth can see and hear it.","g":"mid-heaven","h":"The picture: the sun straight overhead at noon."},"G3322":{"b":"From a word for middle. To be at the middle, mostly of time, halfway through. Picture the exact midpoint of a road between start and finish. When the feast was half over, Jesus went up into the temple and taught.","g":"be about the midst","h":"The picture: the midpoint of the road."},"G3323":{"b":"The title comes from a word meaning to rub with oil. To anoint someone was to pour oil on them and set them apart. Messiah means the anointed one, the promised king, which is Christ in Greek.","g":"Messiah","h":"The picture: one rubbed with oil."},"G3324":{"b":"This just means full, whether a net full of fish or a heart full of feeling. Strong's calls it of uncertain derivation. Nothing lies behind it to picture.","flat":1,"g":"full","h":"No picture."},"G3325":{"b":"This word comes from a word meaning full. It means to fill right up. At Pentecost the mockers said the disciples were full of new wine, sloshing with it, drunk. The word is about being filled to overflowing.","g":"to fill","h":"The picture: filled to the brim."},"G3327":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means \"to pass over from one place to another.\" It is the word for leaving one spot for the next. John uses it for passing out of death into life.","g":"pass over, move","h":"The picture: stepping across to another place."},"G3328":{"b":"The root means to throw. With the word for change it means to throw something across, to turn it about. Abbott says to change one's mind. The islanders threw their opinion right around and called Paul a god.","g":"change mind","h":"The picture: throwing your view over to the other side."},"G3329":{"b":"The word means to lead something across, to turn it about to a new direction. Abbott gives to turn about, direct. Picture a hand on the reins turning the whole animal. That is how James uses it, of small things that steer large ones.","g":"turn about","h":"The picture: a hand on the reins turning the animal."},"G333":{"b":"The root means to be a spectator, to watch as at a show, and \"again\" is added. So it is looking a second time, carefully, going back over with the eyes. Paul walked through Athens looking hard at their altars and found one to an unknown god.","g":"consider","h":"The picture: taking a second, careful look."},"G3330":{"b":"Built from a word meaning to give and one meaning with. It is to give someone a share of what you have. Have two coats, John says, and hand one over. The giving that splits your portion with another.","g":"share, impart","h":"The picture: handing over part of what you hold."},"G3331":{"b":"The word means a change of position, a removal. It is picking something up here and setting it down there. Hebrews uses it for Enoch. God moved him so he did not see death. The same word covers moving an old law aside to make room for a new one.","g":"change, removal","h":"The picture: lifting a thing from one place to another."},"G3332":{"b":"This joins a word for change to airo, to lift or carry away. Metairo is to pick yourself up and move somewhere else. It marks the moment Jesus finishes teaching a crowd and lifts himself away to the next place.","g":"depart","h":"The picture: picking yourself up to move on."},"G3333":{"b":"The word joins \"across\" to \"to call (properly, aloud.\" To call someone over from where they are to where you are. Joseph sends and calls his father Jacob down to Egypt. A voice that summons a man to move.","g":"summon, call for","h":"The picture: calling a man over from where he is."},"G3334":{"b":"Built from a word meaning to stir or move. Metakineo means to shift away, to be moved off a place. Paul says stay in the faith, not shifted away from the hope of the gospel you heard.","g":"move away","h":"The picture: shoved off your spot."},"G3335":{"b":"Meta means with, and lambano means to take. Metalambano pictures reaching in and taking your share, as of food at a table. The farmer who works gets the first share of the crops. To get a portion and use it, not just watch.","g":"partake, share","h":"The picture: taking your share at the table."},"G3336":{"b":"The root means to take and share in. Here it is the taking of food, receiving your portion. Paul says the foods God made are to be received with thanksgiving, not forbidden by those who know the truth.","g":"partaking","h":"The picture: taking your share at the table."},"G3337":{"b":"Built from a word meaning to make different. It is trading one thing for another. Paul says people exchanged the truth of God for a lie, handing over the real thing and taking the false in its place. A swap, straight across.","g":"exchange","h":"The picture: a straight swap."},"G3338":{"b":"Strong's reads this as to care afterwards. It is built from a word for afterward and a word for caring. The concern that arrives once the deed is already done. Judas felt it and carried the silver back. Being sorry, but too late.","g":"regret, repent","h":"The picture: the care that comes too late."},"G3339":{"b":"The word joins \"change\" to a word for fashioning a shape. It is not a new coat of paint. The form underneath is remade. On the mountain Christ's face and clothes are changed this way, and Paul says believers are changed the same, from the inside.","g":"transform","h":"The picture: the shape itself made new."},"G3340":{"b":"Abbott says it means to change one's mind or purpose. Strong's says to think differently or afterwards.\n\nAbbott adds that in the New Testament it always involves amendment. The mind changes and the life follows it.","g":"repent","h":"The picture: changing your mind."},"G3341":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives the plain sense first. After-thought. A change of mind.\n\nSo repentance starts in the head. You look at the thing again and see it differently. The turning follows the seeing.","g":"repentance","h":"The picture: the second thought."},"G3343":{"b":"Strong's: \"to send from elsewhere, i.e. to summon.\" It joins \"send\" with a word for a change of place. You send a messenger out so that a person is fetched and brought back to you.","g":"send for","h":"The picture: send out to bring someone back."},"G3344":{"b":"This word is built from a word for change and a word meaning to twist right around. To turn a thing completely backward. The sun turned to darkness. And it is used for twisting the gospel into its opposite.","g":"pervert, turn","h":"The picture: twisting a thing right around backward."},"G3345":{"b":"The root is schema, the outward figure or fashion of a thing. This verb changes that outward shape. Paul says Satan does it, dressing up as an angel of light. It is a change of costume, the surface made to look like something else.","g":"transform, disguise","h":"The picture: changing the outward shape."},"G3346":{"b":"The parts mean change and to place. To pick a thing up and set it down somewhere else. Enoch was taken, carried over so he did not see death. Jacob's bones were moved to Shechem. Paul marvels the Galatians moved so fast to another gospel.","g":"transfer, change","h":"The picture: lifting a thing and setting it elsewhere."},"G3347":{"b":"Built from meta and epeita, thereafter. Abbott gives afterwards. Hebrews says Esau metepeita wanted the blessing and was rejected. The word marks the too-late moment, wishing that arrives once the door has closed.","g":"afterward","h":"The picture: what comes only after the fact."},"G3348":{"b":"This word is built from with and to hold. To partake is to have a hold on something along with others. Paul uses it of eating from the one loaf. Many hands on the same bread, each with a real and equal share.","g":"partake","h":"The picture: taking hold of the same thing together."},"G3349":{"b":"This word first means to raise on high, into mid-air. From there it means to hang in suspense, tossed and anxious. Do not seek anxiously what you will eat, Jesus says, and do not be left dangling. Your Father knows what you need.","g":"be of doubtful mind","h":"The picture: hung up in mid-air with nothing beneath."},"G335":{"b":"Built from not and aidos, a sense of shame. Abbott gives shamelessness, importunity. Jesus tells of a man knocking at midnight who gets bread not for friendship but for his anaideia. Bare-faced persistence that will not be embarrassed off the step.","g":"importunity","h":"The picture: banging on the door with no shame."},"G3350":{"b":"The word joins change with house. It means moving your dwelling, and in Matthew it names the exile to Babylon. Picture a family torn from its home and marched to a far country. The genealogy of Jesus turns on this uprooting.","g":"carrying away, exile","h":"The picture: a household carried off from home."},"G3351":{"b":"The word behind this one means an emigrant, one who changes his house for another. \"Change\" sits inside it, and the root is the word for house. So to metoikizo is to move a whole household. God moved Abraham this way, out of Haran into the land.","g":"carry away, exile","h":"The picture: a whole household moved to a new home."},"G3352":{"b":"The root means to share, even to eat and drink together. Abbott-Smith gives sharing, fellowship. Paul asks what share light can have with darkness, what portion the two could ever hold in common.","g":"fellowship","h":"The picture: two people sharing one plate."},"G3353":{"b":"This is a sharer, one who holds a thing in common with others. Luke uses it for the fishing partners in the other boat who came to help haul the huge catch. Hebrews calls believers partakers of Christ. Someone who shares in the same thing.","g":"partaker, partner","h":"The picture: fishing partners hauling in one catch."},"G3354":{"b":"Abbott-Smith traces this to the word for a measure. It means to measure a thing by a set standard. Jesus says the measure you use on others is the measure used back on you.","g":"measure","h":"The picture: measuring with a measuring-stick."},"G3355":{"b":"From a word meaning to measure. A metretes is a set measure for liquids, near nine gallons. Six stone jars stood at Cana, each holding two or three such measures. Jesus turned the water in them to wine.","g":"firkin, measure","h":"The picture: the great stone water jars."},"G3356":{"b":"This is built from words for measured and for passion, moderating one's passions. It is feeling held to measure, neither cold nor boiling over. The high priest can deal gently with those who go astray, because he is weak too.","g":"deal gently","h":"The picture: feeling held within measure."},"G3357":{"b":"This comes from a measure, a measuring stick. Moderately means kept within measure. But here it says they were not a little comforted about the boy, which is a way of saying comforted beyond all measure.","g":"moderately","h":"The picture: measured out."},"G3358":{"b":"Abbott says it is that which is used for measuring, a measure. Picture the cup or basket that scoops out grain. \"With the measure you use, it will be measured to you.\"","g":"measure","h":"The picture: the measuring cup."},"G3359":{"b":"This word is built from a prefix and the word for an eye. The forehead is the space above the eyes, the flat front of the head. In Revelation the mark, and the name of God, are placed right there, where everyone can see whose you are.","g":"forehead","h":"The picture: the flat space above the eyes."},"G336":{"b":"The word comes from a root meaning to take up and, by force, to take away, violently. It is the plain word for killing. Saul stood by, giving his glad approval to Stephen's death.","g":"killing, death","h":"The picture: a life taken away."},"G3365":{"b":"The word means by no means, not at all, a hard no. It is what Peter says when the sheet of unclean animals drops from heaven: by no means, Lord, I have never eaten anything unclean. A door slammed shut, even to God's voice.","g":"by no means","h":"The picture: Peter's flat refusal."},"G3368":{"b":"Built from not and pote, ever. Abbott gives never. Paul describes people always learning yet medepote able to reach the knowledge of truth. Endless study, and the door to arriving stays closed at every moment.","g":"never","h":"The picture: the door of ever shut tight."},"G337":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is to take up, and his example is Acts 7:21, Pharaoh's daughter lifting baby Moses out of the water.\n\nThe same word then means to take a man away for good. To kill.","g":"kill, take away","h":"The picture: picked up and carried off."},"G3370":{"b":"The root marks a native of Media, east of Babylon. Luke lists Medos among the nations at Pentecost who heard their own language spoken. The word puts a face from a distant land into the astonished crowd in Jerusalem.","g":"a Mede","h":"The picture: a man from Media in the crowd."},"G3371":{"b":"This joins not to yet, meaning no longer, no more. It draws a line across time and says the thing stops here. So sin meketi, sin no more, tells the healed man the old life ends at this spot. Whatever was going on is not to go on.","g":"no longer","h":"The picture: a line drawn, go no further."},"G3372":{"b":"This word is kin to megas, big, and means length, how far a thing stretches. Paul prays you would grasp the breadth and length and depth and height of Christ's love, a thing too large to measure to its end.","g":"length","h":"The picture: how far a thing stretches."},"G3373":{"b":"The root is the word for length. This word means to grow longer, to stretch out, and it was used of plants shooting up. In Mark 4:27 the farmer sleeps and rises, and the seed sprouts and grows tall, he knows not how.","g":"grow, lengthen","h":"The picture: the stalk stretching taller."},"G3374":{"b":"This comes from the word for a sheep. It is a sheepskin, the rough hide the poor and the prophets wore. The faithful wandered in sheepskins, destitute, afflicted, and badly treated, with nowhere to call home.","g":"sheepskin","h":"The picture: a rough sheepskin cloak."},"G3375":{"b":"A small particle of assurance, verily, truly, surely. Hebrews puts it in God's oath to Abraham: surely I will bless you and multiply you. It is the underline under a promise, the voice saying you can stake everything on this.","g":"surely","h":"The picture: God's word underlined."},"G3376":{"b":"Strong's says this is a primary word, which means it does not come from anything else. It just means a month. There is nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"month","h":"No picture."},"G3377":{"b":"Abbott gives to disclose, to make known, and in court, to inform. Picture the one who steps forward and tells what was hidden. When a plot against Paul was menyo, brought into the open, he was sent away safe, Acts 23:30.","g":"disclose, report","h":"The picture: bringing the hidden thing to light."},"G338":{"b":"This word puts \"not\" in front of aitia, a cause or a legal charge. So anaitios is the one there is no case against, no crime to name. Jesus says the priests would not have condemned this guiltless man if they had understood mercy.","g":"innocent","h":"The picture: no charge to bring."},"G3380":{"b":"The word means not yet. Paul uses it of Jacob and Esau: before the twins were born, before they had done any good or evil, God's choice was already made. It marks the ground just ahead of an event, not yet crossed.","g":"not yet","h":"The picture: before it has happened."},"G3382":{"b":"The word means the thigh. Abbott-Smith gives \"the thigh.\" Picture the strong upper leg, where a robe falls and where a sword hangs. So on his thigh the rider has a name written, King of kings and Lord of lords.","g":"thigh","h":"The picture: the thigh."},"G3384":{"b":"Strong's calls it apparently a primary word. Abbott gives no origin. It means mother, and the sources will not take it back any further than that.","flat":1,"g":"mother","h":"No picture."},"G3386":{"b":"A strengthened particle meaning let alone. Abbott gives much more. Paul says if believers will judge angels, metige the ordinary matters of this life. The word leans on the big case to settle the small one.","g":"how much more","h":"The picture: if the greater, then surely the lesser."},"G3388":{"b":"The root is the word for a mother. This is the womb itself, where a mother carries her child. Luke quotes the law: every firstborn male that opens the womb is holy to the Lord, as Jesus is brought to the temple.","g":"womb","h":"The picture: the mother's womb."},"G3389":{"b":"Meter is mother. The rest is a word meaning to thresh, to beat grain flat on the threshing-floor. So the word pictures a man beating down his own mother. Paul names it among the sins the law stands against.","g":"mother-killer","h":"The picture: beating a mother down like grain."},"G339":{"b":"The roots are \"up\" and \"to sit\". Together they mean to sit up, to rise from lying flat. Luke uses it for the widow's dead son at Nain: Jesus speaks, and the young man sits up on the bier and begins to talk.","g":"sit up","h":"The picture: sitting bolt upright again."},"G3392":{"b":"The first sense is to dye or stain, color soaked into cloth. To defile is to stain a thing so the mark stays. They would not enter Pilate's hall for fear of being defiled before the Passover. A stain that clings.","g":"defile, stain","h":"The picture: a stain soaked into cloth."},"G3393":{"b":"The root means to sully or taint. Where the kindred word was the act of staining, this is the stain itself. Peter warns those who escaped the world's filth against being tangled in it again.","g":"pollution","h":"The picture: the stain left behind."},"G3394":{"b":"The root means to sully, to taint, to smear. So this is the act of defiling. Peter uses it of those who chase the flesh's polluting desires and despise authority. Bold and willful.","g":"uncleanness","h":"The picture: smearing something with a stain."},"G3395":{"b":"This word comes from the verb to mix. It means a mixture. John uses it of the myrrh and aloes Nicodemus brought to bury Jesus, blended together, about a hundred pounds. Two things stirred into one.","g":"mixture","h":"The picture: two spices blended into one."},"G3396":{"b":"This is the plain word for mixing, stirring one thing into another until they are one. At the cross they offer Jesus wine mixed with gall. Pilate had mingled the blood of Galileans with their sacrifices. The word is simple, the scenes are not.","g":"mix","h":"The picture: two things stirred into one."},"G3398":{"b":"Strong's calls it apparently a primary word, so nothing older stands behind it. Abbott-Smith gives small, little, and then only lists how it is used. Size, and nothing more.","flat":1,"g":"small, little","h":"No picture."},"G3399":{"b":"This is the name of a city on the coast of Asia Minor. Its origin is uncertain. A place on the map, with no picture inside the word itself for us to see.","flat":1,"g":"Miletus","h":"No picture."},"G34":{"b":"The root means to lead, to drive. A herd is a mass of animals driven along as one body. The pigs that Jesus sent the demons into were such a herd, and they rushed down the steep bank together into the sea.","g":"herd","h":"The picture: animals driven along together."},"G340":{"b":"The root is kainos, new in the sense of fresh. Abbott gives to renew. Hebrews warns it is impossible to anakainizo some back to repentance. The word is restoring worn things to newness, a freshness given a second time.","g":"to renew","h":"The picture: making a thing fresh and new again."},"G3400":{"b":"This is a Roman mile, which Strong's calls a thousand paces. Jesus says if forced to go one mile, go two. Picture the long stretch of road under your feet, a thousand steps, then a thousand more.","g":"a mile","h":"The picture: a thousand paces of road."},"G3401":{"b":"The root is the word for a mime, an actor. This word is to imitate, to copy the way a mime copies. Paul says imitate us. The writer says imitate the faith of your leaders, watch them and do the same.","g":"to imitate","h":"The picture: an actor copying every move."},"G3402":{"b":"This is the word behind our \"mime.\" A mimetes watches and copies, matching every move he sees. So when Paul says be mimetai of me as I am of Christ, he means watch and do the same. Copy the pattern.","g":"imitator","h":"The picture: a mime copying every move."},"G3403":{"b":"The word means to remind yourself of something. Abbott-Smith notes that with a negative, used of sins, it equals forgiving.\n\nHebrews says God will not remember them. Not forgetfulness. A decision not to raise it.","g":"remember","h":"The picture: never bringing it up again."},"G3404":{"b":"Strong's traces it to a primary word for hatred and stops. There is nothing behind it to look at.\n\nAbbott does note it can carry the softer sense of loving one thing less than another.","flat":1,"g":"hate","h":"No picture."},"G3405":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this means payment of wages. It is built from the word for wages and the word for paying back. What is earned gets handed over, good or bad. Hebrews says Moses looked past Egypt's riches to this payday. He worked for a wage still to come.","g":"recompense, reward","h":"The picture: wages paid into your hand."},"G3406":{"b":"Two words join here, wages and giving back. It names the one who pays what is owed. God is a rewarder of those who diligently seek him, handing out what their faith is due.","g":"rewarder","h":"The picture: the paymaster handing out wages."},"G3407":{"b":"The word comes from the word for wages, pay for service. Abbott says \"a hired servant.\" The lost son remembers that his father's hired hands have bread to spare, and decides to go back and ask to be one of them.","g":"hired servant","h":"The picture: the hired hand working for a wage."},"G3408":{"b":"Abbott says the word properly means wages, hire. What a worker is handed at the end of the day.\n\nThe same word is used for God's reward. Reward in the Gospels is pay language.","g":"wages, reward","h":"The picture: the day's pay."},"G3409":{"b":"The root is misthos, wages, pay for a day's work. Misthoo is to hire someone for it. In the parable the landowner goes out to the market to hire laborers for his vineyard, agreeing on a coin for the day.","g":"hire","h":"The picture: hiring day-workers for a wage."},"G341":{"b":"This is built from a word meaning new, fresh, with ana for again. To make new once more. Paul says though the outward man is decaying, the inward man is renewed day by day, made fresh each morning.","g":"renew","h":"The picture: made fresh each morning."},"G3410":{"b":"The root means to hire, to let out for wages. So this is a place held for a price, a hired dwelling. Abbott says a hired dwelling. Paul lived two years in his own rented house in Rome, welcoming all who came.","g":"hired house","h":"The picture: a house paid for by rent."},"G3411":{"b":"The root is to hire for wages. This is the hired hand, the man who works only for his pay. Jesus says the hireling sees the wolf coming and runs, because the sheep are not his own. He is in it for the money, not the flock.","g":"hireling","h":"The picture: the paid hand who runs when danger comes."},"G3412":{"b":"This is Mitylene, a town on the island of Lesbos. It is a bare harbor name where Paul's ship put in for a night, so there is nothing behind it to picture.","flat":1,"g":"Mitylene","h":"No picture."},"G3413":{"b":"The name asks who is like God, and expects the answer no one. It joins a word meaning who with a word for strength or God. Michael is the archangel who stands guard over God's people.","g":"Michael","h":"The picture: who (is) like God?"},"G3414":{"b":"Abbott says this was \"a weight and a sum of money = 100 shekels.\" Before coins, silver was weighed out to pay. So the mina was both a weight and the money it named. In the parable a servant is handed one to trade.","g":"mina, pound","h":"The picture: money you weigh out."},"G3416":{"b":"This is the name Mnason, a Christian of Cyprus and an early disciple who hosted Paul. Its origin is uncertain and it labels a person, so there is nothing here to picture.","flat":1,"g":"Mnason","h":"No picture."},"G3417":{"b":"From the verb to recall, to bring back to mind. It means remembrance, and the mention Paul makes of his friends. He tells them, I make mention of you always in my prayers. Holding someone in memory before God.","g":"remembrance","h":"The picture: calling you to mind."},"G3418":{"b":"Strong's: \"a memorial, i.e. sepulchral monument.\" Abbott ties it to the word for remembering. A grave is a marker that keeps the dead in memory, a remembering-stone set over the place of burial.","g":"tomb, grave","h":"The picture: a stone that keeps a memory."},"G3419":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is a memorial, record. Then a monument. Then a tomb.\n\nThe common word for a grave is built on remembering. A grave is what keeps the name where people can still see it.","g":"tomb, grave","h":"The picture: a reminder in stone."},"G342":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to renovate, to make new again. Renewing the mind is not a fresh start from nothing. It is the old self worked over and made new, like a house done up again.","g":"renewing","h":"The picture: the old house made new."},"G3420":{"b":"The root is the family of words for calling to mind. Abbott gives memory, remembrance, mention. Peter says he will make sure that after his death they can keep these truths in mneme. A store of memory built to outlast him.","g":"memory","h":"The picture: holding a thing fast in memory."},"G3421":{"b":"From mneme, memory. To mnemoneuo is to call to mind, to remember, to haul a thing back up from the past. So remember Lot's wife, mnemoneuete, and remember my chains, Paul writes. The word tugs the forgotten thing back into view.","g":"remember","h":"The picture: pulling a thing back to mind."},"G3422":{"b":"The root is to remember, to keep in mind. This is a memorial, a thing kept so someone is not forgotten. When the woman poured perfume on Jesus, he said wherever the gospel is preached, her deed will be told as a memorial of her.","g":"memorial","h":"The picture: a keepsake that makes you remember."},"G3423":{"b":"Strong's traces this to giving a souvenir, an engagement present, and so to betroth. It is the promise of marriage sealed with a gift. Mary was betrothed to Joseph this way, pledged to him but not yet taken home.","g":"to betroth","h":"The picture: the engagement gift."},"G3424":{"b":"The pieces mean with difficulty and to talk. It is a man who can barely get words out, tongue-tied. In Mark 7:32 they bring Jesus a deaf man who speaks with great difficulty, and Jesus touches his tongue and opens his ears.","g":"speech-impaired","h":"The picture: words that will not come out."},"G3425":{"b":"This word comes from a word meaning toil. It means hardly, only with great struggle. The spirit tearing at the boy would barely leave him, letting go with difficulty. It names an effort, not a thing you can see.","flat":1,"g":"hardly","h":"No picture."},"G3426":{"b":"Strong's says a modius is a measure for dry goods, the basket or the amount it holds. It is the bushel Jesus names. No one lights a lamp and puts it under the basket. The vessel itself is the picture.","g":"bushel","h":"The picture: the bushel basket over the lamp."},"G3428":{"b":"The root is the word for a paramour, one who breaks a marriage. This is the woman who does it, the adulteress. Jesus calls his generation adulterous, a people unfaithful to God as a wife is unfaithful to her husband. Vows broken.","g":"adulteress","h":"The picture: the wife who breaks her vows."},"G3429":{"b":"From the word for an adulterer. It means to commit adultery. Jesus says a man who divorces his wife and marries another commits it. Scripture also turns the image on a people unfaithful to God. A broken vow.","g":"commit adultery","h":"The picture: breaking the marriage bond."},"G343":{"b":"This is built from a word meaning to cover, with ana reversing it, to uncover. It means to lift the veil off. Paul says in Christ the veil over the old covenant is taken away, and we behold with open face.","g":"unveil","h":"The picture: the veil lifted off."},"G3430":{"b":"The word is plain, adultery, breaking faith with a spouse. John's scene shows it, the woman dragged before Jesus, caught in the act. Jesus says it starts earlier, that such things come out of the heart before they ever reach the bed.","g":"adultery","h":"The picture: the broken marriage bond."},"G3431":{"b":"The root is the adulterer, the man who takes what is bound to another. Moicheuō is to break the marriage covenant. Jesus pushes it inward, the look of lust already commits it in the heart. The prophets call idolatry this too, a covenant broken.","g":"commit adultery","h":"The picture: taking what is bound to another."},"G3432":{"b":"The word names an adulterer, a man unfaithful to the marriage bed. The Pharisee in the temple thanks God he is not one of these. Scripture also uses it of a people who break faith with God, chasing other loves.","g":"adulterer","h":"The picture: the man who steals into another's marriage."},"G3433":{"b":"Abbott ties this to a word for toil. It means barely, scarcely, only with hard struggle. Paul's ship could hardly work its way along the coast against the wind. Peter says the righteous are scarcely saved. Getting through by the narrowest margin.","g":"with difficulty","h":"The picture: barely getting through by hard toil."},"G3434":{"b":"The name comes from a word meaning to reign, the same root behind the word for king. Moloch was a pagan idol, a false king, to whom people offered their children in fire.","g":"Moloch","h":"The picture: the one who reigns."},"G3435":{"b":"Abbott's plain sense is to stain, soil, defile, to smear dirt on something clean. In the New Testament it is always figurative. Revelation praises the few who have not soiled their garments, whose clothes are still unstained.","g":"defile","h":"The picture: a stain on clean cloth."},"G3436":{"b":"The root means to soil, to smear dirty. Strong's gives a stain. Paul says to wash off every defilement of body and spirit, scrubbing the mark out rather than living with it set in.","g":"filthiness, stain","h":"The picture: a stain soaked into cloth."},"G3437":{"b":"The root is memphomai, to blame. Abbott gives blame, complaint. Paul says if anyone has a momphe against another, forgive as the Lord forgave you. The word is the specific fault you are nursing, the charge you keep on file.","g":"complaint","h":"The picture: a grievance held against someone."},"G3438":{"b":"The root means to stay or remain, and this is the place where you stay. Abbott says \"an abode.\" Jesus says his Father's house has many of these, room for all, and that he and the Father will come and make their home with anyone who loves him.","g":"abode, dwelling","h":"The picture: a room kept ready for you to stay."},"G3439":{"b":"Abbott-Smith builds it from only and kind or born. It pictures an only child, the single one of its kind. He points to only sons and daughters, like the widow's only son. John uses it of Jesus, the only Son.","g":"only, only begotten","h":"The picture: the only child."},"G344":{"b":"The root means to bend. With back added, it is to bend back, to return. Picture a path that curves and returns the way it came. Jesus says if the house is not worthy, your blessing of peace bends back to you.","g":"return, turn back","h":"The picture: the road bending back."},"G3440":{"b":"This is the adverb of monos, alone or single. It fences off one thing and shuts out the rest, only this, merely this. So only believe, monon pisteue, strips everything else away and leaves faith standing by itself.","g":"only, merely","h":"The picture: just the one, nothing else."},"G3441":{"b":"Strong's ties this to the verb to stay, to remain. Monos is what is left remaining when the rest are gone, alone, single, by itself. So Jesus goes up the mountain to pray monos, everyone else fallen away, one man left standing before God.","g":"alone, only","h":"The picture: the one left standing alone."},"G3442":{"b":"This joins monos, single, to ophthalmos, the eye. Monophthalmos is one-eyed. Jesus says it is better to enter life with one eye than to keep both and be thrown into the fire. Better maimed and alive.","g":"one-eyed","h":"The picture: a man with only one eye."},"G3443":{"b":"The root monos means alone. So this is to be left by yourself, forsaken and without support. Paul speaks of the widow left truly alone, who sets her hope on God and keeps on in prayer.","g":"left alone","h":"The picture: left standing all alone."},"G3444":{"b":"The word means form, shape, appearance, but deeper, the essential form that makes a thing what it is. Paul says Christ was in the form of God and took the form of a servant. Not a costume. The real shape underneath.","g":"form, shape","h":"The picture: the shape a thing truly has."},"G3445":{"b":"The root is the word for shape. Abbott-Smith says to form. Paul says he is in labor over the Galatians again, until Christ is formed in them, a shape pressed into their lives.","g":"form","h":"The picture: a shape being molded, like a form taking shape in the womb."},"G3446":{"b":"The root means to fashion, to shape. This is the shaping itself, the outline or form of a thing. Paul warns of those who keep the outward form of godliness but have none of its power. A shape with nothing filling it.","g":"form, outline","h":"The picture: the outline of a shape."},"G3447":{"b":"The word joins 'a young bullock' with 'to make.' It is the exact word for what Israel did at Sinai, molding a metal calf and bowing to the work of their own hands.","g":"make a calf","h":"The picture: shaping the golden calf."},"G3448":{"b":"This is a young calf. The father kills the fatted calf when the lost son comes home. Hebrews speaks of the blood of calves. Oddly the word first meant a young shoot on a plant, then any young thing, then the calf in the stall.","g":"calf","h":"The picture: a young calf."},"G3449":{"b":"This word is kin to a word meaning with difficulty. Mochthos is grinding, wearing labor, the kind of toil that leaves you spent. Paul names it among his hardships, working in labor and toil night and day so he would burden no one.","g":"toil","h":"The picture: grinding, wearing labor."},"G345":{"b":"Abbott says it means to recline at table. They did not sit to eat. They lay back on couches, propped on an elbow. That is how John leaned back on Jesus at the last supper.","g":"recline at table","h":"The picture: leaning back at the table."},"G3451":{"b":"The word comes from the Muses. Abbott-Smith gives \"a minstrel, musician.\" Picture a player bent over his strings, filling the hall with sound. So the music of harpists and musicians will be heard in Babylon no more.","g":"musician","h":"The picture: a musician at his instrument."},"G3452":{"b":"This word means marrow, the soft core hidden inside the bone. It is the deepest, most guarded part of the body. God's word reaches even there, dividing joints and marrow, laying the innermost self open.","g":"marrow","h":"The picture: the marrow inside the bone."},"G3453":{"b":"Abbott-Smith traces this to a word meaning to shut the mouth. It was used of being initiated into secret rites, sworn to silence. Paul says he has learned the secret of being content, whether full or hungry.","g":"learn the secret","h":"The picture: lips sealed, let into a secret."},"G3454":{"b":"Abbott-Smith traces this from plain speech to a story, and then to a fable set against a true account. A mythos is invented, not real history. Peter says he did not follow such tales when he told of Christ. He saw it with his eyes.","g":"fable, myth","h":"The picture: a made-up tale."},"G3455":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this word is used of oxen to low or bellow, and of a lion to roar. The word imitates the sound itself. Picture a deep animal roar rolling out. So the mighty angel cried out with a voice like a lion roaring.","g":"to roar, bellow","h":"The picture: an ox bellowing."},"G3456":{"b":"Abbott-Smith traces this to the word for the nose. To mock here is to turn up the nose or sneer at someone, looking down on them. Paul writes that God is not mocked. You cannot sneer at him.","g":"mock","h":"The picture: turning up the nose."},"G3457":{"b":"The word belongs to the mill, its root \"a grinder, a millstone.\" Abbott says \"of a mill.\" Jesus says it would be better to have one of these great stones hung round your neck and be thrown in the sea than to trip a little one.","g":"of a mill","h":"The picture: the heavy grinding stone of a mill."},"G3458":{"b":"A mylos is a mill, and its big stone, the millstone that grinds grain to flour. The kind Jesus names is the great one a donkey turns. Better that hung round your neck in the sea, he says, than to trip a little one.","g":"millstone","h":"The picture: the heavy stone that grinds the grain."},"G346":{"b":"This word gathers many things and presents them as a whole, bringing them under one heading. Strong's notes its root is the word for head. Paul says God will gather up all things in heaven and earth under one head, Christ.","g":"sum up","h":"The picture: everything brought under one head."},"G3460":{"b":"This is a place name, Myra, a city in Lycia on the coast of Asia Minor. There the soldiers found another ship to put Paul aboard. The name has no known meaning behind it, so there is nothing to picture but the port itself.","flat":1,"g":"Myra","h":"No picture."},"G3461":{"b":"This is the number ten thousand, and beyond that a countless crowd. John hears the angels around the throne, ten thousand times ten thousand. A number so large it just means past all counting.","g":"ten thousand","h":"The picture: ten thousand upon ten thousand."},"G3462":{"b":"This word comes from the word for myrrh, a costly perfumed oil. To do it is to rub that fragrant oil onto someone. A woman poured it over Jesus. He said she had anointed his body ahead of time for its burial.","g":"anoint","h":"The picture: rubbing on perfumed oil."},"G3463":{"b":"This is the number ten thousand, the largest single number the Greeks counted with. Past it they just said a myriad, countless. The servant owed ten thousand talents, a debt no one could ever pay. The word means more than you can count.","flat":1,"g":"ten thousand","h":"No picture."},"G3464":{"b":"Strong's says the word points to myrrh, perfumed oil. It is the costly scented oil a woman poured over Jesus. Strong's calls it foreign in origin. Abbott gives no origin, only \"ointment.\"","g":"ointment, perfume","h":"The picture: fragrant oil."},"G3465":{"b":"This is the name of a region of Asia Minor that Paul passed through on his way to the coast. Its origin is uncertain. So there is no meaning behind it to picture. Only a place.","flat":1,"g":"Mysia","h":"No picture."},"G3466":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it is what is known to the initiated. A secret kept inside a circle.\n\nHe is careful to add that it does not mean something too hard to understand. It means something you had to be told.","g":"mystery","h":"The picture: told only to those let in."},"G3467":{"b":"Abbott builds this from a word meaning to close the eyes, short-sighted, blinking at what is near. Peter says the one who lacks these graces is this blind, having forgotten he was cleansed.","g":"short-sighted","h":"The picture: squinting, unable to see far."},"G3468":{"b":"This is a welt, the raised bruise a whip or a blow leaves on the skin. Peter takes it from Isaiah: by his wounds you were healed. The marks on his back are what mended you.","g":"stripe","h":"The picture: the welt a blow leaves on the skin."},"G3469":{"b":"The root is a flaw or blot, a spot on something. To momaomai is to point at the blot, to find fault. Paul takes care that no one can put a spot on the ministry, giving no occasion for blame.","g":"blame","h":"The picture: the blot pointed out."},"G347":{"b":"Ana means back, and klino means to lean or recline. Anaklino pictures leaning back, being laid down. Mary laid the newborn in the manger with this word. It also seats guests reclining at the feast. To lay back and rest.","g":"lay down","h":"The picture: laid back to rest."},"G3470":{"b":"Abbott gives blame, then a physical blemish, a spot. Strong's says a flaw or blot. Peter calls the false teachers blots, feasting alongside believers while reveling in their own deceptions.","g":"blemish","h":"The picture: a blot on a clean surface."},"G3471":{"b":"The root means dull. Abbott-Smith says this verb is used of salt that has lost its flavour, gone tasteless. Jesus warns that salt can become insipid, good for nothing. To be made foolish is to lose the very thing that made you useful.","g":"make foolish, lose savour","h":"The picture: salt gone flat and tasteless."},"G3472":{"b":"The root means dull or stupid, as if shut up. Moria is foolishness, absurdity. Picture a mind closed like a shuttered room, letting nothing in. Paul says the message of the cross looks like this to those who are perishing.","g":"foolishness","h":"The picture: a mind shut up tight."},"G3473":{"b":"Built from a word for dull and stupid and the word for talking. It means foolish talk, the empty babble of a fool. Paul lists it among things that should not come out of a Christian's mouth.","g":"foolish talk","h":"The picture: a fool running his mouth."},"G3474":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this first described the nerves as \"dull, sluggish.\" Then it moved to the mind: dull, stupid, foolish. So a fool here is someone gone numb in the head, slow and heavy where they should be sharp.","g":"foolish","h":"The picture: dull nerves."},"G3475":{"b":"This is a name. Strong's says only that it is of Hebrew origin and does not explain it. Abbott lists spellings and nothing more. There is no picture here to find.","flat":1,"g":"Moses","h":"No picture."},"G3476":{"b":"The name means enchanter, one who whispers spells. Naasson appears in the family line of Jesus, an ancestor of King David listed in the genealogies.","g":"Naasson","h":"The picture: enchanter."},"G3477":{"b":"This is only a name. Strong's traces it to Hebrew and here it marks one man in the family line Luke follows from Jesus back toward Adam. A name stands for a person, not a picture. There is nothing to see.","flat":1,"g":"Nagge","h":"No picture."},"G3478":{"b":"This is the town where Jesus grew up. Strong's says it is of uncertain derivation, so no one is sure what the name means. There is nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"Nazareth","h":"No picture."},"G3479":{"b":"It marks someone from Nazareth, the out-of-the-way town where Jesus was raised. On the cross the charge names him this way. A backwater place that people scorned, turned into his very title.","g":"Nazarene","h":"The picture: the man from Nazareth."},"G3480":{"b":"The name traces to Nazareth, a small place in Palestine. A Nazōraios is a man of that town. It clings to Jesus from cradle to cross sign, and Nathanael sneers, can anything good come out of Nazareth. The name of the nobody town.","g":"Nazarene","h":"The picture: the man from the nobody town."},"G3481":{"b":"The name means given. It comes from a word meaning to give. Nathan here is a son of King David, listed in the family line that Luke traces down to Jesus.","g":"Nathan","h":"The picture: given."},"G3482":{"b":"The name means given of God. It joins a word for to give with a word for strength or God. Nathanael was one of the disciples, the man Jesus called a true Israelite with no guile.","g":"Nathanael","h":"The picture: given of God."},"G3484":{"b":"This is just the name of a village in Galilee. It is the town gate where Jesus stopped a funeral and raised a widow's only son. A place name marks a spot on the map, not a picture, so there is nothing here to see.","flat":1,"g":"Nain","h":"No picture."},"G3485":{"b":"Not the whole temple grounds. Abbott-Smith says this is the inmost part of a temple, the shrine, and traces the word to a verb meaning to inhabit.\n\nIt is the room where someone lives. Paul calls Christians that room.","g":"temple, shrine","h":"The picture: the inner room."},"G3486":{"b":"The name means comfortable, in the sense of comfort or consolation. Naum was an ancestor of Jesus, one of the names Luke lists in the genealogy of Christ.","g":"Naum","h":"The picture: comfortable."},"G3487":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says nard is an Indian plant, crushed to make a costly scented ointment. It travelled a long way to reach a jar. This is the perfume Mary breaks open and pours over Jesus, filling the whole house with its smell.","g":"nard","h":"The picture: a fragrant oil from an Indian plant."},"G3488":{"b":"His name is the name of a flower, the narcissus. Strong's links it to a word for numbness, the same root as narcotic, because of the flower's heavy scent. Paul greets the believers in Narcissus's household.","g":"Narcissus","h":"The picture: the narcissus flower."},"G3489":{"b":"The word joins ship and to break. It means to be shipwrecked, the vessel smashed on the rocks. Paul three times suffered it. He also warns that some have wrecked their faith, running it aground.","g":"shipwreck","h":"The picture: the ship broken on the rocks."},"G349":{"b":"The root means to croak like a raven or to scream. Add a word for up and you get a cry that bursts out and rises. The man with the unclean spirit cried out like this. A raw shriek, not words.","g":"cry out","h":"The picture: a shriek bursting upward."},"G3490":{"b":"This joins naus, a ship, to kleros, a lot or portion. The shipowner is the man whose ship it is, his allotted property. The centurion listened to him and the pilot rather than to Paul. The word names him by the vessel he holds as his own.","g":"shipowner","h":"The picture: the man who owns the ship."},"G3491":{"b":"Strong's traces this to a word meaning to float. It is the plain old word for a ship, a vessel that floats. Luke uses it just once, as the ship runs aground and starts to break up. The word is the boat itself, made to ride on top of the sea.","g":"ship","h":"The picture: a thing that floats on the water."},"G3492":{"b":"The root naus means a boat of any size. A nautes is named for it, the boat-man, the one whose whole work is the ship. These are the sailors who fought the storm with Paul and wanted to abandon the vessel.","g":"sailor","h":"The picture: the man of the boat."},"G3493":{"b":"The name means snorer. It comes from a word for a snorting sound. Nachor was the grandfather of Abraham, named in the line that runs from Shem down to the patriarchs.","g":"Nachor","h":"The picture: snorer."},"G3494":{"b":"This comes from neos, new or young. It means a young man, Strong's says up to about forty, in his fresh strength. Saul is one, holding the coats at the stoning. Eutychus is one, the young man who fell asleep and dropped from the window.","g":"young man","h":"The picture: a man in his fresh strength."},"G3495":{"b":"Strong's calls it a youth under forty. It is a young man, a youth. Abbott points to the young man who ran from Gethsemane and the one sitting in the empty tomb. Not a boy, not yet old. Full strength.","g":"young man","h":"The picture: a young man in his prime."},"G3496":{"b":"This name is two words joined, new and town. The root points to a town with walls. So Neapolis is the fresh walled city on the coast. It was the first patch of Europe Paul's feet touched.","g":"Neapolis","h":"The picture: a brand-new town."},"G3497":{"b":"The name comes from a word meaning pleasantness. Naaman was the Syrian army commander healed of leprosy after washing seven times in the Jordan, at the prophet Elisha's word.","g":"Naaman","h":"The picture: pleasantness."},"G3498":{"b":"Strong's traces it to an old word meaning a corpse, and says nothing more. Abbott-Smith gives no origin. The word means dead, and as a noun, the dead. There is no image behind it.","flat":1,"g":"dead","h":"No picture."},"G3499":{"b":"The root nekros means dead, a corpse. To nekroo is to make dead, to kill off. It is used of Abraham's body, as good as dead, and of Paul's command to treat the sinful parts of you as a corpse.","g":"deaden, mortify","h":"The picture: making a body a corpse."},"G35":{"b":"This comes from the word to trace a family line, with 'not' in front. It means without a recorded pedigree. Melchizedek has no genealogy in scripture, no line of descent set down. So he stands apart.","g":"without descent","h":"The picture: no line in the family tree."},"G350":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it was used of a courtroom, even of examination by torture. It means to sift a matter up and out. Not a gentle chat. It is the hard questioning that digs the truth into the open.","g":"examine, question","h":"The picture: cross-examining under pressure."},"G3500":{"b":"The root means to make dead, to deaden, from the word for a corpse. It names deadness, a state of death. Paul speaks of the deadness of Sarah's aged womb, long past bearing. Abraham looked at bodies as good as dead and still believed.","g":"deadness","h":"The picture: a body gone lifeless."},"G3501":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this is new in respect of time. Recent. Just made.\n\nIt is the word for new wine that bursts old skins, and for the younger son. Fresh, not necessarily different in kind.","g":"new, young","h":"The picture: fresh off the vine."},"G3502":{"b":"Strong's calls this a youngling, a nestling. It is built from the word for new or young. The law let a poor mother bring two young pigeons instead of a lamb. That was Mary's gift for the baby Jesus.","g":"young bird","h":"The picture: a young bird in the nest."},"G3503":{"b":"The word is built from \"new, young, fresh.\" It means youth, the early season of a life. From my youth, the rich ruler tells Jesus, I have kept all these. Do not let anyone look down on your neotes, Paul tells young Timothy.","g":"youth","h":"The picture: the early green years of a life."},"G3504":{"b":"This joins neos, new, and phyo, to grow like a plant. So it is newly planted, a young shoot just put in the ground. Paul says an overseer must not be one, a convert too freshly planted to bear the weight.","g":"new convert","h":"The picture: a seedling just set in the soil."},"G3506":{"b":"Strong's says \"to nod, i.e. signal.\" Abbott says \"to nod or beckon, as a sign.\" At the table Peter cannot speak across the room, so he nods to John to ask Jesus who the betrayer is. A message sent with the head, no words.","g":"nod, beckon","h":"The picture: a nod of the head as a silent signal."},"G3507":{"b":"Abbott-Smith is precise. This word is a single, specific cloud, unlike another Greek word meaning a great indefinite mass of vapour.\n\nSo the cloud at the transfiguration is one cloud, picked out and pointed at.","g":"cloud","h":"The picture: one cloud, not the whole sky."},"G3508":{"b":"The name means my wrestling. It comes from a word meaning to twine or twist together. Naphtali was a son of Jacob, born of Rachel's struggle with her sister, and became a tribe of Israel.","g":"Naphtali","h":"The picture: my wrestling."},"G3509":{"b":"This word means a cloud, and not one puff but a whole mass of them piled up. Hebrews uses it for a huge crowd of witnesses. Picture the sky packed edge to edge with cloud. That is the crowd watching you run.","g":"cloud","h":"The picture: a whole sky packed with cloud."},"G351":{"b":"The root means to scrutinize, to investigate and question closely. This is the preliminary hearing where a case is dug into before trial. Festus holds this examination of Paul to find something to write to Caesar. The word is the close sifting, turning the facts over to see what is there.","g":"investigation","h":"The picture: sifting the facts by questioning."},"G3510":{"b":"The word plainly means kidney. Abbott-Smith notes the plural, \"the kidneys, reins.\" The old writers thought the kidneys, buried deep in the body, held a person's hidden will. So when God says he searches the kidneys and hearts, he sees your deepest self.","g":"kidney, reins","h":"The picture: the kidneys deep inside the body."},"G3511":{"b":"This joins the temple with a word meaning to sweep. The temple-keeper is the one who sweeps and tends the shrine. Ephesus was proudly called the temple-keeper of great Artemis.","g":"temple-keeper","h":"The picture: sweeping the temple floor."},"G3512":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning new, young, fresh. It describes what belongs to young people. Paul tells Timothy to flee youthful lusts. The word points to the green heat of the young, still new, not yet seasoned.","g":"youthful","h":"The picture: fresh and green with youth."},"G3514":{"b":"Netho means to spin, to twist wool or flax into thread on a spindle. It was daily work, the slow making of cloth by hand. Jesus says the lilies neither work nor spin, yet they are clothed better than kings. The flowers make no thread, and still God dresses them.","g":"to spin","h":"The picture: spinning thread from wool."},"G3515":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning not speaking, an infant. It means to be a babe. It pictures a small child with no words yet. Paul says in evil be infants like this, but in understanding be grown.","g":"be a child","h":"The picture: a baby with no words yet."},"G3516":{"b":"Strong's breaks the word into \"not\" and \"word.\" A baby is the little one who cannot speak yet. Paul uses it too for believers still too young to take solid food.","g":"infant, babe","h":"The picture: one who cannot talk yet."},"G3517":{"b":"Strong's traces this name to a root meaning wet, the same base as the word for a boat. It points to the sea. Paul greets Nereus and his sister in the Roman church. A name that smells of saltwater.","g":"Nereus","h":"The picture: the wet sea."},"G3518":{"b":"The name means light of Jah. It joins a word for a lamp or light with Jah, a short form of the Lord's name. Neri appears in the family line that Luke traces to Jesus.","g":"Neri","h":"The picture: light of Jah."},"G3519":{"b":"This is the small form of the word for an island. It means a tiny island, an islet. Running under such a small island, Cauda, the crew barely managed to haul in the ship's boat. The word shrinks the island down, a small speck of land in the sea.","g":"small island","h":"The picture: a little island."},"G352":{"b":"The root means to bend forward, and this word reverses it. Abbott says \"to lift oneself up.\" A woman bent double for years finally straightens. Jesus tells the fearful to straighten up and lift their heads because rescue is near.","g":"straighten, look up","h":"The picture: a bent back straightening up."},"G3520":{"b":"An island, a patch of land surrounded by water. Paul washes up on one, called Malta, after the shipwreck, and John is exiled to another called Patmos. The plain thing itself.","g":"island","h":"The picture: land ringed by sea."},"G3521":{"b":"The root means to abstain from food. This is the fast itself, the empty stomach kept empty on purpose. Anna served God with fasting and prayer night and day. Going without in order to seek him.","g":"fasting","h":"The picture: an empty stomach held on purpose."},"G3522":{"b":"Strong's is direct. To abstain from food, and he notes it is done for religious reasons.\n\nAbbott-Smith gives no story behind the word, only the act and the verses. Skipping the meal is the whole meaning.","g":"fast","h":"The picture: going without food."},"G3523":{"b":"This joins \"not\" to the verb to eat. A nestis is someone who has not eaten. Jesus will not send the crowd away hungry, faint from no food, in case they collapse on the long road home.","g":"fasting","h":"The picture: sent home on an empty stomach."},"G3524":{"b":"The root nepho means to abstain from wine, to keep sober. First the word described a drink with no wine in it, then a person who stays clear-headed. An overseer must be this, sober, not fogged, watchful.","g":"sober","h":"The picture: a cup with no wine."},"G3525":{"b":"The plain meaning is to abstain from wine, to keep sober. From there it grew to mean clear-headed and alert, not fuddled. So \"be nepho and watch\" pictures a guard who has touched no wine, wide awake at his post.","g":"be sober","h":"The picture: a guard who has touched no wine."},"G3526":{"b":"The name is the Latin word niger, black. Simeon, one of the prophets and teachers gathered at Antioch, carried it as his second name when the Spirit set apart Paul and Barnabas.","g":"Niger","h":"The picture: the color black."},"G3527":{"b":"This name comes from the word to conquer or subdue. It means victorious. Nicanor was one of the seven men chosen to help serve the growing church. A name of triumph, given to a servant who waited on tables.","g":"Nicanor","h":"The picture: a conqueror after the battle."},"G3528":{"b":"The word is built on the noun for victory. Abbott-Smith notes it was also a law term, and points to Romans 3:4, where God prevails when he is judged.\n\nVictory in a courtroom, not only on a battlefield.","g":"conquer, overcome","h":"The picture: winning the case."},"G3529":{"b":"This word means victory, conquest. Strong's calls it a primary word, so it comes from nothing older. There is no image behind it. John says our faith is the victory that overcomes the world.","flat":1,"g":"victory","h":"No picture."},"G353":{"b":"Abbott says the word means to take up, to raise. Jesus was taken up into heaven with this word. It also means to take to yourself. Paul says take up the whole armor of God.","g":"take up","h":"The picture: taking up."},"G3530":{"b":"This name is built from two words, one meaning victory or conquest, the other meaning the people. It reads victor among his people. Nicodemus came to Jesus by night with his questions. His name carried a claim of winning.","g":"Nicodemus","h":"The picture: victory among the people."},"G3531":{"b":"The group is named for Nicolaus, a name that means victorious over the people. In Revelation the risen Christ names them twice, praising the church that hates their works. A movement whose very name boasts of ruling the flock, and Christ stands against it.","g":"Nicolaitan","h":"The picture: conqueror of the people."},"G3532":{"b":"This name joins the word for a conquest or triumph with the word for a people. It means victor over the people. Nicolaus was the last of the seven chosen to serve the early church. A name of winning a crowd.","g":"Nicolaus","h":"The picture: victory won over a whole people."},"G3533":{"b":"This joins the word for a conquest to the word for a walled town. It means victory-city. Paul plans to winter there. Cities like this were named to mark a battle won, the triumph built into the very walls.","g":"Nicopolis","h":"The picture: a walled city of victory."},"G3534":{"b":"The word means victory, the conquest that ends a fight. Paul cries that death is swallowed up in victory, and asks, death, where is your win. It is the moment the enemy is beaten and the field is yours. Christ hands us that victory.","g":"victory","h":"The picture: the fight won."},"G3536":{"b":"This is just the name for a person from the city of Nineveh. It comes from the city and nothing more. The Ninevites are the ones Jonah preached to, but the word itself only tells you where they were from.","flat":1,"g":"Ninevite","h":"No picture."},"G3537":{"b":"This word comes from the verb to wash. It names the basin Jesus poured water into before washing the disciples' feet. A plain wash bowl. The word carries the very act it was made for: cleaning.","g":"basin","h":"The picture: a basin of water for washing feet."},"G3538":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this word is usually of a part of the body. Not a full bath. It is the hands, the feet, the face. Jesus takes a basin and washes just the disciples' feet with this word.","g":"wash","h":"The picture: washing hands, feet, or face."},"G3539":{"b":"The root is nous, the mind. To noeō is to perceive with the mind, to grasp what the eyes only look at. Jesus presses the disciples, do you not yet noeō, seeing the loaves multiplied but missing the meaning. To understand is to catch it.","g":"to understand","h":"The picture: catching what the eyes only see."},"G354":{"b":"This word comes from the word to take up. Abbott-Smith gives it as a taking up. The time was drawing near for Jesus to be received up to heaven, so he set his face firmly toward Jerusalem and started walking.","g":"taking up","h":"The picture: being lifted up and taken away."},"G3540":{"b":"From the verb to use the mind. It means a thought, a purpose, a design. Paul says we are not ignorant of Satan's devices, and he takes every thought captive to Christ. The plans the mind turns over.","g":"thought","h":"The picture: the schemes the mind hatches."},"G3541":{"b":"This word means a child born outside the marriage, a son with no legal father to claim him. Hebrews says a real son gets discipline. Skip the discipline and you are treated like one no father owns.","g":"bastard","h":"The picture: a child no father will claim."},"G3542":{"b":"Abbott ties the word to a verb meaning to pasture and says it means \"a pasture, pasturage.\" Jesus says whoever enters through him will go in and out and find pasture, open grazing ground. The same word names a sore that spreads and eats like grazing.","g":"pasture","h":"The picture: green pasture where the flock feeds."},"G3543":{"b":"The root is nomos, law and custom. To nomizō is first to hold by custom, to do what is usually done, then to suppose, to assume as everyone assumes. When Jesus' parents supposed him in the caravan, they simply went by the usual.","g":"to suppose","h":"The picture: going by the usual."},"G3544":{"b":"From the word for law. It means legal, and as a noun the expert in the Mosaic law, the lawyer. One stands up to test Jesus, what must I do to inherit life. A specialist in the rules.","g":"lawyer","h":"The picture: the man who knows the law by heart."},"G3545":{"b":"Strong's ties this word to the rules of the lists, the contest ground. An athlete is crowned only if he competes lawfully, inside the rules. Paul uses it that way for Timothy. Win the race, but win inside the lines.","g":"lawfully","h":"The picture: playing by the rules of the contest."},"G3546":{"b":"This comes from a word for custom or usage, what is done by law. A coin is metal that counts as money only because custom agrees it does. In Matthew 22:19 Jesus asks for the tribute coin and points to the face stamped on it.","g":"coin, money","h":"The picture: a coin worth what custom says."},"G3547":{"b":"Two words joined: law and teacher. This is the man who explains the law of Moses to others. They sit listening to Jesus in Luke, and Paul says some want to be one without understanding what they say. A teacher of the rules.","g":"teacher of the law","h":"The picture: the man who teaches the law."},"G3548":{"b":"Built from nomos, law, and tithemi, to place. Abbott gives legislation, lawgiving. Paul counts the nomothesia among Israel's privileges. The word is the whole event of the law being set down, statutes handed to a people at the mountain.","g":"lawgiving","h":"The picture: the law laid down at Sinai."},"G3549":{"b":"The root is a lawgiver, one who lays down laws. This word is the act of setting law in place, putting rules on the books. Hebrews says the people were given the law under the priesthood. Laws laid down like foundation stones. A new covenant needed new ones.","g":"give law, legislate","h":"The picture: laws laid down like stones."},"G355":{"b":"Strong's says this means \"properly, to use up.\" James and John ask for fire to come down and use up a village. Paul warns that people who bite each other get used up. Spent down to nothing.","g":"consume, use up","h":"The picture: burning through until nothing is left."},"G3550":{"b":"Built from \"law\" and a word meaning to place or lay down, this is the one who sets the law in place. James says there is only one of him, the one who can save and destroy. So who are you to judge your neighbor.","g":"lawgiver","h":"The picture: the one who lays the law in place."},"G3551":{"b":"Abbott-Smith builds this word on a verb meaning to deal out or distribute. Strong's traces the same root and says it means to parcel out, especially food or grazing.\n\nSo a law is first a portion assigned to you.","g":"law","h":"The picture: pasture parcelled out to the animals."},"G3552":{"b":"The root nosos is a disease. So this is to be sick, and Paul turns it on the mind, a man sick with cravings. Paul says such a one is doting, diseased over questions and word-battles, feverish for strife.","g":"be sick","h":"The picture: sick with a fever."},"G3554":{"b":"This word just means disease or sickness. Strong's says its origin is of uncertain affinity, so no one knows where it comes from. There is nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"disease, sickness","h":"No picture."},"G3555":{"b":"This word comes from the word for a nestling. Abbott-Smith gives it as a brood of young birds. How often I longed to gather your children, Jesus says over Jerusalem, as a hen gathers her chicks under her wings, but you would not.","g":"brood","h":"The picture: chicks gathered under the hen's wings."},"G3556":{"b":"The root means a nestling, a newly hatched bird. This is the little chick. In Matthew 23:37 Jesus longs to gather Jerusalem as a hen gathers her chicks under her wings, and grieves that they would not come.","g":"young bird, chick","h":"The picture: chicks under the hen's wing."},"G3557":{"b":"This word comes from a word meaning apart, aside. It means to set money aside for yourself in secret, to skim off the top. Ananias did this, keeping back part of the price he pretended to give whole.","g":"embezzle","h":"The picture: money slipped aside in secret."},"G3558":{"b":"This is the south wind, and by extension the south itself. When the south wind blows you say it will be hot, Jesus says. The gentle south wind rose and the sailors weighed anchor. The warm breeze off the desert.","g":"south wind","h":"The picture: the warm wind from the south."},"G3559":{"b":"The roots are nous, the mind, and tithemi, to place. So the word is putting a thought into someone's mind, a word set there to steer them straight. Paul tells fathers to raise their children in the admonition of the Lord.","g":"admonition","h":"The picture: a thought set in the mind."},"G356":{"b":"Built from ana and logos, a matter of ratio and measure. Abbott gives proportion. Paul says the one who prophesies should do it according to the analogia of faith. Kept in scale, no part swelling past the measure given.","g":"proportion","h":"The picture: measured out to the right scale."},"G3560":{"b":"This word is built from mind and to put, hence to put in mind. To admonish is to place a thought where the other person cannot miss it. It is a gentle warning, laying the truth right in front of them so it stays.","g":"admonish, warn","h":"The picture: setting a thought in someone's mind."},"G3561":{"b":"Built from new and month, the word for the new moon. It named the feast held when the first thin sliver of moon appeared. Paul says let no one judge you over a festival or a new moon or a sabbath.","g":"new moon","h":"The picture: the thin new moon."},"G3562":{"b":"This word is built from mind and a word meaning to hold. To act this way is to keep a firm grip on your own mind. Abbott says it means sensibly, discreetly. The wise man holds onto his wits instead of letting them slip.","g":"discreetly","h":"The picture: keeping a grip on your mind."},"G3563":{"b":"Abbott-Smith calls this the ruling faculty, mind, understanding, reason. Not just where thoughts happen. Where decisions get made.\n\nThat is why Paul asks for it to be renewed. Change the steering and the course changes.","g":"mind","h":"The picture: the part that steers."},"G3564":{"b":"Strong's traces this name to two words, nymphe, a bride, and doron, a gift. So it carries the sense of something given by a bride. Paul greets this believer, whose house held one of the early churches.","g":"Nymphas","h":"The picture: a name meaning the bride's gift."},"G3565":{"b":"Strong's traces it to a verb meaning \"to veil as a bride.\" Abbott: \"a bride, young wife, young woman.\" The word pictures a young woman veiled for her wedding. It can also mean a son's wife, a daughter-in-law.","g":"bride","h":"The picture: a bride behind her veil."},"G3566":{"b":"Abbott says simply a bridegroom, the groom at a wedding. The root is the bride, the veiled young woman. John the Baptist calls himself only the friend of the bridegroom, and names Jesus the groom, come at last for his bride.","g":"bridegroom","h":"The picture: the groom at a wedding."},"G3567":{"b":"This is the bride's room, the wedding chamber. The phrase \"sons of the bridechamber\" means the groom's friends who ran the wedding. Jesus asks if they fast while the groom is with them. You do not mourn in the wedding room.","g":"bridal room","h":"The picture: the wedding chamber."},"G3568":{"b":"Strong's calls it a primary particle of present time. Nothing older lies behind it. Abbott-Smith gives no origin, only the uses: now as against then, and now meaning as things stand. It is a pointer, not a picture.","flat":1,"g":"now","h":"No picture."},"G357":{"b":"The root is a word meaning proportion, the kind of math where you weigh one figure against another. So to consider here is to sit and work the sum. Hebrews says do this with Jesus. Add him up against all you are facing.","g":"consider","h":"The picture: working out the sum."},"G3570":{"b":"This is nyn, now, said with force. Nyni marks the present moment, and often the hinge, the but now where everything changes. So nyni the righteousness of God is revealed apart from law. The word swings the door from the old age into the new.","g":"now","h":"The picture: the great but now that turns the page."},"G3571":{"b":"Strong's calls this a primary word, which means it does not come from anything else. Night is simply night. Abbott-Smith spends his whole entry on grammar, not on any older meaning.","flat":1,"g":"night","h":"No picture."},"G3572":{"b":"This word means to prick or pierce, even to give a nudge. John uses it of the soldier who pierced Jesus' side with a spear, and out came blood and water. A sharp point pushed into flesh.","g":"to pierce","h":"The picture: a spearpoint pushed into the side."},"G3573":{"b":"The root is neuo, to nod. Nystazo is the head drooping as sleep comes, nodding off. While the bridegroom is delayed all ten girls nod and fall asleep, wise and foolish alike, their lamps beside them.","g":"slumber","h":"The picture: the head nodding into sleep."},"G3574":{"b":"The roots are night and day, welded into a single word. Abbott-Smith says a night and a day, the whole round of hours. Paul says he spent one of these adrift in the open sea.","g":"night and day","h":"The picture: one full turn of dark into light."},"G3575":{"b":"The name means rest. It comes from a word meaning quiet. Noah's father named him hoping he would bring comfort from the toil of the ground, and God rested the world through him after the flood.","g":"Noah","h":"The picture: rest."},"G3576":{"b":"This word means sluggish, slow and heavy, like a limb gone numb and slow to move. Hebrews warns against becoming dull of hearing, slothful. Not rushing toward evil, just too heavy to stir toward good. Deadweight.","g":"sluggish, dull","h":"The picture: a limb gone numb and slow."},"G3577":{"b":"This simply means the back, the body's back. Abbott says the back. Paul quotes the Psalm, bow down their back always, a picture of people stooped and burdened, unable to straighten up.","g":"back","h":"The picture: a back bent low under a load."},"G3578":{"b":"This comes from the word for a stranger or guest. It is the welcome given to a stranger, and the room where he stays, a lodging. Paul preached from his rented lodging in Rome. A place kept ready for the one who comes.","g":"lodging","h":"The picture: a room kept for the guest."},"G3579":{"b":"Abbott-Smith builds it from the word for a stranger or guest. It pictures welcoming a stranger into your home as a guest. The same word can flip and mean to strike someone as strange or foreign.","g":"host, lodge","h":"The picture: taking in a stranger."},"G358":{"b":"The word is built from a piece meaning not and the word for salt. It means saltless, without savor. In Mark 9:50 Jesus says salt is good, but if it loses its saltness, how will you season it, so have salt in yourselves.","g":"saltless","h":"The picture: salt gone flat."},"G3580":{"b":"This joins xenos, a stranger, and dechomai, to receive. So it is welcoming a traveler in, opening your door to one you do not know. Paul counts lodging strangers among the good works of an honored widow.","g":"host strangers","h":"The picture: taking a stranger into your house."},"G3581":{"b":"The word means a foreigner, an outsider. Abbott notes the same word covers both sides of hospitality, guest and host. \"I was a stranger and you took me in.\"","g":"stranger, host","h":"The picture: the stranger at the door."},"G3582":{"b":"This was a measure of about a pint, and then the pitcher itself, made of wood or stone. In Mark 7:4 Jesus lists the traditions the Pharisees keep, the washing of cups and pitchers and copper pots.","g":"pitcher, pot","h":"The picture: a pitcher of wood or stone."},"G3583":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means to dry up, parch, wither. It comes from the word for dry. Picture grass under a hot sun, curling and browning. The green fades, the stalk shrivels. The flower falls and the grass withers.","g":"dry up, wither","h":"The picture: a plant drying and shriveling."},"G3584":{"b":"Strong's: \"arid. by implication, shrunken.\" Abbott uses it of a hand \"shrunken by disease, withered.\" It is the word for dry land against the water, and for a limb dried up and useless, like a dead branch.","g":"dry, withered","h":"The picture: dried up and shriveled."},"G3585":{"b":"This word means wooden, made of timber. The root is a piece of wood, a log or a stick. Paul says a great house holds vessels of gold and silver, and also of wood. Wooden pots for the common jobs, cheap and plain.","g":"wooden","h":"The picture: a plain wooden pot."},"G3586":{"b":"Strong's says timber, as fuel or material. Abbott-Smith walks through what gets made from it. A club. Stocks for the feet. A beam. A tree.\n\nThe New Testament also uses this plain word for the cross.","g":"wood","h":"The picture: a piece of timber."},"G3587":{"b":"Strong's ties this to a word for a razor. Xyrao is to shave, to shear the hair clean off the skin. If a woman will not cover her head, Paul says, let her be shorn, the same as shaved bald.","g":"shave","h":"The picture: a razor shaving the hair off."},"G3589":{"b":"The number eighty. Luke uses it for Anna the prophetess, a widow of eighty-four who never left the temple, worshiping night and day. A plain count that here measures a long life of waiting, rewarded by seeing the child at last.","g":"eighty","h":"The picture: eighty years counted."},"G359":{"b":"Abbott says this is a loosing, like a boat untied from where it is moored. From there it means departure. Paul says the time of his departure has come. He pictures his death as a ship's ropes slipped, sailing off from shore.","g":"departure","h":"The picture: a ship loosed from its moorings."},"G3590":{"b":"From the word for eight. Abbott points to the eighth day, when the baby John was brought to be circumcised and named, Luke 1:59. In Israel the eighth day was the day a child was marked as belonging to God.","g":"eighth","h":"The picture: the eighth day."},"G3591":{"b":"Strong's paints a load so heavy the thing carrying it bends and bulges under it. Hebrews says lay aside every weight before you run. Anything that makes you sag on the track. Drop it.","g":"weight","h":"The picture: a load so heavy it makes you bend."},"G3593":{"b":"This word comes from the word for a road. Abbott-Smith gives it as to travel, to journey. A Samaritan, going down the same road, came upon the wounded man. Where others passed by, this traveler stopped.","g":"journey","h":"The picture: a traveler on the road."},"G3594":{"b":"This is the verb of the guide, to lead someone along the road. How can I understand, the eunuch asks, unless someone hodegeo me. The Spirit will hodegeo you into all truth, taking you by the hand down the way.","g":"to guide","h":"The picture: leading someone along the way."},"G3595":{"b":"The word joins \"road\" and \"to lead.\" A hodegos is the one who leads others down the way. Blind hodegoi, Jesus calls the Pharisees, blind guides. A guide who cannot see, leading the blind toward the ditch.","g":"guide","h":"The picture: a guide leading down the road."},"G3596":{"b":"The word is built from 'a road' and 'to travel.' It means to be a wayfarer, out walking the highway. In Acts the men are on the road near the city when Peter falls into his vision.","g":"go on a journey","h":"The picture: feet on the open road."},"G3597":{"b":"The root means to be a wayfarer, to travel the road. Abbott says \"a journey.\" John shows Jesus tired out from exactly this, sitting down at the well because the walk had worn him. The plain weariness of a hard day's road.","g":"journey","h":"The picture: worn out from a long day on foot."},"G3598":{"b":"Abbott starts plain. A way, path, road. Then a traveller's journey along it.\n\nOnly last does it turn into a way of living. So calling Christianity the Way begins with dirt and walking.","g":"road, way","h":"The picture: a road under your feet."},"G3599":{"b":"Abbott says plainly a tooth, and Strong's ties it to the verb to eat, the tooth being what eats. The old law weighed a tooth for a tooth. And Jesus warns of the place of weeping and gnashing of teeth, where rage grinds on itself.","g":"tooth","h":"The picture: a tooth."},"G36":{"b":"This joins not with the word for kin and family stock. It means low-born, of no family, a nobody with no pedigree. Paul says God chose exactly these, the base and despised, to shame the strong of the world.","g":"base, low-born","h":"The picture: the person with no family name."},"G360":{"b":"Built on the word for loosen. Abbott says \"to unloose for departure.\" It is untying the mooring or striking the tent to leave. Paul uses it for death, his desire to loose the ropes and depart to be with Christ.","g":"depart","h":"The picture: loosing the ropes to set out."},"G3600":{"b":"The word means to be in pain, to be tormented, to suffer sharp anguish of body or mind. The rich man cries that he is odynao in the flame. Your father and I, Mary tells the boy Jesus, have been searching for you in pain.","g":"grieve","h":"The picture: writhing in sharp pain."},"G3601":{"b":"Strong's ties this to a word meaning to go down, the way the sun sinks below the edge. Grief here is the ache that drags you downward, the heaviness that pulls the heart low. Paul feels it without ceasing for his own people.","g":"sorrow","h":"The picture: grief that sinks you down."},"G3602":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this comes from a word meaning to lament. Odyrmos is loud grief, the wailing of someone who has lost what they love. Matthew hears it in Rachel weeping for her children and refusing comfort. Not quiet sadness. Open, aching mourning.","g":"lamentation","h":"The picture: loud wailing for the dead."},"G3604":{"b":"The name means strength of Jah. It joins a word for strength or force with Jah, a short form of the Lord's name. Ozias was a king of Judah, listed among the ancestors of Jesus.","g":"Ozias","h":"The picture: strength of Jah."},"G3605":{"b":"This word means to give off a smell, usually a bad one. Martha says it at the tomb. Lord, by now he stinks, he has been dead four days. It is the plain, blunt word for a stench. Death has a smell.","g":"to stink, smell","h":"The picture: the smell off a body four days dead."},"G3606":{"b":"The word points back to a source, the place a thing came from. The unclean spirit says it will return to the house hothen it came out, back the way it left. Hebrews uses it for cause too, tracing an effect to its root.","g":"whence","h":"The picture: the way back to where it came from."},"G3607":{"b":"This is a piece of fine linen, big enough to be a ship's sail. It is a linen cloth, especially a sail. In Peter's vision a great othone came down from the sky, held by its four corners, full of animals. A wide sheet, lowered.","g":"sheet","h":"The picture: a great sheet of linen let down like a sail."},"G3608":{"b":"The root is a linen cloth, the kind big enough for a ship's sail. This is the smaller piece, a strip of fine linen. The grave clothes lay in the tomb, the linen cloths that had wrapped the body. Woven flax.","g":"linen cloth","h":"The picture: strips of fine linen."},"G3609":{"b":"The root oikos means a house, and by extension a family. Oikeios is what belongs to the house, the people under one roof. Paul says you are no longer strangers but of God's household, and calls believers the family of faith.","g":"of the household","h":"The picture: the people under one roof."},"G3610":{"b":"The root is to occupy a house, to reside. An oiketes is the servant who belongs to the household, sleeping under the master's roof. No oiketes can serve two masters, Jesus says. A house-slave answers to one lord, the one whose home he lives in.","g":"house servant","h":"The picture: a servant living in the house."},"G3611":{"b":"Abbott traces it to οἶκος, a house. Strong's: \"to occupy a house, i.e. reside.\" To dwell is to make your home in a place. Paul uses it for sin, or for God's Spirit, living inside a person like a resident in a house.","g":"dwell","h":"The picture: making your home in a house."},"G3612":{"b":"The word means simply a dwelling, from a root meaning to live in a house. It became a soft name for a jail. The angel's light fills the cell where Peter lies asleep in chains.","g":"prison","h":"The picture: a bare room with a locked door."},"G3613":{"b":"The root means to occupy a house, to reside. An oiketerion is a dwelling place, a home to live in. Paul says we long to be clothed with our dwelling from heaven. Jude uses it of angels who left their own home.","g":"dwelling place","h":"The picture: a home to live in."},"G3614":{"b":"Abbott sets it against a close cousin. That word could mean a whole estate. This one is the dwelling only.\n\nHe adds that the same word stretches to cover the people inside it.","g":"house, household","h":"The picture: the building you live in."},"G3615":{"b":"The root is a house. This word is the people of that house, those who live under one roof, your own family. Jesus says a man's enemies will be the members of his own household. The hardest opposition can come from the people closest to you, inside your own doors.","g":"household, relatives","h":"The picture: the people under one roof."},"G3616":{"b":"This joins oikos, a house, and despotes, a master. So it is ruling the household, being master over the home. Paul says let the younger widows marry and guide the house, giving no occasion to the enemy.","g":"manage the home","h":"The picture: the master running the house."},"G3617":{"b":"Abbott-Smith builds this from \"house\" and \"master.\" So it pictures the man who runs the household, the one everyone under that roof answers to. Jesus tells stories about such a man and his servants.","g":"householder","h":"The picture: the master of the house."},"G3618":{"b":"Strong's says the word means to be a house-builder. Abbott starts in the same place, to build a house.\n\nWhen the New Testament speaks of building people up, it is a construction word. Slow work, stone on stone.","g":"build, build up","h":"The picture: a man building a house."},"G3619":{"b":"Abbott-Smith takes it apart. The word for house, plus a verb meaning to build.\n\nIn the New Testament it is nearly always the figure. Building people up. The old English word for it is edify, which hides the house.","g":"building up","h":"The picture: building a house."},"G362":{"b":"The root meno means to stay in place. This is waiting that does not wander off, standing your ground for one whose coming is expected. Paul says they turned to wait for God's Son from heaven.","g":"wait for","h":"The picture: holding your spot until he comes."},"G3621":{"b":"Strong's says the word means to manage a house, an estate. Picture the steward who portions out food and pays the workers and keeps the accounts. So Jesus asks each servant to run his master's house well and give account.","g":"be steward, manage","h":"The picture: the steward running the household."},"G3622":{"b":"This comes from the house-manager. Abbott-Smith gives the office of steward, stewardship, the running of a household. Give an account of your stewardship. It widened to mean God's ordering of his whole plan.","g":"stewardship","h":"The picture: running the household."},"G3623":{"b":"Abbott-Smith builds it from house and to manage. It pictures the trusted servant who runs the household. In Luke 12:42 he is the one who hands out the food at the right time. A slave, yet in charge.","g":"steward, manager","h":"The picture: the servant who runs the house."},"G3624":{"b":"Strong's gives both at once: a dwelling, and by implication a family. Abbott-Smith does the same, house first, then household.\n\nSo the house of David is not a building. It is everyone who came out of it.","g":"house, household","h":"The picture: the house standing for the people inside it."},"G3625":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the word means the inhabited earth. It is literally the being-lived-in land, from the word for dwelling. It pictures all the settled country where people make their homes. The whole lived-in world.","g":"the world","h":"The picture: the inhabited land."},"G3626":{"b":"This joins the word for a house to a word for a keeper or guard. It pictures the one who watches over the home. Paul lists it among what young wives should be, workers at home, keeping the household like a faithful guard.","g":"keeper at home","h":"The picture: the guard who keeps the house."},"G3627":{"b":"This means to feel pity, to have compassion on someone. It comes from a plain word meaning pity. God says he will have compassion on whom he will. A feeling of the heart is not a thing the eye can see.","flat":1,"g":"have compassion","h":"No picture."},"G3628":{"b":"Abbott-Smith pairs this word with splanchna, the inward parts, a heart of compassion. Pity here is not a polite feeling. It is felt low in the body, the gut turning over at another's pain. Paul calls God the Father of such mercies.","g":"mercy, compassion","h":"The picture: a churning deep in the gut."},"G3629":{"b":"Built from a word meaning to pity. Abbott gives merciful. Jesus says be oiktirmon, full of compassion, as your Father is compassionate, Luke 6:36. This is the tender mercy that feels another's pain and then stoops down to it.","g":"compassionate","h":"The picture: gut-pity that stoops to help."},"G363":{"b":"The root means to recall to mind, and the front means up. To bring a memory back up to the surface. Peter hears the rooster and it all comes back. Paul tells Timothy to stir the gift up by remembering. The past pulled back into view.","g":"remind","h":"The picture: pulling a memory back up."},"G3630":{"b":"The word joins wine and to drink. An oinopotes is a wine-drinker, a man too fond of the cup. Jesus says they called him this, a glutton and a winebibber. The Son of Man came eating and drinking, and they used it against him.","g":"a winebibber","h":"The picture: the man always at the wine cup."},"G3631":{"b":"Strong's calls it a primary word, possibly of Hebrew origin, and leaves it there. It means wine.\n\nAbbott gives no derivation either. There is nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"wine","h":"No picture."},"G3632":{"b":"This joins the word for wine to a root meaning to bubble up and overflow. So it is drink spilling past all limit. Peter lists it among the old ways his readers have left behind.","g":"excess of wine","h":"The picture: wine bubbling over the cup."},"G3633":{"b":"Abbott gives to suppose, to expect, to imagine. John ends his gospel, I oiomai the world itself could not hold the books that would be written of all Jesus did, John 21:25. A reckoning made in the mind, weighing what must be true.","g":"suppose, think","h":"The picture: a reckoning made in the head."},"G3635":{"b":"The word comes from a root meaning shrinking, hesitation, the holding back of someone who does not want to move. In Acts the disciples urge Peter not to hold back but to come at once.","g":"delay","h":"The picture: dragging your feet."},"G3636":{"b":"The root means to be slow, to hold back. This is the sluggish one, dragging his feet, shrinking from the work. The master calls the servant who buried his talent wicked and slothful. He did not steal it. He just would not stir himself to use it.","g":"slothful","h":"The picture: the one who drags his feet."},"G3637":{"b":"Built from two plain words, eight and day. It describes something eight days old. Paul says he was circumcised on the eighth day, an eight-day-old infant, a Hebrew of Hebrews.","g":"eighth day","h":"The picture: a baby eight days old."},"G3638":{"b":"This word just means the number eight. Strong's calls it a primary numeral, so it does not come from anything else. There is nothing behind a number to see.","flat":1,"g":"eight","h":"No picture."},"G3639":{"b":"Strong's says this word is \"ruin, i.e. death, punishment,\" from a root meaning to destroy. It is the state of something wrecked and undone. Paul uses it for the sudden ruin that comes on those who reject the truth.","g":"ruin, destruction","h":"The picture: laid in ruins."},"G364":{"b":"Built from a word meaning to remind. The picture is calling a thing back up into the mind. Jesus broke the bread and said, do this in anamnesis of Me, Luke 22:19. Every table a deliberate act of remembering.","g":"remembrance","h":"The picture: calling it back to mind."},"G3640":{"b":"Oligos means little or puny, and pistis means faith. Oligopistos measures a person's faith and finds it small, a scrap where more was needed. Why are you afraid, you of little faith. Not no faith, just too thin for the rising wind.","g":"of little faith","h":"The picture: faith shrunk to a scrap."},"G3641":{"b":"Strong's says the origin is uncertain, so nothing shows through. Abbott-Smith gives few, little, small, slight, and then only lists uses. A quantity word, with no image behind it.","flat":1,"g":"few, little","h":"No picture."},"G3642":{"b":"This joins oligos, little or puny, and psyche, the soul or breath. So it is the person whose spirit has shrunk, the faint-hearted, short of wind. Paul says do not scold them, comfort them and hold them up.","g":"faint-hearted","h":"The picture: the breath run small."},"G3643":{"b":"The root is a word meaning puny, next to nothing. So to despise here is to treat a thing as tiny, not worth your care. Hebrews says do not shrug off the Lord's correction as if it were a small thing.","g":"despise","h":"The picture: treating a thing as puny."},"G3644":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to spoil, to slay. An olothreutes is the destroyer, the one who strikes people dead. Paul warns them not to grumble, as some did and fell to the destroyer.","g":"destroyer","h":"The picture: the one who strikes people dead."},"G3645":{"b":"This comes from the word for ruin and death. It names the one who slays. At the Passover the blood on the doors held back the destroyer, so he could not touch Israel's firstborn.","g":"destroy","h":"The picture: the destroyer that brings ruin."},"G3646":{"b":"This word joins two others: whole, and to set on fire. Other offerings were shared and eaten. This one was not. The whole animal went up in flame on the altar, nothing kept back. That is what the word carries.","g":"burnt offering","h":"The picture: the whole animal burned to ash."},"G3647":{"b":"This word comes from a word meaning complete in every part, sound throughout. It means full soundness of body. Peter says faith in Jesus gave the lame man this, whole health in front of everyone. Not patched up. Every part working.","g":"soundness","h":"The picture: every part whole and in place."},"G3648":{"b":"This word joins whole with the word for a lot or allotted share, with all that fell to you by lot. It means complete in every part, no piece missing. Paul prays God keep them whole, spirit and soul and body. Nothing left out.","g":"whole, entire","h":"The picture: not one part missing."},"G3649":{"b":"The word sounds like the wail it names, a loud shriek of grief. James turns to the rich. Weep and howl, he says, for the misery coming on you. Not a sigh. A scream.","g":"howl","h":"The picture: a loud shriek of grief."},"G365":{"b":"The root is the word for new and fresh. With again in front, it means to renew, to make new once more. Paul says be made new in the spirit of your mind.","g":"renew","h":"The picture: made new again."},"G3650":{"b":"Strong's calls it a primary word. It does not come from anything else. It means whole, entire, complete. There is nothing behind it to look at.","flat":1,"g":"whole, all","h":"No picture."},"G3651":{"b":"This joins holos, whole, and telos, the end or goal. So it means complete right through to the finish, no part left out. Paul prays God would set them apart wholly, spirit, soul, and body kept sound.","g":"wholly","h":"The picture: whole all the way to the finish."},"G3652":{"b":"Strong's reads this name as a short form of a longer one meaning gift of Olympus, heaven-sent. Olympus was the towering mountain the Greeks made the home of their gods. Paul greets Olympas in the last of his Roman greetings.","g":"Olympas","h":"The picture: sent down from Olympus."},"G3653":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this is \"an unripe fig, which grows in winter and usually falls off in the spring.\" Picture hard green figs shaken loose before they ripen, thudding to the ground. So the stars fell to earth like unripe figs in a gale.","g":"unripe fig","h":"The picture: green figs dropping from the tree."},"G3654":{"b":"Built from the word for whole. It means wholly, altogether, and with a not in front, not at all. Jesus says do not swear holos, not at all, not by heaven or earth, Matthew 5:34. No corner left for a loophole.","g":"altogether, at all","h":"The picture: the whole of it, no corner left."},"G3655":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives this as a storm of rain, a shower. When you see a cloud rising in the west, Jesus says, you say at once a shower is coming, and it does. You read the sky but not the times you live in.","g":"shower","h":"The picture: a rainstorm rolling in."},"G3656":{"b":"This comes from a word for a gathered company of people. Strong's: \"to be in company with.\" To be that close to someone, close enough to talk. So on the Emmaus road the two walk side by side, and this is the word for their talking together.","g":"commune, talk","h":"The picture: walking close enough to talk."},"G3657":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives company, association. It is the people you mix with day by day. Paul warns that bad company rubs off, that keeping the wrong crowd slowly wears good habits down.","g":"companionship","h":"The picture: the crowd you spend your time with."},"G3659":{"b":"The word behind it means to gaze wide-eyed at something. Omma is the eye. When the two blind men beg by the road, Jesus touches their eyes, and at once they can see and follow him down it.","g":"eye","h":"The picture: the eyes themselves."},"G366":{"b":"This joins 'again' to a word meaning to keep off wine, to be sober. It pictures a man coming out of a drunken haze back to his senses. Paul hopes such people recover from the devil's snare, like a drunk sobering up.","g":"recover self","h":"The picture: waking up sober again."},"G3660":{"b":"Strong's says this is a longer form of a primary word that is now obsolete. The older word is lost. So we know it means to swear an oath, and no more than that.","flat":1,"g":"swear, take an oath","h":"No picture."},"G3661":{"b":"The word joins same and passion, the thumos that breathes hard. Homothumadon is with one mind, with one accord, a whole crowd breathing as one. Luke keeps using it of the first believers, together in prayer, their many hearts beating to a single pulse.","g":"one accord","h":"The picture: a crowd breathing as one."},"G3662":{"b":"The root is homoios, similar in appearance. Jesus says the Pharisees homoiazo whitewashed tombs, clean and bright outside, full of dead bones within. The word sets one thing beside another and says they match, at least on the surface.","g":"to resemble","h":"The picture: two things that look alike."},"G3663":{"b":"Built from \"similar\" and a word for feeling a sensation, usually a painful one. It means made of the same feelings as another. When the crowd tried to worship them, Paul cried that they were men of like feelings, aching and hungering just as the crowd did.","g":"like feelings","h":"The picture: two people who feel the very same things."},"G3664":{"b":"Homoios means like, resembling, cut from the idea of same. You hold two things up together and they match in form or nature. So the kingdom is homoios a mustard seed, a net, a pearl. Jesus sets it beside a known thing and says, like this.","g":"like","h":"The picture: two things set side by side, matching."},"G3665":{"b":"The root means similar, alike. This is likeness, one thing shaped like another. Hebrews says Christ was tempted in every way just as we are, yet without sin. He matches us point for point in the trial, close enough to feel it all.","g":"likeness","h":"The picture: the matching image."},"G3666":{"b":"The root means similar, alike. To homoioō is to make like or to liken, to hold two things side by side and show they match. Again and again Jesus asks to what he shall liken the kingdom, then lifts up a seed, a net, a coin.","g":"to liken","h":"The picture: two things held side by side."},"G3667":{"b":"Strong's first word is a form. A homoioma is a thing shaped to match another, like a copy cast in one mold. So when Scripture says Christ came in the likeness of men, it means made to look just like us.","g":"likeness","h":"The picture: a copy cast to match."},"G3668":{"b":"This is the adverb of homoios, like. Homoios means in like manner, the same way, do as was just done. So go and do likewise, homoios, tells the lawyer to copy the Samaritan move for move, mercy matched to mercy.","g":"likewise","h":"The picture: do the same, match it."},"G3669":{"b":"The root is homoioo, to make like. Abbott gives likeness. James says with the tongue we bless God and curse men made in his homoiosis. The word is the stamp of resemblance, humans shaped to mirror their Maker.","g":"likeness","h":"The picture: one thing made to resemble another."},"G367":{"b":"The name means Jah has favored. It joins a word for showing favor or grace with Jah, a short form of the Lord's name. Three different men in the New Testament carry this name.","g":"Ananias","h":"The picture: Jah has favored."},"G3670":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is to speak the same language. Then to agree with. Then to confess.\n\nSo confessing sin is not informing God. It is finally saying what he already says about it.","g":"confess, agree","h":"The picture: saying the same thing."},"G3671":{"b":"The root is to assent, to acknowledge, and the word joins \"same\" and \"word.\" To make homologia is to say the same thing God says, out loud. A confession is not private feeling. It is saying it where others can hear.","g":"confession","h":"The picture: saying the same word out loud."},"G3672":{"b":"The root means to say the same thing, to agree out loud. So this means by common consent, what all confess together with one voice. Paul says without controversy, great is the mystery of godliness.","g":"undeniably","h":"The picture: everyone saying the same word."},"G3673":{"b":"Two words, same and craft, the craft meaning a trade or skill. Two workers bent over the same kind of work. Paul stayed with Aquila because they shared a trade, both of them tentmakers.","g":"same trade","h":"The picture: the same workbench."},"G3674":{"b":"This means together, in the same place at the same time. It comes from a word meaning \"same.\" It is a plain position word with nothing to picture, only people gathered into one spot.","flat":1,"g":"together","h":"No picture."},"G3675":{"b":"The Greeks placed thought in the midriff, the partition below the lungs. This word joins \"same\" to that word. So being of one mind is sharing one gut. Peter wants Christians who think and feel as one.","g":"like-minded","h":"The picture: two people sharing one gut."},"G3676":{"b":"This word holds two things at once and says, even so. Abbott gives yet, nevertheless. Paul argues that even omos lifeless things, a flute or a harp, must give distinct notes to be understood, First Corinthians 14:7. Still, all the same.","g":"nevertheless, yet","h":"The picture: two things held at once."},"G3677":{"b":"An onar is a dream, the kind that comes in sleep. Joseph was warned in one to take the child to Egypt. Pilate's wife suffered in a dream over Jesus. Its origin is unknown, but the thing is plain, pictures seen with the eyes shut.","g":"dream","h":"The picture: a dream in the night."},"G3678":{"b":"This is the little-word form of the word for a donkey. It means a young one, a small donkey. Jesus found such a colt and sat on it to ride into the city. Not a warhorse. A little donkey.","g":"young donkey","h":"The picture: a small young donkey."},"G3679":{"b":"The old King James renders this cast in teeth. It comes from a word for a taunt, a disgrace shouted at someone. So to reproach is to fling a person's fault straight into his face.","g":"reproach","h":"The picture: throwing it in your teeth."},"G368":{"b":"Three parts, not, against, and to utter or speak. A thing no one can speak against, with no comeback to throw at it. The town clerk said this truth could not be contradicted, so the crowd should be still.","g":"undeniable","h":"The picture: no word to throw back."},"G3680":{"b":"The root means to rail at, to taunt, to chide. Oneidismos is the reproach itself, the abuse spoken over a person. Hebrews speaks of bearing the reproach of Christ, standing under the jeering that fell on him.","g":"reproach","h":"The picture: jeering thrown in the face."},"G3681":{"b":"The root is tied to onoma, a name. Abbott gives reproach, censure, blame. Elizabeth says God has taken away her oneidos, the disgrace of childlessness she carried. The word is a bad name pinned on you for all to see.","g":"reproach","h":"The picture: a stain on your name in public."},"G3682":{"b":"The name means profitable, useful. Onesimus was a runaway slave, and Paul plays on it: once he was useless to you, now he is useful to you and to me. A name that promised worth, made good only after Christ got hold of him.","g":"Onesimus","h":"The picture: the name that means useful."},"G3683":{"b":"This name joins profit with a word meaning a load that is carried. It means bringer of benefit, a man who hauls help to others. Paul says Onesiphorus often refreshed him and was not ashamed of his chains. His name and his life carried the same load.","g":"name (profit-bearer)","h":"The picture: a man who hauls help to others."},"G3684":{"b":"The root is onos, donkey. Onikos means belonging to an ass. It describes a millstone so heavy that only a donkey can turn it, not the small hand-mill. Jesus says better that stone hung on your neck than to trip a little one.","g":"of a donkey","h":"The picture: the great millstone a donkey turns."},"G3685":{"b":"This word means to have joy or benefit from someone. Strong's calls its base an apparently primary verb, so it does not come from anything you can picture. Paul asks Philemon to let him have this joy.","flat":1,"g":"have joy","h":"No picture."},"G3686":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the word stands for all that the name implies, of rank, authority and character. Acting in someone's name means acting on his authority.\n\nStrong's says the same in three words: authority, character. A name is not a label here.","g":"name","h":"The picture: the name carrying the whole person."},"G3687":{"b":"Straight from the word for a name. It means to name, to call by name, to give a name. Jesus chose twelve and named them apostles. To speak a name over a person or a thing.","g":"to name","h":"The picture: putting a name on someone."},"G3688":{"b":"This is a donkey, the plain working beast of burden. Jesus sent for an onos and rode it into Jerusalem, a king coming lowly, not on a war horse but on a young donkey's colt.","g":"donkey","h":"The picture: a donkey."},"G3689":{"b":"This word just means really, actually, truly. It is built from the Greek word for being. There is no image behind it, only the plain idea of what is so.","flat":1,"g":"really, truly","h":"No picture."},"G369":{"b":"The word comes from a root meaning indisputable, nothing to be spoken against. Cornelius says that when Peter sent for him he came at once, with no argument and no objection raised.","g":"without gainsaying","h":"The picture: not a word said back."},"G3690":{"b":"Abbott calls it sour wine, the ordinary drink of labourers and common soldiers. The root word means sharp. This is the biting, cheap wine a working man carried. Someone lifts a sponge soaked in it up to Jesus on the cross.","g":"sour wine","h":"The picture: the cheap wine of a working man."},"G3691":{"b":"This word means sharp, the edge of a sword or a sickle. In Revelation a sharp sword comes out of the mouth. By stretch it also means swift, since a sharp thing cuts fast. But the first thing to see is the keen blade.","g":"sharp","h":"The picture: the keen edge of a blade."},"G3692":{"b":"This is a hole, an opening in the rock, a cave. Strong's says it can also be a spring where water comes out. Hebrews says the faithful hid in caves and holes in the ground. James pictures a spring pouring from one opening. A gap in the stone.","g":"hole, cave","h":"The picture: a hole in the rock."},"G3693":{"b":"This word means behind, at the back, the side a person cannot see. The sick woman came up behind Jesus to touch his cloak, hoping to go unnoticed. It marks the space at your rear, where things approach unseen.","g":"behind","h":"The picture: coming up at someone's back."},"G3695":{"b":"The root G3696 is a tool or weapon of war. This word means to arm a soldier. Peter tells believers to arm themselves with the same mind as Christ, as a fighter takes up his gear.","g":"arm oneself","h":"The picture: a soldier strapping on his weapons."},"G3696":{"b":"This is a tool, an implement, and often a weapon of war. The soldiers come for Jesus with lanterns and weapons. Paul says offer your body parts as tools of righteousness, not of wrong. An instrument in the hand, used for good or harm.","g":"weapon, tool","h":"The picture: a tool or weapon in the hand."},"G3699":{"b":"This is built from a word meaning somewhere. Hopou marks the place, the very spot where something is or happens. So where your treasure is, there your heart will be. Hopou pins the heart to a location and will not let it drift.","g":"where","h":"The picture: the spot where it happens."},"G37":{"b":"Abbott-Smith explains it as to dedicate, separate, set apart for God. The thing is not improved. It is moved.\n\nCleaning follows, because what is set apart for God is then made to match.","g":"make holy","h":"The picture: set apart on its own shelf."},"G370":{"b":"Built from not and axios, deserving or of equal value. Abbott gives unworthy. Paul asks if the Corinthians are anaxios to judge small matters, since they will judge the world. A thing that does not measure up to the weight.","g":"unworthy","h":"The picture: not weighing enough to match."},"G3700":{"b":"Strong's says this word is looking with wide-open eyes, the way you stare at something remarkable. It is used of the risen Jesus letting himself be seen over forty days. Not a passing glance. Eyes fixed on what you cannot quite believe.","g":"to appear","h":"The picture: eyes wide open, staring."},"G3701":{"b":"The word comes from gazing with eyes thrown wide at something strange. An optasia is an appearing, a thing that comes into view. Zechariah comes out of the temple unable to speak, and they know he has seen one.","g":"vision","h":"The picture: something appearing before wide-open eyes."},"G3702":{"b":"This word means cooked, roasted, broiled. Picture a fish held over the fire. They gave the risen Jesus a piece of broiled fish, and he took it and ate it before them, to show he was truly raised.","g":"broiled","h":"The picture: fish roasted over coals."},"G3703":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the word first meant late summer, the fruit-time, and so came to mean \"ripe fruits.\" Picture baskets heaped with fruit at harvest. So Babylon is told the ripe fruit her soul craved is gone from her.","g":"ripe fruit","h":"The picture: fruit ripe at summer's end."},"G3705":{"b":"Abbott-Smith traces this to the word \"to see,\" and says it means \"that which is seen,\" a sight or spectacle. In Acts it is what appears to someone, the vision Peter and Paul were shown.","g":"vision, sight","h":"The picture: a thing seen."},"G3706":{"b":"This comes from the verb to see. Abbott lists the act of seeing, then the eyes themselves, then \"a vision,\" the thing shown to the inner eye. Your young men shall see visions, Peter says, quoting Joel.","g":"vision, sight","h":"The picture: eyes fixed on what is shown."},"G3707":{"b":"This comes from the word to see. It means visible, able to be looked at. Paul says by Christ all things were made, the things seen and the things unseen, thrones and powers alike.","g":"visible","h":"The picture: what the eye can see."},"G3708":{"b":"Strong's says the word properly means to stare at, and from there to make out clearly.\n\nAbbott-Smith calls it seeing in a lasting sense, not a glance. It also carries a warning use: see, take heed, beware.","g":"see, look at","h":"The picture: eyes fixed on something."},"G3709":{"b":"Strong's says this is properly desire, a reaching forth of the mind. Abbott's first sense is impulse, propensity, disposition.\n\nWrath here is not a sudden flare. It is a settled leaning that ends in action.","g":"wrath, anger","h":"The picture: the mind leaning out."},"G371":{"b":"The adverb from the last word. Abbott gives in an unworthy manner. Paul warns against eating the Lord's bread anaxios, without weighing what it is. The word describes not the person but the manner, a holy thing handled cheaply.","g":"unworthily","h":"The picture: coming to the table the wrong way."},"G3710":{"b":"The root pictures the mind reaching forth, swelling with passion until it boils over. So this is to be provoked, to burn. Be angry, Paul says, and do not sin. Feeling risen to a pitch.","g":"be angry","h":"The picture: the mind swelling up."},"G3711":{"b":"The root is orge, swelling anger. Abbott gives inclined to anger, passionate. Paul says an overseer must not be orgilos. The word is a temperament always near the boil, the man who flares before he thinks.","g":"soon angry","h":"The picture: a short fuse, quick to boil."},"G3712":{"b":"A fathom is the span of both arms held out wide, the reach from fingertip to fingertip. The root means to stretch out, to reach. The sailors measured the sea by arm-spans of rope. Twenty fathoms, then fifteen. The water was getting shallow.","g":"fathom","h":"The picture: arms stretched wide."},"G3713":{"b":"Strong's plain sense is to stretch oneself, to reach out after a thing. Picture an arm extended, straining for what is just past the fingertips. It came to mean to long for. If a man reaches after the office of overseer, Paul says, he wants a good work.","g":"reach after","h":"The picture: an arm stretched out."},"G3714":{"b":"The root is the word for a mountain, the land that lifts itself above the flat. This describes the high, hilly country. Mary hurries into it to reach Elizabeth, up into the hill towns of Judea, away from the level ground.","g":"hill country","h":"The picture: hills rising above the plain."},"G3715":{"b":"The root means to stretch yourself out, to reach after a thing. So this is the hunger that leans toward what it wants. Abbott calls it the general word for longing and appetite. Paul uses it of burning lust.","g":"lust, longing","h":"The picture: reaching out your hand for something."},"G3716":{"b":"The roots are straight and foot. Strong's says to be straight-footed, to go directly forward. Paul saw that Peter and the others were not walking straight toward the truth of the gospel, so he called it out.","g":"walk uprightly","h":"The picture: feet walking a straight line, not weaving off."},"G3717":{"b":"Strong's ties this to the word for a mountain, which lifts itself straight up above the plain. This word is that uprightness. Paul shouted to the crippled man to stand upright on his feet, and he leaped up and walked.","g":"upright","h":"The picture: standing straight up, rising like a mountain from flat ground."},"G3718":{"b":"This joins 'straight' to a word meaning to cut. Abbott says it means to cut straight, as when you cut a road straight through. Paul asks Timothy to handle the word of truth like that. Cut a clean, straight line through it.","g":"rightly divide","h":"The picture: cutting a straight road."},"G3719":{"b":"From a word for the dawn, the rising of light. This verb means to be up at daybreak. All the people came to him early, at dawn, in the temple to hear him. They could not wait for the day.","g":"come early","h":"The picture: up before sunrise."},"G372":{"b":"The root means to stop and repose. Anapausis is the pause when work is set down. The unclean spirit wanders dry places seeking anapausis and finds none. It is the breather a laborer takes when the load is off his back.","g":"rest","h":"The picture: setting down the work to rest."},"G3720":{"b":"From a word for the dawn, the rising of light. This word means early, belonging to daybreak. Some women of our company were at the tomb early, at dawn, the disciples said, and found the body gone. Hope came with the light.","g":"morning, early","h":"The picture: the first grey light of dawn."},"G3722":{"b":"Strong's says \"dawn, as sunrise, the rising of light.\" Abbott says \"daybreak.\" It is the earliest light, before the sun clears the ground. At this hour the women come to the tomb carrying their spices and find the stone rolled away.","g":"dawn, daybreak","h":"The picture: the first grey light of dawn."},"G3723":{"b":"The word comes from \"straight, upright,\" a post standing dead vertical. To do a thing orthos is to do it in a straight manner, no lean, no bend. You have answered rightly, Jesus tells the man. The healed man speaks plainly, straight.","g":"rightly","h":"The picture: a line drawn perfectly straight."},"G3724":{"b":"Strong's says this word is to mark out or bound, the root of our word horizon. It means to draw the border line. So when God appoints or decides a thing, the picture is a boundary drawn in the dirt. The edge is set. You cannot cross it.","g":"appoint, decree","h":"The picture: the line drawn on the ground."},"G3725":{"b":"Abbott-Smith traces this to a word meaning \"a boundary.\" So it names the edge of a territory, the line where one land stops and another begins. In the Gospels it marks the region around a town.","g":"border, region","h":"The picture: a boundary line."},"G3726":{"b":"The root is an oath, pictured as a sacred limit or restraint, a line you swear not to cross. This verb is to put someone under oath, to adjure. The man with the unclean spirit cried out, I adjure you by God, do not torment me.","g":"adjure","h":"The picture: binding someone with an oath."},"G3727":{"b":"Strong's traces this word from a fence, a boundary that holds you back. Abbott-Smith gives no origin. An oath fences you in, a sacred limit you have set and now must not step across.","g":"oath","h":"The picture: a fence you cannot cross."},"G3728":{"b":"One root is the word for an oath, meaning a limit, a sacred restraint. The other means to swear. This word is the swearing of an oath. God made Christ a priest with an oath, the writer says, a binding word the others never had.","g":"an oath","h":"The picture: a line you swear not to cross."},"G3729":{"b":"The root is a violent impulse, a sudden onset. To hormao is to charge, to plunge headlong. The herd of pigs hormao down the steep bank into the sea. One sudden stampede, driven over the edge.","g":"rush","h":"The picture: a herd charging headlong."},"G373":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means \"to give intermission from labour, to give rest, refresh.\" It is stopping the work for a while so strength returns. Jesus says come to me and I will give you rest.","g":"rest, refresh","h":"The picture: a pause from work."},"G3730":{"b":"This is a violent impulse, an onset, a sudden rush forward. In Acts a crowd made a horme to attack Paul, a mob breaking into a charge. James uses it small: the slight push of a hand on the rudder that turns a whole ship.","g":"assault","h":"The picture: a sudden rush forward."},"G3731":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives \"a rush,\" from a word meaning a violent impulse or onset. Picture something flung down with unstoppable force. So an angel throws a great stone into the sea, and Babylon will be cast down with that same rush.","g":"a rush, violence","h":"The picture: a stone hurled down with force."},"G3732":{"b":"The root means a bird, named for rising into the air. Orneon is just that, a bird. In Revelation an angel calls the birds to feast on the fallen. They circle over the battlefield, waiting to come down. Not a gentle picture.","g":"a bird","h":"The picture: birds circling in the air."},"G3733":{"b":"Ornis is a bird, and here a hen. Jesus cries over Jerusalem that he longed to gather her children as a hen gathers her chicks under her wings, and they would not. Wings held open, and no one running in.","g":"hen","h":"The picture: a hen spreading her wings over her chicks."},"G3734":{"b":"Two words, a boundary-line and to place. It means to set the border markers in the ground, fixing where a land begins and ends. God marked out the bounds of every nation's dwelling.","g":"boundary","h":"The picture: the boundary stones set down."},"G3735":{"b":"Strong's calls a mountain the thing that lifts itself above the plain, and links the word to an old verb for rising.\n\nAbbott adds the proverb. Moving mountains meant doing what could not be done.","g":"mountain","h":"The picture: the ground rearing up."},"G3736":{"b":"This means to dig, to burrow down into the ground. A man planted a vineyard and dug a pit for the winepress. The lazy servant dug a hole and buried his master's money. The word is a spade turning earth.","g":"dig","h":"The picture: a spade turning the earth."},"G3737":{"b":"This is the word our \"orphan\" comes from. Abbott says \"orphan, fatherless,\" and then bereft, desolate. Jesus tells the disciples he will not leave them like this, abandoned children with no one, but will come back to them.","g":"orphan","h":"The picture: a child left with no parents."},"G3738":{"b":"The word means to dance. Strong's links it to regular, rank-like motion, dancers moving in order. Jesus quotes the children's complaint, we played the flute and you did not dance. Bodies moving in time to the music, or refusing to.","g":"dance","h":"The picture: dancing in rows."},"G374":{"b":"This is built on the word to convince by argument, with a prefix meaning up. To stir a person up with words, to talk him into a thing. The charge was that Paul was winning men to worship God wrongly.","g":"incite","h":"The picture: talking someone around."},"G3741":{"b":"This word means holy, right in a deep and built-in way. Strong's says its origin is of uncertain affinity, so there is nothing behind it to trace. It points to what is right by its own nature, not to any object you could see.","flat":1,"g":"holy","h":"No picture."},"G3742":{"b":"The root means right by God's own character, the reverent rightness he approves. Paul says the new self is made in righteousness and true holiness. This piety, holiness stands beside justice toward men and points upward, the clean loyalty God himself calls good.","g":"holiness","h":"The picture: right before God."},"G3743":{"b":"The root is hosios, right by God's own standard. Abbott gives piously, holily. Paul says he lived among the Thessalonians hosios and justly and blamelessly. Conduct that answers to what God counts sacred, undefiled living.","g":"holily","h":"The picture: hands kept clean before God."},"G3744":{"b":"The root is to give off a scent. This is a smell, an odour carried on the air. When Mary poured the ointment, the whole house filled with its fragrance. Paul says we spread the aroma of Christ, a scent that reaches everyone near.","g":"odour, fragrance","h":"The picture: a smell filling the room."},"G3747":{"b":"This is simply the word for a bone. Whitewashed tombs, Jesus says, are lovely outside but full of dead men's bones within. Joseph, dying, gave orders about his bones. The word points to the hard frame left when the flesh is gone.","g":"bone","h":"The picture: bare bones inside the tomb."},"G3749":{"b":"The root is a word for an earthen vessel or potsherd, baked clay. Ostrakinos means made of clay, cheap and easily broken. Paul says we hold this treasure in clay jars, so the power is seen to be God's.","g":"earthen","h":"The picture: a jar of baked clay."},"G375":{"b":"Built from a word meaning up and a word meaning to send. It is to send someone up to a higher authority, or to send them back. Pilate sent Jesus up to Herod, and Herod sent him back. Passed along from hand to hand.","g":"send back","h":"The picture: passing a prisoner up the chain."},"G3750":{"b":"The word means smell, the sense itself. It pictures the nose at work, catching a scent. Paul says if the whole body were one eye there would be no hearing, and if all hearing, no sense of smell.","g":"smelling","h":"The picture: the nose catching a scent."},"G3751":{"b":"Strong's calls it the loin, the hip. Abbott says the Hebrews saw it as \"the seat of generative power,\" where a person's children come from. Acts speaks of a promised heir as the fruit of David's loins.","g":"loin, hip","h":"The picture: the hip, where a family line begins."},"G3757":{"b":"The word marks a place, where. Jesus came to Nazareth, hou he had been brought up. And he promises that hou two or three gather in his name, there he is among them. A small word that pins a spot on the map.","g":"where","h":"The picture: a spot pinned on the map."},"G376":{"b":"The word rests on a root meaning maimed. Abbott says \"maimed, crippled.\" Jesus tells the host to invite exactly these, the poor and the maimed, the ones who cannot repay. The broken bodies most feasts leave out.","g":"maimed, crippled","h":"The picture: a body broken and maimed."},"G3760":{"b":"Built from oudeis, not even one. Abbott gives in no wise, by no means. Matthew quotes the prophet that Bethlehem is oudamos least among Judah's rulers. The word is an emphatic no, slamming the door on the very idea.","g":"by no means","h":"The picture: not in the least, no way."},"G3761":{"b":"This word joins one negative to another, neither, nor, not even. It is a piece of grammar, a way of stacking two denials in a row. There is no concrete thing behind it, only the work of saying no and then no again.","flat":1,"g":"neither, nor","h":"No picture."},"G3764":{"b":"Not even yet. Abbott gives not yet. Picture the new tomb in the garden where no one had oudepo been laid, John 19:41. An empty grave, waiting, because the thing it was made for had not yet come to pass.","g":"not yet","h":"The picture: still not, even now."},"G3769":{"b":"The word means a tail. Revelation uses it of locusts with tails like scorpions and of the dragon whose tail sweeps a third of the stars down. It is the plain back end of a beast, and here it stings and drags.","g":"tail","h":"The picture: an animal's tail."},"G377":{"b":"Strong's says it means \"to fall back, i.e. lie down, lean back.\" At the table people ate lying down, so it came to mean reclining for a meal. John leaned back on Jesus this way at the supper.","g":"recline, lean back","h":"The picture: falling back to lean."},"G3770":{"b":"Strong's says it means belonging to or coming from the sky. It is built from the word for sky or heaven. Your heavenly Father is the Father above, over the whole sky.","g":"heavenly","h":"The picture: belonging to the sky."},"G3771":{"b":"The root is the word for the sky, and the ending means \"from.\" So it means straight down out of the sky. God sends rain ouranothen. On the Damascus road a light brighter than the sun came down ouranothen around Paul.","g":"from heaven","h":"The picture: coming down out of the sky."},"G3772":{"b":"Strong's says the word perhaps comes from a root carrying the idea of elevation. He hedges, and Abbott-Smith gives no origin.\n\nWhat both agree on is the plain sense: the vault of the sky, and then the home of God.","g":"heaven, sky","h":"The picture: what is lifted up over you."},"G3773":{"b":"This Latin name means of the city. It is where we get the word urbane. Urbanus was likely a city slave's name. Paul calls him our fellow worker in Christ. A name stamped with the streets of Rome.","g":"Urbanus","h":"The picture: the city."},"G3774":{"b":"The name means flame of Jah. It joins a word for flame with Jah, a short form of the Lord's name. Uriah the Hittite was the loyal soldier whose wife Bathsheba King David took.","g":"Uriah","h":"The picture: flame of Jah."},"G3775":{"b":"Strong's calls it apparently a primary word. It just means the ear.\n\nAbbott notes the writers use it for understanding as well as hearing, but that is how they used it, not something hiding inside the word.","flat":1,"g":"ear","h":"No picture."},"G3776":{"b":"The word grows from the verb \"to be,\" so it means what is yours. Abbott says \"substance, property.\" The younger son demands his share of it, turns land and goods into cash, and wastes the whole estate in a far country.","g":"property, goods","h":"The picture: the family estate, everything you own."},"G378":{"b":"Ana means up, and pleroo means to fill, to cram a net or level a hollow. Anapleroo pictures filling a thing right up to the top, packing the gap full. To fill up the measure of sins, or to take your place in the room.","g":"fill up","h":"The picture: filling the hollow to the top."},"G3781":{"b":"Strong's calls this an ower, a person indebted. First it meant owing money, a real sum written on the books. Forgive us our debts, we pray. Jesus tells of a debtor who owed more than he could ever repay, brought before his master.","g":"debtor","h":"The picture: a man who owes money."},"G3782":{"b":"The root means to owe. This is the debt itself, the amount marked against your name. Paul says pay everyone what you owe them. Whatever stands on the account against another, this word is the sum you still have to hand over.","g":"debt","h":"The picture: the sum you owe."},"G3783":{"b":"The root means to owe. An opheilema is what is owed, a debt, money you are on the hook for. Jesus tells us to pray, forgive us our debts. He puts sin in the language of money owed. Wipe the account clean, as we wipe out what others owe us.","g":"a debt","h":"The picture: money you owe."},"G3784":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is to owe, be a debtor, with money owed and money due.\n\nOnly then does it stretch to ought and must. What you should do is money you already owe.","g":"owe, ought","h":"The picture: a debt on the books."},"G3786":{"b":"Strong's traces this to a word meaning to heap up, to accumulate. Picture a pile growing higher. Ophelos is the gain left when the heap has grown. James asks what the profit is if you bless a hungry man but give him nothing.","g":"profit","h":"The picture: a growing heap."},"G3787":{"b":"This word joins the words for eye and service. It is the work a servant does only while the master's eye is on him. The moment the eye turns away, he stops. Paul says serve as if God always sees, not just when watched.","g":"eye-service","h":"The picture: working only while the eye watches."},"G3788":{"b":"It means the eye. Abbott notes one turn of speech. A bad eye stood for envy.\n\nSo when Jesus talks about a good eye and a bad eye, he is using a common phrase about greed and generosity.","g":"eye","h":"The picture: the bad eye."},"G3789":{"b":"This is a serpent, a snake. Abbott says it stood as a type of wisdom and cunning. Behind it lies the snake in Eden. \"Be wise as serpents and harmless as doves.\"","g":"serpent, snake","h":"The picture: the snake."},"G379":{"b":"The root means to make your legal defense, to speak up for yourself in court. Put not in front and you are left with no defense at all. Paul says those who ignore God stand like a defendant with nothing to say.","g":"without excuse","h":"The picture: a defendant with nothing to say."},"G3790":{"b":"This word first means an eyebrow, then the brow of a hill, its overhanging edge above a drop. The angry crowd led Jesus to the brow of their hill to throw him down headlong. He passed through them and went away.","g":"brow","h":"The picture: the brow of the hill, like an eyebrow."},"G3791":{"b":"This word comes from the word for a crowd or mob. It means to harass, to trouble, the way a jostling throng wears a person down. Luke uses it of people tormented by unclean spirits, brought to the apostles to be freed.","g":"to vex","h":"The picture: a crowd mobbing and jostling you."},"G3792":{"b":"Two words, crowd and make. The root is a throng, a rabble borne along. So this means to manufacture a crowd out of nothing. Jealous men gathered a mob and set the city in an uproar.","g":"gather a mob","h":"The picture: rounding up a mob."},"G3793":{"b":"Strong's says a throng, as borne along. Abbott-Smith calls it a moving crowd, a throng.\n\nThe word has motion in it. Not people standing in a room. People pressing and shifting, carrying you with them.","g":"crowd, multitude","h":"The picture: a crowd being carried along."},"G3794":{"b":"The root means to fortify, to make firm. Abbott-Smith gives a stronghold, fortress. Paul says our weapons pull down strongholds, the mental fortresses where proud arguments hole up against the knowledge of God.","g":"stronghold","h":"The picture: a walled fortress on a hill."},"G3795":{"b":"This word first meant a cooked relish eaten with bread, and came to mean fish, since fish was the common relish. The boy had five loaves and two fish. A bit of cooked fish to go with the bread.","g":"fish","h":"The picture: cooked fish eaten with bread."},"G3796":{"b":"The word comes from the idea of the back, the far end. It means late in the day, at evening, when the sun is behind you and the light is nearly gone. Mark uses it for the hour Jesus looked round the temple and left.","g":"late, evening","h":"The picture: the light going at the end of the day."},"G3797":{"b":"The root means late in the day, toward evening. So this is the latter rain, the last showers before harvest. James says the farmer waits through both rains for his crop. So wait for the coming of the Lord.","g":"latter","h":"The picture: the last rain late in the season."},"G3798":{"b":"The root means late in the day. Opsios is the late hour, evening, when the sun drops and work ends. It is evening when Jesus stills the storm, evening when the risen Lord stands among the locked-in disciples and says peace to them.","g":"evening","h":"The picture: the late hour when the sun drops."},"G3799":{"b":"Strong's ties this to a word meaning to gaze with wide-open eyes. Opsis is what the eyes land on, the face, the outward look of a thing. So do not judge by opsis means do not judge by the surface a man shows.","g":"face, appearance","h":"The picture: the face you turn toward others."},"G38":{"b":"Abbott says the ending marks a process, not a finished state. The root means to purify or consecrate. So this is the work of being made holy, still under way. Holiness being made, not just owned.","g":"sanctification","h":"The picture: the setting apart, still going on."},"G380":{"b":"This word means to unroll. A scroll is kept furled, and to read it you open it out, unwinding the roll. In the synagogue Jesus unrolled the scroll of Isaiah, found his place, and read the words about himself.","g":"unroll","h":"The picture: unrolling the scroll."},"G3800":{"b":"The word began as ration-money, the coins that bought a soldier his food, then plain wages. John tells the soldiers to be content with their opsonion. The wages of sin is death, Paul writes, the grim pay handed to the one who serves it.","g":"wages","h":"The picture: a soldier's pay for his rations."},"G3802":{"b":"The root is a trap, the kind fastened with a noose or a notch to catch a bird. This word is the act of setting it. In Matthew 22:15 the Pharisees plot how to trap Jesus in something he says.","g":"ensnare, entangle","h":"The picture: setting a snare."},"G3803":{"b":"The root means to fix or peg in place, like driving a tent stake. A snare is a trap pegged down, a noose set to snap shut. That day will spring on all the earth like a trap. Fastened and waiting.","g":"snare, trap","h":"The picture: a noose pegged and waiting to spring."},"G3804":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is that which befalls one, a suffering, affliction. The word points to what happens to you, what you undergo rather than do. Paul aches to share Christ's pathēmata, the very blows that fell on him.","g":"suffering","h":"The picture: the blow that falls on you."},"G3805":{"b":"This comes from the word for suffering, pain undergone. It means able to suffer, subject to being hurt. Paul says the promise was that the Christ would suffer, that he could bleed and die. The word puts him in a body that pain can reach, not beyond it.","g":"subject to suffering","h":"The picture: flesh that can be wounded."},"G3806":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is that which one suffers. A pathos is not something you do, it is something done to you, an emotion that seizes and carries you. In the New Testament it is always the bad kind, a desire that has taken the reins.","g":"passion, lust","h":"The picture: something done to you, not by you."},"G3807":{"b":"The roots are pais, a boy, and ago, to lead. The paidagogos was the household slave who walked the boy to school and back and kept him in line, not the teacher. Paul says the Law was this slave, walking us to Christ.","g":"schoolmaster","h":"The picture: the slave who walked the boy to school."},"G3808":{"b":"A small form of the word for a boy. It means a little boy, a lad. There is a lad here with five barley loaves and two fish, Andrew said, though they were little among so many. Small hands held the start of the miracle.","g":"lad, child","h":"The picture: a little boy in the crowd."},"G3809":{"b":"The root means to train up a child, and that includes both lessons and the rod. Paideia is everything a parent does to bring a child up, teaching and correction together. So the Lord's paideia is a Father raising sons, not a judge punishing.","g":"discipline","h":"The picture: a parent raising a child."},"G381":{"b":"The root means to fasten to, and so to set on fire. Abbott says \"to kindle.\" James says how small a spark it takes to set a whole forest ablaze. Jesus came to throw this fire on the earth.","g":"kindle, light","h":"The picture: touching a flame to kindling."},"G3810":{"b":"The root means to bring up a child, to train and, when needed, discipline. A paideutes is that trainer, the teacher who both instructs and corrects. It carries the schooling of a child, lessons and the rod together. The one who shapes the young.","g":"instructor","h":"The picture: a teacher with rod in hand."},"G3811":{"b":"Strong's says this first meant \"to train up a child.\" From there it stretched to teaching anyone, and then to correcting them. So the discipline in this word is a parent's kind. Even the punishment is the care you give your own child.","g":"train, discipline","h":"The picture: raising a child."},"G3812":{"b":"The root is the word for a young child. This word means from childhood on, since he was small. In Mark 9:21 Jesus asks how long this has happened to the boy, and the father answers, from childhood, and it has often thrown him into fire.","g":"from childhood","h":"The picture: ever since he was a small boy."},"G3813":{"b":"This is the small form of the word for child, the way English turns dog into doggy.\n\nAbbott-Smith notes it was also used in friendly address, like calling grown men lads. John writes it to full-grown believers.","g":"little child","h":"The picture: the little one."},"G3814":{"b":"Abbott says the word means a young girl, a maiden. It is the small form of the word for \"child.\" It came to mean a servant girl. The maid at the fire questioned Peter.","g":"maid, servant girl","h":"The picture: a little serving girl."},"G3815":{"b":"Abbott gives it as to play as a child, with singing and dancing. It pictures children at play, laughing and leaping. Paul quotes it darkly, the people rose up to play before the golden calf.","g":"play","h":"The picture: children at play."},"G3816":{"b":"Abbott-Smith lines this word up with Latin puer, French garçon and English boy. One word for a child and for a servant.\n\nActs uses it of Jesus. Both senses are sitting inside it.","g":"child, servant","h":"The picture: calling a servant \"boy\"."},"G3817":{"b":"This means to hit, one sharp blow, and it can also mean a scorpion's sting. Who struck you, they taunted Jesus, after they paio him. In Revelation the sting of the locusts is the paio of a scorpion, a sudden stab of pain.","g":"to strike","h":"The picture: one sharp blow or a scorpion's sting."},"G3819":{"b":"This means long ago, of old, in time past. Hebrews opens with it, God who long ago spoke to the fathers by the prophets. It points back down the years, to what is old and gone by.","g":"long ago","h":"The picture: far back in time."},"G382":{"b":"This is the word to count with 'not' in front. It means past all counting. From one man as good as dead came children as many as the stars of heaven and the sand by the sea.","g":"innumerable","h":"The picture: too many to count."},"G3820":{"b":"Abbott-Smith makes the distinction plain. Not merely old, but worn by use.\n\nThat is why it fits the old garment and the old wineskins. It is also the word Paul uses for the old self.","g":"old, worn out","h":"The picture: a coat worn thin."},"G3821":{"b":"The root means old, not recent, worn out. So this is oldness, the state of the worn and outdated. Abbott says oldness. Paul says we serve in the newness of the Spirit, not in the oldness of the letter.","g":"oldness","h":"The picture: something old and worn thin."},"G3822":{"b":"The word means to make or grow old, worn out by time and use, like a coat gone threadbare. Make purses that do not palaioo, Jesus says, that never wear out. The first covenant, Hebrews says, God has made old, and what grows old is ready to vanish.","g":"make old","h":"The picture: clothes worn thin and old."},"G3823":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this word means wrestling, two bodies gripping and straining against each other. Paul says our wrestling is not against flesh and blood but against unseen powers. It is close and hand-to-hand.","g":"wrestling","h":"The picture: a wrestling match."},"G3824":{"b":"This joins palin, again, to genesis, birth. Palingenesia is being born a second time, or the whole world made new. Jesus uses it for the renewal of all things, when the Son of Man sits on his throne and everything begins again.","g":"regeneration","h":"The picture: a second birth."},"G3825":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is about place, not time: back, backwards.\n\nOnly after that does it mean again, once more. So the ordinary word for again carries a return in it. Doing it again is going back.","g":"again","h":"The picture: turning back the way you came."},"G3826":{"b":"Built from a word for all and a word for a throng, a populace. With the whole multitude together, all at once. They cried out as one, away with this man and release Barabbas. The mob moved as a single body.","g":"all at once","h":"The picture: the whole crowd as one voice."},"G3828":{"b":"Strong's reads this place name as every-tribal, a region of all tribes mixed together, many peoples in one land. Pamphylia sat in Asia Minor. Paul and Barnabas passed through it more than once. A name meaning all races together.","g":"Pamphylia","h":"The picture: a land of all tribes mixed."},"G3829":{"b":"This word is built from all and to receive. It means a place that receives everyone, an inn. The Samaritan brought the wounded man to one of these roadside shelters and cared for him there through the night.","g":"inn","h":"The picture: a roadside inn that takes all comers."},"G383":{"b":"The root means to shake, to rock back and forth, the word behind \"seismic\". First it meant to shake something up and down. Then to stir people up. Mark uses it for the priests who shook the crowd into shouting for Barabbas.","g":"stir up","h":"The picture: shaking a crowd like a tree."},"G3830":{"b":"Built from all and to receive, this word is the innkeeper, the one who takes in all comers. The Samaritan handed him two coins and told him to look after the man, promising to repay whatever more it cost.","g":"host, innkeeper","h":"The picture: the innkeeper who takes over the care."},"G3831":{"b":"Built from \"all\" and the word for the town-square where people gathered, this is the whole town packed into the open square for a festival. Hebrews uses it for the great joyful assembly of heaven.","g":"general assembly","h":"The picture: the whole town packed into the square."},"G3832":{"b":"Two words, all and house. The root behind house means a dwelling and, by extension, a family under one roof. So this means the entire household at once. The jailer believed with everyone in his house.","g":"whole household","h":"The picture: the whole house together."},"G3833":{"b":"The word joins all and weapon. It means the full armour, every piece a soldier wears, nothing missing. The strong man guards his house in his full armour. Paul tells us to put on the whole armour of God. Covered from helmet to boots.","g":"full armor","h":"The picture: a soldier armored head to toe."},"G3834":{"b":"The root means all-working, a person ready to do anything to get their way. It becomes cunning, trickery, the clever hand that stops at nothing. They tried to trap Jesus by such craft. Any means will do.","g":"craftiness","h":"The picture: a hand ready for any trick."},"G3835":{"b":"The roots are all and work, one who will do any deed. Abbott-Smith says ready to do anything, knavish. Paul says, being crafty, he caught them by guile, then insists he never fleeced them.","g":"crafty","h":"The picture: a man who will stoop to any trick to win."},"G3837":{"b":"Built from the word for all. It means everywhere, in all places. The disciples went out and preached everywhere, the Lord working with them. No corner left out.","g":"everywhere","h":"The picture: in every place at once."},"G3838":{"b":"This joins \"all\" to \"the end,\" the point aimed at. Abbott says \"all-complete, entire.\" Hebrews says Christ saves to the uttermost, the whole distance to the goal. Not rescued partway and left. Carried all the way home.","g":"entire, complete","h":"The picture: all the way to the finish, not partway."},"G3839":{"b":"The root is pas, all. Abbott gives every way, entirely. Tertullus tells Felix the people accept his rule pante and everywhere with thankfulness. The word spreads a thing across all directions, leaving no corner uncovered.","g":"entirely","h":"The picture: on every side, from all directions."},"G384":{"b":"The word comes from 'a vessel,' the gear and baggage of a household. It first meant to pack up your kit, then to dismantle and ravage. Certain men, the letter says, had torn up the believers' souls with words.","g":"subvert, unsettle","h":"The picture: a camp torn down and packed up."},"G3840":{"b":"This means from every side, from all directions at once. So many came to Jesus from all sides that he could not enter a town openly. Picture a crowd closing in from every direction, leaving no gap, pressing toward him.","g":"from all sides","h":"The picture: hemmed in from every direction."},"G3841":{"b":"Abbott-Smith builds it from all and to hold power. It pictures the One who holds power over everything, ruler of all. It is a favorite title for God in Revelation.","g":"almighty","h":"The picture: the grip that holds everything."},"G3842":{"b":"Strong's spells this one out. It is built from the word for all and the word for when, so it reads every when.\n\nThat is the whole of it. Not usually. Not mostly. Every single when.","g":"always","h":"The picture: every when."},"G3843":{"b":"From the word for all. It means altogether, by all means, surely. Paul becomes all things to all men, that by all means he might save some. Wholly, without a gap left.","g":"by all means","h":"The picture: all the way, no exception."},"G3845":{"b":"The roots are a step and \"past.\" So it is stepping over a line, putting your foot across it. Jesus asks why they step over God's command to keep their own tradition. To transgress is to cross a boundary on purpose.","g":"transgress","h":"The picture: stepping over the line."},"G3846":{"b":"The parts mean beside and throw. It first meant tossing fodder down beside the horses. For sailors it came to mean throwing the ship across to a place. They crossed over and arrived at Samos.","g":"cross over","h":"The picture: throwing fodder beside the horses."},"G3847":{"b":"Para means across, and baino means to step. Parabasis pictures stepping over a line, crossing the boundary set for you. Sin as a fence you climb past on purpose. Where there is no law there is no line to cross.","g":"transgression","h":"The picture: stepping over the line."},"G3848":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives two senses. First, one who stands beside. Then, a transgressor. Picture a boundary line drawn on the ground and a man who puts his foot across it. That is the lawbreaker, not vague, but over the mark.","g":"transgressor","h":"The picture: the foot that steps over the line."},"G3849":{"b":"The root means to force, and this word bends it toward pressing by pleading. Abbott says \"to constrain by entreaty.\" On the Emmaus road the two disciples all but drag Jesus in, pressing him hard to stay the night with them.","g":"constrain, compel","h":"The picture: pressing someone hard to stay."},"G385":{"b":"The root means to draw, and \"up\" is added. Abbott says \"to draw up.\" Jesus asks who would not haul his ox or his son straight up out of a well on the sabbath. A hard, upward pull on a rope.","g":"draw up, pull out","h":"The picture: hauling an ox up out of a well."},"G3850":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is a placing beside. The word is built from setting one thing next to another so you can compare them.\n\nA parable lays an everyday scene alongside the kingdom and lets you look.","g":"parable","h":"The picture: two things set side by side."},"G3851":{"b":"Abbott-Smith reads this as a word meaning to expose oneself to danger, to hazard one's life, like a gambler risking everything on one throw. Paul says Epaphroditus risked his life to serve, coming close to death.","g":"risk life","h":"The picture: throwing your life onto the table."},"G3852":{"b":"The root means to pass a message along, to enjoin. Abbott notes it was a military order, a command handed down the ranks. The council gave the apostles strict charge to stop teaching. An order coming down from above.","g":"charge, command","h":"The picture: an order passed down the ranks."},"G3853":{"b":"Strong's says the word means to transmit a message. Abbott's first sense is the same, and only after that does it mean to order, command.\n\nA command here is a message handed on, not shouted.","g":"command, charge","h":"The picture: passing an order down the line."},"G3854":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is to be beside or at hand, and from there, to stand by, support.\n\nThe common word for arriving carries the idea of taking your place next to a person. Paul uses it of a time when nobody did.","g":"arrive, come","h":"The picture: showing up beside someone."},"G3855":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means to pass by, and also to pass away. The word joins alongside and go. Jesus passed by and called his followers. And the shape of this world passes by, moving off and gone.","g":"pass by, pass away","h":"The picture: passing on by."},"G3856":{"b":"The root means to exhibit, to put on show. This word means to display someone before the crowd for shame. To fall away and mock Christ is to hold him up to public disgrace.","g":"open shame","h":"The picture: put on public display."},"G3857":{"b":"This is an old Eastern word for a park, the enclosed pleasure-garden of a Persian king, full of trees and water. It came to mean the garden home of the blessed dead. Jesus tells the thief, today you will be with me in paradise.","g":"paradise","h":"The picture: a walled royal garden."},"G3858":{"b":"This joins beside to a word for receiving. To take a thing in near, to welcome it. The good soil receives the word this way. It is not a cold nod but bringing something close and giving it room inside you.","g":"receive, admit","h":"The picture: taking someone in close."},"G3859":{"b":"The root diatribo means to wear or rub through, used of wearing away time. Para adds a sense of aside. So it is time rubbed away in useless wrangling. Paul warns of such among men of corrupt mind who think godliness is gain.","g":"useless wrangling","h":"The picture: time worn away in friction."},"G386":{"b":"That is all the word says. Abbott-Smith gives a raising up, awakening, rising, and notes it was used in inscriptions for putting up a monument.\n\nWhat was lying down gets to its feet.","g":"resurrection","h":"The picture: standing up again."},"G3860":{"b":"Strong's says to surrender, to yield up, to entrust, to transmit. Abbott-Smith's first sense is to give or hand over to another.\n\nThe same word covers handing on a teaching and handing a prisoner to the court. Judas gets this word.","g":"hand over, betray","h":"The picture: putting something into another man's hands."},"G3861":{"b":"Built from para, beside, and doxa, opinion. Abbott gives incredible, marvellous. When the paralytic walks, the crowd says we have seen paradoxos things today. A thing standing right beside your expectations and contradicting them.","g":"strange","h":"The picture: a sight that defies what you expected."},"G3862":{"b":"Abbott says the word means a handing down or over. Tradition is what gets passed from one hand to the next, down the years. Jesus spoke of the tradition of the elders.","g":"tradition","h":"The picture: passed hand to hand."},"G3863":{"b":"The root means warmth of feeling, for or against. The prefix means alongside. To provoke to jealousy is to kindle that heat in someone by setting a rival next to them. God says he will do this to Israel, to stir them by another people.","g":"provoke to jealousy","h":"The picture: stirring up heat beside someone."},"G3864":{"b":"Built from a word for beside and the word for the sea. So it means beside the sea, on the shore. Capernaum, where Jesus settled, sat right at the water. Picture a town at the edge of the sea.","g":"by the sea","h":"The picture: a town at the sea's edge."},"G3865":{"b":"This word joins beside with a word meaning to look at or watch. It means to look past, to overlook. In the early church the Greek widows were being overlooked in the daily food handout, passed over, their need unseen.","g":"to neglect","h":"The picture: your eyes sliding right past someone."},"G3866":{"b":"The root means to place alongside, to set a thing in another's care. A paratheke is a deposit, goods you hand to someone you trust to guard. Paul tells Timothy to guard the deposit given him. The gospel is left in his hands to keep.","g":"a deposit, trust","h":"The picture: something handed over for safekeeping."},"G3867":{"b":"This joins beside with a word for praise. It is advice pressed on you from alongside, urging a course. Paul stood among the frightened crew and urged them to take heart. A voice right at your side, pushing you on.","g":"exhort, urge","h":"The picture: a word spoken at your side."},"G3868":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means \"to beg off, ask to be excused.\" It is asking your way out of something, turning it down. In the parable the invited guests each made an excuse and would not come.","g":"refuse, excuse","h":"The picture: begging to be let off."},"G3869":{"b":"This word joins beside and to sit. Abbott-Smith gives it as to sit down beside. Mary sat herself down right at the Lord's feet and listened to his word, while her sister Martha stayed busy with all the serving.","g":"sit","h":"The picture: sitting down close at someone's feet."},"G387":{"b":"This word comes from a word meaning to drive a person out of home. To turn a place upside down, to drive folk into the street. These men who turn the world upside down have come here too, the mob cried.","g":"stir up","h":"The picture: people driven out of their homes."},"G3870":{"b":"Strong's says it means to call near. You call a person over to stand with you.\n\nThat one word covers begging, urging, and comforting. Abbott lists all three. Whatever the reason, the person is called close.","g":"comfort, urge","h":"The picture: calling someone to your side."},"G3871":{"b":"This word means to cover by hanging something beside, to hide. Abbott-Smith paints a cloth draped across. The meaning of Jesus' words about his death was veiled from the disciples, hidden as if behind a curtain, so they could not grasp it.","g":"hide","h":"The picture: a veil hung over the words."},"G3873":{"b":"Built from beside and to lie, something lying right at your side. Paul says the will to do good lies close at hand, but the doing is not there. Evil lies beside him too, always within reach. Right there next to you.","g":"be at hand","h":"The picture: lying right at your side."},"G3874":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is a calling to one's aid. You send for help and someone comes and stands with you.\n\nThat is why the same word covers comfort, encouragement and pleading. It is all one action.","g":"comfort, encouragement","h":"The picture: calling someone to your side."},"G3875":{"b":"The word comes from calling someone to your side. In court a parakletos is the friend called to stand beside the accused and speak for him. Jesus gives such a helper, the Spirit called alongside. One who takes your side.","g":"advocate, comforter","h":"The picture: a friend called to your side in court."},"G3876":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is a hearing amiss. The roots are para, beside, and akouo, to hear. It started as hearing wrong, letting a word slip past your ear. Then it hardened into disobedience. By one man's failure to listen, many were made sinners.","g":"disobedience","h":"The picture: hearing a word wrong."},"G3877":{"b":"The word is \"follow\" with \"near\" joined on. It means to follow closely, right at the heels, close enough to trace the whole path. Luke uses it for how he traced the events from the start. Timothy has followed Paul's teaching this way, step by step.","g":"follow closely","h":"The picture: following so close you trace every step."},"G3878":{"b":"The root is to hear, and para means beside or past. So it is hearing that slides right past, hearing without heeding. Jesus says if a brother will not listen even to the church, treat him as an outsider. The words came, and he let them go by.","g":"disobey","h":"The picture: hearing the words go past you."},"G3879":{"b":"Built from a word meaning beside and a word meaning to bend forward. It is stooping down and leaning in to peer inside. Peter bent down and looked into the empty tomb and saw the linen cloths lying there.","g":"stoop to look","h":"The picture: bending low to peer inside."},"G388":{"b":"The root means to put someone on a cross. This word adds 'again.' Those who fall away and turn back to sin crucify the Son of God a second time, and hold him up to open shame.","g":"crucify afresh","h":"The picture: nailing him to the cross again."},"G3880":{"b":"The word for take, with beside attached to the front. Abbott-Smith gives to take to or with oneself.\n\nIt covers taking people along on a journey, and also receiving a teaching handed on from someone else.","g":"take along, receive","h":"The picture: taking someone with you."},"G3881":{"b":"Built from beside and an old sense of laying alongside. For sailors it meant to coast, to sail close past the land. Paul's ship crept along the coast of Crete, hugging the shore, laying its course right beside the land.","g":"coast along","h":"The picture: hugging the shore."},"G3882":{"b":"This word is built from beside and the word for the salt sea. Strong's reads it as beside the salt sea. It means the sea coast, the land running right along the water. People came from there to hear Jesus and be healed.","g":"sea coast","h":"The picture: the strip of land along the sea."},"G3883":{"b":"The root means to make different, to change. Strong's hears the shifting of a star's orbit or the moon's phases. James says the Father of lights has none of it. No wobble, no phase, no shadow moving across him.","g":"variableness","h":"The picture: a star shifting in its orbit."},"G3884":{"b":"This word is built from a root meaning to take an inventory, to count things up. Set \"off\" beside it and you get a false count, books cooked so the sum comes out wrong. James warns of the reasoning that misleads. Numbers made to lie.","g":"deceive, delude","h":"The picture: cooking the books."},"G3885":{"b":"Strong's says the word pictures a body as if dissolved. It comes from a word meaning to loosen. The limbs of a paralyzed man hang loose and undone, as though they had come untied.","g":"paralytic","h":"The picture: a body gone slack."},"G3886":{"b":"Built from a word meaning beside and a word meaning to loosen. The joints come loose, slack as an untied cord, and will not hold. They carried a man whose body was loosened this way. The strength let go.","g":"paralyze","h":"The picture: a limb gone slack."},"G3887":{"b":"The roots are \"beside\" and \"to stay.\" So this word is to stay right beside, not to drift off. It is used of remaining alive and of remaining near. The one who looks into the perfect law and stays beside it is blessed.","g":"to remain","h":"The picture: staying put at someone's side."},"G3888":{"b":"The word is \"beside\" plus speech, mythos, \"a tale\" told. To come alongside someone and talk them through it. So the friends came to sit beside Martha and Mary and speak comfort over their dead brother. Words, close up.","g":"comfort, console","h":"The picture: sitting beside someone and speaking soft."},"G3889":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to relate near, to console. It pictures words spoken close beside a grieving person, drawing near to steady them. Paul says the one who prophesies speaks such comfort to the church.","g":"comfort","h":"The picture: words spoken close beside you."},"G389":{"b":"The pieces mean up and to groan or sigh. It is a heavy sigh dragged up from deep inside. In Mark 8:12 the Pharisees demand a sign, and Jesus sighs deeply in his spirit before answering that no sign will be given.","g":"sigh deeply","h":"The picture: a groan heaved up from the chest."},"G3890":{"b":"This is built on the idea of speaking beside someone. Abbott-Smith gives exhortation, persuasion, encouragement, the gentle words a friend gives at your side. Paul appeals to any comfort there is in Christ's love.","g":"comfort","h":"The picture: words spoken close beside you."},"G3891":{"b":"This joins para, alongside or past, to nomos, the law. The law marks a line. To break it is to step past that line, to put your foot outside it. Paul says the judge orders him struck against the law, breaking the very rule he sits to guard.","g":"break the law","h":"The picture: stepping over the line the law draws."},"G3892":{"b":"The root means to be opposed to law, to transgress. So this is law-breaking, going past the boundary. Peter uses it of Balaam's wrongdoing, when a mute donkey checked the prophet's course.","g":"transgression","h":"The picture: stepping across the line of the law."},"G3893":{"b":"The root means to make bitter, to embitter. This word adds 'alongside,' so it is to provoke by souring the mood. In the desert the people turned bitter against God and provoked him to anger.","g":"provoke","h":"The picture: turning something bitter."},"G3894":{"b":"The root means to embitter, from the word for bitter. Provocation is making God's heart bitter, souring it with rebellion. Hebrews recalls Israel in the desert, provoking him at Meribah. The bitter taste that stubborn people leave behind.","g":"provocation","h":"The picture: turning something bitter."},"G3895":{"b":"The root means to fall. This word adds 'aside,' to fall away off the path. Those who have tasted the good gift and then fall away cannot easily be brought back to repentance again.","g":"fall away","h":"The picture: falling off to the side."},"G3896":{"b":"This joins beside with a word meaning to pass in a vessel, to sail. So it means to sail on past a place without stopping. Paul had decided to sail past Ephesus to save time.","g":"sail past","h":"The picture: the ship gliding past a shore."},"G3897":{"b":"Built from two words meaning near and close by. It means nearly, right up alongside. Paul says Epaphroditus was sick, close beside death, almost gone, but God had mercy on him.","g":"almost","h":"The picture: right up against the edge."},"G3898":{"b":"The root means close by, right alongside. This word means in the same way. Since the children share flesh and blood, Jesus took the same flesh and blood himself, standing right beside them in it.","g":"in like manner","h":"The picture: standing right alongside."},"G3899":{"b":"Built from a word meaning beside and a word meaning to travel. It is walking along past something, going right by it. The people who passed the cross walked by this way, close enough to see, and kept moving.","g":"pass by","h":"The picture: walking right past on the road."},"G390":{"b":"Strong's core sense is to overturn, also to return. The word is about turning and moving around. From moving about in a place it came to mean how a person lives and behaves day to day.","g":"behave, live","h":"The picture: how you turn about among people."},"G3900":{"b":"Strong's calls it a side-slip. Abbott-Smith's first sense is a false step, a blunder.\n\nThen it becomes the moral word for a trespass. The image is not rebellion. It is losing your footing.","g":"trespass, slip","h":"The picture: a foot slipping sideways."},"G3901":{"b":"The root means to flow, to run like water. This word is to drift or slip past. A boat not tied fast is carried by the current past the landing. So we must hold the truth, or drift past it.","g":"slip away","h":"The picture: the boat drifting past the landing."},"G3902":{"b":"The word joins beside and to mark. So it means marked on the side. Abbott lands on a figurehead, the carved sign on a ship's prow. Paul's ship out of Malta carried the Twin Brothers as its figurehead.","g":"figurehead","h":"The picture: the carved figurehead on a ship's bow."},"G3903":{"b":"The word leans on skeuos, \"a vessel, implement, equipment or apparatus.\" To lay out the vessels and set everything in place beforehand. Peter grows hungry while below they are making the meal ready. It is also the soldier readying his kit.","g":"prepare, make ready","h":"The picture: laying out the gear before you need it."},"G3904":{"b":"The root means to get ready, to furnish beforehand. To the Jews this became the name for Friday, the day you prepared everything before the Sabbath rest. Jesus was buried as it was ending. It is the day of making ready.","g":"preparation","h":"The picture: the day you get everything ready."},"G3905":{"b":"The root here is teino, to stretch, to pull something out long. So this means to draw a thing out in time. Paul stretched his talk on and on, all the way to midnight.","g":"prolong","h":"The picture: stretching a speech out long."},"G3906":{"b":"This is watching from close beside, keeping your eye upon someone, often with bad intent. The Pharisees watch Jesus narrowly to catch him healing on the Sabbath. Not a friendly glance but the stare of a spy waiting for a mistake.","g":"watch closely","h":"The picture: an eye fixed on you to catch a slip."},"G3907":{"b":"The root means to inspect alongside, to note narrowly, even to spy. Picture someone peering in to catch a sign. The kingdom of God does not come with watching for it, Jesus said. You will not spot it like that.","g":"observation","h":"The picture: watching closely from beside."},"G3908":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is to place beside, set before, and nearly every example is a meal.\n\nThe middle voice turns it into entrusting. Jesus uses that form from the cross when he commits his spirit to the Father.","g":"set before, entrust","h":"The picture: food set in front of you."},"G3909":{"b":"This joins beside and happen. It means to happen to be near or present, to chance by. In the market Paul reasoned with anyone who happened to be standing there, day by day.","g":"meet with","h":"The picture: whoever happened to be there."},"G391":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the old meaning was \"a wheeling about,\" a turning down or back. Later it came to mean the way you live day to day. So behavior is how you carry yourself as you go about among people.","g":"behavior, conduct","h":"The picture: how you turn about."},"G3910":{"b":"Built from para and autos, meaning right at the very moment. Abbott gives momentary, for a moment. Paul calls our affliction parautika, light and lasting only an instant, set against an eternal weight of glory.","g":"momentary","h":"The picture: here this instant, then gone."},"G3911":{"b":"The word is \"carry\" with \"aside\" on it. To paraphero is to bear a thing away, to take it off to one side. Father, take away this cup from me, Jesus prays. Carry it past. Yet not what I will, but what you will.","g":"take away","h":"The picture: a cup carried away from the table."},"G3912":{"b":"The roots are beside and to think. Abbott-Smith says to be beside oneself, deranged. Paul says he is talking like a madman now, standing beside his own good sense as he boasts of his sufferings.","g":"act the fool","h":"The picture: a mind slipped off to one side of itself."},"G3913":{"b":"The root means to misthink, to be out of one's mind. Beside plus mind gives a mind pushed off track. Peter calls Balaam's course this madness, checked when his donkey spoke with a human voice.","g":"madness","h":"The picture: a mind knocked off to the side."},"G3914":{"b":"The root means \"to storm, i.e. (passively) to labor under a gale.\" This word is to sit out the winter, to stay in one place through the season of storms when no ship dares sail. Paul planned to winter at a safe harbor rather than risk the sea.","g":"to winter","h":"The picture: waiting out the storm season in harbor."},"G3915":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to winter near a place, to wait out the rainy season. It is the wintering-over itself. The harbour was judged unfit for it, so they risked sailing on. The word is a ship tied up safe while the cold storms pass.","g":"wintering","h":"The picture: a ship laid up for the winter."},"G3916":{"b":"Strong's takes it apart literally. At the thing itself.\n\nAbbott-Smith gives it as on the spot, forthwith. Luke uses it again and again for healings. No gap between the word and the result.","g":"immediately","h":"The picture: right there on the spot."},"G3917":{"b":"The word means a leopard or panther. Abbott-Smith gives \"a panther, leopard.\" Picture the spotted cat, fast and deadly. So the beast rising from the sea looked like a leopard, built to hunt and kill.","g":"leopard","h":"The picture: a leopard."},"G3918":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives it as to be by, at hand or present. It is the word for being, with alongside stuck on the front.\n\nPaul sets it against being absent. Here in the room, not far off.","g":"be present","h":"The picture: standing right beside you."},"G3919":{"b":"This joins \"beside\" to a root meaning to lead in. In later writers it means to bring in secretly. Peter says false teachers will smuggle in destructive heresies, denying the Master who bought them.","g":"privily bring in","h":"The picture: slipping something in by a side door."},"G392":{"b":"The root means to arrange in an orderly manner, to line things up in their places. This word is putting them in order. Luke uses it for his Gospel. He gathered the reports and set them down in careful order for his reader.","g":"set in order","h":"The picture: setting things in order, one after another."},"G3920":{"b":"The root means to lead in on the sly. Strong's says smuggled in, and Abbott-Smith adds like spies or traitors. Paul warns of false brothers sneaked into the church to spy on their freedom.","g":"brought in unawares","h":"The picture: a spy slipped in through the side door."},"G3921":{"b":"This joins \"beside\" and \"into\" to a root meaning to sink or go down. So it is to slip in secretly, to steal in. Jude says certain ungodly men had crept in among them unnoticed, long ago marked for judgment.","g":"creep in unawares","h":"The picture: slipping in sideways through a gap."},"G3922":{"b":"Built from beside and to enter, coming in off to the side. It can mean slipping in secretly, sneaking through a side way. Paul says the law came in alongside, and elsewhere that false brothers stole in unnoticed. Entering by the side, quietly.","g":"slip in","h":"The picture: sneaking in a side door."},"G3923":{"b":"This joins \"beside\" to a root meaning to carry inward. So it is bringing something in as well. Peter tells readers to bring all diligence in beside their faith, adding virtue to it.","g":"bring in","h":"The picture: carrying something in alongside."},"G3924":{"b":"The roots mean beside and outside. This word points to what stands out beside the rest, except, besides. Paul names all his hardships, then adds what comes upon him besides, outside that list. It sets things apart from the main count.","g":"besides, except","h":"The picture: what is left outside the count."},"G3925":{"b":"Strong's calls it a throwing in beside. It pictures troops set in beside one another, drawn up in rows. So it means an army in array, and then the camp or barracks where the soldiers stay.","g":"camp, army","h":"The picture: ranks drawn up side by side."},"G3926":{"b":"The root means to crowd in, and so to annoy. James rules that the church should not crowd the Gentiles with heavy burdens as they turn to God, only a few needful things.","g":"trouble, annoy","h":"The picture: a crowd pressing in on you."},"G3927":{"b":"The word is built from parts meaning beside and to live in a foreign country. A parepidemos is a stranger staying in a land not his own, here for a while, not from here. Peter calls Christians this. They live in the world like foreigners far from home.","g":"stranger, pilgrim","h":"The picture: the foreigner living far from home."},"G3928":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is to pass, pass by, used of people and of time. Then to pass away, perish.\n\nHeaven and earth passing away is the same word as a man going by on the road.","g":"pass by, pass away","h":"The picture: someone walking past you."},"G3929":{"b":"Abbott builds this from a word meaning to let go, to pass by. So it is a letting go, a passing over of debt or sin. Abbott says passing by. Paul says God passed over sins done beforehand, holding back His hand.","g":"passing over","h":"The picture: letting a debt pass by unpaid for now."},"G393":{"b":"Built from up. Abbott-Smith uses it as intransitive, to rise, of light and of the sun. God makes his sun rise on the evil and the good. Hebrews says the Lord rose, like a dawn, from Judah.","g":"rise, spring up","h":"The picture: the sun coming up."},"G3930":{"b":"Strong's says it means to hold near, to present or afford. The word joins beside with holding. You hold a thing out at someone's side and offer it. That is how it comes to mean to supply or give.","g":"provide, give","h":"The picture: holding something out to a person."},"G3931":{"b":"The root joins para, beside, with a word tied to the public square where people spoke. So it is speech brought right up next to you to steady you, comfort. Paul says these few fellow workers were a comfort to him.","g":"comfort","h":"The picture: a voice speaking close at your side."},"G3932":{"b":"The root is parthenos, a maiden. Abbott gives virginity. Luke says Anna lived with a husband seven years from her parthenia. The word marks the season of maidenhood before a woman is joined to a husband.","g":"virginity","h":"The picture: a young woman's unmarried years."},"G3933":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means a maiden, virgin. Strong's says its origin is unknown. So there is no image behind it. It simply names an unmarried young woman.","flat":1,"g":"virgin","h":"No picture."},"G3934":{"b":"This is the name of a people, the Parthians, from a land east of the empire. It stands in the list of nations who heard the apostles at Pentecost. Strong's calls it foreign in origin and gives no meaning. Just a people's name.","flat":1,"g":"Parthian","h":"No picture."},"G3935":{"b":"The word means to let go slack, to loosen. Hebrews uses it for hands that hang down limp and tired. Lift up the hands that droop, it says, and steady the weak knees.","g":"hang down","h":"The picture: hands that hang down limp."},"G3936":{"b":"Strong's says to stand beside. Abbott gives both halves, to place beside and to stand by or beside one.\n\nWhen Paul asks people to present themselves to God, the word is simply stepping up and standing there.","g":"present, stand by","h":"The picture: standing right next to someone."},"G3937":{"b":"This name is built from beside and to stay. It means constant, one who remains. Parmenas was among the seven chosen to serve tables so the apostles could keep to prayer and preaching. A name for someone who stays put.","g":"Parmenas","h":"The picture: the one who stays beside and does not leave."},"G3938":{"b":"The word joins beside and road. Abbott-Smith gives a passing or passage, going by in passing. Paul says he does not want to see them only in passing, a quick look on his way through. He wants to stay.","g":"way, passage","h":"The picture: passing by on the road without stopping."},"G3939":{"b":"The word joins \"beside\" to the word for keeping a house. Abbott says \"to dwell in a place as a stranger.\" It is the foreigner living among others, never quite belonging. Abraham lived this way in the promised land, in tents, an outsider.","g":"sojourn","h":"The picture: living in a place that is not your home."},"G394":{"b":"The word joins up and to place, to set a thing up where it can be seen. To declare is to lay your case out in the open, to put it up for others. Festus set Paul's case before the king this way.","g":"declare","h":"The picture: laying a case on the table."},"G3940":{"b":"The root means having a home near, a by-dweller, someone who lives beside a people but is not one of them. This word is that life. Israel lived this way in Egypt, and Peter says believers live it now.","g":"sojourning","h":"The picture: living in a house beside people who are not your own."},"G3941":{"b":"The word is \"beside\" plus \"house.\" Strong's: \"a by-dweller,\" someone whose home sits near yours but who is not of the household. A resident foreigner, always a little outside. Peter calls Christians strangers like this, living next door to the world.","g":"stranger, sojourner","h":"The picture: the man who lives next to the house, not in it."},"G3942":{"b":"The word comes from by the way, the roadside. A paroimia is a wayside saying, a proverb passed along the road from mouth to mouth. The dog returns to its vomit, Peter quotes. A saying everyone already knows.","g":"proverb","h":"The picture: a saying picked up by the roadside."},"G3943":{"b":"This word joins beside and the word for wine. It pictures the man who stays near his cup, always at the wine, a heavy drinker. Paul says an overseer must not be like this. Not the one you find lingering by the jug.","g":"given to wine","h":"The picture: the man who lingers at his cup."},"G3944":{"b":"The word joins 'by' with 'to depart, to be gone.' It is used of time slipping away. In past generations, Paul says, God let all the nations walk their own roads.","g":"past, gone by","h":"The picture: a traveler already walked on past."},"G3945":{"b":"Built from para, beside, and homoios, similar. Abbott gives to be like. Jesus says the Pharisees paromoiazo whitewashed tombs. The word lays one thing next to another and finds them close, alike enough that the comparison sticks.","g":"be like unto","h":"The picture: nearly a match, set side by side."},"G3946":{"b":"Built from para, beside, and homoios, similar. Abbott gives much like, like. Jesus tells the Pharisees they do many paromoios things, others just like the tradition he named. The word is near-sameness, one thing shadowing another.","g":"similar","h":"The picture: standing close alongside, much the same."},"G3947":{"b":"The root, oxys, means keen, sharp. To paroxyno is to whet, to draw a sharp edge alongside something. In Athens Paul's spirit was sharpened within him at the idols. Paul also says love is not sharpened, not easily provoked to anger.","g":"provoke","h":"The picture: putting a keen edge on a blade."},"G3948":{"b":"The root means to sharpen alongside, to grind an edge onto a blade. This word is that sharpening turned into feeling. It can spur someone toward love, or cut into a quarrel. Paul and Barnabas had one so sharp they parted ways.","g":"contention","h":"The picture: a blade ground sharp against a stone."},"G3949":{"b":"Built from alongside and to enrage. It means to needle someone into anger, to stir them until they boil over. God says he will provoke his people to jealousy through another nation. Fathers are warned not to goad their children to rage.","g":"provoke to anger","h":"The picture: prodding someone until they boil."},"G395":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means \"a rising,\" said of light, the sun-rising, and so the east. Zechariah calls the coming Messiah the dayspring, the sunrise from on high that visits us.","g":"dawn, east","h":"The picture: the rising of the sun."},"G3950":{"b":"The root means to anger alongside, to provoke. Abbott calls it irritation, a less permanent state than settled wrath. So this is a flash of temper, not a lasting grudge. Paul says do not let the sun go down on it.","g":"rage","h":"The picture: a flash of temper that flames and dies."},"G3951":{"b":"Strong's says the word is 'beside' plus a root meaning to spur. To stir up is to spur a horse forward. The opponents spur the leading women and men of the city against Paul and Barnabas.","g":"stir up","h":"The picture: digging in the spurs."},"G3952":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this became a technical term for the visit of a king. The city prepares, the roads clear, the crowds gather.\n\nThat is the word the New Testament uses for Christ coming back.","g":"coming, arrival","h":"The picture: a king arriving in town."},"G3953":{"b":"This joins para, beside, to a word for cooked food, a relish. A paropsis was first the side dish of dainties, then the plate itself. Jesus says you scrub the outside of cup and platter clean while inside they are full of greed.","g":"platter, dish","h":"The picture: the platter you serve food on."},"G3954":{"b":"Strong's calls it all out-spokenness. Abbott traces it to the words for all and for speech, so it is freedom to say everything.\n\nAbbott adds that the confidence sense grew from the absence of fear that comes with such speech.","g":"boldness, plain speech","h":"The picture: saying all of it."},"G3955":{"b":"The root means all-speech, telling the whole of it out in the open, with frankness, bluntness, publicity. After Damascus, Saul speaks out boldly in the name of Jesus. No part of the truth swallowed.","g":"speak boldly","h":"The picture: saying it all, holding nothing back."},"G3956":{"b":"This word just means all. Strong's calls it a primary word, which means it does not come from anything else. There is nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"all, every","h":"No picture."},"G3957":{"b":"One word does three jobs. It names the festival, and Abbott-Smith says it also stands for the paschal supper and for the lamb itself.\n\nSo when Paul calls Christ our Passover, he means the lamb.","g":"Passover","h":"The picture: the lamb on the table."},"G3958":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means to suffer, to be acted on, as opposed to acting. Usually it is misfortune.\n\nBut he notes it can cover pleasant experiences too. The word itself only says something happened to you.","g":"suffer","h":"The picture: being on the receiving end."},"G3959":{"b":"This is Patara, a place in Asia Minor, a harbor of Lycia where Paul changed ships. It is a bare name of foreign origin, so there is nothing here to picture.","flat":1,"g":"Patara","h":"No picture."},"G396":{"b":"This word joins up with a word meaning a turn. It is to turn something up and over, to tip it onto its end. Paul says false teachers overturn whole households, upending the faith of families. A table flipped, and everything on it spilled.","g":"overturn, subvert","h":"The picture: a table tipped on its end."},"G3960":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says in Homer this word first meant the beat of the heart, a throb. Then it grew to mean striking a blow. Strike the shepherd, the Bible says, and the sheep are scattered.","g":"strike, smite","h":"The picture: a striking blow."},"G3961":{"b":"This means to tread, to stamp down with the feet. Abbott points to treading the winepress, feet crushing the grapes underfoot. Jesus also gives power to tread on snakes and scorpions unharmed. Feet coming down hard.","g":"tread, trample","h":"The picture: feet crushing grapes in the press."},"G3962":{"b":"Strong's calls it apparently a primary word. It does not come from anything else. Abbott-Smith adds no origin, only the uses: a human father, and God as Father. There is no older image here.","flat":1,"g":"father","h":"No picture."},"G3963":{"b":"Patmos is a place, an island in the Aegean Sea where John was sent in exile. Strong's says its name is of uncertain derivation, so we cannot see what it once meant. There is nothing behind it to picture.","flat":1,"g":"Patmos","h":"No picture."},"G3964":{"b":"Pater is father. The rest comes from the same root as the word for a mother-thresher, from beating grain flat on the floor. So it pictures striking a father to the ground, killing him. Paul lists such men among the lawless.","g":"father-killer","h":"The picture: a man who strikes his father down."},"G3965":{"b":"The word grows straight out of father. It means a family or tribe, all those who trace back to one man. Joseph goes up to Bethlehem because he is of the house and family of David. The whole line from a single father.","g":"family, lineage","h":"The picture: everyone descended from one father."},"G3966":{"b":"The word joins \"family line\" to \"to be first (in political rank or power).\" A patriarch is the founding father at the head of the family tree, the one all the others come from. Abraham, the twelve sons, David, the roots of the nation.","g":"patriarch","h":"The picture: the founding father at the head of the line."},"G3967":{"b":"The root is the word for a father. Abbott-Smith says paternal, ancestral. Paul says he burned with zeal for the traditions of his fathers, the ways passed down the family line, holding them tight.","g":"of the fathers","h":"The picture: customs handed down from father to son."},"G3968":{"b":"Abbott traces it to πατήρ, father, and calls it \"fatherland, country, home, native place.\" It is the place of your fathers, the town you come from. A prophet, Jesus says, has no honor in his own hometown.","g":"hometown","h":"The picture: the land of your fathers."},"G3969":{"b":"Strong's reads this name as father's life, from the words for father and for life. So the man greeted in Romans carries a small blessing in his name, a life and a father bound together in one word.","g":"a Christian","h":"The picture: father's life."},"G397":{"b":"This word is built from a word for up and a word for feeding and nourishing. To raise a child by feeding it, year on year, up to full size. Moses was brought up in Pharaoh's house, and Paul at Gamaliel's feet.","g":"bring up","h":"The picture: feeding a child up to full growth."},"G3970":{"b":"Built from \"father\" and a word meaning to hand over, this is what is passed from father to son, placed into the next hand. Peter says Christ bought you out of the empty way of life handed to you like that.","g":"handed down from fathers","h":"The picture: passed down from father to son."},"G3971":{"b":"This word means of the fathers, handed down. It comes from the word for father. Patroos is the inheritance passed down the family line, son from father. Paul kept the law of his fathers and served their God.","g":"of the fathers","h":"The picture: handed down from the fathers."},"G3972":{"b":"Strong's says this is a Latin name and that it means little. That is all he offers.\n\nAbbott-Smith says nothing about the meaning. He only lists the two men who carry it, a Roman official and the apostle.","g":"Paul","h":"The picture: small."},"G3973":{"b":"This word means to stop, cease, leave off. Strong's calls it a primary verb, which means it does not come from anything else. Our word \"pause\" echoes it. There is nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"cease, stop","h":"No picture."},"G3974":{"b":"This is the name of a city in Cyprus, a place in Cyprus where Paul met the sorcerer. Its origin is uncertain. So there is no meaning behind the name to see. Only a place on the map.","flat":1,"g":"Paphos","h":"No picture."},"G3975":{"b":"The word means to thicken, to fatten. Applied to the heart it pictures a layer of fat growing over it until the heart feels nothing. Isaiah's warning, quoted here, is of a heart grown too padded and slow to respond.","g":"thicken, make dull","h":"The picture: fat growing over the heart."},"G3976":{"b":"The root is the foot. This is a fetter, the iron shackle clamped on the ankles. Men had bound the wild man with fetters and chains, but he tore them apart. The word is the shackle meant to hold the feet, and it did not hold.","g":"fetter","h":"The picture: iron shackles on the feet."},"G3977":{"b":"Strong's ties this to the word for foot: level, as easy for the feet. It is ground with no climb in it. Jesus came down from the hills and stood on a level place to teach the crowd.","g":"level, plain","h":"The picture: flat ground, easy on the feet."},"G3978":{"b":"This rests on a word meaning foot-wise, by walking. To make a journey on your own two feet. Paul chose to go by land on foot to Assos while the others sailed around.","g":"go on foot","h":"The picture: going on foot."},"G3979":{"b":"The root is pous, foot. Pezei means on foot, by land instead of by boat. When the crowds hear where Jesus is, they do not wait for a ship. They go around the lake walking, on their own feet.","g":"on foot","h":"The picture: going on your own two feet."},"G398":{"b":"The root means to shine or show, with \"up\" added. Abbott uses it of sailors sighting Cyprus, the land lifting into view, and says \"to bring to light, make to appear.\" The crowd thought God's kingdom would rise into sight at once.","g":"appear","h":"The picture: land rising into view over the sea."},"G3980":{"b":"The word joins \"to be persuaded\" with \"ruler.\" Not obedience forced at swordpoint, but obedience because you were talked round, \"to convince (by argument, true or false).\" We ought to obey God, Peter says, persuaded to follow the one in charge.","g":"obey","h":"The picture: won over to follow the one in charge."},"G3981":{"b":"This is built from a word meaning to convince by argument, true or false. Peithos speech is talk shaped to win you over. Paul says his preaching did not lean on that. His words came with the Spirit's power, not clever persuasion.","g":"persuasive","h":"The picture: words that talk you over."},"G3982":{"b":"One word does three jobs. Abbott-Smith gives to prevail upon or win over, then to be persuaded, then to listen to, obey.\n\nTrust in this word is what is left standing after someone has convinced you.","g":"persuade, trust","h":"The picture: being won over."},"G3983":{"b":"This is the plain word for being hungry. Abbott-Smith then lists its figurative uses, including Matthew 5:6.\n\nSo hungering for righteousness is not a mild wish. It is what a man feels who has not eaten.","g":"be hungry","h":"The picture: an empty stomach."},"G3984":{"b":"This word is a trial, a test by actual experience. Strong's ties it to the idea of piercing through, going right through a thing to prove it. Hebrews says the faithful had trial of mockings and scourgings. Faith proven not in theory but by passing through the fire.","g":"trial, test","h":"The picture: tested by going right through it."},"G3985":{"b":"Abbott gives this word a good sense and a bad sense. God tests to prove a person. The devil tests to trip him.\n\nAbbott's own heading is to test, try, prove. Same action. The difference is who is running it.","g":"test, tempt","h":"The picture: one test, two aims."},"G3986":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives an old sense first. An experiment.\n\nThen he splits the word two ways. A trial in a good or neutral sense, and a trial regarded as leading to sin. One word, two outcomes.","g":"trial, temptation","h":"The picture: a test run."},"G3987":{"b":"This comes from peira, a test or trial. The word means to try, to make an attempt. It is putting something to the proof by having a go at it. Paul says the Jews seized him in the temple and tried to kill him. The word is the attempt, the hands-on try.","g":"try, attempt","h":"The picture: laying hands to a thing to test it."},"G3988":{"b":"This comes from the same word, to convince by argument, true or false. It is the pull of being talked round. Paul warns the Galatians that this persuasion did not come from the God who called them.","g":"persuasion","h":"The picture: being talked into it."},"G3989":{"b":"Pelagos is the open sea, the deep water far from shore. Jesus uses it for where the millstone should drag the offender down, the depth of the sea, not the shallows near the beach. Deep enough that nothing comes back up.","g":"deep sea","h":"The picture: the open deep of the sea."},"G399":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means to carry or lead up. It joins up and carry. A priest carries the offering up to the altar. Peter writes that Jesus carried our sins up onto the tree.","g":"offer up, carry up","h":"The picture: carrying something up."},"G3990":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the word comes from \"a battle-axe,\" and means to cut off the head. Picture the blade falling on the neck. So John sees the souls of those beheaded for their witness to Jesus.","g":"to behead","h":"The picture: the axe that beheads."},"G3991":{"b":"From the word for five. It marks the fifth thing in order. John saw the fifth seal opened and, under the altar, the souls of those who had been slain for the word of God, Revelation 6:9. The fifth in the count.","g":"fifth","h":"The picture: the fifth in the count."},"G3992":{"b":"Strong's says the word looks from the sender's end, not the destination. And especially on a temporary errand.\n\nGo, do this, come back. That is the flavour underneath.","g":"send","h":"The picture: sending someone on an errand."},"G3993":{"b":"Abbott-Smith traces it to a word meaning to work for one's daily bread. Not the beggar with his hand out, but the poor man earning thin. Paul quotes the psalm, God scattered gifts to the poor.","g":"poor","h":"The picture: a laborer working for each day's bread."},"G3994":{"b":"The feminine of the word for a father-in-law. It means a mother-in-law, a wife's mother. Jesus came to Peter's house and found his mother-in-law in bed with a fever, and healed her. A named place in the family.","g":"mother-in-law","h":"The picture: the wife's mother."},"G3995":{"b":"This word means a father-in-law, the father of a man's wife. John uses it of Annas, who was father-in-law to Caiaphas the high priest. It marks a family tie by marriage. The older man whose daughter you married.","g":"father-in-law","h":"The picture: your wife's father."},"G3996":{"b":"This is the word to mourn for, to lament, the word for grieving the dead. Abbott joins it often with weeping. It is sorrow that breaks the surface, not a private ache. The kind everyone can see.","g":"mourn","h":"The picture: grief you cannot hide."},"G3997":{"b":"Strong's ties this to a word for feeling something painful. Penthos is mourning, the grief that shows. It is the weeping and sorrow poured out over a loss. Revelation promises a day when God wipes every tear and this mourning is no more.","g":"mourning, sorrow","h":"The picture: open mourning for the dead."},"G3998":{"b":"The root means starving, indigent, one who works for each day's bread. Picture a hand with nothing left over. Jesus watched a poor widow drop two small coins into the treasury. She gave out of her want, everything she had.","g":"poor","h":"The picture: the empty hand of the poor."},"G3999":{"b":"This is a counting word, five times over, built straight from the number five. Paul uses it to tally his scars. Five times he received the thirty-nine lashes. He is counting the cost of carrying the gospel.","g":"five times","h":"The picture: five times over."},"G4":{"b":"The root is weight, a load, and the not lifts it off. Abbott-Smith says without weight. Paul says he kept himself from being a weight on them, carrying his own costs so they felt nothing.","g":"not burdensome","h":"The picture: a load so light it presses on no one."},"G40":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it first meant dedicated to the gods, sacred. He traces it to a word for religious awe.\n\nSo holy does not start at clean. It starts at set aside, given away, not yours to use.","g":"holy, set apart","h":"The picture: something handed over to the gods."},"G400":{"b":"This word joins up with a word meaning to make a sound. So it is to lift the voice and cry out loud. When Mary arrived, Elizabeth shouted out her blessing with a loud voice. The greeting burst out of her.","g":"cry out","h":"The picture: a voice raised in a shout."},"G4000":{"b":"Five times a thousand, five thousand. It is the crowd Jesus fed from five loaves and two fish, and all ate and were filled. A number that fixes one of his best-known miracles.","g":"five thousand","h":"The picture: the five thousand fed."},"G4001":{"b":"Simply five hundred. Paul reaches for the number as evidence: the risen Christ appeared to more than five hundred brothers at once, most still alive to be asked. In a parable it measures a debt too large to pay.","g":"five hundred","h":"The picture: five hundred witnesses."},"G4002":{"b":"This is the number five. Strong's calls it a primary number, which means it does not come from anything else. Abbott traces it no further. There is nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"five","h":"No picture."},"G4003":{"b":"This word stacks three pieces, five and tenth, to make fifteenth. Luke uses it to fix a date. It was the fifteenth year of Tiberius when the word of God came to John in the wilderness.","g":"fifteenth","h":"The picture: five and ten counted out."},"G4004":{"b":"The number fifty, built on five. When Jesus fed the crowd he had them sit in companies, by hundreds and by fifties on the green grass. A plain count for ordering a multitude.","g":"fifty","h":"The picture: seated in rows of fifty."},"G4005":{"b":"This word comes from the word for fifty. It means the fiftieth, the fiftieth day counted out from Passover. That is the feast that had come when the Spirit fell on the waiting disciples with fire and wind.","g":"Pentecost","h":"The picture: the fiftieth day counted out."},"G4006":{"b":"Strong's one word is reliance. Pepoithesis is the settled trust of a man who leans his full weight on something and finds it holds. Paul says he has this confidence toward God, and none at all in himself.","g":"confidence","h":"The picture: leaning your full weight on something."},"G4009":{"b":"The word means an end, a limit, a boundary. It comes from a word meaning across or beyond. The queen of the South came from the ends of the earth, the farthest edge. Picture the last boundary of the land, as far as you can go.","g":"end, uttermost part","h":"The picture: the far edge of the land."},"G401":{"b":"The root means to pour out. So this is an overflowing, a spilling of excess. Peter says the pagans are surprised the readers no longer run with them into the same flood of wild living.","g":"excess","h":"The picture: a flood poured out past the brim."},"G4010":{"b":"Strong's ties the name to the word for a tower or castle. Pergamum sat high on a fortified hill. So the name means the stronghold, the citadel. Picture a walled tower rising on a height.","g":"Pergamus","h":"The picture: a tower on a hill."},"G4011":{"b":"Strong's says this town's name means a tower, tied to a word for a fortified place. Perga was the city where John Mark left Paul and Barnabas and turned back home.","g":"Perga","h":"The picture: a tower."},"G4013":{"b":"Peri means around, and ago means to lead. Periago pictures leading someone about, or going round and round yourself. Jesus went through all the towns, walking a circuit village to village. Paul asks if he too may lead a wife around.","g":"go about","h":"The picture: walking a circuit of the towns."},"G4014":{"b":"Abbott-Smith notes the sea use, cast off the anchors. The word means to take away what surrounds. In Acts the sailors strip away the anchors ringing the ship. It is also stripping the veil off a face. Taking away, all the way around.","g":"take away, cast off","h":"The picture: cutting the anchors loose."},"G4015":{"b":"Built from \"around\" and a word meaning to flash as lightning. Picture a bolt going off on every side at once. That is what hit Saul on the Damascus road. A light from heaven flashed around him and he fell to the ground.","g":"shine around","h":"The picture: lightning flashing all around you."},"G4016":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives it as to throw around or over. The same word covers siege works thrown around a city and a robe thrown around a man.\n\nClothing here is wrapped on you, often by someone else.","g":"clothe, wrap around","h":"The picture: a cloak thrown round you."},"G4017":{"b":"This word is built from around and to look. It means to sweep your eyes over everyone about you. Jesus looked around at them all in anger and grief. He looked around at those seated in a circle and said, here are my mother and brothers.","g":"look around","h":"The picture: the eyes sweeping the circle."},"G4018":{"b":"This is built from a word meaning to throw around. It is the thing flung about you, a mantle or veil. Paul says a woman's long hair is given to her for such a covering, wrapped around like a cloak.","g":"covering, veil","h":"The picture: a cloak thrown around you."},"G4019":{"b":"This word joins around and to bind. It means to wrap something round and round. John uses it of the cloth tied about the dead man's face. The two small words tell you the action: binding, around.","g":"to bind around","h":"The picture: cloth wound round and round."},"G402":{"b":"The word means to go back, to withdraw. Abbott notes it is often used for avoiding danger. It is the quiet retreat. Joseph took the child and pulled back out of Herod's reach.","g":"withdraw, retire","h":"The picture: slipping away from danger."},"G4020":{"b":"This joins peri, around, and ergazomai, to work. So it is working all around a thing, busy with everything but your own job. Paul writes of some who do no work at all, but are busybodies in what is not theirs.","g":"be a busybody","h":"The picture: fussing all around a task."},"G4021":{"b":"Built from \"around\" and the word for work, it is working all around, fussing at what is not yours, the busybody. The same word names meddling with hidden things: magic. At Ephesus new believers burned their books of curious arts.","g":"busybody, magic","h":"The picture: hands busy all around other people's business."},"G4022":{"b":"This word is built from a word for around and a word for going. To go all the way around, to wander from place to place with no fixed spot. Wandering exorcists roamed like this, and idle widows drifting house to house.","g":"wander about","h":"The picture: wandering round from place to place."},"G4023":{"b":"The roots are \"around\" and \"to hold\". Together they mean to hold something on every side, to encircle it. Luke uses it for the astonishment that seized Peter and gripped him all round when he saw the great catch of fish.","g":"surround","h":"The picture: held all the way around."},"G4024":{"b":"The root means to bind about with a belt, and the front means all around. To cinch a belt round your waist and hitch your robe up for work. Jesus says keep your waist girded, ready. The master girds himself to serve his servants.","g":"gird about","h":"The picture: cinching a belt to work."},"G4025":{"b":"The root means to place around. So this is the putting-on of ornaments, gold hung around the neck and wrists. Peter says do not make that your beauty. The lasting beauty is the gentle spirit within.","g":"wearing","h":"The picture: gold hung around the neck and wrists."},"G4026":{"b":"The word is \"around\" plus \"to stand,\" so \"to stand all around.\" It pictures people standing in a ring, bystanders. Turned the other way it means to stand off, to keep clear. Paul tells Titus to stand well back from foolish arguments.","g":"stand around, shun","h":"The picture: people standing in a ring around."},"G4027":{"b":"This is built from around and to cleanse. Abbott gives it as refuse, rubbish. It pictures the dirt scraped off all around and swept out. Paul says the apostles were made the filth of the world, the sweepings.","g":"filth, refuse","h":"The picture: the sweepings scraped up."},"G4028":{"b":"The word means to cover all around. The soldiers use it when they cover Jesus' face and tell him to guess who struck him. It also names the gold laid over the ark, wrapped on every side. To wrap completely.","g":"cover, blindfold","h":"The picture: a cloth wrapped over the face."},"G4029":{"b":"Built from a word meaning around and one meaning to lie. Something lies all around you, wrapped close. A millstone hung about the neck. Paul's chain wrapped around him. It surrounds you and it weighs on you.","g":"encircle","h":"The picture: a millstone hung round the neck."},"G403":{"b":"Strong's says this word is a recovery of breath. It comes from a verb meaning to cool off, to get relief. Peter promises times of refreshing from the Lord, like cool air after heat, breath coming back to worn-out lungs.","g":"refreshing","h":"The picture: catching your breath in cool air."},"G4030":{"b":"This word joins around and head. It is a helmet, the metal cap that wraps the whole head. Paul calls salvation a helmet. The most vital part, guarded on every side. What covers the head is what keeps you alive in the fight.","g":"helmet","h":"The picture: a helmet around the head."},"G4031":{"b":"This is peri, around, plus kratos, strength or might. It means having full command, a strong hold on every side. With hard work the crew barely got control of the ship's boat, hauling it in. The word is a grip closed all the way around, mastering it.","g":"master, secure","h":"The picture: getting a firm grip all around a thing."},"G4032":{"b":"This word joins all around with a word meaning to conceal by covering. So it is to cover a thing on every side, to hide it fully. Elizabeth kept herself out of sight for five months, wrapping her news close before she let it show.","g":"hide","h":"The picture: covered up on every side."},"G4033":{"b":"Built from a word for around and a word meaning to encircle, to surround. Picture soldiers forming a full circle with no gap. Your enemies will surround you on every side, Jesus said of Jerusalem, and hem you in.","g":"compass round","h":"The picture: a ring drawn all around the city."},"G4034":{"b":"The root means to shine, to beam like a lamp, and \"around\" throws the light on every side. Luke uses it for the night the angel came to the shepherds and the glory of the Lord shone all around them, and they were terrified.","g":"shine around","h":"The picture: light blazing all around you."},"G4035":{"b":"This word joins around and to leave. It means to be left over, the ones still standing when the others are gone. Paul writes of those left alive at the Lord's coming. Not the fallen, but the remainder. Whoever is still here when it happens.","g":"remain, survive","h":"The picture: the ones left standing."},"G4036":{"b":"The word puts \"around\" onto \"sadness.\" It means grieved all around, hemmed in by sorrow with no gap. In Gethsemane Jesus says his soul is perilypos, sad to the point of death, grief pressing in from every direction.","g":"very sad","h":"The picture: grief closed in on every side."},"G4037":{"b":"This word joins around and to stay. It means to hang about waiting for something. Jesus told the disciples not to leave Jerusalem but to wait there for the promise. Stay in one place. Do not move until it arrives.","g":"to wait for","h":"The picture: staying put until it comes."},"G4038":{"b":"This word comes from the word for around. It means round about, on every side. Luke says crowds came from the cities round about Jerusalem, bringing the sick to be healed. The picture is a circle of towns hemming the city in.","g":"round about","h":"The picture: the ring of towns around a center."},"G4039":{"b":"This word joins around with a word meaning to live in a house. It is to dwell round about a place. After John was born and Zechariah spoke again, fear fell on all who lived nearby. The whole neighbourhood talked of it.","g":"dwell around","h":"The picture: living in the houses all around."},"G404":{"b":"This joins 'again' to a word meaning to breathe gently, to cool. It pictures cooling something down, like fanning cool air onto a hot face. Paul says Onesiphorus often refreshed him. He brought cool relief to a man in chains.","g":"refresh","h":"The picture: a cool breath of air."},"G4040":{"b":"This word joins around with the word for a dwelling. Your neighbours are the ones whose houses stand around yours. When Elizabeth bore her son, all these nearby households heard of it and came to rejoice with her.","g":"neighbour","h":"The picture: the houses standing round about."},"G4041":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to be over and above. It came to mean one's own special possession, the thing set aside and kept back as yours. Paul says Christ makes for himself a people of his own, treasured and marked out as his.","g":"peculiar","h":"The picture: kept aside as your own."},"G4042":{"b":"The root means to hold all around, to clasp. So the word is a passage of scripture, a portion marked off from the rest. The eunuch reads the very piece about the lamb led to slaughter.","g":"passage, section","h":"The picture: a section fenced off with a circle."},"G4043":{"b":"Strong's says it means to tread all around, to walk at large. Not one trip from door to door. Going about.\n\nPaul uses it for how you live. Your daily walking is your life.","g":"walk around","h":"The picture: walking all around a place."},"G4044":{"b":"The root means to put on a spit, to run a skewer clean through. So it is to pierce all the way. Paul says those greedy for money pierce themselves through with many sorrows, driving the blade in by their own hand.","g":"pierce through","h":"The picture: run through on a spit."},"G4045":{"b":"The word joins around and fall. It means to fall in with, to land in the middle of. The traveler to Jericho falls among robbers who surround and strip him. James says count it joy when you fall into trials. Caught on every side.","g":"fall among","h":"The picture: falling into a ring of robbers."},"G4046":{"b":"The word means to make around oneself, to acquire and hold. Whoever tries to secure his own life will lose it, Jesus warns. Paul says God purchased the church with his own blood. Drawing a thing in and closing your hands around it.","g":"acquire, purchase","h":"The picture: gathering something around yourself to keep."},"G4047":{"b":"The root means to make around oneself, to acquire, to buy. Peripoiesis is the taking and keeping of a thing as yours. Peter calls believers a people for God's own possession, gathered in and held, bought to be kept.","g":"possession","h":"The picture: gathered in and kept as your own."},"G4048":{"b":"This joins around and break. It means to break or tear off all around, and it was used of garments. Cloth ripped away from every side. The magistrates tore the clothes off Paul and Silas before beating them.","g":"tear off","h":"The picture: clothes ripped off."},"G4049":{"b":"This word joins around and to draw. Abbott-Smith reads it as to draw around, draw off or away. Martha was pulled apart by all her serving, hands full and mind scattered, while Mary simply sat and listened.","g":"cumber, distract","h":"The picture: pulled this way and that until you fray."},"G405":{"b":"Aner is a man, pous is a foot, and the word behind it meant a slave taken in war. So it is the slave-dealer who seizes people and sells them as property. Paul condemns such kidnappers by name.","g":"slave-dealer","h":"The picture: a man dragged off by the feet."},"G4050":{"b":"Strong's calls this superabundance. The root means to be in excess, to overflow. It pictures a measure so full that the extra spills over the side. That is the grace Paul says reigns in life, poured out past the brim.","g":"abundance","h":"The picture: more than the cup can hold."},"G4051":{"b":"This is the overflow, what is left when the measure is already full and more keeps coming. Out of the perisseuma of the heart the mouth speaks, Jesus says. Whatever fills you to the brim spills out in your words.","g":"abundance","h":"The picture: a cup running over."},"G4052":{"b":"The old translators reached for phrases like enough and to spare, and over and above. Abbott's sense is being past the number that was needed.\n\nNot merely full. Spilling.","g":"abound, overflow","h":"The picture: enough and to spare."},"G4053":{"b":"Perissos is built from peri in the sense of beyond. It pictures a measure filled past its edge, more than enough and still more. I came that they may have life, and have it to the full, over the brim. Not just full but spilling.","g":"abundant","h":"The picture: a cup filled past the brim."},"G4055":{"b":"The root means superabundant, more than the measure holds. Perissoteros is the comparative, even more than that. It is the extra that spills past the brim, the abundance beyond need. Grace poured out not by drops but overflowing.","g":"more abundant","h":"The picture: spilling past the brim."},"G4056":{"b":"The root is the overflowing more, past the brim. Perissoterōs is its adverb, all the more, more abundantly still. Paul labored more abundantly than them all, was in prisons more abundantly. Where others give a measure, this word keeps on pouring.","g":"more abundantly","h":"The picture: the measure that keeps pouring."},"G4057":{"b":"The root means over and above, past what the measure holds. Perissos is \"more than ever,\" beyond bounds. Crucify him, they shouted all the perissos, louder and louder. Paul labored perissos, harder than the rest. Always spilling past the line.","g":"exceedingly","h":"The picture: past what the measure holds."},"G4058":{"b":"This word means a dove or pigeon. Strong's says it is of uncertain derivation, so no one knows where it came from. It simply names the bird. There is no picture behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"dove","h":"No picture."},"G4059":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the word means to cut around. From that plain, physical action it came to mean circumcise. The picture is simply the blade going around. Later it is used for cutting away the heart's hardness.","g":"circumcise","h":"The picture: cutting around."},"G406":{"b":"This is Andrew, Peter's brother and one of the twelve. Strong's says the name means \"manly,\" from the word for a man. The name itself carries that meaning.","g":"Andrew","h":"The picture: the manly one."},"G4060":{"b":"Abbott: \"to place or put around.\" It joins \"around\" with \"put.\" It is setting a thing round about, a fence around a vineyard, a robe put on, a crown pressed around the head.","g":"put around","h":"The picture: setting something all around."},"G4061":{"b":"Abbott lists three uses. The rite itself, the state of being circumcised, and then whole groups of people called simply the circumcised.\n\nA mark on the body became the name of a nation.","g":"circumcision","h":"The picture: a mark that names a whole people."},"G4062":{"b":"This is peri, around, plus a word for a turn. Festus shouts that Paul's great learning is turning him around into madness. The image is a mind wheeled full circle, spun off its base. The word is that turning, the twist from sense to raving.","g":"drive mad","h":"The picture: the mind spun right around."},"G4063":{"b":"The pieces mean around and to run. It is running every which way over a whole area. In Mark 6:55 the people run all around that region, carrying the sick on their mats to wherever they hear Jesus is.","g":"run about","h":"The picture: running all around the district."},"G4064":{"b":"The roots mean around and to carry. So it is carrying something here and there. When word spread that Jesus had come, people carried the sick about on their mats, hurrying them wherever they heard he was.","g":"carry about","h":"The picture: carrying the sick from place to place."},"G4065":{"b":"This joins 'around, beyond' to a word meaning to think or hold an opinion. To despise is to set your thoughts beyond a person, as if thinking right over their head. Paul tells Titus to let no one do this. Rank him too low to notice.","g":"despise","h":"The picture: thinking right past someone."},"G4066":{"b":"Built from around and land. It means the region round about, the countryside that circles a town. Word about Jesus spread through all the land around the Jordan.","g":"surrounding region","h":"The picture: the land that rings a town."},"G4067":{"b":"This joins around with a word meaning to rub or wipe. Abbott gives it as that which is wiped off, offscouring. It is the grime you wipe from a dish and throw out. Paul says the apostles became this, the world's scrapings.","g":"offscouring","h":"The picture: the grime wiped off a dish."},"G4068":{"b":"Abbott traces this to a word meaning vainglorious. It means to boast, to vaunt oneself. It names a puffed-up manner, not a thing you can picture. Paul says love does not do this, it does not brag.","flat":1,"g":"vaunt itself","h":"No picture."},"G4069":{"b":"Her name simply means a Persian woman. It likely marked where she or her family came from, the far eastern land of Persia. Paul calls her the beloved Persis, who laboured much in the Lord.","g":"Persis","h":"The picture: a woman from Persia."},"G407":{"b":"The root is the word for a man. Abbott-Smith says to make a man of, to play the man. Paul stacks it with watch and stand firm. Face it like a man, do not shrink back.","g":"act manly","h":"The picture: a boy squaring up as a grown man."},"G4070":{"b":"The word means last year, a year ago, and it grows from a root meaning an end or extremity. Paul reminds the Corinthians they began their collection a year ago. It points back over a finished stretch of time and says, finish it.","g":"last year","h":"The picture: the year already ended."},"G4071":{"b":"Strong's says the word means a flying animal, a bird. The Greeks named the bird by what it does. It flies. \"Look at the birds of the air, they do not sow.\"","g":"bird","h":"The picture: the flying one."},"G4072":{"b":"The word simply means to fly. Strong's calls it a primary verb, nothing behind it. Revelation shows an eagle flying in mid-heaven and an angel flying with good news. The picture is plain, wings beating, a body lifted off the ground.","g":"fly","h":"The picture: a bird on the wing."},"G4073":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this is a mass of live rock, as distinct from a detached stone or boulder. Not a rock you can pick up. The immovable ledge underneath. Build your house on this, and the flood cannot move it.","g":"rock","h":"The picture: solid bedrock, not a loose stone."},"G4074":{"b":"Strong's says the name means a piece of rock, and notes it is larger than another word for stone. Abbott-Smith says plainly, a stone.\n\nSo the name Jesus gave Simon was not a compliment about character. It was a rock.","g":"Peter","h":"The picture: a stone you could pick up."},"G4075":{"b":"The word is rock plus form, rock-like. Abbott-Smith explains it as shallow soil with rock underneath. In the parable seed falls here and springs up fast, but the roots hit stone and cannot go deep, so the sun burns it away.","g":"stony, rocky","h":"The picture: thin soil over hard rock."},"G4076":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives one word: rue, a small garden herb. Jesus scolds the Pharisees for measuring out a careful tithe of even their mint and rue while stepping right over justice and the love of God.","g":"rue","h":"The picture: a sprig of the garden herb rue."},"G4077":{"b":"Strong's ties this word to the idea of gushing plumply, water welling up from its source. Abbott-Smith gives no origin. Jesus speaks of a spring inside a person, water rising up to eternal life.","g":"spring, fountain","h":"The picture: water gushing up from the ground."},"G4078":{"b":"This means to make fast, to fix. It is the word used for pitching a tent, driving the pegs into the ground. The true tent was set up by the Lord himself, not raised by human hands.","g":"pitch a tent","h":"The picture: driving in the tent pegs."},"G4079":{"b":"This is the rudder, and the word comes from the blade of an oar. A rudder is a broad blade dragged in the water to steer a ship. The crew had tied theirs up in the storm and now loosed them to run for the beach.","g":"rudder","h":"The picture: the steering blade in the water."},"G408":{"b":"His name joins two words, man and conquest. It means man of victory. Paul calls Andronicus his kinsman and fellow prisoner, in Christ before Paul himself was. His name carries a conqueror inside it.","g":"Andronicus","h":"The picture: a man standing in victory."},"G4081":{"b":"This is clay, the wet mud a potter works. Paul asks if the clay can argue with the potter who shapes it. Jesus spat on the ground, made clay, and smeared it on the blind man's eyes. Soft earth in a maker's hands.","g":"clay","h":"The picture: wet clay in the potter's hands."},"G4082":{"b":"A pera is a leather pouch for food, a traveler's bag slung over the shoulder. Jesus sent them out with no pera, no bread bag for the road. They were to lean on others, carrying no packed provisions of their own.","g":"bag, scrip","h":"The picture: a leather food-bag."},"G4083":{"b":"The word first means the forearm. Because it was used to measure, it became a cubit, a set length. Jesus asks who can add a single cubit to his life by worrying. The picture is the arm laid out as a measuring stick.","g":"cubit","h":"The picture: the forearm used as a ruler."},"G4084":{"b":"Strong's says it means \"to squeeze,\" then to seize by the hand, to arrest, or to catch in hunting. Abbott-Smith says \"to lay hold of.\" It is the firm grab that does not let go. They tried to seize Jesus but could not.","g":"seize, arrest","h":"The picture: grabbing hold."},"G4085":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives this as to press, press down or together. Think of a seller pushing grain down hard in the cup so more will fit. That is the full measure Jesus says will be poured back into your lap.","g":"press down","h":"The picture: grain pressed down to pack the measure full."},"G4086":{"b":"Built from a word for persuasive and the word for speech. It means smooth, plausible talk, arguments that sound right but are not proof. Paul warns that no one delude them with such persuasive words.","g":"enticing words","h":"The picture: a smooth tongue talking you into it."},"G4087":{"b":"The root means sharp and acrid, bitter to taste. This word is to make bitter. In Revelation the little scroll turns the stomach bitter. Paul tells husbands not to be bitter against their wives, sharp and souring toward them.","g":"to embitter","h":"The picture: a bitter taste on the tongue."},"G4088":{"b":"The root means sharp and acrid, \"acridity (especially poison).\" First it is a taste, the bitterness that makes you wince. Then it turns to temper, a soured heart. Peter tells Simon he is in the gall of bitterness, poisoned inside.","g":"bitterness","h":"The picture: a bitter taste in the mouth."},"G4089":{"b":"The first sense is sharp, pointed. Then sharp to the tongue, and so bitter to taste. So bitterness here is a sharp thing, something that pricks. James uses it of bitter envy in the heart.","g":"bitter","h":"The picture: a sharp point."},"G409":{"b":"This joins aner, a man, and phonos, murder. So it is a man-slayer, one who sheds another's blood. Paul lists him among the lawless and disobedient, those the law was made to name and restrain.","g":"murderer","h":"The picture: the man who kills a man."},"G4090":{"b":"The root means sharp and acrid, the taste that stings the tongue. As an adverb pikros is bitterly. When the cock crows and Peter remembers, he goes out and weeps bitterly, tears with that sharp sting in them.","g":"bitterly","h":"The picture: a taste sharp and bitter on the tongue."},"G4091":{"b":"A Roman personal name. Strong's says the Latin means close-pressed, that is firm. Abbott-Smith says nothing about the meaning at all and simply identifies the man. A man's name is not a word picture.","flat":1,"g":"Pilate","h":"No picture."},"G4092":{"b":"The old sense is \"to blow, burn.\" Later it meant to swell up, as a body burns with fever. Abbott points to the body becoming swollen. The islanders watched Paul, waiting for the snakebite to make him swell and drop.","g":"swell, burn","h":"The picture: the body swelling with fever heat."},"G4093":{"b":"This is the little form of a word for a plate or board. A pinakidion is a small tablet for writing on. Zechariah asked for one and wrote on it, His name is John. At once his tongue was freed.","g":"writing tablet","h":"The picture: a small wooden writing board."},"G4094":{"b":"This began as a flat board or plank, then any flat wooden thing, and so a serving plate. They carried John the Baptist's head in on a pinax. A flat dish brought to the table.","g":"platter","h":"The picture: a flat serving dish."},"G4095":{"b":"The word means to drink. Abbott notes an old use that stretches it. The earth absorbing rain, in Hebrews 6:7.\n\nSoil drinks. That is the same word Jesus uses of the cup.","g":"drink","h":"The picture: ground drinking the rain."},"G4096":{"b":"Strong's says plumpness, richness, oiliness. So this is fatness, the rich sap that feeds a tree. Abbott says fatness. Paul says the wild branch grafted in shares the root and the fatness of the good olive tree.","g":"fatness","h":"The picture: the rich oily sap of the olive root."},"G4097":{"b":"Strong's ties this to travel, to traffic by travelling. It pictures a trader carrying goods to market to sell. It is also used of selling a person into slavery. Paul says he is sold under sin.","g":"sell","h":"The picture: the traveling trader."},"G4098":{"b":"Abbott starts with descent. Falling down or falling from. Seed falls by the road. Stars fall from the sky.\n\nHis second heading is prostration. The same word for people going down on their faces.","g":"fall","h":"The picture: dropping to the ground."},"G4099":{"b":"This is the name of a region of Asia Minor that Paul travelled through. It is likely a foreign word. So there is no meaning behind it to picture, only a place with a name.","flat":1,"g":"Pisidia","h":"No picture."},"G41":{"b":"The root means sacred, set apart, consecrated. This is holiness itself, the quality of belonging wholly to God. Hebrews says God disciplines us so we may share his holiness. Not our achievement but his own nature, handed to the children he trains.","g":"holiness","h":"The picture: set apart for God."},"G410":{"b":"The root means to call in a debt, to bring someone to account. Put not in front and no account can be called against you. Paul wants leaders like this. Not sinless in theory, but with no open charge anyone can bring.","g":"blameless","h":"The picture: no charge that can be called in."},"G4100":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives this verb a second sense: to entrust. The same word covers being entrusted with a job or a message.\n\nSo believing is not only agreeing. It is putting something down in someone else's hands and leaving it there.","g":"believe, trust","h":"The picture: handing something over for safekeeping."},"G4101":{"b":"The root is the word for trust. Strong's says this means genuine, unadulterated, the real thing. It describes Mary's jar of nard, pure and undiluted. Trustworthy perfume, poured out whole over Jesus, not a cheap mix.","g":"genuine, pure","h":"The picture: perfume you can trust, not watered down."},"G4102":{"b":"Abbott-Smith builds this word on the verb to persuade. Strong's starts it at persuasion.\n\nSo faith is not a leap taken with eyes shut. It is what is left standing after you have been won over.","g":"faith, trust","h":"The picture: a mind that has been convinced."},"G4103":{"b":"This grows from peitho, to persuade or win over. A pistos person is one who has won your trust, someone you can be sure of and lean your weight on. So the faithful servant is not just busy. He is reliable, the kind you would stake something on.","g":"faithful","h":"The picture: someone you can lean your weight on."},"G4104":{"b":"Abbott's sense is to make trustworthy, to make firm. It comes from the word for faithful and sure. So Paul tells Timothy to hold to what he has learned and been made sure of, truth set solid enough to stand on.","g":"assure","h":"The picture: made solid enough to stand on."},"G4105":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is to cause to wander, lead astray. Strong's says to roam from safety.\n\nDeceiving someone is walking them off the road. Abbott points to Matthew 18 for the plain sense of going astray.","g":"lead astray, deceive","h":"The picture: off the path."},"G4106":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it first means a wandering. Then a going astray, an error. To be deceived is to be led off the road and left roaming, thinking you are headed home while you drift further away.","g":"error, delusion","h":"The picture: wandering off the path."},"G4107":{"b":"The root means roving, like a tramp. This is a wanderer, and Jude uses it of wandering stars, drifting with no path. He says the blackness of darkness is kept for them forever.","g":"wandering","h":"The picture: a star wandering off its course."},"G4108":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is just wandering. A planos roves with no fixed path. As a person it is one who makes others wander too, off the road and lost. That is why they called Jesus a deceiver, a man leading the people astray.","g":"deceiver","h":"The picture: a wanderer who leads you off the road."},"G4109":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is anything flat and broad, later a flat stone, a tablet. This is the word for the tablets of stone the law was cut into. Paul says his letter is written on tablets of human hearts, not stone.","g":"tablet","h":"The picture: a flat stone tablet."},"G411":{"b":"The root means to narrate all the way through, and the not in front blocks it. Strong's says not expounded in full. Paul calls God's gift that, indescribable, past any words to finish.","g":"unspeakable","h":"The picture: a story so big you can never tell it to the end."},"G4110":{"b":"The root means to mould, to shape by hand, like clay. So this is the thing moulded, what is formed. Abbott says that which is moulded or formed. Paul asks whether the thing formed can say to its maker, why did you make me thus.","g":"thing formed","h":"The picture: a clay pot shaped by the potter's hands."},"G4111":{"b":"This means to mould, to shape with the hands, the way a potter works wet clay. Paul asks whether the thing formed can argue with the one who formed it. The potter holds the right over the lump. Hands pressing clay into shape.","g":"mould, form","h":"The picture: a potter shaping clay."},"G4112":{"b":"The root means to mould, to shape like clay. So this is something formed, then made-up, feigned. Peter says false teachers will exploit you with moulded words, stories shaped to fit their greed.","g":"feigned","h":"The picture: a shape moulded by hand from clay."},"G4113":{"b":"From platys, broad, spread out flat. A plateia is the wide street, the open square of a town. They love to pray standing on the plateia to be seen by everyone. The wide flat road where the whole crowd passes through.","g":"street","h":"The picture: the wide open street."},"G4114":{"b":"The root means spread out flat, broad. This word is the width of a thing, how far it reaches side to side. Paul prays the Ephesians would grasp the breadth of Christ's love, how wide it opens out.","g":"breadth","h":"The picture: spread out wide and flat."},"G4115":{"b":"The root means broad, spread out flat. This verb is to make wide. Jesus says the Pharisees make broad their phylacteries, the little prayer boxes, so people will notice. They widen them for show.","g":"widen","h":"The picture: spreading something out wide."},"G4116":{"b":"The word means spread out flat, broad. Jesus says wide is the gate and broad the road that leads to destruction. Picture an easy open highway, plenty of room, many walking it. The narrow way is harder to find.","g":"wide, broad","h":"The picture: the wide flat road."},"G4117":{"b":"The root pleko means to twine or braid. A plegma is something woven together, here the braids of hair. Paul says women should adorn themselves not with braided hair and gold, but with good works.","g":"braided hair","h":"The picture: braided hair."},"G4119":{"b":"This is the comparative of polys, much or many. Pleion means more, a greater quantity, the larger part. So the widow put in pleion than all the rich, more, though her two coins were less. The word weighs the heap and finds hers the greater.","g":"more","h":"The picture: the bigger heap, the greater number."},"G412":{"b":"This is built from a word meaning to speak out, with a not in front. So it names a thing that cannot be spoken out. Peter points to a joy too big to get into words, joy unspeakable and full of glory.","g":"unspeakable","h":"The picture: joy too big for words."},"G4120":{"b":"This means to twist and braid, to weave strands together. The soldiers plaited a crown out of thorn branches and pressed it on Jesus' head. The word is fingers twisting the sharp twigs into a ring to mock a king.","g":"plait","h":"The picture: twisting strands into a braid."},"G4121":{"b":"Abbott ties it to πλέον, the word for \"more.\" Strong's says it means to increase and to superabound. The picture is a heap that keeps growing past full, spilling over into more and more.","g":"abound, increase","h":"The picture: the pile grows past full."},"G4122":{"b":"The root means holding or desiring more. Abbott-Smith's first sense is to have more, to have the advantage. It hardens into overreaching, defrauding. Picture a hand reaching past its own portion into someone else's. Paul says he never did this to them.","g":"defraud, overreach","h":"The picture: reaching over to grab more than your share."},"G4123":{"b":"The two roots are \"more\" and \"to hold.\" This word is one who wants to hold more, and more again. It is greed that never closes its hand. Paul lists it among the sins that shut a person out of the kingdom.","g":"greedy person","h":"The picture: the hand that always grabs for more."},"G4124":{"b":"Abbott-Smith unpacks this as a desire for advantage, grasping and pushing to get the bigger share. So it is not just liking money. It is the reaching hand that always wants more than its part.","g":"greed, covetousness","h":"The picture: always grabbing for more."},"G4125":{"b":"This word means a rib, and so the side of the body where the ribs are. A soldier pierced Jesus' side with a spear, and at once blood and water came out. The angel struck Peter on the side to wake him.","g":"side, rib","h":"The picture: the ribs, the side of the body."},"G4126":{"b":"Strong's links this to plunging through the water. It means to sail, to travel by ship. They were sailing when the storm hit and Jesus slept. Paul crosses the sea in it toward Rome. A boat cutting through the waves.","g":"sail","h":"The picture: a boat plunging through waves."},"G4127":{"b":"Abbott-Smith starts with a blow, a stripe, a wound. Paul uses it for beatings he took.\n\nRevelation uses the same word for the plagues. A disaster is pictured as a strike that lands on the world.","g":"blow, wound","h":"The picture: the mark a blow leaves."},"G4128":{"b":"Strong's calls it a fulness, and from that, a large number, throng, populace.\n\nAbbott uses it for a great number of things as well as of people. A crowd in this word is a container that is full.","g":"crowd, multitude","h":"The picture: filled to the brim."},"G4129":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this comes from a word meaning \"to be full.\" So to multiply is to make a thing full, to swell its numbers. God tells them to increase and multiply, and the early church grew.","g":"multiply, increase","h":"The picture: filling up in number."},"G413":{"b":"This word joins not and to fail or run out. Abbott-Smith gives it as unfailing. Jesus tells them to store up treasure in heaven, a supply that never gives out, where no thief comes near and no moth eats it away.","g":"that faileth not","h":"The picture: a purse that never runs empty."},"G4130":{"b":"Abbott-Smith describes this as what fills or takes possession of the mind. Not topped up. Taken over.\n\nLuke uses the same word for being filled with the Spirit and for being filled with rage.","g":"fill","h":"The picture: filled until it takes over."},"G4131":{"b":"The root means to pound, to strike a blow. A plektes is a striker, the man quick to throw a punch and start a brawl. Paul bars him from leadership. Not the one whose first answer is his fists.","g":"striker, brawler","h":"The picture: the man quick with his fists."},"G4132":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives this as a flood of sea or river. It is water risen high and driving hard against whatever stands in it. When the flood struck the house built on rock, it held. The house on sand collapsed.","g":"flood","h":"The picture: a river swollen and bursting its banks."},"G4134":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is full, filled, a vessel with no empty space left. Stephen was plērēs of the Spirit, filled to the brim. John says Jesus came full of grace and truth, no room in him for anything less.","g":"full","h":"The picture: a vessel filled to the brim."},"G4135":{"b":"This is built from full and to carry. To bring a thing all the way full, filled to the brim. Paul was fully convinced God could do what he promised, with no half measure. To carry out a task filled up and complete, nothing left short.","g":"fully assure, accomplish","h":"The picture: carried full to the brim."},"G4136":{"b":"The root means to carry out fully, to completely assure. The \"full\" is right in the word. This is confidence filled up to the top, with nothing lacking. Paul wants believers full like that, in hope and in understanding.","g":"full assurance","h":"The picture: filled to the brim."},"G4137":{"b":"Strong's gives both images. To cram a net. To level up a hollow.\n\nAbbott points to the same two verses. The net full of fish, and the valleys filled before the Lord comes. Then prophecy filled up too.","g":"fill, fulfil","h":"The picture: a net crammed full, a valley filled in."},"G4138":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the word was used of a ship's crew or cargo, and even of the loaded ship itself. It means the full complement. Everything that fills a thing to the brim. Also used for basketfuls of bread.","g":"fullness","h":"The picture: a ship with full crew and cargo."},"G4139":{"b":"Abbott-Smith traces it to a word meaning near. The neighbor is simply the person close by. Not a category. Not far away. The one right next to you. Love that one as yourself.","g":"neighbor","h":"The picture: the one standing near."},"G414":{"b":"The root means to hold oneself up against something, to bear it. Anektoteros is \"more bearable.\" It will be more bearable for Sodom on that day than for the town that heard and shrugged. A lighter load to carry.","g":"more tolerable","h":"The picture: a lighter load to carry."},"G4140":{"b":"The root means to fill. This is a filling up, satiety, being stuffed full. Paul says harsh rules against the body do nothing to check the full satisfaction of the flesh. The appetite finds its fill anyway.","g":"indulgence","h":"The picture: the belly filled to the brim."},"G4141":{"b":"The word means \"to strike, smite.\" Strong's links it to a word for flattening out. Picture a blow landing hard enough to flatten what it hits. So a third of the sun and moon were struck, and their light went dark.","g":"to strike","h":"The picture: a heavy blow striking down."},"G4142":{"b":"This is the small version of the word for ship. The ending shrinks it to a little boat. Jesus asked for a small boat kept ready so the pressing crowd would not crush him. A dinghy, not a great vessel.","g":"little boat","h":"The picture: a little boat."},"G4143":{"b":"Strong's calls it a sailer. Abbott traces it to the verb for sailing.\n\nSo the name of the boat is just what it does. It sails. Most of the Gospels' boats are small fishing craft.","g":"boat, ship","h":"The picture: the thing that sails."},"G4144":{"b":"This word comes from the word to sail, to pass in a vessel. Ploos is the voyage, the whole passage across the sea. Paul warned that the voyage ahead would end in loss, the sailing dangerous now the fast was past.","g":"voyage","h":"The picture: the sea voyage from port to port."},"G4145":{"b":"From ploutos, wealth, fulness. Plousios is the rich man, barns full, purse heavy, hands overflowing. So it is hard for a plousios to enter the kingdom, harder than a camel through a needle's eye. The word is a man weighed down with having.","g":"rich","h":"The picture: full barns and a heavy purse."},"G4146":{"b":"The root is the word for wealthy, rich. This adverb means richly, the way a rich man gives, without counting. God's Spirit is poured out on us richly, and he gives us all things richly to enjoy.","g":"richly","h":"The picture: a rich man's open hand."},"G4147":{"b":"The root is wealth. Ploutéō is to be rich, to become rich, barns and coffers filling up. Laodicea boasts, I am rich, and does not know it is poor. Paul flips it, Christ grew poor so that by his poverty we might become truly rich.","g":"to be rich","h":"The picture: barns and coffers filling up."},"G4148":{"b":"The root ploutos means wealth as fulness, money and possessions heaped up. To ploutizo is to make someone rich, to fill them full. Paul says God made you rich in everything, and that having nothing he yet made many rich.","g":"make rich","h":"The picture: heaped with wealth."},"G4149":{"b":"Strong's explains the word as wealth in the sense of fulness. Not a pile counted out, but a container filled up.\n\nAbbott-Smith says it is used of outside possessions and also of moral and spiritual things.","g":"riches","h":"The picture: full to the brim."},"G415":{"b":"This is the word for compassionate with a not fixed on the front. So it means without mercy. It names a heart that feels nothing at another's pain and holds back the pity it could give. Paul lists it among a darkened mind's marks.","g":"merciless","h":"The picture: a hand that gives no pity."},"G4150":{"b":"This word is for washing things, especially clothing. Strong's pictures a plunge, cloth dunked and worked in the water. The fishermen are washing their nets when Jesus calls them. In Revelation the saints wash their robes white.","g":"wash","h":"The picture: scrubbing clothes in the water."},"G4151":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is air in motion. Wind, and breath.\n\nStrong's says the same: a current of air, a breath, a breeze. Everything else the word carries grows out of that. You cannot see it, but you can feel it move.","g":"spirit, breath, wind","h":"The picture: moving air."},"G4152":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is of or caused by the wind, air or breath. The word is built on the word for spirit, which is also the word for breath.\n\nSpiritual means driven by that breath.","g":"spiritual","h":"The picture: moved by breath."},"G4153":{"b":"This is the adverb, spiritually. Its root idea is non-carnal and ethereal, belonging to air as opposed to what is gross and solid. To weigh things spiritually is to weigh them by the Spirit. The natural mind cannot.","g":"spiritually","h":"The picture: airy, not solid."},"G4154":{"b":"This word means to breathe or blow, used of the wind. The wind blows where it wishes. The winds beat on the house in the parable. It is the moving air you feel but cannot see. This is the word that stands close beside spirit.","g":"blow, breathe","h":"The picture: the wind on your face."},"G4155":{"b":"The root means to breathe hard. This word is when the breath is cut off, to choke or throttle. The forgiven servant grabbed his fellow by the throat. The thorns choke the young plant. The word is air stopped.","g":"choke","h":"The picture: hands closing on a throat."},"G4156":{"b":"This word comes from a word meaning to choke or throttle. Pniktos is meat from an animal choked to death and not bled. The council told the Gentile believers to keep clear of what is strangled.","g":"strangled","h":"The picture: an animal choked, throat shut."},"G4157":{"b":"The root means to breathe hard, to blow. Abbott says \"a blowing, blast, wind.\" At Pentecost the Spirit comes with the sound of a rushing wind filling the house. The same word means the breath God gives to every living thing.","g":"breath, wind","h":"The picture: a rush of wind, a hard breath."},"G4158":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says \"reaching to the feet.\" The word is built on the word for foot. Picture a long robe hanging past the ankles, the kind a priest wears. So John sees Christ among the lampstands dressed in that full-length robe.","g":"ankle-length robe","h":"The picture: a robe that falls to the feet."},"G4159":{"b":"Pothen asks whence, from what place or source. Abbott lays out its uses, of place, of origin, of parentage, of cause. So whence has this man this wisdom, pothen, is the town asking where it all came from, unable to trace the carpenter's son to any school.","g":"whence","h":"The picture: tracing a thing back to where it came from."},"G416":{"b":"The root is the plain word for wind. This is what wind does to a thing that cannot hold its place. James says the doubter is like a sea wave, blown wherever the wind shoves it.","g":"driven with wind","h":"The picture: wind driving a thing that cannot hold still."},"G4160":{"b":"Strong's says it is apparently stretched out from an obsolete primary word. That word is lost, so there is nothing to see. Abbott-Smith just lists the two senses, to make and to do.","flat":1,"g":"do, make","h":"No picture."},"G4161":{"b":"This is a thing that has been made, a piece of work, from the word to make. The made world points back to its Maker. And Paul says believers are God's workmanship, an object shaped and finished by his own hands.","g":"workmanship","h":"The picture: a crafted, handmade thing."},"G4163":{"b":"The root is to make or do. This is a maker. In Greek it meant a poet, one who makes with words, and Paul quotes their poets. In James it means a doer of the word, not just a hearer. One who actually makes it happen.","g":"doer, poet","h":"The picture: a maker."},"G4164":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it first meant many-coloured, variegated, like a patterned cloth. From there it came to mean varied or manifold. Troubles of many kinds are troubles of many colors, all mixed together.","g":"various, manifold","h":"The picture: many colors."},"G4165":{"b":"Abbott-Smith traces this to the word for a shepherd. It means to act as a shepherd, to tend the flock, to lead and feed and guard. Jesus tells Peter to shepherd his sheep.","g":"shepherd, tend","h":"The picture: tending the flock."},"G4166":{"b":"Strong's says the roots are of uncertain affinity, so there is no story behind the word. But the word itself is already a picture.\n\nAbbott-Smith lists it used of Christ, then of church leaders. Our word pastor comes from it.","g":"shepherd","h":"The picture: a man with sheep."},"G4167":{"b":"The root is the shepherd's work of tending, and poimne is his flock, the sheep gathered under him. Strike the shepherd and the poimne scatters, Jesus says. There will be one poimne, one shepherd. Sheep known and led by one man.","g":"flock","h":"The picture: a flock of sheep."},"G4168":{"b":"The root is a flock of sheep. This is the little flock, the sheep kept together under one keeper. Fear not, little flock, Jesus says. The church is watched over the same way, like sheep in a fold.","g":"flock","h":"The picture: sheep gathered under one shepherd."},"G417":{"b":"Abbott notes the four winds of the earth came to mean the four quarters of the heavens. Wind turned into direction.\n\nHe adds one figure of speech, wind used for teaching that keeps shifting.","g":"wind","h":"The picture: the four winds as a compass."},"G4170":{"b":"From polemos, war. To polemeo is to wage it, to fight. Michael and his angels fought the dragon. James asks where your quarrels come from and gives them this battlefield word. Actual war, swords out, in the field.","g":"make war","h":"The picture: swords out on the field."},"G4171":{"b":"Strong's gives it as warfare, either a single encounter or a whole series. Abbott-Smith gives war, and then battle.\n\nStrong's traces it to a word meaning to bustle, but that is all. No picture worth the name.","flat":1,"g":"war, battle","h":"No picture."},"G4172":{"b":"Strong's says a town, properly one with walls, of greater or less size.\n\nAbbott-Smith sets it against villages and open country. What makes it a city is not how many live there. It is the wall around it.","g":"city, town","h":"The picture: a town inside its walls."},"G4173":{"b":"Built from the word for a town, properly one with walls, and a word meaning to be first in power. A politarches is the town's chief ruler. The mob at Thessalonica dragged Jason before these city rulers, a title since found on real inscriptions there.","g":"city ruler","h":"The picture: the chief man over a walled town."},"G4174":{"b":"This is built from the word for a townsman, one who belongs to a city. Citizenship is having your name written on the roll of a town. Paul's rights came from being a citizen, a full member of the city with a claim on it.","g":"citizenship","h":"The picture: a name on the city roll."},"G4175":{"b":"This comes from the life of a citizen in a city. It means citizenship, or the commonwealth you belong to. Paul says our citizenship is in heaven, our real city is there, and from it we wait for a Savior.","g":"citizenship","h":"The picture: your name on another city's roll."},"G4176":{"b":"Same root as citizenship, the word for a townsman. This one is the verb, to live as a citizen day by day. Paul tells believers to live as citizens of heaven, to carry themselves as people who belong there.","g":"live as citizen","h":"The picture: a townsman in his city."},"G4177":{"b":"A polites is built from polis, \"a town (properly, with walls.\" The picture is the wall around a city. A citizen is not a visitor passing through. He lives inside the walls, and the town belongs to him.","g":"citizen","h":"The picture: the walled town you belong to."},"G4178":{"b":"This is built from polys, many, made into a word of frequency. Pollakis means many times, often, the same thing happening over and over. So the demon pollakis threw the boy into fire and water, again and again, and often Paul longed to come to Rome.","g":"often","h":"The picture: again and again, many times over."},"G4179":{"b":"Strong's builds it from a word for much and a word for braiding or folding. Manifold means many folds. Picture cloth doubled again and again, each layer more. Whoever leaves home for the kingdom receives manifold more, stacked in folds.","g":"manifold more","h":"The picture: cloth folded over many times."},"G418":{"b":"Strong's reads it as unadmitted, from a word meaning admitted or let in. Picture a thing barred at the door, never allowed through. It cannot be, Jesus says, that no stumbling blocks come. Some things simply get no entry.","g":"impossible","h":"The picture: the door that will not let it in."},"G4180":{"b":"This joins two words, much and word. It pictures a pile of words heaped up. Jesus warns against it in prayer. The pagans think they will be heard for their much speaking, as if God were won by sheer volume.","g":"much speaking","h":"The picture: a pile of words heaped up."},"G4181":{"b":"The root is a division or share, a piece of a whole. This word means in many parts. God did not speak all at once but a piece at a time, to one man now, another later, across the years.","g":"in many parts","h":"The picture: given one piece at a time."},"G4182":{"b":"Built from much and many-coloured. Abbott-Smith says it means much variegated, of greatly differing colours. Picture a cloth woven of many shades. Paul uses it for the many-coloured wisdom of God.","g":"manifold","h":"The picture: cloth of many colours."},"G4183":{"b":"Strong's gives no source word at all, only a note about the different forms this word takes. Abbott-Smith gives no history either. It means much, many, great. Nothing sits underneath it.","flat":1,"g":"much, many","h":"No picture."},"G4184":{"b":"Built from \"much\" and the word for the guts, the inward parts. The ancients felt deep feeling down in the bowels, not the head. So this is a God whose insides churn with pity. Full of it, James says.","g":"very pitiful","h":"The picture: pity felt down in the guts."},"G4185":{"b":"The word joins much and cost. Abbott-Smith reads it very costly, very precious, of great value. Think of the flask of pure nard the woman breaks over Jesus, worth nearly a year of wages, poured out in one moment.","g":"costly","h":"The picture: the jar of costly perfume."},"G4186":{"b":"The roots are \"much\" and \"price.\" So this means costing a great deal. The merchant found one pearl of great price and sold everything to buy it. Mary poured out ointment worth a year of wages. Much money paid.","g":"very costly","h":"The picture: a price hard to pay."},"G4187":{"b":"The old word behind this pictured much turning, many twists. It means in many ways. God spoke by dream, by law, by vision, by prophet, taking many different roads to reach his people.","g":"in many ways","h":"The picture: the road that turns many ways."},"G4188":{"b":"From the word to drink, poma is simply the thing you drink, a beverage. Paul says the fathers all drank of a spiritual Rock that followed them through the desert, and that Rock was Christ.","g":"drink","h":"The picture: the cup you drink."},"G4189":{"b":"The root means evil that is active and hurtful, not just bad but harmful in effect. Jesus says the Pharisees are clean outside but inside full of greed and wickedness. Badness that reaches out and injures.","g":"wickedness","h":"The picture: evil that does harm."},"G419":{"b":"The root means to explore, to search out. Put the not in front. So it is what cannot be searched out. Abbott says unsearchable. Paul cries that God's judgments are unsearchable, his ways past finding out, too deep to reach bottom.","g":"unsearchable","h":"The picture: depths no search can reach the bottom of."},"G4190":{"b":"Abbott traces it to a verb meaning to toil. First it described people oppressed by toils, and things that were toilsome and painful.\n\nThen it slid to worthless, and then to wicked. Evil starts as grinding work.","g":"evil, wicked","h":"The picture: worn out by hard labour."},"G4192":{"b":"This word first means labour, hard toil, the kind that wears the body down. Then it means the pain that toil leaves behind, distress and suffering. In Revelation people gnaw their tongues for pain, and pain will one day be no more.","g":"pain, toil","h":"The picture: back-breaking labor."},"G4193":{"b":"This means a native of Pontus, and the root of Pontus is a sea. So the word carries a man from the sea-country of Asia Minor. Aquila, born there, met Paul in Corinth.","g":"of Pontus","h":"The picture: a man from the sea-country."},"G4194":{"b":"This is just a Roman family name, Pontius, the first name of Pilate. Strong's says it is of Latin origin. It is a label for a man, not a word built from a picture. There is nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"Pontius","h":"No picture."},"G4195":{"b":"The word means \"a sea.\" Strong's says so, and the region Pontus took its name from lying along the Black Sea. Abbott notes it borders that water. It is one of the far coasts the Pentecost pilgrims came from, a place called after the sea.","g":"Pontus","h":"The picture: the open sea the region is named for."},"G4196":{"b":"This is the name Publius, the leading man of Malta who took the survivors in and lodged them. Strong's says it is Latin. A name carries nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"Publius","h":"No picture."},"G4197":{"b":"The word comes from the verb to travel. Abbott says \"a journey.\" Luke shows Jesus making his way toward Jerusalem, town by town. James uses it for a rich man who fades even while still on the move, out on his travels.","g":"journey","h":"The picture: the road walked town to town."},"G4198":{"b":"Abbott-Smith builds this verb on a noun meaning a ford, a crossing place.\n\nSo the word is not just moving. It is the shallow spot where you can get across, and the going that follows it.","g":"go, travel","h":"The picture: a ford across a river."},"G4199":{"b":"This word means to ravage and lay waste, the way an army sacks a town. Paul once did this to the church, tearing it apart house by house, before Christ met him on the road and stopped him.","g":"ravage","h":"The picture: a town sacked and laid waste."},"G42":{"b":"Built from the word for holy, meaning set apart. Abbott says it is the settled state that sanctifying produces. Paul urges, perfect hagiosyne in the fear of God, Second Corinthians 7:1. The finished condition of a life wholly set apart to God.","g":"holiness","h":"The picture: the finished state of set-apart."},"G420":{"b":"This joins a word meaning to hold oneself up against, to put up with, to the word for evil. It pictures a man bracing under wrong and not striking back. Paul says the Lord's servant must be like this. He takes the blow and holds.","g":"patient","h":"The picture: holding up under wrong."},"G4200":{"b":"The root means to procure, to find a way to get something. Strong's ties it to the word for a way or a means. So this is money-getting, treating a thing as a source of income. Paul warns of those who see godliness as a means of gain.","g":"gain, money-getting","h":"The picture: a way to make money."},"G4201":{"b":"Strong's says this Roman name apparently means swinish, from the Latin word for pig. It is the first name of Porcius Festus, the governor who took over from Felix. The name itself, Strong's suggests, points back to the farm animal, the pig.","g":"Porcius","h":"The picture: a pig."},"G4202":{"b":"The plain sense is sexual unfaithfulness. Abbott-Smith then notes the word is used as a picture of idolatry, pointing to Hosea.\n\nSo chasing other gods gets described as cheating on a spouse.","g":"sexual sin","h":"The picture: a marriage betrayed."},"G4203":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is to prostitute the body for hire. The root is the word for a prostitute. This verb is that trade made into an action. The prophets used it for chasing other gods, Israel selling herself, leaving her husband behind.","g":"commit fornication","h":"The picture: the body sold for money."},"G4204":{"b":"Abbott says a prostitute, harlot, the body sold for money. Jesus shocks the religious, the pornai go into the kingdom ahead of you. Rahab the harlot is named among the faithful. And John draws idolatrous Rome as the great harlot riding the beast.","g":"harlot","h":"The picture: the body sold for money."},"G4205":{"b":"Strong's ties this word to selling, from a root akin to the base of the verb to sell. It pictures a man who sells his body. It widened to mean anyone living in sexual sin.","g":"fornicator","h":"The picture: one who sells himself."},"G4206":{"b":"This means far off, a long way away. The root is the word for \"in front.\" Jesus quotes Isaiah, this people honors me with their lips but their heart is far from me. The mouth is near and the heart is off in the distance.","g":"far off","h":"The picture: a long way off."},"G4207":{"b":"The root means at a distance, and this adds \"from.\" Abbott says \"from afar.\" The ten lepers, unclean and kept out, stand far off and call to Jesus across the gap. The faithful in Hebrews see the promise the same way, from a distance.","g":"from afar","h":"The picture: standing at a distance, held back."},"G4208":{"b":"From a word meaning forwards, at a distance. This is the comparative form, farther on ahead. Jesus acted as if he would go farther, on down the road. That step made the two beg him to come in and stay.","g":"farther","h":"The picture: the road stretching farther on."},"G4209":{"b":"Behind this word is the purple-fish, a shellfish crushed for the costly dye it gave. From the creature the word passed to the color, then to a robe dyed with it. The soldiers throw a porphyra on Jesus to mock him as a king.","g":"purple","h":"The picture: the sea-snail that bleeds royal dye."},"G421":{"b":"This is built from a word for a track or footprint, with not in front. It means a trail you cannot follow. Paul says God's ways cannot be traced out, like steps that leave no print in the ground.","g":"unsearchable","h":"The picture: footprints you cannot follow."},"G4210":{"b":"The color comes from a shellfish, the \"purple\" mussel, crushed for its dye. Purple cloth was costly, the color of kings. So the soldiers throw a purple robe on Jesus to mock him as a king before they kill him.","g":"purple","h":"The picture: dye squeezed from a sea-shell."},"G4211":{"b":"The purple in this word came from a mussel, a sea snail crushed for its dye. Join that to the word for selling and you get a woman who trades in purple cloth. Lydia sold this purple when God opened her heart.","g":"seller of purple","h":"The picture: the shellfish that bleeds purple."},"G4212":{"b":"Built from the word for how much. Abbott gives how often. Jesus weeps over the city, posakis, how often I longed to gather your children as a hen gathers her chicks, and you would not, Matthew 23:37. A count of refused mercies.","g":"how often","h":"The picture: counting the times."},"G4213":{"b":"This word comes straight from the word to drink. It means the drinking itself, the draught, the mouthful going down. So when Jesus says his blood is true drink, the word underneath is the plain act of swallowing.","g":"drink","h":"The picture: a swallow of drink going down."},"G4215":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is a river, stream, torrent, running water you can drink. So when Jesus promises rivers of living water flowing out of the believer, picture not a trickle but a torrent, moving, loud, and alive.","g":"river","h":"The picture: running water you can drink."},"G4216":{"b":"The word joins the word for river to a word meaning to be carried. Abbott-Smith gives \"carried away by a stream.\" Picture a river in flood dragging you downstream. So the serpent spewed out a river to sweep the woman away.","g":"carried off by flood","h":"The picture: swept off your feet by a flood."},"G4218":{"b":"Pote means once, formerly, at some time gone by. Abbott points to Paul, you were pote darkness but now light in the Lord. So the word marks the old life, the once upon a time before grace, set against the now.","g":"once, ever","h":"The picture: back then, once, in the old days."},"G422":{"b":"The word at its core means to feel shame. The front of it cancels that out. Paul wants a workman who has no cause for shame, one who need not drop his eyes. His work stands up to inspection.","g":"not ashamed","h":"The picture: a face that need not look away."},"G4220":{"b":"This word asks which of two. It sets a fork in front of you, this one or that one. Jesus uses it about his teaching. Whether it comes from God or from himself, the one who wants to do God's will shall know.","g":"whether","h":"The picture: this road or that one."},"G4221":{"b":"Strong's calls it a drinking vessel, and adds that figuratively it means a lot or fate.\n\nAbbott shows both sides. A cup of prosperity and a cup of adversity. Whatever you are handed to drink.","g":"cup","h":"The picture: a cup put into your hand."},"G4222":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means to give to drink. It is also used of watering plants. Picture holding a cup to thirsty lips, or pouring water at the roots. Paul says he planted, and another watered with this word.","g":"give drink, water","h":"The picture: pouring out water to drink."},"G4223":{"b":"Strong's says the name means little wells, the mineral springs the town was known for. It is the port we now call Pozzuoli on the Bay of Naples. Paul landed here and found believers who asked him to stay a week.","g":"Puteoli","h":"The picture: little wells of mineral spring water."},"G4224":{"b":"The root simply means to drink. This word is a drinking bout, a carousal, hours spent at the cup. Peter names it among the things his readers used to do and now leave off.","g":"drinking bout","h":"The picture: a long night at the cup."},"G4225":{"b":"An indefinite word, somewhere, someplace, or of a number, about. The writer of Hebrews quotes Scripture loosely, someone pou has testified somewhere, Hebrews 2:6, naming no chapter and no verse, only that God once said it.","g":"somewhere, about","h":"The picture: somewhere, no chapter named."},"G4226":{"b":"This is the question word for place, where. Abbott's first sense is simply where. It scans the ground for a spot that cannot be found. So where is he that is born King sends the wise men searching, and where, O death, is your sting asks for a place no longer there.","g":"where","h":"The picture: a finger pointing, asking which spot."},"G4227":{"b":"Pudens is a Christian who greets Timothy. The name is Latin and carries the sense of modest, but no root lies behind it in Greek. It is simply the name of a man in Rome.","flat":1,"g":"Pudens","h":"No picture."},"G4228":{"b":"Strong's calls it a primary word, so nothing lies behind it. Abbott notes one habit of speech. Feet can stand for the whole person, when that person is on the move.","flat":1,"g":"foot","h":"No picture."},"G4229":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is that which has been done, a deed, act. The word comes from doing. A matter or affair is, at root, a thing that has been done. Even a lawsuit is one.","g":"matter, deed","h":"The picture: a thing done."},"G423":{"b":"The roots are a, not, and epilambanomai, to seize, to take hold of. So the word is a man no one can grab, no handle to seize him by. An overseer must be like this, blameless, with nothing an accuser can catch hold of.","g":"blameless","h":"The picture: no handle to grab."},"G4230":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to busy oneself, to trade. It means the affairs and business of life. Paul says no soldier gets tangled in them. The picture is a man tied up in his own trading, too busy to fight.","g":"affair","h":"The picture: getting tangled in business."},"G4231":{"b":"The root is a word for a deed or affair. Abbott says the verb means to be engaged in business, to trade. The master gave each servant a pound and said occupy till I come. Put your hands to work with it.","g":"trade, occupy","h":"The picture: the merchant busy at his trade."},"G4232":{"b":"This is a borrowed Latin word for the governor's palace. Abbott's first sense is \"headquarters in a Roman camp.\" It names the building where Pilate judged Jesus. The word is a place-name with no image inside it.","flat":1,"g":"governor's palace","h":"No picture."},"G4233":{"b":"Abbott says in Athens this was \"one who exacts payment, a collector,\" and then a court officer. Jesus warns of the man who hands you to this officer, and the officer throws you in prison until you have paid the last coin.","g":"officer, collector","h":"The picture: the officer who collects the debt."},"G4234":{"b":"From a verb meaning to do repeatedly, to practise. A deed, an act, often a settled practice. Paul says put to death the deeds of the body, and Ephesus burns its books of magic practices. Doing that becomes a habit.","g":"deed","h":"The picture: the thing you do again and again."},"G4236":{"b":"This word means gentleness, a meek and humble spirit. The sources give only its sense, with no root behind it to picture. It is the quality itself. Paul tells Timothy to follow after it, along with faith, love, and patience.","flat":1,"g":"meekness","h":"No picture."},"G4237":{"b":"Abbott-Smith calls it a garden-bed. Strong's guesses it started as an onion-patch. Picture rows of green plants set in tidy blocks. Mark uses it for the crowd on the hillside, sat down in orderly groups, block after block, like a planted garden.","g":"garden plot","h":"The picture: neat beds in a vegetable garden."},"G4238":{"b":"Strong's says this word is to perform repeatedly or habitually, and marks it off from another verb that means a single act.\n\nSo it is not one deed. It is the habit, the pattern you keep.","g":"practise, do","h":"The picture: doing it again and again."},"G4239":{"b":"Strong's calls this a primary word meaning mild, and by implication humble. It is the gentle, meek spirit. Nothing lies behind it to trace, and it names a quality, not a thing. Jesus blesses the meek, promising them the earth.","flat":1,"g":"meek","h":"No picture."},"G424":{"b":"This word is built from a word for up and a word meaning to come or go. It simply means to climb up. Paul uses it for going up to Jerusalem, the road that rises to the city on the hill.","g":"go up","h":"The picture: climbing the road up to the city."},"G4240":{"b":"The root is mild, gentle, humble. Prautēs is gentleness, meekness, not spineless but soft-handed on purpose. Paul says restore the fallen one in a spirit of prautēs, the way you set a broken bone, firmly and without roughness. Strength kept deliberately tender.","g":"meekness","h":"The picture: strength kept soft-handed."},"G4241":{"b":"The old sense was to be clearly seen, to tower up above the others. From what is conspicuous came what is fitting, since the right thing shows plainly. What suits the moment is what stands out as proper.","g":"be fitting","h":"The picture: the thing that stands out from the rest."},"G4242":{"b":"The word comes from being a senior, an elder sent to speak for others. Abbott's last sense is \"an embassy,\" the ambassadors themselves. Jesus says a weaker king sends envoys to ask terms of peace while the other army is still far off.","g":"embassy","h":"The picture: envoys sent to sue for peace."},"G4243":{"b":"The root means to be the elder, the senior. Because age carried weight, the senior man was sent as the envoy. So Paul says we are ambassadors for Christ, standing in his place while God pleads through us.","g":"be ambassador","h":"The picture: the elder sent as envoy."},"G4244":{"b":"The word gathers the elders into one body. Built from the word for an older man, it names the whole council of them. The elders lead Jesus to their council. Paul says a body of elders laid hands on Timothy. The seniors seated together.","g":"body of elders","h":"The picture: a council of gray-haired elders."},"G4245":{"b":"Abbott starts with the plain noun. An old man. This word is its comparative form, so it means the older one.\n\nOnly later does it become a title. The office keeps the shape of grey hair.","g":"elder","h":"The picture: the older man."},"G4246":{"b":"The word plainly means an old man. Zacharias protests that he is one when the angel promises him a son. Paul calls himself one when he pleads for Onesimus. Age enough to have earned gray hair and a slower step.","g":"old man","h":"The picture: an old man, gray and bent."},"G4247":{"b":"This is simply the word for an aged woman, the female form of the word for an old man. Paul tells Titus how the aged women should live, reverent in behavior. The word points to the gray-haired women of the church.","g":"aged woman","h":"The picture: an old woman."},"G4248":{"b":"This word means head foremost, pitched forward. It comes from a word meaning fore, in front. Luke uses it of Judas' death: falling headlong, he burst open. A body thrown forward onto the ground.","g":"headlong","h":"The picture: falling face-first, head first."},"G4249":{"b":"This word means to saw in two. It is the plain and brutal picture of a body cut through with a saw. Among the faithful who suffered, some were stoned, some were sawn asunder.","g":"saw asunder","h":"The picture: sawn in two."},"G425":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the first sense is a loosening, relaxation. The root means to let up or slacken. Picture a rope pulled tight, then eased off. That is the relief Paul speaks of, the strain slackened after the pressure.","g":"relief, rest","h":"The picture: a tight rope let loose."},"G4251":{"b":"This is a name. Strong's says it is the feminine of the Latin Priscus, meaning ancient. It belongs to a Christian woman, Aquila's wife. A name points to a person, not to a picture.","flat":1,"g":"Prisca","h":"No picture."},"G4252":{"b":"The name is the affectionate little form of Prisca. Picture her with her husband Aquila, taking the learned Apollos aside to explain the way of God more exactly, Acts 18:26. A woman whose name means small, teaching a great preacher.","g":"Priscilla","h":"The picture: little Prisca."},"G4254":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives the plain sense. To lead on, lead forth or forward.\n\nIt also works without an object. To go before, to precede. Jesus uses it of himself going on ahead of the disciples.","g":"go before","h":"The picture: walking ahead of the others."},"G4255":{"b":"The root means to take for oneself, to prefer, with before in front. Chosen and picked up ahead of time. Paul says each should give what he has settled in his heart beforehand, not squeezed out.","g":"purpose, choose","h":"The picture: reaching out and taking the thing you want."},"G4256":{"b":"This joins before with a word for a legal charge or crime. So it is to bring an accusation ahead of time. Abbott says to accuse or charge beforehand. Paul had already charged both Jews and Greeks with being under sin.","g":"charge beforehand","h":"The picture: charges laid before the trial begins."},"G4257":{"b":"Built from before and the word to hear. It means to hear ahead of time. Paul says the Colossians heard before, in the true word of the gospel, of the hope laid up for them in heaven.","g":"hear before","h":"The picture: news reaching your ear beforehand."},"G4258":{"b":"The root means to miss the mark, as an arrow falls short. With pro in front it means to have sinned before, in the past. Paul warns those who sinned earlier and have not repented that he will not spare them.","g":"sin before","h":"The picture: the arrow that missed before."},"G4259":{"b":"This word joins a word for in front of with the word for a yard open to the sky. It is the porch before the courtyard. Peter slipped out here after the servant girl questioned him. This is where the cock crowed.","g":"porch, forecourt","h":"The picture: the porch in front of the courtyard."},"G426":{"b":"The word means to examine judicially, to investigate. Luke uses it darkly: the commander orders Paul examined by flogging to drag out the truth. The lash was the interrogation. It is inquiry with force behind it, testing a man till he breaks.","g":"examine judicially","h":"The picture: questioning under the lash."},"G4260":{"b":"The parts mean \"forward\" and the foot. Probaino is to step ahead, to walk on. James and John were mending nets when Jesus, going a little further, saw them. Luke uses the same word for people well advanced in years, far along the road of life.","g":"advance","h":"The picture: feet stepping forward."},"G4261":{"b":"The word throws something forward. Abbott uses it of trees, \"to put forth, produce\" their leaves. Jesus points at the fig tree shooting out its buds: when the leaves come, you know summer is near. Growth pushed out where all can see.","g":"put forth, shoot forth","h":"The picture: a tree pushing out its new leaves."},"G4262":{"b":"From a word for a sheep. This describes the sheep-gate in Jerusalem, where flocks were brought through the wall. By it lay a pool where the sick waited. There Jesus found a man who had been ill thirty-eight years.","g":"sheep gate","h":"The picture: the sheep-gate flocks passed through."},"G4263":{"b":"Strong's says the word means something that walks forward. Abbott notes it once covered small cattle in general before it settled on sheep.\n\nA plain farm word. Sheep are named for the way they plod along.","g":"sheep","h":"The picture: the animal that walks forward."},"G4264":{"b":"This word is built from two pieces, one meaning the front, the other meaning to force. Put together it is shoving someone forward. In Matthew 14:8 the girl is pushed by her mother to ask for John's head. She did not think of it herself.","g":"urge, push forward","h":"The picture: pushed to the front from behind."},"G4265":{"b":"The word is built from two smaller words: \"fore\" and \"to look at.\" Put them together and you get eyes that look down the road before anyone else does. Hebrews says God saw the thing coming and set it up in advance.","g":"provide, foresee","h":"The picture: eyes that look ahead."},"G4266":{"b":"This is built from before and to happen. It means to happen beforehand, already done and behind you. Paul uses it of sins committed in earlier time, the wrongs God passed over in his patience before the cross.","g":"be past","h":"The picture: already done and behind you."},"G4267":{"b":"Built from before and to know. The picture is knowing a thing before it comes to pass. Paul says those God proginosko, He knew and set His love upon before they were ever born, Romans 8:29. Foreknown, then called.","g":"foreknow","h":"The picture: known before he drew a breath."},"G4268":{"b":"The root means to know beforehand, to see a thing before it arrives. Peter says believers are chosen by God's foreknowledge, and that the cross was no accident, delivered up by God's set plan and foreknowledge. He saw it all first.","g":"foreknowledge","h":"The picture: known before it came."},"G4269":{"b":"The roots are pro, before, and a word meaning to come to be, to be born. Abbott's plain sense is born before. A progonos is someone born ahead of you, further up the family line. Paul served God as his forefathers did.","g":"forefather","h":"The picture: the ones born before you."},"G4270":{"b":"The root is to write, with \"before\" in front. It means to write beforehand, and also to placard, to post a notice where all can see. Paul says Christ crucified was placarded before the Galatians' own eyes.","g":"placard, write before","h":"The picture: a notice posted in public."},"G4271":{"b":"This word is built from two others, one meaning fore or in front, one meaning clear. So it means plain out in front, plain before all men. Nothing tucked away. Paul says some people's sins are like this, obvious before they even arrive.","g":"obvious, evident","h":"The picture: out where everyone can see it."},"G4272":{"b":"The root means to give. Add the word for before. So it is to give first, ahead of the other. Abbott says to give before, give first. Paul says no one has first given to God, so that God would owe him anything back.","g":"give first","h":"The picture: putting a gift in first, before any is given back."},"G4273":{"b":"Strong's traces this to giving someone forward into the enemy's hands. That is the traitor. Judas is named among the twelve as the one who became this. To pass a person over to those who want to destroy him.","g":"betrayer, traitor","h":"The picture: handing a man over to the enemy."},"G4274":{"b":"The root means to run forward, to outstrip. This is the scout who runs ahead of the army, the forerunner. Jesus went in ahead of us behind the veil, opening the way for us to follow.","g":"forerunner","h":"The picture: the runner who goes in ahead."},"G4276":{"b":"This joins before and to hope. It is hope that arrives ahead of time, that got there first. Paul speaks of those who first trusted in Christ, whose hope was set on him before the wider world came in.","g":"first trust","h":"The picture: hope that got there first."},"G4278":{"b":"The word means to begin before, to make the first start. Paul uses it of the Corinthians, who a year earlier were first to begin the relief collection. Now Titus goes to help them finish what their hands were first to set moving.","g":"begin before","h":"The picture: the first to start."},"G4279":{"b":"The front piece of this word means fore, out in front. It is a promise placed ahead of time, spoken before the thing arrives. God gave this promise beforehand through his prophets. The word goes out in front of what it pledges.","g":"promise before","h":"The picture: a word sent out ahead."},"G428":{"b":"This is euthetos, well placed, with 'not' in front. It means badly placed, unfit. The haven at Fair Havens was not well set to winter in, too exposed to ride out the storms. The word says the place sat wrong, not fit for the job.","g":"not fit","h":"The picture: a harbour set in the wrong spot."},"G4280":{"b":"This is built from before and a word meaning to utter, to speak or say. So it means to say a thing ahead of time. It is the word for foretelling, speaking of something before it comes to pass.","g":"foretell","h":"The picture: said before it happened."},"G4281":{"b":"Abbott: \"to go forward, go on, advance,\" and also to go before. It joins \"before\" with \"go.\" Jesus went a little farther ahead to pray. John would walk on before the Lord to prepare his way.","g":"go ahead","h":"The picture: walking on ahead of the others."},"G4282":{"b":"Built from fore and to prepare, to get something ready ahead of time. Paul speaks of vessels of mercy God prepared beforehand for glory, and good works made ready in advance for us to walk in. The way laid out before you arrive.","g":"prepare beforehand","h":"The picture: a room made ready before the guest comes."},"G4283":{"b":"The root means to announce good news, with before in front. Abbott-Smith says to announce glad tidings beforehand. Paul says Scripture preached the gospel to Abraham early, promising the nations would be blessed.","g":"preach good news before","h":"The picture: a herald running ahead with good news."},"G4284":{"b":"This joins the word for in front of with to hold. Abbott's running sense is to have the start, and so to excel. Paul asks whether the Jews are out ahead of everyone else. His answer is no, all alike are under sin.","g":"excel, be better","h":"The picture: out in front at the start of a race."},"G4285":{"b":"The root means to lead, to go in front. Add the word for before. So it is to go ahead as leader. Abbott says to go before as leader. Paul turns it around, in honor go first, outdoing one another in showing respect.","g":"prefer, lead","h":"The picture: walking out ahead to lead the way."},"G4286":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means \"a setting forth.\" It named the loaves laid out before God in the temple. The same word means a purpose, the plan you set out in front of yourself and mean to do.","g":"purpose, showbread","h":"The picture: bread set out in front."},"G4287":{"b":"The roots are before and to place. Abbott-Smith says a day appointed beforehand, a term set in law. Paul says an heir waits like a child until the day the father set, then comes into everything.","g":"time appointed","h":"The picture: a date set down in advance, fixed and waiting."},"G4288":{"b":"The root means forward in spirit, the mind already tipped ahead toward a thing. This is eagerness, the will straining forward before you are asked. The Bereans received the word with all readiness of mind.","g":"readiness, eagerness","h":"The picture: the spirit leaning forward."},"G4289":{"b":"The roots are \"forward\" and a word for passion, breathing hard. So it is the heart leaning ahead, eager to go. In the garden Jesus says the spirit is willing but the flesh is weak. The will strains forward while the tired body holds back.","g":"willing","h":"The picture: the spirit straining forward."},"G429":{"b":"The root is the word for finding, the \"eureka\" word. The front part adds the hunt, finding by searching. Luke uses it for the shepherds, who hurried and searched out Mary and Joseph and the baby lying in the manger.","g":"find out","h":"The picture: searching until you find it."},"G4290":{"b":"The root means \"forward in spirit,\" ready and predisposed. So this is doing a thing eagerly, with a ready mind. Peter tells the elders to shepherd like that, not grudgingly but leaning in.","g":"willingly","h":"The picture: leaning forward, eager to go."},"G4291":{"b":"This word is built from before and to stand. The leader is the one who stands out in front of the others. Not barking orders from behind, but placed ahead where all can see him. To rule here is to stand before the people.","g":"rule, preside","h":"The picture: the one who stands out in front."},"G4292":{"b":"This word grows from a root meaning to call, spoken aloud. Abbott-Smith gives to call forth, then to challenge. Picture a man shouting across a field, daring another to step out and fight. Paul says do not provoke each other.","g":"provoke","h":"The picture: calling someone out to fight."},"G4293":{"b":"This word is built from a piece meaning \"before\" and a word meaning to proclaim, promulgate. Picture a herald shouting news in the street, only ahead of time. So the prophets did not guess. They announced what was coming before it came.","g":"foretell","h":"The picture: the herald who calls it out before it happens."},"G4294":{"b":"The root means to repair or put right, with before in front. Abbott-Smith says to make ready beforehand. Paul sends men ahead to get the promised gift arranged early, ready and not squeezed out at the last.","g":"make ready beforehand","h":"The picture: mending and setting a thing in order ahead of time."},"G4295":{"b":"The word is before plus to lie. Something lies stretched out in front, set forth for you. Hebrews speaks of the joy set before Jesus and the race set before us. The picture is a thing placed ahead, in plain view, waiting.","g":"set before","h":"The picture: laid out in front of you."},"G4296":{"b":"The word joins 'before' with 'to herald, as a public crier.' John went ahead of Jesus like a town crier, proclaiming a baptism of repentance before the Lord ever appeared.","g":"before preach","h":"The picture: a herald crying the news ahead."},"G4297":{"b":"The root prokopto means to drive forward as if beating a path ahead, cutting a way through. Prokope is that forward progress on a journey. Paul says his chains have served to push the gospel forward, not hold it back.","g":"progress","h":"The picture: cutting a path forward."},"G4298":{"b":"Abbott: to cut forward a way. The picture is hacking a path ahead, clearing the ground to move on. Jesus grew, cutting forward in wisdom and stature. Later it simply means to make progress, to advance further than before.","g":"advance","h":"The picture: hacking a path forward."},"G4299":{"b":"This joins pro, before, and krino, to judge. So it is judgment made in advance, the verdict fixed before the evidence is in. Paul charges Timothy to do nothing by prejudice, favoring no one.","g":"prejudice","h":"The picture: the verdict reached before the trial."},"G43":{"b":"This word comes from a word for a bend. It means the bent arm, the curve where you cradle a child. Old Simeon took the baby Jesus into the crook of his arms and blessed God, ready now to die in peace.","g":"arm","h":"The picture: the crook of a bent arm."},"G430":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the word means to hold up. It joins up with holding. You prop yourself up under a hard person or a hard time and do not collapse. That is how it comes to mean to bear with and put up with.","g":"bear with, endure","h":"The picture: holding yourself up under it."},"G4300":{"b":"The root means to ratify, to give it the force of law. Abbott-Smith says to confirm beforehand. Paul says God ratified his covenant with Abraham long before, and the later law cannot cancel that signed deal.","g":"confirm beforehand","h":"The picture: a contract sealed and made binding ahead of time."},"G4301":{"b":"The word joins take and beforehand. Strong's pictures a man who eats before others have an opportunity. Paul uses it that way at the supper, where some seize their own meal and leave the rest hungry. To grab first.","g":"take before","h":"The picture: grabbing your food before anyone else."},"G4302":{"b":"The word puts \"before\" in front of \"say.\" Strong's says it means to say beforehand, to foretell. You speak the thing out ahead of time, as a warning. Paul told them plainly before it happened.","g":"foretell","h":"The picture: saying it beforehand."},"G4303":{"b":"Built from \"before\" and the word for a witness giving testimony, this is a witness who speaks ahead of the event, telling the court what will happen. Peter says Christ's Spirit did this in the prophets, foretelling his suffering.","g":"testify beforehand","h":"The picture: a witness who speaks before it happens."},"G4304":{"b":"Built from a word for before and a word meaning to turn a thing over in the mind. To prepare a speech in advance. Do not rehearse beforehand what to answer, Jesus said. When they drag you before rulers, the words will be given you.","g":"meditate before","h":"The picture: rehearsing your lines beforehand."},"G4305":{"b":"This joins before and to be anxious. It is worry run ahead of the moment, fretting rehearsed in advance. Jesus tells his own not to be anxious beforehand about what to say. In that hour the Spirit will give them the words.","g":"worry beforehand","h":"The picture: worry rehearsed in advance."},"G4306":{"b":"The roots are pro, before, and noeo, to see with the mind. Abbott's first sense is to foresee, to see a thing coming. So to provide is to look ahead and get ready. Paul says provide for your own, and see beforehand what is honest.","g":"provide","h":"The picture: seeing it coming."},"G4307":{"b":"The word is fore plus seeing, looking ahead. It means planning before the need arrives. Tertullus flatters the governor for his forethought. When Paul uses it, it is God's care that looks down the road and supplies before you get there.","g":"providence","h":"The picture: eyes on the road ahead."},"G4308":{"b":"The word is \"before\" plus \"to see,\" \"to behold in advance.\" To see a thing ahead of time, or keep it in view in front of you. David says I foresaw the Lord always before my face, his eyes set on God ahead of every step.","g":"foresee","h":"The picture: eyes on something before it arrives."},"G4309":{"b":"The root means to mark out a boundary, the same word behind horizon. The front means beforehand. To draw the line ahead of time, to fix the limits in advance. Paul says God marked out beforehand those he would bring into his family.","g":"predestine, foreordain","h":"The picture: a boundary line drawn ahead of time."},"G431":{"b":"This word means a cousin, family but not your brother, the child of your parent's brother or sister. Paul sends greeting from Mark, the cousin of Barnabas, marking the family tie so the church would welcome him.","g":"cousin","h":"The picture: kin from the next branch of the family."},"G4310":{"b":"Pascho means to feel something, usually pain. Pro sets it earlier. So it is suffering already gone through, hurt endured beforehand. Paul reminds them he had suffered and been shamefully treated at Philippi before he ever came to them.","g":"suffer beforehand","h":"The picture: the pain that came before."},"G4311":{"b":"Strong's: \"to send forward, i.e. escort.\" Abbott: \"to set forward on a journey, escort.\" It joins \"forward\" with \"send.\" You go out with someone to see them safely on their way, walking part of the road with them.","g":"escort, send on","h":"The picture: seeing a traveler off on the road."},"G4312":{"b":"Built from \"forward\" and the word to fall, it is falling forward, headlong, before you have caught your balance. The clerk warns the crowd to do nothing headlong, to hold still and act with care rather than tip into a rash mistake.","g":"rash, headlong","h":"The picture: pitching forward and falling on your face."},"G4313":{"b":"The root means to travel, to journey, and \"before\" puts you out in front. It is going ahead of someone on the road. Zechariah sings that his son John will go before the Lord to prepare his way, the runner clearing the path.","g":"go before","h":"The picture: walking ahead to clear the road."},"G4315":{"b":"This word joins before with the word for the Sabbath, the day of weekly repose from work. So it is the Sabbath-eve. Jesus died on this day. They hurried to bury him before sundown, when all work had to stop.","g":"Sabbath eve","h":"The picture: the eve before the day of rest."},"G4316":{"b":"The root is the town square, where people met and spoke. This word means to greet someone by name. God addressed his Son by name, calling him a high priest after the order of Melchizedek.","g":"call by name","h":"The picture: hailed by name in the marketplace."},"G4317":{"b":"The word is \"lead\" with \"toward\" on it, to bring or lead a person up close. Christ suffered once to prosago us to God, Peter writes, to take us by the hand and bring us near. Elsewhere it means simply to draw near, to approach.","g":"bring near","h":"The picture: leading someone forward by the hand."},"G4318":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is a bringing to. The word is being led forward into someone's presence, like a man brought in before a king. Paul says through Christ we have this access to grace, led in, not shut out.","g":"access","h":"The picture: led in before a king."},"G4319":{"b":"The word is built from asking, but with a front piece meaning over and over. Abbott-Smith lands on beg, ask alms. Picture the blind man sitting by the road, hand out, asking again and again. That is the word.","g":"beg","h":"The picture: the beggar who keeps asking."},"G432":{"b":"This is simply the herb dill, a small garden plant. In Matthew 23:23 Jesus says the Pharisees carefully tithe their dill and mint and cummin, counting out tiny seeds, while they ignore justice and mercy.","g":"dill, anise","h":"The picture: a sprig of dill."},"G4320":{"b":"This word joins toward and to go up. Abbott-Smith gives it as to go up higher. Take the lowest place at a feast, Jesus says, so the host may come and tell you, friend, move up higher, and you are honored before all the guests.","g":"go up","h":"The picture: being moved up to a better seat."},"G4321":{"b":"This word joins besides and to use up. Abbott-Smith gives it as to spend besides. The bleeding woman had spent everything she had on doctors over twelve years, and not one of them could heal her.","g":"spend","h":"The picture: spending your last coin trying to get well."},"G4322":{"b":"This is built from words meaning to fill up completely by adding more. It pictures topping up what is short until the measure is full. Paul says this service fills up what the saints lack and overflows in thanks to God.","g":"supply fully","h":"The picture: topping up what is short."},"G4323":{"b":"This is built from words meaning to lay a thing before someone. In the middle it means to set your case before another to consult them. Paul says when God called him, he did not lay it before flesh and blood for advice.","g":"consult","h":"The picture: the matter laid before someone."},"G4324":{"b":"This word joins in addition with the word for making threats. It means to threaten some more. The council, unable to punish Peter and John because of the crowd, threatened them again and let them go. Warning stacked on warning.","g":"to threaten further","h":"The picture: piling one more threat on top."},"G4325":{"b":"This word joins besides and to spend. Abbott-Smith gives it as to spend besides. The Samaritan left money with the innkeeper and promised that whatever more he spent on the man, he would pay it all back when he returned.","g":"spend more","h":"The picture: covering whatever extra it costs."},"G4326":{"b":"Underneath is the word for begging, to beg as if binding oneself, holding out the hand. Add a prefix and it means to need something more. Paul said God does not beg from us, as if he lacked anything.","g":"need further","h":"The picture: the open, begging hand."},"G4327":{"b":"Abbott says the word means to receive to oneself, to accept gladly. \"This man welcomes sinners.\" It also means to wait for with hope. Simeon was waiting to receive the comfort of Israel.","g":"receive, wait for","h":"The picture: welcoming someone in."},"G4328":{"b":"Strong's says the word comes from a root meaning to watch, dokeuo (to watch). It is not idle waiting. It is looking down the road, eyes on the horizon, waiting for the one who is coming.","g":"await, expect","h":"The picture: watching the road for someone."},"G4329":{"b":"The root means to watch for a thing, in hope or in fear. Abbott says \"expectation.\" Jesus says hearts will fail for dread and for this, men's eyes fixed on what is coming over the world. The watching that is half terror.","g":"expectation","h":"The picture: watching the horizon for what is coming."},"G433":{"b":"The roots are ana, up, and heko, to arrive. So the word is to have come up to the mark. What reaches the proper level is what is fitting, what is due. Paul says speak what is fitting, come up to the standard.","g":"be fitting","h":"The picture: come up to the mark."},"G4330":{"b":"This is pros, toward, plus eao, to let be or permit. It means to permit further progress. Here the wind will not allow it. The ship cannot get past, held back as if the wind itself blocks the way forward. The word is that permission denied.","g":"permit further","h":"The picture: the wind refusing to let them by."},"G4332":{"b":"The word means to sit near, to attend as a servant. It pictures a servant seated close by the altar, always on duty. Paul says those who serve there share in what is offered there.","g":"wait at","h":"The picture: sitting at the altar in service."},"G4333":{"b":"Built from a word for besides and a word for toil. Abbott says it means to gain besides, by working. Your pound has made ten pounds more, the servant reports. Labor added to labor, and more on top of it.","g":"gain besides","h":"The picture: extra earned on top."},"G4334":{"b":"Abbott gives the plain sense. To approach, to draw near.\n\nThen he notes its use for approaching God. Hebrews uses it of coming right up to the throne. The word is ordinary. The place is not.","g":"come near","h":"The picture: stepping up close."},"G4335":{"b":"Abbott gives the word two senses. Prayer to God, and a place of prayer.\n\nThe second covers a synagogue and also a spot out in the open, which is where Acts 16 puts it.","g":"prayer","h":"The picture: the spot where people pray."},"G4336":{"b":"This joins toward to a word meaning to wish or beg. Prayer here is a wish turned in one direction, aimed straight at God. So to pray is not to talk into the air. It is to face someone and bring your asking to him.","g":"pray","h":"The picture: turning your face toward God to ask."},"G4337":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the first sense is to turn to, bring to, often with a ship understood. To bring to port, land.\n\nPaying attention is not passive. It is turning the wheel toward something.","g":"pay attention","h":"The picture: steering the ship into port."},"G4338":{"b":"Built from toward and the word for a spike or nail. It means to nail something fast. Paul says God took the record of our debt and nailed it to the cross, spiked through and done with.","g":"nail to","h":"The picture: a nail driven through it."},"G4339":{"b":"The word rests on \"to come near.\" A proselytos is one who has arrived, a stranger who has crossed over, here a convert who has come into Judaism from another people. Jesus rebukes those who cross land and sea to win just one.","g":"proselyte","h":"The picture: the newcomer who has come over from outside."},"G434":{"b":"The word means not tame. It is built by negating a word for tame or gentle. Paul uses it for savage people in the last days. The picture is a wild animal that no one has broken, snarling and untamed.","g":"fierce","h":"The picture: a beast that will not be tamed."},"G4340":{"b":"The word joins for with a set time. It means lasting only a while, temporary. Abbott-Smith notes it is used of short-lived plants. In the parable the seed on rock believes for a season, then falls away when trouble comes. Green for a moment, then gone.","g":"temporary, for a season","h":"The picture: a plant that lasts only a season."},"G4341":{"b":"Abbott says the plain verb means to call to, and the middle voice makes it to call to oneself.\n\nSo the calling points back at the one doing it. Come here, rather than just listen.","g":"call to oneself","h":"The picture: calling someone over."},"G4342":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the root behind it means strong, steadfast. Add toward, and it means to hold on toward something, to stick close and keep at it. The first believers kept at prayer together this way.","g":"persevere, hold fast","h":"The picture: sticking close and staying strong."},"G4343":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to be earnest towards a thing, to hold fast and not let go. Abbott gives stedfastness, perseverance. Paul asks for it in prayer, gripping on and keeping at it, watching with all steadfastness.","g":"perseverance","h":"The picture: gripping on and not letting go."},"G4344":{"b":"The word means something for the head, a cushion. In Mark 4:38 the storm rages and the boat is filling, but Jesus is in the stern asleep on the cushion, and the terrified disciples wake him.","g":"pillow, cushion","h":"The picture: a cushion under the head."},"G4345":{"b":"Underneath is the word for casting lots, to allot to, assign to by lot. As if names were drawn and some were handed to Paul. Certain Greeks and leading women were joined to him and Silas.","g":"associate with","h":"The picture: thrown in by lot."},"G4346":{"b":"This joins pros, toward, and klino, to lean or tilt. So it is leaning to one person over another, taking sides. Paul charges Timothy to keep these rules, doing nothing by partiality.","g":"partiality","h":"The picture: leaning toward one side."},"G4347":{"b":"The root word means to glue. This is what happens when a man leaves his father and mother and holds to his wife. Not two people standing near each other. Two things stuck fast, so that pulling them apart would tear them.","g":"cleave, join","h":"The picture: two things glued together."},"G4348":{"b":"The root means to stub your foot, to trip up. A proskomma is the stone in the path that catches your toe. So when Paul says put no proskomma in your brother's way, he means lay down nothing he will trip over.","g":"stumbling block","h":"The picture: the stone that stubs your toe."},"G4349":{"b":"The root means to strike against, to trip up. Abbott-Smith gives an occasion of stumbling. Paul says he puts no such stone in anyone's way, nothing that would make them fall.","g":"offence, stumbling","h":"The picture: stubbing your foot on a stone in the path."},"G435":{"b":"Abbott says this is a man, Latin vir. Not mankind in general but the grown male, and often the husband. So where anthropos is any human being, aner points to the man in the room, the one a woman calls husband.","g":"man, husband","h":"The picture: the grown man, the husband."},"G4350":{"b":"Strong's: \"to stub on, i.e. trip up.\" Abbott: \"to strike (e.g. hand or foot) against.\" Your foot hits a rock and you trip. From that Paul makes stumbling over a stone in the road.","g":"stumble","h":"The picture: stubbing your foot on a stone."},"G4351":{"b":"This joins pros, toward, to a word meaning to roll. Proskylio is to roll something up against an opening to block it. Joseph rolls a great stone across the door of the tomb, sealing Jesus inside.","g":"roll to","h":"The picture: rolling the great stone against the door."},"G4352":{"b":"Abbott-Smith traces this word to a verb meaning to kiss. Worship pictures leaning toward someone to kiss them.\n\nStrong's adds a guess about a dog licking its master's hand. Abbott-Smith does not. The kiss is the safer picture.","g":"worship","h":"The picture: a kiss toward someone."},"G4353":{"b":"The root means to prostrate oneself in homage, to kneel low. A proskynetes is a worshipper, one who bows down. God seeks true worshippers, Jesus told the woman, who worship in spirit and truth. It is a posture of the heart, not a place.","g":"worshipper","h":"The picture: bowing face to the ground."},"G4354":{"b":"Built from \"toward\" and a word meaning to talk, to utter words. It is turning to face a person and speaking with them. Paul asked to see the Jewish leaders in Rome so he could speak to them face to face.","g":"speak to","h":"The picture: turning toward someone to talk to them."},"G4355":{"b":"This is \"take\" with \"toward\" in front. Abbott-Smith says it means \"to take to oneself.\" So it pictures reaching out and drawing a person in. Paul uses it for welcoming someone as a friend.","g":"receive, welcome","h":"The picture: taking someone to yourself."},"G4356":{"b":"The root means to take to yourself, to admit to friendship or hospitality. So this is a receiving, a taking-in. Abbott says a receiving. Paul says if Israel's setting aside brought the world so much, their being received back brings life from the dead.","g":"receiving","h":"The picture: taking someone in as a welcomed guest."},"G4357":{"b":"This word is built from with and to stay. It means to keep remaining beside someone or something, not leaving. The crowd stayed with Jesus three days with nothing to eat. Paul urged Timothy to remain at Ephesus. To stay put and hold on.","g":"remain with","h":"The picture: staying on beside someone."},"G4358":{"b":"Abbott ties this to a word for an anchorage, a safe mooring. It means to bring a ship in and tie it up. In Mark 6:53 Jesus and the disciples cross the water, come to land at Gennesaret, and moor the boat to the shore.","g":"moor, land at","h":"The picture: bringing the boat to anchor."},"G4359":{"b":"The root simply means to owe. This word adds 'besides,' so it is to owe on top of what you already owe. Paul reminds Philemon that he owes him his very self, a debt beyond the account.","g":"owe besides","h":"The picture: a debt on top of the debt."},"G436":{"b":"Abbott breaks it into \"against\" and \"stand.\" It means to plant yourself facing someone and hold your ground. \"Resist the devil and he will flee.\" That resisting is standing firm against him.","g":"resist, oppose","h":"The picture: standing against."},"G4360":{"b":"The word means to be angry with, to feel indignant, even loathing. Hebrews quotes it of God in the desert: for forty years I was grieved with that generation. Their constant grumbling wore on him until he turned away. Anger mixed with weariness.","g":"be angry","h":"The picture: turning away in disgust."},"G4361":{"b":"The word puts 'very' in front of a root meaning to famish. Peter grows sharply hungry on the roof, and while the meal is being made he falls into the vision of the sheet.","g":"very hungry","h":"The picture: a stomach growling for food."},"G4362":{"b":"This word joins to and a verb meaning to peg or fix in place, the word for driving a tent stake. It means to fasten to, and so to crucify. Peter says wicked hands fastened Jesus to the cross. Pinned there like a peg.","g":"to crucify","h":"The picture: nailing something fast to the wood."},"G4363":{"b":"Abbott: \"to fall down at one's feet, fall prostrate before.\" People threw themselves down at Jesus' feet. The same word can also mean wind that falls hard against a house and beats on it.","g":"fall down before","h":"The picture: falling down at someone's feet."},"G4364":{"b":"Built from a word for toward and a word meaning to make or do. To make a move as if to do a thing, to act it out. At Emmaus Jesus made as though he would go further on. The pretend drew them to press him to stay.","g":"make as though","h":"The picture: making a move as if to leave."},"G4365":{"b":"The pieces mean toward and to travel. It is journeying up to a person, coming near. In Mark 10:35 James and John come up to Jesus and ask him to do whatever they request, that they may sit at his right and left.","g":"approach","h":"The picture: walking up to someone."},"G4366":{"b":"The root means to break or burst, and \"toward\" throws it against a thing. It is a torrent hurling itself at a wall. Jesus tells of the flood that burst against two houses, one on rock that stood, one on sand that fell.","g":"dash against","h":"The picture: a flood smashing against the house."},"G4367":{"b":"The root means to arrange in an orderly manner, to assign each thing its place. Add toward, and you get a command aimed at a person. Not a wish but an order that puts you in position. Do this, stand here.","g":"command","h":"The picture: setting each thing in its rank."},"G4368":{"b":"The root means to stand before. A patroness is the person who stands in front, between you and trouble, taking the lead in your defense. Paul says Phoebe stood like that for many, and for him too.","g":"patroness","h":"The picture: the one who stands out in front of you."},"G4369":{"b":"Strong's says to place additionally, to lay beside.\n\nAbbott-Smith notes an odd use borrowed from Hebrew. It can mean doing something again. You add another action on top of the last one.","g":"add","h":"The picture: laying one more on the pile."},"G437":{"b":"This is built from a word meaning back or in turn and a word meaning to acknowledge fully, confess. So it is praise given back in answer. Anna, seeing the child, answered God's gift aloud, giving thanks and telling his praise.","g":"give thanks","h":"The picture: praise given back in answer."},"G4370":{"b":"The roots mean toward and to run. So it is running up to someone. A man ran to Jesus, fell on his knees, and asked what he must do to inherit eternal life. The crowd too came running to greet him.","g":"run toward","h":"The picture: running up to someone and stopping."},"G4371":{"b":"This word is built on the word to eat. It means something eaten alongside bread, usually fish. From the shore the risen Jesus called, Children, have you any fish. They had caught nothing. Then the net filled.","g":"fish, relish","h":"The picture: a bit of fish to eat with the bread."},"G4372":{"b":"This word first meant freshly slain, an animal just killed and still new. From there it came to mean simply new and fresh. Christ opened a new and living way for us through the veil.","g":"new, fresh","h":"The picture: fresh, like meat just killed."},"G4373":{"b":"This comes from a word for something recently slain, still fresh from the kill. From meat just slaughtered came the sense of anything lately done. The Jews had recently been driven out of Rome by Claudius.","g":"recently","h":"The picture: freshly killed meat."},"G4374":{"b":"Carry, with toward attached. Strong's reads it as to bear towards. Abbott-Smith's first sense is to bring to, lead to, used of people brought to someone.\n\nThen it becomes the word for offering a sacrifice.","g":"bring to, offer","h":"The picture: carrying something toward someone."},"G4375":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to be a friend to, with toward in front. It names what draws affection toward it. Paul tells us to fix our minds on such things, whatever is lovely, whatever pulls the heart to love it.","g":"lovely","h":"The picture: what draws you to love it."},"G4376":{"b":"Abbott: \"a bringing to, offering.\" It comes from a word meaning to carry toward. An offering is something carried up to the altar and set before God. In the letters it becomes the one sacrifice of Christ.","g":"offering","h":"The picture: a gift carried up and presented."},"G4377":{"b":"This word is built from toward and a word meaning to emit a sound. It means to call out to someone, to send your voice their way. Children calling to their playmates in the market. Pilate calling out to the crowd. The voice sent toward a person.","g":"call to","h":"The picture: the voice aimed at a person."},"G4378":{"b":"This means a pouring or sprinkling upon. At the first Passover the blood was struck and poured on the doorframes, so the destroyer would pass over that house and spare the firstborn inside.","g":"sprinkling","h":"The picture: blood poured over the doorposts."},"G4379":{"b":"This word means to touch. Strong's sharpens it to lay a finger on. The lawyers load people with heavy burdens but will not so much as touch those loads with one of their own fingers to help carry them.","g":"touch","h":"The picture: laying a single finger on the load."},"G438":{"b":"This word simply means a flower, a blossom. It is a primary word, not built from anything else. James and Peter use it the same way. The rich man and all flesh are like the flower of the grass, bright at dawn and fallen by noon.","g":"flower","h":"The picture: a flower in the grass."},"G4380":{"b":"The root means an accepter of a face. You look at the outside, the face and the clothes, and let that decide. James says favor the rich man's face over the poor man's and you have broken the law.","g":"show partiality","h":"The picture: judging a man by his face."},"G4381":{"b":"The word joins 'the face' with 'to take or receive.' An accepter of a face judges people by their outward look. Peter learns that God is not one of these and takes no man by his face.","g":"respecter of persons","h":"The picture: a judge who looks at the face."},"G4382":{"b":"The root word means \"an accepter of a face.\" It pictures someone who looks at a person's face, their rank, wealth, or looks, and decides for them because of it. So favoritism is weighing the face instead of the person. With God there is none of it.","g":"favoritism","h":"The picture: judging by the face."},"G4383":{"b":"Strong's calls it the front, as being towards view. The part of a person you meet.\n\nAbbott lists the phrase face to face, and also a warning. Judging by the face means judging by appearance.","g":"face","h":"The picture: the side turned toward you."},"G4385":{"b":"This means to stretch forward, to stretch out. Abbott says it is used of getting a man ready for scourging. They stretched Paul out and bound him with thongs so the lash could fall. The word is the stretching of the body before the first blow.","g":"stretch out, bind","h":"The picture: a body stretched out and tied for the whip."},"G4387":{"b":"The root is fore, in front of, what comes before. Proteros is the former, the earlier one in the line. Paul says strip off the proteros self, the old you that walked in front, before Christ. Peter warns against the former lusts of your old ignorance.","g":"former","h":"The picture: the one who walked in front."},"G4388":{"b":"The roots are pro, in front of, and tithemi, to place. So the word is to set a thing out in front where all can see it, like bread laid on a table. In the middle voice it turns inward, to set a plan before yourself, to purpose.","g":"set forth, purpose","h":"The picture: setting a thing out in front."},"G4389":{"b":"The parts mean forward and a turn, a turning about. To turn someone forward, to nudge him to move ahead. The brothers turned Apollos toward Achaia, urging him on and writing ahead for him.","g":"encourage","h":"The picture: turning a man forward."},"G439":{"b":"The root is a live coal. Abbott says \"a heap of burning coals.\" Peter warms himself at one of these in the courtyard, and there he denies Jesus. By the lake afterward, Jesus has another coal fire going, with fish laid on it.","g":"fire of coals","h":"The picture: a heap of glowing coals."},"G4390":{"b":"The root is the word for running, with \"before\" in front. Abbott says \"to run on, run in advance.\" John says the other disciple outran Peter to the tomb. Zacchaeus, too short to see, runs ahead of the crowd and climbs a tree.","g":"outrun, run ahead","h":"The picture: outrunning the others to get there first."},"G4391":{"b":"The word puts \"before\" in front of \"to be present.\" Abbott says \"to be before or previously.\" Luke notes that Herod and Pilate had already been enemies before this day, and on it became friends. A thing that was true beforehand.","g":"exist before","h":"The picture: already there before the day began."},"G4392":{"b":"The parts mean in front and to show. It is the front you hold up so people see one thing while another hides behind. The scribes say long prayers as a show, covering greed. A pretext is a mask worn out front.","g":"pretext","h":"The picture: a front held up to hide behind."},"G4393":{"b":"The roots are \"forward\" and \"to carry\". Together they mean to carry a thing out, to bring it forth. Jesus says a good person brings forth good out of the store of the heart, and an evil one brings out evil.","g":"bring forth","h":"The picture: bringing goods out into the open."},"G4394":{"b":"This comes from prophetes, the foreteller, the one who speaks God's word forth. Propheteia is that speaking, the gift of telling out God's will and purpose. So prophecy came not by the will of man, holy men spoke as they were carried along, mouths for a word not their own.","g":"prophecy","h":"The picture: speaking out what God has said."},"G4395":{"b":"Abbott-Smith calls this telling forth the Divine counsels. Saying out what God says.\n\nHe adds that predicting the future is incidental to the word, not the heart of it. The job is speaking, not guessing.","g":"prophesy","h":"The picture: speaking it out loud."},"G4396":{"b":"Abbott-Smith calls him an interpreter or forth-teller of the divine will, and builds the word from a verb meaning to speak forth.\n\nSo the job is not mainly telling the future. It is saying out loud what God means.","g":"prophet","h":"The picture: someone speaking out in front."},"G4397":{"b":"The root is the prophet, a foreteller, one who speaks before the thing comes. So this is the prophetic word. Peter says it is made surer, a lamp shining in a dark place until day breaks.","g":"prophetic","h":"The picture: the word of the one who spoke it beforehand."},"G4398":{"b":"The root is the word for a prophet, one who tells forth God's word. This is the woman who does it. Luke names Anna, old and widowed, who never left the temple and spoke of the child to all who waited for redemption.","g":"prophetess","h":"The picture: a woman who speaks for God."},"G4399":{"b":"The two pieces mean before and to arrive. Together it is beating someone to it, arriving before they do. In Matthew 17:25 Jesus speaks first, before Peter can get his question out. He was there ahead of him.","g":"anticipate","h":"The picture: getting there first."},"G44":{"b":"The word comes from a root meaning a bend or a curve, the same idea as a curved arm. A hook is bent metal. In Matthew 17:27 Jesus tells Peter to throw in a hook and pull up the fish with the coin in its mouth.","g":"fish-hook","h":"The picture: a bent fish-hook."},"G440":{"b":"This is a live coal, a burning ember. Abbott says coal, charcoal, a burning coal. Paul quotes the Proverb, by feeding your enemy you heap live coals on his head, kindness that burns through his hatred.","g":"live coal","h":"The picture: a glowing live coal."},"G4400":{"b":"This word is built from a word for beforehand and the word for the hand. To take a thing into your hand ahead of time, to pick it out and set it aside. God chose Paul this way, marked out in advance.","g":"choose, appoint","h":"The picture: taken into the hand beforehand."},"G4401":{"b":"The root means to vote by raising the hand. With 'before' in front, it means chosen ahead of time. Peter says God picked out the witnesses of the risen Jesus beforehand.","g":"choose before","h":"The picture: hands raised beforehand to choose."},"G4402":{"b":"This name joins before with the word for a round dance or choir, the ring of singers who danced. It means something like leader of the dance. Prochorus was one of the seven chosen to serve tables in the early church.","g":"Prochorus","h":"The picture: the front of a ring dance."},"G4403":{"b":"This is the stern, the back end of a boat. In the storm Jesus was in the stern, asleep on the cushion, while the disciples panicked. The word puts you at the rear of the little ship, the one calm spot in the pitching boat.","g":"stern","h":"The picture: the back end of the boat."},"G4404":{"b":"The root is before, the front of the day. Prōi is early morning, first light before the world stirs. While it was still prōi, dark even, Jesus slipped out to a lonely place to pray. And it was prōi when the women found the stone rolled away.","g":"morning","h":"The picture: first light before the world stirs."},"G4405":{"b":"The word means daybreak, first light, the early watch. Proia is the morning itself. It is early morning when the chief priests take counsel and lead Jesus away to Pilate. The night of trials gives way to day.","g":"morning, dawn","h":"The picture: the first light of morning."},"G4406":{"b":"The root means at dawn, the first light of day. So this is the early rain, the first showers of the season that a farmer waits for. James says be patient like him, waiting for the early and the late rains.","g":"early","h":"The picture: the first rain at daybreak."},"G4407":{"b":"From the word for dawn, daybreak. So it means belonging to the morning. In Revelation it describes the star that rises at dawn, the morning star Christ promises. Picture first light and the last star before day.","g":"morning","h":"The picture: the morning star at dawn."},"G4408":{"b":"This is the prow, the forward point of a ship, from the word for fore, the front. The sailors pretended to drop anchors from the prow so they could escape. Later the prow stuck fast while the stern broke apart in the waves.","g":"prow","h":"The picture: the front of the ship."},"G4409":{"b":"This comes from the word for first, foremost. It means to hold first place. Paul says of Christ that in everything he might be first, the head, the beginning, before all things.","g":"be first","h":"The picture: standing at the front of the line."},"G441":{"b":"This word joins the words for man and to please. A man-pleaser aims everything at winning human approval, always playing to the crowd. Paul sets it against serving God. One eye forever on what people think, never on what God sees.","g":"men-pleaser","h":"The picture: playing to the crowd."},"G4410":{"b":"The word joins \"first\" to \"bench.\" It is the chief seat, the front-row place in the synagogue where all can see who sits there. The ones Jesus warns love these seats, the visible spot that says you matter most.","g":"chief seat","h":"The picture: the front-row seat everyone sees."},"G4411":{"b":"The word joins \"first\" and reclining at the meal. In those days you ate lying down, and the protoklisia was the top couch, the seat of honor. The Pharisees loved the protoklisia, Jesus says. Do not grab the best place. Take the lowest.","g":"chief seat","h":"The picture: the top couch at the feast."},"G4412":{"b":"This is protos used as an adverb, first. It grows from the word for foremost, whatever comes at the front, before anything else. So seek first the kingdom, proton, puts God at the head of the line, ahead of every other thing you chase.","g":"first","h":"The picture: first, before all the rest."},"G4413":{"b":"This grows from the little word pro, meaning in front of. Protos is whoever stands at the very front, first in time, place, or rank. So the first shall be last turns the line around, and the one at the front walks to the back.","g":"first","h":"The picture: the one at the front of the line."},"G4414":{"b":"This joins protos, first, to histemi, to stand. It first meant the man who stands in the front rank of soldiers. From there it means a leader, a ringleader. Paul is charged as a front-rank man of the Nazarenes, the one out ahead of the rest.","g":"ringleader","h":"The picture: the soldier in the front rank."},"G4415":{"b":"The root is the word for first-born. This is what belonged to him, the double share and the family blessing that fell to the oldest son. Hebrews holds up Esau, who sold his for one bowl of stew.","g":"birthright","h":"The picture: the eldest son's inheritance."},"G4416":{"b":"Abbott builds it from \"πρῶτος, τίκτω\", first and bring forth. Strong's: \"first-born.\" It is the first child a mother bears, who by old right held the top place among all the children.","g":"firstborn","h":"The picture: the first child born."},"G4417":{"b":"Strong's says this first means to trip. The root is to fall. Picture your toe catching and your body pitching forward. James uses it for sin. We all stumble. Not a bold leap into evil, but a foot that catches and trips.","g":"stumble, fall","h":"The picture: catching your foot and stumbling."},"G4418":{"b":"This word means the heel. Jesus quotes a psalm: the one who ate my bread has lifted up his heel against me. The picture is a friend at your table who turns and kicks. A heel raised to strike.","g":"heel","h":"The picture: a lifted heel."},"G4419":{"b":"The root is a wing. This word is a little wing, and the Greeks used it for a high point or edge, a turret or the tip of a roof. The devil sets Jesus on the pterygion of the temple, its highest edge, and dares him to jump. The top corner, far above the ground.","g":"pinnacle","h":"The picture: the little wing at the temple's highest edge."},"G442":{"b":"From the word for a human being. It means human, belonging to man. Paul says no trial has taken you but what is human, what people can bear. Weighed to the size of a man, not beyond.","g":"human","h":"The picture: cut to human size."},"G4420":{"b":"The root means to fly, and this is the wing, the feathered thing that lifts a bird. How often I would have gathered you as a hen gathers her chicks under her pteryges, Jesus says. The wing spread wide to shelter the small.","g":"wing","h":"The picture: a wing spread over the young."},"G4421":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives winged, and as a noun, birds. The root is the verb to fly. Paul says flesh differs, one kind for people and another for birds, each body made its own way.","g":"bird","h":"The picture: a winged thing in the air."},"G4422":{"b":"Strong's traces this to the idea of causing to fly away, a creature startled into sudden flight. Abbott says \"to be terrified.\" Jesus tells them not to be scared like this at news of wars. The disciples jump when they think they see a ghost.","g":"frighten, terrify","h":"The picture: a bird bursting into flight in fright."},"G4423":{"b":"Abbott says this word is \"a fluttering, excitement\" stirred up by feeling, especially fear. The root means to scare. Peter tells wives to do right and not be shaken by any such flutter of terror.","g":"alarm, terror","h":"The picture: the flutter of a startled heart."},"G4424":{"b":"This is Ptolemais, a place in Palestine, a coastal city named after a king Ptolemy. It labels a harbor where Paul stayed a day, so there is nothing here to picture.","flat":1,"g":"Ptolemais","h":"No picture."},"G4425":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this is a winnowing shovel or fan. The farmer throws the threshed grain up with it, and the wind carries off the light chaff while the heavy grain falls back. John says Christ holds this fork. He will clear his threshing floor, keeping wheat and burning chaff.","g":"winnowing fork","h":"The picture: the fork that tosses grain into the wind."},"G4426":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this word means to be startled, frightened. It is the sudden fright that makes a body jump. Paul says do not be frightened in any way by those who oppose you.","g":"frighten","h":"The picture: flinching in sudden fright."},"G4427":{"b":"From a word meaning to spit. Ptysma is spittle, saliva. Jesus spat on the ground, made clay from the dust, and spread it on the blind man's eyes. Dust and spittle became the means of healing.","g":"spittle","h":"The picture: spit mixed into the dust."},"G4428":{"b":"This word means to fold, to furl. Of a scroll, it is to roll it shut again. Jesus finished reading, rolled up the scroll, handed it back to the attendant, and sat down as every eye watched him.","g":"roll up","h":"The picture: rolling the scroll back up."},"G4429":{"b":"This simply means to spit. Jesus spat and touched the deaf man's tongue, and he spat on the eyes of a blind man before healing him. The word is a plain, earthy act, using his own spit as part of the cure.","g":"spit","h":"The picture: spitting on the ground."},"G443":{"b":"This word is built from the word for man and a word meaning to kill. A man-killer. Jesus says the devil was one of these from the beginning, a murderer who deals in the death of people.","g":"murderer","h":"The picture: the one who kills a man."},"G4430":{"b":"The root means to fall. A ptoma is what has fallen and does not rise, a corpse. Where the carcase is, there the eagles gather. They took John's fallen body and laid it in a tomb. The body dropped and lifeless on the ground.","g":"corpse","h":"The picture: the body that has fallen and stays down."},"G4431":{"b":"The root is to fall. Ptosis is the fall itself, the crash of something coming down. Jesus ends the story with the house on sand. The rain beat it and it fell, and great was the fall of it. The same word later marks the rise and fall of many.","g":"a fall","h":"The picture: the house crashing down."},"G4432":{"b":"The root ptocheuo means to be a beggar, to sink into want. Ptocheia is a beggar's poverty, having nothing. Paul says Christ, being rich, became poor for your sakes, so that his poverty might make you rich.","g":"poverty","h":"The picture: a beggar with nothing."},"G4433":{"b":"The root names a pauper, one who cringes. Abbott-Smith says to be a beggar, to beg. Paul says Christ was rich, yet for our sake became a beggar, so that we through his poverty might be rich.","g":"become poor","h":"The picture: a beggar crouched with his hand out."},"G4434":{"b":"Abbott traces this to a verb meaning to crouch, cower, and defines it as one who crouches and cowers.\n\nSo the poor here are not merely short of money. They are beggars, ducked down, hands out.","g":"poor, beggar","h":"The picture: a man crouching down."},"G4435":{"b":"This word is the closed hand, the fist. In Mark 7:3 it describes how the Pharisees wash, scrubbing one hand with the fist of the other, keeping the tradition of the elders before they eat.","g":"fist","h":"The picture: a clenched fist."},"G4436":{"b":"In the old story Python was a serpent slain by Apollo at Delphi. His name then stuck to fortune-tellers, as if a spirit spoke through them. The slave girl who followed Paul had such a python-spirit.","g":"python spirit","h":"The picture: the snake at Delphi."},"G4437":{"b":"The word first means close, compact, solid, things packed thick with no gaps. From there it comes to mean often, since frequent events crowd close in time. Paul tells Timothy to take a little wine for his frequent illnesses.","g":"often, frequent","h":"The picture: packed tight and close together."},"G4438":{"b":"This comes from a word for the clenched hand, the fist. It means to box. It pictures a fighter with fists raised, throwing real punches. Paul says he fights so, not beating the air, but landing blows on himself.","g":"box, fight","h":"The picture: fists raised in the ring."},"G4439":{"b":"This word means a gate. Strong's calls it a primary word, which means it does not come from anything else. It plainly names the gate of a city or a road. There is nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"gate","h":"No picture."},"G444":{"b":"Strong's breaks this word into two pieces, man and the countenance, which is the face. A human being is the creature with a man's face.\n\nAbbott-Smith gives no origin, only the plain meaning: a human being, male or female.","g":"human being, man","h":"The picture: the one with a face."},"G4440":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives two senses. The porch or vestibule of a house or palace, and the gate tower of a walled town.\n\nThis is where the beggar lay and where the servant girl answered. It is the threshold, not the room.","g":"gateway, porch","h":"The picture: the gateway of a big house."},"G4441":{"b":"This word just means to ask in order to find something out. Strong's says it is a middle voice prolonged from a primary verb. There is no image behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"inquire, ask","h":"No picture."},"G4442":{"b":"Strong's calls it a primary word. Abbott gives no origin. It means fire, plain and simple, and there is nothing behind it to uncover. Abbott simply lists where it burns.","flat":1,"g":"fire","h":"No picture."},"G4443":{"b":"This simply means a fire, the blaze itself, from the word for fire. On the cold rainy shore of Malta the islanders kindled one, and Paul gathered sticks to feed it. A snake driven out by the heat fastened on his hand. Real flames.","g":"fire","h":"The picture: a blaze of flames."},"G4444":{"b":"This is a plain old word for a tower or castle. In the parable it is the watch-tower in a vineyard, the high stone lookout raised so a guard can see thieves coming. The owner builds one, then leaves the vineyard to tenants.","g":"tower","h":"The picture: the watch-tower over the vineyard."},"G4445":{"b":"The root is fire. To have a fever, in Greek, is to be on fire, the body burning from the inside. Matthew says Peter's mother-in-law lay sick with a fever. Jesus touched her hand and the fire went out. She got up and served them.","g":"to have a fever","h":"The picture: the body on fire with fever."},"G4446":{"b":"It comes from the word for fire. A pyretos is the body on fire, burning with fever. Peter's mother-in-law was gripped by a great one. The word underneath is flame, heat blazing under the skin till it breaks.","g":"fever","h":"The picture: the body on fire."},"G4447":{"b":"The word comes from the word for fire. Abbott-Smith gives \"fiery.\" Picture breastplates glowing red like live coals. So the riders wore armor the color of fire, and their horses breathed out smoke.","g":"fiery","h":"The picture: the color of fire."},"G4448":{"b":"This comes from the word for fire. Pyroo is to be set ablaze or glow, and it was used of metal heated until the dross burns off and it can be refined. The fiery darts, the melting elements, the gold in the furnace all trace to fire.","g":"to burn, refine","h":"The picture: metal glowing in the furnace."},"G4449":{"b":"The root is pyrrhos, the color of flame, from pyr, fire. Pyrrhazo is to glow red like that. A red sky at evening means fair weather, Jesus says, and yet you read the sky but not the times.","g":"be red","h":"The picture: the sky glowing fire-red."},"G4450":{"b":"This word comes from the word for fire. Pyrrhos is flame-colored, fiery red. The second horse of Revelation came out red as fire, and its rider was given power to take peace from the earth.","g":"red","h":"The picture: the color of fire."},"G4451":{"b":"The root means to set on fire and, by that, to refine. Pyrosis is the burning that melts metal down to purify it. Peter tells his readers not to be surprised at the fiery trial. The heat is not there to destroy them. It is there to refine.","g":"burning, fiery trial","h":"The picture: metal in the fire."},"G4453":{"b":"Strong's says the word is to barter, as a pedlar does. Abbott-Smith puts exchange or barter first and selling second.\n\nIt is trade at street level. Goods changing hands in the open.","g":"sell","h":"The picture: the peddler's stall."},"G4454":{"b":"This just means a colt, the young of a donkey. Strong's calls it apparently a primary word, which means it does not come from anything else. There is nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"colt","h":"No picture."},"G4455":{"b":"A word meaning ever, at any time, and with a negative in front, never at all. No one has ever seen God, John writes, the only Son has made him known. It sweeps across all time and finds not one instance.","g":"ever, at any time","h":"The picture: not once, ever."},"G4456":{"b":"The word comes from a word for a stone, and for the hard callus that forms on worked hands. To harden the heart is to let it grow a thick callus over it. That is what happened to them. The heart turned to stone.","g":"harden","h":"The picture: skin turned to hard callus."},"G4457":{"b":"The root means to petrify, to turn to stone. Abbott says this is a covering with a callus, a hardening. So it is the thick, dead skin that grows over a heart. Jesus grieved at the hardness of their hearts. Feeling sealed off under a callus.","g":"hardness","h":"The picture: a callus grown over the heart."},"G4458":{"b":"This little tag means somehow or anyhow, by some means, perhaps. It never stands alone, only clinging to other words to soften them. It is the shrug in a sentence, the wave of the hand that says by whatever route, this might come about.","g":"somehow","h":"The picture: some way or other."},"G4459":{"b":"This is the question word for manner, in what way, how. It asks after the road something takes, but the road is only a figure of speech. There is no object to see here, just a way of asking how a thing happened.","flat":1,"g":"how","h":"No picture."},"G446":{"b":"Built from a word meaning in place of and a word for highest. The proconsul stands in for the highest officer, ruling a province for Rome. Paul met such a man, Sergius Paulus, and he believed. A deputy in the top seat.","g":"proconsul","h":"The picture: a man in the place of the highest ruler."},"G4460":{"b":"The name means proud. Behind it lies a word meaning roomy or broad. Rahab was the woman of Jericho who hid the Israelite spies and was spared, later named in the family line of Jesus.","g":"Rahab","h":"The picture: proud."},"G4461":{"b":"The title means my master. It became the term of honor for a Jewish teacher of the law. People addressed Jesus as Rabbi, giving him the respect owed to a master teacher.","g":"Rabbi","h":"The picture: my master."},"G4462":{"b":"The word is Aramaic. Abbott-Smith gives its meaning plainly: my master. It is warmer than plain Rabbi, the \"my\" making it personal. Blind Bartimaeus calls Jesus this, and so does Mary at the empty tomb, turning and knowing his voice.","g":"Rabboni","h":"The picture: my master, said to his face."},"G4463":{"b":"The root is the word for a stick, a cane, a cudgel. This word is to strike with a stick, to bring it down on a person. The magistrates at Philippi tore off Paul's clothes and had him beaten with rods.","g":"beat with rods","h":"The picture: a rod beating down on a man's back."},"G4464":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it is a staff or rod. The same word covers the plain stick you lean on for a journey and the scepter a king holds to rule. One piece of wood, humble or royal.","g":"rod, staff","h":"The picture: a stick in the hand."},"G4465":{"b":"This is built from the word for a rod and the word for holding. A rhabdouchos is one who carries a rod or staff of office. He was the Roman officer who walked before the magistrates bearing the bundle of sticks that meant their power.","g":"lictor, serjeant","h":"The picture: the officer who carries the bundle of rods."},"G4466":{"b":"The name means friend. Behind it lie words for pasture and for an associate or companion. Ragau was a patriarch, one of the ancestors of Abraham in the line after the flood.","g":"Ragau","h":"The picture: friend."},"G4467":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to act recklessly or wrongly, doing a thing the lazy, easy way. From cutting corners came the sense of a crime. Gallio said if it were a real wrong he would listen.","g":"crime","h":"The picture: the corner-cut deed."},"G4468":{"b":"The word first meant ease, doing a thing with no effort. It slid into meaning casual wickedness, villainy. Paul says Elymas is full of it, an easy hand at every kind of fraud.","g":"mischief","h":"The picture: taking the easy, crooked road."},"G4469":{"b":"Strong's says this is a curse word meaning O empty one, thou worthless. It comes from Aramaic. Picture a hollow vessel with nothing inside. To spit this at a brother, Jesus warns, answers to the court.","g":"Raca","h":"The picture: the empty vessel."},"G447":{"b":"Strong's: \"to let up, i.e. (literally) slacken.\" Picture a taut rope given slack. In the Philippi jail every prisoner's chains were loosed, the tension gone. Of a person it means to let go, to leave without support. I will never leave you, God promises.","g":"loose, leave","h":"The picture: a taut rope suddenly given slack."},"G4470":{"b":"The root means to tear or break apart. A rhakos is what is left, a rag, a torn scrap of cloth. Jesus says no one uses a scrap of new cloth to patch an old coat. The new pulls at the old and the tear gets bigger. The wrong patch ruins both.","g":"a rag, cloth","h":"The picture: a torn scrap of cloth."},"G4471":{"b":"The name comes from a word meaning a height, a high place. Ramah was a town in Israel, remembered as the place where weeping was heard for the children who were gone.","g":"Ramah","h":"The picture: a height."},"G4472":{"b":"The word means to sprinkle, to besprinkle. Moses sprinkled the people and the book with blood, the writer recalls. It is the priest flicking drops for cleansing. Our hearts are sprinkled clean from a guilty conscience.","g":"to sprinkle","h":"The picture: blood flicked in drops."},"G4473":{"b":"This is the word for sprinkling. Abbott points to the ceremonial sprinkling of blood for purification. Picture the priest flicking drops from his hand onto the people. To be sprinkled is to be marked clean by scattered blood.","g":"sprinkling","h":"The picture: drops of blood flicked from the hand."},"G4474":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this first meant to strike with a rod, then to hit someone across the face with the flat of the hand. Jesus says if a man slaps your right cheek, turn the other to him as well. Not to strike back but to offer the other side.","g":"to slap","h":"The picture: a slap across the face."},"G4475":{"b":"The root simply means to slap. Strong's adds the palm of the hand. This is the open-handed blow the guards give Jesus, and the one the officer gives him for how he answered the high priest. A strike with the bare hand.","g":"slap","h":"The picture: the flat of a hand across the face."},"G4476":{"b":"This is a needle, the kind you sew with. Abbott ties it to the word for sewing. Jesus says it is easier for a camel to go through the eye of a needle than for a rich man to enter the kingdom. Picture that tiny hole.","g":"needle","h":"The picture: the eye of a sewing needle."},"G4477":{"b":"This is a second Greek spelling of the name Rahab. Strong's tells us only that she was a Canaanitess, a woman of Canaan. So the picture is the woman herself, a foreigner whose name was written into Israel's own story.","g":"Rahab","h":"The picture: Rahab of Canaan."},"G4478":{"b":"The name comes from a word meaning a ewe, a female sheep. Rachel was the beloved wife of Jacob and mother of Joseph and Benjamin, a shepherd's daughter who watered her father's flock.","g":"Rachel","h":"The picture: a ewe."},"G4479":{"b":"The name means fettering by beauty, one who binds or captivates. Rebecca was the wife of Isaac and mother of Jacob and Esau, chosen at a well far from Isaac's home.","g":"Rebecca","h":"The picture: fettering by beauty."},"G448":{"b":"This is built from a word meaning gracious and favorable, cheerful as attractive, propitious, with a not in front. So it means merciless, no favor turned toward you. James warns that judgment will be without mercy to the one who showed none.","g":"without mercy","h":"The picture: a face with no favor in it."},"G4480":{"b":"Strong's says this was a \"four-wheeled carriage,\" a Gallic word for a riding wagon. Picture a heavy coach rolling on four wheels. So chariots are among the luxuries Babylon can no longer sell.","g":"carriage","h":"The picture: a four-wheeled wagon."},"G4481":{"b":"This is the name of an Egyptian idol mentioned by Stephen in Acts. Its meaning cannot be recovered with confidence from the Hebrew, so no clear word picture stands behind the name.","flat":1,"g":"Remphan","h":"No picture."},"G4482":{"b":"A primary word meaning simply to flow, as water runs. Picture a stream pouring out. Whoever believes in me, Jesus said, out of his heart will flow rivers of living water. Not a trickle but rivers, always moving.","g":"flow","h":"The picture: water running and flowing."},"G4483":{"b":"Strong's links this word for speaking to a word meaning to flow, as water runs, through the idea of pouring forth. Speech pours out of the mouth the way a stream runs down its channel. What is said flows out, poured forth into the air.","g":"speak, say","h":"The picture: words pouring out like water."},"G4484":{"b":"This is the name of Rhegium, a town on the Italian coast. Strong's says it is of Latin origin. It is only a place name, with nothing behind it to see. The ship touched there on the way to Rome.","flat":1,"g":"Rhegium","h":"No picture."},"G4485":{"b":"This word comes from the word to break or wreck. Abbott-Smith lands it on that which is torn, and in the New Testament, ruin. The house without a foundation did not lean. It tore apart and fell, and great was its collapse.","g":"ruin","h":"The picture: a house cracking apart and crashing down."},"G4486":{"b":"This word means to rend, to break asunder. New wine bursts old skins with it, ripping them wide. It can also mean the voice breaking forth in a shout. Something held under pressure until it tears open.","g":"break, burst","h":"The picture: old wineskins bursting open."},"G4487":{"b":"This comes from the verb to utter, to speak. A rhema is a word actually said, breath shaped into sound, not ink on a page. So man lives by every rhema from God's mouth, every living word he speaks, not by bread alone.","g":"word, utterance","h":"The picture: a word spoken out loud."},"G4488":{"b":"This is a name and nothing more. Strong's traces it to Hebrew. It marks an ancestor in Jesus' family tree. A name is a label for a person, so there is no image hidden behind it to picture.","flat":1,"g":"Rhesa","h":"No picture."},"G4489":{"b":"The root means to utter, to speak or say. A rhetor is a public speaker, here a lawyer brought in to argue the case. The priests hire Tertullus, this speaker, to accuse Paul before the governor. The word is the man on his feet, making the speech.","g":"orator","h":"The picture: a hired speaker rising to plead."},"G449":{"b":"This puts \"not\" before nipto, to wash the hands. Aniptos means unwashed. The dispute is whether eating with unrinsed hands defiles a person. Jesus says the dirt on the hands is not what makes a heart unclean.","g":"unwashed","h":"The picture: hands that have not been rinsed."},"G4490":{"b":"From rheo, to utter or speak, this means said in stated terms, spelled right out, leaving no doubt. Paul says the Spirit expressly warns that in later times some will depart from the faith.","g":"expressly","h":"The picture: said out loud in plain words."},"G4491":{"b":"The word means a literal root. Abbott-Smith says it is then used of cause, origin, source. So it is what feeds a thing from below and out of sight. A family root. The hidden source of good or of evil.","g":"root","h":"The picture: the root under the plant."},"G4492":{"b":"A plant sends its roots down into the soil to stand firm. This word means to cause to take root, to fix in place. Paul asks that people be rooted in love, held the way a tree is held. Not floating, but anchored.","g":"root, establish","h":"The picture: a plant sending down roots."},"G4493":{"b":"The root means to fling with a quick toss. Abbott-Smith lists the flapping of wings, the flight of a javelin, the twinkling of an eye. That fast. That is how quickly Paul says we will be changed.","g":"twinkling","h":"The picture: the flick of an eyelid."},"G4494":{"b":"The word first meant to fan a fire, to whip up a breeze with a fan or bellows. Then it meant to whip the sea into waves. James pairs it with wind: the doubter is a wave fanned up and heaved about.","g":"toss","h":"The picture: a fan whipping up a fire."},"G4496":{"b":"Strong's says it means to fling, \"with a quick toss.\" It is a fast throw, quicker than a careful hurl. Judas flung down the silver coins. Sick people were laid down at Jesus' feet to be healed.","g":"throw, fling","h":"The picture: a quick toss."},"G4497":{"b":"The name means a people has enlarged. It joins a word meaning to broaden with a word for a people. Roboam was Solomon's son, the king under whom the kingdom of Israel split in two.","g":"Rehoboam","h":"The picture: a people has enlarged."},"G4498":{"b":"Strong's says the name probably comes from a word for a rose. Rhoda is the servant girl who hears Peter knocking and, in her joy, runs off and leaves him standing at the gate.","g":"Rhoda","h":"The picture: a rose."},"G4499":{"b":"Strong's traces this island's name to the rose. So Rhodes is the rose-island. Paul's ship came there straight from Cos, on the last run toward Jerusalem.","g":"Rhodes","h":"The picture: the island of roses."},"G45":{"b":"The word comes from a root for a bend, \"an arm (as curved).\" An anchor is the hooked iron that bites the seabed and holds. Hope, says Hebrews, is an anchor of the soul, sure and steadfast, gripping the ground behind the veil.","g":"anchor","h":"The picture: the hooked iron that grips the seabed."},"G450":{"b":"Abbott lists the plain uses first. Rising from lying down. Rising from sitting. Getting up to leave.\n\nThe same ordinary word is used of the dead. They get up, the way you get up in the morning.","g":"rise, stand up","h":"The picture: getting up off the ground."},"G4500":{"b":"Abbott traces this to the whistling of an arrow. So it means with a rushing, whizzing sound, like roaring flames. Peter says the heavens will pass away with that roar, and the elements melt with fervent heat.","g":"with a crash","h":"The picture: the whistle of an arrow through the air."},"G4501":{"b":"Abbott calls it a large broad sword, the kind the Thracians carried. Not a small dagger but a long, heavy blade. Simeon told Mary a rhomphaia would run through her own soul. The great sword, turned on a mother's heart.","g":"sword","h":"The picture: a great Thracian broadsword."},"G4502":{"b":"The name joins two words: to see, and a son. It sounds like behold, a son. Reuben was Jacob's firstborn, the son Leah named when she saw the Lord had noticed her.","g":"Reuben","h":"The picture: behold, a son."},"G4503":{"b":"The name means friend. Behind it lies a word for a female companion or associate. Ruth was the Moabite widow who clung to Naomi, gleaned in Boaz's field, and became great-grandmother of King David.","g":"Ruth","h":"The picture: friend."},"G4504":{"b":"The name is Latin. Strong's says it means red. It was a common nickname, likely for red hair or a ruddy face. Mark names Rufus as a son of the man made to carry Jesus' cross, a real person his readers knew.","g":"Rufus","h":"The picture: Red, a man's nickname."},"G4505":{"b":"In older Greek this word meant the rush or force of a moving body. Later it settled into a narrow road, a lane, a street. Jesus says do not sound a trumpet in the streets when you give. Picture the crowded lane where everyone would see.","g":"street, lane","h":"The picture: a narrow crowded lane."},"G4506":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means to draw to oneself, and so to rescue. Picture reaching into danger and dragging a person toward you, out of the water or the fire. That is the word for God delivering us from evil.","g":"rescue, deliver","h":"The picture: pulling someone to yourself."},"G4507":{"b":"The root is the plain word for dirty, grimy, shabby. Here it is moral dirt, the grime on a life. James says strip it off like filthy clothes and take in the planted word instead.","g":"filthiness","h":"The picture: grime on a life."},"G4508":{"b":"From a word meaning dirt. Abbott pictures old, shabby clothing, the grimy garment of a poor man. In James it is the dirty clothes of the visitor who gets pushed aside. The word is plain grime.","g":"dirty, filthy","h":"The picture: dirty, shabby clothes."},"G4509":{"b":"The word means dirt, filth. Peter uses it of the bodily grime a bath removes. He says baptism is not about washing that off. It reaches deeper, to a clean conscience before God.","g":"filth","h":"The picture: grime washed off the skin."},"G451":{"b":"The name means favored. Behind it lies the idea of grace freely shown. Anna was the elderly prophetess who never left the temple, and who gave thanks when she saw the infant Jesus.","g":"Anna","h":"The picture: favored."},"G4510":{"b":"The word comes from the word for dirt. Abbott-Smith gives \"to make filthy.\" Picture something growing grimy and stained the longer it is left. So the warning stands, let the one who is filthy be filthy still.","g":"to be filthy","h":"The picture: cloth caked with dirt."},"G4511":{"b":"The root means to flow, as water runs. This is a flowing, an issue. A woman had a flow of blood for twelve years and no one could stop it. She touched Jesus' cloak, and at once the flowing dried up. The word is the leak that would not close.","g":"issue, flow","h":"The picture: blood flowing and not stopping."},"G4512":{"b":"Strong's calls it a fold that draws together, a wrinkle, the kind on skin or on cloth. Paul says Christ will present the church without spot or wrinkle, smooth and unblemished.","g":"wrinkle","h":"The picture: a wrinkle in the cloth."},"G4514":{"b":"The name traces to Rome, whose very word means strength. A Rhōmaios is a Roman, and the title carried weight. Paul plays it like a card, I am a Rhōmaios, and the soldiers who bound him for the lash draw back afraid. Citizenship as armor.","g":"Roman","h":"The picture: citizenship worn as armor."},"G4515":{"b":"This word means in Latin, the language of Rome. John says the sign above Jesus was written three ways, and this was the ruler's own tongue. It comes from the name Rome. The empire posted its verdict in its own words.","g":"in Latin","h":"The picture: the charge over the cross, spelled out in Latin."},"G4516":{"b":"Strong's says the name of Rome comes from a word meaning strength. The city's very name carried the sound of power. So when Paul longs to reach Rome, the name in his mouth is the name of might, and he goes there in chains.","g":"Rome","h":"The picture: strength."},"G4517":{"b":"The word means to strengthen, to be strong. Greeks ended their letters with it the way we say goodbye, but underneath it says 'be strong.' The council's letter to Antioch closes on it.","g":"farewell, be strong","h":"The picture: a strong, healthy body."},"G4518":{"b":"This is an Aramaic word spoken straight from the cross, meaning you have forsaken me. It is not built from smaller Greek parts, so there is no older image inside it, only the cry itself, torn out of Psalm 22.","flat":1,"g":"you have forsaken me","h":"No picture."},"G4519":{"b":"This is a Hebrew word carried straight into Greek, meaning armies or hosts. The Lord of Sabaoth is the Lord of armies, the ranks of heaven at his command. James warns that the cries of the cheated reached the ears of that commander.","g":"hosts, armies","h":"The picture: ranks of armies."},"G452":{"b":"The name means Jah has favored. It joins a word for showing grace with Jah, a short form of the Lord's name. Annas was a high priest before whom Jesus was brought on the night of his trial.","g":"Annas","h":"The picture: Jah has favored."},"G4520":{"b":"This is built from the Sabbath, the day of rest when all work stops. It means a keeping of sabbath, a sabbath rest. A rest still remains for God's people, when their labor is finally laid down.","g":"sabbath rest","h":"The picture: the day the work stops."},"G4521":{"b":"The word comes from a root meaning to repose, to rest. The Sabbath is the day of weekly rest from ordinary work, set apart from the beginning when God rested from all he had made.","g":"Sabbath","h":"The picture: repose."},"G4522":{"b":"This is a dragnet, a great seine hauled through the sea that sweeps up every kind of fish. Jesus says the kingdom is like this net. Picture a long net dragged to shore, heavy and full.","g":"dragnet","h":"The picture: the dragnet hauled to shore."},"G4523":{"b":"Strong's traces the name to Zadok, Sadoc, an Israelite, the priest whose line held the temple. The Sadducees were his heirs, the priestly aristocracy. They ran the temple, denied the resurrection, and clashed hard with Jesus over both.","g":"Sadducee","h":"The picture: the heirs of Zadok the priest."},"G4524":{"b":"The name means just. It comes from a word meaning to be righteous or right. Sadoc appears among the ancestors of Jesus in the genealogy that Matthew records.","g":"Zadok","h":"The picture: just."},"G4525":{"b":"The plain sense is a dog wagging its tail to fawn. From there it stretched to mean swaying or unsettling a person, shaking them loose. Paul says no one should be moved and shaken by these troubles.","g":"shake, disturb","h":"The picture: a dog wagging its tail."},"G4526":{"b":"Sackcloth is a coarse cloth, usually made of hair, worn as a sign of grief. Jesus says if the miracles done in these towns had been done in Tyre, they would have repented in sackcloth and ashes. Scratchy mourning cloth against the skin.","g":"sackcloth","h":"The picture: rough hair-cloth worn in grief."},"G4527":{"b":"The name comes from a word meaning a missile of attack, a weapon thrown or hurled. Sala was a patriarch, one of the ancestors of Abraham in the line after the flood.","g":"Shelah","h":"The picture: a missile of attack."},"G4528":{"b":"The name means I have asked God. It joins a word meaning to inquire or ask with a word for strength or God. Salathiel stands in the family line of Jesus, after the exile to Babylon.","g":"Shealtiel","h":"The picture: I have asked God."},"G4529":{"b":"Strong's traces the name to a word for the sea's billow, the surge that breaks on the beach. Salamis is the seaside city of Cyprus where Paul and Barnabas first preach the word.","g":"Salamis","h":"The picture: surf surging on the shore."},"G453":{"b":"This is not joined to a word for using the mind, for thinking a thing through. The foolish person here leaves the mind switched off. Jesus calls the two on the road slow of heart. Paul: O foolish Galatians, who has bewitched you.","g":"foolish","h":"The picture: the mind left idle."},"G4530":{"b":"Strong's traces this place name to a word meaning to waver, agitate, rock. Abbott adds nothing but the location. So the picture the source offers is shaking ground, a place whose name it links to rocking. John was baptizing near Salim.","g":"Salim","h":"The picture: unsteady ground that rocks."},"G4531":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the proper sense is of the action of wind, storm, etc., to agitate, shake. Think of a reed bent by the wind, or a house rocked in a gale. That which cannot be shaken is what stands when everything else is tossed.","g":"shake","h":"The picture: tossed by wind and storm."},"G4532":{"b":"The name means peaceful. It comes from a word meaning complete or whole. Salem was the city where Melchizedek reigned as priest-king, later understood as Jerusalem, the city of peace.","g":"Salem","h":"The picture: peaceful."},"G4533":{"b":"The name means investiture, the putting on of a garment. It comes from a word for a dress or clothing. Salmon was the father of Boaz, an ancestor of King David and of Jesus.","g":"Salmon","h":"The picture: investiture."},"G4534":{"b":"Abbott names this a promontory of Crete, a headland of rock reaching into the sea. That is the picture. Paul's ship sailed slowly under Crete, over against Salmone, as the wind fought them.","g":"Salmone","h":"The picture: a cape of rock reaching into the sea."},"G4535":{"b":"Abbott says it is the tossing, the rolling swell of the sea, the heave of an earthquake. Picture waves rising and pitching. The sea and the waves will roar, Jesus said, and men's hearts will fail them for fear.","g":"wave","h":"The picture: the heaving swell of the sea."},"G4536":{"b":"Abbott says a trumpet, used in war and in religious ceremonies, the brass horn that cut through noise. Paul hangs the resurrection on one, at the last salpinx the dead rise. The Lord descends with the trump of God. And seven of them sound the end.","g":"trumpet","h":"The picture: the brass horn that cuts through."},"G4537":{"b":"This comes from the word for a trumpet. Abbott-Smith says it means \"to sound a trumpet.\" In Revelation the angels blow, and Paul says the trumpet will sound at the last day.","g":"sound a trumpet","h":"The picture: blowing a trumpet."},"G4538":{"b":"The word comes from a verb meaning to sound a trumpet blast. Abbott-Smith gives \"a trumpeter.\" Picture a man lifting the horn to his lips. So the sound of trumpeters will never be heard in the city again.","g":"trumpeter","h":"The picture: a trumpeter raising his horn."},"G4539":{"b":"Salome is a name. The sources give its Hebrew root but do not translate it here. They tell us only that she was an Israelite woman, one who followed Jesus. There is nothing in the file to picture behind the name.","flat":1,"g":"Salome","h":"No picture."},"G454":{"b":"The word is \"no\" joined to the word for mind, without understanding. It swings from folly to blind rage, thinking gone. Luke uses it for the teachers who watched Jesus heal on the Sabbath and were filled with mindless fury.","g":"folly, rage","h":"The picture: the mind switched off with rage."},"G4540":{"b":"The name means watch-station, a place of watching or guarding. Samaria was the capital city of the northern kingdom of Israel, and the whole region around it kept the name.","g":"Samaria","h":"The picture: watch-station."},"G4541":{"b":"This means an inhabitant of Samaria, a people the Jews despised. Yet Jesus makes one the hero of his parable and heals a Samaritan leper who alone returns to give thanks. The outsider who does right.","g":"Samaritan","h":"The picture: the man from Samaria."},"G4542":{"b":"The word means a Samaritan woman. John gives her the whole of chapter four, the woman who came to Jacob's well at noon and found Jesus asking her for a drink. One word for a region's daughter, and one of his longest conversations.","g":"Samaritan woman","h":"The picture: the woman at the well."},"G4543":{"b":"The name joins two lands, Samos of Thrace. It is an island standing off the Thracian coast. So the picture is a peak in the sea. Paul's ship ran a straight course to Samothrace on the way to Macedonia.","g":"an island","h":"The picture: Samos out in the sea of Thrace."},"G4544":{"b":"This is Samos, an island in the sea, a point the ship reached on its way south. It is a bare place name of uncertain origin, so there is nothing here to picture.","flat":1,"g":"Samos","h":"No picture."},"G4545":{"b":"The name means heard of God. It joins a word meaning to hear with a word for strength or God. Samuel was the prophet Hannah bore after prayer, saying she had asked him of the Lord.","g":"Samuel","h":"The picture: heard of God."},"G4546":{"b":"The name means sunlight. It comes from the word for the sun. Samson was the strong man of Israel, a Nazirite judge whose strength lay in his uncut hair until Delilah betrayed him.","g":"Samson","h":"The picture: sunlight."},"G4547":{"b":"Strong's calls it a slipper or sole-pad. A sandal is just a piece of leather under the foot, held on with straps. When Jesus sends the disciples out he lets them wear these, and nothing else. Travel light.","g":"sandal","h":"The picture: a flat sole strapped to the foot."},"G4548":{"b":"Strong's says simply \"a plank.\" Abbott says a board, plank. It is one flat piece of a ship's timber. When the boat broke apart, men grabbed a plank and rode it in to the beach.","g":"plank, board","h":"The picture: a loose plank of wood."},"G4549":{"b":"The name means asked. It comes from a word meaning to inquire or ask for. Saul was the Jewish name of the apostle Paul, and before him the name of Israel's first king.","g":"Saul","h":"The picture: asked."},"G455":{"b":"Abbott's first example is a door or gate. Then tombs, then heaven, then a mouth.\n\nHe notes that opening the mouth toward someone meant speaking freely. Nothing held back.","g":"open","h":"The picture: a door swinging open."},"G4550":{"b":"Strong's: \"rotten, i.e. worthless.\" Abbott uses it of trees and fruit. A bad tree gives rotten fruit, and rotten fish are thrown out. From spoiled food the word moves to worthless, harmful talk.","g":"rotten, bad","h":"The picture: rotten fruit."},"G4551":{"b":"This woman's name comes from the word for a sapphire, the blue jewel. With her husband Ananias she lied about the price of land and fell dead. A name bright as a gem, over a heart that was not honest.","g":"Sapphira","h":"The picture: a blue sapphire gem."},"G4552":{"b":"The word means sapphire. Abbott-Smith notes it may be lapis lazuli. Picture a stone of deep blue, flecked with gold. So the second foundation of the city wall was sapphire.","g":"sapphire","h":"The picture: a deep blue stone."},"G4553":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says a plaited rope, then a hamper, a basket made of ropes. Paul was lowered down the city wall in one of these, through a window, dropped to the ground to slip away from the guards.","g":"basket","h":"The picture: a big basket woven out of rope."},"G4554":{"b":"Sardis is a place, the chief city of Lydia. Strong's says the name is of uncertain derivation, so no one knows what it is built from. It is a spot on the map, nothing inside to see.","flat":1,"g":"Sardis","h":"No picture."},"G4555":{"b":"This is a gemstone, the sardine, a deep red stone. Strong's calls it a gem, so called. John sees God on the throne with the look of this stone, red like fire. Picture a blood-red jewel.","g":"sardine gem","h":"The picture: a blood-red jewel."},"G4557":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this is \"a stone marked by the red of the sard and the white of the onyx.\" Picture layered bands, one blood-red, one milk-white. So sardonyx was the fifth foundation of the city wall.","g":"sardonyx","h":"The picture: a stone banded red and white."},"G4558":{"b":"The name means refinement. It comes from a word meaning to fuse or smelt metal. Sarepta was the town where the widow fed Elijah, and her jar of flour and oil did not run out.","g":"Zarephath","h":"The picture: refinement."},"G4559":{"b":"From sarx, flesh, the meat stripped off an animal. Sarkikos means belonging to that flesh, run by the body and its appetites. Paul calls the quarreling church still carnal, still driven by the meat and not by the Spirit.","g":"fleshly, carnal","h":"The picture: the meat off the bone."},"G456":{"b":"The root means to be a house-builder, and \"again\" sits in front. So it is raising up what has fallen. God promises to build again the tent of David that has fallen down, setting the collapsed house back on its feet.","g":"rebuild","h":"The picture: raising a fallen house back up."},"G4560":{"b":"The root is the word for flesh, the meat of an animal stripped of its skin. The ending marks what a thing is made of. So this word means made of flesh. Paul calls people this when he means soft and weak, still mere meat.","g":"fleshly","h":"The picture: made of meat."},"G4561":{"b":"Strong's begins here: flesh as stripped of the skin, the meat of an animal.\n\nFrom there it becomes the body, and then human nature with its weaknesses. Abbott-Smith notes the sense of a nature open to feeling and desire.","g":"flesh","h":"The picture: meat with the skin taken off."},"G4562":{"b":"The name means tendril, the curling shoot of a vine. It comes from a word meaning to intwine. Saruch was a patriarch, one of the ancestors of Abraham after the flood.","g":"Serug","h":"The picture: tendril."},"G4563":{"b":"Strong's says the word behind this is a broom. The verb is to sweep. The woman who lost a coin lit a lamp and swept the whole house until she found it. The word is the broom going across the floor.","g":"sweep","h":"The picture: a broom across the floor."},"G4564":{"b":"The name comes from a word meaning a mistress, a noble lady who rules. Sarah was the wife of Abraham, promised a son in old age and named mother of nations by God.","g":"Sarah","h":"The picture: a mistress."},"G4565":{"b":"The name comes from a word meaning to be straight or even. Sharon was a broad, level plain along the coast of Israel, known for its flowers and rich pastureland.","g":"Sharon","h":"The picture: level and even."},"G4567":{"b":"Abbott says the word means the adversary, and notes it came into Greek from Hebrew and Aramaic.\n\nSo Satan is less a name than a job description. The one who stands against you.","g":"Satan","h":"The picture: the adversary."},"G4568":{"b":"A saton is a dry measure borrowed from Hebrew, about a peck and a half of flour. In the parable the woman works yeast into three of them, a huge batch of dough. The measure tells you how much bread is coming.","g":"measure","h":"The picture: a basket holding about a peck and a half."},"G4569":{"b":"This is Saul, the Jewish name of the apostle Paul. It is a name only, carried over from Hebrew. There is nothing behind it to picture or to see.","flat":1,"g":"Saul","h":"No picture."},"G457":{"b":"This comes from the word to open. It means an opening. Paul uses it of his mouth, praying that words would be given him when he opens his mouth to make known the gospel.","g":"opening","h":"The picture: a mouth opening to speak."},"G4570":{"b":"Sbennymi is to put out a fire, to quench it. Faith quenched the violence of the flames. The shield of faith stops the fiery darts and snuffs them out. Do not quench the Spirit, Paul says. Do not douse the flame.","g":"quench","h":"The picture: putting out a fire."},"G4573":{"b":"Abbott traces this to a word for reverential awe. It is awe that bends the body low. So to sebazomai is to bow in worship. Paul says the nations bowed this way to created things instead of the Creator.","g":"worship","h":"The picture: awe that bows the head."},"G4574":{"b":"The root means to venerate, to adore. This word is the thing that adoring lands on: an object of worship, the idol, the altar, whatever people bow to. Paul looked over the objects of worship in Athens and pointed to one altar left for a god unknown.","g":"object of worship","h":"The picture: the idol or altar people bow down to."},"G4575":{"b":"This word comes from a word meaning to venerate and adore. Sebastos is the revered one, the august. It became the Roman Emperor's own title, Augustus, the man the world was told to bow before. Paul was sent to stand there.","g":"Augustus","h":"The picture: the one the world bows before."},"G4576":{"b":"This word means to worship, to revere. Strong's says it comes from an apparently primary verb, which means it does not come from anything else. Despite being a worship word, it hides no picture. There is nothing to see.","flat":1,"g":"worship, revere","h":"No picture."},"G4577":{"b":"The word is a cord, a chain, something that binds or drags. Strong's links it to a root meaning to trail. Peter says God bound the fallen angels in chains of darkness, held for judgment.","g":"chain","h":"The picture: a heavy chain."},"G4578":{"b":"Abbott says the word means a shaking, a commotion. It is used for a storm tossing the sea and for the ground quaking. Our word \"seismic\" comes straight from it.","g":"earthquake","h":"The picture: a shaking."},"G4579":{"b":"This is to rock, to shake back and forth. It is the root behind our \"seismic.\" The earth seio when Jesus died, and the rocks split. The whole city was seio, shaken, when he rode in, everyone asking who is this.","g":"to shake","h":"The picture: the ground shaking."},"G458":{"b":"The word is law with a not in front, no law. Anomia is life lived as if no rule binds you, each doing what is right in his own eyes. Jesus turns away the workers of anomia, busy in his name but a law to themselves.","g":"lawlessness","h":"The picture: life with no law over it."},"G4580":{"b":"This is the name Secundus, a Christian who went with Paul. It is Latin for second, likely a birth-order name, and labels a person, so there is nothing here to picture.","flat":1,"g":"Secundus","h":"No picture."},"G4581":{"b":"Seleucia is a name, a port city in Syria. It marks where Paul and Barnabas sailed from on their first journey. The sources give it no meaning to open, so there is nothing here to see.","flat":1,"g":"Seleucia","h":"No picture."},"G4582":{"b":"The moon. Strong's ties the name to brightness. Peter quotes Joel, the sun to darkness and the moon to blood before the great day of the Lord. The night light that fails when the end nears.","g":"moon","h":"The picture: the moon turned to blood."},"G4583":{"b":"The root is the moon. People once thought the moon could strike a person and bring on fits, so this word means moonstruck. Matthew uses it for a boy who falls in seizures. They named the illness after the moon they blamed. Jesus healed the boy the moon could not touch.","g":"to be moonstruck","h":"The picture: struck by the moon."},"G4584":{"b":"The name means famous. Behind it lies a word for something heard, a report or renown. Semei appears among the ancestors of Jesus in the family line that Luke records.","g":"Shimei","h":"The picture: famous."},"G4585":{"b":"The word means fine wheaten flour, the finest sifted grain. Abbott-Smith gives \"fine wheaten flour.\" Picture soft pale flour running through the fingers. So fine flour is one more good the merchants weep over.","g":"fine flour","h":"The picture: fine white flour."},"G4586":{"b":"Built from a word meaning to revere. Abbott gives grave, dignified, worthy of respect. Deacons must be semnos, men whose bearing makes others take them seriously, First Timothy 3:8. Whatever is honorable, Paul says, dwell on it.","g":"honorable, grave","h":"The picture: bearing that commands respect."},"G4587":{"b":"Built from the word for honorable. Abbott gives gravity. An overseer must keep his children submissive with all semnotes, a dignity that carries weight, First Timothy 3:4. The seriousness of bearing that makes others respect a home and a life.","g":"gravity, dignity","h":"The picture: weight that makes others respect you."},"G4588":{"b":"Sergius is a name, a Roman, the proconsul of Cyprus who wanted to hear the word. The sources give it no meaning to unfold. There is no picture behind it, only the name of a man.","flat":1,"g":"Sergius","h":"No picture."},"G4589":{"b":"The name means put or substituted. It comes from a word meaning to place or set. Seth was the son granted to Adam and Eve in place of Abel, whom Cain had killed.","g":"Seth","h":"The picture: put, i.e. substituted."},"G459":{"b":"Strong's builds this from \"a negative particle\" and the word for law. Abbott writes it plainly: \"(ἀ. neg., νόμος).\" Take the law away and this is what is left. It names a person the law does not hold.","g":"lawless","h":"The picture: no law."},"G4590":{"b":"The name means name. It comes from a word for an appellation, the name by which someone is called. Shem was a son of Noah, carried through the flood in the ark and father of many nations.","g":"Shem","h":"The picture: name."},"G4591":{"b":"The root is a sign. To signify is to give a sign that points beyond itself. Jesus said this signifying by what kind of death he would die. Agabus signaled a coming famine. A marker held up so you can read what is coming.","g":"signify","h":"The picture: holding up a sign."},"G4592":{"b":"Abbott says it is a sign, mark, token, used of what distinguishes a person or thing from others.\n\nHis first example is Judas. The kiss was the agreed mark, so the soldiers knew which man to take.","g":"sign","h":"The picture: a mark that tells one from another."},"G4593":{"b":"The root is semeion, a sign or mark. This means to set a mark on a thing so you notice it and keep it in mind. Paul says if any man will not obey the letter, mark that man and keep away from him.","g":"mark, note","h":"The picture: putting a mark on someone."},"G4594":{"b":"The word hides the word for day inside it, the span from dawn to dark. Semeron is this one, today, the daylight you are standing in now. So today this scripture is fulfilled, and today you will be with me in paradise, both land on this very day.","g":"today","h":"The picture: this day, from dawn to dark."},"G4595":{"b":"This word means to rot, to putrefy, the way meat or fruit turns and starts to stink. James says the riches you hoarded have already rotted. The wealth you clutched is decaying in your hands.","g":"be corrupted","h":"The picture: meat left to rot."},"G4596":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the word comes from the Seres, a people of India who first sold silk. It means \"silk, silken.\" Picture bolts of smooth shining cloth. So Babylon's merchants mourn that no one buys their silk anymore.","g":"silk","h":"The picture: smooth silk cloth."},"G4597":{"b":"The word means a moth, the clothes moth that eats through cloth. Jesus warns against storing treasure where moth and rust destroy it. The moth works quietly, and the fine garment is ruined from the inside.","g":"moth","h":"The picture: the moth in the clothes."},"G4598":{"b":"Built from two words, moth and to eat, this is cloth chewed full of holes by moths. James says the fine clothes you stored up are moth-eaten. Your treasure is quietly being eaten alive.","g":"motheaten","h":"The picture: cloth chewed full of holes by moths."},"G4599":{"b":"The root means strength, and Strong's links it to the word for standing. So this is putting strength in, making a person stand steady. Peter says after a little suffering God himself will do this for you.","g":"strengthen","h":"The picture: bracing someone so they stand firm."},"G46":{"b":"The word puts not in front of the word for a cloth-dresser, the worker who shrinks and finishes new cloth. So it means cloth still raw, not yet shrunk. Jesus says no one sews such a patch on an old coat. When it shrinks it tears away and makes the hole worse.","g":"new (cloth)","h":"The picture: new cloth not yet shrunk."},"G460":{"b":"The word means without law, lawlessly. Paul uses it of the nations who never had Moses: all who sinned without the law will also perish without the law. It pictures a life with no rulebook overhead, and that is no shelter from judgment.","g":"lawlessly","h":"The picture: with no law over you."},"G4600":{"b":"Siagon is the jawbone, the cheek, the side of the face. Jesus says when someone strikes you on the one cheek, turn to him the other. The word points to the very spot where the blow lands. He tells you to offer it again.","g":"cheek, jaw","h":"The picture: the side of the face."},"G4601":{"b":"From the word for silence. To be silent, to hold your peace, and also to keep a thing secret. The crowd tries to trap Jesus with a question and cannot, so they fall silent. A hush that stops the mouth.","g":"keep silent","h":"The picture: the room falls silent."},"G4602":{"b":"Strong's traces this to a word for hushing, the sound hist or hush. Silence here is not empty air. It is a crowd going still when a hand is raised. In Revelation, heaven itself falls quiet for a while.","g":"silence","h":"The picture: a finger to the lips."},"G4603":{"b":"The root is iron. This word means made of iron, the hard grey metal that does not bend. The prison gate of iron opened by itself for Peter. Christ rules the nations with a rod of iron. Strong and unyielding.","g":"of iron","h":"The picture: the hard grey metal."},"G4604":{"b":"The word means iron. Abbott-Smith gives simply \"iron.\" Picture the hard grey metal, heavy and cold in the hand. So iron was one more cargo the fallen city can no longer sell.","g":"iron","h":"The picture: a bar of iron."},"G4605":{"b":"The name means fishery, a place of fishing. Sidon was an ancient coastal city of the Phoenicians, often named alongside Tyre in the Bible as a center of trade.","g":"Sidon","h":"The picture: fishery."},"G4606":{"b":"The root is Sidon, a place in Palestine. This word marks a person who belongs to it. Luke recalls how, in a great famine, God sent Elijah past all the widows of Israel to help one woman of Sidon instead.","g":"of Sidon","h":"The picture: a person from the town of Sidon."},"G4607":{"b":"This is a Latin word, from sica, a dagger carried under their clothing. The Sicarii were assassins who hid a short blade in their robes, slipped close in a crowd, and struck. The commander asks if Paul is one of them. The word names the weapon.","g":"assassin","h":"The picture: a dagger hidden under the cloak."},"G4608":{"b":"This is a borrowed word for intensely fermented liquor, the drink that makes a man drunk. The angel says John the Baptist must never touch wine or strong drink. He is set apart from the cup all his life.","g":"strong drink","h":"The picture: strong fermented drink."},"G4609":{"b":"Silas is the short form of Silvanus, which Strong's reads as silvan, of the woods. He is Paul's road companion, the man beside him when the Philippian jail shook. Beaten and chained, the two of them sang hymns to God at midnight.","g":"Silas","h":"The picture: the man who sang in the jail."},"G461":{"b":"The word joins up and straight. It means to set upright again, to restore. The woman bent double for eighteen years is straightened and stands tall. Hebrews says lift up the drooping hands and weak knees. A crooked thing made straight.","g":"make straight","h":"The picture: straightening a bent back upright."},"G4610":{"b":"This is Silvanus, the same man as Silas. Strong's says the name is Latin and means \"silvan,\" of the forest, of the woods. So the name itself carries trees in it. He carried Peter's letter and stood beside Paul.","g":"Silvanus","h":"The picture: a man of the woods."},"G4611":{"b":"The name means rill, a small running stream. Behind it lies the idea of water sent out. Siloam was a pool in Jerusalem where Jesus sent a blind man to wash, and he came back seeing.","g":"Siloam","h":"The picture: rill."},"G4612":{"b":"This word, borrowed from Latin, means a half-girding, a narrow cloth tied around the waist. A workman's apron. Cloths and aprons that had touched Paul were carried to the sick, and they were healed.","g":"apron","h":"The picture: the workman's apron."},"G4613":{"b":"The name means hearing. It comes from a word meaning to hear intelligently, to listen and heed. It was a very common name, worn by nine different men in the New Testament, including Simon Peter.","g":"Simon","h":"The picture: hearing."},"G4614":{"b":"This is Sinai, and Strong's names it \"a mountain in Arabia.\" A real peak in the desert, where God came down in fire and gave the law to Moses. Paul makes the mountain stand for the old covenant of law.","g":"Sinai","h":"The picture: the mountain where the law came down."},"G4615":{"b":"This is the mustard plant, grown from the smallest seed a farmer sowed. Faith like a grain of sinapi, Jesus says, moves mountains. The seed is a speck, yet it becomes a bush where the birds can nest.","g":"mustard","h":"The picture: the tiny mustard seed."},"G4616":{"b":"Abbott: fine linen cloth, the kind used for wrapping dead bodies. Joseph took Jesus down and wound him in it. A young man once wore one and left it behind to run away naked. A clean sheet of linen.","g":"linen","h":"The picture: a white linen sheet."},"G4617":{"b":"Abbott builds it from a word for a sieve. To sift is to shake grain so the chaff falls through the mesh. Satan wants to sift you like wheat, Jesus told Peter, shaking you hard to see what holds.","g":"sift","h":"The picture: grain shaken in a sieve."},"G4618":{"b":"The word is built from grain. It means grain-fed, an animal fattened up for a feast. When the lost son comes home the father says bring the fatted calf and kill it. The best-fed beast in the yard, saved for a celebration.","g":"fatted","h":"The picture: the calf fattened on grain."},"G4619":{"b":"The root is the word for grain, especially wheat. This word is an animal stuffed with grain until it is fat and ready to eat. In Matthew 22:4 the king says his oxen and fatlings are killed for the wedding feast.","g":"fatling","h":"The picture: the calf fattened on grain."},"G462":{"b":"The word is hósios, reverent rightness before God, with the not bolted onto the front. Unholy, profane. Paul lists it among the traits of the last days: lovers of self and money, ungrateful, unholy. Nothing in them bends the knee to the sacred.","g":"unholy","h":"The picture: no reverence left."},"G4620":{"b":"This word joins grain and measure. Abbott-Smith gives it as a measured portion of food. The faithful manager is the one his master leaves in charge to hand out each servant's ration of grain at the right time.","g":"portion of food","h":"The picture: a measured ration of grain doled out."},"G4621":{"b":"Strong's says it is of uncertain derivation. Abbott-Smith says it means wheat or corn. It just names the grain. There is nothing hidden behind the word.","flat":1,"g":"wheat, grain","h":"No picture."},"G4622":{"b":"The name comes from a word for a monumental or guiding pillar, a landmark. Zion was a hill of Jerusalem, and the name came to stand for the whole city and the people of God.","g":"Zion","h":"The picture: a guiding pillar."},"G4623":{"b":"Strong's says this word can mean to be calm, like quiet water. It means to be silent, to hush. Jesus spoke it to the storm on the lake: be still. And the wind and the water went quiet.","g":"be silent","h":"The picture: still, quiet water."},"G4624":{"b":"Abbott says the word properly means to put a snare or stumbling-block in the way. Strong's says to trip up.\n\nMaking someone fall is not an accident here. Something was placed there on purpose.","g":"cause to stumble","h":"The picture: a stick set in the path."},"G4625":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it properly means the bait-stick of a trap. That is the little stick that springs the snare when an animal touches it. So a stumbling block is the hidden thing that trips you and shuts the trap.","g":"stumbling block","h":"The picture: the trigger stick of a trap."},"G4626":{"b":"The word simply means to dig. The wise builder digs deep to lay his foundation on rock. The gardener digs around the barren fig tree to give it one more year. The steward admits he is not strong enough to dig.","g":"dig","h":"The picture: breaking ground with a spade."},"G4627":{"b":"This word comes from a word meaning to dig or scoop out. Skaphe is a small boat, a skiff, once a log hollowed by hand. It is the ship's little boat the sailors let down and then cut loose in the storm.","g":"boat","h":"The picture: a small boat hollowed out."},"G4628":{"b":"This word simply means the leg, from the hip down to the foot. The soldiers came to break the legs of the men crucified beside Jesus, to hasten death, but found him already gone.","g":"leg","h":"The picture: the leg, hip to foot."},"G4629":{"b":"The root means to cover or shelter. A skepasma is a covering, whatever you wrap over yourself, clothing. Paul says having food and covering, we should be content with these.","g":"covering","h":"The picture: a covering wrapped over you."},"G463":{"b":"The root means to hold yourself back, to hold up against. Forbearance is punishment held in check, the hand raised but not brought down. God's forbearance holds the blow, giving time to turn. A pause before the strike falls.","g":"forbearance","h":"The picture: a raised hand held back."},"G4630":{"b":"This is the name Sceva, a Latin word for left-handed, borne by a Jewish chief priest. It labels a person, so there is nothing here to picture. His seven sons tried and failed at exorcism.","flat":1,"g":"Sceva","h":"No picture."},"G4631":{"b":"This comes from skeuos, a vessel or piece of equipment. It means the ship's tackle, its gear and rigging. With their own hands the crew threw this overboard to lighten the load. The word gathers up all the spare tackle, the ropes and tools that work the ship.","g":"tackle","h":"The picture: the ropes and rigging of a ship."},"G4632":{"b":"Abbott-Smith lists pots, tools, household goods, and the tackle or gear of a ship. Ordinary useful stuff.\n\nThen it gets used of people. Paul is called a chosen vessel. A thing picked up and used.","g":"vessel, tool","h":"The picture: gear on a ship."},"G4633":{"b":"Strong's calls it a tent or cloth hut. Abbott-Smith gives tent, booth, tabernacle.\n\nThe same plain word covers a shelter thrown up on a hillside and the tabernacle in the desert. Both are cloth over poles.","g":"tent, tabernacle","h":"The picture: a tent of cloth."},"G4634":{"b":"Built from a word for a tent and a word meaning to peg, to set up a tent. The name is tent-pitching. Picture families driving pegs and raising booths of branches. Jesus went up at the Feast of Tabernacles, which remembered the tents in the desert.","g":"tabernacles","h":"The picture: pegs driven to pitch the booths."},"G4635":{"b":"Two words, tent and make, the tent being a cloth hut. Hands sewing together heavy cloth into shelter. This was Paul's own trade, and he worked at it while he preached in Corinth.","g":"tent-maker","h":"The picture: stitching a tent."},"G4636":{"b":"The root is a tent or cloth hut, something pitched for a while and struck again. Paul calls the body this tent. If our earthly tent is taken down, he says, we have a lasting building from God.","g":"tabernacle","h":"The picture: the body as a tent."},"G4637":{"b":"The root is a tent, a hut, a temporary shelter. This word is to pitch your tent and live in it. The Word became flesh and pitched his tent among us. God camping with people, close and near.","g":"dwell","h":"The picture: pitching a tent to live in."},"G4638":{"b":"This word comes from a word meaning to pitch a tent, to camp. Skenoma is the tent itself. Peter calls his own body his tent, soon to be folded up and laid down when he dies.","g":"tabernacle","h":"The picture: the tent you live in."},"G4639":{"b":"This is a shadow, caused by interception of light, the dark shape cast when something stands in the way of the sun. Hebrews calls the law a shadow of the good things to come. Real enough to see, but only the outline of the body casting it.","g":"shadow","h":"The picture: the shape thrown when light is blocked."},"G464":{"b":"The root is the word for competing for a prize in the games, straining every muscle. Add \"against\" and you get two fighters locked together. Hebrews says you have not yet struggled against sin to the point of shedding your blood.","g":"strive against","h":"The picture: two fighters locked together."},"G4640":{"b":"The word means to leap. Strong's ties it to the quickening of a child not yet born. When Mary greets Elizabeth, the baby John leaps inside her. The same word is used for skipping and jumping for joy.","g":"leap","h":"The picture: a baby kicking in the womb."},"G4641":{"b":"The roots are heart and \"dry, hard, tough.\" So it is a heart gone hard, like ground baked dry. Jesus says Moses allowed divorce only because their hearts were this hard. Not soft and able to bend, but stiff and cracked.","g":"hardness of heart","h":"The picture: a heart gone dry and hard."},"G4642":{"b":"The root means to dry out, and a dried thing turns hard and stiff. Skleros is hard to the touch, then hard in temper. You are a skleros man, the servant says to his master, reaping where you did not sow. A hard word, a stiff wind.","g":"hard","h":"The picture: something dried stiff and hard."},"G4643":{"b":"The root means dry, hard, tough. So this is the quality of being hardened. Abbott uses it of stubbornness. Paul says a hard and unrepentant heart stores up trouble for itself, like ground too dry to take the rain.","g":"hardness","h":"The picture: ground baked dry and hard."},"G4644":{"b":"The word joins 'hard or tough' with 'neck.' It is an animal stiffening against the yoke. Stephen calls the crowd stiff-necked, too hard to bow their heads to God.","g":"stiffnecked","h":"The picture: the ox that will not bend its neck."},"G4645":{"b":"The root means dry, hard, tough. To harden is to bake something soft until it turns stiff and unyielding, like clay left in the sun. Scripture warns, harden not your hearts. A heart can set like dried ground that no water gets into.","g":"harden","h":"The picture: soft ground baked hard."},"G4646":{"b":"The word means curved, bent, winding, the opposite of straight. The crooked roads shall be made straight, John cries, quoting the prophet, every twist pulled level for the Lord. Turned on people it means warped and dishonest.","g":"crooked","h":"The picture: a road that twists and bends."},"G4647":{"b":"Abbott-Smith runs from anything pointed to a stake to a thorn. Paul calls his affliction that, a thorn in the flesh, something jabbing that he begged God three times to pull out.","g":"thorn","h":"The picture: a sharp stake or thorn driven into the flesh."},"G4648":{"b":"The root is a scout or sentry, and also a goal, the mark you fix your eye on. To watch closely, to keep something in your sights. Paul says keep your eye on those who split the church. Fix your gaze and do not look away.","g":"consider, take heed","h":"The picture: a scout with his eye on the mark."},"G4649":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives two senses, a watchman who scans, and a mark on which to fix the eye. Paul says he presses toward the mark for the prize, his eyes locked on the goal ahead.","g":"goal, mark","h":"The picture: the mark you fix your eye on."},"G465":{"b":"This joins \"in place of\" to a word meaning to swap. An antallagma is what you hand over in exchange, the price for a thing traded. Jesus asks what a man would give in exchange for his soul. Nothing weighs enough.","g":"exchange","h":"The picture: the price laid on the scale in trade."},"G4650":{"b":"This word means to scatter, to drive apart. The wolf comes and skorpizo the sheep, sending them fleeing every way. He who does not gather with me, Jesus says, skorpizo. To pull together or to fling apart, one or the other.","g":"scatter","h":"The picture: sheep flung apart."},"G4651":{"b":"This is the scorpion, named from its sting. Strong's traces the name to a word meaning to pierce, the curled tail that stabs. Jesus gives his own the power to tread on serpents and scorpions and take no harm. A real creature, a real sting.","g":"scorpion","h":"The picture: the scorpion's stinging tail."},"G4652":{"b":"The root is the word for darkness, shadiness. This word means dark, full of darkness. If your eye is bad, Jesus says, your whole body is full of darkness, a house with the lamp gone out, black all through.","g":"dark","h":"The picture: a room with no light in it."},"G4653":{"b":"Abbott's sense is darkness, the plain dark of a room with no lamp. John uses it for the world the light stepped into. The light shines in the skotia, and the darkness has never once managed to put it out.","g":"darkness","h":"The picture: a room with no lamp."},"G4654":{"b":"The root is darkness. To skotizo is to go dark, to have the light put out. The sun will be skotizo, Jesus says of the last days, the moon giving no light. Paul uses it of a mind, a heart gone dark inside.","g":"to darken","h":"The picture: the sun going dark."},"G4655":{"b":"Strong's defines darkness as shadiness, obscurity, and traces it to the word behind shadow.\n\nSo the picture is not black night. It is something shaded, where you cannot make things out clearly.","g":"darkness","h":"The picture: shade."},"G4656":{"b":"The root skotos means darkness. To skotoo is to make dark, to blot out the light. Revelation uses it of the sun going black, and Paul of a mind darkened, the understanding shut off from light.","g":"darken","h":"The picture: the light blotted out."},"G4657":{"b":"Strong's reads it as what is thrown to the dogs, refuse and dung. Paul says he counts all his old advantages as skybalon, garbage, so that he may gain Christ and be found in him.","g":"refuse, dung","h":"The picture: scraps thrown to the dogs."},"G4658":{"b":"To a Greek the Scythian, from what is now Russia and Siberia, was the wildest of barbarians, the roughest outsider imaginable. Paul names him beside the Greek and the Jew to say Christ erases the line between civilized and savage.","g":"Scythian","h":"The picture: the wild man from the far north."},"G4659":{"b":"The word joins sullen and face. It means a gloomy, dragged-down look, the face someone puts on. Jesus says the hypocrites make their faces like this when they fast, so people can see how hard they suffer. They pull a sad face for the crowd, and that is all the reward they get.","g":"gloomy-faced","h":"The picture: a long, sullen face."},"G466":{"b":"Built from a word meaning to fill up, to make full, with in turn added. Paul says he fills up in his own body what is still lacking of Christ's afflictions, taking his turn to fill the gap.","g":"fill up","h":"The picture: filling up what is still empty."},"G4660":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this first meant to skin, to flay, to rend. From that raw image it came to mean to wear a person out, to trouble them. The synagogue ruler is told not to trouble the teacher further. The word underneath is skinning.","g":"trouble, harass","h":"The picture: skin torn off."},"G4661":{"b":"This word comes from the word to strip or flay. Abbott-Smith gives it as the arms taken off a defeated foe, the spoils. When someone stronger overpowers the armed man, he takes the armor he trusted and divides up the plunder.","g":"spoil","h":"The picture: armor stripped off a beaten enemy."},"G4662":{"b":"The word joins 'a maggot or worm' with 'to eat.' It is what struck Herod after he took the crowd's worship: he was eaten by worms and died where he sat.","g":"eaten of worms","h":"The picture: worms feeding on flesh."},"G4663":{"b":"This word is a grub, a maggot, an earthworm, the kind that eats dead flesh. In Mark 9:48 Jesus warns of the place where their worm does not die and the fire is not quenched, a picture of ruin that never ends.","g":"worm","h":"The picture: the maggot that feeds on the dead."},"G4664":{"b":"The word comes from the word for emerald, a green gem. Abbott-Smith gives \"emerald-green.\" Picture the deep green light of that stone. So the rainbow around God's throne shone emerald green.","g":"of emerald","h":"The picture: the green of an emerald."},"G4665":{"b":"The word means emerald. Abbott-Smith gives \"emerald or other transparent green stone.\" Picture a bright, clear green gem. So the fourth foundation of the city wall was emerald.","g":"emerald","h":"The picture: a clear green stone."},"G4666":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says myrrh is a resinous gum used as an unguent and for embalming the dead. It has a bitter, heavy scent. The wise men bring it to Jesus. The same spice wrapped his body in the tomb. A birth gift that already smells of burial.","g":"myrrh","h":"The picture: the burial spice."},"G4667":{"b":"The city's name is the same word as myrrh, the bitter fragrant resin used to anoint the dead. The letter to Smyrna is written to a suffering church. The name itself carries the scent of myrrh.","g":"Smyrna","h":"The picture: myrrh."},"G4669":{"b":"The word comes from myrrh, the bitter perfume. To do this is to lace a drink with it, drugging the wine. At the cross they offered Jesus wine mixed this way. It would dull the pain. He would not take it.","g":"mix with myrrh","h":"The picture: wine drugged with myrrh."},"G467":{"b":"Anti means in return, and apodidomi means to give back. Antapodidomi is paying back in full, matching what was given, coin for coin. It runs both ways, God repaying kindness and repaying evil. Vengeance is mine, I will repay.","g":"repay","h":"The picture: paying back coin for coin."},"G4670":{"b":"The name means a burnt district, scorched volcanic or bituminous ground. Sodom was the city destroyed by fire from heaven for its wickedness, spared only by Lot and his daughters.","g":"Sodom","h":"The picture: a burnt district."},"G4672":{"b":"The name means peaceful. It comes from a word meaning safe. Solomon was the son of David who reigned in peace and built the temple, granted wisdom greater than all who came before.","g":"Solomon","h":"The picture: peaceful."},"G4673":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives this as an urn, then a coffin. Here it is the open bier, the wooden frame the body lay on as it was carried. Jesus walked up and touched it, and the bearers stopped in their tracks.","g":"bier","h":"The picture: the open bier the dead are carried on."},"G4674":{"b":"This is the possessive of the word you, meaning thy or thine. Abbott shows it marking what belongs to you, your kinsfolk, your goods. It ties a person to their own, but the tie is grammar. There is nothing here to see or hold.","flat":1,"g":"thine","h":"No picture."},"G4676":{"b":"Strong's calls it \"a sudarium (sweat-cloth),\" a rag for wiping sweat off the face. The same cloth was tied over a dead man's face. So the napkin folded up in the empty tomb was a burial sweat-cloth, left behind.","g":"napkin, handkerchief","h":"The picture: a cloth for wiping sweat."},"G4677":{"b":"Strong's says this name means lily. It comes from the Hebrew word for the flower. Susanna was one of the women who traveled with Jesus and paid for his needs out of their own pockets. Her name is a blossom.","g":"Susanna","h":"The picture: a lily."},"G4678":{"b":"It starts on the ground. Abbott-Smith says the word ranges from knowledge of the arts and matters of daily life all the way up to the highest sense.\n\nWisdom begins as know-how, the kind that makes something well.","g":"wisdom","h":"The picture: a craftsman's skill."},"G4679":{"b":"Built on sophós, wise. On its good side it means to make wise, instruct: the Scriptures can make a child wise for salvation. On its dark side it means to devise cleverly, and Peter uses it of cunningly invented myths. The same skill, aimed at truth or fiction.","g":"make wise","h":"The picture: made wise, or made up."},"G468":{"b":"Strong's says \"a requital,\" and adds \"properly, the thing\" given. It is the return handed back for what was done. Jesus says invite those who cannot pay you back, so no such return comes to your hand.","g":"recompense","h":"The picture: the payment handed back in return."},"G4680":{"b":"Abbott-Smith spreads the word wide. Skilled, clever, wise, whether in handicraft, the affairs of life, the sciences or learning.\n\nSo wisdom starts as knowing how to do something well. Paul calls himself a skilled builder.","g":"wise","h":"The picture: the skilled craftsman."},"G4681":{"b":"This is just the name of a place, Spain, the far western edge of the empire Paul hoped to reach. Strong's says the name is of foreign origin, so there is nothing behind it to picture.","flat":1,"g":"Spain","h":"No picture."},"G4682":{"b":"This word first means to tear or mangle, then to convulse, to throw a body into violent shaking. The unclean spirit tore at the boy, threw him down, and convulsed him. It is like hands ripping cloth, wrenching a person.","g":"convulse","h":"The picture: a body wrenched and thrown about."},"G4683":{"b":"Strong's traces this to a strip of cloth, the idea of wrapping in strips. Abbott-Smith names the swathing-band. It is what Mary does to the newborn, winding him tight in cloth bands and laying him in a feeding trough.","g":"swaddle","h":"The picture: a baby bound in strips of cloth."},"G4684":{"b":"This word means to live riotously, soft and self-indulgent, from a root meaning wantonness and luxury. James says the rich fattened themselves in pleasure while others starved. The plump, easy life spent only on itself.","g":"live in luxury","h":"The picture: the plump, self-indulgent life."},"G4685":{"b":"The word means to draw, to pull. Abbott-Smith shows its object: a sword. In Mark, when they come to arrest Jesus, a bystander draws his blade and strikes off a man's ear. The pull of steel from the belt.","g":"draw","h":"The picture: pulling a sword from its sheath."},"G4686":{"b":"First this meant a coil, anything rolled up tight. Then it named a cohort of soldiers packed together like a wound rope. The band that came for Jesus with lanterns and weapons was this word. A tight-wound mass of armed men.","g":"band, cohort","h":"The picture: a coil of rope wound tight."},"G4687":{"b":"Strong's gives the plain motion: to scatter. Abbott-Smith's examples are all farm work and the parables built on it.\n\nSowing is not careful placement. It is a wide throw, and the seed lands where it lands.","g":"sow","h":"The picture: the hand throws the seed."},"G4688":{"b":"This is a Latin word for a military scout or bodyguard, a soldier who watches. It came to mean the guard who carries out executions. In Mark 6:27 Herod sends one to the prison, and he beheads John and brings the head on a platter.","g":"executioner, guard","h":"The picture: the armed guard sent to watch and strike."},"G4689":{"b":"This word is wine poured out over an altar, a drink-offering emptied to the last drop. Paul says his own life is being poured out like that. Not spilled by accident, but given up on purpose. The cup emptied for God.","g":"poured out","h":"The picture: wine poured out on the altar."},"G469":{"b":"This is built from a word meaning to give back. It is the return payment, what comes back to you in exchange for what you did. Paul tells servants they will receive from the Lord the reward, the wage handed back for faithful work.","g":"reward","h":"The picture: the payment handed back."},"G4690":{"b":"Strong's puts it exactly: something sown. The word is built straight on the verb to sow.\n\nThe same word covers plant seed and a person's descendants. Children are what was planted and came up later.","g":"seed, offspring","h":"The picture: the thing that was sown."},"G4691":{"b":"Strong's calls this a seed-picker, as the crow. It pictures a bird pecking scraps of grain off the ground. In slang it meant a loafer who lives on bits picked up in the market. The Athenians sneered that Paul was this kind of babbler.","g":"babbler","h":"The picture: a crow pecking seeds."},"G4692":{"b":"Strong's ties this to the word for a foot. To speed, to hurry. The shepherds came with haste to find the baby. Jesus tells Zacchaeus to hurry down from the tree. Feet moving fast toward something you cannot wait to reach.","g":"hasten","h":"The picture: feet moving fast."},"G4693":{"b":"A spelaion is a cave, a hollow in the rock. Lazarus was buried in one with a stone laid across it. You have made my house a den of robbers, Jesus said in the temple. A dark hollow cut into the hillside.","g":"cave, den","h":"The picture: a cave in the rock."},"G4694":{"b":"The word is a rock or reef in the sea that the waves dash over, unseen until a ship strikes it. Jude says such men are hidden reefs at your love feasts, eating with you while endangering all.","g":"reef, spot","h":"The picture: a hidden reef that wrecks ships."},"G4695":{"b":"From a word for a stain or blemish. So it means to spot something, to leave a mark that soils it. Picture a drop of dirt on clean cloth. James uses it of keeping oneself unstained by the world.","g":"to stain","h":"The picture: a stain on the cloth."},"G4696":{"b":"This word means a spot or stain, the kind that mars a clean cloth. One mark spoils the whole garment. Paul wants the church presented without spot or wrinkle. So the picture is a robe held up to the light and checked for stains.","g":"spot, stain","h":"The picture: a stain on the cloth."},"G4697":{"b":"Strong's says it means \"to have the bowels yearn.\" The Greeks felt deep emotion low in the body, in the gut. So when Jesus had compassion, it was a churning felt deep inside, not a polite sympathy.","g":"have compassion","h":"The picture: a gut wrenched with pity."},"G4698":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says these are the inward parts, the heart, liver, and lungs. The guts. People felt their deepest feelings there. So this word came to mean tender pity, love felt deep in the belly.","g":"compassion, pity","h":"The picture: a gut feeling."},"G4699":{"b":"This is a sponge, the sea sponge that soaks up liquid. At the cross someone filled a sponge with sour wine, put it on a reed, and held it up to Jesus' lips. The word is that soft thing dripping and lifted to his mouth.","g":"sponge","h":"The picture: a sponge soaked full."},"G47":{"b":"This word comes from a root meaning clean. Purity here is a life kept clean, the way a white cloth is kept from every stain. Paul tells Timothy to treat the younger women in all purity. Spotless conduct, nothing soiled.","g":"purity","h":"The picture: a cloth kept clean."},"G470":{"b":"This puts \"against\" in front of \"answer.\" Abbott says \"to answer again, reply against.\" Paul asks who you are to answer God back. It is not a reply but a retort, an answer aimed against the one who spoke.","g":"answer back","h":"The picture: an answer sent back the other way."},"G4700":{"b":"This word just means ashes, the grey dust left after a fire. People sat in sackcloth and ashes to show grief and sorrow for sin. Jesus says if these miracles had been done in Tyre they would have repented in ashes long ago.","g":"ashes","h":"The picture: a handful of ashes."},"G4701":{"b":"The root is to scatter seed across a field. This is that seed, and the sowing of it. Peter says you were born again from seed that never rots, the living word of God. A sowing that never dies.","g":"seed","h":"The picture: seed scattered across a field."},"G4702":{"b":"The root is seed scattered on the ground. This word is the field where that seed has grown, the standing grain. The disciples walked through the grainfields on the Sabbath and pulled off heads of wheat to eat.","g":"grainfields","h":"The picture: a field of standing grain."},"G4703":{"b":"The root means to scatter, to sow. This is the seed itself, grain thrown out across the ground by a farmer's hand. Jesus' sower flings it. Paul turns it into a picture of giving, seed scattered that grows into more.","g":"seed","h":"The picture: grain flung across a field."},"G4704":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it first means to make haste. The word comes from a word for speed. From hurrying came the idea of being eager and giving your full effort. Do your best, and do it quickly.","g":"be diligent, hurry","h":"The picture: hurrying to get it done."},"G4705":{"b":"The root spoude means speed, haste, eagerness. Spoudaios first meant quick, in a hurry. From haste it came to mean diligent, earnest, the person who hurries to get a thing done. Paul found Titus more earnest than ever.","g":"diligent","h":"The picture: moving in haste."},"G4709":{"b":"The word carries haste and zeal together, doing a thing eagerly and quick. The elders beg Jesus spoudaios, earnestly, to come heal the servant. Bring these people on their way diligently, Paul tells Titus, with real care and no delay.","g":"diligently","h":"The picture: moving fast, no dragging feet."},"G4710":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this comes from a word \"to hasten,\" and it first means \"haste, speed.\" Mary went to the hill country in a hurry. From that speed it grew to mean eagerness, the zeal that will not drag its feet.","g":"diligence, haste","h":"The picture: moving in a hurry."},"G4711":{"b":"This is a large woven basket, a flexible mat-basket for carrying provisions on a journey. Seven spyrides of scraps were gathered after the four thousand ate. Later Paul was let down the city wall hidden in one.","g":"basket","h":"The picture: a woven food basket."},"G4712":{"b":"This was a fixed measure of length, then the racecourse that ran that distance. In a race all the runners run but only one gets the prize, Paul says, using it. Picture the marked track with feet pounding down it toward the finish line.","g":"racecourse, stadium","h":"The picture: the marked running track."},"G4713":{"b":"This is an earthen jar, first used for racking off wine, named from the word to stand because it stood to settle. Here it is the golden jar that held the manna inside the ark.","g":"jar, pot","h":"The picture: an earthen jar set to stand."},"G4714":{"b":"Built from the word to stand. Its first sense is a standing, place, status. But a standing-up became an uprising, and then a sharp dispute. Barabbas was in prison for an uprising.","g":"uprising, dissension","h":"The picture: a standing-up that becomes a riot."},"G4715":{"b":"A stater was a coin, but the name means a stander, a set standard of weight. Abbott lists its senses as a weight and a coin. Before it was money it was a measured lump of metal. In Matthew 17:27 it is the coin in the fish's mouth.","g":"coin, stater","h":"The picture: a fixed weight of silver."},"G4716":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the old sense is an upright pale or stake. A pole, nothing more.\n\nOnly in later writers does it mean the Roman execution frame. The word was ordinary before Rome made it terrible.","g":"cross","h":"The picture: a bare stake in the ground."},"G4717":{"b":"The oldest meaning is farm and army work. Abbott-Smith gives to fence with pales, impalisade, that is to set a row of stakes.\n\nOnly later writers use it for crucify. The cross begins as a stake.","g":"crucify","h":"The picture: driving stakes into the ground."},"G4718":{"b":"The word means a bunch of grapes, the ripe cluster hanging on the vine. Do men gather grapes from thorns, Jesus asks. A good tree shows itself by fruit like this, heavy clusters you can pick and eat.","g":"grapes","h":"The picture: a hanging cluster of grapes."},"G4719":{"b":"This is the head of grain, the ripe ear standing out from the stalk. The disciples plucked the stachys on the Sabbath, rubbing the kernels in their hands. First the blade, then the ear, then the full corn in the ear.","g":"ear of grain","h":"The picture: a head of grain on the stalk."},"G472":{"b":"The word joins against and hold. Abbott-Smith says to hold firmly to, to cleave to. Jesus says no one can serve two masters. You will hold fast to one, gripping him tight, while the other slips from your hand.","g":"hold fast, cleave to","h":"The picture: gripping one thing and not letting go."},"G4720":{"b":"His name is a common Greek word. It means a head of grain, the ripe ear standing out at the top of the stalk. Paul calls Stachys his beloved. A man named for the part of the wheat that is ready to harvest.","g":"Stachys","h":"The picture: a head of grain on the stalk."},"G4721":{"b":"The word means a roof, a thatch or deck over a building. They dug through the roof to let the paralytic down to Jesus. The centurion says he is not worthy to have Jesus come under his roof. The plain covering overhead.","g":"roof","h":"The picture: the roof of a house."},"G4722":{"b":"The root is the word for a roof. Abbott says it means to cover closely, to keep water in or out. A roof holds off the storm without a word. So love bears all things, roofing over what would otherwise flood in.","g":"to bear, cover","h":"The picture: a roof that keeps out the rain."},"G4723":{"b":"The word traces back to \"stiff, hard, solid.\" A steiros woman is barren, her womb closed like stiff ground where no seed takes. Elizabeth was called this all her years. Blessed are the barren, Jesus says in the dark days coming.","g":"barren","h":"The picture: hard ground that grows nothing."},"G4724":{"b":"Homer used this word for furling sail, drawing the canvas in. From there it means to pull yourself back, to hold aloof and keep clear. Paul draws in, avoiding any way a man could blame him over the gift.","g":"withdraw, avoid","h":"The picture: furling the sail."},"G4725":{"b":"The word comes from a root meaning to wind around, to enwreath. It is the flower garland the priest of Zeus carries, ready to sacrifice oxen to Paul and Barnabas as gods.","g":"garland, wreath","h":"The picture: a garland of leaves for the altar."},"G4726":{"b":"The root means to be in straits, pressed into a narrow place, until a sigh escapes. This word is that groan. God said he had heard the groaning of his people in Egypt and had come down to bring them out.","g":"groaning","h":"The picture: the groan forced out of a tight place."},"G4727":{"b":"The root means narrow, hemmed in by things pressing close. A groan is what gets squeezed out when you are in a tight place. Jesus looks up and groans before healing. Creation and we ourselves groan, pressed and longing for release.","g":"sigh, groan","h":"The picture: a groan squeezed out in a tight place."},"G4728":{"b":"The word means narrow, with obstacles standing close on either side. Strong's pictures things standing close about, pressing in. Jesus says enter by the narrow gate, the tight door, the pinched road that few ever find.","g":"narrow","h":"The picture: the narrow gate."},"G4729":{"b":"The roots are stenos, narrow, and choros, space. Picture being crammed into a space too tight to turn in. Paul says we are pressed on every side but not crushed, and tells the Corinthians they are cramped in their own hearts, not his.","g":"cramp, distress","h":"The picture: crammed into a tight space."},"G4730":{"b":"Abbott says this word first means \"narrowness of space, want of room.\" The root behind it means narrow, from obstacles standing close about. So distress is the feeling of walls pressing in with nowhere to move. That is why the old translators rendered it anguish.","g":"distress, anguish","h":"The picture: no room to turn around."},"G4731":{"b":"The word means hard, firm, solid, from the root to stand. It is used of solid food as against milk, and of a firm foundation. Peter tells believers to resist the devil solid in the faith, standing unmoved.","g":"solid, firm","h":"The picture: solid ground underfoot."},"G4732":{"b":"This word comes from a word meaning solid and stiff. To make firm, to set a thing hard like stone. The lame man's feet and ankles were made firm by this word, and he stood and walked.","g":"strengthen","h":"The picture: set solid and firm as stone."},"G4733":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to make solid, to harden into firmness. It can mean a solid support or foundation. Paul says he rejoices to see the firmness of their faith in Christ, set like a solid thing.","g":"steadfastness","h":"The picture: a solid, set foundation."},"G4734":{"b":"The name is a short form built on stephanos, the wreath given to the winner of a race. So the name means crowned. Stephanas was a real man, one of the first Paul baptized, who gave himself to serve the saints.","g":"Stephanas","h":"The picture: the winner's wreath."},"G4735":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this is the garland given as a prize for victory or as a public honour. It comes from a verb meaning to encircle.\n\nIt is the runner's wreath, not the king's gold crown. That is a different word.","g":"crown, wreath","h":"The picture: the winner's wreath."},"G4737":{"b":"The root is the wreath handed out as a prize in the public games. Not a metal crown but a circle of leaves pressed onto the winner's head. Paul says no one gets this wreath unless he competes by the rules. The honor goes to the one who finishes right.","g":"to crown","h":"The picture: the winner's wreath."},"G4738":{"b":"Strong's traces this to a word meaning to stand, because the chest stands out in front of the body. The tax collector beat his breast and begged for mercy. The part that stands forward, over the heart.","g":"breast, chest","h":"The picture: the chest standing out in front."},"G4739":{"b":"This word grew out of the idea of standing. Abbott-Smith gives to stand firm, stand fast. It pictures staying on your feet, planted. Stand fast in the faith. Stand fast in the freedom Christ gave you.","g":"stand fast","h":"The picture: holding your ground."},"G474":{"b":"Built from a word for against and a word for throwing. Abbott says it means to throw in turn, to exchange. Here it is words tossed like a ball. Jesus asked what words they were throwing to and fro as they walked in sorrow.","g":"exchange, bandy","h":"The picture: words thrown back and forth."},"G4740":{"b":"The root means to set fast, to fix in place. So this is firmness, standing steady. Peter warns readers not to be carried off by error and fall from their own firm footing.","g":"stedfastness","h":"The picture: a post set firm in the ground."},"G4741":{"b":"Abbott says the word means to fix, to set fast, to make fast. Jesus \"set his face\" to go to Jerusalem, fixed it there. To strengthen a person is to make them stand firm.","g":"establish, strengthen","h":"The picture: fixing something firmly in place."},"G4742":{"b":"Abbott-Smith traces this to a word meaning to prick. A stigma is a tattoed mark or brand, pricked into the skin to show who owns you. Paul says he carries the marks of Jesus on his body.","g":"mark, brand","h":"The picture: a brand pricked into the skin."},"G4743":{"b":"The root is a mark pricked or punched into something with a point. A stigme is that tiny dot, and here it means a moment. The devil showed Jesus all the kingdoms in one such prick of time, gone as fast as it came.","g":"moment","h":"The picture: a single prick of a pin."},"G4744":{"b":"This word means to gleam, to flash with brightness, to glisten. In Mark 9:3 Jesus is transfigured, and his clothes become dazzling white, shining brighter than any launderer on earth could bleach them.","g":"shine, gleam","h":"The picture: cloth flashing with light."},"G4745":{"b":"Strong's calls it \"a colonnade or interior piazza,\" a covered walkway held up by a row of standing pillars. The word may come from the verb to stand. Solomon's porch was one of these, along the Temple wall, sheltering people from sun and rain.","g":"porch","h":"The picture: a covered walk of standing pillars."},"G4746":{"b":"Strong's says this is a spread of loose stuff for a couch, tramped flat, and so a leafy branch cut for that use. In Mark 11:8 the crowd spreads their cloaks and branches cut from the fields on the road before Jesus.","g":"branch","h":"The picture: leafy branches spread underfoot."},"G4747":{"b":"A stoicheion is one thing standing in a row, like a single letter of the alphabet or a soldier in rank. So the stoicheia are the ABCs, the first basic pieces. The elementary things of the world, step one in the line.","g":"element, rudiment","h":"The picture: letters of the alphabet in a row."},"G4748":{"b":"Strong's says this means to march in (military) rank. Abbott-Smith adds it is built from a word for a row. It is soldiers in file, each man keeping step. So walking by the Spirit means falling in line, matching the pace set for you.","g":"walk orderly","h":"The picture: soldiers keeping step in a row."},"G4749":{"b":"This word first meant equipment or gear. It came to mean fine clothing, flowing raiment, a festal robe. The father calls for the best robe for his returned son. Scribes love to walk about in long robes.","g":"robe","h":"The picture: a long flowing robe."},"G475":{"b":"This joins 'opposite' to a word meaning to set or arrange. It means to place yourself facing against someone, to stand in opposition. Paul speaks of those who oppose the truth. They set themselves squarely in its path.","g":"oppose","h":"The picture: planting yourself in the way."},"G4750":{"b":"It means a mouth. But Abbott notes the Greeks used the same word for the edge of the sword, following a Hebrew phrase.\n\nA blade has a mouth. That is the word behind speech in the New Testament.","g":"mouth","h":"The picture: the edge of a sword."},"G4751":{"b":"The root is stoma, the mouth. A stomachos is a little mouth, an opening, and it became the word for the stomach itself. Paul tells Timothy to take a little wine for his stomach's sake and his weak health.","g":"stomach","h":"The picture: the mouth of the stomach."},"G4752":{"b":"The root is a word for serving as a soldier, going out on campaign. Strateia is the warfare itself, the whole expedition. Paul says the weapons of our warfare are not fleshly but mighty through God to pull down strongholds.","g":"warfare","h":"The picture: soldiers on campaign."},"G4753":{"b":"From the word for going to war, serving in a campaign. It means an army, a host of troops. The armies of heaven follow the rider on the white horse. A body of soldiers on the march.","g":"army","h":"The picture: the marching army."},"G4754":{"b":"The word grows from stratos, an encamped army. To strateuomai is to serve as a soldier under a commander, to go to war. Paul turns it inward. We do not war after the flesh. The soldier in camp, called up for a harder campaign.","g":"serve as soldier","h":"The picture: an army in its camp."},"G4755":{"b":"Abbott-Smith builds it from army and to lead. It pictures the one who leads the troops, a general. In Acts it also names the officer who commanded the temple guard.","g":"captain, magistrate","h":"The picture: the man who leads the army."},"G4756":{"b":"The word means an army, a host drawn up together. Luke uses it for the sky over Bethlehem, a great company of the heavenly army appearing with the angel, ranks of them praising God over the shepherds' field.","g":"host, army","h":"The picture: an army drawn up in ranks."},"G4757":{"b":"Strong's describes this soldier as a camper-out. Abbott-Smith gives no origin at all, so this is Strong's reading.\n\nEither way it is the ordinary ranker, not an officer. Paul calls Timothy one of these.","g":"soldier","h":"The picture: a man living in a camp."},"G4758":{"b":"This joins the word for an army to a word that first meant to gather or pick out. To enlist is to select men and gather them into the ranks. Paul says the soldier wants to please the one who chose him for the army.","g":"enlist soldiers","h":"The picture: picking men for the army."},"G476":{"b":"This is an opponent in a lawsuit, the man on the other side of the case, the one suing you. Peter says the devil is your antidikos, prowling like a lion. The accuser who wants you condemned.","g":"adversary","h":"The picture: your opponent across the courtroom."},"G4760":{"b":"Abbott builds it from a word for an army and a word for a plain, level ground. A body of troops spread over a field. When you see Jerusalem surrounded by armies, Jesus said, know that her ruin is near.","g":"army","h":"The picture: an army camped on the plain."},"G4761":{"b":"The root means to twist, to turn right around. This word is to twist, even to torture on the rack. Peter says the untaught wrench the Scriptures, pulling the words out of shape, to their own destruction.","g":"wrest, twist","h":"The picture: wrenching something on a torture rack."},"G4762":{"b":"Strong's says to twist, to turn quite around or reverse.\n\nAbbott-Smith lists many verses where someone simply turns to face another person. The same word covers a change of heart. Same motion, different level.","g":"turn","h":"The picture: turning right around."},"G4763":{"b":"The root carries the idea of straining strength that spills over into luxury. Abbott says to run riot, wax wanton. Revelation uses it of Babylon, who glorified herself and lived in luxury, until the kings who shared her excess weep at her smoke.","g":"live luxuriously","h":"The picture: drunk on luxury."},"G4764":{"b":"Strong's roots this in straining, strenuousness, strength. Think of muscle flexed hard, then turned to reckless excess. Abbott gives insolent luxury. It names Babylon's delicacies, strength spent on wanton comfort, and the merchants who grew rich on it.","g":"luxury","h":"The picture: strength flexed into reckless excess."},"G4765":{"b":"The word is a little sparrow, the smallest thing sold in the market. Jesus says two are sold for a penny, yet not one falls to the ground without your Father. The cheapest bird, and God marks its fall. You are worth more.","g":"sparrow","h":"The picture: a little sparrow."},"G4766":{"b":"Stronnymi is to spread something out flat, a carpet, a couch, a bed. The crowds spread their cloaks on the road before Jesus. The upper room stood ready, spread with cushioned couches. Cloth laid down to cover the bare ground.","g":"spread, strew","h":"The picture: cloaks spread on the road."},"G4767":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to hate. It describes what is hated and hateful, odious to all. Paul recalls that we ourselves once lived hateful and hating one another. There is no image here, only the thing everyone turns from.","flat":1,"g":"hateful","h":"No picture."},"G4768":{"b":"The word paints something turned sombre and dark. Of the sky it means clouding over toward storm. Of a face it means falling. When Jesus tells the rich man to sell all, his face darkens like a sky before rain, and he walks away.","g":"be gloomy, overcast","h":"The picture: the sky darkening over."},"G4769":{"b":"This is a pillar, a column. Abbott says it is regarded especially as a support, the thing that holds the weight up. Its root is the word to stand. Paul calls James, Peter, and John pillars, and the church the pillar of the truth.","g":"pillar","h":"The picture: a pillar holding up the roof."},"G477":{"b":"This joins 'opposite' to a word meaning to place. An antithesis is one thing set down against another, facing it. Paul uses it for the clashing claims of false knowledge. Two positions planted against each other.","g":"opposition","h":"The picture: two things set face to face."},"G4770":{"b":"This name comes from a colonnade or interior piazza, a covered porch in Athens. The teachers met there, so they were named for the porch. Stoic thinkers argued with Paul in the same market.","g":"Stoic","h":"The picture: the painted porch."},"G4772":{"b":"The word rests on a relative by blood. It gathers all such people, the whole kin. When Elizabeth's neighbors object that no one in her kindred bears the name John, this is the word. The family you were born into.","g":"kindred","h":"The picture: everyone born of the same blood."},"G4773":{"b":"The word joins with and kin. A syngenēs is one born of the same stock, blood family. Paul says he could wish himself cursed for his syngeneis, his kinsmen by blood. And the angel tells Mary that Elizabeth, her relative, is with child.","g":"relative","h":"The picture: born of the same stock."},"G4774":{"b":"This joins with and to know. Strong's calls it fellow knowledge, two minds knowing the same thing. A shared understanding leaves room. Paul says his word here is by permission, an allowance he grants, not a command he lays down.","g":"permission","h":"The picture: two minds knowing together, making room."},"G4775":{"b":"The root means to sit, and \"together\" sets you beside others. It is to take a seat in the group. Mark uses it for Peter, sitting with the guards at the fire in the courtyard while, inside, Jesus is on trial.","g":"sit with","h":"The picture: sitting down among them."},"G4776":{"b":"The word joins \"together\" to the word for sitting down. Strong's says \"to give or take a seat in company with.\" Peter sits down with the guards around the courtyard fire, one more in the circle, and there he is asked if he knows Jesus.","g":"sit together","h":"The picture: taking a seat in the same circle."},"G4777":{"b":"This word joins together with a word meaning to undergo hardship. It is taking your share of the suffering, shouldering the heavy load beside someone else. Paul tells Timothy to suffer hardship with him for the gospel. Not watching from safety, but carrying the same weight.","g":"suffer hardship with","h":"The picture: carrying the hard load together."},"G4778":{"b":"This joins a word for maltreat with a word meaning together. It is to share the rough treatment of others rather than escape it. Moses chose to be ill-used with God's people over the pleasures of sin.","g":"suffer with","h":"The picture: taking the rough treatment alongside them."},"G4779":{"b":"Abbott: \"to call together.\" Strong's: \"to convoke.\" It joins \"together\" with \"call.\" You call out and people come in from around. The woman calls her friends together to rejoice over the coin she found.","g":"call together","h":"The picture: calling everyone together."},"G478":{"b":"Strong's sees an army here, troops set down in a line to stand against the enemy. That is what resisting sin looks like. Not a wish. A row of soldiers dug in and holding the ground.","g":"resist","h":"The picture: troops set in line against the enemy."},"G4780":{"b":"This word joins together and to cover. Abbott-Smith gives it as to veil or cover completely. But nothing is covered up that will not be uncovered, Jesus says. Every hidden thing will be pulled out into the open.","g":"cover","h":"The picture: a cloth thrown right over to hide it."},"G4781":{"b":"The root means to bend. Add the word for together. So it is to bend completely, to bow down. Abbott says to bend together. Paul quotes the Psalm alongside the last word, bow down their back forever, a people bent low.","g":"bow down","h":"The picture: bent double, the back bowed to the ground."},"G4782":{"b":"This is syn, with, plus katabaino, to go down. It means to travel down in someone's company. The leading men of Jerusalem go down to Caesarea with Festus to press their case against Paul. The word is the walk downhill made side by side.","g":"go down with","h":"The picture: walking down the road together."},"G4783":{"b":"The root means to deposit your vote together with, to side with. Abbott-Smith gives agreement. Paul asks what agreement God's temple could ever cast with idols, whose stones fall in the same jar.","g":"agreement","h":"The picture: dropping your voting stone into the same jar."},"G4784":{"b":"Built from a word for together and a word meaning to place down, to deposit. Abbott says it means to deposit one's vote with another, to agree. Joseph of Arimathea had not consented to their plan. He withheld his vote.","g":"consent","h":"The picture: dropping your vote in the same box."},"G4785":{"b":"Deep in this long word sits a verb meaning to count with pebbles, the old way of voting. It means to reckon someone into a group. Matthias was numbered with the eleven apostles, his place among them counted and sealed.","g":"to number with","h":"The picture: a pebble dropped in to count someone in."},"G4786":{"b":"This is built from with and a word for mixing a drink, pouring wine and water together. God has blended the body together, mixing the parts into one so that no member stands alone.","g":"blend together","h":"The picture: wine blended in the cup."},"G4787":{"b":"The word joins 'together' with a root meaning to stir. Abbott's first sense is to move together. In Acts it is a mob stirred as one body, shoved into an uproar against Stephen.","g":"stir up","h":"The picture: a whole crowd moved at once."},"G4788":{"b":"The word is \"close\" with \"together\" on it, to shut in on all sides. It is used of the great catch of fish, the net drawn tight so none escape. Paul turns it upward: God shut up all under sin, so mercy could reach every last one.","g":"shut up","h":"The picture: a net closing round a shoal of fish."},"G4789":{"b":"The root means a sharer by lot, an heir. The prefix means together. So a joint-heir is one who draws from the same inheritance alongside another. Paul says we are joint-heirs with Christ, sharing the very same estate.","g":"joint-heir","h":"The picture: sharing the inheritance."},"G479":{"b":"This word joins in return and to invite. Abbott-Smith gives it as to invite in turn. When you give a dinner, Jesus says, do not invite friends who will just invite you back. Invite the poor, who cannot repay you.","g":"bid again","h":"The picture: the dinner invitation handed back to you."},"G4790":{"b":"The roots are sun, together, and koinoneo, to share. So the word is to have a share in something along with others. Paul tells them to have no share in the works of darkness, and thanks the Philippians for sharing in his trouble.","g":"share with","h":"The picture: a share held in common."},"G4791":{"b":"The root means a sharer, one who has something in common with others. The prefix means together. So this is a partner who holds the same thing jointly, whether the gospel, suffering, or grace. Not a bystander, but a co-owner.","g":"fellow-partaker","h":"The picture: holding the same thing in common."},"G4792":{"b":"The word joins 'together' with 'to carry off.' Abbott's second sense is to take up a body for burial. Devout men carry Stephen's broken body away and bury it with loud grief.","g":"carry, bury","h":"The picture: carrying a body to the grave."},"G4793":{"b":"The roots are sun, together, and krino, to judge. Picture setting two things side by side to weigh them against each other. Paul warns against the ones who measure themselves by themselves, comparing themselves with themselves, and so miss the mark.","g":"compare","h":"The picture: two things set side by side."},"G4794":{"b":"This word joins together and to bend forward. Abbott-Smith gives it as to be bowed down. A woman had been bent double for eighteen years, unable to lift herself at all, until Jesus laid his hands on her and she straightened.","g":"bow together","h":"The picture: a body bent double, unable to straighten."},"G4795":{"b":"This is built from with and a word meaning to happen. Abbott gives chance, coincidence. So it is two paths crossing by accident. By such chance a priest came down the same road where the beaten man lay.","g":"chance","h":"The picture: two paths crossing by accident."},"G4796":{"b":"Two words, with and rejoice. To be glad together. The shepherd calls his neighbors, rejoice with me, I found my lost sheep. Joy that pulls others in to share it.","g":"rejoice with","h":"The picture: come celebrate with me."},"G4797":{"b":"Built from a word meaning together and a word meaning to pour. Picture different things poured into one jar and stirred to a muddle. So a crowd is thrown into confusion, all mixed up and roaring. The whole city was stirred.","g":"confuse, stir up","h":"The picture: liquids poured together into a muddle."},"G4798":{"b":"Built from a word for together and a word meaning to use. Abbott says it means to associate with, to have dealings in common. Jews would not share a vessel with Samaritans. How is it you ask a drink of me, the woman said.","g":"have dealings with","h":"The picture: sharing the same cup."},"G4799":{"b":"The root means to commingle promiscuously, to pour things together into one muddle. So this is a mixed-up mess of a crowd. The whole city poured together in confusion, most not knowing why they had come.","g":"confusion","h":"The picture: liquids poured together."},"G48":{"b":"From hagnos, clean and pure. To hagnizo is to make clean, the washing you went through before you could come near God. Purify yourselves. Draw near with hands scrubbed. A real washing of the body before worship.","g":"purify","h":"The picture: washing clean before worship."},"G480":{"b":"This word is built from opposite and to lie down. Abbott's first sense is to lie opposite to. An enemy here is not rushing at you. He is laid right across from you, planted in your way, blocking. So an adversary is what lies against you.","g":"oppose","h":"The picture: something lying across your path."},"G4800":{"b":"The roots are sun, together, and zao, to live. So the word is to share one life, to be alive alongside someone. Abbott sets it against dying together. If we died with Christ, we will also live with him, sharing his life.","g":"live with","h":"The picture: two alive together."},"G4801":{"b":"This joins \"together\" to a word for a team of oxen yoked side by side. Syzeugnymi is to put two under one yoke. Of marriage Jesus says what God has yoked, let no man split apart. One yoke, two joined to pull as one.","g":"yoke together","h":"The picture: two oxen under one yoke."},"G4802":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means to search or examine together. It joins together and to seek. People digging into a question side by side. Often the joint search turned into a heated argument.","g":"dispute, discuss","h":"The picture: searching it out together."},"G4804":{"b":"The root means to seek something out together, to search by discussion. It slid into meaning to argue and wrangle. A disputer is the professional debater. Paul asks where the disputer of this age has gone.","g":"disputer","h":"The picture: two men wrangling over a question."},"G4805":{"b":"This is built from a word meaning to yoke together, like two oxen sharing one wooden yoke. It means yokefellow. Paul asks his true yokefellow to help these two women make peace.","g":"yokefellow","h":"The picture: two oxen under one yoke."},"G4806":{"b":"This is built from with and a word meaning to make alive, to give life. It means to be brought to life together with another. Paul says when we were dead in our sins, God made us alive together with Christ.","g":"make alive with","h":"The picture: the dead made alive."},"G4807":{"b":"Abbott calls it the mulberry tree, known for roots that grip the earth hard. Jesus said if you had faith like a mustard seed you could tell this tree to be uprooted and planted in the sea, and it would obey.","g":"sycamine tree","h":"The picture: the deep-rooted mulberry tree."},"G4808":{"b":"Abbott says a fig-tree, and the root is the fig itself. Jesus looked for fruit on one and found only leaves, so he cursed the barren tree. He tells us to read the seasons by its softening branch and budding leaf.","g":"fig tree","h":"The picture: the fig tree."},"G4809":{"b":"Abbott builds the name from a word for fig and a word for the black mulberry, a fig-mulberry tree. Zacchaeus was short and could not see over the crowd, so he ran ahead and climbed one to watch Jesus pass.","g":"sycamore tree","h":"The picture: the sycamore Zacchaeus climbed."},"G4810":{"b":"The word means a fig, the fruit. Jesus asks whether people gather figs from thistles. A good tree gives good fruit. The fig is the plain sweet fruit that only its own kind of tree can bear, telling you what the tree really is.","g":"fig","h":"The picture: a ripe fig."},"G4811":{"b":"The two roots are \"fig\" and \"show\". Strong's traces this to a fig-informer, someone who reported illegal fig exports from Greece. From that came the sense of shaking people down. In Luke, John tells soldiers not to extort or accuse people falsely.","g":"extort, defraud","h":"The picture: the man who informs on smuggled figs."},"G4812":{"b":"Abbott-Smith reads this as booty plus to lead, to carry someone off as spoil, to drag them away captive. Paul warns, see that no one takes you captive through empty philosophy and hollow deceit.","g":"carry off, spoil","h":"The picture: carried off as plunder."},"G4813":{"b":"The root is booty, something stripped like a hide. Abbott-Smith says to strip, plunder, spoil. Paul says he robbed other churches, taking their pay, so he could serve Corinth without charging them.","g":"rob, strip","h":"The picture: stripping the gear off a fallen soldier."},"G4814":{"b":"Two words, with and to talk. To converse, to talk together. On the mount Moses and Elijah appear and talk with Jesus. Voices in conversation, side by side.","g":"talk with","h":"The picture: talking together."},"G4815":{"b":"Strong's says it means to clasp, i.e. seize. The word joins together with taking. Hands close and grip. It is used to arrest a prisoner, and also for a woman conceiving, the womb taking hold of new life.","g":"seize; conceive","h":"The picture: hands closing around something."},"G4816":{"b":"Abbott: \"to bring together, collect, gather up.\" It joins \"together\" with a word for gathering. It is picking things up and bringing them into one place, like gathering weeds to burn or good fruit into a basket.","g":"gather","h":"The picture: gathering things into one pile."},"G4817":{"b":"The root means to take an inventory, to reckon up. Add the word for together, and you get men totting up a matter among themselves. The priests reasoned it out. If we say from heaven, he will ask why we did not believe.","g":"reason together","h":"The picture: adding up the sum together."},"G4818":{"b":"This joins with and a word meaning to grieve. Abbott gives to be moved to grief by sympathy. So it is pain felt right alongside. Jesus looked around in anger and grief together, sorrowing at the hardness of their hearts.","g":"be grieved","h":"The picture: grief felt right alongside."},"G4819":{"b":"Abbott's oldest sense is \"to stand with the feet together.\" Strong's says events walk together and so take place. When things fall together, something happens. Peter says do not be surprised at the trial that befalls you.","g":"happen","h":"The picture: things falling together."},"G482":{"b":"The word means to take hold of in turn. Picture reaching out and gripping a person to steady them. God takes hold of Israel his servant to help him. Jesus says we must take hold of the weak this way. A hand that grips and lifts.","g":"help, support","h":"The picture: catching hold of someone to hold them up."},"G4820":{"b":"The parts mean together and to throw. To throw things together. In speech that is to confer or argue. In the mind it is to turn matters over, fitting them side by side. Mary threw all these things together and pondered them in her heart.","g":"confer, ponder","h":"The picture: throwing things together."},"G4821":{"b":"This is built from with and to rule. It means to reign together, to share the throne. Paul says if we endure with Christ, we shall also reign with him, seated where he is seated.","g":"reign with","h":"The picture: sharing the throne."},"G4822":{"b":"Syn means together. Symbibazo pictures forcing separate parts into one, knitting them tight. Paul uses it of the body joined and held together, every joint supplying its part. He also uses it of a mind putting facts together to reach a conclusion.","g":"knit together","h":"The picture: knitting the parts into one."},"G4823":{"b":"The word is \"counsel\" with \"together\" joined to it. It means to put your heads together, to plot or plan as one. It is what the enemies of Jesus do, taking counsel together how they might trap him in his words.","g":"take counsel","h":"The picture: heads leaned in together to plan."},"G4824":{"b":"From the word for an adviser, one who counsels with you. It is counsel taken together, a plan hatched in a huddle. The Pharisees take counsel how to destroy Jesus. Minds joined to decide.","g":"counsel","h":"The picture: heads put together to plot."},"G4825":{"b":"This is built from with and a word for counsel, objectively advice. It pictures one who sits at your side to advise. Paul asks who has been God's counsellor. No one sat beside him to guide his plans.","g":"counsellor","h":"The picture: someone at your side giving advice."},"G4826":{"b":"This is a Hebrew personal name, Shimon, worn by several men in the story. The sources pass it straight through without a stated meaning, so there is nothing concrete here to picture.","flat":1,"g":"Simeon","h":"No picture."},"G4827":{"b":"This word joins two smaller words: together and to learn. A symmathetes is someone learning alongside you. Thomas says it to the other disciples. Not students who happen to share a teacher. Fellow learners, in it together.","g":"fellow disciple","h":"The picture: learners in the same room."},"G4828":{"b":"The roots are sun, together, and martureo, to bear witness. Picture a second witness standing up in court to back the first. That is the word in Romans 8. The Spirit bears witness with our spirit that we are God's children, a second voice confirming the first.","g":"bear witness with","h":"The picture: a second witness in court."},"G4829":{"b":"This joins together with a word meaning to apportion, to share out. It pictures a portion divided and passed around. Paul says those who serve at the altar share together in the altar's offerings.","g":"be partaker with","h":"The picture: the portion divided and shared out."},"G483":{"b":"Strong's builds this word from against and to speak. So it pictures speaking against someone, talking back, saying the opposite. It is used for people who opposed and contradicted what they were told.","g":"contradict, oppose","h":"The picture: speaking against."},"G4830":{"b":"This is built from with and a word for a sharer, one who holds a portion. A symmetochos holds his share together with others in the same thing. Paul says the Gentiles are fellow heirs, joint partakers of the promise.","g":"partaker","h":"The picture: hands on the same portion."},"G4831":{"b":"Built from together and the word to imitate, the word behind mimic. It means being a fellow copier. Paul says join together in imitating me, and watch closely those who walk the same way.","g":"fellow imitator","h":"The picture: copying together, step for step."},"G4832":{"b":"Built from together and shape. It means shaped to match, formed to the same pattern. God means to conform his people to the image of his Son, pressing them into the same shape. One form stamped again and again on many.","g":"conformed to","h":"The picture: pressed into the same mould."},"G4833":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning shaped together, sharing one form. It means to be made like, pressed into the same shape. Paul wants to be formed to Christ's death, so as to reach the resurrection.","g":"conform","h":"The picture: pressed into the same shape."},"G4834":{"b":"This word joins together with a word for feeling and suffering. To sympathize is to feel another's pain as if it struck your own body, a shared ache. Hebrews says our high priest is touched with the feeling of our weaknesses. He feels it with us.","g":"sympathize","h":"The picture: feeling another's pain in your own body."},"G4835":{"b":"The root means to experience pain jointly. This word joins \"with\" to \"suffer.\" So it is feeling what another feels, aching when they ache. Peter lists it among the marks of a true church.","g":"sympathetic","h":"The picture: feeling the other person's pain."},"G4836":{"b":"Built from a word for together and a word meaning to come near, to arrive. To gather together at a spot. The crowds that had come together to watch the crucifixion saw what happened and went home beating their breasts.","g":"come together","h":"The picture: a crowd gathering at one place."},"G4837":{"b":"The root means to call someone near, to your side, to console. Add the word for together. So it is people drawing close to strengthen one another. Paul wanted this shared comfort with the believers at Rome, his faith and theirs.","g":"comfort together","h":"The picture: called to each other's side for comfort."},"G4838":{"b":"The word stacks up \"together\" and \"to receive near, i.e. associate with oneself.\" To bring a person along as a traveling companion. Barnabas wanted to take Mark along again. Paul refused, and over that companion they split and went separate ways.","g":"take with","h":"The picture: bringing a companion along at your side."},"G484":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to take hold of in turn, to help. It pictures a hand laid hold of to lift someone up. Paul lists it among the gifts, helps set beside leaders and healers in the church.","g":"help","h":"The picture: a hand laid hold of to lift you."},"G4840":{"b":"This is syn, with, plus pareimi, to be at hand. It means to be present alongside, close by. Festus points to all the men standing there with them in the hall. The word puts bodies in the room, present and near, not far off.","g":"present with","h":"The picture: people standing right here beside you."},"G4841":{"b":"Built from with and to feel pain. It means to hurt alongside someone, to bear the same suffering they carry. Paul says if we suffer with Christ we will also be glorified with him. When one part of the body aches, the whole body feels it.","g":"suffer with","h":"The picture: two bodies feeling one wound."},"G4842":{"b":"This is built from with and a word meaning to dispatch or send. It means to send one person along with another. Paul sent a trusted brother together with Titus, so the large gift would be handled above suspicion.","g":"send with","h":"The picture: the companion sent along."},"G4843":{"b":"The parts mean together, around, and take, so the sense is to throw the arms about one. A full embrace, wrapping someone up. Paul went down and threw his arms around the fallen boy.","g":"embrace","h":"The picture: arms thrown around."},"G4844":{"b":"The word joins 'together' with 'to drink.' The apostles are the ones who ate and drank with Jesus after he rose, proof to themselves that they were truly with him.","g":"drink with","h":"The picture: sharing a cup at one table."},"G4845":{"b":"The word means to fill completely. Luke uses it for the boat in the storm filling with water as the disciples take on the waves. He also uses it of time, when the day of Pentecost was fully come. Filled to the brim.","g":"fill up","h":"The picture: a boat filling up with water."},"G4846":{"b":"The root is to throttle or strangle, to close off the breath. Thorns sympnigo the young wheat, crowding round it till it cannot breathe. The crowd did the same to Jesus, pressing so tight it nearly crushed him. Choked out.","g":"choke","h":"The picture: thorns strangling the young wheat."},"G4847":{"b":"Built from together and townsman. A sympolites is someone from your own town, sharing your streets and your gate. Paul tells the Gentiles they are no longer strangers but fellow townsmen with God's people.","g":"fellow citizen","h":"The picture: sharing the same town."},"G4848":{"b":"The word is \"travel\" with \"together\" joined to it. It means to journey together, to walk the same road in company. Crowds symporeuomai with Jesus toward Jerusalem. On the Emmaus road the risen Christ falls into step and walks along with two of them.","g":"journey together","h":"The picture: walking the same road side by side."},"G4849":{"b":"The root means to drink in company. A symposium was a drinking-party, a room of people reclining together with cups. Mark borrows the word for the crowd on the grass, sat down in groups to be fed, like guests at a shared table.","g":"company, party","h":"The picture: guests sharing a drink together."},"G485":{"b":"The root means to speak against, to dispute. This word is the speaking back, the contradiction, and then the strife it becomes. Men swear by one greater than themselves to end all their arguing, the writer says. It is talk set against talk.","g":"dispute, strife","h":"The picture: words spoken back against."},"G4850":{"b":"This joins \"together\" to a word meaning older, a senior. So it is a fellow-elder. Peter, writing to elders, does not stand above them. He calls himself one gray head among them.","g":"co-elder","h":"The picture: the older man standing beside you."},"G4851":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the first sense is to bring together. You gather things into one place. What is good for you is what all pulls together in your favor. So the word for advantage begins with carrying things into one heap.","g":"be profitable","h":"The picture: things carried into one pile."},"G4852":{"b":"The root means to speak, to make your thoughts known. Add the word for together. So it is to say the same thing alongside someone. Abbott says to consent, confess. Paul says he agrees with the law that it is good.","g":"consent, agree","h":"The picture: saying the same thing right along with another."},"G4853":{"b":"This joins syn, together, and phyle, a tribe or clan. So it is one who shares your tribe, your own countryman. Paul says the Thessalonians suffered from their own countrymen, just as the churches in Judea did from theirs.","g":"countryman","h":"The picture: a man of your own tribe."},"G4854":{"b":"The root is to grow, as a plant does. Add the word for together. So it is grown up together, joined as one growth. Abbott says united with. Paul says we are grown together with Christ in the likeness of his death.","g":"grown together","h":"The picture: two plants grown together at the root."},"G4855":{"b":"This word joins together and to grow. Abbott-Smith reads it as to grow together with. The seed fell among thorns, and the thorns grew up alongside it, wrapping around the young plant and choking it dead.","g":"spring up with","h":"The picture: thorns coming up tangled in the same soil."},"G4856":{"b":"Syn means together, and the root means sounding alike. Symphoneo is to sound together in tune, and it is the root of our word symphony. If two of you agree on earth about anything. Voices landing on one note, no clash.","g":"agree","h":"The picture: voices in tune together."},"G4857":{"b":"The root means to sound in harmony, where we get symphony. Abbott-Smith gives concord, agreement. Paul asks what harmony Christ can have with Belial, two notes that will never blend.","g":"concord","h":"The picture: two notes struck together in tune."},"G4858":{"b":"This word joins together and sound. Abbott-Smith gives it as music, a concert of instruments sounding as one. Our word symphony comes from it. Coming in from the field, the older brother heard music and dancing and asked what it all meant.","g":"music","h":"The picture: instruments sounding together."},"G4859":{"b":"This joins together with a word for a tone or voice. It means sounding together, agreeing in sound. It pictures two notes ringing in tune, a symphony. Paul says a husband and wife should part only by such agreement.","g":"agreement","h":"The picture: two notes in tune."},"G486":{"b":"Built from \"back\" and a word for hurling abuse, this is an insult thrown back for insult, curse for curse. Peter says when Christ was reviled, he did not fire back. He handed it to the God who judges rightly.","g":"revile again","h":"The picture: throwing an insult back."},"G4860":{"b":"The root means to use pebbles in enumeration, one small stone for each thing counted. Together it means to add up a total. The Ephesians counted the price of their burned magic books, fifty thousand pieces of silver.","g":"reckon up","h":"The picture: counting with pebbles."},"G4861":{"b":"Built from together and the word for soul, which underneath means breath. Sympsychos is being of one soul, one breath. Paul asks the church to be like-minded, joined in one spirit.","g":"one soul","h":"The picture: breathing as one."},"G4863":{"b":"Two small words joined: with and lead. Strong's reads it as to lead together, collect or convene.\n\nA crowd does not gather itself. Someone brings it in. Abbott-Smith adds a second use, to receive hospitably.","g":"gather together","h":"The picture: leading people in."},"G4864":{"b":"Before it was a building, it was an act. Abbott-Smith's first sense is a bringing together, and one old use is a gathering in of harvest.\n\nThe word names the gathering, not the room.","g":"synagogue, assembly","h":"The picture: bringing in the harvest."},"G4865":{"b":"The root is the word for the games, the contest where athletes strain for the prize. Add together in front. Abbott says it is sharing in a contest. Paul asks the Romans to strive together with him in prayer. Prayer as teamwork in the arena.","g":"strive together","h":"The picture: fighting side by side in the arena."},"G4866":{"b":"This word joins together with a word meaning to compete in the games. It is two athletes struggling side by side in the same contest. Paul says the church should strive together for the faith. Not spectators, but teammates in one hard match.","g":"strive together","h":"The picture: athletes struggling side by side."},"G4867":{"b":"The word joins together with a piece meaning to hoard, to heap up. It means to gather people into one assembly. Demetrius calls the silversmiths together to stir up trouble. The believers are gathered together praying for Peter.","g":"gather together","h":"The picture: pulling a crowd together into one place."},"G4868":{"b":"The roots mean to lift and together. The phrase is to take up the accounts together, to settle up. A king decided to settle accounts with his servants, and one owed ten thousand talents. It is the day the books are opened and totaled.","g":"settle accounts","h":"The picture: pulling the accounts together to reckon."},"G4869":{"b":"The roots are sun, together, and aichmalotos, a prisoner of war. Picture captives roped in a line, taken by the spear. Paul calls certain friends his fellow prisoners, taken captive alongside him for the gospel.","g":"fellow prisoner","h":"The picture: captives roped together."},"G487":{"b":"Lytron is the ransom paid to loosen a prisoner's chains, and anti means in his place. So it is the price laid down instead of the captive. Paul says Christ gave himself a ransom for all.","g":"ransom","h":"The picture: the price paid to free a captive."},"G4870":{"b":"The roots mean together and to follow. It is walking the same road with someone, close behind. Jesus let no one follow along with him into the house except Peter, James, and John. Keeping step at his side.","g":"accompany","h":"The picture: walking the same road together."},"G4871":{"b":"This word joins together with a word for thronging or crowding. It means to gather in one place. Luke uses it of the risen Jesus with his followers, some read it as eating with them, all of them drawn close around him.","g":"to assemble","h":"The picture: people crowded into one place."},"G4872":{"b":"The root means to go up, and \"together\" means alongside. It is walking up the road with someone. Mark uses it for the women who came up with Jesus from Galilee to Jerusalem, the long climb up to the city, and who stayed to the end.","g":"come up with","h":"The picture: climbing the road together."},"G4873":{"b":"This word is built from together and to recline. At a feast people lay back on couches around the table. This word puts them there side by side, reclining together at the meal, the ones lying at table with Jesus.","g":"recline together","h":"The picture: guests lying back at the same table."},"G4874":{"b":"The heart of this word is mignumi, to mix. The picture is stirring things together into one blend. Paul uses it for company you keep, and tells them not to mix themselves in with a so-called brother who lives in open sin.","g":"keep company","h":"The picture: stirred into the mix."},"G4875":{"b":"The root means to rest, to lie down and repose. Add together. Abbott says it is to lie down to rest with someone, then to be refreshed in spirit with them. Paul hopes to come and be refreshed among the Romans.","g":"refresh with","h":"The picture: lying down to rest together."},"G4876":{"b":"The parts mean together and facing. To come face to face with someone on the road. A man carrying a water jar will meet you, Jesus tells them. Melchizedek met Abraham this way. It also names an event that meets you, that befalls you.","g":"meet with","h":"The picture: coming face to face on the road."},"G4878":{"b":"Abbott says it means to take hold at the side for assistance, to \"help in bearing.\" Picture someone grabbing the far end of a load so you do not carry it alone. Paul says the Spirit does this with our weakness.","g":"help, assist","h":"The picture: taking the other end of a heavy load."},"G4879":{"b":"The roots are sun, along with, and apago, to lead away. Picture being swept off along with a moving crowd. Paul says even Barnabas was carried away with the pretending, led off his feet by the pull of the group.","g":"carry away with","h":"The picture: swept off with the crowd."},"G488":{"b":"This word joins in return and to measure. Abbott-Smith gives it as to measure in return. The measure you use on others is the very cup scooped back to you. Give generously, and generously it comes back.","g":"measure again","h":"The picture: the same measuring cup handed back."},"G4880":{"b":"Three words pressed together: with, off, die. It means to die in company, side by side. Peter says he will die with Jesus rather than deny him. Paul says if we died with him, we will also live with him.","g":"die with","h":"The picture: dying alongside someone."},"G4881":{"b":"This joins a word to destroy utterly with a word meaning together. It is to perish in the same ruin as others. Rahab, who welcomed the spies, did not perish along with those who refused to believe.","g":"perish with","h":"The picture: swept away along with the rest."},"G4882":{"b":"The roots are together and to send out on a mission. Abbott-Smith says to send along with. Paul says he sent Titus, and sent the brother alongside him, no one traveling with the gift alone.","g":"send with","h":"The picture: two travelers sent off down the road together."},"G4883":{"b":"This is built from a word for a joint, an articulation of the body, and a word meaning to lay. It pictures parts fitted and jointed together, stones laid so they lock. Framed this way, the whole building grows into a temple.","g":"framed together","h":"The picture: joints fitted and locked together."},"G4884":{"b":"The word is \"snatch\" strengthened, to seize and carry away, to grab hold and drag off. The demon had often synarpazo the man, seizing him and hurling him down. A mob grabs Gaius and rushes him into the theater. Violent hands.","g":"seize","h":"The picture: grabbed and dragged off by force."},"G4885":{"b":"Built from together and to grow. So it means to grow up side by side. Jesus says let the wheat and the weeds grow together until harvest. Picture two plants rising in the same field, roots tangled.","g":"grow together","h":"The picture: two plants growing side by side."},"G4886":{"b":"The word is \"together\" plus \"band.\" Strong's: \"a joint tie, i.e. ligament.\" It is the cord that binds parts into one, the way ligaments hold a body together. Love, Paul says, is the band that ties everything into one whole.","g":"bond, band","h":"The picture: the ligament that ties the body together."},"G4887":{"b":"The root means to bind, to tie fast. Add \"together\" and you get prisoners on the same chain. Hebrews says remember those in prison as if you were chained beside them. Their chain is your chain.","g":"bound with","h":"The picture: prisoners on the same chain."},"G4888":{"b":"This joins with and to make glorious. Abbott gives to glorify together. So it is being raised to shine alongside another. If we suffer with Christ, Paul says, we are also glorified together with him.","g":"glorify together","h":"The picture: raised to shine alongside."},"G4889":{"b":"This word means a fellow-servant. It joins together and servant. Abbott-Smith speaks of servants of the same divine Lord. It is the picture of two workers under one master, side by side, owing the same duty.","g":"fellow-servant","h":"The picture: another servant beside you."},"G489":{"b":"This joins in-return with the word for wages, the pay given for work. It is payment handed back, a return that matches the deed. Paul uses it for what sin earns in the body, and for open love repaid in kind. Wages that answer what was done.","g":"recompense","h":"The picture: wages paid in return."},"G4890":{"b":"The root means to rush together, to hastily assemble. This is a mob forming fast. People come running from every side into one place. In Acts the whole city runs together against Paul. The word carries the speed and the danger of it.","g":"running together","h":"The picture: a crowd rushing together."},"G4891":{"b":"The roots are sun, together, and egeiro, to wake, to rouse from sleep. Picture being woken up alongside someone. Paul says God raised us up together with Christ, roused from the sleep of death and lifted with him.","g":"raise together","h":"The picture: woken up together."},"G4892":{"b":"Abbott-Smith breaks the word into two parts. With, plus a word meaning a seat.\n\nSo a council is people seated together. The court that tried Jesus was named for its chairs, not for its power.","g":"council, Sanhedrin","h":"The picture: sitting down together."},"G4893":{"b":"Strong's calls it co-perception. Abbott's ethical sense is innate discernment, a self-judging consciousness.\n\nConscience in this word is a second party inside you, watching what the first one does.","g":"conscience","h":"The picture: knowing along with yourself."},"G4894":{"b":"The word is \"together\" plus \"to see.\" Abbott: \"to see in one view.\" It is taking in the whole of a thing at a glance, and from there, to grasp it, to become aware. Peter, seeing how it stood, came to the house where they prayed.","g":"be aware, know","h":"The picture: taking it all in at one glance."},"G4895":{"b":"The word joins with and to be. It means to be in someone's company, present alongside them. The disciples are with Jesus as he prays alone. Paul's companions are with him on the road. Simply being there, together.","g":"be with","h":"The picture: being right there in someone's company."},"G4897":{"b":"The word joins \"together\" and \"with\" to the word for entering. Abbott says \"to enter together.\" John notes the disciples had not gone into the boat with Jesus. Later one disciple goes in with him through the gate into the high priest's court.","g":"enter together","h":"The picture: going in through the door alongside someone."},"G4898":{"b":"Built from \"together\" and a word meaning away from home, abroad. A synekdemos is the man who is abroad with you, sharing the road far from his own town. The mob at Ephesus seized Gaius and Aristarchus, Paul's traveling companions.","g":"fellow-traveler","h":"The picture: two people far from home, on the road together."},"G4899":{"b":"This joins \"together\" to a root meaning to select, to pick out. So it is being chosen side by side with others. Peter passes on greetings from the church, chosen together with his readers.","g":"chosen together","h":"The picture: picked out alongside you."},"G49":{"b":"The root word means to make clean. This is the ceremony of washing, the ritual that makes a person pure again. In Acts, Paul goes through it in the temple. It is not a feeling. It is a real act of being cleaned.","g":"purification","h":"The picture: water washing something clean."},"G490":{"b":"This is a place name. Strong's says the city was named after a Syrian king. That is all the sources give. It is a spot on the map, not a word with an image behind it.","flat":1,"g":"Antioch","h":"No picture."},"G4900":{"b":"The root means to drive or push, the way wind pushes or oars push a boat. In Acts, Moses tries to force two quarreling countrymen back into peace, and one of them turns on him.","g":"drive together","h":"The picture: shoving two back together."},"G4901":{"b":"The root means to attest further, to back up a witness. This word adds 'together with.' God joined in, adding his own testimony to the message by signs and wonders, a second witness standing with the first.","g":"bear witness with","h":"The picture: a second witness backing the first."},"G4902":{"b":"This joins together with a word meaning to follow. To follow along at someone's side, to travel in company. Several men, named one by one, went with Paul as far as Asia.","g":"accompany","h":"The picture: companions on the road."},"G4903":{"b":"The root is a fellow-worker, a co-laborer. Picture two men in the same field, hands on the same task. God works together with those who love him, all things pulling toward good. Not alone, but alongside.","g":"work together","h":"The picture: two workers in one field."},"G4904":{"b":"Abbott-Smith simply calls this \"a fellow-worker.\" Strong's builds it from \"with\" and \"work.\" So it pictures someone laboring right next to you. Paul uses it for the partners who shared his mission.","g":"fellow worker","h":"The picture: working alongside."},"G4905":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is to come together, assemble. His second is to accompany, to travel along with someone.\n\nThe word for the church gathering is also the word for going with a person on the road.","g":"come together","h":"The picture: walking in together."},"G4906":{"b":"Built from a word meaning together and a word meaning to eat. It is sharing a meal, food at one table. They grumbled that Jesus welcomed sinners and ate with them. To eat with someone is to sit close.","g":"eat with","h":"The picture: food at the same table."},"G4907":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is a running or flowing together, like two streams meeting in one bed. Strong's calls it a mental putting together. Understanding is the moment the scattered facts flow into one current, and you see how the pieces join.","g":"understanding","h":"The picture: two streams flowing into one."},"G4908":{"b":"The root means to put together, to bring things into one. A synetos person is one who fits the pieces and sees the whole. Jesus says the Father hid these things from the wise and understanding and showed them to little children.","g":"prudent, understanding","h":"The picture: pieces put together in the mind."},"G4909":{"b":"The parts mean together and to think well of. To add your approval to what others are doing, to nod along with them. Paul stood by, consenting, while Stephen was stoned and holding the coats. Agreeing so fully you share the guilt.","g":"consent","h":"The picture: nodding along with the crowd."},"G491":{"b":"This word tags a person by his city. Abbott gives a citizen of Antioch, a man of that place. So the picture is someone marked by where he is from. Nicolas, chosen among the seven, was a convert of Antioch.","g":"of Antioch","h":"The picture: a man marked by his city."},"G4910":{"b":"The parts mean together and to fare well. Put them at a table and you get a feast shared in company. A rich meal eaten side by side. Peter uses it of false teachers feasting among the believers.","g":"feast together","h":"The picture: a feast shared at one table."},"G4911":{"b":"This joins together and stand-up. It is a mob getting to its feet all at once, one body rising to rise together against someone. The crowd stood up as one against Paul and Silas.","g":"rise up together","h":"The picture: the crowd rising as one."},"G4912":{"b":"This is built from \"with\" and \"hold.\" Abbott-Smith says it means \"to hold together,\" and then \"to hem in, press on every side.\" So it is a crowd squeezing you, or a feeling that grips and will not let go.","g":"press, grip","h":"The picture: pressed in on every side."},"G4913":{"b":"This joins with and a word for delight. Abbott gives to rejoice with or in. So it is joy that leans in and agrees. Paul says he delights in the law of God after the inward man, even while another law fights him.","g":"delight","h":"The picture: joy that leans in and agrees."},"G4914":{"b":"Built from a word for together and a word for habit. Custom is the way a people always does a thing, the track worn deep by doing it over and over. Pilate frees a prisoner at the feast because that is the custom.","g":"custom","h":"The picture: the track worn deep by habit."},"G4915":{"b":"The roots are together and age. Abbott-Smith says one of the same age, an equal in years. Paul says he outran his peers, the men his own age, racing ahead of them all in the old religion.","g":"equal in age","h":"The picture: two people the same age growing up side by side."},"G4916":{"b":"Built from together and to bury. It pictures being laid in the grave alongside another. Paul says in baptism we were buried with Christ, lowered into the tomb with him, so that we could rise to walk a new life. Down into the same grave.","g":"buried with","h":"The picture: laid in the same grave."},"G4917":{"b":"This joins \"together\" to a word meaning to crush. Synthlao is to be dashed down and broken to bits. Jesus says whoever falls on this stone will be shattered like that, broken to pieces against it.","g":"break, shatter","h":"The picture: shattered to pieces on the ground."},"G4918":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this word means to press on all sides. It is what a crowd does when it packs in so tight there is no room to move. In Mark the crowds squeeze against Jesus as he walks. Bodies against bodies, pressing.","g":"crowd, press","h":"The picture: a crowd pressing in from every side."},"G4919":{"b":"This joins together with a word meaning to crumble. To break a thing into small crumbs, and so to crush someone's spirit. Paul asked why they wept and were crushing his heart.","g":"crush, break","h":"The picture: crumbling to pieces."},"G492":{"b":"The word puts \"opposite\" in front of \"pass by.\" Abbott says \"to pass by opposite to.\" It is the priest and the Levite in the story, seeing the beaten man and walking by on the other side. Deliberate distance.","g":"pass by opposite","h":"The picture: crossing to the far side of the road."},"G4920":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is to bring or set together. Only after that does it mean to perceive or understand.\n\nUnderstanding is not one flash. It is two things laid side by side until they fit.","g":"understand","h":"The picture: the pieces put together."},"G4921":{"b":"Strong's says it means to set together. You place someone alongside yourself and vouch for them. That is how it means to commend. The same word can mean things standing together, holding as one.","g":"commend; stand with","h":"The picture: setting one person beside another."},"G4922":{"b":"The word joins 'together' with 'to travel.' It is the men walking the Damascus road beside Saul, who heard the voice with him but saw no one there.","g":"journey with","h":"The picture: companions on the road."},"G4923":{"b":"This word joins together with the word for a road. It is a band of people walking the same road, a caravan. Leaving Jerusalem, Mary and Joseph thought the boy Jesus was somewhere in the group. A day passed before they missed him.","g":"caravan, company","h":"The picture: a company traveling the same road."},"G4924":{"b":"This word joins \"together\" with a root meaning to occupy a house, to reside. So it is a husband and wife sharing the same home. Peter tells husbands to live with their wives this closely, and with honor.","g":"dwell together","h":"The picture: two people under one roof."},"G4925":{"b":"The root means to be a house-builder. With together in front, it means to build up together. Abbott-Smith speaks of many materials built into one structure. Paul says Christians are joined like stones into one house for God.","g":"build together","h":"The picture: stones laid into one house."},"G4926":{"b":"The word joins 'together' with a root meaning to be in company and converse. Peter walks in talking with Cornelius and finds a whole houseful of people waiting for him.","g":"talk with","h":"The picture: two men talking face to face."},"G4927":{"b":"This joins together with a boundary-line. Two buildings standing side by side, sharing one border. The house where Paul taught stood right next to the synagogue, wall against wall.","g":"border on","h":"The picture: walls sharing a border."},"G4928":{"b":"The root means to hold together, to press in. Abbott says \"a narrow place,\" then \"straits, distress.\" It is the feeling of walls closing in with no room. Jesus says the nations will be in this kind of distress, hemmed and anxious.","g":"distress, anguish","h":"The picture: being squeezed into a narrow place."},"G4929":{"b":"The root means to arrange in order, to set each thing in its place like troops in a line. Add \"together\" and it is to direct or ordain. The disciples did as Jesus had arranged for them, going to fetch the colt exactly as ordered.","g":"appoint","h":"The picture: setting each thing in its place."},"G493":{"b":"This name is short for Antipatros, built from words meaning instead of and father. So the name carries father inside it. Antipas was Christ's faithful witness, killed at Pergamum where Satan's throne stood.","g":"a Christian","h":"The picture: a name built from father."},"G4930":{"b":"From a word meaning to complete entirely. It is the consummation, all things drawn together to their end. Jesus speaks of the end of the age, when the harvest comes and the reapers are the angels. The final wrapping-up.","g":"consummation, end","h":"The picture: everything brought to its finish."},"G4931":{"b":"This is together joined to a word for bringing to an end. To finish completely, every part carried through to the close. The devil, when he had finished every test, left Jesus. The disciples ask when all things will reach their end.","g":"complete, finish","h":"The picture: every last part carried to the end."},"G4932":{"b":"The root belongs to cutting, to a keen edge. So this is to cut down, to cut short. Abbott says to cut short. Paul quotes Isaiah, the Lord will finish the work and cut it short in righteousness upon the earth.","g":"cut short","h":"The picture: cutting a thing short with a blade."},"G4933":{"b":"The root means to guard a thing by keeping your eye upon it. The \"together\" adds close. So it is holding something safe by never looking away. Mary kept all these things, watching over them in her heart.","g":"keep, preserve","h":"The picture: keeping your eye on it."},"G4934":{"b":"The word is \"together\" plus \"to place.\" Abbott: \"to place or put together.\" Set two things side by side so they line up. That is how the Greek sees an agreement, two people laying their terms together until they match.","g":"agree, covenant","h":"The picture: two things laid side by side to match."},"G4935":{"b":"The root means to cut together, to trim down by cutting. To speak this way is to cut your words short. In Acts, Tertullus asks the governor to hear them briefly, promising to keep it cut down and quick.","g":"briefly","h":"The picture: cutting it short."},"G4936":{"b":"The roots mean together and to run. So it is a crowd running to the same place at once. When the people saw where Jesus was headed, they ran together on foot from all the towns and got there ahead of him. Feet pounding toward one point.","g":"run together","h":"The picture: a crowd running to one spot."},"G4937":{"b":"This word means to shatter, to break in pieces by crushing. The wild man snapped his chains with it. The alabaster jar was broken open with it. A bruised reed he will not break. God will soon crush Satan under your feet. Ground to bits.","g":"shatter, crush","h":"The picture: grinding to pieces."},"G4938":{"b":"The root means to crush completely, to shatter. So this is a fracture, a breaking. Abbott says a fracture, then calamity, destruction. Paul quotes the Psalm, ruin and misery are in their ways, wreckage left wherever they go.","g":"destruction","h":"The picture: something shattered to pieces."},"G4939":{"b":"The word joins 'together' with 'a nurse.' It means foster-brothers, raised side by side. Manaen had grown up with Herod the tetrarch, and now he stands among the prophets at Antioch.","g":"brought up with","h":"The picture: two children fed by one nurse."},"G494":{"b":"This town was named from Antipater, a father's name pressed into a city. Abbott sets it between Joppa and Caesarea. So the picture is a stop on the coast road, where soldiers brought Paul by night.","g":"a place","h":"The picture: a town on the coast road."},"G4940":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives this as to meet with, to fall in with. Jesus' mother and brothers came looking for him but could not get to him because of the crowd packed around the door. They simply could not reach him.","g":"come at, meet","h":"The picture: pushing through a crowd to reach someone."},"G4941":{"b":"This is a woman's name, Syntyche. Underneath is a word meaning to meet by chance, to fall in together. Paul urges her and Euodia to be of the same mind and end their quarrel.","g":"Syntyche (name)","h":"The picture: a chance meeting on the way."},"G4942":{"b":"The root is to act under a mask, and with is added. Abbott-Smith says to play a part with. Paul says even Barnabas joined the pretense, all of them wearing the same mask over their real convictions.","g":"dissemble with","h":"The picture: actors playing a false part together on one stage."},"G4943":{"b":"The roots stack up as together, under, and work. Abbott-Smith says to help together, join in serving. Paul pictures their prayers as many hands helping under one weight along with him.","g":"help together","h":"The picture: shoulders under the same load."},"G4944":{"b":"The root is to feel the pains of childbirth. Add the word for together. So it is to be in labor as one. Abbott says to be in travail together. Paul says creation groans and travails together until now, like a mother waiting to deliver.","g":"travail together","h":"The picture: labor pains, the whole world in travail."},"G4945":{"b":"This puts syn, together, with omnuo, to swear an oath. A conspiracy here is a group bound by a shared oath. More than forty men swear together not to eat until Paul is dead. The word is the oath that ties the plotters to each other.","g":"conspiracy","h":"The picture: men taking an oath together."},"G4946":{"b":"This is the name of Syracuse, the main city of Sicily. Strong's says the name is of uncertain derivation, so there is no meaning behind it to picture. The ship carrying Paul put in there for three days.","flat":1,"g":"Syracuse","h":"No picture."},"G4947":{"b":"The name means a rock. It comes from a word for a stone, something pressed hard or to a point. Syria was a region north of Israel, home to Damascus and often at war with God's people.","g":"Syria","h":"The picture: a rock."},"G4948":{"b":"This word marks a person by his homeland, Syria. Abbott gives simply a Syrian. So the picture is a man named by his country. Naaman the Syrian, the leper, was cleansed while many in Israel were not.","g":"a Syrian","h":"The picture: a man named by his country."},"G4949":{"b":"This name joins Syria with Phoenicia, and Phoenicia means palm-country, the coast of palm trees. She is a woman from that land. In Mark 7:26 she begs Jesus to drive the demon from her daughter, and her faith wins her request.","g":"Syrophenician","h":"The picture: a woman from the land of palms."},"G4950":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to drag or trail, because the waves drag the sand into shifting banks. The Syrtis was a stretch of quicksands off the African coast. The sailors feared being swept onto it. The word is sand pulled together by the sea into a trap.","g":"quicksands","h":"The picture: a sandbank where the sea drags the sand."},"G4951":{"b":"This word means to trail, to drag something along the ground behind you. The disciples dragged the net heavy with fish. A mob dragged Paul out of the city. Not lifting but hauling, scraping along the dirt.","g":"drag, draw","h":"The picture: hauling something along the ground."},"G4952":{"b":"The root means to mangle or tear, from the idea of a spasm gripping the muscles. Add \"together\" and the whole body is seized at once. Mark uses it for the spirit that throws the boy to the ground, convulsing him from head to foot.","g":"convulse","h":"The picture: the body wrenched and thrown."},"G4953":{"b":"This word is built from together and a word meaning to give a sign. It is a fixed sign or signal set between two sides beforehand. Judas gave the soldiers one. The man I kiss is the one. His kiss was the agreed signal.","g":"signal, token","h":"The picture: the signal agreed in advance."},"G4954":{"b":"Built from together and body. A syssomos is a fellow member of the same body. Not allies who happen to agree, but a hand and a foot on one frame. Paul says Gentiles share the very body with Israel.","g":"same body","h":"The picture: parts of one body."},"G4955":{"b":"This word joins together with a word meaning a standing, a rising up. It marks men who stand up as one against the rulers. Barabbas was such a rebel, jailed with fellow rioters for murder in the uprising. The crowd chose him over Jesus.","g":"fellow rebel","h":"The picture: standing up together in revolt."},"G4956":{"b":"The root means to set people together, to introduce. Abbott-Smith says for bringing together, commendatory. Paul asks if he needs such a letter to prove himself, when their changed lives are his letter.","g":"of commendation","h":"The picture: a letter of introduction carried in the hand."},"G4957":{"b":"Built from a word meaning together and a word meaning to impale on the cross. Two men nailed up alongside each other. Robbers were crucified with Jesus. Paul says the old self was crucified with Christ, nailed up beside him and left to die.","g":"crucify with","h":"The picture: two crosses raised side by side."},"G4958":{"b":"This is built from \"together\" and \"draw.\" You draw the cloth together around something. Abbott points to enshrouding a body for burial. So when the young men systello Ananias, they folded the sheet in tight around him and carried him out to bury.","g":"wrap up","h":"The picture: wrapping a body for burial."},"G4959":{"b":"The root means to be in straits, pressed narrow, and so to sigh or groan. Add the word for together. Abbott says to groan together. Paul says the whole creation groans as one, straining toward the day it is set free.","g":"groan together","h":"The picture: groaning together under a weight."},"G496":{"b":"The word joins 'against' with 'to fall.' Its first sense is to fall against or upon. Stephen says they always push against the Holy Spirit, forever falling the wrong way.","g":"resist","h":"The picture: throwing yourself against a wall."},"G4960":{"b":"The roots are together and to keep step in line. Abbott-Smith says to stand in the same rank. Paul lines Hagar up with the earthly Jerusalem, the two standing in one column of slavery.","g":"answer to, correspond","h":"The picture: soldiers standing in the same column, rank lined up with rank."},"G4961":{"b":"This word joins together with the word for a soldier, one who camps out on campaign. It is the man in the tent beside you, sharing the same war. Paul calls his coworkers fellow-soldiers. Not friends at a distance, but comrades under the same fire.","g":"fellow-soldier","h":"The picture: the man in the tent beside you."},"G4962":{"b":"This joins \"together\" to strepho, to twist. Systrepho is to twist things into a bundle, and so to draw people into a tight crowd. Paul does it with sticks for the fire. Here it gathers the disciples close around Jesus in Galilee.","g":"gather together","h":"The picture: sticks twisted into one bundle."},"G4963":{"b":"The root means to twist together, i.e. collect, the way loose strands are wound into one cord. This word is that twist turned into people. Jews wound themselves this way against Paul, banding together under an oath to kill him.","g":"band together","h":"The picture: strands twisted together into one cord."},"G4964":{"b":"This is built from a word for the outward shape or figure of a thing, with together in front. To be conformed is to be pressed into the same mould as everything around you. Paul says do not let the world stamp its shape on you.","g":"conform","h":"The picture: pressed into a mould."},"G4965":{"b":"The name comes from a word meaning to become tipsy, linked to strong drink. Sychar was a town in Samaria, near the well where Jesus rested and spoke with the woman drawing water.","g":"Sychar","h":"The picture: drunken."},"G4966":{"b":"The name means ridge. It comes from a word for the neck between the shoulders, the place where a burden is carried. Shechem was both a man and a town in the hill country of Israel.","g":"Shechem","h":"The picture: ridge."},"G4967":{"b":"This word comes from a word meaning to butcher an animal for food or sacrifice. Sphage is the slaughter, the cutting of the throat. Led like a sheep to the slaughter, and he did not open his mouth.","g":"slaughter","h":"The picture: the animal led to the knife."},"G4968":{"b":"The root means butchery, the killing of beasts for food or sacrifice. In Acts, Stephen asks whether Israel really brought God these slain animals during the forty years in the desert.","g":"slain beast, victim","h":"The picture: the animal on the slaughter block."},"G4969":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this is to slay, slaughter, especially of victims for sacrifice. It is the altar word, cutting the throat of the offering. Revelation calls Jesus the Lamb that was slain.","g":"slay, slaughter","h":"The picture: the knife at the altar."},"G497":{"b":"The root means to serve as a soldier, to campaign. Add the word for against. So it is to wage war on. Abbott says to make war against. Paul says another law wars against the law of his mind and takes him captive.","g":"war against","h":"The picture: an army marching out against another."},"G4970":{"b":"This word just means very much or exceedingly. It comes from a word for \"excessive, violent,\" but that is only force, not an image. There is nothing here to picture.","flat":1,"g":"exceedingly","h":"No picture."},"G4971":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning vehemently, in a high degree, much. It names sheer force. Luke uses it at sea. The ship was so violently tossed by the storm that the next day they threw the cargo overboard.","g":"exceedingly","h":"The picture: hit with full force."},"G4972":{"b":"The old way to seal a letter was to press a signet ring into soft wax. Strong's says the word means to stamp with a signet or private mark. Sealing kept a thing safe, secret, and marked as yours.","g":"seal","h":"The picture: pressing a seal into wax."},"G4973":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means a seal, signet. Picture a ring stamped into soft wax, leaving a mark. That mark showed who owned a thing and proved it was genuine. It is used for God's mark on his own.","g":"seal","h":"The picture: a signet pressed into wax."},"G4974":{"b":"This word means the ankle. Strong's links it to the idea of a ball, from the round shape of the ankle bone. Luke uses it of the lame man: his feet and ankle bones took strength, and he leaped up. The round joint holding him up.","g":"ankle","h":"The picture: the round knob of the ankle bone."},"G4975":{"b":"Abbott gives almost, nearly. On the next Sabbath, Luke says, schedon the whole city gathered to hear the word of God, Acts 13:44. Not quite all of them, but so close it filled the town. A hair short of complete.","g":"almost","h":"The picture: a hair short of all."},"G4976":{"b":"This is the outward figure or fashion of a thing, the shape it holds at the moment, from a word meaning to hold. Paul says the fashion of this world is passing away, its shape changing like a stage set struck between scenes.","g":"fashion","h":"The picture: the outward shape of a thing."},"G4977":{"b":"This word means to split or tear. Strong's calls it a primary verb, which means it does not come from anything else. The meaning is plain and physical, but there is no older picture behind it.","flat":1,"g":"split, tear","h":"No picture."},"G4978":{"b":"Abbott: \"a rent.\" It comes from σχίζω, to split. It is the tear you get when new cloth is sewn onto old and pulls away. From a torn garment the word moves to a split among people.","g":"division, tear","h":"The picture: a tear in a piece of cloth."},"G4979":{"b":"The word is a little \"rush,\" the reedy plant. Abbott says \"a rope, properly one made of rushes.\" Jesus knots these cords into a whip to drive the traders from the temple. Sailors later cut ropes like these to let a boat fall away.","g":"rope, cord","h":"The picture: a rope braided from rushes."},"G498":{"b":"Built from a word meaning against and a word meaning to draw up in order, like ranking troops. To resist is to form your line facing the other side. God sets himself against the proud but gives grace to the humble.","g":"oppose, resist","h":"The picture: a battle line drawn up facing the enemy."},"G4980":{"b":"The root is schole, time off from work, and from it we get the word school. Here it means a house left empty, swept and standing open. Jesus warns that an empty life does not stay empty. Something worse moves back in.","g":"empty, be at leisure","h":"The picture: the empty house standing open."},"G4981":{"b":"This word first meant leisure, a withholding of oneself from work. Only later did it come to mean a school, the place you spent your free hours. Paul taught daily in the lecture hall of Tyrannus.","g":"school","h":"The picture: time off work."},"G4982":{"b":"Abbott starts with saving someone from peril, injury or suffering. Then he adds healing, restoring to health.\n\nRescue and recovery are the same word. When the New Testament says saved, that is the word underneath.","g":"save, rescue","h":"The picture: pulled out of danger."},"G4983":{"b":"Strong's calls it the body as a sound whole. Abbott-Smith stretches it past people to the bodies of animals and even to objects, the way English says heavenly bodies.\n\nSo body means the complete thing, not just skin and bone.","g":"body","h":"The picture: the whole thing, in one piece."},"G4984":{"b":"The root is the word for the body. This means bodily, having physical shape. Luke uses it at Jesus' baptism, when the Spirit came down on him in bodily form, like a dove, something the crowd could actually see.","g":"bodily","h":"The picture: in a form you can touch."},"G4985":{"b":"This comes from the word for the body. It means bodily, in physical form. Paul says the whole fullness of God lives in Christ bodily, in a real body of flesh, not just as an idea.","g":"bodily","h":"The picture: in flesh and bone."},"G4986":{"b":"Strong's reads this name as of a safe father, from the words for to save and father. So the name holds a rescue in it. Sopater of Berea was one who traveled with Paul into Asia.","g":"Sopater","h":"The picture: a rescue hidden in a name."},"G4987":{"b":"The word means to pile up, to make a heap. Paul quotes it about heaping coals of fire on an enemy's head by returning kindness. The point is not to burn him but to melt him down.","g":"heap up","h":"The picture: coals heaped on the head."},"G4988":{"b":"The name joins two roots, to save and to strengthen: of safe strength. In Acts a Sosthenes is dragged and beaten before Gallio's seat. By First Corinthians a Sosthenes stands beside Paul as brother. The name held while the story turned.","g":"Sosthenes","h":"The picture: the name that means safe-strong."},"G4989":{"b":"This is a longer form of Sopater, and carries the same sense, of a safe father, a father saved. So again the name holds a rescue. Sosipater was a kinsman of Paul who sent greetings to Rome.","g":"Sosipater","h":"The picture: a father saved."},"G499":{"b":"The root is a die struck to leave a stamp, and this word is the matching impression, the copy that answers to the mold. Peter says baptism corresponds to the flood, water answering to water. The shape pressed to fit the original.","g":"counterpart, figure","h":"The picture: wax pressed into a seal."},"G4990":{"b":"Abbott-Smith notes this was a common title for kings in the Greek and Roman periods. Rulers called themselves saviour.\n\nSo when Luke gives the title to a baby in a feed trough, it is taken off the emperor.","g":"saviour","h":"The picture: a title kings claimed."},"G4991":{"b":"Wider than church language. Abbott-Smith gives deliverance, preservation, salvation, safety, and points to the Latin word behind health.\n\nIt covers rescue from enemies as much as rescue from sin. The word means getting out alive.","g":"salvation","h":"The picture: being brought out safe."},"G4992":{"b":"The root means rescue, being pulled to safety out of danger. Simeon held the child and said his eyes had seen God's salvation. Paul calls it a helmet, a guard for the head. Safety carried near.","g":"salvation","h":"The picture: pulled out to safety."},"G4993":{"b":"The root means safe and sound in mind, held together, self-controlled. The man who lived among the tombs is found sitting, clothed, in his right mind. To have your thoughts back in order, no longer wild. A steady, settled head.","g":"sound mind","h":"The picture: the wild man now sitting calm."},"G4994":{"b":"This means to make sound-minded, to recall a person to their senses. Abbott gives the sense train. The older women are to train the young wives this way, steadying their minds and bringing them back to sober, sound thinking.","g":"train","h":"The picture: bringing someone to their senses."},"G4995":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to make sound in mind. Abbott gives self-control, self-discipline. So the picture is a mind kept sound and reined in. God gave us not fear but power, love, and a mind held steady.","g":"sound mind","h":"The picture: a mind kept sound and reined in."},"G4996":{"b":"This comes from a word for sound in mind, self-controlled. Abbott gives with sound mind, prudently, soberly. So it means living with a level head. Grace teaches us to live soberly, uprightly, and godly in this present age.","g":"soberly","h":"The picture: living with a level head."},"G4997":{"b":"This word comes from a word meaning safe and sound in mind. Sophrosyne is a mind kept whole and reined in, not carried off. Paul told Festus he was not mad but speaking words of truth and a sober mind.","g":"self-control","h":"The picture: a mind held whole and steady."},"G4998":{"b":"The two roots are to save, to keep safe, and the midriff, which the Greeks took as the seat of the mind. So this word is one whose mind is kept sound and safe, in control of itself. Overseers and older men are to be this.","g":"self-controlled","h":"The picture: a mind kept safe and whole."},"G4999":{"b":"Strong's says this means huts or wooden-walled buildings, from the Latin taberna. The place called Three Taverns was named for such roadside shelters. Believers walked this far out to meet Paul on his way to Rome.","g":"taverns","h":"The picture: rough wooden-walled huts by the road."},"G5":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this is the Aramaic word for father, the plain family word a small child speaks at home. It is not a title. So when we cry Abba, Father, we are using the word a child uses, not a formal name.","g":"Abba, father","h":"The picture: a child's word for father."},"G50":{"b":"This puts not in front of the verb to perceive or think. Agnoeo is to not know, the mind failing to grasp what is in front of it. So I would not have you agnoeo, ignorant, brothers, Paul says again and again, unwilling to leave them groping in the dark.","g":"be ignorant","h":"The picture: the mind left in the dark."},"G500":{"b":"The word joins anti and Christ. The root can mean both against and instead of. So the antichrist is not only Christ's enemy. He takes the guise of Christ, standing in his place while opposing him. John says many are already here.","g":"antichrist","h":"The picture: the one who stands in Christ's place against him."},"G5000":{"b":"This is a woman's name, and Strong's says it means the gazelle, a swift and graceful animal. Her Greek name Dorcas means the very same thing. So when Peter raised Tabitha from death, the name over her was a leaping deer.","g":"Tabitha","h":"The picture: a gazelle."},"G5001":{"b":"Abbott-Smith calls this a military term, a company, troop, division, rank. It is men lined up in order, each standing in his own place. Paul uses it for the resurrection, saying each will be raised in his own turn.","g":"order, troop","h":"The picture: soldiers drawn up in ranks."},"G5002":{"b":"The word comes from a root meaning to arrange in orderly rows, to assign each thing its place. So a set day is one fixed in advance. On the appointed day Herod puts on his royal robes.","g":"set, appointed","h":"The picture: things set out in fixed order."},"G5003":{"b":"The root pictures a man worn down under a hard load, enduring trial after trial. James tells the proud to feel it. Be miserable, mourn, weep. Stop laughing and let the full weight land on you.","g":"be afflicted","h":"The picture: worn down under a hard load."},"G5004":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is hard work. From the grind of heavy labor the word came to mean wretchedness, the worn-out misery of a hard road. Paul says ruin and misery mark the path of those who turn from God. The ache of a life ground down.","g":"misery","h":"The picture: a life ground down by hard toil."},"G5005":{"b":"Strong's builds this from a word for a weight and a word for a hard testing. The wretched man bears a heavy load through trial, worn down under it. Paul cries, wretched man that I am, who will free me. Crushed beneath a weight he cannot lift.","g":"wretched","h":"The picture: crushed under a heavy load."},"G5006":{"b":"The word comes from the word for a talent, a set weight on the scales. Abbott-Smith gives \"of a talent's weight,\" around a hundred pounds. So hailstones of a talent's weight fell from the sky and crushed the people below.","g":"a talent's weight","h":"The picture: a hailstone too heavy to lift."},"G5007":{"b":"Strong's says the word first meant a balance, the scale that holds weights. From the scale it came to mean a weight, then a large sum of money. Jesus told a parable of servants given talents.","g":"talent","h":"The picture: the weighing scale."},"G5008":{"b":"This is an Aramaic word Jesus actually spoke. Strong's says it means the fresh one, a young girl. In Mark 5:41 Jesus takes the dead child by the hand and says, Talitha koum, little girl, get up, and she rises.","g":"talitha, maiden","h":"The picture: a little girl."},"G5009":{"b":"The word is a storeroom, an inner chamber deep in the house. Abbott-Smith notes it was a place for privacy. Jesus says go into your inner room and shut the door to pray. The picture is a closed back room where no one watches.","g":"inner room, closet","h":"The picture: the inner room of the house."},"G501":{"b":"The root is antlos, \"bilge-water in a hold,\" the dirty water pooling in the bottom of a ship. First it meant to bail that out. Then just to draw water with a bucket. So the servants draw the water Jesus turns to wine.","g":"draw water","h":"The picture: bailing water out of a ship's hold."},"G5010":{"b":"Built from a word meaning to arrange. Abbott-Smith first pictures the disposition of an army, battle array. From troops in rank it came to mean good order. Do all things properly and in order.","g":"order, arrangement","h":"The picture: troops drawn up in ranks."},"G5011":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is \"low-lying.\" Strong's: \"depressed, i.e. humiliated.\" The root idea is physically low, near the ground. From there it means low in rank or brought down, and then humble in heart.","g":"humble, lowly","h":"The picture: down low to the ground."},"G5012":{"b":"This is made from a word for low and the word for the mind. The root means depressed, brought down low. Humility is a mind held low, close to the ground, not the head lifted up. It is choosing the low place on purpose.","g":"humility","h":"The picture: a mind held low to the ground."},"G5013":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the plain sense is to make low. It is used of bringing a mountain down flat. From that comes the meaning to humble a person. To take what is high and press it down low.","g":"humble, bring low","h":"The picture: leveling a hill."},"G5014":{"b":"The root means to press down, to make low. This word is that low place, small and overlooked. Mary sings that God looked on her low estate, a poor young woman of no rank, and lifted her up from it.","g":"low estate","h":"The picture: brought down low to the ground."},"G5015":{"b":"Strong's says this word is used to stir or agitate (roil water). Think of a clear pool churned until the mud rises. That is the word for a troubled heart. Not just sad. Stirred up and cloudy.","g":"trouble, stir up","h":"The picture: water stirred up and muddy."},"G5017":{"b":"The root means to stir or agitate, to roil water, churning clear water into mud. This word turns that into a crowd. When Peter escaped the jail, there was no small stir among the guards, people churned up and troubled.","g":"stir, uproar","h":"The picture: water stirred up and muddied."},"G5018":{"b":"The word means someone of Tarsus, the city in Asia Minor. It is Paul's own label. I am a Jew of Tarsus, he tells the tribune, a citizen of no ordinary city. The Lord tells Ananias to find Saul of Tarsus praying.","g":"of Tarsus","h":"The picture: the man from Tarsus."},"G5019":{"b":"This is the name of a city in Asia Minor, the town Paul came from. A place on the map, with no picture folded inside the word itself for us to see.","flat":1,"g":"Tarsus","h":"No picture."},"G502":{"b":"From a word meaning to draw water. An antlema is the thing you draw with, a bucket. Sir, you have nothing to draw with, the woman said, and the well is deep. Yet Jesus offered her living water.","g":"thing to draw with","h":"The picture: a bucket lowered down the well."},"G5020":{"b":"This comes from Tartarus, the Greek name for the lowest dungeon of the underworld. So the word means to cast into that pit. Peter says God did not spare the angels who sinned but threw them there in chains.","g":"cast to hell","h":"The picture: throwing down into the deep pit."},"G5021":{"b":"Abbott: \"to draw up in order, arrange in place.\" The first sense is military. The picture is troops lined up in their ranks. From setting soldiers in place the word means to appoint someone to a task or position.","g":"appoint, arrange","h":"The picture: soldiers drawn up in their ranks."},"G5022":{"b":"This is just the word for a bull, a full-grown ox. In the feast the king's oxen and fatted beasts are killed for the table. In Hebrews it is the bulls whose blood, poured out year on year, could never truly take away sin.","g":"bull, ox","h":"The picture: a bull led to the altar."},"G5027":{"b":"The root means to perform funeral rites, to bury. This word is the burial itself. In Matthew 27:7 the priests use Judas's silver to buy the potter's field as a place to bury strangers.","g":"burial","h":"The picture: laying a body in the ground."},"G5028":{"b":"The root means to bury, to lay in the ground with funeral rites. A taphos is the grave itself, the tomb. You are like whitewashed tombs, Jesus tells them, clean on the outside but full of dead men's bones. The stone chamber for the dead.","g":"grave, tomb","h":"The picture: the cut stone where a body is laid."},"G5029":{"b":"The root means swift, quick, fleet of foot. From the sense of something soon came the meaning perhaps, maybe. Paul says perhaps someone would dare to die for a good man. The word carries a quickness, a maybe that could arrive at any moment.","g":"perhaps","h":"The picture: fleet of foot."},"G503":{"b":"This joins anti, against, to ophthalmos, the eye. It means to face something eye to eye. Sailors used it for a ship beating up against the wind, meeting it head-on. Paul's ship could not face the wind this way, so they let it drive them. The word is eye against eye.","g":"face the wind","h":"The picture: looking the wind straight in the eye."},"G5030":{"b":"The root means fleet, quick on the feet. This is the adverb quickly, hastily. Abbott notes it can carry a hint of rashness, moving so fast you have not stopped to think.","g":"quickly","h":"The picture: at a run."},"G5031":{"b":"The root means speed, a brief space of time. This is swift, of swift approach. Peter feels it two ways: his own death is coming soon, and false teachers bring swift destruction on themselves. Something that will be here before you are ready.","g":"swift","h":"The picture: coming on fast."},"G5032":{"b":"The comparative of the word for swift, meaning more quickly. Picture John outrunning Peter to the empty tomb, reaching it tachion, sooner, because love ran faster that morning, John 20:4. This is the word for the quicker foot.","g":"more quickly","h":"The picture: the quicker foot."},"G5034":{"b":"The root means fleet, quick. This is swiftness, speed itself. In the phrase in speed it means quickly, soon. The things that must shortly come to pass. Haste built into the word.","g":"speed","h":"The picture: at full speed."},"G5035":{"b":"The root is fleet, fast on the feet. Tachu is quickly, speedily, forthwith, no dragging of heels. The angel says go tachu and tell the disciples he is risen, and the women run. And the risen Christ keeps promising, behold, I come tachu.","g":"quickly","h":"The picture: fast on the feet."},"G5036":{"b":"The word means quick, swift, speedy. James says let every man be swift to hear, slow to speak, slow to anger. It is the speed of someone who moves the moment they are called, with no delay between hearing and acting.","g":"swift","h":"The picture: quick off the mark."},"G5038":{"b":"A wall, especially the one ringing a town. Abbott lands there. It is the wall Paul was lowered down in a basket to escape, and the great wall of the new Jerusalem. The barrier around a city.","g":"wall","h":"The picture: the city wall."},"G5039":{"b":"This word comes from an old word for a mark or sign. It means proof so solid it settles the question. Luke says the risen Jesus showed himself alive by many such proofs over forty days. Not a hint. A clinching sign.","g":"proof","h":"The picture: a fixed mark that settles it."},"G504":{"b":"The word is no plus water. It means waterless, dry, a parched place. Jesus says the unclean spirit wanders through waterless places seeking rest and finds none. Picture cracked, dusty ground where nothing drinks and nothing grows.","g":"waterless, dry","h":"The picture: dry ground with no water."},"G5040":{"b":"This is the small form of the word for child, like saying little one. It is what a parent calls a small child, a term of endearment. John uses it for grown believers. He is calling tough adults his babies, out of love.","g":"little children","h":"The picture: a father's word for his small child."},"G5041":{"b":"Teknon is a child, and the rest comes from a word for bringing to birth. So it is bearing children. Paul says he wants the younger widows to marry and bear children and keep a house, giving no cause for slander.","g":"bear children","h":"The picture: bringing children into the world."},"G5042":{"b":"Teknon is a child, and the rest comes from a word for bringing to birth. So it is childbearing, a mother bringing her child into the world. Paul says she shall be kept safe through childbearing, if they continue in faith.","g":"childbearing","h":"The picture: a mother bringing a child to birth."},"G5043":{"b":"Abbott defines it as that which is begotten, born. The word looks back at birth, not at age or size.\n\nSo children of God is not a soft phrase. It says where you came from.","g":"child","h":"The picture: the one who was born."},"G5044":{"b":"This joins teknon, a child, and trepho, to feed and nourish. So it is rearing children, feeding them along until they are grown. Paul lists it among the good works that mark a widow worthy of honor.","g":"raise children","h":"The picture: feeding children up to grown."},"G5045":{"b":"A tekton is a craftsman, especially one who works wood, the carpenter with his tools and timber. It is the trade the town knew Jesus by. They ask, is this not the carpenter, and take offense at him.","g":"carpenter","h":"The picture: the craftsman shaping wood."},"G5046":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means having reached its end, finished, mature.\n\nOf people it is full-grown, and he sets it opposite the word for an infant. Perfect here does not mean flawless. It means done growing.","g":"complete, mature","h":"The picture: fully grown."},"G5047":{"b":"The root means complete, full-grown, the way a grown man is finished where a child still has growing to do. This word is that completeness. Paul says love is the bond that ties everything together in perfect unity. The finished state, with nothing missing.","g":"completeness","h":"The picture: full-grown, nothing left to add."},"G5048":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives the sense as bringing to maturity or completeness. Full grown, finished, arrived at what it was for.\n\nSo perfect here is not flawless. It is a thing that has reached its end and stopped growing.","g":"make complete","h":"The picture: grown all the way up."},"G5049":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning complete, finished. Abbott gives completely, perfectly. So it is being carried all the way to the end. Peter says set your hope fully, without wavering, on the grace that is coming.","g":"completely","h":"The picture: carried all the way to the finish."},"G505":{"b":"The root is the word for an actor deciding to speak or act under a false part, playing a role on stage. Put \"not\" in front and you have a person with no mask on. So anupokritos love is real love, not a part played for show.","g":"sincere, unfeigned","h":"The picture: a face with no mask on."},"G5050":{"b":"The word means completion, a thing brought all the way to its end. Abbott-Smith ties it to the verb for finishing. Elizabeth blesses Mary for trusting that what the Lord promised would be done, run right through to the finish.","g":"completion","h":"The picture: reaching the finish line."},"G5051":{"b":"This word means the one who finishes. It comes from a word meaning to complete, to carry a thing all the way to its end. Hebrews says Jesus does not just start faith in you. He runs it clear to the finish line.","g":"finisher","h":"The picture: the one who runs it to the finish line."},"G5052":{"b":"This word joins completion and to carry. Abbott-Smith gives it as to bring fruit to perfection. The seed among thorns sprouts and even sets fruit, but the cares and pleasures of life choke it before the fruit ever ripens.","g":"bring fruit to perfection","h":"The picture: fruit ripening all the way to full."},"G5053":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means to complete or finish, and especially \"to complete life,\" which is to die. So death here is a life brought to its end, the last page written and the book closed.","g":"die","h":"The picture: finishing your life."},"G5054":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to finish. Abbott gives the end of life, death. So death is a life reaching its finish. Joseph kept the child in Egypt until the end of Herod, until the old king's death.","g":"death","h":"The picture: the finish line of a life."},"G5055":{"b":"This word means to bring a thing to its end. Abbott-Smith notes it also plainly means to pay, as with the temple tax in Matthew 17.\n\nSo finished can mean settled in full.","g":"finish, complete","h":"The picture: the bill paid off."},"G5056":{"b":"Strong's says this is properly the point aimed at as a limit, and traces it to setting out for a definite goal.\n\nSo the end is not just where things stop. It is what they were headed for.","g":"end, goal","h":"The picture: the mark you were aiming at."},"G5057":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives the first sense as a farmer of taxes. The Gospel word is his subordinate, who collected taxes or tolls in one district.\n\nAbbott-Smith notes the phrase that keeps coming back. Tax collectors and sinners.","g":"tax collector","h":"The picture: the man who bought the tax rights."},"G5058":{"b":"This is the toll house, the booth where the collector sat beside the road and took the money. Matthew was sitting at his when Jesus said follow me. He got up and left the booth behind.","g":"tax booth","h":"The picture: the tax booth by the road."},"G5059":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means a wonder, marvel. Strong's calls its origin uncertain. It names something amazing that makes people stare, but the word carries no image of its own.","flat":1,"g":"wonder, marvel","h":"No picture."},"G506":{"b":"The root means to arrange under, to place in order beneath. With \"not\" in front it means unarranged, out of rank. It describes people who will not be put under any order, unruly and insubordinate. The law is laid down for them.","g":"unruly","h":"The picture: the soldier who won't fall into rank."},"G5060":{"b":"His Latin name simply means third, likely a third-born son or slave. Tertius was the man who actually wrote Romans down as Paul spoke it. He signs his own greeting into the letter.","g":"Tertius","h":"The picture: the third child."},"G5061":{"b":"Just a name, Tertullus, the hired speaker who accused Paul before the governor. Strong's says its origin is uncertain. A name has nothing behind it to picture.","flat":1,"g":"Tertullus","h":"No picture."},"G5062":{"b":"The word is the tens of tessares, four, ten fours making forty. Abbott simply gives forty. So forty days in the wilderness, forty years in the desert, the number falls again and again on the seasons of testing that stretch just long enough to try a soul.","g":"forty","h":"The picture: forty counted out."},"G5063":{"b":"The word joins forty and year: of forty years, forty years old. Stephen uses it of Moses, who at forty turned to visit his brothers. Paul uses it of the wilderness, forty years God bore with the people. Long enough to shape or waste a life.","g":"forty years","h":"The picture: a full forty years."},"G5064":{"b":"This is the number four. Strong's calls it a plural number and says nothing more. Abbott adds only a list of verses. There is nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"four","h":"No picture."},"G5065":{"b":"The word means fourteenth. Luke counts with it through Paul's shipwreck: when the fourteenth night came, still driven across the sea, the sailors sensed land. On that fourteenth day Paul urged them all to eat. A number marking how long the terror dragged on.","g":"fourteenth","h":"The picture: the fourteenth night at sea."},"G5066":{"b":"This word is built on the word for four. It means four days along. Martha uses it of Lazarus, four days dead. In her world that was past all hope, well beyond any waking. The number marks how far gone he was.","g":"fourth day","h":"The picture: the fourth day in the grave."},"G5067":{"b":"This simply means fourth, built on the number four. In Matthew the fourth watch is the last stretch of night, just before dawn. That is when Jesus came walking on the sea. A plain number marking the darkest hour.","g":"fourth","h":"The picture: the fourth watch."},"G5068":{"b":"The word joins \"four\" to the word for angle or corner. Abbott-Smith gives \"square.\" Picture a shape with four equal corners. So the holy city lies foursquare, its length and its width exactly the same.","g":"foursquare","h":"The picture: a perfect square."},"G5069":{"b":"The word comes from 'four.' A quaternion is a squad of four Roman soldiers. Herod hands Peter over to four such squads, sixteen men in all, to guard one sleeping prisoner.","g":"quaternion","h":"The picture: four soldiers standing guard."},"G507":{"b":"Abbott traces it to ἀνά, up. The word simply means up or above. In John 2 the servants fill the stone jars \"up to the brim,\" and this is the word marking the very top.","g":"up, above","h":"The picture: up to the brim."},"G5070":{"b":"Four times a thousand. Abbott points to the hillside where Jesus fed four thousand men from seven loaves, Matthew 15:38. Picture that crowd, four ranks of a thousand, all seated and all fed and none of them sent away hungry.","g":"four thousand","h":"The picture: four ranks of a thousand, all fed."},"G5071":{"b":"Four hundred. Stephen recalls that Abraham's offspring would be strangers and afflicted four hundred years, Acts 7:6. Picture four centuries of waiting in a foreign land before God brought them out. The plain number holds a long, hard silence.","g":"four hundred","h":"The picture: four centuries of waiting."},"G5072":{"b":"This joins four and month. Abbott gives of four months, four months. So it counts the calendar. You say there are four months and then the harvest, Jesus tells them, but lift your eyes, the fields are already white.","g":"four months","h":"The picture: four months on the calendar."},"G5073":{"b":"Built from the word for four. Fourfold means four times over. Zacchaeus stood and said if he had cheated anyone he would restore it four times as much. Picture one taken and four handed back.","g":"fourfold","h":"The picture: one coin paid back as four."},"G5074":{"b":"This word is built from the words for four and foot. A four-footed animal. In Peter's vision the sheet came down from heaven full of four-footed beasts, and a voice said rise, kill, and eat.","g":"four-footed beast","h":"The picture: an animal on four feet."},"G5075":{"b":"The word means to be a tetrarch, and the root tells you a tetrarch is the ruler of a fourth part of a country. Herod's kingdom was split into pieces, and each man governed his own quarter. To rule one slice of a divided land.","g":"be tetrarch","h":"The picture: the ruler of one quarter of the land."},"G5076":{"b":"The word joins \"four\" to \"rule.\" A tetrarch is the governor of a fourth part of a region, a man handed one slice of a kingdom split four ways. It marks Herod as a small ruler, not a king over the whole.","g":"tetrarch","h":"The picture: one ruler over a quarter of the land."},"G5077":{"b":"The root is ashes. So the word means to burn something to ash. Peter says God turned Sodom and Gomorrah to ashes, making them a warning to all who would live ungodly.","g":"turn to ashes","h":"The picture: burning a city down to ashes."},"G5078":{"b":"This word comes from a word meaning to produce or bring forth, as a mother or the earth brings forth. Techne is skill that makes a thing, a trade of the hands. Paul worked his, making tents, and the silversmiths worked theirs.","g":"craft, trade","h":"The picture: the hands that make a thing."},"G5079":{"b":"This comes from techne, \"art (as productive), i.e. (specially), a trade, or (generally) skill,\" the root of our word technical. A technites is a hands-on craftsman. Demetrius the silversmith was one. And God is called this, whose city has foundations.","g":"craftsman, builder","h":"The picture: a skilled worker at his trade."},"G508":{"b":"Two words: \"up\" and \"ground\". Put together it means above the ground, the upper floor of a house. Strong's calls it the second floor. Jesus sends the disciples to a large upper room, furnished and ready, to eat the Passover.","g":"upper room","h":"The picture: a room up above the ground."},"G5080":{"b":"The word means to liquefy, to melt down, to melt away. Peter says the heavens will be set ablaze and the elements will melt with the heat on the day of God. Everything solid runs like wax.","g":"melt","h":"The picture: metal melting down in the heat."},"G5081":{"b":"The word joins afar with a ray of light. It means seeing sharp and bright even at a distance. In Mark 8:25 Jesus touches the blind man's eyes a second time, and now he sees everything clearly, far and near.","g":"clearly","h":"The picture: light shining clear from far off."},"G5083":{"b":"Strong's is exact. This is guarding by keeping the eye upon something. A different word means stopping it escaping. Another means walls and soldiers.\n\nThis one is a watchman looking. Keep my commandments means watch them.","g":"keep, guard","h":"The picture: keeping your eye on it."},"G5084":{"b":"The root means to guard something by keeping the eye upon it. This word turns that watching into a place. A prison is where eyes stay on you. So the apostles were put in teresis, under guard, watched.","g":"prison, hold","h":"The picture: an eye kept on you so you cannot leave."},"G5085":{"b":"Strong's traces this name back to the river Tiberis, the Tiber, in Rome. Herod built the town and named it for the emperor Tiberius, who was named for that river. A Roman name pinned onto a Galilee lake.","g":"Tiberias","h":"The picture: a Roman name on a Galilee lake."},"G5086":{"b":"This is just the name of the emperor Tiberius. Strong's says it is of Latin origin, perhaps tied to the river Tiber. Even so, here it only names the man on the throne. There is no picture to draw.","flat":1,"g":"Tiberius","h":"No picture."},"G5087":{"b":"Strong's is careful here. This word puts a thing in a horizontal posture. A different word is for setting something upright.\n\nSo it is laying down, not standing up. Jesus lays down his life with this word behind it.","g":"put, place","h":"The picture: laying something down flat."},"G5088":{"b":"Strong's says to produce, from seed, as a mother, a plant, or the earth.\n\nAbbott-Smith notes the same word is used of ground bringing up plants and of desire giving birth to sin. One process, many places.","g":"give birth","h":"The picture: a mother giving birth."},"G5089":{"b":"This means to pluck, to pull off. The disciples plucked the ears of grain and rubbed them in their hands. A small tearing motion, pulling the head from the stalk. That is the word for what they did that Sabbath.","g":"pluck","h":"The picture: pulling the heads off the stalks."},"G509":{"b":"The word means from above, from the top. The temple curtain tore from above to the bottom. The same word means \"again,\" and Jesus told Nicodemus he must be born from above.","g":"from above, again","h":"The picture: from the top down."},"G5090":{"b":"Strong's marks this as an Israelite, a name of Aramaic form whose meaning the sources leave unsure. So the picture is the man himself, the father named in his son's title. Blind Bartimaeus sat begging by the Jericho road, son of Timaeus.","g":"Timaeus","h":"The picture: the father in the blind man's name."},"G5091":{"b":"Abbott-Smith puts the money sense first. To fix the value, price. The one place it means that in the New Testament is the price put on Christ.\n\nHis second sense is to honour. To honour someone is to say what they are worth.","g":"honour","h":"The picture: setting the price."},"G5092":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is a valuing, and then a price paid or received. This is money language.\n\nThe same word means honour. To honour someone is to put a high price on them.","g":"honour, price","h":"The picture: the price on the tag."},"G5093":{"b":"This comes from a word for worth. Abbott-Smith says it is used primarily of money value, of something that costs. So a precious thing is one you would pay for. It can be a costly jewel or a person held in honor.","g":"precious, costly","h":"The picture: it carries a price."},"G5094":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning valuable, costly. Abbott gives preciousness, worth. So the picture is a heavy price. The sea merchants weep over Babylon, over all her costliness laid waste in a single hour.","g":"costliness","h":"The picture: a heavy price tag."},"G5095":{"b":"Strong's says this Greek name is built from two words, one for honour and one for God, and gives the meaning as dear to God.\n\nAbbott-Smith records no origin. So this is Strong's reading of an ordinary Greek name.","g":"Timothy","h":"The picture: dear to God."},"G5096":{"b":"This name comes from the word for value or honor, the worth set on a thing. It means valuable, honored. Timon was one of the seven chosen to serve in the early church. His name marks a thing held precious.","g":"Timon","h":"The picture: something worth a good price."},"G5097":{"b":"This word is built from two things, honor and a guard. Underneath punishing a wrong lies the idea of guarding someone's honor. To punish is to stand watch over what was trampled, and to answer the insult done to it.","g":"punish","h":"The picture: a guard set over honor."},"G5098":{"b":"The root means to guard one's honor and so to avenge. This word grew to mean the penalty itself. How much worse the punishment for those who trample the Son of God underfoot.","g":"punishment","h":"The picture: the avenging of a wrong."},"G5099":{"b":"This is a paying word. It means to pay a price, but as a penalty, settling a debt of punishment. Paul says those who reject the gospel shall pay the penalty, everlasting destruction from the face of the Lord.","g":"pay the penalty","h":"The picture: paying the penalty owed."},"G51":{"b":"This comes from the word not to know. It is a fault done in ignorance, a wrong committed without meaning to. Once a year the high priest offered blood for his own and the people's sins of ignorance.","g":"sin of ignorance","h":"The picture: the wrong done without knowing."},"G510":{"b":"This word means upper, and locally more remote. It points to the higher, inland country above the coast road. Paul came down through that high country and reached Ephesus.","g":"upper","h":"The picture: the high inland country."},"G5102":{"b":"The word comes from the Latin titulus, a notice board. Abbott says \"a title, inscription.\" Pilate wrote one and fixed it to the cross, King of the Jews, in three languages, so everyone passing could read the charge.","g":"title, placard","h":"The picture: a written placard nailed up for all to read."},"G5103":{"b":"This is a man's name, Paul's companion. Strong's says it is of Latin origin but uncertain significance. No one knows what it means, so there is nothing to see behind it.","flat":1,"g":"Titus","h":"No picture."},"G5109":{"b":"This is a wall, the side wall of a house. Paul turns on the high priest and calls him a whitewashed wall, white paint over rot. The image is a wall that looks clean on the outside. The word gives you the wall to picture.","g":"wall","h":"The picture: the wall of a house."},"G511":{"b":"The root means upward, on top. Abbott's first sense is \"of motion, higher.\" Jesus says take the low place, then be told to move up higher at the table. It is the better seat, further up.","g":"higher, above","h":"The picture: moving up to a higher seat."},"G5110":{"b":"The root is tikto, to give birth. Tokos first meant offspring, what is born. Then it meant interest, money that breeds more money. Jesus says the servant should at least have put the coin to the bankers to come back with its offspring.","g":"interest, usury","h":"The picture: money giving birth to more money."},"G5111":{"b":"Abbott points to Joseph of Arimathea, who took courage and went in to Pilate to beg for the body of Jesus. That is tolmaō. Not merely feeling brave but doing the risky thing, stepping through a door you could be killed for opening.","g":"to dare","h":"The picture: stepping through a dangerous door."},"G5112":{"b":"This word just means more daringly, with greater confidence. Its root only means bold, an attitude with nothing to see. Paul says he has written the more boldly to the Romans on some points. There is no thing behind it.","flat":1,"g":"more boldly","h":"No picture."},"G5113":{"b":"The root means to venture, to dare. So this is a bold, reckless man. Peter uses it of the false teachers, presumptuous and self-willed, not even afraid to slander angelic beings.","g":"daring man","h":"The picture: the man who dares anything."},"G5114":{"b":"This word means sharp, and here sharper. Strong's says it cuts as if by a single stroke, not by hacking blows. God's word is sharper than any two-edged sword, cutting clean and deep.","g":"sharper","h":"The picture: the blade that cuts in one clean stroke."},"G5115":{"b":"The word plainly means a bow, the weapon that shoots arrows. Abbott-Smith gives just \"a bow.\" Picture the curved wood strung tight, ready to fire. So the rider on the white horse carries a bow and goes out to conquer.","g":"a bow","h":"The picture: an archer's bow."},"G5116":{"b":"The word means topaz. Strong's says it is probably the chrysolite, a clear yellow stone. Picture a gem catching light like pale gold. So topaz was the ninth foundation of the city wall.","g":"topaz","h":"The picture: a topaz stone."},"G5117":{"b":"Abbott quotes a good definition. A portion of space viewed by what occupies it.\n\nOther Greek words mean a region or a field. This one is a spot, defined by whatever is standing there.","g":"place, spot","h":"The picture: the space a thing takes up."},"G5119":{"b":"Abbott gives then, at that time, whether of past events or things still to come. The word drops a pin on the timeline and says right there. So Matthew's then nails the story to a moment, one thing happening hard after another.","g":"then","h":"The picture: a pin dropped on the timeline."},"G512":{"b":"This word joins \"not\" with a word meaning helpful and serviceable. Something useless gives no service, like a tool that will not do the job it was made for. Hebrews calls the old commandment weak and unprofitable, and so set aside.","g":"useless, unprofitable","h":"The picture: a tool that does no work."},"G5121":{"b":"This is a run-together of the and enantion, which means facing, over against. Picture standing face to face on the opposite side. So the word means the other way round. Instead of punishing the man, Paul says, you should rather forgive him.","g":"on the contrary","h":"The picture: standing face to face."},"G5122":{"b":"This is two words squeezed into one, the and name. It means simply by name. So it works like a name tag pinned on. Matthew brings in a rich man of Arimathea, Joseph by name, who came for the body of Jesus.","g":"named","h":"The picture: a name tag pinned on."},"G513":{"b":"An axine is an axe. Strong's links it to a word for breaking, the tool that splits wood. John says the axe is already lying at the root of the trees. Not the branches, the root. Any tree that bears no good fruit gets cut down and burned.","g":"an axe","h":"The picture: the axe laid to the root."},"G5131":{"b":"A tragos is a male goat. Strong's links the name to gnawing, the craunching sound of the animal chewing. Hebrews says the blood of goats could never take away sins. Year after year the goats died, and the guilt stayed. Something better was needed.","g":"a he-goat","h":"The picture: the he-goat."},"G5132":{"b":"Strong's says the word describes the table as being four-legged. It is furniture, plain and sturdy. It also names the money-changer's counter, a table used as a bank. Jesus overturned those tables in the temple.","g":"table","h":"The picture: the four-legged stand."},"G5133":{"b":"The root is a table, named for its four legs. The banker was the man at the table where coins were counted and lent. In Matthew 25:27 the master says the lazy servant should at least have put the money with the bankers to earn interest.","g":"banker, money-changer","h":"The picture: the money-changer at his table."},"G5134":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives one word: a wound. Our word trauma comes straight from it. The robbers' victim lay covered in wounds, and the Samaritan cleaned and bound each one before carrying him off to shelter.","g":"wound","h":"The picture: an open wound."},"G5135":{"b":"The root is the Greek word for a wound, the one behind our word trauma. Abbott simply says \"to wound.\" In the story the tenants beat the owner's servant and send him away wounded. Real cuts on a real body.","g":"wound","h":"The picture: opening a wound in the flesh."},"G5136":{"b":"Strong's says this is to expose the gullet of a victim for killing, the throat bent back and bared. It came to mean laid open. Before God every hidden thing lies bare, like a throat turned up to the knife.","g":"laid open","h":"The picture: the throat bared for the knife."},"G5137":{"b":"This is the neck. The father ran and fell on his lost son's neck to embrace him. Paul says friends risked their own necks for his life. It is the place a yoke is laid, or arms are thrown in welcome. The neck bears the load, or the kiss.","g":"neck","h":"The picture: arms thrown around the neck."},"G5138":{"b":"Strong's ties it to a word for breaking or cracking, as if the ground were jagged with rents. It means rough, rocky. Luke quotes Isaiah: the rough roads will be made smooth, the broken ground levelled to welcome the Lord.","g":"rough, rocky","h":"The picture: jagged, broken ground."},"G5139":{"b":"This region's name comes from a word meaning uneven and rocky. Trachonitis was the broken, boulder-strewn land south of Damascus. Luke lists it among the districts ruled when John began to preach. The name itself paints the ground.","g":"Trachonitis","h":"The picture: rough, rocky country."},"G514":{"b":"Abbott-Smith traces this word to a verb used in the sense to weigh, and his first sense is of weight, worth.\n\nWorthy means it weighs the same as the thing set against it. It balances out.","g":"worthy","h":"The picture: the scales balance."},"G5140":{"b":"Strong's calls it a primary plural number. Abbott gives no origin at all. It is the number three, and there is nothing standing behind it to look at.","flat":1,"g":"three","h":"No picture."},"G5141":{"b":"This means to tremble, to shake, especially with fear. The woman who had touched Jesus, knowing what had happened to her, came and fell down before him trembling. The word is the shaking you cannot hold still, fear moving through the limbs.","g":"tremble","h":"The picture: the body shaking with fear."},"G5142":{"b":"This means to feed and make grow, to rear a child. Abbott-Smith notes it is used of animals, to fatten. James warns the rich that they have fattened their hearts for a day of slaughter.","g":"feed, nourish, rear","h":"The picture: fattening up."},"G5143":{"b":"The word means to run. Abbott-Smith points out where the figure comes from. Runners in a race, used of swiftness or of effort to reach an end.\n\nPaul uses it of his own work. Even a message can run.","g":"run","h":"The picture: the runner in a race."},"G5144":{"b":"The root is three, ten times over for thirty. It is the wage Judas took to hand Jesus over, thirty pieces of silver, the price once set for a gored slave. The good soil yields thirtyfold. And Jesus was about thirty when he began his work.","g":"thirty","h":"The picture: the wage paid for betrayal."},"G5145":{"b":"The number three hundred. In Mark it prices the alabaster jar: this perfume could have been sold for three hundred denarii and given to the poor. Nearly a year's wages poured out on Jesus in a moment. A count measuring both waste and worship.","g":"three hundred","h":"The picture: three hundred days' wages."},"G5146":{"b":"The word joins three and a spear point. It named a caltrop, a spiked thing thrown in war that always lands point up, then a thorny plant with the same bite, a thistle. Jesus says grapes do not come from thistles. What grows tells you what the plant is.","g":"a thistle","h":"The picture: the three-pointed thorn."},"G5147":{"b":"Strong's says this is a rut or worn track, from a word meaning to rub. It is the trail rubbed smooth and bare by feet passing over it again and again. Make his paths straight, John cries. Clear the beaten track for the Lord.","g":"path","h":"The picture: a path worn into the ground."},"G5148":{"b":"Two words, three and a year. A stretch of three full years marked off. Paul reminded the elders that for three years, night and day, he had not stopped warning each one of them with tears.","g":"three years","h":"The picture: three turnings of the year."},"G5149":{"b":"The word first means to creak or squeak, a grating sound. Used of teeth it is the grinding gnash. In Mark 9:18 the father says the spirit throws his son down, and he foams and grinds his teeth and goes stiff.","g":"gnash, grind","h":"The picture: the harsh grinding of teeth."},"G515":{"b":"The root means worth that is comparable or suitable, as if it measures up on the scale. To deem someone worthy, to count them fit. The centurion said he was not worthy to have Jesus under his roof. Weighed and found to match.","g":"deem worthy","h":"The picture: measured and found to match."},"G5150":{"b":"This joins three and month. Abbott gives a space of three months. So it marks time on the calendar. By faith Moses was hidden three months by his parents, who saw the child was beautiful and feared no king.","g":"three months","h":"The picture: three moons on the calendar."},"G5151":{"b":"The root is three. Tris means three times over. The cock will not crow, Jesus says, before you deny me tris, and Peter does, three times in the dark. Paul begs three times for the thorn to go, and three times over is beaten with rods.","g":"thrice","h":"The picture: three times over."},"G5152":{"b":"Two words, three and a roof. It means the third roof up, the third story of a house. Eutychus sat in a high window on that third floor, fell asleep, and dropped to the ground.","g":"third story","h":"The picture: three floors stacked."},"G5153":{"b":"This joins three times and a thousand. It counts a crowd of three thousand. So the picture is a great number gathered. At Pentecost, when Peter had spoken, three thousand received the word and were baptized in one day.","g":"three thousand","h":"The picture: three thousand added in one day."},"G5154":{"b":"This is the ordinal of treis, three. Abbott points to te trite hemera, the third day. So on the third day he rose is counted like steps, one, two, three, and on that third step the tomb stands empty.","g":"third","h":"The picture: the third in the count."},"G5155":{"b":"The word comes from the word for hair. Abbott-Smith gives \"of hair.\" Picture rough dark sackcloth woven from goat hair, the kind worn in mourning. So when the sixth seal broke, the sun turned black as that hair-cloth.","g":"of hair","h":"The picture: cloth woven from hair."},"G5156":{"b":"The root means to tremble. This is the shaking itself, the body quaking with fear. The women left the tomb with trembling. Paul came in weakness and fear and much trembling. The knees will not hold still.","g":"trembling","h":"The picture: the body shaking."},"G5157":{"b":"This means a turning, especially the wheeling of the sun and stars across the sky. They rise, cross, and set, throwing shadows as they go. James says God has no such turning. The lights move. He holds still.","g":"turning","h":"The picture: the sun wheeling across the sky."},"G5158":{"b":"Strong's says the word means a turn, and so a manner or way. It comes from the word \"to turn.\" The way you turn is your way of doing things, and even your character.","g":"manner, way","h":"The picture: which way you turn."},"G5159":{"b":"The word joins a person's manner with 'to bear as a burden.' For forty years, Paul says, God put up with Israel in the desert, carrying their habits like a weight on his back.","g":"suffer the manners","h":"The picture: carrying someone's ways like a load."},"G516":{"b":"The root means deserving, comparable, a match in worth. To walk axios of the Lord is to live so your life measures up to the name you carry. The walking matches the calling. The two weigh the same.","g":"worthily","h":"The picture: a life that measures up to the name."},"G5160":{"b":"Abbott's sense is nourishment, food, from a root meaning to feed and rear. Trophē is what keeps a body going, the daily rations. Jesus says the worker deserves his trophē, his keep, the bread that pays him for the labor.","g":"food","h":"The picture: the daily rations that keep you going."},"G5161":{"b":"This word comes from the word for nourishment and food. The name Trophimos means well-nourished, a child raised up fed and cared for. He was a companion of Paul, left sick at Miletus.","g":"Trophimus","h":"The picture: a child raised up well-fed."},"G5162":{"b":"The root trepho means to feed and nourish. A trophos is a nurse, the woman who feeds and tends a little one. Paul says he was gentle among them as a nurse cherishing her own children.","g":"nurse","h":"The picture: a nursing mother feeding her child."},"G5163":{"b":"This is the groove a cart wheel wears into the road. Follow the rut and the wheel rolls straight. Hebrews says make straight tracks for your feet, so the lame are not thrown off the way but healed.","g":"path","h":"The picture: the rut a cart wheel cuts in the road."},"G5164":{"b":"This is a wheel, named from a word meaning to run because it runs as it rolls. James says the tongue sets the whole wheel of life on fire, a blaze that spins round and round with the turning.","g":"wheel, course","h":"The picture: a wheel rolling as it runs."},"G5165":{"b":"A tryblion is a bowl or dish, the common bowl set on the table for dipping. Jesus says the one who dips his hand in the bowl with him will betray him. Sharing the same dish, and still a traitor.","g":"dish, bowl","h":"The picture: the shared bowl on the table."},"G5166":{"b":"The word means to collect the vintage, to bring in the grape harvest. Men do not gather grapes from a bramble, Jesus says. In Revelation an angel is told to gather the clusters of the earth's vine, for they are ripe. Harvest work.","g":"gather grapes","h":"The picture: cutting ripe grapes from the vine."},"G5167":{"b":"Strong's says the turtle-dove is named as cooing. The name copies the soft murmuring sound the bird makes. Mary's offering after Jesus' birth was two of them, the poor family's gift when a lamb was out of reach.","g":"turtle-dove","h":"The picture: the dove named for its cooing."},"G5168":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it is a hole, worn through by rubbing, like a rut worn into a road. Here it is the eye of a needle, that tiny gap the thread passes through. Jesus says a camel would sooner pass through it than a rich man enter God's kingdom.","g":"needle's eye","h":"The picture: the eye of a needle."},"G5169":{"b":"The word comes from a verb meaning to bore, to drill a hole. This is the hole itself, and here it is the eye of a needle. In Matthew 19:24 Jesus says a camel passing through it is easier than a rich man entering the kingdom.","g":"needle's eye","h":"The picture: the eye of a needle."},"G517":{"b":"Abbott-Smith builds this from the word for sight. The root means capable of being seen. Put not in front and you get the un-seeable. Paul calls God the invisible one. Real and present, but no eye lands on him.","g":"invisible","h":"The picture: there, but the eye finds nothing."},"G5170":{"b":"Her name comes from a word for luxury, the soft life of ease and delicacies. Yet Paul says Tryphaena labours in the Lord. A woman named for comfort who is praised for her hard work.","g":"Tryphaena","h":"The picture: soft, dainty living."},"G5171":{"b":"The word means to live soft and dainty, to feast at a full table every day. James says the rich have fattened themselves this way, faring sumptuously, on the very day of slaughter.","g":"live in pleasure","h":"The picture: feasting at a full table every day."},"G5172":{"b":"Strong's traces this to a word for being broken down and softened by indulgence. It means luxury, dainty ease. Jesus asks what the crowds went out to see: those dressed in soft luxury live in kings' palaces, not in the desert.","g":"luxury","h":"The picture: soft living in a palace."},"G5173":{"b":"Her name is built on the same word as Tryphaena's, the word for luxury and soft living. It means luxuriating. Paul names the two together and says both labour in the Lord. Names of ease, lives of work.","g":"Tryphosa","h":"The picture: living in luxury."},"G5174":{"b":"This is Troas, a city near the Hellespont by the site of old Troy. Paul sailed from here, and here he left his cloak behind. The word is the name of a place, nothing to picture.","flat":1,"g":"Troas","h":"No picture."},"G5176":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is animals gnawing, munching, crunching. The word carries the very sound of chewing. Later it just meant to eat. But when Jesus says whoever eats my flesh, this earthy word is underneath. Real chewing, not a polite figure of speech.","g":"gnaw, chew, eat","h":"The picture: teeth crunching on food."},"G5177":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this means \"to hit,\" and sets it against the word for missing the mark. So to obtain something is to hit what you aimed at. The archer's arrow lands where he meant it to.","g":"obtain, happen","h":"The picture: hitting the mark."},"G5178":{"b":"This comes from a word for a drum. Victims were stretched over a drum-shaped frame and beaten to death. Some believers were tortured this way and would not accept release, hoping for a better resurrection.","g":"torture","h":"The picture: stretched on the frame and beaten."},"G5179":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the first sense is the mark of a blow. It is used of the nail-prints in Jesus' hands. The dent a strike leaves behind. From that comes the idea of a stamp, a pattern, a model to copy.","g":"type, pattern, mark","h":"The picture: the mark left by a blow."},"G518":{"b":"Someone goes, sees, and returns to tell it. Abbott-Smith says the word is used of a messenger, speaker, or writer, to report, announce, declare.\n\nThis is plain reporting of what happened, not persuasion.","g":"report, announce","h":"The picture: coming back with word."},"G5180":{"b":"This word means to beat, to strike, to thump with blow after blow. Strong's calls it a primary verb, so it does not come from anything else. The beating is its plain meaning.","flat":1,"g":"beat, strike","h":"No picture."},"G5181":{"b":"This name means a tyrant, from the word for a lord and master. So the picture sits in the name. Yet in the lecture hall of a man called Tyrannus, Paul reasoned daily for two years, and all Asia heard the word.","g":"Tyrannus","h":"The picture: a name that means tyrant."},"G5183":{"b":"This is only the word for a Tyrian, someone from the coastal city of Tyre. It marks where a person came from and nothing more. There is no image behind it, just a town on the sea.","flat":1,"g":"Tyrian","h":"No picture."},"G5184":{"b":"The name means a rock. It comes from a word for a stone, something pressed hard or to a point. Tyre was a great Phoenician seaport built on rocky ground, famous for its trade and wealth.","g":"Tyre","h":"The picture: a rock."},"G5185":{"b":"Strong's reads this as opaque, as if smoky, and links it to a word for smoke.\n\nAbbott-Smith gives only blind, with no history at all. So the smoke belongs to Strong's, not to settled fact.","g":"blind","h":"The picture: sight gone smoky."},"G5186":{"b":"This word comes from a word meaning smoky, clouded over. To blind is to fill the eyes with smoke so no light gets through. Scripture says God blinded their eyes so they would not see and turn.","g":"to blind","h":"The picture: eyes clouded as if by smoke."},"G5187":{"b":"The root typho means to make smoke, to smolder without flame. Abbott says the word means to be wrapped in smoke. So pride is a head full of smoke, all puffed up and clouded. A new convert may be lifted up this way and fall.","g":"puffed up","h":"The picture: a head full of smoke."},"G5188":{"b":"This means to make a smoke, to smolder slowly without a flame. Matthew uses it of the smoking wick Jesus will not put out, still faintly glowing. Picture a thread of smoke off a dying flame.","g":"to smoke","h":"The picture: a wick smoldering."},"G5189":{"b":"Abbott ties this to typhon, a hurricane, a typhoon. Under it is a word for making smoke, the storm boiling up dark like smoke. A wind of this kind, tempestuous, swept down on the ship. The word is the whirlwind itself, violent and churning.","g":"tempestuous","h":"The picture: a whirlwind rolling like smoke."},"G519":{"b":"Abbott traces this to a word meaning to press or strangle, to choke off the breath. In Matthew 27:5 Judas throws down the silver and goes and hangs himself, the word underneath being this word for a throat squeezed shut.","g":"hang oneself","h":"The picture: the throat squeezed shut."},"G5190":{"b":"This name comes from a word for chance or fortune, and means fortunate. Tychicus carried Paul's letters and news between the churches, a trusted messenger. His name means lucky, the one things go well for.","g":"Tychicus","h":"The picture: the fortunate one."},"G5191":{"b":"The word comes from the hyacinth gem, deep blue. Abbott-Smith says it was \"doubtless meant to describe the blue smoke of a sulphurous flame.\" Picture dusky blue smoke curling up. So the riders' breastplates were blue like that smoke.","g":"deep blue","h":"The picture: the dark blue of smoke."},"G5192":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this was first \"a flower, prob. the dark blue iris,\" and later a blue stone. Picture the deep blue of iris petals caught in a gem. So jacinth was the eleventh foundation of the city wall.","g":"jacinth","h":"The picture: a dark blue flower."},"G5193":{"b":"The root is simply glass. This word means glassy, made of glass. John sees a sea of glass before God's throne, clear and still. No waves, no storm. Smooth as glass in front of God.","g":"glassy","h":"The picture: smooth clear glass."},"G5194":{"b":"This is glass, or a clear transparent stone you can see straight through. John says the city's street is pure gold, clear as glass. Picture something so clear the light passes right through it.","g":"glass","h":"The picture: clear glass you see through."},"G5195":{"b":"The root is insolence, the pride that lords it over another. To hybrizo is to treat someone with contempt, to insult and rough them up. The Son of Man will be hybrizo, Jesus says, mocked and shamed by men who think themselves above him.","g":"insult","h":"The picture: shoving someone with contempt."},"G5196":{"b":"This word means insolence, the overbearing kind that rides right over other people. It also names the battering a ship takes from a storm. Paul warned the voyage would bring hybris, hurt and heavy loss, and it did.","g":"insult, injury","h":"The picture: force that overbears and batters."},"G5197":{"b":"The root means to do violence, to abuse. This is the man who treats others roughly, the insolent one who insults and harms. Paul lists him among those who have turned from God. Not just proud in thought, but violent with his hands.","g":"insolent man","h":"The picture: a bully who roughs people up."},"G5198":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means to be sound and healthy in the body. Paul then stretches it to teaching. Sound doctrine is healthy teaching, the kind that keeps the church well and whole.","g":"be healthy","h":"The picture: sound and healthy."},"G5199":{"b":"Abbott says sound, whole, healthy, a body working as it should. Our word hygiene comes from it. Jesus asks the man at the pool, do you want to be made hugiēs, whole. The withered hand stretches out hugiēs. He uses it for teaching too, doctrine that is sound.","g":"sound","h":"The picture: a body working as it should."},"G52":{"b":"Built from a word meaning not to know. Abbott gives ignorance, sometimes willful blindness. Peter tells the crowd, you acted in agnoia, you did not know what you were doing, Acts 3:17. The times of ignorance God overlooked, but now calls all to turn.","g":"ignorance","h":"The picture: standing in the dark."},"G520":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means to lead away, especially of leading to trial, prison and death. Picture guards taking a man by the arm and marching him off to court. The same word marks the road that leads away to ruin.","g":"lead away","h":"The picture: a prisoner marched off."},"G5200":{"b":"The word means wet, moist, the opposite of dry. Of wood it means sappy and green, still full of life. If they do this to the green tree, Jesus said on the way to the cross, worse will come to the dry.","g":"green, moist","h":"The picture: green sappy wood."},"G5201":{"b":"The word is built from water. It is the jar a household keeps water in and carries to the well. Jesus has the servants fill six of these at Cana. The Samaritan woman leaves hers at the well and runs to tell the town.","g":"water jar","h":"The picture: a jar for carrying water."},"G5202":{"b":"This joins hydor, water, and pino, to drink. So it means to be a water-drinker, taking no wine at all. Paul tells Timothy to stop this and use a little wine for his stomach and his frequent illnesses.","g":"drink water","h":"The picture: drinking water only."},"G5203":{"b":"This word is built on the word for water. Abbott-Smith gives it as dropsical, suffering from dropsy. A man stood before Jesus with his body bloated and swollen with trapped fluid. Jesus healed him on the Sabbath and let him go.","g":"have the dropsy","h":"The picture: a body swollen full of water."},"G5204":{"b":"The word ties to the word for rain, a shower falling. Hydor is plain water, the stuff you drink and wash in. So when Jesus offers living water, he takes the most ordinary thing in the world and makes it the picture of life that never runs dry.","g":"water","h":"The picture: rain, and the water it leaves."},"G5205":{"b":"This word means rain, especially a sudden shower. It comes from a word meaning to rain. God did not leave himself without witness, giving rain from heaven and fruitful seasons. Water coming down on the ground.","g":"rain","h":"The picture: rain falling from the sky."},"G5206":{"b":"Strong's breaks this into son and to place. Adoption is the placing of someone as a son. A father takes a child who was not his and sets him in the son's own place. That is the word Paul uses for what God does with us.","g":"adoption","h":"The picture: a child set in the place of a son."},"G5207":{"b":"Strong's calls this apparently a primary word. Nothing older lies behind it. Abbott-Smith gives no origin either, only the uses: a son, and then descendants more widely. It simply means son.","flat":1,"g":"son","h":"No picture."},"G5208":{"b":"This is a forest, a stand of timber, and by turn the wood you burn. James sets a spark against it. See how small a flame, and how great a woodland it sets on fire. That is the tongue.","g":"forest, fuel","h":"The picture: a whole forest set to burn."},"G521":{"b":"The root means to train up a child, to educate. The front of the word cancels it. So this is someone never trained, untaught. Paul says to avoid ignorant arguments. They come from a mind that was never schooled.","g":"unlearned","h":"The picture: a child never taught."},"G5211":{"b":"This is a man's name. Strong's ties it to Hymen, the god of weddings. It tells you nothing true about the man, who in fact opposed the faith and wrecked the faith of others. Just a name.","flat":1,"g":"name","h":"No picture."},"G5212":{"b":"This is simply the possessive your, yours, for a group. It marks that something belongs to you rather than to another. A pointer of ownership, not a thing in itself, so there is no image here to draw.","flat":1,"g":"yours","h":"No picture."},"G5214":{"b":"The word is built from the word for a hymn, a religious ode. It means to sing praise to God. After the last supper, before they walked out to the Mount of Olives, Jesus and the disciples did this together. They sang a hymn.","g":"sing a hymn","h":"The picture: voices singing a song of praise."},"G5215":{"b":"In old Greek a hymnos was a festival song, sung in praise of gods and heroes. The root simply means to sing. In the New Testament it is a song of praise turned toward God. Words set to a tune and lifted up together.","g":"hymn","h":"The picture: a festival song of praise."},"G5217":{"b":"Strong's describes it as withdrawing, as if sinking out of sight. Quietly gone.\n\nAbbott adds something useful. It was a word of the vulgar language. Common street speech, not polished Greek.","g":"go away","h":"The picture: slipping out of sight."},"G5218":{"b":"Strong's says the word means attentive hearkening. Underneath obedience is a listening ear. You lean in, you hear, and then you do. The word joins \"under\" to \"hearing.\"","g":"obedience","h":"The picture: listening from underneath."},"G5219":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives an ordinary sense before the religious one. To answer a knock at a door.\n\nHis first entry is to listen and attend. Obedience starts as hearing. You come because someone called.","g":"obey","h":"The picture: answering the door."},"G522":{"b":"The two roots mean to lift and away. To lift a thing off and carry it off. Jesus says the day will come when the bridegroom is lifted away from them, and then they will fast. Not lost quietly, but taken.","g":"take away","h":"The picture: lifting something up and away."},"G5220":{"b":"This joins under with the word for a man. So it literally says a woman under a man, that is, a married woman. Abbott says married. Paul uses her to show how the law binds only while the husband is still alive.","g":"married woman","h":"The picture: a woman placed under a husband."},"G5221":{"b":"This is built from a word meaning opposite, facing. It means to go out and meet someone coming toward you. Abbott notes it is even used of armies meeting in battle. You do not wait. You go to meet.","g":"to meet","h":"The picture: going out to meet him face to face."},"G5222":{"b":"This is going out to meet a person, not waiting at home. You see them coming down the road and you step out to greet them. The virgins go out with their lamps to meet the bridegroom. It is the step toward the one arriving.","g":"meeting","h":"The picture: walking out to meet someone coming."},"G5223":{"b":"The root means to come into existence, to be present or at hand. So hyparxis is what is actually at hand: your property, your wealth. Not money in theory but goods you can point to. When the first believers gave up their property, they gave up things they could touch.","g":"property, wealth","h":"The picture: everything you own, spread out at hand."},"G5225":{"b":"Not simply to be. Abbott-Smith says this word expresses continuance of an antecedent state or condition. It looks back at what was already true.\n\nPaul uses it of Christ, and one version renders it being originally in the form of God.","g":"to be, exist","h":"The picture: being there already."},"G5226":{"b":"Under this word lies a sense of yielding, giving way. Strong's calls it a surrender. Picture a man who steps back and lets another pass. Hebrews says yield to those who lead you. Stop pushing against them.","g":"submit","h":"The picture: stepping back and giving way."},"G5227":{"b":"This word is built on a root meaning opposite, standing face to face. With \"under\" added, it is the opponent set against you across the field. Colossians says the record of debt stood opposed to us, then was nailed to the cross. The enemy that once faced us down.","g":"adversary, opposed","h":"The picture: the one standing against you."},"G5229":{"b":"The roots are huper, over, and airo, to lift. So the word is to lift yourself up over everyone else. Pride is raising your own head above the crowd. Paul was given a thorn so he would not be lifted up too high.","g":"exalt self","h":"The picture: lifting yourself over others."},"G523":{"b":"The root means to ask, and \"back\" turns it into demanding a thing returned. Jesus says when someone takes what is yours, do not demand it back. The same word names the night a man's own life is demanded back from him.","g":"demand back","h":"The picture: a hand held out demanding it back."},"G5230":{"b":"Abbott gives it as past the bloom of youth. It pictures a flower whose blossom has passed its peak and begun to fade. Paul uses it of a young woman no longer in her first prime.","g":"past the prime","h":"The picture: the blossom past its peak."},"G5232":{"b":"Auxano is the word for a plant growing and enlarging. Hyper piles over on top of it. So it is growth that runs beyond the ordinary. Paul thanks God the Thessalonians' faith grows exceedingly, more than expected.","g":"grow exceedingly","h":"The picture: a plant shooting up past its size."},"G5233":{"b":"This joins hyper, over, and baino, to step. So it is putting your foot past the boundary, stepping over the mark. Paul warns no man should overstep and cheat his brother in business. The line is there to be kept.","g":"overstep","h":"The picture: stepping over the line."},"G5234":{"b":"The root means to hurl beyond where others land, to surpass. Abbott-Smith gives above measure. Paul says his beatings and imprisonments went far past anyone else's, thrown well beyond the normal count.","g":"beyond measure","h":"The picture: a throw that sails clean past the usual mark."},"G5235":{"b":"The word is over plus throw. Abbott-Smith says to throw over or beyond. Picture a throw that flies past where anyone else landed. Paul uses it of a love and a power that overshoot every limit, going further than the eye expected.","g":"exceed, surpass","h":"The picture: a throw that sails past the mark."},"G5236":{"b":"This is literally a throwing beyond, like a javelin that flies past every other cast. Our word hyperbole comes from it. Paul uses it for grace and power that go past all measure. It overshoots, beyond where anyone can reach.","g":"exceeding, excellence","h":"The picture: a throw that sails past every mark."},"G5237":{"b":"The word means to overlook, to let your eyes slide past a thing and not stop on it. It is built on over. God overlooked the times of ignorance and now calls all men to turn.","g":"overlook","h":"The picture: the gaze passing over."},"G5239":{"b":"The roots are beyond and stretch out. Abbott-Smith says to stretch out overmuch. Paul says he is not overreaching his bounds to claim them. They really do fall inside the field God gave him.","g":"stretch beyond","h":"The picture: an arm reaching so far it strains past its length."},"G524":{"b":"Built from a word meaning to smart or feel pain, with away in front. It means to cease to feel pain for, to grow callous, like a hand so hardened it feels nothing. Paul says some lose all feeling and give themselves to sin.","g":"past feeling","h":"The picture: skin gone numb."},"G5240":{"b":"This word stacks over onto pour out. Abbott-Smith reads it as to pour out over, to overflow, run over. It is the measure filled so full it spills down the sides. That is how Luke pictures the way God gives to you.","g":"run over","h":"The picture: a cup filled past the brim."},"G5241":{"b":"The root means to meet with someone, to entreat them. Add the word for over or for the sake of. So it is to plead for another. Abbott says to intercede or make petition for. Paul says the Spirit pleads for us with groans too deep for words.","g":"intercede","h":"The picture: stepping in to plead on your behalf."},"G5242":{"b":"The word is over plus hold. Abbott-Smith says to rise above, to overtop. Picture one thing lifted higher than all the rest, like a peak over the plain. Paul uses it of the governing authorities and of Christ, who tops them all.","g":"excel, surpass","h":"The picture: held up over everything around it."},"G5243":{"b":"The root means appearing above others, showing yourself over their heads. That is pride, looking down on people. In Mark 7:22 Jesus lists it among the evils that come out of the human heart and defile a person.","g":"pride","h":"The picture: holding yourself above the crowd."},"G5244":{"b":"Built from a word meaning above and a word meaning to show or shine. The proud man shows himself off above everyone else, head lifted over the crowd. God scatters the proud in the thoughts of their hearts.","g":"proud","h":"The picture: showing yourself off above the crowd."},"G5245":{"b":"The root means to conquer, to subdue. Add the word for over and beyond. So it is to win overwhelmingly, more than a conqueror. Abbott says to be more than conqueror. Paul says in all these hardships we are more than conquerors through the one who loved us.","g":"more than conqueror","h":"The picture: winning far past a bare victory."},"G5246":{"b":"The root is a mass that bulges under its own load. Add over and it swells too big. So the words of these men are puffed up, great swelling speech, bigger than the truth inside them.","g":"swelling, insolent","h":"The picture: a swollen, over-loaded mass."},"G5247":{"b":"The word first meant a projection or height, the peak of a mountain, from holding itself above the rest. It came to mean high rank. Paul asks prayer for kings and all who are in that high place.","g":"excellency","h":"The picture: the peak of a mountain."},"G5248":{"b":"The base means to overflow, to spill past the brim, and the front piece means over and beyond. Where sin increased, grace overflowed even more, past all measure. A cup already full and still pouring over the edge.","g":"overflow","h":"The picture: a cup running over."},"G5249":{"b":"This joins over and abundantly. It pictures a cup filled past the brim, spilling over the top. So it means beyond all measure. The crowd was astonished beyond measure, saying Jesus has done all things well.","g":"beyond measure","h":"The picture: spilling over the top."},"G525":{"b":"The word joins away and change. It means to release, to be set loose and quit of something. Hebrews says Christ frees those held all their lives in fear of death. In Acts the diseases leave the sick. A grip let go, and you walk off.","g":"deliver, depart","h":"The picture: breaking loose and walking away free."},"G5250":{"b":"Pleonazo means to grow more and more. Hyper piles over on top. So it is abundance that overflows, far past the edge. Paul says the grace of the Lord was exceeding abundant to him, more than his sin.","g":"overflow","h":"The picture: grace flooding past the brim."},"G5251":{"b":"Built from above and a word meaning to lift up. It means to raise to the very highest place. Paul says God lifted Jesus higher than all and gave him the name above every name.","g":"highly exalt","h":"The picture: lifted up above everything."},"G5252":{"b":"This joins over and to think. Abbott gives to be overproud, high-minded. So it is rating yourself higher than you truly stand. Paul says do not think of yourself more highly than you ought, but think with sober judgment.","g":"think too highly","h":"The picture: rating yourself higher than you stand."},"G5253":{"b":"The word holds hyper, \"over, above.\" Strong's: \"a higher part of the house.\" It is the room at the top, built on the flat roof. The disciples gathered in one of these upstairs rooms to wait and pray after Jesus rose.","g":"upper room","h":"The picture: the room built on the flat roof."},"G5254":{"b":"This joins \"under\" to a root meaning to hold. So it is to hold yourself beneath something, to bear it, to undergo. Jude says Sodom is undergoing the penalty of eternal fire, a warning held up to all.","g":"suffer, undergo","h":"The picture: holding yourself up under a weight."},"G5255":{"b":"This word comes from a word meaning to hear from underneath, as one placed under another. To obey is to keep your ear turned up to the one over you. Christ became obedient this way, all the way to death.","g":"obedient","h":"The picture: listening from underneath."},"G5256":{"b":"This word comes from a word for an under-oarsman, the man pulling an oar low in the ship's belly. To serve is to row where you are placed. Paul's own hands served his needs and his companions'.","g":"minister, serve","h":"The picture: the oarsman pulling below deck."},"G5257":{"b":"Abbott-Smith breaks the word open. Under, plus a word meaning a rower. He calls it properly an under rower.\n\nFrom there it widens to any servant or attendant, from temple officers to Christian ministers.","g":"servant, officer","h":"The picture: the rower on the lower bench."},"G5258":{"b":"Hypnos is plain sleep. Eutychus sank into it on the windowsill and fell three floors while Paul preached. Paul uses it another way too. Now is the hour to wake from sleep. The heavy drowse of a body gone under.","g":"sleep","h":"The picture: a body gone under in sleep."},"G526":{"b":"The roots are apo, away, and allotrios, belonging to another, a stranger. So the word is to be made foreign, pushed out as an outsider. Paul says people were once alienated from the life of God, shut out like strangers from their own family.","g":"alienate","h":"The picture: made a stranger."},"G5260":{"b":"The word is built from 'under' and 'throw.' Abbott's first sense is to throw or put under. In Acts, men are secretly put up to lie about Stephen, planted from below to say what he never said.","g":"suborn","h":"The picture: slipping something in under the table."},"G5261":{"b":"This is a writing-copy, the row of letters a teacher pens at the top of the page for the child to trace underneath. Peter says Christ is that line. He wrote the strokes. You trace his steps.","g":"example","h":"The picture: the letters a child traces to learn to write."},"G5262":{"b":"The root means to show under the eyes, to hold a thing up where you can see it. It is a pattern to copy or a warning to avoid. Jesus washed their feet and said, I have given you an example. A model set right in front of you.","g":"example, pattern","h":"The picture: a model held up before your eyes."},"G5263":{"b":"Hypo means under, and deiknumi means to show. Hypodeiknumi is to put a thing right under your eyes, to point and trace it out. I will show him how much he must suffer. Shown by demonstration, not merely told in words.","g":"show, warn","h":"The picture: pointing a thing under your eyes."},"G5264":{"b":"The word is \"receive\" with \"under\" on it, to take a person in under your own roof. Martha hypodechomai Jesus into her house. Zacchaeus climbs down and receives him gladly. Rahab welcomed the spies this way, taking them in as guests.","g":"receive as guest","h":"The picture: welcoming a guest in under your roof."},"G5265":{"b":"The roots mean under and to bind. So it is binding something under the foot, strapping on sandals. Jesus told the twelve to wear sandals for the road. The same picture is behind \"your feet shod.\" You tie the shoe under the sole before you set out.","g":"put on sandals","h":"The picture: strapping sandals under your feet."},"G5266":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it is a sole bound under the foot, a sandal. The word means, literally, the thing bound underneath. John said he was not worthy to untie the strap of Jesus' sandal.","g":"sandal","h":"The picture: a sole strapped under the foot."},"G5267":{"b":"This joins under with the word for justice or a legal decision. So it is to stand under judgment, brought to trial. Abbott says brought to trial, answerable to. Paul says the whole world stands answerable to God, every mouth stopped.","g":"guilty","h":"The picture: standing in the dock, answerable to the court."},"G5268":{"b":"This joins hypo, under, to zygos, the yoke. A hypozygion is the animal that lives under the yoke, the beast of burden, in plain speech a donkey. It is the colt the King rides into Jerusalem, meek, not on a war-horse.","g":"donkey","h":"The picture: the beast that works under the yoke."},"G5269":{"b":"This is hypo, under, plus zonnumi, to gird with a belt. It means to undergird a ship, to frap it. The crew passed ropes right under the hull and belted them tight to hold the timbers together. The word is the ship strapped like a belt around the waist.","g":"undergird","h":"The picture: cables belted around the ship's hull."},"G527":{"b":"Apalos means tender and soft. It describes the fig branch in spring when it turns soft and green and pushes out its leaves. Jesus says when you see the branch go tender you know summer is near. Read the season.","g":"tender","h":"The picture: the soft new twig of the fig tree."},"G5271":{"b":"Abbott says the word meant to answer on the stage, to play a part. An actor speaks lines that are not his own, behind a mask. The spies pretended to be sincere. A pretender wears a role, not a face.","g":"feign, pretend","h":"The picture: an actor playing a part."},"G5272":{"b":"Abbott's second sense is play-acting. The word came off the stage, an actor speaking under a part that was not his own. Jesus lays it on the Pharisees. Clean on the outside, playing a role, and someone else hiding behind the mask.","g":"hypocrisy","h":"The picture: an actor playing a part."},"G5273":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this word meant a stage player, actor. A person who speaks lines that are not his own and wears a face that is not his. Jesus uses it for people who perform their goodness for a watching crowd.","g":"hypocrite","h":"The picture: an actor on a stage."},"G5274":{"b":"Built from a word meaning under and a word meaning to take. It is to take something from below and bear it up from beneath. A cloud took Jesus up out of their sight. It also means to take up an answer, and to suppose.","g":"take up","h":"The picture: lifting something up from underneath."},"G5275":{"b":"The root means to leave, to be left behind. Add the word for under. So it is to leave remaining. Abbott uses it of survivors. Paul quotes Elijah, I alone am left, and God answers that seven thousand remain.","g":"be left, remain","h":"The picture: the few left standing when the rest are gone."},"G5276":{"b":"The pieces mean under and a wine-trough. It is the vat set below the press to catch the juice as grapes are crushed. In Mark 12:1 the man plants a vineyard, digs the winepress pit, builds a tower, and rents it to farmers.","g":"winefat","h":"The picture: the pit dug under the winepress."},"G5277":{"b":"This word means to leave behind, to bequeath, the way a man leaves something for those who come after. Peter says Christ left you this: his own steps, laid down for you to walk in.","g":"leave","h":"The picture: something left behind for those who follow."},"G5278":{"b":"Strong's says it means to stay under (behind), and so to remain. When the weight comes, you do not run out from under it. You stay put and hold. That is what this word for patient endurance pictures.","g":"endure, remain","h":"The picture: staying under the load."},"G5279":{"b":"Strong's says it means \"to remind quietly.\" The word carries \"under.\" It is a gentle prompt slipped underneath, not a loud command. You bring a thing quietly back up into someone's mind, rather than ordering them.","g":"remind","h":"The picture: a quiet nudge to remember."},"G528":{"b":"The word is built on \"opposite\", the idea of coming face to face. It means to meet, to encounter someone on the way. Jesus says a man carrying water will meet the disciples in the city, and they are to follow him.","g":"meet","h":"The picture: someone coming to meet you face to face."},"G5280":{"b":"The root means to remind quietly, to suggest something to the memory. The 'under' in it makes the nudge gentle, from below. Paul stirs Timothy by putting him in remembrance. Not a shout. A quiet prompt to recall what he knows.","g":"remembrance","h":"The picture: a quiet nudge to the memory."},"G5281":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is a remaining behind. Then patient enduring, endurance.\n\nSo this is not gritted teeth. It is staying in place. The others left and you are still standing there.","g":"endurance, patience","h":"The picture: still there when the rest have gone."},"G5282":{"b":"This word is built from a word for under and a word for using the mind. To think underneath, a hidden guess running below the surface. The sailors suspected land was near and dropped a line to measure the depth.","g":"suspect","h":"The picture: a thought running under the surface."},"G5283":{"b":"This joins hypo, under, and noeo, to think. So it is the thought moving below the surface, a private suspicion of others. Paul says such disputes give rise to envy, strife, and evil surmisings.","g":"suspicion","h":"The picture: a thought running underneath."},"G5284":{"b":"This is built from under and to sail. It means to sail on the sheltered side of an island, where the land itself blocks the wind. Paul's ship ran under the lee of Cyprus and Crete to hide from the gale.","g":"sail under","h":"The picture: a ship in an island's shelter."},"G5285":{"b":"This is hypo, under, plus pneo, to breathe or blow. It means to blow gently. When a light south wind breathed over the sea, they thought they could make it. The word is the same as the word for breath, here a wind breathing softly, easy and mild.","g":"blow softly","h":"The picture: a soft breeze breathing over the water."},"G5286":{"b":"This word is built from under and foot. It is the stool you rest your feet on. God says he will make his enemies the footstool under his feet. A real low bench, and his foes laid down there beneath the sole.","g":"footstool","h":"The picture: the low bench for the feet."},"G5287":{"b":"The word is under plus stand. Abbott-Smith says a support, a base, a foundation. It is what stands beneath a thing and bears its weight. Hebrews says faith is this for what we hope for, the ground under it, holding it up.","g":"substance, confidence","h":"The picture: what stands underneath and holds it up."},"G5288":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is nautical, \"to draw in, let down\" a sail, to take in canvas. From there, to pull yourself back out of sight, to cower and shrink. Paul says he kept back nothing, drew in no sail, but told the whole counsel of God.","g":"draw back, shun","h":"The picture: pulling in the sail, taking in canvas."},"G5289":{"b":"The root means to draw back out of sight, to cower or shrink. This word is a shrinking back from danger. We are not of those who shrink back to ruin, but of those who believe and are saved.","g":"draw back","h":"The picture: shrinking back into cover."},"G529":{"b":"The root means to meet, to encounter. This is the meeting itself, going out to greet someone coming. At midnight the cry goes up, the bridegroom is here, go out to meet him. Believers too are caught up to meet the Lord in the air.","g":"meeting","h":"The picture: going out to meet the one arriving."},"G5290":{"b":"Strong's reads it as turning under or behind, that is, to return. Abbott gives simply to turn back, return.\n\nLuke uses it constantly. People go somewhere, then they turn and walk home again.","g":"return","h":"The picture: turning back the way you came."},"G5291":{"b":"Built from a word for under and a word meaning to spread, as you spread a carpet or couch. As Jesus rode the colt into Jerusalem, the crowd spread their cloaks on the road under him, making the way royal.","g":"spread","h":"The picture: cloaks spread like a carpet."},"G5293":{"b":"An army word first. Abbott-Smith says it means to place or rank under, the way troops are ordered in a line.\n\nThen it becomes to subject, and in the middle voice, to put yourself under. It is about position.","g":"submit, subject","h":"The picture: soldiers in rank."},"G5294":{"b":"This is built from under and to place. Paul uses it of Priscilla and Aquila, who laid down their own necks for him. The picture underneath is a neck placed under the blade, life put on the line.","g":"lay down","h":"The picture: the neck laid under the blade."},"G5295":{"b":"This is hypo, under, plus trecho, to run. Sailors used it for running in under the lee of land, into its wind-shadow. The ship ran under a small island called Cauda and got a moment's shelter. The word is that dash into cover behind the land.","g":"sail under","h":"The picture: ducking in under the shelter of an island."},"G5296":{"b":"This is an outline or rough sketch, the draft an artist lays down for others to trace. The root is a stamp or mold. Paul tells Timothy to hold the pattern of sound words. Lay your life over the outline you were given.","g":"pattern, sketch","h":"The picture: the artist's rough sketch to copy."},"G5297":{"b":"The roots are hupo, under, and phero, to carry. Picture getting under a load and bearing it up on your back. So to endure is to carry weight from below. Paul says God gives a way out so you can bear it.","g":"endure, bear","h":"The picture: carrying a load from underneath."},"G5298":{"b":"The roots suggest drawing back, giving way, retiring under and out of sight. It is to withdraw quietly. Luke uses it for Jesus, who again and again slipped away from the crowds into lonely places to pray, alone.","g":"withdraw","h":"The picture: slipping quietly back and away."},"G5299":{"b":"Abbott says \"to strike under the eye, give a black eye.\" It is a boxing word. The persistent widow so wears the judge down that it is like she is landing blows. Paul says he buffets his own body to keep it in line.","g":"buffet, wear out","h":"The picture: a boxer's punch under the eye."},"G53":{"b":"The root sense is clean, washed and fit to approach God, free from anything that would stain. The picture is a person scrubbed for worship, hands and heart with no dirt on them. Kept undefiled, pure enough to draw close.","g":"pure","h":"The picture: scrubbed clean and ready to come near."},"G530":{"b":"The word means one time, and in Hebrews once for all. Not once among many but the single time that never needs doing again. Christ entered the holy place hapax, one stroke, the sacrifice finished, the door of it shut behind him forever.","g":"once","h":"The picture: the single time, never repeated."},"G5300":{"b":"The word is simply a hog, here a sow. It is a plain naming of the animal. Peter uses it in the proverb: the washed pig goes straight back to rolling in the mud, just as false teachers return to sin.","g":"sow, swine","h":"The picture: a pig, a sow."},"G5301":{"b":"Hyssop is a plant. Abbott says a bunch of it \"was used in ritual sprinklings.\" At the cross they put a sponge of sour wine on a stalk of hyssop and lift it to Jesus' mouth. A common herb, reaching up to a dying man.","g":"hyssop","h":"The picture: a bunch of hyssop used to sprinkle."},"G5302":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means to come late, be behind. It is built on the word for later. Picture the runner who finishes last, or the guest who arrives too late. From that comes the sense of falling short and lacking.","g":"fall short, lack","h":"The picture: coming in behind."},"G5303":{"b":"Abbott says it means \"that which is lacking, deficiency, shortcoming.\" The word points to the empty part, what has fallen short and is not yet filled. Paul uses it for what people still need, and for the gap he wants to fill up.","g":"lack, shortfall","h":"The picture: what is still missing."},"G5304":{"b":"The root means to fall short, to be left behind, to run out. This word is the state of not having enough. Mark uses it for the widow who drops in two coins. She gave out of her want, her empty purse, everything she had.","g":"want, need","h":"The picture: coming up short."},"G5305":{"b":"This is a time word, afterward, at last, eventually. It only fixes when something happens, later in the order of events. Nothing concrete stands behind it, just the position of coming after the rest.","flat":1,"g":"afterward","h":"No picture."},"G5306":{"b":"Strong's traces this to a word meaning behind. So it points to what comes later, lagging behind the present. Paul says in the latter times, the days still behind him, some will fall away from the faith.","g":"latter","h":"The picture: the time that trails behind."},"G5307":{"b":"This word means woven. It comes from the verb to weave. John uses it of the same seamless tunic, woven as one piece throughout. The threads were crossed on a loom into a single whole, not cut and stitched together.","g":"woven","h":"The picture: cloth made on a loom."},"G5308":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means high, lofty, said of a mountain. Then it turns to people: to think \"high things\" is to be proud. What is lifted up in place becomes what is lifted up in the heart.","g":"high, lofty","h":"The picture: high and lofty."},"G5309":{"b":"This word joins 'lofty', meaning high up in place, to the word for the mind. To be highminded is to set your own thoughts up above everyone else. Not tall in body. Tall in your own eyes.","g":"highminded","h":"The picture: looking down from up high."},"G531":{"b":"The root means to go against or overstep a command. Put 'not' in front and it is what never passes over. Christ's priesthood does not pass to a successor. It stays with him, never handed on.","g":"unchangeable","h":"The picture: what is never handed on."},"G5310":{"b":"The word is the \"-est\" of high, the highest of all. Abbott uses it for the heights of heaven, \"glory in the highest.\" It is also a name for God, the Most High.","g":"highest, most high","h":"The picture: the very top."},"G5311":{"b":"This is height, altitude, the high sky above you. Zechariah sings of the sunrise coming to us from on high. Jesus tells them to wait for power from on high. The word points straight up, to the heights where heaven is.","g":"height","h":"The picture: the high sky overhead."},"G5312":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives the physical action first. To lift or raise up.\n\nJohn uses it for Christ being lifted up. Luke sets it opposite the word for bringing low. To exalt is simply to raise.","g":"lift up, exalt","h":"The picture: raising something high."},"G5313":{"b":"The root means to lift up high. This is a raised thing, a height, and so also a high wall built up as a barrier. Paul says no height, nothing lifted up however high, can separate us from God's love. No wall stands tall enough.","g":"height, barrier","h":"The picture: a high wall thrown up."},"G5314":{"b":"The root is simply to eat. Phagos is the man who does too much of it, a glutton. Jesus says people called him this, a glutton and a drunkard, a friend of tax collectors and sinners. They threw the insult at him for eating with the wrong crowd.","g":"a glutton","h":"The picture: the man who eats too much."},"G5315":{"b":"This is a plain old verb for one thing, to eat. It fills out the tenses of esthio, the everyday word for putting food in your mouth. So take, eat, this is my body puts phago at the center of the table, the simple act of a shared meal.","g":"eat","h":"The picture: teeth into food."},"G5316":{"b":"Abbott's sense is to bring to light, cause to appear, and then simply to give light, shine.\n\nStrong's ties it to the word for light. To appear in this word is to be lit up.","g":"shine, appear","h":"The picture: light making a thing visible."},"G5317":{"b":"The name means earthquake. It is linked to a word for a rill, a channel cut through the ground. Peleg was a patriarch, and Scripture notes that in his days the earth was divided.","g":"Peleg","h":"The picture: earthquake."},"G5318":{"b":"Strong's starts with shining, and then apparent.\n\nAbbott-Smith gives it as open to sight, visible. Paul sets it against the word for hidden. What is shining is simply what can be seen.","g":"visible, open","h":"The picture: brought into the light."},"G5319":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means to make visible, clear, manifest or known. Strong's says to render apparent.\n\nNothing is being created here. Something already real is being brought out into the open.","g":"make known","h":"The picture: bringing it out where eyes can land on it."},"G532":{"b":"The root means to get ready, to furnish. Put not in front and the table is bare. Abbott-Smith says unprepared. Paul worries the Macedonians might come and find the gift not gathered.","g":"unprepared","h":"The picture: the host caught with nothing ready when guests arrive."},"G5320":{"b":"The root means shining, brought into the light where all can see. This word is openly, in full view. After the leper spread the news, Jesus could no longer go into a town openly, out in plain sight, but stayed in lonely places.","g":"openly","h":"The picture: out in the open light."},"G5321":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to render apparent, to make plain. A phanerosis brings a hidden thing out into open light. Paul says the Spirit is shown openly in each believer for the good of all.","g":"manifestation","h":"The picture: brought out into open light."},"G5322":{"b":"This word comes from the verb to shine. It means a lantern or torch. John notes that the soldiers came for Jesus carrying these, with lanterns and torches and weapons, to find the Light in the dark.","g":"lantern","h":"The picture: a lantern carried in the dark."},"G5323":{"b":"The name means face of God. It joins a word meaning to turn or face with a word for strength or God. Phanuel was the father of the prophetess Anna, who saw the infant Jesus in the temple.","g":"Phanuel","h":"The picture: face of God."},"G5324":{"b":"The root means to shine, to bring a thing into the light. So this is something made visible, a spectacle you cannot look away from. Hebrews says the sight at Sinai was so terrible that even Moses shook with fear.","g":"sight","h":"The picture: a sight lit up before your eyes."},"G5325":{"b":"The root means to make a thing appear, to put on a spectacle. This word is a showy display, all surface. Agrippa and Bernice come into the hall with great pomp, robes and ceremony. The word is the glittering show, made to be looked at.","g":"pomp, show","h":"The picture: a dazzling show put on for the eyes."},"G5326":{"b":"The root means to appear or be made visible. A phantasma is only an appearance, a spectre with nothing solid behind it. When the disciples see Jesus walking on the sea they cry out, sure they are seeing a ghost.","g":"ghost, apparition","h":"The picture: a ghost on the water."},"G5327":{"b":"This is a gap or chasm, a ravine torn open by the winter flood. Strong's ties it to breaking and bursting. The prophet's words say every such valley will be filled to make a level road for the coming Lord.","g":"ravine, valley","h":"The picture: a ravine cut by a winter torrent."},"G5328":{"b":"This is Pharaoh, the general title of the kings of Egypt. It comes from a foreign word, so the Greek carries no picture. A ruler's title, nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"Pharaoh","h":"No picture."},"G5329":{"b":"The name comes from a word meaning a break or bursting out. Phares was a son of Judah, named when he broke out first at birth ahead of his twin, and an ancestor of Jesus.","g":"Perez","h":"The picture: a break."},"G533":{"b":"The root is to disown, and apo pushes it away. Aparneomai is to deny, to refuse to recognize, to ignore, to turn your face from someone you know. Peter does it, I do not know the man. And Jesus asks each of us to disown our own self and follow.","g":"to deny","h":"The picture: turning your face from someone you know."},"G5330":{"b":"Strong's says the name means a separatist. Someone set apart, and religious about it.\n\nAbbott only points to the Aramaic form behind it and does not explain the sense. So the meaning here comes from Strong's.","g":"Pharisee","h":"The picture: the separated ones."},"G5331":{"b":"The root means to administer drugs. Pharmakeia is the mixing of potions and spells, and our word pharmacy comes straight from it. In the New Testament it means sorcery, and stands among the works of the flesh Paul warns against.","g":"sorcery","h":"The picture: mixing drugs and potions."},"G5333":{"b":"Abbott says this is one devoted to magical arts, a magician or sorcerer. He is the worker of spells and secret craft. Revelation lists such men shut outside the city gates.","g":"sorcerer","h":"The picture: the sorcerer at his craft."},"G5334":{"b":"Abbott traces this word to one meaning to shine, to bring to light. The word means information laid before the authorities, especially about a crime. So the report is a wrongdoing pulled out of the dark and shown in the open. Word reached the commander this way.","g":"report","h":"The picture: a hidden thing dragged into the light."},"G5335":{"b":"This word means to assert, to claim, to profess out loud. It is built from the word to say. Often the claim has nothing behind it. Claiming to be wise, they became fools, and accusers asserted charges they could not prove.","g":"assert","h":"The picture: a bold claim spoken out."},"G5336":{"b":"This is the manger, the crib animals eat their fodder from, its name tied to eating. There was no room in the inn, so Mary laid the newborn in a phatne, the wooden feed-box of the stable. A cattle trough for a cradle.","g":"manger","h":"The picture: the animals' feeding trough."},"G5337":{"b":"Abbott's plain sense is slight, worthless, of no account. Strong's says foul or flawy, something with a flaw in it. Only later does it mean wicked. Whoever does such worthless deeds hates the light and stays away from it.","g":"evil, worthless","h":"The picture: cheap and good-for-nothing."},"G5338":{"b":"This is light, brightness, and Abbott says it is used mostly of the moon or a lamp. Jesus says in the last days the sun will darken and the moon will not give its light. This is that soft glow going out, the night lamp of the sky put dark.","g":"brightness","h":"The picture: the glow of the moon."},"G5339":{"b":"Strong's calls this of uncertain affinity. It means to spare someone or to hold yourself back. The sources give no origin, so there is nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"spare, hold back","h":"No picture."},"G5340":{"b":"The root means to spare, to hold back. Sparingly is the stingy, tight-fisted hand. Paul says the one who sows sparingly, scattering little seed, will also reap sparingly, and that God loves a cheerful giver.","g":"sparingly","h":"The picture: the tight-fisted sower."},"G5341":{"b":"This is a cloak, the heavy outer garment. Strong's ties the name to a word for showing, since the cloak is what shows on the outside over all the rest. Paul asks Timothy to bring the cloak he left at Troas. A cold man wants his coat.","g":"cloak","h":"The picture: the coat worn over everything."},"G5342":{"b":"Strong's calls it a primary verb. Nothing lies behind it. Abbott gives the senses plainly. To carry, and also to bear in the sense of putting up with something.","flat":1,"g":"carry, bear","h":"No picture."},"G5343":{"b":"Strong's calls it apparently a primary verb, so nothing stands behind it. Abbott gives to flee from or away, take flight.\n\nIt means running. The word carries no picture beyond the running itself.","flat":1,"g":"flee","h":"No picture."},"G5344":{"b":"This is the name of a Roman governor. Strong's says the name means \"happy.\" Abbott gives no origin at all, only the man. So the sources leave nothing to picture beyond a Roman's name.","flat":1,"g":"Felix","h":"No picture."},"G5345":{"b":"The root means to speak. A pheme is what gets spoken and passed on, a saying, a report running from mouth to mouth. Matthew says after Jesus raised the girl, the report of it went out into all that land. The talk traveled faster than he did.","g":"fame, report","h":"The picture: word spreading mouth to mouth."},"G5346":{"b":"Strong's defines it as showing or making known one's thoughts. The word is about getting what is inside out into the open.\n\nAbbott says it is mostly used when quoting someone's actual words.","g":"say","h":"The picture: putting your thoughts out where they can be seen."},"G5347":{"b":"This is a Roman name. Strong's says it means \"festal,\" that is, festive or holiday-like. Abbott-Smith gives no origin at all. Festus was the governor who heard Paul's case.","g":"Festus","h":"The picture: festive."},"G5348":{"b":"This word means to come before another, to anticipate, to arrive ahead. We who are alive will not go before those who sleep, Paul says. Later it just meant to arrive at last. The kingdom of God has come upon you. Reaching the spot.","g":"arrive, come before","h":"The picture: getting there first."},"G5349":{"b":"The root means, properly, to shrivel or wither, then to spoil. Phthartos is anything that can rot, like fruit going soft or a flower drying up. So when Scripture calls man phthartos, it says we spoil. We do not last.","g":"perishable","h":"The picture: fruit shriveling on the branch."},"G535":{"b":"This word comes from a word meaning to finish. It means completion, the point where a job is fully done. The tower builder must count whether he has enough to finish, or people will mock the half-built walls. Completion is a state, not a thing.","flat":1,"g":"finishing","h":"No picture."},"G5350":{"b":"This word means to utter a clear sound, to give voice. Balaam's donkey did this, speaking out with a man's voice to stop the prophet on the road. A clear sound where none should be.","g":"speak","h":"The picture: a clear sound breaking out."},"G5351":{"b":"Strong's says it means \"to shrivel or wither,\" and from there to spoil or ruin. The first picture is a plant drying up. Then it means to spoil anything, and at last to corrupt a person's character.","g":"corrupt, ruin","h":"The picture: it shrivels and spoils."},"G5352":{"b":"The word means autumnal, from a root meaning to wither and shrivel. Jude calls the false men late-autumn trees, past the season, bearing nothing, twice dead and pulled up by the roots.","g":"fruitless","h":"The picture: bare autumn trees with no fruit."},"G5353":{"b":"The root means to utter a clear sound. This is that sound, a musical note struck or sung. Paul says their voice went out to all the earth. Elsewhere it is the note of a pipe or harp. A clear tone ringing out into the air.","g":"sound, note","h":"The picture: a clear note ringing out."},"G5354":{"b":"This comes from a word for ill-will and spite. Abbott gives to envy. So the picture is a grudging eye fixed on what another holds. Paul says let us not be conceited, provoking and envying one another.","g":"envy","h":"The picture: a grudging eye on what another has."},"G5355":{"b":"Strong's links this to a word meaning to shrivel or wither, to spoil. So envy is that inward rot, ill will at another's good. Abbott notes Pilate saw it was for envy the leaders handed Jesus over. A spite that eats its owner.","g":"envy","h":"The picture: the rot that spoils from inside."},"G5356":{"b":"Abbott ties it to φθείρω, to spoil or destroy. Strong's: \"decay, i.e. ruin.\" It is the slow wasting of a thing that falls apart, food going bad, a body returning to the ground.","g":"decay, ruin","h":"The picture: rotting away."},"G5357":{"b":"The old word \"vial\" makes us think of a small tube. Abbott-Smith says it is really a shallow bowl, the wide dish used for pouring out an offering. In Revelation the bowls of God's wrath are poured on the earth.","g":"bowl, vial","h":"The picture: a shallow pouring bowl."},"G5358":{"b":"This joins the word for a fond friend to the word for good. It pictures someone who treats goodness like a dear friend, drawn to it and glad of it. An overseer must be like this, a friend of the good.","g":"lover of good","h":"The picture: a friend to what is good."},"G5359":{"b":"The name is built from a word for one fond of his brothers. It was named for a king called brother-lover. So the city's name means the love between brothers. Picture two brothers standing close.","g":"Philadelphia","h":"The picture: brothers standing together."},"G536":{"b":"Abbott says the word comes from a verb meaning \"to make a beginning in sacrifice, offer first fruits.\" The very first part of the crop was given to God before the rest was touched. Paul calls Christ this, the first of a harvest still to come.","g":"firstfruits","h":"The picture: the first handful of the harvest."},"G5360":{"b":"The word joins love and brother, fond of brethren, fraternal. It is the warmth between children of one household who grew up under one roof. The New Testament uses it for how Christians treat each other. Like family, not strangers.","g":"brotherly love","h":"The picture: brothers under one roof."},"G5361":{"b":"This word joins \"fond, friendly\" to the word for a brother. Abbott says it means loving like a brother. Peter uses it of Christians loving one another, as if the same blood ran between them.","g":"love as brethren","h":"The picture: treating each other like brothers."},"G5362":{"b":"This joins the word for a fond friend to the word for a man or husband. Of a wife it means loving her husband. Abbott notes it turns up often on old gravestones. The young women are to be friends to their own men.","g":"love her husband","h":"The picture: a wife who loves her husband."},"G5363":{"b":"This is built from love and mankind, love toward people. The islanders showed it when they lit a fire and welcomed the soaked, shivering survivors. Kindness held out to strangers you owe nothing. Plain human warmth toward those who wash up cold.","g":"kindness","h":"The picture: warmth held out to strangers."},"G5364":{"b":"This joins philos, friend, to anthropos, man. It means to treat a person the way you treat a friend, kindly and warmly. Julius the centurion treated Paul this way, letting him visit friends for care. The word is love shown to a fellow human, friend to friend.","g":"kindly","h":"The picture: a friendly hand held out to a stranger."},"G5365":{"b":"This joins philos, loving, and argyros, silver. So it is the love of silver, gripping coins tight. Paul says the love of money is a root of all kinds of evil, and some reaching for it wandered from the faith.","g":"love of money","h":"The picture: hands clinging to silver."},"G5366":{"b":"The word joins \"loving\" to \"silver,\" the metal in the coins. Strong's says \"fond of silver.\" Abbott says \"loving money.\" Luke says the Pharisees were like this, and they scoffed when Jesus said you cannot serve both God and money.","g":"covetous","h":"The picture: a man in love with silver coins."},"G5367":{"b":"This joins the word for a fond friend to the word for self. A lover of self is a man who is friendly to no one but himself. Paul lists it first among the marks of the last days. The friendship all turns inward.","g":"lover of self","h":"The picture: his own best friend."},"G5368":{"b":"This is love as warm affection. Abbott-Smith gives a second sense with no metaphor at all. To kiss.\n\nHis first example is Matthew 26:48. That is Judas in the garden, using affection as a signal.","g":"love, kiss","h":"The picture: a kiss."},"G5369":{"b":"This joins the word for a fond friend to a word for sensual delight. It pictures a person who courts pleasure like a dear friend. Paul says the last days hold such people. Lovers of pleasure rather than lovers of God.","g":"lover of pleasure","h":"The picture: a friend to pleasure."},"G537":{"b":"This is pas, all, made stronger. Hapas gathers up the whole, altogether, every single one with none left out. So when hapas the multitude is amazed, or all things are held in common, the word sweeps the room and leaves nothing on the side.","g":"all","h":"The picture: every last one, the whole lot."},"G5370":{"b":"It comes from phileo, to have affection for a friend. A philema is that affection made physical, love pressed onto a cheek. The early churches greeted with a holy one. Judas turned it into a signal, betraying with a kiss.","g":"a kiss","h":"The picture: love pressed onto a cheek."},"G5371":{"b":"His name comes from the word to love, to be a friend. It means friendly. Philemon is the man Paul writes to about the slave Onesimus. A name full of affection, fitting for the appeal Paul makes to him.","g":"Philemon","h":"The picture: the friendly one."},"G5372":{"b":"His name comes from the word to love, to have affection for. It means beloved, amiable. Yet Paul lists him among those whose teaching eats like gangrene. A man named beloved who wandered from the truth.","g":"Philetus","h":"The picture: the beloved one."},"G5373":{"b":"This comes from the word for a friend. Abbott gives friendship. So it is the bond that ties friends close. James warns that friendship with the world is enmity with God, an affection that takes sides.","g":"friendship","h":"The picture: the bond that ties friends close."},"G5374":{"b":"This word marks a person by his city, Philippi in Macedonia. Abbott gives a Philippian. So the picture is a believer named by his town. Paul thanks the Philippians, who alone shared with him when he first left Macedonia.","g":"Philippian","h":"The picture: a believer named by his town."},"G5375":{"b":"The city is named after a man, Philip, and that name means \"fond of horses.\" Philippi was the first place in Europe to hear the gospel. There Paul and Silas sang in the stocks and the prison shook.","g":"Philippi","h":"The picture: a city named for a lover of horses."},"G5376":{"b":"Strong's says the name means fond of horses, built from the word for loving and the word for horse.\n\nIt is a Greek name, not a Hebrew one. Beyond that it says nothing about the men who carried it.","g":"Philip","h":"The picture: a man who loves horses."},"G5377":{"b":"This joins the word for a fond friend to the word for God. It means one who holds God dear as a friend. Paul sets it against lover of pleasure. The same warmth, but here it is aimed at God.","g":"lover of God","h":"The picture: a friend to God."},"G5378":{"b":"Strong's reads this name as fond of words, from the words for loving and word. So a lover of words is stamped in the name. Philologus was one of the saints Paul greeted in the closing lines to Rome.","g":"a Christian","h":"The picture: a name that means word-lover."},"G5379":{"b":"The root is a word meaning fond of strife, keen for a fight. Picture two who would rather argue than agree. A dispute arose among the disciples over which of them was reckoned the greatest. The appetite to win crept in.","g":"strife","h":"The picture: the one who loves a quarrel."},"G538":{"b":"This word means to deceive, to cheat. Strong's says it is of uncertain derivation, so there is no root to open, and deceit itself has no shape to draw. No picture here.","flat":1,"g":"deceive","h":"No picture."},"G5380":{"b":"This joins fond with a word for strife. It means fond of strife, always ready for a quarrel. It pictures the person who loves a good fight. Paul says if anyone is set on this, the churches have no such custom.","g":"contentious","h":"The picture: the one who loves a fight."},"G5381":{"b":"The word is built from love and stranger. Not love of friends but love of strangers, the guest you have never met. Hebrews says some who welcomed strangers this way entertained angels without knowing it.","g":"hospitality","h":"The picture: love of the stranger at your door."},"G5382":{"b":"The roots are philos, loving, and xenos, a stranger or guest. So the word is a lover of strangers, one who opens the door to the traveler. Paul lists it for overseers, and Peter says show it to one another without grumbling.","g":"hospitable","h":"The picture: the door opened to a stranger."},"G5383":{"b":"This joins \"fond of\" to the word for foremost, first. So it is loving to be number one. John says Diotrephes, who loves to be first among them, will not receive the brothers.","g":"love preeminence","h":"The picture: pushing to be first in line."},"G5384":{"b":"Abbott-Smith sets this word against the word for slave and points to John 15:15. A slave is told what to do. A friend is told what the master is thinking.\n\nThat is the word Jesus uses for his followers.","g":"friend","h":"The picture: not a servant, a friend."},"G5385":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning fond of wise things. Abbott gives the love and pursuit of wisdom. So the picture is reaching after wisdom. Paul warns the church against the false kind, philosophy and empty deceit that takes a man captive.","g":"philosophy","h":"The picture: the love of wisdom."},"G5386":{"b":"Two words, friendly and wise, the second meaning wise in a most general application. A philosopher is not a title earned but a fondness, a friend of wise things. Athens was full of such men when Paul came.","g":"philosopher","h":"The picture: a friend of wisdom."},"G5387":{"b":"Abbott builds this from a word for family affection, the natural love of parents and children. So it is that same warm bond, now among believers. Abbott says tenderly loving. Paul says be devoted to one another like family.","g":"kindly affectioned","h":"The picture: the way a family holds its own close."},"G5388":{"b":"This joins the word for a fond friend to the word for a child. It means loving one's children, the warmth of a mother. It stands right beside loving her husband. The young wife is to hold her little ones dear.","g":"love her children","h":"The picture: a mother fond of her children."},"G5389":{"b":"The roots are philos, loving, and time, honor. So the word is to be a lover of honor, to chase after being esteemed. In Paul it softens into ambition aimed well. He made it his aim to preach where Christ was not named.","g":"be ambitious","h":"The picture: in love with honor."},"G539":{"b":"From a word meaning to cheat, to trick. Abbott gives deceit, deceitfulness. Jesus warns of the deceitfulness of riches, how wealth lies to you and chokes the seed. A false promise dressed up to look true.","g":"deceit","h":"The picture: the bait that fools you."},"G5390":{"b":"Strong's explains this as acting \"with friendliness of mind.\" It is built from words for loving and the mind. That is a warm way of treating someone, a manner, not an object you can picture. Publius welcomed Paul this way.","flat":1,"g":"courteously","h":"No picture."},"G5392":{"b":"Abbott: \"(< φιμός, a muzzle).\" You strap a muzzle on an ox so it cannot eat while it treads the grain. From that the word means to shut someone's mouth, to put them to silence.","g":"muzzle, silence","h":"The picture: a muzzle strapped over the mouth."},"G5393":{"b":"His name comes from the word for a blaze. It means blazing. Paul greets Phlegon among the believers at Rome. A man named for fire.","g":"Phlegon","h":"The picture: a blazing flame."},"G5394":{"b":"From the word for a blaze, a flame. So it means to set alight, to set on fire. James says the tongue sets a whole life ablaze. Picture one small flame catching and spreading.","g":"set on fire","h":"The picture: a flame catching."},"G5395":{"b":"Phlox is a flame, a blaze of fire. The rich man begged for water, tormented in the flame. The bush burned with it and was not eaten. Eyes like a flame of fire. A real tongue of fire you can watch leap and flicker.","g":"flame","h":"The picture: a tongue of fire."},"G5396":{"b":"The root is a garrulous person, a prater, from a word meaning to bubble up. So this is to talk nonsense. John says Diotrephes was babbling wicked words against them, empty talk poured out.","g":"prate against","h":"The picture: words boiling over into empty chatter."},"G5397":{"b":"Strong's traces this to a word meaning to bubble. A phlyaros is a person who bubbles over with talk, words spilling out that carry nothing. Paul says idle widows become tattlers, going house to house saying what they ought not.","g":"tattler","h":"The picture: water bubbling over."},"G5398":{"b":"The root is fear, plain alarm and fright. This word describes the thing that causes it, something so terrible you pull away. Hebrews says it is a fearful thing to fall into the hands of the living God. Not comforting here. Fearful.","g":"fearful, terrible","h":"The picture: the thing that makes you step back."},"G5399":{"b":"Abbott says that in Homer it meant to put to flight. Fear was not a feeling. It was legs moving.\n\nLater it softened into being afraid, and then into awe. Fearing God grew out of fleeing.","g":"fear","h":"The picture: running away."},"G54":{"b":"The root means properly clean, then innocent and pure. Hagnotes is pureness, cleanness of life. Paul lists it among the marks of a true servant of God, by pureness, by knowledge, by patience, by kindness.","g":"pureness","h":"The picture: washed clean."},"G540":{"b":"This is the word for father with 'not' in front. It means one with no father named in the record. Melchizedek appears in scripture with no listed father, and so stands as a picture of the eternal Son.","g":"without father","h":"The picture: no father's name in the record."},"G5400":{"b":"From a word meaning to frighten. A phobetron is a thing that causes fright, something that sends people running. There will be great signs and terrors from heaven, Jesus warned. Fear made visible, hanging over the world.","g":"fearful sight","h":"The picture: a terror in the sky."},"G5401":{"b":"In Homer this word meant flight. Abbott-Smith then defines it as that which causes flight: fear, dread, terror.\n\nFear is named for what it makes you do. The same word later covers reverence toward God.","g":"fear","h":"The picture: running away."},"G5402":{"b":"Her name means bright. Strong's ties it to the word for light. Phoebe was a servant of the church at Cenchreae, the woman trusted to carry Paul's letter all the way to Rome. A bright name for a trusted messenger.","g":"Phoebe","h":"The picture: bright, shining."},"G5403":{"b":"This word comes from the word for palm-tree. Phoinike is palm-country, the coastal land named for its palms. The believers scattered by persecution traveled as far as Phoenicia, carrying the word along the shore.","g":"Phoenicia","h":"The picture: the land of palm trees."},"G5404":{"b":"This word means the date-palm, the tall tree of the desert springs. Its branches are the ones the crowd cut and waved over the road when Jesus rode into the city. Green fronds in his path.","g":"palm tree","h":"The picture: a palm tree by the desert spring."},"G5406":{"b":"The root is murder, the shedding of blood. A phoneus is the one who does it, the murderer. They asked for Barabbas, a murderer, to be freed instead of Jesus. You killed the Author of life, Peter tells them. The hand that spilled blood.","g":"murderer","h":"The picture: the hand that took a life."},"G5407":{"b":"The root is the murderer, the one who sheds blood on purpose. Phoneuō is that act. The commandment says do not phoneuō, and Jesus traces it upstream to the anger that would kill if it could. James says the rich condemned and murdered the innocent.","g":"to murder","h":"The picture: the one who sheds blood."},"G5408":{"b":"This just means murder, slaughter. Strong's says it comes from an old root meaning to slay. Nothing is pictured behind it, only the deed itself.","flat":1,"g":"murder","h":"No picture."},"G5409":{"b":"This is a form of phero, to carry, shaped for what you carry all the time. So it means to wear. Those in soft clothing wear it in palaces. As we have worn the image of the earthly man, we shall wear the heavenly.","g":"wear","h":"The picture: clothes worn every day."},"G541":{"b":"The root means to beam forth. This is the light that streams off a shining body, its radiance. The Son is called the shining-out of God's glory, the brightness that pours from the source.","g":"brightness","h":"The picture: the light that streams off the sun."},"G5410":{"b":"Strong's says this is a forum or market-place, from the Latin forum. It is the open square where a town bought and sold. In Appii Forum it names the Market of Appius, a stop where friends came to meet Paul.","g":"forum, market","h":"The picture: the open market square of a town."},"G5411":{"b":"The root means to bear or carry. Strong's calls tribute a load, something borne. The tax is a weight the conquered people carry and hand up. They asked if it was lawful to pay tribute to Caesar. A burden brought and given away.","g":"tribute, tax","h":"The picture: a load carried and handed over."},"G5412":{"b":"The word means to load up, Strong's says as you load a ship or a pack animal. Piling weight on until the back bends. Jesus calls the weary and heavy laden to come to him. People loaded down with burdens too big to carry. He says he will give them rest.","g":"to load, burden","h":"The picture: the pack animal loaded down."},"G5413":{"b":"A phortion is a load, the cargo stowed in a ship's hold. Jesus says his own is light, while the scribes pile heavy ones on men's backs. Each will carry his own load. A pack strapped on to be borne down the road.","g":"burden","h":"The picture: cargo in the hold."},"G5415":{"b":"This is a man's name, Latin for fortunate. Strong's says it is of Latin origin. It names a real Christian who came to Paul and refreshed his spirit. A name meaning lucky is still only a name, with nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"Fortunatus","h":"No picture."},"G5416":{"b":"The root is a word meaning to whip, to lash as a public punishment. The Latin behind it is flagellum, a whip. Jesus made a whip of cords and drove them all out of the temple, with their sheep and oxen.","g":"scourge","h":"The picture: a whip of cords."},"G5417":{"b":"The word is borrowed from the Latin flagellum, a whip. Phragelloo is to scourge, to flog with the lash as a public punishment. Pilate has Jesus scourged and then hands him over to be crucified, the whip before the cross.","g":"scourge","h":"The picture: the Roman lash coming down."},"G5418":{"b":"The root means to fence in, to wall off. A phragmos is the fence or hedge a man builds around his vineyard to close it in. In Ephesians Paul uses it for the wall between two peoples that Christ tore down.","g":"fence, hedge","h":"The picture: the hedge set around a vineyard."},"G5419":{"b":"Strong's links this word to another that means to fence or enclose. To explain a thing is to fence it in, to mark its edges so it stands clear. In Matthew 15:15 Peter asks Jesus to make the parable plain to them.","g":"explain, declare","h":"The picture: putting a fence around a meaning."},"G5420":{"b":"The word means to fence or inclose, to block something up. Picture piling a barrier across a gap so nothing can pass. Abbott points to stopping the mouths of lions, and Paul uses it for every mouth stopped and silent before God.","g":"stop, block up","h":"The picture: a fence blocking a gap."},"G5421":{"b":"A phrear is a hole dug in the ground to hold water, a well. Jesus sat by one in Samaria and asked for a drink. Revelation uses the same word for the shaft of the abyss. A deep hole, water at the bottom or darkness.","g":"well, pit","h":"The picture: a well dug in the ground."},"G5422":{"b":"The word puts together mind and deceive. Abbott-Smith says it means to deceive one's own mind, to be fooled by your own fancies. It is the man who talks himself into believing he is something he is not.","g":"deceive","h":"The picture: fooling your own mind."},"G5423":{"b":"This joins a word for the mind to a word for delusion and trickery. A phrenapates is one who tricks the very thinking of others. Paul warns of such deceivers in Crete. They do not just lie about facts. They fool the mind itself.","g":"deceiver","h":"The picture: a trickster who fools the mind."},"G5424":{"b":"Strong's says this first named the midriff, the wall of muscle that partitions the body below the ribs. The Greeks placed thought there. Paul says in your thinking be grown men, not children.","g":"understanding","h":"The picture: the midriff below the ribs."},"G5425":{"b":"First it meant to bristle, to go rough, the way hair stands up and skin prickles with a cold shiver. James says even the demons believe God is one, and it makes them shudder like that.","g":"tremble","h":"The picture: hair bristling, skin prickling with a chill."},"G5426":{"b":"Strong's describes it as being mentally disposed in a certain direction. Not one thought. A tilt.\n\nThat is why Jesus tells Peter he is minding the things of men. Peter is leaning the wrong way.","g":"think, be minded","h":"The picture: which way your mind leans."},"G5427":{"b":"Built from a word meaning to set the mind. Abbott calls it the content of the mind, what it is fixed on. Paul says the phronema of the flesh is death, but the mind set on the Spirit is life and peace, Romans 8:6.","g":"mindset","h":"The picture: what the mind is set on."},"G5428":{"b":"The root means to exercise the mind, to have a settled way of thinking. This is practical wisdom, prudence, knowing how to act. Gabriel says John will turn the disobedient to the prudence of the righteous. Not clever thoughts but good sense steering real choices.","g":"prudence","h":"The picture: wisdom that knows what to do."},"G5429":{"b":"The root is phrēn, the midriff, where the Greeks placed the seat of thought. Phronimos is not book-clever but gut-wise, practically wise, sensible, prudent. The five wise virgins bring extra oil. The wise man builds on rock. Sense you can act on.","g":"wise","h":"The picture: gut-wise, sense you can act on."},"G543":{"b":"The root means unpersuadable, one who will not be talked into obeying. So it is disobedience, and Paul calls the rebellious the sons of disobedience. Not ignorance but a set jaw, refusing to yield.","g":"disobedience","h":"The picture: the will that will not be moved."},"G5430":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning thoughtful, shrewd, discreet. Abbott gives sensibly, prudently. So it is acting with a sharp, careful head. The master commended the unjust steward because he had acted shrewdly for his own future.","g":"wisely","h":"The picture: acting with a shrewd head."},"G5431":{"b":"This traces back to a word that first meant the midriff, the part of the body the Greeks felt did the thinking. To take thought was to work something over deep in the gut. Paul wants Titus careful to keep believers in good works.","g":"be careful","h":"The picture: a worry sitting in the gut."},"G5432":{"b":"Strong's says this word means to mount guard as a sentinel, to post spies at the gates. It comes from the word for a guard. It is a soldier keeping watch over a city. God's peace guards the heart and mind like that.","g":"to guard","h":"The picture: a soldier standing watch."},"G5433":{"b":"Strong's says this word is the snort of a spirited horse. Abbott adds the neighing and prancing. The believers quote a psalm with it: why did the nations rage. The picture is a proud horse tossing its head, stamping, out of control.","g":"to rage","h":"The picture: a war-horse snorting and prancing."},"G5434":{"b":"Abbott says this comes from a word meaning to parch. So it is a stick dried out by heat, a dry stick or brushwood. Paul gathered a bundle of these for the fire, and a snake came out of the heat.","g":"dry stick","h":"The picture: a dry stick that catches fast."},"G5435":{"b":"This is the name of a region in Asia Minor. It came into Greek from some foreign tongue. A place on the map, with no picture inside the word itself for us to see.","flat":1,"g":"Phrygia","h":"No picture."},"G5436":{"b":"His name comes from a word meaning to run away, to flee. It means fugitive. Paul names him among those who turned away from him in Asia. A man whose very name is running, and run he did.","g":"Phygellus","h":"The picture: the man who ran away."},"G5437":{"b":"The root means to run away, to flee. This word is the running itself, the escape. In Matthew 24:20 Jesus tells them to pray their flight will not fall in winter, when running is hardest.","g":"flight","h":"The picture: running for your life."},"G5438":{"b":"One word for the guarding, the guards, and the place they guard. Abbott-Smith lists all three.\n\nKeeping watch through the night and sitting in a cell share a word. Both involve someone standing over you.","g":"prison, watch","h":"The picture: standing guard at night."},"G5439":{"b":"The root is phylax, a watcher or sentry. To imprison someone is to put a guard on them so they cannot leave. Paul admits he once did this to believers, locking them up under watch. The word is really about the man standing guard at the door.","g":"imprison","h":"The picture: a sentry set over you."},"G544":{"b":"The root means unpersuadable. Apeitheō is not just breaking a rule but refusing to be won over, deaf to all pleading. God says all day long he stretched out his hands to an apeithēs people, and still they would not be moved.","g":"to disobey","h":"The picture: the one who will not be won over."},"G5440":{"b":"The root means to keep watch, to guard. The word first meant a guard's outpost. Then it meant anything that guards you, an amulet. Here it is the little box of Scripture strapped to the forehead. In Matthew 23:5 Jesus says the proud make theirs wide to be seen.","g":"phylactery","h":"The picture: a guard's outpost shrunk to a box on the brow."},"G5441":{"b":"This word comes from a word meaning to keep watch. A phylax is the sentry, the man standing guard at the prison door. They found the guards still posted, the doors still shut, but the apostles gone.","g":"guard","h":"The picture: the sentry at the prison door."},"G5442":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is to guard, watch. He lists guarding people, protecting property, and then keeping a law or a command.\n\nObeying in this word is standing over the thing like a guard.","g":"guard, keep","h":"The picture: a sentry on watch."},"G5443":{"b":"Strong's calls a tribe an offshoot, a shoot growing off the main stem, and from there a race or clan.\n\nAbbott defines it as men united by kinship or habitation. Family, growing outward.","g":"tribe","h":"The picture: a branch off the trunk."},"G5444":{"b":"Strong's calls it a sprout, then a leaf. It is the green thing that opens on a twig. Jesus points at the fig tree. When its leaves come out, you know summer is near. A small green sign that reads the season for you.","g":"leaf","h":"The picture: a leaf on the branch."},"G5445":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this is that which is mixed or kneaded, a lump of dough. It comes from a word meaning to mix. Paul says a little yeast works through the whole lump. Real dough on the board, all of it changed by a little.","g":"lump","h":"The picture: a lump of kneaded dough."},"G5446":{"b":"The root phusis means growth, the way a seed germinates and expands on its own. So physikos is what grows in a thing by nature, not added from outside. Paul uses it for what is natural against what is against nature.","g":"natural","h":"The picture: a seed growing on its own."},"G5447":{"b":"The root means physical, instinctive. So this is acting by raw nature, by instinct. Jude says these men, like unreasoning animals, understand only what they know by instinct, and in it they corrupt themselves.","g":"naturally","h":"The picture: knowing by instinct, like an animal."},"G5448":{"b":"Abbott ties it to phusa, a bellows. To physioo is to blow up with air, to inflate. Knowledge puffs a man up, all swelled air and no weight. Pride pictured as a bag blown big and empty.","g":"puff up","h":"The picture: a bag blown up with air."},"G5449":{"b":"Strong's says the word means growth. It comes from a word meaning to grow, like a plant springing up. Your nature is what grows in you on its own, not what you were taught.","g":"nature","h":"The picture: what grows up in you."},"G545":{"b":"This is not joined to a word meaning to persuade. The one who will not be talked round, who refuses to be won over. John's task is to turn such hard, unpersuadable hearts back. Disobedience here is a mind that bolts the door.","g":"disobedient","h":"The picture: the mind that will not be talked round."},"G5450":{"b":"The root means to inflate, to puff up. Abbott-Smith says a swelling with pride. Paul fears finding them like that, puffed up big and full of nothing, egos blown out past their real size.","g":"swelling, conceit","h":"The picture: a bladder blown up fat with air."},"G5451":{"b":"The root means to set a plant out in the earth. This word is the plant itself, the thing growing in the soil. In Matthew 15:13 Jesus says every plant his Father did not plant will be pulled up by the roots.","g":"plant","h":"The picture: a plant set in the ground."},"G5452":{"b":"Strong's says it means to set out in the earth, to put a plant in the ground. Paul uses it for planting a vineyard, and also for planting truth in people. One plants, another waters.","g":"plant","h":"The picture: putting a plant into the ground."},"G5453":{"b":"The word means to sprout and grow. Strong's guesses it began as a word for swelling up. The seed springs up and, without moisture, dries away. Hebrews warns of a root of bitterness that springs up. Green pushing through dirt.","g":"spring up, grow","h":"The picture: a shoot pushing up through the soil."},"G5454":{"b":"A pholeos is a hole, a den, an animal's lair. Jesus says foxes have their dens and birds have their nests, but the Son of Man has nowhere to lay his head. Even wild animals have a hole to crawl into. He had less.","g":"a hole, den","h":"The picture: the fox's den."},"G5455":{"b":"The verb made from the word for voice. Abbott-Smith notes it is used of animal cries too, of a cock, to crow.\n\nThe word that calls a person by name also makes the rooster's noise. Sound carrying.","g":"call out","h":"The picture: a rooster crowing."},"G5456":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is simply a voice, the sound of a person. It widens to any sound, a trumpet, thunder, rushing wind. So the voice crying in the wilderness is phone, a sound cutting the air that you cannot help but hear.","g":"voice, sound","h":"The picture: a sound cutting the air."},"G5457":{"b":"Strong's traces it to an old verb meaning to shine or make manifest, especially by rays.\n\nAbbott lists what carries it. The sun. A lamp. A torch. A fire someone is warming at. Light you can point to.","g":"light","h":"The picture: rays going out."},"G5458":{"b":"This is a light-giver, the word used for the sun and stars set in the heavens. The root simply means light. Paul says believers shine as lights in a dark and crooked world. Small fixed points that hold back the night.","g":"light, luminary","h":"The picture: a star fixed in the sky."},"G5459":{"b":"This joins \"light\" to \"carry,\" the light-bearer. Abbott says it is the morning star that rises before dawn. Peter says let it rise in your hearts, the promise of full day coming.","g":"morning star","h":"The picture: the star that carries in the light."},"G546":{"b":"This word means to menace, to threaten. Strong's says its origin is of uncertain derivation, so there is no root reaching back to a real thing. The rulers threatened the apostles and let them go. The meaning is plain, but there is nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"threaten","h":"No picture."},"G5460":{"b":"This comes from phos, light. Photeinos means bright, flooded with light. If your eye is sound, Jesus says, your whole body is photeinos, lit up inside. Full of light, like a room with the lamp burning and no dark corners.","g":"bright","h":"The picture: a room flooded with light."},"G5461":{"b":"Strong's says it means to shed rays, to shine. The word comes from the word for light. It can mean to light up a room, or to open someone's eyes so they finally see the truth.","g":"give light, enlighten","h":"The picture: shedding light."},"G5462":{"b":"The root means to shed rays, to shine. Photismos is the light itself, the brightness that breaks in. Paul says the God who made light shine out of darkness has shone in our hearts, in the face of Christ.","g":"light","h":"The picture: rays breaking in."},"G5463":{"b":"Abbott shows the same word used as a greeting. At meeting, hail. It also opened letters.\n\nSo the New Testament word for joy was the everyday hello. Rejoice was how you said good day.","g":"rejoice","h":"The picture: the word you say when you meet someone."},"G5464":{"b":"The word means hail. Strong's ties it to a word meaning to let down, to lower, hail dropped from above. In Revelation hail and fire fall on the earth, and great hailstones come down out of heaven on people.","g":"hail","h":"The picture: ice falling from the sky."},"G5465":{"b":"This word means to lower, to let down, as into a void. Let down your nets for a catch, Jesus tells Peter. They lowered the paralytic through the roof. Paul was let down the wall in a basket. Slackening the rope and letting it sink.","g":"let down, lower","h":"The picture: lowering something on a rope."},"G5466":{"b":"This names a person from Chaldea. Strong's places it in the region of the lower Euphrates. So the picture is a man of that far land. Stephen says God called Abraham out of the land of the Chaldeans.","g":"Chaldean","h":"The picture: a man of the far Euphrates land."},"G5467":{"b":"The word means hard, hard to deal with, hard to bear, painful, grievous. Matthew uses it of two demoniacs so fierce no one could pass that road. Paul uses it of the last days, when hard seasons will come. Something you cannot easily get past.","g":"fierce, difficult","h":"The picture: too hard to handle."},"G5468":{"b":"Built from the word for a bridle and the word for leading. Abbott gives to lead with a bridle. So it means to steer an animal by the bit in its mouth. James uses it of a man who can bridle his tongue.","g":"to bridle","h":"The picture: leading a horse by the bridle."},"G5469":{"b":"This is the bit, the curb, the head-stall put on a horse. A small piece of metal set in the mouth. James says it turns the whole animal. A little thing steers something far bigger than itself.","g":"bridle, bit","h":"The picture: the bit in a horse's mouth."},"G547":{"b":"This word comes from a word meaning to menace. Apeile is a threat, the promise of harm held over your head. Saul came breathing threats against the disciples, this very word, harm hanging in every breath.","g":"threat","h":"The picture: harm held over your head."},"G5470":{"b":"The word comes from the word for copper. Abbott-Smith gives \"brazen (i.e. of copper).\" Picture a dull metal statue, cold and lifeless. So people kept worshipping gods of copper that cannot see or hear or walk.","g":"brazen, coppery","h":"The picture: idols cast in copper."},"G5471":{"b":"This comes from the word for copper, the metal itself. A coppersmith is the man who works it, hammering the metal at his forge. Paul warns of Alexander the coppersmith, who did him much harm. A worker in copper who worked against Paul.","g":"coppersmith","h":"The picture: a man hammering copper."},"G5472":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this was \"a green silicate of copper found in the mines near Chalcedon,\" the town it is named for. Picture a stone with copper's green sheen. So chalcedony was the third foundation of the city wall.","g":"chalcedony","h":"The picture: a green copper stone."},"G5473":{"b":"The root is the word for copper, the metal. This is a vessel made of it, a copper pot or dish. In Mark 7:4 it is among the things the Pharisees carefully wash, cups, pitchers, and copper pots, keeping the old rules.","g":"copper pot","h":"The picture: a copper pot."},"G5474":{"b":"This is a name for burnished copper, a shining alloy. Its parts are the word for copper and the word for incense. John sees the feet of Christ like this, gleaming bronze as if glowing in a furnace.","g":"fine brass","h":"The picture: gleaming burnished bronze."},"G5475":{"b":"This is copper, or its alloy brass, the metal of pots and small coins. Sounding brass, Paul says, chalkos clanging with no love behind it. Take no chalkos in your purse, Jesus said. The cheapest coin in the belt.","g":"brass, copper","h":"The picture: a copper pot or coin."},"G5476":{"b":"The word means earthward, down to the dirt. Abbott says \"on or to the ground.\" Jesus spits on the ground and makes clay to open a blind man's eyes. When soldiers come for him and he speaks, they fall backward to the ground.","g":"on the ground","h":"The picture: down onto the bare ground."},"G5477":{"b":"The name means humiliated, brought low. Canaan was the early name for the land of Palestine, the land promised to Abraham and later given to Israel.","g":"Canaan","h":"The picture: humiliated."},"G5478":{"b":"This marks a person from Canaan, the old name of the land. Abbott gives Canaanite. So the picture is a woman of that country. A Canaanite woman cried after Jesus to have mercy and heal her daughter.","g":"Canaanite","h":"The picture: a woman of Canaan."},"G5479":{"b":"This comes from chairo, to be cheerful, calmly happy. Chara is that gladness itself, delight welling up. So the joy set before Christ, or the joy of a shepherd who finds one lost sheep, is this, a heart lit up from the inside.","g":"joy","h":"The picture: a face lit up with gladness."},"G548":{"b":"This word is built from away and to be. It means simply to be away, off somewhere else. Paul writes that though his body is absent his spirit is present with them. The word puts him at a distance, out of the room but not out of mind.","g":"be absent","h":"The picture: standing off at a distance."},"G5480":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to engrave. It is a mark scratched or stamped in, like a brand cut into skin. The mark of the beast is this word. It is not painted on to be washed off. It is cut in.","g":"mark, stamp","h":"The picture: a mark cut into the surface."},"G5481":{"b":"This was a stamp or impress, as on a coin or seal. The die is cut once, then pressed into the metal, leaving its exact mark. The Son is the exact impress of God's very being.","g":"exact image","h":"The picture: the stamp pressed into a coin."},"G5482":{"b":"From a word meaning to sharpen to a point. Abbott says a charax is a pointed stake. Armies drove rows of them into the ground as a wall around a besieged town. Jesus foretold such a bank thrown up against Jerusalem.","g":"trench, rampart","h":"The picture: sharpened stakes driven in."},"G5483":{"b":"The word is built on the word for grace. Abbott-Smith says that in later Greek it means to forgive freely, and his first example is a debt in Luke 7:42.\n\nForgiving is treated as giving. The money is simply let go.","g":"give freely, forgive","h":"The picture: the debt torn up."},"G5485":{"b":"Strong's says graciousness, as gratifying. Abbott-Smith puts gracefulness and loveliness of form first, the quality that draws favourable regard.\n\nSo grace starts as beauty. Something in it makes you glad, before it ever becomes a gift.","g":"grace, favour","h":"The picture: something lovely enough to win you over."},"G5486":{"b":"Abbott calls it a gift of grace, a free gift. The root means to grant as a favor, to hand something over for nothing. A charisma is not wages you earned but a present pressed into your hand, including the gifts of the Spirit.","g":"gift","h":"The picture: a present pressed into your hand."},"G5487":{"b":"The root is the word for grace, a gift freely given. This verb means to pour that grace over someone. Gabriel greets Mary with it, calling her one deeply favored, chosen and covered in kindness she did not earn.","g":"favor, grace","h":"The picture: someone covered in favor."},"G5488":{"b":"The name means parched, dried by heat. It comes from a word meaning to glow. Haran was the city in Mesopotamia where Abraham stopped and stayed before God led him on to Canaan.","g":"Haran","h":"The picture: parched."},"G5489":{"b":"The word is a sheet of paper, made from strips of papyrus. Strong's calls it writing-material to be scribbled over. John says he had much to write, but would not use paper and ink. He hoped to come and speak face to face.","g":"paper","h":"The picture: a sheet of papyrus paper."},"G5490":{"b":"Abbott traces it to a word meaning to yawn. Picture the ground gaping wide, a mouth too broad to cross. Between the rich man and Lazarus a great chasm was fixed, so no one could pass over.","g":"gulf, chasm","h":"The picture: the earth yawning open."},"G5491":{"b":"This is the lip, named as a pouring place, the edge where words pour over. This people honours me with their lips, Jesus quotes, but their heart is far off. It also means the brink of a thing, even the seashore, the sand along the sea's lip.","g":"lip","h":"The picture: the rim where words spill out."},"G5492":{"b":"This comes from a word for winter storm, the pouring rain and cold. It means to be driven and tossed by a tempest. Day after day the gale threw the ship about with no let-up. The word puts the vessel in the teeth of the storm, thrown wherever the wind wills.","g":"storm-tossed","h":"The picture: a ship battered by a winter gale."},"G5493":{"b":"This word joins storm and to flow. It means a torrent fed by winter rain, a bed dry in summer and rushing in the wet months. Jesus crossed one, the Kidron, on the night he was arrested.","g":"winter torrent","h":"The picture: a stream that runs only in the winter rains."},"G5494":{"b":"This is the word for winter and for the storm winter brings, rain driving down. No sun nor stars appeared for many days as the tempest lay on the ship. Pray your flight is not in winter. Wind and cold and a pouring sky.","g":"storm, winter","h":"The picture: a driving winter storm."},"G5495":{"b":"Strong's suggests the word comes from a root meaning hollow, the shape a hand makes when it grasps. He marks it perhaps, and Abbott-Smith gives no origin.\n\nAbbott does add that the hand stands for a person's power.","g":"hand","h":"The picture: the hollow of a cupped hand."},"G5496":{"b":"The word means to take someone by the hand and lead. It is the word for guiding a blind person. Saul was struck blind on the road, so the men with him took his hand and led him into the city.","g":"lead by hand","h":"The picture: leading a blind person by the hand."},"G5497":{"b":"The word joins 'the hand' with 'to lead.' Struck blind for fighting the gospel, Elymas gropes around for someone to take his hand and guide his steps.","g":"lead by the hand","h":"The picture: leading a blind man by the hand."},"G5498":{"b":"Built from hand and write, a paper written by hand. It was often a signed bond, a record of debt. Paul says God wiped out the handwriting of debt against us and nailed it to the cross.","g":"handwriting","h":"The picture: a handwritten IOU."},"G5499":{"b":"This is built from hand and make: something formed by human hands. The false witnesses say Jesus threatened the temple made with hands. Stephen says God does not live in such places. It marks a thing as man-made, shaped by fingers.","g":"made by hands","h":"The picture: a thing shaped by human hands."},"G55":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning clean and pure. It means to act with pure motives, nothing hidden underneath. Paul says some preach Christ sincerely, out of love, with clean hands and no schemes.","g":"purely","h":"The picture: clean, with nothing mixed in."},"G550":{"b":"Strong's reads it as to say off for oneself, to disown. The roots are away and speak. You put your words between yourself and the thing. Paul says he renounced the hidden, shameful ways, spoken off for good.","g":"renounce","h":"The picture: waving something away with a word."},"G5500":{"b":"This began as voting in the Athenian assembly by stretching out the hand, a show of hands to choose a man. So to cheirotoneo someone is to appoint him. Titus was chosen this way by the churches to travel with the gift.","g":"appoint, choose","h":"The picture: raising your hand to vote."},"G5501":{"b":"It is the comparative of bad, worse. The word tracks a slide downhill. The house swept clean but left empty draws back seven worse spirits, and the man's last state is cheirōn than the first. Evil men, Paul says, grow cheirōn and cheirōn.","g":"worse","h":"The picture: the slide downhill."},"G5502":{"b":"This is a Hebrew word carried straight into Greek, the name of the winged figures over the ark. It is a borrowed name, not a Greek word with a meaning inside it, so there is nothing to picture.","flat":1,"g":"cherubim","h":"No picture."},"G5503":{"b":"The word means a widow. Abbott-Smith notes Revelation 18:7 uses it of a city forsaken.\n\nThat is the feel of the word. Not just a woman without a husband. A place where someone used to be.","g":"widow","h":"The picture: a city left empty."},"G5504":{"b":"This word just means yesterday, the day before now. Strong's says its origin is uncertain. Hebrews says Jesus Christ is the same yesterday, today, and forever. A plain time word with no image built into it.","flat":1,"g":"yesterday","h":"No picture."},"G5505":{"b":"From chilioi, a thousand. A chilias is a group of one thousand, a full thousand reckoned as one block. So the thousands of thousands around the throne are counted in these blocks, crowds too vast to number one by one.","g":"thousand","h":"The picture: a thousand counted together."},"G5506":{"b":"Abbott-Smith spells it out. The commander of a thousand.\n\nIn the New Testament he is usually a Roman tribune in charge of a cohort. The rank is written into the name itself.","g":"commander","h":"The picture: the officer over a thousand."},"G5507":{"b":"This is simply the number a thousand. Strong's says it is a plural of uncertain affinity, so no one knows where it came from. It is a number and nothing more. There is no picture to see.","flat":1,"g":"thousand","h":"No picture."},"G5508":{"b":"This is Chios, an island in the sea, one the ship lay near overnight on the voyage. It is only a place name of uncertain origin, so there is nothing here to picture.","flat":1,"g":"Chios","h":"No picture."},"G5509":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this is the garment worn next the skin, the inner tunic, as opposed to the cloak worn over it. When Jesus says give your cloak as well, this is the undergarment beneath it.","g":"tunic","h":"The picture: the shirt next to the skin."},"G551":{"b":"The root means to test, to put a thing through a trial. Add the \"not\" and you get one who cannot be put to this test at all. James says God cannot be tempted by evil. No trial touches him there.","g":"not to be tempted","h":"The picture: metal that no trial can test."},"G5510":{"b":"Chion is snow. At the tomb the angel's appearance is like lightning and his clothing white as snow, so bright the guards shake and fall like dead men. Snow-white, the color of something not of this world.","g":"snow","h":"The picture: fresh white snow."},"G5511":{"b":"A chlamys is a short military cloak, the kind a soldier wore. The soldiers strip Jesus and throw a scarlet chlamys on him, press a crown of thorns down, and mock him as king. A soldier's cloak for a false coronation.","g":"robe, cloak","h":"The picture: a soldier's cloak thrown over his shoulders."},"G5512":{"b":"Strong's says \"to throw out the lip,\" to jeer. Abbott ties it to a word for a jest and says \"to mock, jeer.\" When Paul spoke of the dead rising, some in Athens curled their lips and laughed him off. The mocking mouth made plain.","g":"mock, jeer","h":"The picture: pushing out the lip in a sneer."},"G5513":{"b":"The word means \"warm, tepid.\" It comes from a word meaning to become warm. Picture a cup of water gone lukewarm, not hot enough to soothe, not cold enough to refresh. So the church makes Christ want to spit it from his mouth.","g":"lukewarm","h":"The picture: water neither hot nor cold."},"G5514":{"b":"Her name means green. Abbott says it pictures tender foliage, the soft new green of fresh growth. Paul heard of the quarrels at Corinth from the people of Chloe's household. Her name is the color of spring.","g":"Chloe","h":"The picture: fresh green shoots."},"G5515":{"b":"The word is the green of new growth. Jesus sits the crowd down on the green grass with this word. But turned toward a face it means pale, drained. The fourth horseman rides a chloros horse, the sick green-grey of a corpse.","g":"green, pale","h":"The picture: the green of fresh grass, or a sickly pale."},"G5517":{"b":"The root means loose dirt, a heap of soil poured out. So this word means earthy, made of dust. Paul calls the first man this, formed from the ground, of the dust, before the man from heaven.","g":"earthy","h":"The picture: made of loose dirt."},"G5518":{"b":"This is a dry measure, a bit less than a quart, about a day's grain for one man. In Revelation a whole day's wage buys just one of these. Picture a small cup of wheat, one day's food.","g":"a measure","h":"The picture: a day's cup of grain."},"G5519":{"b":"This word just means a pig. Strong's says it is of uncertain derivation, so no one knows where it comes from. There is nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"pig, swine","h":"No picture."},"G552":{"b":"The root means a test, an attempt, experience. Put 'not' in front and you get the one who has never made the trial. A baby fed on milk is untried in the word of righteousness, still a beginner.","g":"unskilled","h":"The picture: hands that have never tried it."},"G5520":{"b":"From a word for gall or bile, the bitter fluid in the body. The old idea was that anger came from stirred-up bile. Jesus asked why they were angry with him for making a man whole on the sabbath. Anger tasted bitter as gall.","g":"be angry","h":"The picture: bitter bile rising inside."},"G5521":{"b":"Chole is gall, the bitter bile of the body, named perhaps for its greenish color. It stood for anything bitter or poisonous. At the cross they offer Jesus wine mixed with gall, and having tasted the bitterness he will not drink.","g":"gall","h":"The picture: the bitter green bile."},"G5522":{"b":"Strong's calls it a heap, as poured out, loose dirt. Abbott-Smith starts with earth or soil, then dust. It is the dry ground that runs through your fingers. The disciples shake this off their feet against a town that will not hear them.","g":"dust","h":"The picture: loose dirt you can pour out."},"G5523":{"b":"Chorazin is a place, a town of Galilee. Strong's says the name is of uncertain derivation, so no one knows what it is built from. It is a spot on the map, with nothing to see.","flat":1,"g":"Chorazin","h":"No picture."},"G5524":{"b":"The word first meant to lead and pay for a chorus. In Athens a rich citizen bore the whole cost of the singers and dancers for a festival. So it came to mean to supply lavishly. God supplies and multiplies your seed.","g":"supply","h":"The picture: the patron who paid for the chorus."},"G5525":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives one word: a dance. Strong's adds a ring, a round dance. When the lost son came home, the house broke into music and dancing, a circle of celebration, because the father's son was found alive.","g":"dancing","h":"The picture: people dancing in a ring."},"G5526":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the word was used of animals, to feed, fatten. It is a barnyard word. The flock filled with grass. Later it means to fill people with food. Blessed are the hungry, for they shall be filled full.","g":"fill, satisfy","h":"The picture: cattle fed full on fodder."},"G5527":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is fodder, the feed you throw to livestock. It grows from a word meaning to fatten with food. When famine strikes in Acts, the word for their food is the word for animal feed.","g":"food, fodder","h":"The picture: hay for the animals."},"G5528":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the first sense is an enclosure, a feeding place. It was the pen where animals fed. From there the word moved to the grass itself, the green fodder they ate. Grass that is here today and gone tomorrow.","g":"grass","h":"The picture: the fenced feeding place."},"G5529":{"b":"This is just a man's name, and Strong's says its origin is uncertain. He was Herod's steward, and his wife Joanna helped support Jesus out of her own money. A name with no known root gives nothing to picture.","flat":1,"g":"Chuza","h":"No picture."},"G553":{"b":"A stacked word built on receiving, with prefixes that stretch it out and forward. It means to await or expect eagerly. Creation itself waits on tiptoe for the sons of God to be revealed. Straining toward the arrival.","g":"wait for","h":"The picture: watching the road for someone to come."},"G5530":{"b":"Abbott's sense is to use, make use of, and Strong's links it to the hand, to handle. To chraomai is to take a thing in hand and put it to work. Paul tells the freed slave, if you can gain your freedom, use it. Use the world, but do not lean on it.","g":"to use","h":"The picture: taking a thing in hand."},"G5531":{"b":"This word means to lend. In Jesus' story, a man bangs on his friend's door at midnight, asking to borrow three loaves for a guest who has just arrived. Keep knocking, Jesus says, and the door will open.","g":"lend","h":"The picture: handing over bread at midnight."},"G5532":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is need, necessity, the gap between what you have and what you must have. Chreia is the lack itself. So your Father knows what things you have chreia of, the empty places, before you ever ask him to fill them.","g":"need","h":"The picture: the empty place that must be filled."},"G5533":{"b":"The word joins \"a debt\" and \"one who owes\". It is the debtor, the person who borrowed and must pay back. Jesus tells of two such men who owed a lender, one a large sum, one small, and both were let off.","g":"debtor","h":"The picture: the man who owes money."},"G5534":{"b":"This comes from a word about furnishing what is needed. Abbott gives it is necessary. So it names what a moment calls for, what must be. Out of the same mouth come blessing and cursing. These things, James says, ought not to be so.","g":"ought","h":"The picture: what the moment calls for."},"G5535":{"b":"Strong's traces this to a word for need. Abbott gives to have need of. Jesus says your Father knows the things you chreizo, the things you are short of, before you ever ask Him, Matthew 6:32. Known lack, already seen.","g":"to need","h":"The picture: the thing you are short of."},"G5536":{"b":"The word comes from to use. Money is named here as simply the useful thing, what you need and handle. It is hard, Jesus says, for those who have it to enter the kingdom. Simon even tries to buy the Spirit with it.","g":"wealth, money","h":"The picture: the useful stuff."},"G5537":{"b":"This grows from a word for business and money. Abbott-Smith says it first meant to transact business, then to give an official answer, like a ruler's reply. In the Bible it is God giving that word, warning or directing.","g":"warned by God","h":"The picture: an official answer."},"G5538":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to utter an oracle, to speak from God. Abbott gives a divine response, an oracle. So it is heaven's answer spoken back. To Elijah the divine reply came, I have kept for myself seven thousand men.","g":"God's answer","h":"The picture: God's answer spoken back."},"G5539":{"b":"The root means employment, putting a thing to use. Useful means fit to be used, a tool that earns its keep. Paul says striving about words is not useful. It sits in the hand and does no work.","g":"useful","h":"The picture: a tool that gets used."},"G554":{"b":"This word means to strip off clothes or armor, pulling the old garment right off. Paul says you have put off the old self like a filthy robe. Not straightened up, but taken off entirely and dropped. And Christ stripped the powers bare.","g":"put off, strip","h":"The picture: stripping off the old clothes."},"G5540":{"b":"The root is simply to use, to furnish what is needed. Paul turns it to the body: women exchanged the natural use for what is against nature. The word means employing a thing for its purpose, and Paul's point is the design was traded away.","g":"use","h":"The picture: what a thing is for."},"G5541":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning useful, serviceable, kind. Abbott gives to be kind. So the picture is love that makes itself useful. Love is patient, love is kind, putting itself to work for the good of others.","g":"be kind","h":"The picture: love that makes itself useful."},"G5542":{"b":"This joins a word for pleasant or kind with a word for speaking. It is talk that sounds good, fair and smooth on the ear. Abbott says here it is used in a bad sense. Paul warns that such honeyed words deceive simple hearts.","g":"fair speech","h":"The picture: smooth, sweet-sounding talk."},"G5543":{"b":"The root means to furnish what is needed, so this word is serviceable, good, fit for use. It describes the old wine that is mellow and the easy yoke that does not rub the neck raw. Of God it means kind. Useful, gentle, good to have.","g":"good, kind","h":"The picture: the yoke that fits without chafing."},"G5544":{"b":"The root means useful, fit for service. So this kindness is not just a warm feeling. It is goodness that actually does something for you. Abbott sets it opposite severity. Usefulness turned toward people.","g":"kindness","h":"The picture: goodness put to use."},"G5545":{"b":"The root means to smear or rub with oil. A chrisma is the oil itself, or the rubbing of it on. John tells believers they have an anointing from God that teaches them. The old kings and priests had oil poured on their heads. This oil is the Spirit, and it stays.","g":"anointing","h":"The picture: oil rubbed on."},"G5546":{"b":"This word comes from Christos, the Anointed One, the one smeared with oil and set apart. A Christian is one who belongs to him, stamped with his name. Outsiders at Antioch coined the label first.","g":"Christian","h":"The picture: the Anointed One's name stamped on you."},"G5547":{"b":"Abbott-Smith builds this word from the verb to anoint. Strong's says it means anointed.\n\nSo Christ is not a surname. It is a title. It marks out the one who was set apart by anointing.","g":"Christ, anointed one","h":"The picture: oil poured over someone's head."},"G5548":{"b":"This means to smear or rub with oil. Oil poured and rubbed over the head to set a man apart as priest or king. God anointed Jesus with the Holy Spirit, marked out and set apart. Oil on the skin.","g":"anoint","h":"The picture: oil rubbed on the head."},"G5549":{"b":"The root is chronos, time. To chronizo is to let time run on, to be long in coming. If that servant says my master chronizo, Jesus says, and starts to beat the others, the delay shows what his heart really is.","g":"to delay","h":"The picture: the master long in coming."},"G555":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to strip off completely, like peeling off a garment. It means a putting off. Paul says in Christ you were stripped of the body of the flesh, the old self taken off like a coat.","g":"putting off","h":"The picture: stripping off old clothes."},"G5550":{"b":"Strong's says the origin is uncertain, so nothing shows through. Abbott-Smith defines it as a space of time, whether long or short. This is clock time, plain duration, with no image inside it.","flat":1,"g":"time","h":"No picture."},"G5551":{"b":"Two parts, time and a rut or worn track. To wear time down the way feet grind a rut into a path. Paul would not wear away his days in Asia, hurrying on toward Jerusalem.","g":"spend time","h":"The picture: wearing a rut in the road."},"G5552":{"b":"From chrysos, gold. Chryseos means golden, made or overlaid with gold, catching the light. So Revelation fills heaven with golden lampstands, golden bowls, a golden crown, the whole scene gleaming with the metal that does not tarnish.","g":"golden","h":"The picture: made of gold, gleaming."},"G5553":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this is the small form of the word for gold. So it is a piece of gold, a coin or ornament rather than the raw metal in bulk. Peter says faith is tested like gold in fire.","g":"gold","h":"The picture: a little piece of gold."},"G5554":{"b":"Built straight from two words, gold and finger-ring, this is a man with a gold ring on his hand. James pictures him walking into your meeting while everyone scrambles to give him the good seat.","g":"gold ring","h":"The picture: a gold ring on the hand."},"G5555":{"b":"The name joins the word for gold to the word for stone. Strong's calls it \"gold-stone, i.e. a yellow gem.\" Picture a stone glowing warm yellow like gold. So chrysolite was the seventh foundation of the city wall.","g":"chrysolite","h":"The picture: a golden-yellow stone."},"G5556":{"b":"Strong's says the name joins the word for gold to the word for a leek, a \"greenish-yellow gem.\" Picture a stone the pale green-gold of a leek stalk. So chrysoprase was the tenth foundation of the city wall.","g":"chrysoprase","h":"The picture: a stone the color of a leek."},"G5557":{"b":"Gold, the metal itself and golden things, ornaments, coins, idols. The wise men lay it before the child with frankincense and myrrh. The precious metal, plain and heavy in the hand.","g":"gold","h":"The picture: gold."},"G5558":{"b":"From the word for gold. So it means to cover a thing in gold, to gild it. John sees the harlot decked and covered with gold. Picture a surface overlaid with shining gold.","g":"to gild","h":"The picture: a surface covered in gold."},"G5559":{"b":"This does not mean the whole body but its surface or skin. The outermost layer, what your hand touches. Aprons that had lain against Paul's skin were taken to the sick as if the touch clung to them.","g":"body, skin","h":"The picture: the skin itself."},"G556":{"b":"This joins away with a word meaning to push, the way wind pushes or oars drive a boat. To shove a person off. Gallio drove the accusers away from the judgment seat.","g":"drive away","h":"The picture: shoved off like a boat by oars."},"G5560":{"b":"This word means lame, limping. Strong's calls it a primary word, so it does not come from anything else. It simply names a limp. There is nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"lame","h":"No picture."},"G5561":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the oldest sense is a space, place. Room first, then the country that fills the room.\n\nMatthew uses it for the land and shadow of death. A whole region sitting under it.","g":"land, region","h":"The picture: open ground."},"G5562":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means to make room, to give way. The word comes from the word for space. It is the picture of clearing space so more can fit, or stepping aside to let something pass.","g":"make room, contain","h":"The picture: making room."},"G5563":{"b":"Strong's says the word means to place room between, to part. You open up a gap between two things once joined. \"What God has joined together, let no one separate.\"","g":"separate, depart","h":"The picture: putting space between."},"G5564":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means an estate, a property, a piece of land. It is a smaller form of the word for land, so it pictures a modest plot. The field of blood was bought with Judas' silver.","g":"field, plot","h":"The picture: a little patch of ground."},"G5566":{"b":"This is a Latin word for the northwest wind. It names one of the directions the harbour faced, toward the northwest. There is no deeper root to open up. The word simply is that wind, blowing in cold and hard from the top left corner of the sky.","g":"northwest wind","h":"The picture: the wind out of the northwest."},"G5567":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the first sense is to pull, twitch, twang, like a bowstring. It grew into playing a stringed instrument with the fingers. So making melody to God started as a finger plucking a string and letting it ring.","g":"sing, make melody","h":"The picture: plucking a taut string."},"G5568":{"b":"It comes from a word meaning to twitch or twang a string. A psalmos began as fingers plucking a harp. Before it was words on a page it was a sound, a plucked string carrying a song of praise to God.","g":"psalm","h":"The picture: fingers plucking a harp string."},"G5569":{"b":"The word joins false and brother. A pseudadelphos looks like one of the family but is a pretender in the ranks. Paul counts perils among false brethren, and warns of those who crept in to spy out our freedom.","g":"false brother","h":"The picture: the pretender in the family."},"G557":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to convict, refute, to prove a thing worthless. With a prefix it means being shown up and thrown out as nothing. The craftsmen feared their trade would be brought to contempt.","g":"contempt","h":"The picture: exposed and cast aside."},"G5570":{"b":"The roots are false and one sent out. Abbott-Smith says a false apostle. Paul warns of men playing the messenger of Christ, sent by nobody, dressing themselves up as apostles of light.","g":"false apostle","h":"The picture: an impostor wearing a badge no one gave him."},"G5571":{"b":"This word comes from the word to lie. Pseudes is false, a person or thing that does not match the truth. Think of the false witness rising to his feet in court, saying what did not happen, as they did against Stephen.","g":"false","h":"The picture: the false witness on his feet."},"G5572":{"b":"This joins \"untrue, deceitful\" to the word for an instructor. So it is a false teacher. Peter warns that just as false prophets rose among Israel, such teachers will slip in with destructive lies.","g":"false teacher","h":"The picture: the teacher who lies."},"G5573":{"b":"This joins pseudes, false, and lego, to speak. So it is one who speaks falsely, a lying tongue. Paul warns that some will depart from the faith through the hypocrisy of such liars, their conscience seared.","g":"speaking lies","h":"The picture: a tongue that speaks lies."},"G5574":{"b":"This word just means to tell a lie. Strong's says it is the middle voice of an apparently primary verb, so it does not come from anything else. There is nothing behind it to see.","flat":1,"g":"lie","h":"No picture."},"G5575":{"b":"This joins \"false\" to martys, a witness. A pseudomartyr is one who stands up to testify to a lie. At Jesus' trial the council hunts for such false witnesses to put him to death, but their stories do not agree.","g":"false witness","h":"The picture: the lying witness in the dock."},"G5576":{"b":"The word joins \"false\" and \"witness.\" To pseudomartyreo is to stand up in court and swear to a lie. Do not pseudomartyreo, says the commandment. Against Jesus many did, and their testimonies did not even agree.","g":"bear false witness","h":"The picture: a lying witness in court."},"G5577":{"b":"This joins \"false\" to the word for a witness who testifies. A pseudomartyria is a lie told under oath, someone standing up to swear to what never happened. It is one of the evils Jesus says pours out of the heart.","g":"false witness","h":"The picture: a witness swearing to a lie."},"G5578":{"b":"This joins two words. Strong's traces the front half to a word for the untrue and deceitful. The back half is a foreteller. So a false prophet is not a mistaken man. He is a mouth faking the voice of God.","g":"false prophet","h":"The picture: a prophet who lies."},"G5579":{"b":"The root means to utter an untruth or attempt to deceive by falsehood. Abbott keeps setting this word opposite the truth. So a lie is not just a wrong fact. It is a fake made to pass for the real thing.","g":"lie","h":"The picture: the counterfeit set against the real."},"G558":{"b":"This joins away with a word meaning not a slave, a free citizen. An apeleutheros is a slave who has been set free, chains struck off. Paul says the slave called in the Lord is the Lord's freedman.","g":"freedman","h":"The picture: the slave whose chains are off."},"G5580":{"b":"This joins \"false\" to Christos, the Anointed One. A pseudochristos is a counterfeit Messiah, a man claiming the office he was never given. Jesus warns that such pretenders will rise and, if they could, deceive even the chosen.","g":"false Christ","h":"The picture: a pretender to the anointed throne."},"G5581":{"b":"This joins a word meaning untrue to the word for a name. It is where we get pseudonym. Paul warns of knowledge that is falsely so called. The name on it is a lie. What is inside does not match the label.","g":"falsely called","h":"The picture: a false name on the label."},"G5582":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to utter an untruth. Abbott gives a lie, falsehood. So the picture is something made up against the truth. Paul rejects the twisted claim that God's honor is served by a man's lie.","g":"a lie","h":"The picture: something made up against the truth."},"G5583":{"b":"The same root means to deceive by falsehood. Here it is made a person, a liar. Jesus calls the devil this and names him the father of it. The lie now has a face and a mouth.","g":"liar","h":"The picture: the man behind the lie."},"G5584":{"b":"Abbott traces this to a word meaning to touch. It means to feel or grope about, hands out in the dark, searching for something solid. So the risen Jesus says handle me and see, a ghost has no flesh to grip.","g":"feel, handle","h":"The picture: hands groping in the dark."},"G5585":{"b":"Strong's says this is \"to use pebbles in enumeration.\" Before there were sums on paper, people reckoned with small stones. Jesus says a man building a tower first sits and counts the cost, moving the pebbles, before he lays a stone.","g":"count, reckon","h":"The picture: counting out the cost with pebbles."},"G5586":{"b":"This word is a pebble, a little stone worn smooth by handling. People voted by dropping pebbles in a jar, so it also came to mean a vote. Paul cast his stone against the saints, agreeing to their death.","g":"pebble, vote","h":"The picture: a small stone worn smooth in the hand."},"G5587":{"b":"The root is simply to whisper. Abbott-Smith says a whispering, and then secret slander. Paul fears finding this among them, the low voices that spread poison about a person while their back is turned.","g":"whispering","h":"The picture: a hand cupped to the ear, hissing gossip."},"G5588":{"b":"The root means whispering, the secret running-down of others. So this is the person who murmurs low so no one else hears. Abbott says a whisperer. Paul lists them among those whose hearts have gone wrong.","g":"whisperer","h":"The picture: someone whispering behind a hand."},"G5589":{"b":"This is a little word for a little thing, a crumb, the scrap that falls when bread is broken. The woman tells Jesus even the dogs eat the crumbs under the children's table. She asks only for a scrap.","g":"crumb","h":"The picture: a crumb dropped from the table."},"G559":{"b":"Just a name, of Latin origin, with no meaning handed down. Paul calls Apelles approved in Christ, tested and proven true. The name itself shows nothing to see.","flat":1,"g":"Apelles","h":"No picture."},"G5590":{"b":"Strong's leads with breath. Abbott says breath of life.\n\nThe soul was first the breathing in you. When Jesus talks about losing your soul, this is the word. The breath that keeps you alive.","g":"soul, life","h":"The picture: breath."},"G5591":{"b":"This is built on psyche, the word for breath, the plain animal life. A psychikos person runs on nature alone, the life that breathing keeps going, and no more. Paul sets it against the Spirit. Breath-life is not enough.","g":"natural","h":"The picture: the plain breath-life of an animal."},"G5592":{"b":"This word comes from a word meaning to breathe gently, to blow soft and cool. It is the chill in the air. Peter stood warming himself at the fire because of the psychos, the cold of the night.","g":"cold","h":"The picture: a cool breath of night air."},"G5593":{"b":"The word means cold, chilly. Abbott-Smith notes it stands for cold water. Jesus says whoever gives even a cup of cold water to a little one will not lose his reward. The smallest kindness, a cold drink, is seen and counted.","g":"cold","h":"The picture: a cup of cold water."},"G5594":{"b":"This word first means to breathe gently, to blow. Blow on something hot and it cools. So the word came to mean to grow cold. In Matthew 24:12 Jesus says that because evil spreads, the love of many will grow cold.","g":"grow cold","h":"The picture: breath cooling something warm."},"G5595":{"b":"The root is a word for a crumb or morsel, a mouthful. It first meant to feed with small bits, the way you feed a child or someone sick. So to feed your enemy is close, hand-to-mouth care.","g":"feed, nourish","h":"The picture: feeding by small morsels."},"G5596":{"b":"Strong's: \"a crumb or morsel (as if rubbed off),\" a single bite pinched from the loaf. At the supper Jesus dips this piece and hands it to Judas. One small mouthful, and the betrayer takes it.","g":"sop, morsel","h":"The picture: a bite of bread pinched from the loaf."},"G5597":{"b":"Strong's says this means to rub out kernels from husks with the fingers or hand. The disciples did exactly this walking through a field on the Sabbath, rolling the wheat heads in their palms and eating the grain.","g":"rub","h":"The picture: rubbing grain from the husk in your hands."},"G56":{"b":"The word is knowledge with a not fixed to the front. Ignorance, the blank where knowing should be. Paul jolts the Corinthians: wake up, stop sinning, for some have no knowledge of God. He says it to their shame, a darkness better light could clear.","g":"ignorance","h":"The picture: simply not knowing."},"G560":{"b":"This joins a word for from or back and a word meaning to hope. Abbott's New Testament sense is to hope to receive from or in return. So it is expecting nothing back. Lend, Jesus says, hoping for nothing again, and your reward will be great.","g":"expect back","h":"The picture: expecting nothing back."},"G5601":{"b":"The name means serving. It comes from a word meaning to work or serve. Obed was the son of Boaz and Ruth, the father of Jesse and grandfather of King David.","g":"Obed","h":"The picture: serving."},"G5602":{"b":"Strong's puts it in this same spot, here. Hode plants a flag on the ground where you stand and says the thing is right here. So they say we have only five loaves hode, here in our hands, nothing more, when Jesus asks what they have.","g":"here","h":"The picture: this very spot, right here."},"G5603":{"b":"From ado, simply to sing. An ode is a song, sad or glad, words lifted on a tune. They sing a new song before the throne. The plain sound of a raised voice, no instrument needed for it.","g":"song","h":"The picture: a raised voice singing."},"G5604":{"b":"This is the sharp pang of childbirth, the labor pain that grips and will not stop. Jesus calls the wars and famines the beginning of these, the first contractions before something is born. Sudden and unavoidable, like a woman's travail.","g":"birth pang","h":"The picture: the pains of a woman in labor."},"G5605":{"b":"The root odin is a birth-pang. To odino is to be in labor, gripped by the throes of giving birth. Paul says he is in these pains again over the Galatians, laboring until Christ is formed in them.","g":"travail in birth","h":"The picture: the pains of childbirth."},"G5606":{"b":"The omos is the shoulder, named as the place a burden rides. Jesus says the teachers tie heavy loads and lay them on other men's shoulders but will not lift a finger. The shepherd, though, carries the found sheep home on his.","g":"shoulder","h":"The picture: the shoulder that carries the load."},"G5608":{"b":"Strong's traces this to a word meaning a sum or price. To buy is to hand over what a thing costs. In Acts it is Abraham paying silver for a field to bury his dead.","g":"buy","h":"The picture: the price counted out."},"G5609":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives one word: an egg. No father whose son asks for an egg would hand him a scorpion instead, Jesus says. If flawed fathers give good gifts, how much more the Father in heaven.","g":"egg","h":"The picture: an egg."},"G5610":{"b":"Abbott gives the older sense first. Any time or period fixed by nature, especially a season. Spring comes when it comes.\n\nOnly later does it shrink to a twelfth part of the day. An hour.","g":"hour, time","h":"The picture: the season, fixed by nature."},"G5611":{"b":"This word comes from the word for an hour or season. It first meant timely, ripe, said of fruit picked at just the right moment. From there it came to mean beautiful, the bloom of a thing at its best. Whitewashed tombs, Jesus says, look horaios outside.","g":"beautiful","h":"The picture: fruit at the peak of its season."},"G5612":{"b":"The word is to roar or howl, used of animals. Abbott names the lion. Peter says the devil prowls like a roaring lion, looking for someone to swallow. Stay awake.","g":"roar","h":"The picture: a lion roaring for its prey."},"G5615":{"b":"This word only means in the same way, likewise. It points back to a pattern already given and repeats it. There is no object or action of its own to see here, just the shape of one thing matching another.","flat":1,"g":"likewise","h":"No picture."},"G5616":{"b":"Hosei means as if, as it were, like. It sets one thing beside another to show a likeness. So the Spirit descends hosei a dove, and the tongues appear hosei of fire. Not a dove, not fire, but so like it the eye reaches for the word like.","g":"as if, about","h":"The picture: laid alongside, as if it were."},"G5617":{"b":"The name means deliverer, one who saves. Hosea was a prophet of Israel, called to preach faithfulness to a people who had turned away, using his own marriage as a living picture.","g":"Hosea","h":"The picture: deliverer."},"G562":{"b":"The root means to finish or reach the end, and the a undoes it. So it is having no end, no limit you could ever reach. Paul warns against endless genealogies that breed questions instead of building faith.","g":"endless","h":"The picture: a road with no far end."},"G5621":{"b":"The root is the ear, and this is its small form, a little ear or the lobe. When they came for Jesus, Peter's sword took off the servant's otion. Jesus touched the ear and healed it, mending what the blade had cut.","g":"ear","h":"The picture: the little ear cut off."},"G5622":{"b":"The word means profit, advantage, benefit, what you actually get out of something. Paul asks, then what advantage has the Jew. And answers, much in every way. It weighs a thing and asks the plain question, what good does this bring me.","g":"profit","h":"The picture: what you gain from it."},"G5623":{"b":"Abbott's sense is to help, benefit, do good, profit. It asks whether a thing actually helps or only looks good. Jesus asks what it ōpheleō a man to gain the whole world and lose his soul. In the end the world profits him nothing.","g":"to profit","h":"The picture: whether a thing actually helps."},"G5624":{"b":"Strong's traces this to a word for gain. Abbott gives useful, profitable. All Scripture is ophelimos, Paul says, it pays out for teaching, correcting, and training in righteousness, Second Timothy 3:16. A thing that leaves you better off than before.","g":"profitable","h":"The picture: the thing that pays off."},"G563":{"b":"This is not joined to a word meaning to drag all around, to distract with care. It pictures a person not yanked this way and that by worries. Paul wants them to serve the Lord pulled in no direction but one.","g":"without distraction","h":"The picture: not yanked this way and that."},"G564":{"b":"The root means to cut around, to circumcise. With 'not' in front, it means uncircumcised. Stephen turns the word onto the heart, calling them uncircumcised in heart, sealed shut against the Spirit.","g":"uncircumcised","h":"The picture: flesh never cut."},"G565":{"b":"Strong's builds it from two pieces: away, and come.\n\nAbbott-Smith adds that late writers gave it a finishing force, so it can mean arriving at the far end. You leave here, and the thought follows you all the way there.","g":"go away, depart","h":"The picture: walking off from where you were."},"G568":{"b":"Strong's gives the active sense as to have out, to receive in full.\n\nAbbott-Smith notes it was the word written on receipts. When Jesus says the hypocrites have their reward, this is the word. The account is settled.","g":"have in full","h":"The picture: paid in full."},"G569":{"b":"The alpha in front cancels believing. It means to disbelieve, be faithless. When word came that Jesus was alive, they would not believe it. Abbott notes it can even slide into disobeying. The head that shakes at the news.","g":"disbelieve","h":"The picture: too good to be believed."},"G57":{"b":"This is the word for known with a not in front. Abbott gives unknown. So it names what no one can name. In Athens Paul found an altar inscribed to the unknown God, and told them who he is.","g":"unknown","h":"The picture: an altar to a God no one knows."},"G570":{"b":"The alpha at the front cancels faith. This is want of faith, unbelief. In his own hometown Jesus marveled at their unbelief and could do little work there. A heart that will not be won over blocks even his hands.","g":"unbelief","h":"The picture: the town that would not believe."},"G571":{"b":"Abbott-Smith splits it into a negative plus the word for trustworthy. Not-trusting.\n\nIt works both ways. Of a thing it means incredible. Of a person it means one who will not trust.","g":"unbelieving","h":"The picture: no trust in it."},"G572":{"b":"The root pictures cloth folded in a single layer, not doubled over. A single, undivided heart with no hidden second fold. So haplotes is sincerity, and also open-handed giving, a life folded just one way, plain and straight.","g":"sincerity","h":"The picture: cloth folded just once."},"G573":{"b":"Strong's says this pictures something folded together into one, single, not doubled or divided. Abbott-Smith says simple, single. Jesus says if your eye is single, your whole body is full of light. One focus, not split two ways. A heart folded into one piece.","g":"single, clear","h":"The picture: cloth laid in a single fold."},"G574":{"b":"The root pictures cloth folded just once, a single fold, nothing doubled or hidden. So God gives with one open hand, no strings, no second thought. Ask him for wisdom and it comes to you plainly.","g":"liberally","h":"The picture: cloth folded just once, single."},"G576":{"b":"The word is \"step\" with \"off\" joined to it, built on the word for a foot. It means to step off, to disembark. The fishermen apobaino from their boats to wash the nets. Used of events, it means how a thing turns out in the end.","g":"disembark","h":"The picture: stepping off the boat onto shore."},"G577":{"b":"Two words joined: throw and away. In Mark the blind man throws off his cloak to run to Jesus. So when Hebrews says do not throw away your confidence, the picture is a coat flung aside and left in the dust.","g":"cast away","h":"The picture: flinging off your coat."},"G578":{"b":"This word means to look away from all else at one object, to turn the eyes from everything and fix them on one thing. Moses looked away from Egypt's treasure and gazed steadily at the reward.","g":"look steadfastly","h":"The picture: eyes turned from all else to one thing."},"G579":{"b":"The root means to throw off or cast away. An apobletos is something tossed out, rejected. Paul says every creature of God is good, and nothing is to be thrown away if received with thanksgiving.","g":"to be rejected","h":"The picture: a thing thrown out as rubbish."},"G58":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the word comes from a word meaning to bring together. The market was the town square, the spot where people came together to buy, sell, and talk. It is a gathering place.","g":"market, square","h":"The picture: the place where people gather."},"G580":{"b":"The root means to throw off, to cast away. In the storm the crew threw the cargo overboard to save the ship. Paul uses the same word two ways here: no life would be thrown away, though the ship itself would be lost.","g":"loss","h":"The picture: cargo thrown overboard."},"G581":{"b":"Built from \"away\" and \"to become,\" this means to be gone, removed, departed from life. Peter says Christ carried our sins so that we, dead to them, might be done with them for good and live for what is right.","g":"being dead","h":"The picture: gone, departed from life."},"G582":{"b":"The root means to write off a copy, to enrol on a list. This is the register itself, a census. Luke uses it for the count ordered by Caesar that sent Joseph and Mary to Bethlehem, their names written into Rome's roll.","g":"census","h":"The picture: names written down on a list."},"G583":{"b":"The word is \"write\" with \"off\" in front, to copy off, to write a name onto a list. Caesar orders the whole world apographo, registered for the tax. So Joseph goes up to Bethlehem to have his name written on the roll.","g":"enrol","h":"The picture: a name written down onto the roll."},"G584":{"b":"The word is built on a verb meaning \"to show,\" to point at. With apo it means to show off, to put on display. Abbott: \"to bring out, show forth, exhibit.\" God set the apostles out last of all, like men led out to die.","g":"show, prove","h":"The picture: pointing a thing out for all to see."},"G585":{"b":"This rests on a word meaning to show off, to exhibit. An apodeixis holds a thing up for all to see, plain proof on display. Paul's preaching was this kind of showing, the Spirit's power set out in the open.","g":"demonstration","h":"The picture: held up for all to see."},"G586":{"b":"The word means to pay a tenth of, to set aside one part in ten and hand it over. The Pharisee brags he tithes even his garden herbs, counting out a tenth of the mint leaves while the weightier things go untouched.","g":"tithe","h":"The picture: counting off one part in ten."},"G587":{"b":"This word comes from the same root as welcome, to take fully and approve. What is acceptable gets received gladly, taken in rather than turned away at the door. Paul says caring for family is acceptable before God. The kind of thing he receives with open hands.","g":"acceptable","h":"The picture: received gladly, not turned away."},"G588":{"b":"Apo means fully, and dechomai means to receive. Apodechomai is taking someone in completely, both hands out. Luke uses it of the crowd that welcomed Jesus back by the shore. Not a grudging nod but a full, glad welcome.","g":"welcome, receive","h":"The picture: taking someone in with both hands."},"G589":{"b":"This is built from a word for a foreign traveller, a man away from his own people. It is the owner in Jesus' stories who goes into a far country and leaves servants in charge. To pack up and be gone, far from home.","g":"go abroad","h":"The picture: leaving home for a far country."},"G59":{"b":"Strong's says the word properly means to go to market, and then to purchase. Abbott starts with frequenting the marketplace.\n\nWhen the New Testament says redeemed, this is the word. Bought, with a price named.","g":"buy, redeem","h":"The picture: going to market."},"G590":{"b":"This word joins a word for away with the word for your own people. It means someone gone abroad, far from home. In the parable a man like this leaves his house and servants and travels to a distant country. He is out of reach.","g":"foreign traveller","h":"The picture: away from your own people."},"G591":{"b":"Give, with back attached. Abbott-Smith's sense is to give up or back, restore, return, and then to render what is due, to pay.\n\nReward and repayment are the same motion. What is owed goes back to its owner.","g":"give back, repay","h":"The picture: handing it back."},"G592":{"b":"The root means to mark out a boundary, the word behind horizon. So this is to divide off, to make separations. Jude says these men draw such lines, splitting the church, following instinct and lacking the Spirit.","g":"separate","h":"The picture: drawing a line to fence people off."},"G593":{"b":"Two words, to test and away. It means to examine something and reject it, like builders inspecting a stone and tossing it. The stone the builders rejected became the cornerstone. Judged, then discarded.","g":"reject","h":"The picture: tested, then thrown away."},"G594":{"b":"This word comes from a root meaning to take fully, to welcome. It is the warm reception a trusted guest is given, taken in with both hands. Paul says the saying is worthy of all acceptance. A message you receive gladly, not at arm's length.","g":"acceptance","h":"The picture: welcomed in with both hands."},"G595":{"b":"This means a laying aside, a putting off. Peter uses it of laying the body down like a garment. Picture pulling off a coat and setting it away. Something you take off and lay down.","g":"putting away","h":"The picture: a coat taken off and laid down."},"G596":{"b":"From a word meaning to put away, a place where you lay things up, a barn. The farmer gathers his wheat into the apotheke. The rich fool built bigger ones and died that very night. A grain store, packed full and shut.","g":"barn","h":"The picture: a barn packed with grain."},"G597":{"b":"This joins 'away' to a word meaning to amass or reserve, the root behind our word treasure. It pictures piling something up and storing it off for later. Paul tells the rich to store up a good foundation for the time to come.","g":"lay up in store","h":"The picture: laying treasure in a store."},"G598":{"b":"This word means to press hard. Strong's says to crowd from every side. The people were packed so tight around Jesus they were crushing against him, yet he asked who touched him. One touch was different from all that pressing.","g":"press","h":"The picture: a crowd squeezing in from every side."},"G599":{"b":"Strong's reads the front of this word as off, and translates it to die off. Abbott-Smith notes the same finishing force in the verb.\n\nThe prefix carries the action through to the end. Not fading. Done.","g":"die","h":"The picture: dying clean off."},"G6":{"b":"The name comes from a word meaning emptiness or vanity, a breath that quickly passes. Abel was the son of Adam, the shepherd whose offering God accepted and whose brother Cain killed him.","g":"Abel","h":"The picture: emptiness or vanity."},"G60":{"b":"The root is the word for the town-square, the place of public resort, the market. An agoraios is one who hangs about it, a loafer of the marketplace. At Thessalonica the crowd gathered such market idlers to make a mob and drag believers out.","g":"low, baser sort","h":"The picture: the idle men who hang around the market square."},"G600":{"b":"Abbott: \"to restore, i.e. to a former condition.\" A withered hand is put back to how it should be. The word means to set a thing back into its old, right state, whole again.","g":"restore","h":"The picture: setting a thing back the way it was."},"G601":{"b":"Strong's says it is to take off the cover. The thing was already there. The cloth comes away.\n\nThis is the word behind Revelation. Not new information arriving. Something long present being shown.","g":"reveal","h":"The picture: pulling the cover off."},"G602":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives the literal sense. An uncovering, a laying bare.\n\nSo a revelation is not new information arriving. It is a cover coming off something already there. The last book of the Bible is named with this word.","g":"revelation","h":"The picture: pulling the cover off."},"G603":{"b":"This word paints a person craning the neck, head thrust forward, watching the road for someone to appear. It joins the head and to watch. Paul says all creation waits like this, on tiptoe, longing for God's children to be revealed.","g":"earnest expectation","h":"The picture: craning the neck to watch the road."},"G604":{"b":"The root katallasso means to change from enemy to friend, to settle a quarrel. The added apo makes it complete, all the way. Paul says God reconciled all things to himself through the cross, the whole feud fully ended.","g":"reconcile fully","h":"The picture: enemies made friends again."},"G605":{"b":"This word means restoration, setting something back to its right state. Abbott notes it was used for repairing and restoring temples. Peter speaks of the time when God will restore all things. Not scrapped and replaced. Put back, made right again.","g":"restitution","h":"The picture: putting a thing back the way it was."},"G606":{"b":"The word is \"away\" plus \"to lie.\" Abbott: \"to be laid up, in store, laid away.\" Picture something set on a shelf and kept, out of reach until it is needed. So the reward laid up in heaven is not spent. It waits.","g":"be laid up, reserved","h":"The picture: a thing set on a shelf and kept."},"G607":{"b":"This word puts together \"off\" and \"head.\" It means exactly what it looks like, to take the head away from the body. It is the flat, plain word for what was done to John the Baptist in the prison.","g":"behead","h":"The picture: the head struck off."},"G608":{"b":"This word joins off and to close. Abbott-Smith gives it as to shut fast. Once the master of the house gets up and shuts the door, Jesus says, those left outside knock and call, but he answers that he does not know them.","g":"shut up","h":"The picture: the door shut and barred."},"G609":{"b":"The root means to chop, and the front means off. To cut clean off, to amputate. Peter swings and takes off the servant's ear. Jesus says if your hand trips you, cut it off. Sailors cut the ropes and let the boat drop.","g":"cut off","h":"The picture: chopping clean off."},"G61":{"b":"The root means to drive or bring. This word is the catch itself, the haul. Jesus tells Peter to push out and let the nets down for a catch, and they bring in so many fish the nets begin to tear.","g":"catch, haul","h":"The picture: a netful of fish hauled in."},"G610":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says a judicial sentence, the verdict read out in court. Paul says he felt the sentence of death inside himself, already condemned, so that he would lean on God who raises the dead.","g":"sentence","h":"The picture: a judge handing down the sentence."},"G611":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense for this verb is to separate, to distinguish. The second is to choose.\n\nOnly then does it mean to answer. An answer is a thing you have sorted out and picked, not a noise you make back.","g":"answer, reply","h":"The picture: sorting things apart."},"G612":{"b":"Built from the word for answering. Picture the boy Jesus in the temple, and the teachers amazed at His apokrisis, the answers coming back from a twelve year old, Luke 2:47. This is the word for the reply given.","g":"answer","h":"The picture: the reply given back."},"G613":{"b":"The root means to conceal by covering, to put something out of sight. To apokrypto is to hide it fully away. You have hidden these things from the wise and clever, Jesus prays, and shown them to little children instead.","g":"hide","h":"The picture: covering a thing over to hide it."},"G614":{"b":"The root is to conceal, to hide away. This word is hidden, kept out of sight, and so also treasured. Jesus says nothing is hidden that will not be brought to light. Whatever is stored in the dark will one day be uncovered.","g":"hidden","h":"The picture: something tucked out of sight."},"G615":{"b":"This puts the word off onto the verb to slay. Strong's calls it to kill outright, the force of the word meaning finished, dead. So when the prophets are killed, the word carries no vagueness. The deed is done, the life put clean away.","g":"kill","h":"The picture: struck down, killed outright."},"G616":{"b":"Abbott says the root means to be pregnant, and the added off points to the safe delivery at the end. So the picture is a mother bringing her child into the world. James uses it of how desire gives birth to sin.","g":"give birth","h":"The picture: a mother giving birth."},"G617":{"b":"The word is \"roll\" with \"away\" in front. It names one act, rolling the great round stone back from the mouth of the tomb. Who will do it for us, the women ask on the way. They find it already rolled away.","g":"roll away","h":"The picture: the heavy stone rolled back from the door."},"G618":{"b":"One sense Abbott-Smith lists is to take apart or aside. In Mark 7:33 Jesus takes the deaf man away from the crowd before healing him. The word also means to get back what is owed you.","g":"receive, take aside","h":"The picture: taking someone off to the side."},"G619":{"b":"The root means to take of a thing and enjoy it, like tasting good food set before you. Paul says God gives us richly all things to enjoy. Gifts meant to be taken and savored, not just stored away. Though wealth is a poor thing to trust.","g":"enjoyment","h":"The picture: tasting the good thing set before you."},"G62":{"b":"This word joins not with the word for letters or writing. It means someone with no schooling, unable to read and write. The rulers saw that Peter and John were such men, unlettered, and marveled at their boldness.","g":"unlearned","h":"The picture: a man who never learned his letters."},"G620":{"b":"Apo means away, and leipo means to leave. Apoleipo pictures something left behind when you go, set down and not taken up. Paul: the cloak I left at Troas, bring it. It also means to be left remaining, a rest still waiting.","g":"leave behind","h":"The picture: the cloak left behind."},"G621":{"b":"Strong's says it means to lick clean. Picture a tongue passing over a wound again and again. The beggar Lazarus lay at the rich man's gate, and even the dogs came and licked his sores.","g":"lick","h":"The picture: dogs licking the sores."},"G622":{"b":"Abbott says the word covers destroying and losing. Then he explains the New Testament use of being lost. It rests on the relation between shepherd and flock.\n\nLost does not mean gone. It means missing from the fold.","g":"destroy, lose","h":"The picture: the sheep that wandered off."},"G623":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to destroy fully, and Abbott names him the Destroyer. So the picture stands in the name itself. The angel of the abyss is called Abaddon in Hebrew and Apollyon in Greek, the Destroyer.","g":"Apollyon","h":"The picture: the Destroyer."},"G624":{"b":"Strong's traces this name to Apollo, tied to the sun. So Apollonia is the town that carries the sun-god's name. Paul walked through it on his way to Thessalonica and did not stay.","g":"Apollonia","h":"The picture: the sun-god's town."},"G625":{"b":"This is a personal name. Strong's traces it only to Apollonia, a place, and Abbott to the longer name Apollonios. Neither source gives a concrete meaning to draw, so the name carries no picture of its own.","flat":1,"g":"Apollos","h":"No picture."},"G626":{"b":"Abbott-Smith builds it from from and word. It pictures making a reasoned speech to defend yourself. This is where the English word apology comes from. Not saying sorry, but making your case in court.","g":"defend oneself","h":"The picture: talking your way clear."},"G627":{"b":"Abbott calls this a speech in defence, the words a man says to clear himself before judges. Our word apology comes from it. Peter tells believers to be ready to make this defence for their hope. Stand up and speak your case.","g":"defence","h":"The picture: the speech you make in court."},"G628":{"b":"The root means to bathe, and not to splash one part. Strong's marks it as the whole person, a complete wash. So when Paul says his sins were washed away, the word underneath is a full bath. Nothing left dirty.","g":"wash away","h":"The picture: a full bath."},"G629":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it is release effected by payment of ransom. It pictures paying a price to set a slave or prisoner loose. The price is handed over, and the person walks out free.","g":"redemption","h":"The picture: buying a captive free."},"G63":{"b":"This word is built from the word for a field and the word for an open yard. It means to camp out under the sky. The shepherds were doing this by night, out in the fields with their flock, when the angel's light broke over them.","g":"camp out","h":"The picture: sleeping out in the open fields."},"G630":{"b":"Abbott gives the first sense as to set free, release. His examples include a debtor let off in Matthew 18:27.\n\nThe same word covers dismissing a crowd, and divorcing a wife. Letting go, in every direction.","g":"release, send away","h":"The picture: letting the prisoner go."},"G631":{"b":"This word means to wipe off, wipe clean. Jesus tells the seventy that if a town will not receive them, they should wipe even its dust off their feet against it. Leave nothing of the place clinging to you.","g":"wipe off","h":"The picture: wiping the dust off your feet."},"G632":{"b":"Abbott traces this to a word meaning to distribute. It was used of an official who renders to all their dues. Peter tells husbands to assign honor to their wives, handing over what is owed them.","g":"give, apportion","h":"The picture: dealing out each person's share."},"G633":{"b":"The pieces mean off and to wash. It is scrubbing something off, and here Pilate washes it off his own hands. In Matthew 27:24 he takes water and washes his hands before the crowd, saying he is innocent of this man's blood.","g":"wash off","h":"The picture: rinsing your hands clean."},"G634":{"b":"The word joins 'off' with 'to fall.' At Damascus, when Ananias lays hands on Saul, something like scales falls off his eyes and his sight comes rushing back.","g":"fall off","h":"The picture: something dropping off."},"G635":{"b":"The root means to wander, to roam away from the road. Add \"away\" and someone is drawn right off it. Mark warns of false prophets who would lead even the chosen astray, and Paul says the love of money pulls people off, wandering into ruin.","g":"lead astray","h":"The picture: led off the path and lost."},"G636":{"b":"The word is \"away\" plus \"to pass in a vessel.\" To set sail and leave the shore behind. From Antioch they sailed away on the missionary journeys, the harbor shrinking astern as the ship stood out to sea.","g":"sail away","h":"The picture: a ship pulling away from the shore."},"G638":{"b":"The root means to throttle or strangle, even to drown. Luke uses it twice: the thorns that grow up and choke the young wheat until it dies, and the herd of pigs that rush into the lake and drown.","g":"choke","h":"The picture: the life choked out of it."},"G639":{"b":"This is no joined to a word for a way or road. To have no way out, no path forward. Paul stands perplexed but not crushed. The women find no way to explain the empty tomb. Stuck, with every road blocked.","g":"be at a loss","h":"The picture: no road out."},"G64":{"b":"This was a hunting and fishing word. The root means a haul of fish, the catch dragged in. Abbott says it is used when the leaders try to catch Jesus in his words. They cast for him like men netting fish.","g":"catch, entrap","h":"The picture: hauling in a catch of fish."},"G640":{"b":"The root means to have no way out, built from a word for a passage. No road forward, hemmed in on all sides. On the earth there will be distress of nations in perplexity, Jesus said, and no way through.","g":"perplexity","h":"The picture: a road with no way through."},"G641":{"b":"The root means to fling, with a quick toss. Add the word for off and away. So this is throwing your own body clear with a jerk. In Acts the swimmers cast themselves overboard to reach the land.","g":"cast, hurl","h":"The picture: flinging yourself off the edge."},"G642":{"b":"The root is orphanos, an orphan, a child bereaved of parents. With apo, away, it means to be torn from someone that way. Paul says being pulled from them, even for a short time, left him feeling orphaned.","g":"torn away","h":"The picture: a child left an orphan."},"G643":{"b":"This means to pack up one's baggage, to gather your gear and carry it off. After these days Paul and his friends packed their bags and went up to Jerusalem.","g":"pack up","h":"The picture: bundling up the baggage."},"G644":{"b":"The root is the plain word for shade, a shadow. This is the shadow a thing throws as it turns. With God there is none. The sun moves and casts shadows across the ground. He never does.","g":"shadow","h":"The picture: the shadow a thing throws as it turns."},"G645":{"b":"The root is to draw, and apo makes it draw away. One of them apospao his sword and struck. It also means to tear people apart, to pull a man from his friends. Jesus apospao himself from the disciples to pray, a stone's throw off.","g":"draw away","h":"The picture: a sword drawn from the sheath."},"G646":{"b":"The word Strong's links it to means divorce, something that cuts a bond. Abbott says it comes from a word meaning to stand off. Apostasy is not a small doubt. It is standing up and walking away from what you were joined to.","g":"falling away","h":"The picture: walking out of a marriage."},"G647":{"b":"The root means to stand away, to depart. This word is the writing of divorce, the certificate that puts a wife away. Moses allowed a man to hand her a bill of divorce, Jesus says, but from the beginning it was not so.","g":"divorce","h":"The picture: the paper that sends her away."},"G648":{"b":"The pieces mean off and a roof. It means to take the roof away. In Mark 2:4 four men cannot reach Jesus through the crowd, so they climb up, tear open the roof over his head, and lower their friend down.","g":"unroof, uncover","h":"The picture: pulling the roof off."},"G649":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it properly means to send away, to dispatch on service. Strong's adds, properly on a mission.\n\nThe synonym note says this word suggests official sending. Not just going. Being handed a job and sent to do it.","g":"send out","h":"The picture: a man sent off with orders."},"G65":{"b":"This joins wild and olive, the wild olive tree. Paul pictures Gentiles as a branch cut from a wild olive and grafted into the cultivated tree of God's people. Growing where you were not planted, made to bear from another's root.","g":"wild olive tree","h":"The picture: a wild olive branch grafted in."},"G650":{"b":"Abbott traces this to a word meaning to rob. To strip a man of what is his, to hold back what he is owed. Jesus lists it: do not defraud. It is money kept back by fraud, wages a worker earned and never sees.","g":"defraud","h":"The picture: wages held back."},"G651":{"b":"This comes from a verb meaning \"to send out (properly, on a mission).\" Abbott's older sense is a sending away, even an expedition. So apostleship is not a title to sit in. It is being sent, given a commission and pointed out the door.","g":"apostleship","h":"The picture: a man sent out on a mission."},"G652":{"b":"Abbott's first entry is startling. In one old Greek writer the word means a fleet, an expedition.\n\nThen a messenger sent on a mission. Then the Twelve. Something launched and sent out.","g":"apostle, sent one","h":"The picture: a fleet putting out to sea."},"G653":{"b":"This word is built on the word for the mouth. In late Greek it meant to fire questions at someone to draw words out. The scribes pressed Jesus hard, lying in wait to catch something from his mouth to use against him.","g":"provoke to speak","h":"The picture: pumping words out of someone's mouth."},"G654":{"b":"Built from away and turn. Strong's gives to turn away or back. It pictures turning your face from someone. Jesus tells Peter to turn his sword back into its place. It can also mean leading others astray.","g":"turn away","h":"The picture: turning your back on it."},"G655":{"b":"This joins away and a word meaning to hate. Abbott gives to abhor. So it is recoiling from a thing in disgust. Let love be genuine, Paul says, abhorring what is evil and clinging to what is good.","g":"abhor","h":"The picture: recoiling from evil in disgust."},"G656":{"b":"This word is built from a word for away and the word for the synagogue, the assembly of people. It means shut out of the gathering, barred from the room. That fear kept many quiet who believed in Jesus.","g":"expelled","h":"The picture: shut out of the meeting room."},"G657":{"b":"Strong's reads it as to say adieu, by departing or dismissing. The parts mean off and to arrange. Paul says farewell and sails away. Jesus says whoever will not renounce all he owns cannot follow. To turn, wave goodbye, and let go.","g":"bid farewell, renounce","h":"The picture: turning to wave goodbye."},"G658":{"b":"This joins \"off\" to the word for finishing a task or paying off a debt. Abbott says \"to bring to an end, complete, accomplish.\" James says sin, once it is fully finished, gives birth to death. Nothing left half-done.","g":"finish, complete","h":"The picture: carrying a work through to done."},"G659":{"b":"Abbott: \"to put off from oneself as a garment.\" It joins \"off\" with \"put.\" You strip off clothing and lay it aside. Paul uses it for stripping off the old way of living like a dirty coat.","g":"put off","h":"The picture: taking off a coat and setting it down."},"G66":{"b":"The root is the word for a field, the open country. This word means what belongs to the wild fields, untamed, growing on its own. John ate wild honey, gathered from the open country, kept by no one's hand.","g":"wild","h":"The picture: growing wild in the open field."},"G660":{"b":"Strong's says this means \"to brush off.\" It is built on a word for jostling something loose. Paul shakes the snake off his hand into the fire, and the disciples shake the dust off their feet. A clean, deliberate flick.","g":"shake off","h":"The picture: shaking dust off your feet."},"G661":{"b":"The root means to pay a price, and often to pay it as a penalty. This word is to pay off in full, down to the last coin. Paul tells Philemon that whatever Onesimus owes, he himself will repay it.","g":"repay","h":"The picture: paying the debt in full."},"G662":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to dare, to venture, pushed to its limit. Abbott gives to make a bold venture. So it is taking a bold plunge. Isaiah grows very bold, Paul says, and cries that God was found by those who never sought him.","g":"be very bold","h":"The picture: taking a bold plunge."},"G663":{"b":"Abbott says this word comes from a verb meaning to cut off. Picture a rock face sheared straight down, steep and sharp. So the severity of God in Romans is not a mood. It is a hard edge that will not bend.","g":"severity","h":"The picture: the clean cut of a blade."},"G664":{"b":"This is the adverb from the same family as severity, built from off and to cut. It means abruptly, curtly, with a sharp cutting edge. Paul would rather write now than come and have to use such sharpness in person.","g":"sharply","h":"The picture: the sharp, clean cut."},"G665":{"b":"This joins 'away' to a word for a turn. It means to turn yourself away from something. Paul says of people with a false show of godliness, turn away from these. Pivot your body and go the other direction.","g":"turn away","h":"The picture: turning away and leaving."},"G666":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to be away. Abbott gives absence. So the picture is the empty place when someone is gone. Paul says obey, not only when I am present, but now much more in my absence.","g":"absence","h":"The picture: the empty place when someone is gone."},"G667":{"b":"The root means to bear or carry, and the front means away. To haul a thing off to somewhere else. They carry Jesus off to Pilate. Angels carry the beggar away to Abraham's side. To pick up and remove.","g":"carry away","h":"The picture: hauling something off."},"G668":{"b":"The word joins away and to run. It means to run off and get clear, to escape. Peter says some have escaped the filth of the world by knowing Christ. They ran out of it. He warns that a man can also get pulled back in.","g":"to escape","h":"The picture: running clear away."},"G669":{"b":"This word is built from a word for out and a word meaning to utter a clear sound. To speak out plainly, to ring the voice out. Peter stood and spoke out to the crowd on the day the Spirit came.","g":"speak out","h":"The picture: a clear voice rung out."},"G67":{"b":"Strong's traces this name to two words, one meaning wild and one meaning a horse. So Agrippa's very name pictures a man breaking a wild horse. He heard Paul's defense and said he was almost persuaded to be a Christian.","g":"Agrippa","h":"The picture: the wild-horse tamer."},"G670":{"b":"This joins off with a word meaning to load up a vessel or animal. So it means to take the load off, to unload. At Tyre the ship was to unlade her cargo, and Paul found disciples there.","g":"unload","h":"The picture: lifting cargo off the ship."},"G671":{"b":"This names the act of using up, using a thing to the full until nothing is left. Paul quotes the rule-makers who fret over things that perish in the using, food and drink that are gone the moment you consume them.","g":"using up","h":"The picture: used up until it is gone."},"G672":{"b":"The roots mean off, away, and to move or make room. This word is to withdraw, to take yourself off. Depart from me, Jesus says to the workers of lawlessness. Go away, put space between us. It is turning and leaving.","g":"to depart","h":"The picture: stepping back and away."},"G673":{"b":"Built from \"away\" and a word meaning to place room between, to part. It is opening a gap so two things are no longer one. After their sharp quarrel Paul and Barnabas parted this way. In Revelation the sky splits apart like a scroll.","g":"separate","h":"The picture: two things pulled apart with space opened between."},"G674":{"b":"Built from a word for off and a word for breath. Abbott says it means to breathe out life, to leave off breathing, to faint. Men will faint for fear, Jesus said, at what is coming on the world. Terror takes the breath away.","g":"faint","h":"The picture: the breath leaving the body."},"G675":{"b":"This is the Roman name Appius. It appears in Appii Forum, the Market of Appius, a town on the road to Rome. It is only a name, of Latin origin, with nothing behind it to picture. Believers came out to meet Paul there.","flat":1,"g":"Appius","h":"No picture."},"G676":{"b":"The root means to go toward, and the a undoes it. So it is what you cannot approach, no way to draw near. Paul says God dwells in light no man can approach, whom no eye has seen or can see.","g":"unapproachable","h":"The picture: a light no one can walk up to."},"G677":{"b":"This word is built from a word for not and a word meaning to stub your foot and trip. Aproskopos is a clear path where no toe catches. Paul kept a conscience that trips no one, toward God and toward men.","g":"without offence","h":"The picture: a foot that never stubs or trips."},"G678":{"b":"Buried in this word is the Greek for the face. To judge \"by faces\" is to be swayed by how a man looks. This word is the \"not\" of that. Peter says God judges each one without a glance at the face.","g":"without respect of persons","h":"The picture: not swayed by a man's face."},"G679":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this means \"without stumbling, sure-footed.\" It is built from a word for tripping, with \"not\" set in front. Picture a walker on rough ground whose foot never catches. So God is the one able to keep you from falling.","g":"without sin","h":"The picture: the foot that does not trip."},"G68":{"b":"Strong's defines it as a field, a drive for cattle, and stretches it to the country and to a farm.\n\nAbbott keeps the same range. A field, the country, a piece of ground. Plain outdoor land.","g":"field, country","h":"The picture: open ground where cattle are driven."},"G680":{"b":"Strong's says the word means to attach oneself to, that is, to touch. Touching here is a kind of holding on. The sick woman fastened her hand to Jesus' cloak. Abbott has no entry for this word.","g":"touch","h":"The picture: fastening yourself to something."},"G681":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the proper sense is to fasten to, and from there, of fire, to kindle.\n\nSo touching here is not a brush of the fingers. It is taking hold, the way flame grabs a lamp wick.","g":"touch, kindle","h":"The picture: fire catching hold."},"G682":{"b":"Apphia is a woman greeted in the letter to Philemon, likely of his household. Strong's says her name is probably of foreign origin. There is nothing behind it to picture. It simply names her.","flat":1,"g":"Apphia","h":"No picture."},"G683":{"b":"This joins away to a word meaning to shove. To push a thing off with both hands, to thrust it from you and refuse it. Israel shoved Moses aside, saying who made you ruler. Paul asks, has God pushed away his people. A hard rejecting shove.","g":"reject, thrust away","h":"The picture: shoving something away with both hands."},"G684":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first words for it are destruction, waste, loss.\n\nIt is what the disciples said about the costly ointment. Why this waste. The same word carries the heaviest sense in the New Testament, the loss of eternal life.","g":"destruction, waste","h":"The picture: something thrown away."},"G688":{"b":"The name comes from a word meaning to grow dusky at sundown. Arabia was the desert region south and east of Israel, a land of wandering peoples and shifting sands.","g":"Arabia","h":"The picture: land of the dusky evening."},"G689":{"b":"The name means high. It comes from a word meaning to be high or lifted up. Aram appears among the ancestors of Jesus, one of the names in the family line from Abraham to David.","g":"Aram","h":"The picture: high."},"G69":{"b":"The word is \"sleep\" with a \"not\" fixed to it. It means to be sleepless, to keep awake when others are down. It is the watchman's word. Watch and pray, Jesus says. Keep awake at all times, staying alert through the dark.","g":"keep awake","h":"The picture: lying awake through the night."},"G690":{"b":"This word marks a person by his homeland, Arabia. Abbott gives an Arabian. So the picture is a man named by his country. At Pentecost even Arabians heard the mighty works of God spoken in their own tongue.","g":"an Arabian","h":"The picture: a man named by his country."},"G691":{"b":"The root means inactive, not working. So this word is to be idle, to loiter. Peter says the judgment on false teachers is not idle. It has not fallen asleep. It is coming.","g":"linger, be idle","h":"The picture: standing idle, doing nothing."},"G692":{"b":"Abbott builds it from \"ἀ- neg., ἔργον\", \"not\" and \"work.\" Strong's: \"inactive, i.e. unemployed.\" The picture is a person standing around with no work in their hands. Then it describes anything useless, like faith with no deeds.","g":"idle, lazy","h":"The picture: no work in the hands."},"G693":{"b":"This word comes from the word for silver, the metal. Argyreos means made of silver. Demetrius made silver shrines of the goddess and feared his trade would collapse. In a great house are vessels of gold and silver.","g":"of silver","h":"The picture: made of silver."},"G694":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it is properly a piece of silver. From that come three uses. The metal, money in general, and a silver coin.\n\nThe thirty pieces are this word. Money named after what it was made of.","g":"silver, money","h":"The picture: a piece of silver."},"G695":{"b":"Two words, silver and to chop or beat. A silversmith is a silver-beater, pounding the metal into shape. Demetrius beat out little silver shrines of Artemis and feared Paul would ruin his trade.","g":"silversmith","h":"The picture: hammering silver."},"G696":{"b":"The root means shining, and argyros is the bright metal, silver. Take no argyros in your belts, Jesus told them. James warns the rich that their silver has rusted. The gleaming coin that men trust and hoard.","g":"silver","h":"The picture: shining silver."},"G697":{"b":"The name means \"rock of Ares, a place in Athens,\" the hill of the war-god, also called Mars' Hill. A bare outcrop of stone where the high court met. Paul stood on it and preached the unknown God to the philosophers.","g":"Areopagus","h":"The picture: a bare rock hill named for the war-god."},"G698":{"b":"This word rests on the rock of Ares, Mars' Hill in Athens. An Areopagite was a judge of the court that met on that stony hill. Dionysius, one of these judges, believed.","g":"Areopagite","h":"The picture: the court on the rock."},"G699":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to be agreeable, to seek to please. Abbott gives pleasing, desire to please. So the picture is setting out to win favor. Paul prays that we walk worthy of the Lord unto all pleasing, aiming to please him in all.","g":"pleasing","h":"The picture: setting out to please."},"G7":{"b":"The name means father, or worshipper, of Jah. It joins a word for father with Jah, a short form of the Lord's name. Abia stands in the family line of Jesus, a king descended from Solomon.","g":"Abijah","h":"The picture: father of Jah."},"G70":{"b":"The word means sleeplessness, a keeping awake through the night. Paul lists it among his hardships, in watchings often, nights spent on guard or at labour with no rest for the body.","g":"sleeplessness","h":"The picture: the sleepless night."},"G700":{"b":"Strong's traces this to a word meaning to lift up. To please someone is to raise their spirits, to lift the face. Paul says he no longer tries to please men but God, choosing carefully whose face he most wants to lift.","g":"to please","h":"The picture: lifting someone's face."},"G701":{"b":"Built from the word for to please. Abbott gives pleasing, agreeable. Jesus says of the Father, I always do the things arestos to Him, the things that please, John 8:29. A whole life aimed at another's pleasure, not its own.","g":"pleasing","h":"The picture: aimed at another's pleasure."},"G702":{"b":"This is a man's name, Aretas, an Arabian king. Strong's says it is of foreign origin, carried into Greek from outside. He ruled the land around Damascus in Paul's story. A foreign king's name holds nothing to picture behind it.","flat":1,"g":"Aretas","h":"No picture."},"G703":{"b":"Strong's traces this to a word for the male, the one strong for lifting. Arete first meant manliness, valor, the strength that stands out. Later it became virtue, moral excellence. Behind the noble word is raw strength on display.","g":"virtue, excellence","h":"The picture: the strength that shows in valor."},"G704":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives one word: a lamb. Jesus sends the seventy out like lambs into the middle of wolves. A lamb has no fang and no claw. Its only safety is the shepherd who sent it out.","g":"lamb","h":"The picture: a lamb."},"G705":{"b":"The root is a number. This verb is counting, ticking off a total one at a time. Jesus says even the hairs on your head are numbered. God has counted them. Not a rough guess, an exact tally.","g":"count","h":"The picture: counting them one by one."},"G706":{"b":"Strong's calls it a number as reckoned up, the total you reach by counting. An arithmos is the tally itself. So the arithmos of the beast is 666, a figure to be counted out, and the arithmos of the sealed is a hundred forty-four thousand. Numbers meant to be reckoned.","g":"number","h":"The picture: the tally, things reckoned up."},"G707":{"b":"The name comes from a word meaning a height, a high place. Arimathaea was a town in Palestine, the home of Joseph, the rich man who gave his own tomb for the body of Jesus.","g":"Arimathaea","h":"The picture: a height."},"G708":{"b":"This name is built from a word meaning best and a word meaning to rule. It reads best-ruling. Aristarchus traveled with Paul and was dragged into the theater at Ephesus with him. His name claims the finest rule.","g":"Aristarchus","h":"The picture: the best ruler."},"G709":{"b":"The word grows from the best meal of the day. It means to sit and eat, to dine. On the shore the risen Jesus says come and have breakfast. A Pharisee asks him to dine, and is shocked he does not wash first.","g":"dine","h":"The picture: sitting down to the main meal."},"G71":{"b":"Strong's calls it a primary verb. Nothing lies behind it. Abbott notes one odd extra use. It can mean to spend or keep a day, the way we say to keep a holiday.","flat":1,"g":"lead, bring","h":"No picture."},"G710":{"b":"The word means the left, the left hand, counted as the second-best side. Jesus says when you give, do not let your left hand know what your right hand is doing. Keep the giving so quiet even your other hand misses it.","g":"left hand","h":"The picture: the left hand."},"G711":{"b":"Abbott reads this name as best-counselling, from the words for best and counsel. So the man's name holds wisdom in it. Paul sends greetings to the household of Aristobulus in the last lines to Rome.","g":"a Christian","h":"The picture: a name that means best counsel."},"G712":{"b":"This is a meal, first a morning meal and later the main dinner. In the parable the king says my dinner is ready, my oxen and fatlings are killed, come to the wedding. The word is the food set out and waiting.","g":"dinner","h":"The picture: a meal spread on the table."},"G713":{"b":"Built from a word meaning to suffice, even to ward off. Abbott gives sufficient. Jesus says do not worry about tomorrow, arketos to the day is its own trouble, Matthew 6:34. Each day already carries just enough of its own.","g":"enough, sufficient","h":"The picture: enough, no more needed."},"G714":{"b":"Strong's: \"to ward off.\" Abbott: \"to keep off.\" The old idea is fending something away, like holding off an enemy at the door. From holding trouble back it comes to mean having enough. Be content with what you have.","g":"be enough","h":"The picture: holding trouble off."},"G715":{"b":"The word means a bear. Abbott-Smith gives simply \"a bear.\" Picture the heavy animal with crushing paws. So the beast's feet were like a bear's feet, made to pin down and maul.","g":"a bear","h":"The picture: a bear."},"G716":{"b":"A chariot, and Abbott traces the word to a verb meaning \"to join,\" since a chariot is a thing fitted and bolted together. The Ethiopian sits reading in one of these as it rolls along, and Philip runs up beside the wheels.","g":"chariot","h":"The picture: a war-cart fitted and bolted together."},"G717":{"b":"The name comes from a word for a mountain, joined to the place-name Megiddo. Armageddon means the mountain of Megiddo, named in Revelation as the gathering place for the last great battle.","g":"Armageddon","h":"The picture: the mountain of Megiddo."},"G718":{"b":"The root is a joint where parts meet, like a carpenter's fit. From joining comes betrothing. Paul says he joined the church to one husband, Christ, to present her as a pure bride.","g":"espouse, betroth","h":"The picture: two pieces fitted together at the joint."},"G719":{"b":"This is a joint, the place where two parts fit together. It shares its base with the word for a chariot, a thing fitted from many pieces. God's word cuts even to the joints, where bone meets bone.","g":"joint","h":"The picture: where two bones fit together."},"G72":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to lead, to bring along. A manner of life is the path a person is led down day by day. Paul says Timothy has fully known his way of life. Not just belief. The road he walked.","g":"manner of life","h":"The picture: the road you are led down."},"G720":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is to deny, say no.\n\nThe stronger sense is to refuse to acknowledge, to disown. Abbott lists it for denying Jesus and for denying yourself. Not only no. Cutting the tie.","g":"deny, disown","h":"The picture: saying no."},"G721":{"b":"Strong's calls it a lambkin. Abbott says it is the small form of the ordinary word for lamb, a little lamb.\n\nThe name for Christ in Revelation uses this small word, not the large one.","g":"lamb","h":"The picture: a little lamb."},"G722":{"b":"The word comes straight from the plow. It means to break the ground with one. Jesus asks which of you tells a servant just in from ploughing to sit and eat. Paul says the ploughman ought to plough in hope of a share.","g":"plow","h":"The picture: driving a plow through the field."},"G723":{"b":"This word comes from the word to plough. Abbott-Smith gives it as a plough. Jesus says no one who puts his hand to the plough and looks back is fit for the kingdom. A plough cuts straight only when the eyes stay ahead.","g":"plough","h":"The picture: a hand on the plough."},"G724":{"b":"The root means to seize or snatch. This is the plunder itself, what greedy hands grab. Jesus says the Pharisees clean the outside of the cup, but inside it is full of extortion. The gleaming cup holds the loot of what they seized.","g":"plunder","h":"The picture: hands full of stolen goods."},"G725":{"b":"The root means to seize or snatch. Harpagmos is plunder, a thing grabbed and clutched. Paul says Christ did not treat equality with God as something to snatch and cling to, but let it go and became a servant.","g":"thing seized","h":"The picture: something snatched and clutched."},"G726":{"b":"Abbott says the word means to seize, snatch away, carry off by force. It is the grab of a robber or a wolf. Paul uses it for being caught up to heaven, snatched off the ground.","g":"seize, snatch","h":"The picture: snatching and carrying off."},"G727":{"b":"The root means to seize, to snatch away by force. A harpax is a grabber, a robber, a wolf in the fold. Beware false prophets, Jesus says, inwardly harpages, ravening wolves that tear and take.","g":"extortioner","h":"The picture: a wolf snatching prey."},"G728":{"b":"Strong's says this is part of the purchase-money given in advance as security for the rest, a first installment. In modern Greek it is the engagement ring. Paul calls the Spirit God's down payment on us, the promise that the whole is coming.","g":"pledge, earnest","h":"The picture: the down payment."},"G729":{"b":"This word means not sewn, built on the word for a needle. Jesus' tunic was woven in one piece from top to bottom, no seam, no stitching. The soldiers would not tear it. They cast lots for it whole.","g":"without seam","h":"The picture: a robe with no seam anywhere."},"G73":{"b":"First it was the place where games were held, then the contest itself, the wrestling and the race. This is the word behind our \"agony.\" So \"fight the good agon of faith\" pictures an athlete straining in the arena, not resting.","g":"contest, fight","h":"The picture: athletes straining in the arena."},"G730":{"b":"Strong's connects this to lifting, calling the male the stronger for lifting. Handle that lightly, for Abbott-Smith gives no such origin and only says male. So the safe meaning is simply male, man.","g":"male","h":"The picture: the one who lifts."},"G731":{"b":"The root means spoken out plainly, and the not seals the lips. Strong's gives unsaid, inexpressible. Paul says he was caught up and heard things no man is permitted to speak, sealed behind his teeth.","g":"unspeakable","h":"The picture: words the mouth is forbidden to say."},"G732":{"b":"The root means to strengthen, to have health. Put \"not\" in front and you have the arrostos, the person with no strength left, the sick. Jesus laid hands on a few arrostoi and healed them. Bodies drained of their power.","g":"sick","h":"The picture: a body with no strength left."},"G733":{"b":"The word joins two plain words, male and couch or bed. Paul coins it for a man who beds a man. He lists it among the sins that shut people out of the kingdom of God.","g":"sodomite","h":"The picture: two plain words, male and bed."},"G734":{"b":"His name joins Artemis, a Greek goddess, to the word for a gift. It means gift of Artemis. Paul may send him to Titus in Crete. A Christian worker whose old pagan name still carried a goddess in it.","g":"Artemas","h":"The picture: a gift of the goddess Artemis."},"G735":{"b":"Artemis, the great goddess of the Ephesians. Picture Demetrius the silversmith and his craftsmen, whose trade in silver shrines was drying up as the gospel spread, Acts 19:24. Their riot for Artemis was really about the money.","g":"Artemis","h":"The picture: the goddess whose shrines paid the bills."},"G736":{"b":"Strong's calls this something hung up, and Abbott ties it to a word meaning to fasten to. It names a sail, the foresail hoisted at the bow. Making for shore, they raised it to the wind to drive the ship in. The word is the sail hung and spread.","g":"mainsail","h":"The picture: a sail hung up to catch the wind."},"G737":{"b":"Arti means just now, this very moment, the knife-edge of the present. Abbott sets it against past and future both. So now we see through a glass darkly, arti, but then face to face. The word pins you to the present with the future still ahead.","g":"now, just now","h":"The picture: this exact moment, right now."},"G738":{"b":"Built from \"just now\" and \"born,\" this is a baby only moments old. Peter says be like that with the word: a newborn crying for milk, hungry for the pure milk that makes you grow.","g":"new born","h":"The picture: a baby only moments old."},"G739":{"b":"This word means fitted, complete. Paul says Scripture makes the man of God complete, fully equipped for every good work. The picture is a tool or a body with every part in place, nothing missing, ready for the job.","g":"complete","h":"The picture: fitted with every part."},"G74":{"b":"The root is a word for a contest held in the arena, a wrestling match. Picture an athlete straining every muscle to the limit. In agony Jesus prayed in the garden, and his sweat became like drops of blood. The struggle was real.","g":"agony","h":"The picture: the wrestler straining in the arena."},"G740":{"b":"Strong's calls it bread as raised, and links it to a word for lifting up. Abbott gives no origin at all, so this rests on Strong's alone.\n\nThe plain meaning is safe. A loaf.","g":"bread, loaf","h":"The picture: a loaf that has risen."},"G741":{"b":"This is a kitchen word. Abbott-Smith says that with food it means to season. Think of salt or spice rubbed into a dish to give it flavor. So when Paul says let your speech be seasoned, he means make your words taste of something.","g":"season, spice","h":"The picture: spice worked into food."},"G742":{"b":"Arphaxad was a patriarch after the flood, a son of Shem and ancestor of Abraham. The name is probably of foreign origin, so no clear Hebrew meaning can be recovered from it.","flat":1,"g":"Arphaxad","h":"No picture."},"G743":{"b":"This word joins chief and the word for messenger. An angel is a messenger, one sent to carry word. An archangel is the chief among them. Paul says the Lord comes down with the archangel's voice. The head messenger's shout.","g":"archangel","h":"The picture: the chief messenger."},"G744":{"b":"Abbott-Smith traces this to the word for \"beginning.\" So something ancient is not just old, it reaches back to the start. Revelation calls Satan the old serpent, the one there from the first.","g":"ancient, old","h":"The picture: back at the beginning."},"G745":{"b":"Strong's reads this name as people-ruling, from the words for to rule and people. So the name carries a throne. Archelaus, son of Herod, reigned over Judea, and Joseph feared to settle there with the child.","g":"a king","h":"The picture: a name that means ruler of the people."},"G746":{"b":"One word covers the start of a thing and the rule of a ruler.\n\nAbbott-Smith gives a third sense that is easy to miss: an extremity, a corner. A beginning is an edge, the place where you get a grip.","g":"beginning, rule","h":"The picture: a corner you take hold of."},"G747":{"b":"The word joins \"first\" to \"to lead.\" Strong's: \"a chief leader.\" He is the one out in front, the founder who starts the thing and the trailblazer others follow. Jesus is called the author of life and the leader of our faith.","g":"author, captain","h":"The picture: the leader out front who breaks the trail."},"G748":{"b":"This joins the words for chief and sacred. Abbott gives high-priestly. So the picture is the high priest's own household. Those of the high-priestly family gathered in Jerusalem to question Peter and John.","g":"of the high priest","h":"The picture: the high priest's household."},"G749":{"b":"Strong's builds this from two words and renders it chief priest, or chief of the priests.\n\nAbbott-Smith notes that in the plural it covers more than one man. It takes in former high priests and members of high priestly families.","g":"high priest","h":"The picture: the chief among the priests."},"G75":{"b":"It comes from agon, the arena where the crowd gathered for the games. Agonizomai is the athlete straining every muscle for the prize, the wrestler locked in the fight. Paul: I have fought the good fight. Underneath lies the sweat of the contest.","g":"strive, fight","h":"The picture: straining for the prize in the arena."},"G750":{"b":"This joins \"chief\" to the word for a shepherd. So it is the head shepherd. Peter has just called elders shepherds. Now he names Christ the one above them, whose return brings their reward.","g":"chief shepherd","h":"The picture: the head shepherd over the whole flock."},"G751":{"b":"This name is built from the words for ruler and horse. It means master of the horses, the man who commands the cavalry. Paul tells Archippus to fulfill the ministry he was given. His very name carries a war-horse and its rider.","g":"name (horse-ruler)","h":"The picture: the master of the horses."},"G752":{"b":"Abbott-Smith ties it to the word for synagogue, joined to chief. It names the officer who ruled the synagogue and oversaw the worship. Jairus, a ruler of the synagogue, fell at Jesus' feet.","g":"synagogue ruler","h":"The picture: the man in charge of the gathering."},"G753":{"b":"This joins chief with a word for a craftsman in wood. An architekton is the master builder over the workers. Paul says like a wise master builder he laid the foundation, and another builds on it.","g":"masterbuilder","h":"The picture: the master craftsman."},"G754":{"b":"Built from a word for chief and a word for a collector of public revenue. The head man over the tax gatherers. Zacchaeus was such a man, rich from the tolls, until Jesus called him down from the tree.","g":"chief tax collector","h":"The picture: the chief man at the toll booth."},"G755":{"b":"The word joins chief with the name for a dining room of three couches. He is the superintendent of the banquet, in charge of the tables and food. At Cana he tastes the water made wine and calls the bridegroom over.","g":"master of the feast","h":"The picture: the head man of the banquet hall."},"G756":{"b":"Abbott gives this word two senses, to begin and to rule. Strong's says the form carries the idea of precedence.\n\nSame root either way. To begin is to be first in time. To rule is to be first in rank.","g":"begin","h":"The picture: the one who goes first."},"G757":{"b":"One word does two jobs. Abbott-Smith lists them side by side: to begin, and to rule. Strong's takes it as to be first.\n\nFirst in time and first in rank turn out to be the same idea.","g":"rule, begin","h":"The picture: standing at the head."},"G758":{"b":"Strong's defines it simply as a first, in rank or power. It is the participle of the verb for going first.\n\nAbbott lists rulers, judges and magistrates under it. All of them are the ones out front.","g":"ruler, chief","h":"The picture: first in the line."},"G759":{"b":"This is fragrant spice, its name tied to a word for sending off scent. These are the burial spices. The women buy aroma and come at dawn to anoint the body of Jesus, and find the tomb already open and empty.","g":"spice","h":"The picture: sweet spices carried to the tomb."},"G76":{"b":"The name comes from a word meaning ruddy, and so a human being, mankind. Adam was the first man, formed from the ground, and his name stands for humanity itself.","g":"Adam","h":"The picture: a human being."},"G760":{"b":"Asa is a name in Jesus' family line, a king of Judah. Strong's says it is of Hebrew origin, brought straight into Greek. The word points to the man, with nothing to see inside.","flat":1,"g":"Asa","h":"No picture."},"G761":{"b":"The root means to rock, to shake, to topple. Put not in front and it becomes unshakable. The wrecked ship's prow stuck fast and would not move. Paul uses the same word for a kingdom that nothing can shake loose.","g":"immovable","h":"The picture: stuck fast, unshaken."},"G762":{"b":"The root means to quench, to put out a fire. With \"not\" in front, this word is unquenchable, the fire that will not die down. John says Christ will burn the chaff with fire that cannot be put out.","g":"unquenchable","h":"The picture: a fire that cannot be put out."},"G763":{"b":"Strong's root means irreverent. Reverence bends the knee, and this word is the refusal to bend it. The asebeia man will not honor what he should honor. Abbott gives ungodliness, impiety. It is not one bad deed but a whole life with its back turned to God.","g":"ungodliness","h":"The picture: a man who will not bow."},"G764":{"b":"This comes from a word for irreverent, impious, a life with the reverence cut out. Abbott gives to be ungodly, act profanely. So it is living as though God were owed no awe. Sodom's ashes were set as an example to the ungodly.","g":"be ungodly","h":"The picture: living with no reverence for God."},"G765":{"b":"Abbott-Smith builds it from a word meaning to reverence, with a not in front. So it pictures a person who gives God no reverence at all. Not weak worship, but none.","g":"ungodly","h":"The picture: no reverence at all."},"G766":{"b":"Strong's takes the front as a negative and the rest from a word for being self-controlled. So it means the opposite. Abbott lists licentiousness, wantonness, excess. All restraint thrown off. Wild appetite with nothing holding it back.","g":"licentiousness","h":"The picture: no brakes at all."},"G767":{"b":"The word is built from a mark, with 'not' in front. So it means unmarked, a thing with no stamp on it to tell you what it is. Paul uses it in reverse. He says his city is not unknown, not a nowhere place. It has a mark.","g":"unmarked, obscure","h":"The picture: a coin with no stamp."},"G768":{"b":"The name comes from a word meaning to be straight, used in the widest sense. Asher was a son of Jacob and one of the twelve tribes of Israel, settled in fertile land by the sea.","g":"Asher","h":"The picture: straight and upright."},"G769":{"b":"Abbott-Smith glosses it as weakness, frailty, sickness. It is the noun of the word meaning strengthless.\n\nPaul uses it of his own body in 2 Corinthians 12:9. That is where God says his power lands.","g":"weakness, sickness","h":"The picture: nothing left in the tank."},"G77":{"b":"This is not joined to a word for expense or cost. It means without expense, free of charge. It pictures a gift handed over with no bill to pay. Paul preaches the gospel this way, asking nothing for it.","g":"without expense","h":"The picture: the gift with no bill."},"G770":{"b":"Abbott's sense is to be weak, feeble, and then specifically of bodily debility, to be sick.\n\nThe same word covers a man in bed and a man weak in faith. Romans 14 uses it that way.","g":"be weak, be sick","h":"The picture: strength gone."},"G771":{"b":"Abbott builds this on a word meaning to be feeble, without strength. It is a weakness a person cannot carry on their own. Paul says the strong should bear the infirmities of the weak. Not scold them. Carry them.","g":"infirmity, weakness","h":"The picture: a body with no strength."},"G772":{"b":"Abbott-Smith splits the word open. A negative, then the word for strength. Strengthless.\n\nPaul plays with it in 1 Corinthians 1:25. What looks like God with no strength still beats us.","g":"weak","h":"The picture: no strength in it."},"G773":{"b":"This is a place name, used of the Roman province. Strong's says it is of uncertain derivation, which means nobody knows where the name came from. There is no picture inside it.","flat":1,"g":"Asia","h":"No picture."},"G774":{"b":"This word marks a person by his region, Asia, the western edge of Asia Minor. Abbott gives Asian, of Asia, Asiatic. So the picture is a man named by his province. Certain of Paul's companions from Asia went on ahead to Troas.","g":"of Asia","h":"The picture: a man named by his province."},"G775":{"b":"An Asiarch was one of the officers whose duty it was to celebrate at their own charges the public games and festivals. They footed the bill for the shows. Some of them were Paul's friends and warned him.","g":"Asiarch","h":"The picture: the men who paid for the games."},"G776":{"b":"This is built from a word meaning without food. It names going without eating, a long fast. In the storm no one had eaten for many days, sick and afraid. Paul stands up and points to their long abstinence. The word is the empty stomach, no bread taken.","g":"fasting","h":"The picture: empty stomachs, no food for days."},"G777":{"b":"This is 'not' in front of sitos, grain or wheat, the stuff of bread. It means fasting, having eaten nothing. Paul says they have gone on this way, no food taken, through the whole storm. The word is an empty table, not a crumb of grain touched.","g":"fasting","h":"The picture: not a bite of bread eaten."},"G778":{"b":"Abbott gives the sense to practise, to exercise. The word was used for training the body like an athlete in the ring. Paul says he exercises himself to keep a clear conscience. The picture is the daily discipline of a man in training, working at it.","g":"exercise, train","h":"The picture: an athlete training his body."},"G779":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this is a leather bottle, a wine-skin. Wine was kept in a bag made from a whole animal hide. Jesus said new wine needs new skins, since an old, stiff one would burst.","g":"wineskin","h":"The picture: an animal skin for wine."},"G78":{"b":"Just a name in the list. Strong's ties it to Hebrew. It is one link in the long chain of fathers and sons that Luke records. A name points to a man, not to a thing you can see or draw.","flat":1,"g":"Addi","h":"No picture."},"G780":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to be glad. Abbott gives gladly. So the picture is a glad welcome at the door. When Paul and his company reached Jerusalem, the brothers received them gladly.","g":"gladly","h":"The picture: a glad welcome at the door."},"G781":{"b":"This is the word for wise with a not fixed in front. Abbott gives unwise, foolish. So it names a man walking as a fool. Look carefully how you walk, Paul says, not as the unwise but as the wise, redeeming the time.","g":"unwise","h":"The picture: walking as a fool, not a wise man."},"G782":{"b":"Strong's says the word pictures enfolding someone in the arms, but admits its guess rests on a presumed form.\n\nAbbott-Smith gives to welcome, greet, salute, and notes it was often done with a kiss. Greeting meant contact.","g":"greet, welcome","h":"The picture: a greeting with a kiss."},"G783":{"b":"The root means to enfold in the arms, to welcome. So a greeting here is not a nod. Abbott points to greetings in the market and the greeting Paul signs at the end of a letter. A warm embrace.","g":"greeting","h":"The picture: arms thrown around you."},"G784":{"b":"The root means to stain or soil, and the thing itself is a spot. With \"not\" in front, this word is unstained, without a single spot. The lamb was without blemish. James says pure religion keeps itself unspotted from the world.","g":"unspotted","h":"The picture: cloth without a stain."},"G785":{"b":"Strong's says this first named a round shield, then a serpent that coils itself like one, the asp. Abbott says an asp. Paul quotes the Psalm, the poison of asps is under their lips, the venom carried in their words.","g":"asp","h":"The picture: a coiled asp with its poison."},"G786":{"b":"When two sides made a treaty they poured out wine as an offering. This word means without that offering. No drink poured means no truce made. Paul uses it for people you cannot make peace with. Nothing seals them.","g":"truce-breaker","h":"The picture: no wine poured to seal peace."},"G787":{"b":"An assarion was a small Roman coin, Abbott-Smith says one-tenth of a drachma, small change. Jesus says two sparrows sell for one assarion, yet not one of them falls to the ground without your Father. Cheap birds, barely worth a coin, and God watches each one.","g":"a small coin","h":"The picture: the coin a sparrow costs."},"G788":{"b":"This is the comparative of the word for near. It means nearer, very close. Sailing close in along the coast of Crete, they kept the land near at hand. The word is that closeness, the ship creeping in tight against the shore rather than out in open sea.","g":"near, close","h":"The picture: hugging in close to the shore."},"G789":{"b":"This is the name of a coastal city of Asia Minor, where Paul rejoined the ship after walking overland. It is likely a foreign word. So there is no meaning behind it to picture. Only a place.","flat":1,"g":"Assos","h":"No picture."},"G79":{"b":"This is the feminine of adelphos, brother. An adelphe is a sister, and the word stretches to a sister in the faith. So Paul commends Phoebe our adelphe, family not by blood but by the same new birth, kin in the household of God.","g":"sister","h":"The picture: a sister, born of the same mother."},"G790":{"b":"This is not joined to a word meaning to stand. Abbott reads it as to be homeless, to lead a vagabond life. It pictures a person with no place to settle, always moving on. Paul says the apostles have no certain home.","g":"homeless","h":"The picture: no place to settle."},"G791":{"b":"The root is the word for a city. Like our word \"urbane,\" it started as city-polish, the refined look of town people, and came to mean handsome. So the baby Moses was asteios, a beautiful child, fair to look at.","g":"fair, handsome","h":"The picture: the polish of someone from the city."},"G792":{"b":"Strong's describes a star as strown over the sky, connecting it to a word for scattering. Abbott-Smith gives no origin, so this is Strong's reading.\n\nRevelation holds seven of them in one hand.","g":"star","h":"The picture: lights scattered across the sky."},"G793":{"b":"The root means to set fast, to fix firmly in place. Put not in front of it. So this is something never fixed, never planted, a post that was never driven into the ground. Peter uses it of unstable souls.","g":"unstable","h":"The picture: a post never driven in."},"G794":{"b":"The root is the special word for family love, the bond between parent and child, kin for kin. Put not in front and that natural tie is gone. Paul names it as a mark of a broken world. A heart cold to its own blood.","g":"unloving","h":"The picture: a home with the family bond cut."},"G795":{"b":"The roots are a, not, and stochos, a mark or aim. So the word is to miss the mark, to shoot and not hit. It is the archer's picture again. Some have swerved from the target of faith and wandered into empty talk.","g":"miss the mark","h":"The picture: the arrow misses."},"G796":{"b":"Strong's gives lightning, by analogy, glare. It comes from a word meaning to flash. It pictures lightning flashing from one side of the sky to the other. It can also mean the bright shine of a lamp.","g":"lightning","h":"The picture: the flash of lightning."},"G797":{"b":"Strong's says \"to flash as lightning.\" The root is the word for a star. Jesus says his coming will be like lightning that flashes from one end of the sky to the other, seen everywhere at once. At the tomb, angels' clothes flash like this.","g":"flash, lighten","h":"The picture: lightning flashing across the sky."},"G798":{"b":"This comes from aster, \"a star (as strown over the sky),\" as if scattered like seed across the dark. Astron is the star or the cluster of them. Real points of light overhead, thrown out by the handful.","g":"star","h":"The picture: stars scattered across the night sky."},"G799":{"b":"Strong's reads this name as incomparable, one you cannot set beside another and match. So the name means without equal. Asyncritus was among the believers Paul greeted by name in the closing of Romans.","g":"a Christian","h":"The picture: a name that means without equal."},"G8":{"b":"The name means father of abundance, one who is liberal. It joins a word for father with a word meaning to jut over or exceed. Abiathar was a priest who served King David and shared his flight.","g":"Abiathar","h":"The picture: father of abundance."},"G80":{"b":"Abbott-Smith breaks the word open: a joining piece plus the word for womb. Born of the same parent.\n\nStrong's says the same. So calling a fellow believer brother is not a polite title. It claims shared origin.","g":"brother","h":"The picture: out of the same womb."},"G800":{"b":"The root means sounding together, in tune. Put the not in front and you get music out of harmony. Abbott says discordant, at variance. The Jews at Rome were like this among themselves over what Paul told them.","g":"discordant","h":"The picture: notes that will not sound together."},"G801":{"b":"The root pictures a mind that puts things together, that connects one fact to the next. Asunetos is the mind that cannot. Their foolish heart was darkened, Paul says. Looking at the made world and never joining it to God.","g":"without understanding","h":"The picture: a mind that cannot connect the pieces."},"G802":{"b":"The root means to place things together, to strike an agreement. Put the not in front. So it is a person who will not hold to what was settled. Abbott says false to engagements, not keeping covenant. Paul names it a mark of a broken people.","g":"covenant-breaker","h":"The picture: breaking a bargain you shook on."},"G803":{"b":"The word means firmness, then certainty and safety. Luke writes his account so his reader may know the firm truth of what he was taught. It is the sense of standing on ground that will not shift.","g":"certainty, safety","h":"The picture: solid ground underfoot."},"G804":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this is built from a word meaning to trip up, with not in front. Safe means un-trippable. So when Hebrews calls hope a sure anchor, the word underneath says your feet will not slide out from under you.","g":"safe, sure","h":"The picture: footing that will not slip."},"G805":{"b":"The word means to make firm, to make secure. It is what the chief priests do to the tomb, sealing the stone and setting a guard so the body cannot be taken. In Acts it locks Paul's feet in the stocks. To fasten down tight.","g":"make secure","h":"The picture: sealing a door so it cannot be forced."},"G806":{"b":"The word means securely, safely. In Mark the men are told to lead Jesus away safely, and in Acts the jailer keeps Paul safely. The picture is a grip that holds, a hold nothing can slip out of.","g":"safely, surely","h":"The picture: held so tight he cannot slip away."},"G807":{"b":"The root means shapeless, without proper form. To behave unbecomingly is to act out of shape, in a way that has lost its decency and form. Paul uses it of love, which never behaves this way.","g":"behave unseemly","h":"The picture: a thing out of shape."},"G808":{"b":"The root means shapeless, without proper form, from not plus shape. It points to what is unseemly and indecent, and to nakedness. Behind the idea of shame is a thing gone out of its right shape. Not as it was meant to look.","g":"shameful thing","h":"The picture: something out of its right form."},"G809":{"b":"This is not joined to a word for shape or form. Abbott gives it first as shapeless, then uncomely. It pictures the parts of the body we keep covered, the less presentable ones. Paul says we give these more honor, not less.","g":"uncomely","h":"The picture: the part kept covered."},"G81":{"b":"From the word for a brother. So the church is pictured as a brotherhood, one family of brothers. Peter uses it for the whole Christian community. Not a club you join, but a family bound like blood.","g":"brotherhood","h":"The picture: a family of brothers."},"G810":{"b":"The roots are a, not, and sozo, to save. So the word is the state of one who cannot be saved from himself, a life thrown away. Paul ties it to drunkenness, the reckless waste that pours a person out.","g":"riot, excess","h":"The picture: a life that cannot be saved."},"G811":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning wasteful, prodigal, money poured out and lost. Abbott gives wastefully. So the picture is a purse emptied on nothing. The younger son went to a far country and wasted all he had in reckless living.","g":"riotously","h":"The picture: money poured out and wasted."},"G812":{"b":"The picture is a soldier marching who steps out of line, or an apprentice skipping his work. So it means to be idle and out of order. Paul says he did not behave that way among them, but worked night and day.","g":"be idle","h":"The picture: a soldier quitting his rank."},"G813":{"b":"Tasso means to line up in order. The a cancels it. The word was used of soldiers not keeping the ranks, an army in disarray. Paul tells them to warn the disorderly, those who will not hold their place.","g":"unruly","h":"The picture: a soldier who breaks rank."},"G814":{"b":"The root is a military word. Soldiers were arranged in ranks, and this word is what happens when a man breaks rank, unarranged, out of line. Paul rebukes those living disorderly and idle. The one who will not keep step with the rest.","g":"disorderly","h":"The picture: a soldier out of rank."},"G815":{"b":"The word is \"child\" with \"no\" fixed to the front. Abbott says \"childless.\" The Sadducees pose a man who dies and leaves no child, so his brother must marry the widow. An empty cradle driving the whole question.","g":"childless","h":"The picture: a house with no child in it."},"G816":{"b":"Abbott traces the word to a root meaning strained, intent, stretched tight. It is the hard, fixed stare. They fixed their eyes on Stephen, and his face shone like an angel's.","g":"gaze, stare","h":"The picture: straining the eyes."},"G818":{"b":"The root joins a negative with the word for honor and worth. To dishonour, to insult, to treat as worth nothing. In the parable they beat the master's servant and sent him away shamed. Honor torn off.","g":"dishonour","h":"The picture: stripped of honor."},"G819":{"b":"The same root, honor with a no in front. This is the state of dishonour, disgrace. Paul says the body is sown in dishonour and raised in glory. Laid low, counted worthless, before the turn comes.","g":"dishonour","h":"The picture: sown in the ground in shame."},"G82":{"b":"This is the word \"clear\" with \"not\" stuck on the front. Strong's says \"hidden.\" Jesus uses it for graves that do not show, so people walk over them without knowing what lies beneath. Hidden, giving no sign.","g":"hidden, unseen","h":"The picture: an unmarked grave you walk over."},"G820":{"b":"The a at the front means \"not.\" What it cancels is a word for value, the money paid for something. So atimos is the thing marked worthless, no price on it. A prophet, Jesus says, is priced that way in his own town.","g":"dishonoured","h":"The picture: the thing with no price on it."},"G822":{"b":"Strong's says \"mist.\" Abbott says \"vapour.\" James says your life is exactly this, a vapor that shows for a moment and then is gone. The breath you see on a cold morning, there and then not. It rises off the ground and disappears.","g":"vapour, mist","h":"The picture: a wisp of mist that vanishes."},"G823":{"b":"Strong's says uncut, indivisible, an atom of time. Split a second down and down until you cannot split it more. In that flash, Paul says, the dead will be raised and changed.","g":"moment","h":"The picture: a sliver of time too small to cut in two."},"G824":{"b":"This is \"not\" plus \"place,\" topos, a spot. Abbott: \"out of place, not befitting.\" A thing sitting where it does not belong. The Greeks used it for what is wrong or harmful. When Paul is bitten and takes no harm, this is the word.","g":"harm, improper","h":"The picture: a thing sitting where it does not belong."},"G825":{"b":"Attalia is a name, a city in Pamphylia. It marks the port where Paul and Barnabas came down to sail home. The sources give it no meaning to unfold, so there is nothing here to picture.","flat":1,"g":"Attalia","h":"No picture."},"G826":{"b":"The root is a beam of light, the radiance of daybreak. Abbott-Smith gives to shine forth. Paul says the god of this age blinds people so the light of the gospel cannot dawn on them.","g":"shine forth","h":"The picture: the first ray of dawn breaking through."},"G827":{"b":"This word is a ray of light, the brightness of daybreak. The first shaft of sun over the horizon. Paul talked with the believers until dawn, then left.","g":"daybreak","h":"The picture: the first ray of dawn."},"G828":{"b":"This is the title of the Roman emperor, taken from a Latin word for majesty and honor. Here it stands as a name, Augustus. A title like this points to the man on the throne, not to a thing you can see.","flat":1,"g":"Augustus","h":"No picture."},"G829":{"b":"The word joins self and pleasure: self-pleasing, arrogant. It is the man who consults his own liking and no one else's. Paul says an overseer must not be like this. Such a person plants himself at the center and expects the world to bend.","g":"self-willed","h":"The picture: pleasing only yourself."},"G83":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning hidden, indistinct, out of sight. Paul warns against trusting in the uncertainty of riches. The word underneath says the thing is hidden. You cannot see where it will go.","g":"uncertainty","h":"The picture: something hidden from sight."},"G830":{"b":"The word joins self and to choose. It means self-chosen, done of your own accord. Paul says the Macedonians gave beyond their power on their own, with no one having to ask or press them.","g":"of own accord","h":"The picture: the choice no one had to ask for."},"G831":{"b":"The root is autos, self. The word behind it meant one who acts on his own authority, an autocrat answering to no one. Paul says he does not permit a woman to seize authority that way over a man.","g":"dominate","h":"The picture: acting as if the power were yours alone."},"G832":{"b":"The root is a flute. This verb is playing one, blowing into the pipe. Jesus quotes the children in the market, we played the flute and you would not dance. The word is the tune nobody moved to.","g":"play the flute","h":"The picture: blowing into a flute."},"G833":{"b":"Strong's says it is a yard, open to the wind. Abbott-Smith says it is the open courtyard a house is built around. Peter warmed himself in one while Jesus was tried inside.","g":"courtyard","h":"The picture: a yard open to the sky."},"G834":{"b":"An auletes is a flute-player. At a death, hired players filled the house with wailing music. Jesus comes to the dead girl's home and finds the flute-players already there. He tells them to leave, the girl is not dead but asleep. They laughed. Then he raised her.","g":"a flute-player","h":"The picture: flute-players at a funeral."},"G835":{"b":"The root is aule, an open courtyard. To aulizomai is to pass the night there, out under the sky. Each evening in that last week Jesus leaves the city and lodges out on the Mount of Olives, sleeping in the open.","g":"lodge","h":"The picture: spending the night out in the open."},"G836":{"b":"Strong's calls it a flute, as blown. It pictures a hollow pipe with air pushed through it to make a note. Paul asks how anyone will know the tune if the pipe gives no clear sound.","g":"pipe, flute","h":"The picture: air blown through a pipe."},"G837":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's examples are the lilies of the field and infants growing up. Luke uses it of John and of Jesus.\n\nNothing forced. It is what living things do when they are left to it.","g":"grow, increase","h":"The picture: a plant and a baby."},"G838":{"b":"This is the word for growth, the way a plant gets taller or a child gains height. The root means to grow, to wax, to enlarge. Paul says the body grows itself up in love. Slow increase you can actually measure.","g":"growth, increase","h":"The picture: a plant getting bigger."},"G839":{"b":"Strong's traces it to a word for a breeze, the morning air. So \"tomorrow\" pictures the cool fresh morning coming on. Abbott gives no origin. \"Do not worry about tomorrow.\"","g":"tomorrow","h":"The picture: the fresh morning air."},"G84":{"b":"This grows from a word meaning hidden, indistinct. It means uncertainly. It pictures a runner racing toward a goal he cannot clearly see. Paul says he runs not like that, but with his eyes fixed on the mark.","g":"uncertainly","h":"The picture: running toward a mark you cannot see."},"G840":{"b":"Abbott traces it to a word for drying up and says it means \"harsh to the taste,\" the pucker of unripe or sour wine. Then it came to mean a harsh person. The frightened servant calls his master an austere man, hard and sharp.","g":"harsh, severe","h":"The picture: the harsh, dry bite of sour wine."},"G841":{"b":"The word joins self and enough. It means having your sufficiency in yourself, enough and to spare, not craving more. Paul says God can give you all sufficiency, and that godliness with contentment is great gain.","g":"contentment","h":"The picture: enough, with nothing lacking."},"G842":{"b":"Built from self and a word meaning to be enough. It means self-sufficient, content, carrying your supply within. Paul says he has learned in whatever state he is to be content, whether full or hungry.","g":"content","h":"The picture: needing nothing from outside."},"G843":{"b":"This joins the word for self to a word meaning to judge against, to sentence. A factious man is self-condemned. He is his own judge handing down the guilty verdict. No one else needs to condemn him. He has done it himself.","g":"self-condemned","h":"The picture: passing sentence on yourself."},"G844":{"b":"This joins autos, self, to make \"self-moved,\" where we get automatic. Automatos means happening of its own accord, with no hand pushing. Jesus says the earth bears fruit by itself, first the blade, then the ear, then the grain, while the farmer sleeps.","g":"of its own accord","h":"The picture: the ground bearing fruit all by itself."},"G845":{"b":"This word joins self with a word meaning to gaze with wide-open eyes. An eye-witness is one who saw the thing himself. Luke says his account rests on such people. Not rumor passed along, but men who watched it happen.","g":"eye-witness","h":"The picture: seeing it with your own eyes."},"G847":{"b":"The word simply means here, in this (or that) place. Jesus says it in Gethsemane: sit here while I go over there and pray. It pins people to a spot, marking the ground where the disciples waited and slept while he agonized nearby.","g":"there","h":"The picture: right on this spot."},"G849":{"b":"This joins autos, self, to cheir, the hand. It means with one's own hands. On the third day they threw the ship's tackle overboard with their own hands, no one else's. The word puts the crew's hands on the gear, doing the hard thing themselves.","g":"own hands","h":"The picture: your own two hands doing the work."},"G85":{"b":"Strong's traces this to being sated to loathing, so full you feel sick. It means to be in deep distress, unsettled and heavy. In the garden Jesus began to be sorrowful and troubled. The word is that churning, restless weight before the cross.","g":"distressed","h":"The picture: the sick, restless heaviness of too much."},"G850":{"b":"Abbott ties this to a word for drought. It means dry, then squalid and dark. Peter calls the world a dark place, and the prophetic word a lamp shining in it until the day dawns.","g":"dark, dismal","h":"The picture: a dry, dusty, dismal place."},"G851":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means to take from, to take away, to take off. It joins away and take. Peter used it when he took off the servant's ear with his sword. It is removing a thing completely.","g":"take away, cut off","h":"The picture: taking something clean off."},"G852":{"b":"The root means to shine or show. Put 'not' in front and you get what does not show, the hidden thing. Yet no creature is hidden from God. All lies bare and open before his eyes.","g":"hidden","h":"The picture: kept out of the light."},"G853":{"b":"The root means not-showing, out of sight. To aphanizo is to make a thing vanish, and so to destroy it. Moth and rust do this to treasure on earth, eating it until there is nothing left to see.","g":"destroy, vanish","h":"The picture: making a thing vanish from sight."},"G854":{"b":"This comes from the word to render unseen, to make disappear. The old covenant is growing old and worn, and is close to fading away out of sight, like something ready to vanish.","g":"vanishing","h":"The picture: fading out of sight."},"G855":{"b":"Built from a not and a word meaning to shine or show. Not-shown, out of sight. Their eyes were opened and they knew him, and then he vanished from their sight. There one moment, and simply gone.","g":"vanished","h":"The picture: the figure that stops showing."},"G856":{"b":"Built from \"away\" and a word for sitting, an aphedron is the place set apart to sit, the latrine. Jesus makes a blunt point with it. Food goes in, passes through, and out to the privy. It never touches the heart.","g":"privy, drain","h":"The picture: the place you go to sit apart."},"G857":{"b":"The root pheidomai means to spare. The a in front cancels it. So this is unsparing treatment, driving the body hard and giving it no quarter. Paul says such harsh handling of the flesh has a show of wisdom but no real value.","g":"harsh treatment","h":"The picture: showing the body no mercy."},"G858":{"b":"Strong's traces this word to a picture of ground with no stones, smooth and even. From that comes its meaning: simplicity, a plain and single heart. The first believers ate together with this, hearts smooth and open, nothing hidden underneath.","g":"simplicity","h":"The picture: smooth ground with no stones to trip on."},"G859":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the plain sense is dismissal, release. The word comes from letting go. Picture a captive set free and sent out. That is what forgiveness does with sin. It sends it away and opens the door.","g":"forgiveness, release","h":"The picture: the prison door swung open."},"G86":{"b":"Strong's says the word properly means unseen. It is built from not and to see. Hades is the hidden place of the dead, the world out of sight where departed souls go, beyond our seeing.","g":"Hades, the grave","h":"The picture: the unseen place."},"G860":{"b":"A ligament is the tough band that fastens one bone to another. This word is that fastening, the joint. Paul says the whole body is held together by every joint. The parts do not float free. They are tied to one another.","g":"joint, ligament","h":"The picture: the ligament that ties bone to bone."},"G861":{"b":"It comes from a word meaning undecaying, what will not rot. The body is sown perishable and raised in aphtharsia. Where everything here spoils, browns and falls apart, this does not. Flesh that will never decay.","g":"incorruption","h":"The picture: flesh that will not rot."},"G862":{"b":"Abbott builds it from φθείρω, to spoil, with \"not\" set in front. Strong's: \"undecaying.\" Everything else spoils and fades, but this word says of a thing: not that. It will never rot. Peter uses it for a kept inheritance.","g":"imperishable","h":"The picture: what cannot rot."},"G863":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is to send forth, send away, let go. He notes it was used of debts, to remit them.\n\nSo forgiving is not feeling better about a wrong. It is dropping what the other person owes.","g":"forgive, leave, let go","h":"The picture: opening your hand and letting go."},"G864":{"b":"The word means to arrive, to reach a place. Strong's notes it here of a report spreading forth. Paul tells the Romans their obedience has reached all men. The good news of them has traveled the whole way.","g":"come abroad","h":"The picture: news that travels until it reaches everyone."},"G865":{"b":"This is the word for one who loves good, a promoter of virtue, with 'not' set in front. So it names someone who is no friend to good at all. Paul lists such people in the last days, turned against what they should love.","g":"despiser of good","h":"The picture: no friend to what is good."},"G866":{"b":"This word joins \"not\" with a word meaning fond of silver. The greedy man loves the gleam of coins. This word is the opposite, free of the love of money. Hebrews ties it to contentment. Hands not clutching after silver.","g":"not greedy","h":"The picture: not in love with silver."},"G867":{"b":"This grows from a word meaning to go forth, to set out. Oddly it can mean both arriving and leaving. Paul used it of his going, warning that after his departure fierce wolves would come among them.","g":"departing","h":"The picture: the setting-out."},"G868":{"b":"Abbott says the word means to stand off, to withdraw from. You step back and stand apart. It is used of falling away from God. This is the root behind the word \"apostasy.\"","g":"depart, fall away","h":"The picture: standing away."},"G869":{"b":"Strong's ties this to a word meaning not visible, unseen. Suddenly is what comes at you out of the unseen, with no warning. A sound from heaven came like this at Pentecost, all at once, from nowhere they could point to.","g":"suddenly","h":"The picture: out of the unseen, with no warning."},"G87":{"b":"The root means to separate, to sort things into piles. Put a \"not\" in front and you get one who refuses to sort people, drawing no line between rich and poor. James says heaven's wisdom is like that. It takes no sides.","g":"without partiality","h":"The picture: refusing to sort people into piles."},"G870":{"b":"Built from the word for fear, with the not set in front. Zechariah sings that we would be rescued to serve God aphobos, without fear, all our days, Luke 1:74. The trembling taken out of worship, and boldness put in.","g":"without fear","h":"The picture: the trembling taken out."},"G871":{"b":"The root means to make one thing like another, to shape a match. Melchizedek is made like the Son of God, formed in the record to resemble him, a priest who abides forever.","g":"made like","h":"The picture: shaped to match another."},"G872":{"b":"This word joins away and to see. It means to turn your eyes off everything else and fix them on one point. The runner looks away from the crowd to Jesus alone. One gaze, and all the rest falls out of view.","g":"look, fix gaze","h":"The picture: eyes turned off everything but one thing."},"G873":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says it means to mark off by boundaries, to separate from. It is the picture of drawing a line to fence one thing apart from another. Like a shepherd dividing the sheep from the goats.","g":"separate, set apart","h":"The picture: drawing a boundary line."},"G874":{"b":"Apo means from, and the root means to rush forward. Aphorme was the base an army launched its attack from, the starting point. Paul warns that sin takes aphorme, a foothold to spring from. Give it no ground to launch from.","g":"opportunity","h":"The picture: the base an army attacks from."},"G875":{"b":"The root means froth, the slaver on the lips. This verb is what a body does in a fit, foaming at the mouth. Mark uses it for the boy thrown down by a spirit, rolling and foaming while his father begs Jesus for help.","g":"foam","h":"The picture: foam at the mouth."},"G876":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives one word: foam. Strong's says froth, or slaver. A spirit would seize the man's son, throw him into convulsions, and leave him foaming at the mouth, bruising him hard before it finally let go.","g":"foaming","h":"The picture: foam at the mouth."},"G877":{"b":"Built from a word meaning mindless. Paul asks the Corinthians to bear with him in a little aphrosyne, a little folly, as he is forced to boast, Second Corinthians 11:1. From the heart, Jesus says, this foolishness comes pouring out.","g":"foolishness","h":"The picture: the mind switched off."},"G878":{"b":"Strong's says this word is, properly, mindless. It is built from not and the word for the mind. A fool here is not stupid so much as senseless, acting with no mind switched on.","g":"foolish","h":"The picture: nobody home."},"G879":{"b":"This word is built from the word for sleep. Strong's reads it as to drop off in slumber. As they sailed, Jesus fell asleep in the boat, so worn out that even the storm crashing over the sides did not wake him.","g":"fall asleep","h":"The picture: dropping off to sleep."},"G88":{"b":"The root means to leave off or to fail, to be absent. Put not in front and it means never leaving off, no gap, no break. Paul carries an unceasing sorrow, and prays without a break. Like a stream that runs on and never stops.","g":"without ceasing","h":"The picture: a stream that never stops."},"G880":{"b":"The word is \"not\" plus \"voice,\" so \"voiceless, i.e. mute.\" No sound coming out. The lamb is this before its shearers, silent. So are the idols, mouths that cannot speak. And every sound in the world has meaning, Paul says, none is voiceless.","g":"dumb, mute","h":"The picture: an open mouth with no sound."},"G881":{"b":"The name means possessor. It comes from a word meaning to seize or hold fast. Achaz was a king of Judah, listed among the ancestors of Jesus in Matthew's genealogy.","g":"Ahaz","h":"The picture: possessor."},"G882":{"b":"This is a place name, the Roman province of Achaia in Greece. Strong's calls it of uncertain derivation. A place name like this carries no picture.","flat":1,"g":"Achaia","h":"No picture."},"G883":{"b":"This name is drawn from Achaia, which Strong's calls Greece. So the man is named for his land. Achaicus came to Paul with Stephanas and Fortunatus, and refreshed his spirit, one Paul was glad to see.","g":"a Christian","h":"The picture: a man named for Greece."},"G884":{"b":"The word is \"no\" joined to the word for giving a kindness freely. So it means the person who receives a favor and returns none, thankless. Jesus says God himself is kind even to the ungrateful, to those who never thank him.","g":"ungrateful","h":"The picture: taking the gift and giving no thanks."},"G885":{"b":"Achim is a name in Jesus' family line. Strong's says it is probably of Hebrew origin, carried into Greek. The word points to the man and holds no picture of its own.","flat":1,"g":"Achim","h":"No picture."},"G886":{"b":"The word carries hand inside it, with a front piece meaning not. So it means not made by hands. Jesus speaks of a temple not built by human hands, and Paul of a house in heaven that no workman ever raised.","g":"not made by hands","h":"The picture: a building no hands ever touched."},"G887":{"b":"Abbott says the word is a mist, and especially a dimness of the eyes. Strong's calls it a cataract. At Paul's word a mist falls on Elymas and he gropes about for a hand to lead him.","g":"mist","h":"The picture: a mist over the eyes."},"G888":{"b":"This is \"not\" joined to a word meaning useful. Achreios means useless, of no profit. Jesus tells the servants to say, when they have done all they were told, we are unprofitable servants, we only did our duty. No claim on thanks.","g":"unprofitable","h":"The picture: the servant who is no use at all."},"G889":{"b":"The root means useless. So this word is to make useless, to spoil. Abbott says to make useless, unprofitable. Paul quotes the Psalm, they have all together turned useless, like something gone off that no one can use.","g":"become useless","h":"The picture: gone bad and good for nothing."},"G89":{"b":"Built from a word meaning never leaving off, with no gap. Paul says pray adialeiptos, without ceasing, First Thessalonians 5:17. Not one endless prayer but a line never quite broken, the way a fire is kept from ever going out.","g":"without ceasing","h":"The picture: a line never quite broken."},"G890":{"b":"This is the word for useful, employed, with 'not' set in front. So it means useless. Paul plays on it. Onesimus was once unprofitable to you, but now profitable. The runaway who did no work now works.","g":"unprofitable","h":"The picture: a tool that does no work."},"G892":{"b":"Achyron is chaff, the light dry husks that come off the grain. Strong's notes it scatters easily. A breath of wind takes it. John says the chaff will burn with unquenchable fire. When the harvest is sorted, the empty husks have no weight and no future.","g":"chaff","h":"The picture: husks blowing away in the wind."},"G893":{"b":"This is the word for falsehood with a not set in front. Abbott gives free from falsehood, truthful. So the picture is one with no lie anywhere in him. God, who cannot lie, promised eternal life before the ages began.","g":"cannot lie","h":"The picture: no lie anywhere in him."},"G894":{"b":"This is wormwood, a plant so bitter it stands for bitterness itself. In Revelation a star called Wormwood falls and turns the waters bitter. Picture the bitter herb poisoning the streams.","g":"wormwood","h":"The picture: the bitter wormwood plant."},"G895":{"b":"This is not joined to psyche, breath and life. It means lifeless, with no breath in it. It pictures things that never breathed yet still make sound, like a pipe or a harp. Paul uses them to picture unclear speech.","g":"without life","h":"The picture: things with no breath in them."},"G896":{"b":"Abbott notes the name is Hebrew for lord, a master. Baal was the god of the Canaanites. So the name itself claims lordship. God tells Elijah he kept seven thousand who never bent the knee to this false lord.","g":"Baal","h":"The picture: a false lord men bowed down to."},"G897":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this name comes from an Assyrian word, Bab-ili, meaning \"Gate of God.\" So the proud city named itself a doorway to heaven. In Revelation it stands for Rome and for tyranny.","g":"Babylon","h":"The picture: the gate of God."},"G898":{"b":"From baino, to step, this is a stair-step, one of the degrees of a stairway. From there it means a standing gained, a step up. Paul says deacons who serve well gain a good standing and boldness in the faith.","g":"standing","h":"The picture: a stair-step you climb."},"G899":{"b":"Abbott points to \"the deep sea.\" Strong's calls it profundity, how far down a thing reaches. It is the deep water where Peter let down the nets. Paul uses it for the deep riches of God.","g":"depth","h":"The picture: how far down the deep water goes."},"G9":{"b":"Strong's marks this as a region of Syria. Abbott adds no meaning, only the place. So the picture is the land itself. Luke dates the coming of God's word by it, naming Lysanias tetrarch of Abilene.","g":"a region","h":"The picture: the land of Abilene itself."},"G90":{"b":"The root means to rot thoroughly, to decay. The front of the word cancels it. So this is soundness that does not rot, purity that will not spoil. Paul wants such uncorrupt teaching from Titus, a doctrine no decay can touch.","g":"uncorruptness","h":"The picture: what will not rot."},"G900":{"b":"This word comes from the word for deep, going down. Abbott-Smith gives it as to deepen. The wise builder dug down deep, past the loose topsoil, and set his foundation on solid rock so the flood could not shake it.","g":"deepen","h":"The picture: digging down deep to the rock."},"G901":{"b":"Strong's calls it \"profound (as going down).\" It simply means deep. Abbott points to the well at Sychar, where the woman says the water is deep and Jesus has nothing to draw with. It is used too of deep sleep and the deep of night.","g":"deep","h":"The picture: water that goes far down."},"G902":{"b":"This word means a palm branch. The crowd cut them and waved them as Jesus rode into Jerusalem. Abbott says the word came into Greek from Egyptian. So skip the guesswork about roots. The real picture is the branch itself.","g":"palm branch","h":"The picture: a palm branch waved in the road."},"G903":{"b":"The name means not of the people, that is a foreigner. It joins a word for not with a word for a people. Balaam was the Mesopotamian seer hired to curse Israel, who blessed them instead.","g":"Balaam","h":"The picture: not of the people, a foreigner."},"G904":{"b":"The name means waster, one who lays waste. It comes from a word meaning to annihilate. Balak was the king of Moab who hired Balaam to curse Israel as they camped near his land.","g":"Balak","h":"The picture: waster."},"G905":{"b":"This is a purse, a little pouch you drop coins into, its name tied to throwing them in. Carry no balantion on the road, Jesus tells them, no money-bag. Sell your goods, he says elsewhere, and make purses that do not wear out.","g":"purse","h":"The picture: a small bag for coins."},"G906":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the word properly belongs to a weapon or missile. Strong's says to throw, more or less violent.\n\nFrom there it softens. It also means to pour a drink, or simply to put something somewhere.","g":"throw, cast, put","h":"The picture: hurling a spear."},"G907":{"b":"Abbott gives two examples from an old historian. Soldiers wading breast deep. And the sinking of ships.\n\nThe word is to dip, immerse, sink. Not sprinkled on top. Under.","g":"baptize, immerse","h":"The picture: a ship going under."},"G908":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first word for it is immersion.\n\nHe notes a second use that gets missed. Jesus calls his coming suffering a baptism. Being put under water and being swamped by trouble are the same picture.","g":"baptism","h":"The picture: going right under."},"G909":{"b":"The root means to dip, to plunge a thing right under until it is soaked through. A baptismos is a washing by dipping. Mark uses it of the Jewish rinsing of cups and pots, the ceremonial dipping of things clean before use.","g":"washing","h":"The picture: a thing plunged under water."},"G91":{"b":"Abbott-Smith gives a second sense of to injure, hurt. This is not an abstract fault. Someone is on the receiving end.\n\nDoing wrong here means somebody walks away damaged.","g":"wrong, harm","h":"The picture: a person left hurt."},"G910":{"b":"The root means to immerse, submerge, to push fully under water. A Baptistēs is the dipper, and the name belongs to John, who stood in the Jordan and plunged the crowds beneath it, drowning the old life and raising them up wet and new.","g":"Baptist","h":"The picture: the dipper who plunges you under."},"G911":{"b":"Abbott's second sense is \"to dip in dye, to dye.\" You push the cloth under and it comes up a new color all the way through. That is bapto. Not a splash on the surface, but soaked and stained clear through.","g":"dip","h":"The picture: cloth pulled up out of the dye."},"G912":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the name means, literally, son of a father. That is all the name tells us. He is the prisoner the crowd chose instead of Jesus. The name itself carries only that plain meaning.","g":"Barabbas","h":"The picture: son of a father."},"G913":{"b":"The name comes from a word meaning lightning. Barak was the Israelite commander who, at the prophetess Deborah's call, led the army that broke the forces of Sisera.","g":"Barak","h":"The picture: lightning."},"G914":{"b":"The name means knee, and so blessing, of Jah. It joins a word for a knee with Jah, a short form of the Lord's name. Bending the knee was the posture of blessing. Barachias was the father of Zechariah.","g":"Berechiah","h":"The picture: blessing of Jah."},"G915":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says the word likely copies the sound of foreign speech, descriptive of unintelligible sounds. To Greek ears a stranger's talk was just \"bar-bar,\" noise. So the word for foreigner began as a mockery of how outsiders sound.","g":"barbarian, foreigner","h":"The picture: babble you cannot understand."},"G916":{"b":"This is the verb of weight, to press something down. In Gethsemane the disciples' eyes were heavy, weighed down by sleep. Paul felt crushed beyond his strength. The picture is a load pushing on you until you sag toward the ground.","g":"weigh down","h":"The picture: eyelids pressed down by weight."},"G917":{"b":"This comes from barys, heavy. As an adverb it means heavily, with difficulty. Said of ears it means they have grown too heavy to hear well. The quote is of people whose hearing has gone dull and slow, barely catching the sound.","g":"heavily, dull","h":"The picture: ears too heavy to hear."},"G918":{"b":"The name is Aramaic, bar Tolmai, son of Tolmai. Picture him among the twelve Jesus named, standing in the list right next to Philip, Matthew 10:3. His whole name is a fact about whose son he was.","g":"Bartholomew","h":"The picture: son of Tolmai."},"G919":{"b":"Abbott reads the Aramaic as son of Joshua, for bar means son. So the name says son of Jesus, though the man wore it falsely. Bar-Jesus the sorcerer withstood Paul, and was struck blind for a season.","g":"Bar-jesus","h":"The picture: son of Joshua."},"G92":{"b":"Built from the word for to do wrong. Abbott gives a wrong, an injury, a misdeed. Gallio tells the crowd, if it were some adikema or vicious crime, I would hear you, Acts 18:14. Not wrong in the abstract but a particular wrong done.","g":"wrong, misdeed","h":"The picture: a specific wrong done."},"G920":{"b":"Abbott reads the Aramaic as son of Jonah, for bar means son. So the name marks a father. Jesus calls Peter blessed, Simon son of Jonah, for flesh and blood had not revealed it to him.","g":"Bar-jonas","h":"The picture: son of Jonah."},"G921":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says Bar is the Aramaic word for son, used as a prefix. The rest of the name is explained in Acts 4:36 as encouragement.\n\nHe notes the second half is not certain. But Luke gives us the meaning himself.","g":"Barnabas","h":"The picture: son of encouragement."},"G922":{"b":"Baros is weight, a heavy load. Bear one another's burdens, the crushing loads too big for one back. Yet the light affliction works an eternal weight of glory, a heaviness that presses the scale down for good. Real, pulling heft.","g":"weight, burden","h":"The picture: a heavy weight pressing down."},"G923":{"b":"The name is Aramaic, son of Sabba. Bar means son, the way many Jewish names named the father. Two men carry it, the Joseph passed over when the lot fell to Matthias, and the Judas sent from Jerusalem with the letter.","g":"Barsabas","h":"The picture: son of Sabbas."},"G924":{"b":"Strong's reads the name as son of Timaeus, for bar means son. So the title names the father. Blind Bartimaeus sat begging by the road out of Jericho, and cried to the Son of David for mercy.","g":"Bartimaeus","h":"The picture: son of Timaeus."},"G926":{"b":"The root is a word for weight, a load. Jesus says the teachers tie up heavy burdens and lay them on other people's shoulders. It also names a savage wolf and a weighty letter. Something that presses down because it truly weighs.","g":"heavy","h":"The picture: a load too heavy to carry."},"G927":{"b":"The word joins two pieces, one meaning heavy or weighty, the other meaning price or value. Something like this is weighed down with worth. In Matthew 26:7 a woman pours ointment of great value over Jesus, and some call it waste.","g":"very costly","h":"The picture: heavy with worth."},"G928":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this properly meant \"to rub on the touchstone,\" the black stone that told whether gold was real. From testing by rubbing it grew to testing by torture, and then simply to torment.","g":"torment","h":"The picture: the testing stone."},"G929":{"b":"The root means to torture. Basanismos is the pain itself, the torment inflicted on a body. In Revelation it names the suffering of the lost. There is no softening it. The word means agony laid on someone.","g":"torment","h":"The picture: pain put on a body."},"G93":{"b":"This is the opposite of dike, right or justice, with the a of not in front. Adikia is injustice, unrighteousness, everything out of true. So those who hold down the truth in adikia are bending it out of line, refusing to let the straight thing stand straight.","g":"unrighteousness","h":"The picture: the crooked, what does not line up with right."},"G930":{"b":"The root means to torture. This word is the man who does it. Abbott says it was used of a gaoler, the keeper of the prison. In Matthew 18:34 the master hands the unforgiving servant over to the torturers until he pays.","g":"torturer, jailer","h":"The picture: the jailer who inflicts pain."},"G931":{"b":"This word first means a touchstone, a dark stone jewelers used to test whether metal was true gold. From testing metal it moved to testing people by torture, then to torment itself. They brought Jesus all who were racked with such torment.","g":"torment","h":"The picture: the stone that tests gold."},"G932":{"b":"Abbott-Smith puts the abstract sense first: sovereignty, royal power, dominion. Only second does it mean a kingdom, the territory or people.\n\nSo the kingdom of God is first God ruling, and only after that a place.","g":"kingdom, reign","h":"The picture: a king's power to rule, not his land."},"G933":{"b":"This word comes from the word for kingly. Strong's says it means a palace. Jesus asks what the crowd went out to see. Men in soft, fine clothes live in palaces, not in the wilderness where John preached in rough camel hair.","g":"palace","h":"The picture: a king's palace."},"G934":{"b":"The root is the word for a king. So this means kingly, belonging to the crown. Peter says you are a royal priesthood, a holy nation. Ordinary people, and yet the king's own.","g":"royal","h":"The picture: belonging to the king."},"G935":{"b":"Strong's traces this to a word for a foundation of power. The king is the base the whole nation rests on. So when Revelation calls Christ King of kings, it says he is the ground under every throne, the stone that holds them all up.","g":"king","h":"The picture: the foundation power stands on."},"G936":{"b":"From basileus, king. To basileuo is to be king, to reign, to hold the throne and rule. So grace basileuo, reigns, through righteousness, and the saints will reign with Christ. Sin once sat the throne. Now grace takes the seat.","g":"reign, rule","h":"The picture: taking the throne and ruling."},"G937":{"b":"The root is the king. This word marks what belongs to him, his land, his robes, his servant. A royal official came to Jesus about his dying son. There is also a royal law, one that rules over the rest.","g":"royal","h":"The picture: the king's own land and servants."},"G938":{"b":"The word means a queen, from the verb to rule. Jesus speaks of the queen of the South who came from the ends of the earth to hear Solomon's wisdom. A crowned woman who traveled far, and something greater than Solomon is here.","g":"queen","h":"The picture: a queen."},"G939":{"b":"This word comes from the verb to walk. It means a step, and then the foot itself, the base you stand on. Luke uses it of the lame man at the temple gate: his feet and ankles were made strong, and he stood and walked.","g":"foot","h":"The picture: the foot you walk on."},"G94":{"b":"Strong's builds this from a negative particle and the word for justice. So an unjust person is one with the \"not\" in front, someone missing what is right. Abbott-Smith sets it opposite to the righteous man.","g":"unjust","h":"The picture: without justice."},"G940":{"b":"Strong's says to fascinate by false representations, and Abbott-Smith adds to blight by the evil eye. Paul asks the Galatians who bewitched them, as if some spell had been thrown to blind their eyes.","g":"bewitch","h":"The picture: the evil eye cast to put someone under a spell."},"G941":{"b":"Abbott-Smith's first sense is to take up with the hands, to lift, and his example is the crowd picking up stones in John 10:31.\n\nSo bear one another's burdens means get your hands under it.","g":"carry, bear","h":"The picture: hands lifting a stone."},"G942":{"b":"This is a bramble, a thorny brier shrub. You do not gather grapes from it, Jesus says. It is the bush that burned and was not consumed when God spoke to Moses. A low tangle of thorns you would rather not touch.","g":"bramble bush","h":"The picture: a tangle of thorns."},"G944":{"b":"The word means a frog. Abbott-Smith gives simply \"a frog.\" Picture the small croaking creature hopping out of the mud. So three unclean spirits came out like frogs from the mouth of the dragon.","g":"a frog","h":"The picture: a frog."},"G945":{"b":"Named perhaps after a famous stammerer, joined to the word for word. So it means to stammer, to repeat idly. Jesus warns against heaping up such babble in prayer. Picture the mouth stuck, saying the same thing again and again.","g":"vain repetitions","h":"The picture: the stammering mouth."},"G946":{"b":"The root means to be disgusted, to recoil. A bdelygma is what makes you sick to look at, tied here to idols. Not merely bad but revolting, the thing you shove away in disgust. It is the word behind the abomination of desolation.","g":"abomination","h":"The picture: the thing that turns your stomach."},"G947":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to be disgusted, to detest. It describes something so foul it makes you recoil. Paul says some claim to know God but their works deny it, abominable and disobedient. The word is a stomach turning away.","g":"abominable","h":"The picture: something that turns the stomach."},"G948":{"b":"Strong's traces this to a word meaning to stink. To abhor is to react to a stench, turning the face away in disgust. It is used of loathing idols. Not a calm dislike, but the sharp recoil from something that reeks.","g":"abhor","h":"The picture: recoiling from a stench."},"G949":{"b":"Strong's ties this to the word for the foot, the base you stand on. Firm means it holds your weight, like ground that will not give way. Hebrews calls hope an anchor that is bebaios. Something you can plant your feet on and not slip.","g":"firm, steadfast","h":"The picture: firm ground under your feet."},"G95":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning unjust, with the right taken out. Abbott gives unjustly, undeservedly. So it is a wrong you never earned. It is grace, Peter says, when a man bears up under grief suffered unjustly.","g":"unjustly","h":"The picture: a wrong suffered undeserved."},"G950":{"b":"This means to make firm or secure. Abbott-Smith notes it was a legal term, to guarantee the validity of a purchase, confirming that a title holds. God confirms his promises and keeps you firm to the end.","g":"confirm, establish","h":"The picture: guaranteeing a sale."},"G951":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to make firm and steady. An oath sets a promise solid, past all argument. Among men an oath is the end of every dispute, the thing that makes a matter sure.","g":"confirmation","h":"The picture: set firm and settled."},"G952":{"b":"Abbott-Smith ties this to a threshold, a place open to be trodden by anyone. Profane means unfenced, common, the opposite of the holy ground set apart. It is the courtyard everyone walks across, nothing kept sacred about it.","g":"profane","h":"The picture: ground any foot may tread."},"G953":{"b":"The root pictures ground anyone may cross, open like a doorway anyone can step through. To profane is to treat the holy that way, common, walked on. Jesus says the priests work on the Sabbath and profane it, yet are guiltless. He points past the rule to something greater than the temple.","g":"to profane","h":"The picture: walking common feet across holy ground."},"G954":{"b":"This is Beelzebul, a name used for Satan. The sources argue over what its parts once meant, offering several guesses that do not agree. Because the meaning is uncertain even to them, there is no sure picture to draw.","flat":1,"g":"Beelzebul","h":"No picture."},"G955":{"b":"The name means worthlessness. It became a name for utter wickedness, and in Scripture stands as an epithet of Satan himself, the source of all that is worthless and vile.","g":"Belial","h":"The picture: worthlessness."},"G956":{"b":"The root is the word to throw. A belos is the thing thrown, a spear or arrow, a flaming dart. Paul says the shield of faith puts out all the fiery darts of the evil one.","g":"dart, arrow","h":"The picture: an arrow in flight."},"G957":{"b":"This is the comparative of good, meaning better, one thing weighed above another. Abbott gives better, very well. Paul tells Timothy, you know very well, better than I need say, how much Onesiphorus served at Ephesus.","g":"better","h":"The picture: one good thing set above another."},"G958":{"b":"The name means son of the right hand. It joins a word for a son with a word for the right hand or side, the place of honor and strength. Benjamin was the youngest son of Jacob and Rachel.","g":"Benjamin","h":"The picture: son of the right hand."},"G959":{"b":"The name means victory bringer, from the words for bearing and conquest. Picture Bernice sweeping into the hall with great pomp beside King Agrippa to hear Paul, Acts 25:23. A name of triumph, worn to a prisoner's hearing.","g":"Bernice","h":"The picture: a name that means victory."},"G96":{"b":"The root is the assayer's word, a coin proven good after assay, current after assayal. Add the not, and you get metal that does not pass. Real silver goes through the fire and stands. False silver is thrown out. So a person can be tried and found wanting.","g":"rejected","h":"The picture: metal that fails the test."},"G960":{"b":"Berea was a city of Macedonia. Its name is the whole picture here, for Luke praises its people: more noble than those in Thessalonica, they received the word eagerly and searched the Scriptures daily to see whether these things were so.","g":"Berea","h":"The picture: the town that checked the Scriptures."},"G961":{"b":"This word marks a person by his city, Berea in Macedonia. Strong's gives of Berea. So the picture is a man named by his town, from the place whose people searched the Scriptures daily. Sopater the Berean traveled with Paul.","g":"of Berea","h":"The picture: a man named by his town."},"G963":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this place name may mean \"house of affliction,\" or perhaps \"house of dates.\" Strong's chooses date-house. So the village near Jerusalem was a house of something, likely the date palm. It was Mary and Martha's town.","g":"Bethany","h":"The picture: house of dates."},"G964":{"b":"Strong's reads the name as house of kindness, from words for a house and mercy. Abbott says the origin is unsure, so this is Strong's reading. At this pool a man had lain sick thirty-eight years, and there Jesus healed him.","g":"Bethesda","h":"The picture: a house named for mercy."},"G965":{"b":"Abbott says the name means \"house of bread.\" That is what the word behind Bethlehem pictures, a place named for bread. It is the small town six miles south of Jerusalem.","g":"Bethlehem","h":"The picture: the house of bread."},"G966":{"b":"The name means house of fish, a fishing town on the Sea of Galilee. Abbott gives it plainly. Peter, Andrew and Philip came from there. Picture nets drying by the shore and boats pulled up on the sand. A village of fishermen.","g":"Bethsaida","h":"The picture: the house of fish."},"G967":{"b":"The name means \"house of unripe figs.\" It was a village near Jerusalem, named for the green figs that grew there. From here Jesus sent two disciples to fetch the colt. The place carried the smell of the orchard in its very name.","g":"Bethphage","h":"The picture: a house among the fig trees."},"G968":{"b":"Abbott-Smith says this first meant a step or stride, from the word \"to go.\" Then it became a raised place, a platform reached by steps, where a Roman judge sat to rule. Paul stood before such a seat.","g":"judgment seat","h":"The picture: a platform reached by steps."},"G969":{"b":"The word means beryl. Abbott-Smith calls it \"a jewel of sea-green colour.\" Picture a stone the pale green of shallow sea water. So beryl was the eighth foundation of the city wall.","g":"beryl","h":"The picture: a sea-green jewel."},"G97":{"b":"Add \"not\" to the word for a trick or bait and you get a liquid with nothing slipped into it, no water, no filler. Peter uses it just so. Crave the pure, unwatered milk of the word.","g":"sincere","h":"The picture: milk with nothing slipped into it."},"G970":{"b":"This word means force, the shove of muscle and violence. Strong's ties it to the word for life, the raw energy in a living body. The mob pressed so hard with bia that soldiers had to carry Paul up the stairs.","g":"violence","h":"The picture: the shove of muscle and force."},"G971":{"b":"The root is force, raw strength. The word means to force, to press, to shove your way in. Jesus says the kingdom of heaven suffers violence, and the forceful seize it. Whether it is stormed by enemies or grabbed by the eager, the word is all push and press.","g":"to force","h":"The picture: forcing your way through by strength."},"G972":{"b":"This word comes from the word for force. It means violent, powerful. Luke uses it of Pentecost: a sound came like a rushing, violent wind that filled the whole house. Not a breeze. A blast with force behind it.","g":"violent","h":"The picture: the force of a rushing wind."},"G973":{"b":"From a word meaning to force, to crowd oneself into a place. So this is a forceful, violent person. Jesus says the violent take the kingdom by force. Picture a man shoving his way through a crowd to get in.","g":"violent one","h":"The picture: shoving through the crowd."},"G974":{"b":"The root is a roll, a scroll. This word is the small version, a little book. An angel gives John this little scroll and tells him to eat it. Sweet in the mouth, bitter in the stomach. Small enough to swallow.","g":"a little book","h":"The picture: a little scroll in the hand."},"G975":{"b":"Strong's calls it a diminutive, the little version of the bigger word for a book. Abbott says the same.\n\nAbbott's first sense is a paper or written document, like a bill of divorce. Everyday paperwork.","g":"book, scroll","h":"The picture: a small roll of paper."},"G976":{"b":"Strong's says this word properly meant the inner bark of the papyrus plant. That bark was made into sheets to write on. So a book began as the soft inside of a reed by the river.","g":"book, scroll","h":"The picture: the inner bark of a reed."},"G977":{"b":"The word is built on a root for grazing and feeding, to pasture. It simply means to eat. Gather the fragments left by those who had eaten, Jesus said, so nothing is lost. They filled twelve baskets from the leftovers.","g":"eat","h":"The picture: eating your fill."},"G978":{"b":"This is the name of a region of Asia, and the Spirit did not let Paul go there. Its origin is of uncertain derivation. So there is nothing behind the name to picture, only a place on the map.","flat":1,"g":"Bithynia","h":"No picture."},"G979":{"b":"Strong's calls this a primary word, which means it does not come from anything older. It means life, and also the living you get by, like the widow who gave her whole livelihood. Nothing lies behind it.","flat":1,"g":"life, livelihood","h":"No picture."},"G98":{"b":"This word just means belonging to Adramyttium, a seaport in Asia Minor. The ship Paul first sailed on came from there. It is a place name turned into a label for the ship. There is no image hidden inside it.","flat":1,"g":"of Adramyttium","h":"No picture."},"G980":{"b":"The root is the life you are living now. Strong's puts it as \"to spend existence,\" as if life were a sum you spend. Peter says to spend the rest of it by God's will, not by human cravings.","g":"live","h":"The picture: spending out the days you are given."},"G981":{"b":"This comes from a word meaning to spend one's life. Abbott gives manner of life. So the picture is the daily way a life is lived out. Paul points to his manner of life from youth, known to all the Jews.","g":"manner of life","h":"The picture: the way a life is lived out."},"G982":{"b":"The word comes from the word for life, the ordinary living of it. It means the everyday affairs, food and money and work, the cares that fill a day. Jesus warns not to let the cares of this life choke the heart.","g":"of this life","h":"The picture: the daily business of getting by."},"G983":{"b":"From blapto, to hinder and injure, this is what does harm, hurtful. Paul says those who want to be rich fall into foolish and hurtful desires that wound and drown men in ruin.","g":"hurtful","h":"The picture: what wounds you."},"G984":{"b":"Strong's says the word first meant to hinder, to hold back, and from there to injure. It is harm that stops you. Mark's longer ending promises that deadly poison will not hurt the disciples, and Luke's demon leaves its victim without injuring him.","g":"hurt, injure","h":"The picture: knocked back and hurt."},"G985":{"b":"The word means to sprout, to bud. In the parable the wheat sprouts and puts out grain, and the weeds show up among it. Hebrews uses it of Aaron's dead staff that budded. The picture is green pushing up out of the ground.","g":"sprout, bud","h":"The picture: a seed breaking into sprout."},"G986":{"b":"Strong's links the name to a word meaning to germinate, to sprout. Blastus is Herod's chamberlain, the man Tyre and Sidon win over first when they come to sue for peace.","g":"Blastus","h":"The picture: a green sprout pushing up."},"G987":{"b":"Abbott says it is to speak lightly or profanely of sacred things, and marks it as the opposite of speaking well.\n\nAbbott also uses it flatly of slandering people. Blasphemy and gossip are the same verb.","g":"blaspheme, slander","h":"The picture: speaking cheap about holy things."},"G988":{"b":"Abbott's first sense is railing slander. This is not calm disagreement. It is speech thrown to wound, to drag a name through the mud. Aimed at God, it becomes the mouth set against heaven, tearing at the one name that cannot be torn down.","g":"blasphemy","h":"The picture: words hurled to tear a name down."},"G989":{"b":"The word joins a root for injuring to pheme, speech. Words meant \"to injure,\" aimed at men or at God. Paul says he was once a blasphemer, his mouth used as a weapon against the name of Christ.","g":"blasphemer","h":"The picture: words used as a weapon."},"G99":{"b":"This is a place name, the Adriatic sea, the waters between Greece and Italy where the ship drifted for two weeks. It is named after a town near its shore. The name has no meaning to open up, only the sea it marks on the chart.","flat":1,"g":"Adriatic sea","h":"No picture."},"G990":{"b":"The root means to look at. This word is a look, a glance, what the eye takes in. Peter says righteous Lot, by what he saw and heard among the wicked, was tortured in his soul.","g":"seeing, a look","h":"The picture: a glance of the eye."},"G991":{"b":"Strong's calls it a primary verb, so nothing older stands behind it. Abbott-Smith gives no origin, only the uses: bodily sight, then mental sight, then which way a thing faces.","flat":1,"g":"see, look","h":"No picture."},"G992":{"b":"This word comes from the word to throw or put. Abbott-Smith reads it as that which one must put. Jesus uses it of new wine. It must be put into new wineskins, not old brittle ones that would split and spill.","g":"must be put","h":"The picture: new wine going into fresh skins."},"G993":{"b":"Strong's says this name means sons of commotion, sons of uproar. Jesus gives it to James and John in Mark 3:17. It is a nickname for two loud, stormy brothers, marking their fiery temper.","g":"Boanerges","h":"The picture: two brothers full of uproar."},"G994":{"b":"Abbott-Smith traces this to a word for a cry. The note there says it expresses emotion, whether joy or fear. So this is not a calm call. It is a voice raised from strong feeling.","g":"cry out, shout","h":"The picture: a shout."},"G995":{"b":"This is a shout, a loud call for help. James says the cries of the harvesters you cheated have reached the ears of the Lord of hosts. The shout went up, and God heard it.","g":"cry","h":"The picture: a loud shout for help."},"G996":{"b":"The plain word means help. But both sources note a sea use: ropes passed under and around a ship to bind the hull together in a storm. Frapping. The sailors used these on Paul's ship. Help you can tie around a breaking thing.","g":"help","h":"The picture: ropes wrapped around a hull."},"G997":{"b":"Abbott builds it from \"βοή + θέω, to run\", a shout and running. You hear a cry and run toward it. The word means to come to the aid of someone calling for help.","g":"help","h":"The picture: running toward a cry for help."},"G998":{"b":"Strong's builds this from a cry for help and a word meaning to run. So a helper here is the one who hears you shout and comes running. The Lord is my helper, says Hebrews. He runs at the cry.","g":"helper","h":"The picture: the one who comes running at your cry."},"G999":{"b":"This is a hole in the ground, a pit. The root means to deepen. Jesus says if a blind man leads a blind man, both fall into the pit. And who would not lift his sheep out of a pit on the Sabbath.","g":"pit","h":"The picture: a hole dug in the ground."}};